<HEADLINE>
COYOTES SHIP JANNEY TO TAMPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig Janney, the first-line center and No. 4 scorer for the
Coyotes last season, predicted he wouldn't play in Phoenix next
season. On Thursday, he was proven correct.
</P>
<P>
   In what some characterize as a money-saving and roster-clearing
move, Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith traded Janney to Tampa
Bay for journeyman left wing/enforcer Louie DeBrusk and the
Lightning's first pick of the fifth round in the amateur entry
draft this month.
</P>
<P>
   Janney, who didn't return phone calls, produced 10 goals and 43
assists in 68 games. He is entering the final year of his contract
and is scheduled to earn $1.7 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay General Manager Phil Esposito insinuated that budget
concerns by the Coyotes were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Coyotes) have a budget thing going on over there,''
Esposito told the Tampa media. ``With (Sandy) McCarthy, (Enrico)
Circcone and (Andrei) Nazarov, we have plenty of toughness on our
team. What we wanted was somebody to get the puck to our wings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are negotiating what could be a costly contract
extension with Captain Keith Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   With their expected decision not to bring back veteran Mike
Gartner, who either will retire or become a free agent July 1, the
Coyotes will save $1.5 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   The additional savings made by eliminating Janney's salary can
be targeted to retain Tkachuk, possibly without having to also part
company with assistant captain Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't characterize it as that (a cost-saving move),
although it is a significant payroll deduction,'' Smith said.
``It's a trade that clarifies our situation in the middle and
clearly sets up Jeremy Roenick and Cliff Ronning as our top two
centers. It also gives Daniel Briere a chance to push for a roster
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long we can keep Briere in the (American
Hockey League). I think he's a player and he's going to be an
excellent NHL player in time, but he'll have to earn a spot in
training camp. I expect Craig Janney to have a very good season in
Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   Briere, who scored one goal in five games in Phoenix, led
Springfield scoring with 36 goals, 56 assists and 92 points in 68
games, fourth in the AHL.
</P>
<P>
   League sources sources said the Coyotes have been trying to
trade Janney for two weeks and were considering making him
available on the waiver wire or in this month's expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Tkachuk and Janney are close, and the captain has
made no secret that he prefers Janney to center him.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the trade will sour Tkachuk on completing a
contract extension, Smith answered strongly, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said earlier that the team faces three options with
Tkachuk: It can re-sign him to an extension, he can sit out next
season without pay or the team can trade him, and he added that all
three are viable.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors are rampant in the NHL that Tkachuk's contract demands
could mean the Coyotes can't afford to keep both him and Roenick,
but the trade of Janney and Smith's declaration of Roenick as his
top-line center contradicts them.
</P>
<P>
   Center is a position where the Coyotes have an abundance of
players, with Roenick, Ronning, recently re-signed Mike Stapleton,
Bob Corkum, Juha Ylonen, Mark Janssens and Briere.
</P>
<P>
   Corkum and Janssens are restricted Group II free agents.
</P>
<P>
   In DeBrusk, the Coyotes obtained an enforcer who might end up in
Springfield. Enforcer is another position where they seem to have
players in abundance, with Jim McKenzie, Jim Cummins, Janssens and
Sean Gagnon. Like Janssens, McKenzie and Gagnon are restricted free
agents who might receive offers the team won't match. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
