<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN_BICKLEY_PIPPEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENCY SETS PIPPEN FREE OF BULLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ You should've seen the grin. It was devious,
liberated, warranted. And it beamed from Scottie Pippen like a man
leaving Alcatraz for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   See, the sentence is about to expire, the suppression nearly
over. One victory away from a place he has always wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   In demand. In control. And if Jerry Colangelo is smart, on his
way to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``To play without him is like a slap in the face for me,''
Michael Jordan said. ``But I want him to do well. I think he's
entitled to find out what his net worth is.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Bulls brace themselves for a final farewell, a weepy
sentiment is emerging and the posturing has already begun. On
Thursday, Phil Jackson talked about rays of hope that could prolong
a dynasty. Jordan claimed his teammate is keeping his options open,
already putting the heat on ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Except Pippen walked into a room and slammed the door shut. And
you should've seen the grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really want to know?`` Pippen said. ``I want the
opportunity to go out and open all the doors to the free agent
market. I don't have any intentions of coming back here next
season, even though I stated a couple of days ago that I would look
to come back. I think this is the last run for this ballclub.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Many options &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, will it pave the way for Colangelo's first real banner?
</P>
<P>
   After a monstrous performance in the Finals, Pippen will find
plenty of suitors. He wants to be wanted, flooded with offers. And
while there were rumblings among agents last week that Pippen's
price tag will be too high for the Suns, a team that must allocate
some cap room for a center, this isn't about money alone.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he just ruled out the Bulls, which could be his most
lucrative option.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably is,'' Pippen said. ``But I don't want to come back
and play for four years and just go for a title for one season. I
have to look at the longevity of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Colangelo should be licking his chops. Pippen is
yearning for a new beginning, and the Suns are a perfect fit. And
whatever Colangelo can't give him in annual salary, he should give
him in years, just like A.C. Green.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, this is where Colangelo's reputation pays
off. This is when he can swoop in, provide a friendly haven for
abused athletes, show them an organization that doesn't run on
contention. Precisely what Pippen is looking for.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that's a stretch, know that Pippen makes $2.7
million a year. If you blame him for signing the contract, know
that other organizations willingly reward underpaid superstars. If
you can't relate to a millionaire livid over his working
conditions, know that every profession is relative, centered around
respect.
</P>
<P>
   And for all the vindictive tweakings Bulls' management has
directed at Pippen, one story tells all _ the day he asked General
Manager Jerry Krause if he could buy a championship trophy replica
only to hear he wasn't deserving. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Out of Jordan's shadow &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forget the mindless chatter that Pippen can't survive without
Jordan, that he's not a fourth-quarter assassin. Forget the laundry
list, too. He is far removed from his petulant past, and in the
past three years, Pippen has matured greatly, emerging from
Jordan's shadow into a leader.
</P>
<P>
   No player is like Pippen, a stallion that has never been
unleashed in an up-tempo offense. He has championship pedigree. He
can show a team how to win.
</P>
<P>
   The real concern is how much he has left. Pippen will turn 33
later this year, and when you factor in two Olympic appearances and
six championship runs, no one has played more games in the past
decade. Risk or rationale?
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Classic Sports, the Suns versus Bulls in 1993, and I was
looking at the difference between Michael and Scottie in five
years,'' Jackson said. ``Scottie is still so terrific in his speed
and anticipation. He is always there, always a harassing person.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he will be there for the taking. And worth every penny. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
