<HEADER>
A5830 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-12 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jazz too pathetic &QL; 
to warrant any pity
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ This has become so much more than a rout.
</P>
<P>
   It is sheer embarrassment, an utter humiliation for the Utah
Jazz that is so complete, it is almost painful to watch. Like the
episodes of Jerry Springer, we can only peer at it through cracks
in our fingers and shake our heads at the indignity to which people
are willing to subject themselves before the harsh, unforgiving eye
of national television.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shame in losing in the NBA Finals to Michael Jordan
and the Chicago Bulls. Plenty of others have shared in that
experience of misery. It is the manner of the Jazz defeat that is
so troubling. So complete and so demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the Jazz in this series is like watching the same
skinny kid get his lunch money stolen by the same school bully day
after day. Rather than scorn, we want to pity them, which for a
supposedly hard-nosed group of competitors is far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Big game, small people. That's how the Jazz will be remembered.
A legacy of shrinking in the spotlight, of shriveling in the
clutch, of taking a step out in the middle of the grandest stage
and forgetting every line that had been rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone, John Stockton, Jeff Hornacek, Bryon Russell, Greg
Foster, Greg Ostertag, Shandon Anderson, Howard Eisley, Jerry
Sloan. All of them.
</P>
<P>
   Late collapses a constant
</P>
<P>
   Especially Malone and Stockton. For the pair of original Dream
Teamers, this has been the ultimate nightmare. It's an experience
that will have so many re-examining their careers and re-evaluating
their places in basketball history.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it is not the losing that makes this so difficult to
swallow. But the way in which the losses have come, by Utah's
shortcomings down the stretch in every game. By an inability to
perform at the time when the fire of competition is hottest and the
greatest stars are defined.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: The Jazz lost Game 3 by an all-time NBA
Finals-record margin of 42 points and scored a mere 54 points, a
low for any NBA team in the era since the shot clock was adopted.
And that was not the depth of ignominy. It is, instead, all these
fourth quarters, all these missed opportunities that get stuck in
the Jazz's throat like a watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 on Wednesday night was no different. Malone took just
three shots in the fourth quarter and scored his only basket in the
final 10 seconds. Stockton kept beating defenders off the dribble
and finding a path to the basket but was unable to get the
basketball to the rim with shots that could have made the
difference for Utah and tied the series.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it has been since the Finals began, with the Jazz
playing the fourth quarter like it was on a treadmill moving in
reverse. Utah coughed up a seven-point lead in the last four
minutes of Game 1 and barely hung on to win in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this effort so embarrassing isn't that the Bulls are
playing an overwhelming brand of basketball. No, athletes can
accept getting whipped by a team that is clearly superior. What the
elite athletes can't _ or shouldn't _ accept is to knuckle under to
their own fear.
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to Bulls' intimidation
</P>
<P>
   That's what we're talking about here. Intimidation. The Jazz
can't beat the Bulls and Jordan simply because they are the Bulls
and Jordan. The Jazz is being consumed by the aura of the five-time
NBA champions and the pressure of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   How else can we explain the Mailman, who is giving rise to a
whole cottage industry of postal jokes? He is a fourth-quarter
ghost, a chiseled, muscle-bound shrinking violet. Worse than
missing clutch shots, he isn't taking them.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, 36, is showing his age. He plays half the game now and
can't do many of the things he did a year ago. Hornacek limps
around on bad wheels and is ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, Anderson, Ostertag, Foster and the rest are healthy but
unable to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan, their coach, has tried goading, cajoling, insulting them,
and none of it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   They were so awesome against the Lakers and have been so small
against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Jazz lost in the Finals to the Bulls but
maintained a dignity, a drive to get back here. This time, the Jazz
said, it would be different. It is. It is worse.
</P>
<P>
   Will Utah stay together for another season? Or will this break
the Jazz?
</P>
<P>
   There has been so much talk of the impending end of the dynasty,
of this being Chicago's ``last dance.'' But it is an image of the
Jazz, looking like wallflowers, that will linger when the music
stops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
