<HEADER>
A5833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-12 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: JARVIS FITS AT ST. JOHN'S
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The bleeding has stopped, finally.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last week, Rob Ades, the lawyer for Mike Jarvis,
had predicted that when the smoke cleared and Jarvis was introduced
as St. John's head basketball coach there would be no warm, fuzzy
feelings. There would be no hugs.
</P>
<P>
   But here they were Thursday, at the end of an hourlong news
conference, and the Rev. Donald Harrington, the St. John's
president, and Jarvis gave each other a long hug.
</P>
<P>
   This was more than a photo opportunity. This was a celebration
of two ships more or less rejoicing that they did not pass in the
night. For the 53-year-old Jarvis, the new job represents the
opportunity of a lifetime. Regarded as one of the ``hot coaching
prospects'' for the last six years, Jarvis finally cashed in with a
contract reportedly worth $5 million over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis had hit a ceiling at George Washington. At St. Johns, in
New York, he has a larger stage, access to all-America caliber
players and a mega-conference, the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was happy and excited to get this opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   For conservative St. Johns, the bold move effectively marks the
first time since 1965 _ when Lou Carnesecca took over from Joe
Lapchick _ that university actually pursued and hired its first
choice for basketball coach. St. John's desperately needed and
wanted a high profile coach to complement a larger quest for
expansion, Harrington explained Thursday. This meant establishing a
major investment in technology, opening a campus in Rome, establish
a global presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basketball is an important thing for us,'' Harrington said,
``not just because it helped us maintain a major sports program,
but also because it is an excellent means for us to communicate St.
Johns to alumni and friends. We have people who know about St.
John's, read about St. John's, only because of the basketball
team.''
</P>
<P>
   What these friends have read for the last six years has been
disastrous. There was the ``loyalty hiring'' hiring of Brian
Mahoney in 1992 to replace the legendary Lou Carnesecca, whom
Mahoney had served for a number of years. There was the firing of
Mahoney in 1996. Then there was the embarrassment of being rebuffed
by several high profile coaches before finally settling for Fran
Fraschilla of Manhattan. Last month came the messy parting with
Fraschilla, followed by a very public private pursuit of candidates
to fill the vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of Jarvis marks the end of that ugly, sometimes
nasty, epoch of St. Johns basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, and necessarily, Jarvis is the first outsider to take
up residence in Alumni Hall, a non-New Yorker, a non-white male. He
also becomes the Big East's fifth African-American head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of conferences made up of historically black college
conferences, the Big East has more African-American head coaches
than any major Division I conference in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the nice platitudes and homilies to the Vincentian
mission at St. John's, the most persistent question surrounding
Jarvis is permanency: Will he stay or will he bolt to the National
Basketball Association at the first opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   ``I take that as a compliment that somebody would think I would
be good enough to be a head coach in the NBA,'' said Jarvis, who in
1995 interviewed for the Boston Celtics job. ``That's how I take
it. Look at my track record.'' St. John's is still in denial over
the amount of money being tossed at Jarvis. Although Harrington
denied Nike was directly involved in the contract, he later said
the burden of Jarvis' salary would be reduced because of
contributions being made by Nike and Host Communications, the
nation's leading sports marketer.
</P>
<P>
   A number of professors and students and one assistant soccer
coach have expressed outrage over reported involvement by Nike.
</P>
<P>
   For St. John's, the program, will never be the same in terms of
aspirations and expectations. They could have hired Paul Hewitt of
Siena and been happy, could have hired Davidson's Bob McKillop and
been happy, but for the presence they wanted, Jarvis was the man.
</P>
<P>
   And he may be a more permanent presence than people think.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis is reluctant to move. He lived in the same house in
Cambridge, Mass., for 17 years. He told his wife they could get a
new home anywhere, as long as it was it was in Cambridge. But after
he took the George Washington job, and watched that work out well,
he changed his philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move to Washington taught me that it's not so much the
place _ that's just building and structures _ as much as it's the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The people at St. John's like Jarvis; Jarvis likes the people.
It's what they call a fit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
