r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CLUBHOUSELEADERS-     06-12 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CLUBHOUSELEADERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS NEEDED FOR SUCCESS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Oakland Athletics of the late 1980s, as talented a
collection of players the game had seen in decades, had it. So has
nearly every World Series champion.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator to almost all championship clubs is
strong leadership from within. Very few rudderless clubs are
capable of winning a championship of any kind, whether it's a
division title or the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is not overrated,'' said Reggie Smith, an integral
part of the great Dodgers clubs of the 1970s. ``You do need to have
it, regardless of where it comes from. Look at the teams that do
well and they all have someone or several that the other players
trust and respond to.''
</P>
<P>
   The current Dodgers and Colorado Rockies, a pair of sputtering
clubs who, by most accounts, should be better, have each been
accused of lacking leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone associated with the Rockies believes the
club dearly misses first baseman Andres Galarraga and shortstop
Walt Weiss. Neither player was very vocal, but each set an example
that was undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss those guys more than anyone around here wants to
admit,'' one Rockies player said. ``They kept some of the, quote,
stars around here in check. Everyone had to work as hard as they
did because you looked foolish if you didn't. That's not the case
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The tremendously talented Dodgers have been referred to as
classic underachievers the past four years. A lack of leadership
among the players has been blamed for most, if not all, of the
Dodgers' shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' primary whipping boy always was catcher Mike
Piazza, the highest-paid player and the one in the spotlight. It
always seemed to be Piazza's fault when the Dodgers' pitching staff
didn't perform at the same level as Atlanta's famed staff.
</P>
<P>
   During spring training, former Los Angeles center fielder Brett
Butler, now retired, laced into Piazza for his lack of leadership
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza is the greatest hitter I have ever been around,
but you can't build around Piazza because he is not a leader,''
Butler told the ``Los Angeles Times.'' ``Mike Piazza is a moody,
self-centered, '90s player. We're in crunch time during pennant
races the last two years and all Piazza seems to care about is
winning the MVP from Larry Walker or the batting title from Tony
Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to spend $100 million and build your team around
that or pay for a less-talented guy who is more of a leader?''
</P>
<P>
   Butler's words ricocheted throughout the Dodgers' clubhouse.
Some players privately agreed with Butler. Some, of course, did
not. Either way, Piazza, now with the New York Mets, did not seem
to leave many friends behind.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Piazza being jettisoned from LA in one of the
biggest trades in baseball history last month, several Dodgers
spoke of the club's situation finally being relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electricity in here is unbelievable,'' second baseman Eric
Young said. ``It was like we're starting a brand new season. You
hate to see a guy like Mike Piazza leave, but we knew something had
to be done. It just wasn't clicking. But now, everything is
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ramon Martinez said, ``Everybody can see the difference
in the team. Everyone is excited again, and we feel good about the
team. You can see a big difference on the bench in the games.
Everything is better now.''
</P>
<P>
   To put the blame for the Dodgers' shortcomings squarely on
Piazza is not fair, said former Dodgers great and current San Diego
coach Davey Lopes, considered one of the best leaders of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't force leadership on a player,'' Lopes said. ``Some
players have enough problems worrying about themselves and can't
carry the emotional and physical weight of also being the team's
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like charisma; you can't turn it on if you don't have it.
Being a leader is an intangible that some players are born with.
It's how others perceive you to be. Organizations make mistakes and
think they can make someone a leader. You can't assume the role, it
has to come from the person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it can take years to discover a leader or bring one
into an organization. As an expansion club, the Diamondbacks are at
a disadvantage because they were thrown together for the first time
during spring training. Jay Bell is a candidate. Someone who might
emerge at some point is rookie first baseman Travis Lee, who could
develop into a silent leader.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego third baseman Ken Caminiti, considered one of the
great silent leaders, never asked for the role. Like a truly great
leader, he never pushed it away when it was headed in his
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it comes from the way you carry yourself and the way
you play the game,'' said Caminiti, the unanimous National League
MVP in 1996. ``It's something you earn. I don't mind it at all. If
you have respect you can say whatever. But you have to be
constructive, not a (jerk). You can't have a winning club without
leaders among the players. It can't come from the (coaching)
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Leadership can come in many different forms. Those Oakland clubs
that went to the World Series three consecutive years from 1988 to
1990 were loaded with players who went in their own direction.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson, Jose Canseco, Dennis Eckersley and Dave Parker
weren't exactly the kind of players who would take kindly to any
player getting in their face and telling him what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Those A's clubs that averaged more than 100 victories over a
three-year period may have seemed more like rock stars on tour, but
they weren't without leadership from within the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Carney Lansford provided some with his
blue-collar, workmanlike approach that helped him serve as the
leader for the bulk of the A's. For the rest, the superstars, there
was center fielder Dave Henderson, who surprisingly wielded more
clout than may have been known at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's constant gap-toothed smile provided the perfect
cover for his often pointed jokes in the clubhouse and the dugout.
It was not uncommon to hear Henderson making comments such as:
</P>
<P>
   ``The right fielder (Canseco) should have made that catch in the
sixth inning. If he had we would have won the game. Maybe he was
checking out some babe in the stands. All I know is the next time,
he better have his head in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco would laugh along with several other teammates at the
inference, but the message was sent crystal clear. The other A's
all knew what was being said, even if it was disguised as a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson would just as easily rankle Canseco as he would Rickey
Henderson or Bob Welch or even Manager Tony La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hendu said what had to be said,'' said Dave Stewart, a 20-game
winner on those Oakland staffs. ``He wasn't shy with his criticisms
but he never embarrassed a player. He said it to get the player
thinking and nine out of 10 times it worked.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
