<HEADLINE>
TOURISM BUREAU TRYING TO REBRAND PHOENIX AS DESTINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG ANDERSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phoenix is a sweltering, barren desert devoid of culture,
activities and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   That's what many who have never visited the Valley said when
asked for their impressions of our fair city, according to the
bureau responsible for promoting tourism in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   So the Phoenix and Valley of the Sun Convention and Visitors
Bureau has decided to change its logo, marketing strategy and name
_ to the Greater Phoenix Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about rebranding the visitors bureau,''
Corporate Communications Director Brent DeRaad said. ``It's about
rebranding Phoenix as a destination.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau unveiled a Phoenix promotional campaign Thursday to
about 250 local politicians, business owners and tourism industry
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   One major change is the elimination of ``Valley of the Sun''
from the bureau's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that outside this metropolitan area, nobody knew what
the Valley of the Sun was,'' DeRaad said.
</P>
<P>
   The name change, which takes effect June 24, is not nearly as
important as the bureau's new marketing strategy, DeRaad said.
</P>
<P>
   In a partnership with Phoenix-based advertising and public
relations firm E.B. Lane, the bureau plans to launch an aggressive
ad campaign designed to change America's perceptions of Phoenix, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is a $5 billion-a-year industry in Phoenix, second only
to high-tech as the Valley's leading moneymaker.
</P>
<P>
   While there hasn't been a decrease in visitors to the area,
DeRaad said the competition is getting tougher and it is better to
take a proactive approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we do all we can to reach all the people
we can,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Radcliffe, the bureau's president and chief executive
officer, said he has always wanted to do more to promote Phoenix
but the funding just wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Phoenix City Council approved a new $5 million
budget that will allow the bureau to undertake a more extensive
campaign than was previously possible.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach will include heavy promotion of golf, hiking
and resort opportunities in the area, DeRaad said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there will be a new logo to replace the familiar but
undistinctive Phoenix bird.
</P>
<P>
   The new symbol will be a luggage tag with ``PHX'' _ the city's
airport code _ stamped across it.
</P>
<P>
   DeRaad said it was designed to help more people think of Phoenix
as a travel destination.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau hired several photographers to take pictures of the
area that would capture the attention and imagination of potential
tourists, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The photos will be used in print advertisements nationwide. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
