<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS FEAST ON ANGELS  
 DAAL MANAGES 8 STRONG INNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buck Showalter occupies a comfort zone the size of a thimble. No
lead is too big, no situation too safe for the Diamondbacks
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But even Showalter was feeling pretty good about his team's
chances late in the game Wednesday night against the Anaheim
Angels. The Diamondbacks
</P>
<P>
   were on their way to a 10-2 victory, ending the Angels'
nine-game winning streak. Pitcher Omar Daal was going eight strong
innings, the longest start of his career. The only remaining
suspense was whether Jay Bell would hit for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks' shortstop got the tough stuff out of the way
early, hitting a triple off starter Ken Hill to score the first of
four second-inning runs, then dunking a Hill pitch into the pool at
Bank One Ballpark in the third for a two-run homer and a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   His next time up, in the fifth, Bell singled. This was after
Travis Lee and Matt Williams hit back-to-back homers off reliever
Pep Harris to make it 8-1. All Bell now needed was a double. Many
of the 40,819 in attendance were aware of that. So was Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something few people have done in their careers,'' said
Bell, who is in his 10th big league season and never has done it.
``To get four hits in a game is difficult in itself. And to get
four hits in that progression is even tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Bell faced Mike Holtz, who has a pretty good
curve ball. That suited Bell's needs. You don't really try to hit a
double, but ``my doubles come when I get something I can hook down
the line,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz threw Bell a curve, a pitch he could handle. He hooked it
down the line.
</P>
<P>
   Just foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all kind of body-languaging (that),'' Showalter said.
``But it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell went on to strike out, but he still had a productive
evening _ three hits, two runs, three RBIs _ and raised his batting
average to .237. That doesn't sound like much, but it's the highest
it's been in nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bell is snapping out of his usual early season doldrums.
Typically, ``April and May have never been great months for me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last several weeks I've felt a lot better. I'm swinging
the bat fairly consistently, and that's been encouraging and fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell and teammates had 15 hits off four Angels pitchers and
continued to have fun at the expense of American League pitching.
On Sunday, the Diamondbacks beat Oakland, 12-4. Then they returned
home Tuesday and lost to Anaheim, 10-8. The 30 runs is the highest
three-game total of the season.
</P>
<P>
   As the Diamondbacks feasted, Daal hung around at the table. A
converted reliever who moved into the rotation when Joel Adamson
went down with a rotator-cuff injury in early May, Daal pitched
longer than he ever had before in his 16th career start.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't just quantity, but quality. The 26-year-old
Venezuelan left-hander, taken with the second pick in the second
round of the expansion draft from Toronto, gave up one earned run
and four hits in the eight innings. He struck out six and walked
none for the first time in a game he had started.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a starter, you know you have to go five, six,
seven, eight inings, so you have to combine your pitches,'' he
said. ``You throw the fastball, the change-up.''
</P>
<P>
   And a slider, which Daal said was his best pitch. He began
working that in with the change-up after sticking mostly with
fastballs and curves early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Daal fell behind Fielder, 3-0, in the seventh with two on and no
outs. He threw a change-up for a strike. Then he threw another
strike and then on 3-2 threw a nasty slider that Fielder grounded
to Bell, who started a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love being a starter,'' Daal said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
