<HEADER>
A5843 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-AZR &LR;      06-12 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE PANEL CHAIRWOMAN SAYS TRAFFIC STOP RACIALLY MOTIVATED
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY RUBEN NAVARRETTE JR. 
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Members of Phoenix's race relations initiative expressed outrage
Wednesday over allegations that their chairwoman suffered a
humiliation they say is common for Black motorists - being detained
by police while driving a new car in a predominantly White
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that someone who is trying to solve this problem
could herself become a victim,'' said Paul Atkinson, a board member
of the ``We're All on the Same Team'' initiative. The project,
which began in November and is sponsored by the city, aims at
promoting racial harmony in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County's top cop angrily denied that his office
unfairly targets minorities and defended the traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fed up with this,'' said Sheriff Joe Arpaio. ``My deputy
stopped a car with a faulty taillight and I think he should get a
commendation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have saved lives. He did exactly what he was supposed
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arpaio said, his ``zero tolerance'' policy concerning
misbehavior by his crew includes racial prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The chairwoman, Connie Worrell, said she was driving near
Litchfield Park on Friday morning when she noticed a sheriff's
patrol car trailing her. After what she estimated was two miles,
she was pulled over and asked for her driver's license. A sheriff's
deputy told her he had stopped her because her car's taillight was
out.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy then asked a series of questions that she considered
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if that was my car,'' Worrell said at a press
conference Wednes day. ``And then he asked me if I lived in the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Worrell does own the 1997 Buick Century she was driving and she
does live within a few miles of the intersection where she was
stopped. Litchfield Park, which is predominantly White, is one of
the most affluent communities in the West Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell said that after she an swered the deputy's questions af
firmatively, the deputy told her that ``everything checked out''
and that she was free to go. Later, she said, she discovered that
the taillight was working properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the feeling that he thought that I didn't belong in that
neighbor hood and that I didn't belong in that car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She claimed that the traffic stop was racially motivated and sug
gested that she would not have been stopped if she were White.
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference, other members of the initiative
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a racial problem and we have to be aware of
it,'' said Tina Robbins, chairwoman of the Human Relations
Commission for the City of Phoenix, which oversees the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had been me, I don't think this would have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The deputy, Christopher Tovar, is a recent addition to the
Maricopa County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the sheriff's office denied that race played a
role in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that this kind of thing doesn't happen,''
said Sgt. Dave Trombi. ``But I am saying that it didn't happen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Worrell said her experience is one that is all too familiar to
many minorities. Because of that, she said, many of them view
encounters with the police with a natural apprehen sion, to which
many Whites cannot relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have in the back of our minds that this could be a
dangerous situation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the commis sion feared that the incident was
indicative of a culture that tolerates, and even encourages,
officers mak ing snap judgments about people who ``fit the
profile'' of likely offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Other city officials were also concerned, but not entirely sur
prised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all susceptible to being stopped when we are perceived
to be out of place,'' said Phoenix Councilman Cody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``And sometimes that just means driving a nice car in a bad
neighbor hood or a not-so-nice car in a nice neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident is a local example of what some argue is a national
phenomenon _ the feeling among minorities that they are routinely
harassed by police.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, in response to com plaints to lawmakers about unfair
traffic stops, the U.S. House passed a bill that would require the
Justice Department to conduct a two-year nationwide study to
determine whether Blacks are being harassed through routine vehicle
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins said the ``We're All on the Same Team'' initiative
includes efforts to increase police sensitivity toward people of
different races. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
