<HEADLINE>
ABOUT 9 IN 10 AT SKY HARBOR MEET JET NOISE STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether you believe your ears or not, quieter jet engines have
become the norm at Sky Harbor International Airport, where nearly
nine out of 10 planes have achieved stricter federal standards for
noise.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next year, all commercial aircraft are to be
equipped with quieter engines, according to a Federal Aviation
Authority mandate. At Sky Harbor, 86 percent of the planes already
meet that standard, airport officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem: Some residents in the airport's flight path
say they aren't hearing the results. Mary Vrizuela, for example,
said she hasn't noticed a hush over her north Tempe neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the noise levels are louder,'' said Vrizuela, a
lifelong resident of the Riverside neighborhood, due east of Sky
Harbor. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``They're just too close to the house. They need to go down the
river bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the adjoining Sunset neighborhood, Arnold Ramirez has a
similar complaint. &UR; Perhaps engines are getting quieter, he said,
but it doesn't do a lot of good if planes fly off course.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``There's times you have to keep the door closed because you
can't hear the TV,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, standing in his front yard, with midday air traffic
passing overhead, Ramirez was able to carry on a conversation
without interruption.
</P>
<P>
   For years, residents of neighborhoods in north Tempe, central
Phoenix and elsewhere have complained about loud jets taking off
and landing at Sky Harbor. Federal officials say they can't
describe exactly how much less noise the new engines make. But they
say the engines definitely are quieter than the old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Now, airport officials say, the challenge is to keep the planes
in their proper flight paths as they land and take off from the
airport.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Planes departing to the east are supposed to follow the Salt
River bed until they reach Price Road, said John Solomon, assistant
aviation director for Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The city's flight-track monitoring system reports that during
the past four months, 95 percent of the flights departing to the
east stayed on course.
</P>
<P>
   To try and boost that figure, airport officials next week will
begin sending notices to pilots who deviate from the flight plan,
Solomon said. The idea is to serve as a reminder that there are
strict rules for approaching and leaving Sky Harbor, whose air
traffic makes it the busiest two-runway airport in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, signs are going up at the runways' eastern ends to
remind pilots of the departure path, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those procedures, coupled with the quieter plane engines, should
actually shrink the area around the airport where noise is most
severe, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Sky Harbor's 86 percent rate puts it ahead of the national rate.
As of the end of 1997, 80 percent of the planes operating in the
U.S. were equipped with the quieter engines, said Mitch Barker, an
FAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Many airlines and engine manufacturers say they'll easily meet
the Dec. 31, 1999, deadline for the new engine-noise requirements.
</P>
<P>
   At America West Airlines, 83 percent of the fleet already meets
the new noise requirements, said Ron Aramini, senior vice president
of operations.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the airline will start retrofitting 14 of its
737-200s with ``hush kits,'' which are designed to make older
engines meet the FAA standards. Four older planes will be retired
before the deadline, Aramini said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the airline's fleet is relatively new and came
equipped with the quieter Stage 3 engines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Engine manufacturer General Electric said the noise requirements
aren't an issue anymore. All new planes are built to that standard,
or higher, said Rick Kennedy, manager of media relations for GE
Aircraft Engines.
</P>
<P>
   Europe may be driving the push to even quieter engines, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have such congestion in those cities,'' he said of
crowded European centers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
