<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PRO BASKETBALL: MALONE HAS LED THIS SERIES NOWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ You wanted it to be a compelling series filled with
drama, passion and big shots at the buzzer. Instead, we have Karl
Malone and his assembled troupe on the world stage playing the
roles of fine actors from a small repertory theater, miles from
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The only intriguing subplot Friday at the United Center is what
will Dennis Rodman wear to the parade? If Michael Jordan and
Scottie Pippen win their sixth title in eight seasons _ and leading
3 games to 1, they are almost a lock _ a great run in modern sports
history will be properly saluted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when the confetti stops raining down at the United Center
around midnight, it will be the yawning climax to one of the
National Basketball Association's most turbulent and troubled
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   Young knuckleheads playing for themselves instead of their
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Miami and New York's warped views of manhood.
</P>
<P>
   A dynasty so bored with watching the peasants flail at one
another, it needed to create internal dissension just to make
winning interesting again. On it went for several months, the
league drowning in egos and excess and the unthinkable: Michael is
really leaving?
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, along came the playoffs and the Jazz, a team of
savvy veterans and a nice mix of young players that shared the ball
and cared about playing defense. They didn't have the highest
payroll nor did they have the most talent, but the sum of all their
parts was good enough to supposedly give the Bulls their stiffest
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   They had a coach who shot from the hip, two future Hall of
Famers, Malone and John Stockton, who had the same type of John
Elway-sentiment working for them as they forever plied their trade
without a title. They also had a lot of fairly anonymous guys who
did not try to call attention to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In a league of booming individualism and merchandising, they
were that interesting concept: a team.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here they are, one game from going home to Salt Lake City.
They have not been humbled so much as humiliated, losing Game 3 by
42 points, blowing uncontested layups and failing to block out for
rebounds in the final minutes of Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think failure is the right word,'' Malone said
Wednesday. He added that he did not think you can measure a
successful career by whether you win a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the team with the two best players in the game is always
unbeatable. Maybe depth and having a great bench mean little when
the game is on the line in the finals. Maybe having the most
accomplished player in the world always beats having two aging
All-Stars.
</P>
<P>
   You get few chances in your career to win the ultimate prize,
and the Jazz has come up so short it's almost as if the players do
not believe they can beat Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Utah Coach Jerry Sloan admitted Thursday he has stayed with
several of his reserves too long, waiting for results that never
came. But give Bulls Coach Phil Jackson credit. He has pushed all
the right buttons after losing Game 1 in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is not merely about matchups and Pippen creating
havoc on defense. When you keep missing five-footers and free
throws, when perhaps the greatest power forward to play the game
does not beg for the ball in the clutch, something else is at work.
</P>
<P>
   Say what you will about Reggie Miller, but he and the Pacers did
not back down. They showed emotion after a big victory and stood up
to the Bulls with the sincere belief that they were just as
deserving Eastern Conference champions before falling in seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Utah? Malone has had the personality of a three-minute egg in
these finals, bowing his head instead of pumping his fist,
answering an authoritative Jordan dunk on one end with an
off-the-mark 15-footer on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has to show some kind of emotion out there,'' said the
reserve center Greg Foster. Forget the good-guy image and all that
stuff. I don't buy into that. Yeah, sure, there is a sportsmanship.
You don't want to go out there and do anything dirty. But you got
to play physical and you've got to play with emotion, especially in
the finals. It seems to me we're playing tentative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz did not have to beat the Bulls to be a good story, but
Utah could have given us a decent series. It would been a nice
cleansing device after all the monotonous courtroom drama, fines
and suspensions that crippled the NBA this season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we get the Bulls in a stampede again. The multinational
conglomerate grows, the small businesses suffer and a July lockout
is looming.
</P>
<P>
   Great game, huh?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
