<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME HOCKEY GAME FROM DISPARATE CAMERA ANGLES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whose hockey would you rather watch? Fox's or CBC's?
The heretic's broadcast or the traditionalist's? While most of us
cannot view the Canadian Broadcasting Company's telecasts, a few
cognoscenti have written or called to say CBC produces hockey games
the way it should be done.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is not being judged because Fox and CBC represent
near-polar opposites in production philosophies. CBC has been
producing ``Hockey Night in Canada'' for nearly 50 years, Fox has
carried hockey for four years and ESPN for nine.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to compare Fox and ESPN, but not in the ways they
broadcast the same game. Fox and CBC show the same game
simultaneously (as in Game 1 of the National Hockey League finals
Tuesday). ESPN and CBC also telecast the same game simultaneously
(like Game 2 Thursday night). But Fox and ESPN never do.
</P>
<P>
   So the decision here was to examine the impact of each network's
differing production styles, using the first period of Game 1 as a
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a few words about their philosophies:
</P>
<P>
   ``In hockey, we need to be spectacular to get interest,'' said
Sandy Grossman, Fox's lead hockey director. ``Hockey on TV doesn't
excite people the way it does when they see it live. So I try to
take risks, but they're usually calculated risks, even if once in a
while I get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Said John Shannon, ``Hockey Night's'' executive producer: ``We
live in a country with a party called the Progressive
Conservatives. We see innovation, but people expect things out of
us that we can't change.''
</P>
<P>
   The easiest measure of the differences between Fox and CBC is to
calculate how much time is spent covering the game from the high
center ice camera, which provides a safe, standard view of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Fox employed that view 50 times in the first period,
for 14 minutes 25 seconds. CBC used it 42 times, but for 18:12,
holding to the view for as long as 1:40. Fox never held it for more
than 48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Fox employs robotic cameras mounted behind the goal and along
the sideboards overlooking the face-off circles, to capture
close-up action in the corners, behind the goal, and to peer from
behind or in front at power plays.
</P>
<P>
   Fox used those cameras 40 times for 5:12 in the period. CBC cut
23 times for 1:19 to what seemed to be a combination of Fox's
angles, to which it has access, and its own hand-held cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent cuts to robotic cameras like Fox's are generally
avoided by CBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't cut, you have more of a chance of seeing the
puck,'' Shannon said. ``That equation works for us. We let the high
camera tell the story. When the whistle blows, we'll get you inside
the game with replays.''
</P>
<P>
   The different styles can provide dramatically different viewing
experiences, such as Detroit's second goal late in the period by
Nicklas Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of a commercial, Fox was primed to cover a face-off
from the robotic camera mounted above the goal. The camera followed
the action for 36 seconds. Grossman never cut away, a potentially
dangerous strategy; the farther the puck moves from the goal, the
harder it is to see it, and the likelier that the puck and shooter
could move out of the camera's frame.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Yzerman's pass to Lindstrom stayed within the frame.
``It was like everybody stepped aside to let me see the goal,''
Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, CBC stuck to its high center ice camera for 36
seconds, cutting to an angle like Fox's only for a replay of
Lidstrom's goal.
</P>
<P>
   A Fox tool used by neither CBC nor ESPN is the FoxTrax cartoon
comet tail that ignites a puck blue or orange depending on shot
speed. In that first period, the puck was illuminated blue 39
times, and orange seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of like the comet streaks,'' said Shannon, uttering
sacrilege to Canadian purists.
</P>
<P>
   On 16 occasions, FoxTrax displayed a white, computer-generated
version of the puck whenever it moved out of camera view along the
sideboards.
</P>
<P>
   You will never see comet tails or computerized pucks on CBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBC does a very solid job, but I've just got a different
attitude toward the way hockey should be covered,'' said Grossman,
who also directs Fox's top football games. ``It's not right or
wrong, it's what you want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Olbermann's Apology
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, ESPN and Keith Olbermann were at war. He left
``Sportscenter'' on a wave of acrimony so bitter it puzzled ESPN,
where he made his name. Thursday, he apologized, not for leaving,
but for being nasty. In a commentary on the SportsFan Radio
Network, he said: ``I'm not backing off from some of my criticisms,
but I am very sorry, and I am publicly apologizing, to my former
colleagues and employers there that it all got messy. For me, a lot
of it was simply this: I had a lot of fun on that show and a big
part of me didn't want to go, and I wasn't mature enough to deal
with it any other way.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
