<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAINIER-AVALANCHE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUNT RAINIER AVALANCHE STRIKES CLIMBERS; 11 ARE RESCUED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A dozen climbers nearly 12,000 feet up Mount Rainier
were caught in an avalanche on Thursday afternoon near a rock
formation called Disappointment Cleaver. Six climbers were able to
stop their falls and were uninjured, while the others, attached to
the same rope, were hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Five of those had been pulled to safety by 8 p.m. and had minor
injuries; the climber who had fallen the farthest, and was most
likely hurt the most, was still out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've accounted for everyone, but that's not
confirmed,'' said Dawn Adams, a spokeswoman for the National Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   The park service said late on Thursday night that one man was
dead, but his identity was not available.
</P>
<P>
   Of the injured climbers, one had a knee injury, two had injured
hands and a couple were suffering from hypothermia, Ms. Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 were being led by Rainier Mountaineering, the only
guiding company that operates on that side of the mountain, she
said. They were descending when the avalanche hit; it was not clear
if they had reached the summit of the 14,410-foot peak, about 60
miles southeast of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   About 2:30 p.m. rangers were notified of the accident by another
climber on the mountain who was using a cellular phone. Rescuers
reached the climbers within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The large rock formation, which splits the Emmons and Ingraham
Glaciers, is at 11,500 feet and is named Disappointment Cleaver
because many people who fail to reach the summit turn around at
that point, said Gus Bush, operations leader for Tacoma Mountain
Rescue, which sent 12 volunteers to assist.
</P>
<P>
   The injured climbers appeared to have gone over an edge and
stopped their fall with their ice axes, said a park spokesman, Dave
Uberuaga, but they were on too steep a slope to return to safety.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue had been hampered by weather, with a low cloud
ceiling that made it difficult to dispatch helicopters to the
mountain. Most of the injured climbers were walking around,
Uberuaga said.
</P>
<P>
   As more rescuers reach the scene, the search would continue on
for people who might be underneath the snow. Search dogs had been
called to the scene, Uberuaga said, adding that he did not know how
many other parties were climbing today.
</P>
<P>
   Spring snow often turns to a slushy consistency, especially in
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat today and the sun coming down on it, probably
triggered it,'' Bush said. Temperatures have recently reached the
upper 70s and lower 80s.
</P>
<P>
   The worst climbing accident on Mount Rainier occurred on June
21, 1981, when 11 people died in an ice fall at 11,000 feet on a
guided climb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
