<HEADER>
A5869 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMYS-LA-LADN     06-12 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAMMY IS SINGING L.A. TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And the Grammy goes to ... Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy Awards will return to the Shrine Auditorium next
year, and the city is negotiating to host the music industry's
biggest night out again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement on the 41st annual ceremony in 1999 is expected
in a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   City officials are angling for an agreement from the National
Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences to bring the televised
ceremony in 2000 to Staples Center in downtown Los Angeles. The
$300 million, 20,000-seat Staples Center should be completed by
October 1999, in time for a New Year's Eve celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Grammys take place the last week of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're continuing to work closely with (NARAS president)
Michael Greene on the Grammys in 2000,'' said Cody Cluff, a member
of the L.A. Sports &AMP; Entertainment Commission, a mayoral appointed
board that tries to attract sports and entertainment events to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff said the city wants a two-year commitment from NARAS to
ensure Los Angeles hosts the ceremony in 2000, but a final decision
isn't expected until after the 1999 event.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles _ home to the majority of the academy's 9,000 voting
members and major record labels _ hosted the Grammys at the
6,300-seat Shrine for seven of the past 13 years but lost the big
show to New York in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 40th annual gala took place Feb. 25 at Radio City
Music Hall. Two weeks before the event, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani became embroiled in a tiff with Greene and said he didn't
care if the Grammys never returned to the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   If the Staples Center works out to everyone's satisfaction, the
awards show may never have to go back to the city that never
sleeps.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan is confident that once the
Grammys are held in the new arena, ``they will never have to leave
Los Angeles again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The venue, which soon will be the new home to the Los Angeles
Kings, Clippers and Lakers sports teams, is located on what was the
North Hall of the Convention Center at 11th Street and Figueroa
Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
