<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEOWN-KEOWN-SFCHRON-GIANTS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NENTH' INNING BELONGS TO GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM KEOWN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
  
  Robb Nen is the closest thing baseball has to an arcade game. He
throws, the numbers flash and everybody gasps. There always have
been questions in Robb Nen's life, and the answer was always the
same: Throw harder.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With an arm like that, who could blame him for relying a little
too much on power? If that was your arm, you'd air it out, too. If
that was your arm, you might charge people money to touch it.
</P>
<P>
   So, if faced with a tough patch in the ninth inning, with
everybody in the building standing there, watching you, what would
you do? Simple: You'd try to blow the circuit on the radar gun.
</P>
<P>
   But the arm, important as it is, obscures many things about Nen.
For one thing, he isn't flashy. Unlike some uncommonly hard
throwers _ Baltimore's Armando Benitez is the most notorious
offender _ Nen doesn't throw the ball and then stare at the numbers
on the scoreboard, hoping to see the magical 100.
</P>
<P>
   The best closer in the National League knows the numbers lie. He
knows it doesn't matter that much. ``If you get to the big leagues,
you can hit a 100 mph fastball,'' Nen says. ``I know not to get too
excited about how hard I'm throwing. I know it can be hit. Believe
me, I've seen it get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't seen it much this year. Nen has 19 saves and a 1.30
ERA. He's getting through the ninth inning _ the ``Nenth'' inning,
as the budding slogan goes _ with machine-like efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to believe, but Nen wasn't a sure thing last year. He
was often a wreck, unable to bend his mind around a walk or a hit.
When bad things happened to good pitches, he couldn't get over it.
He thought too much about his mechanics, and if you've ever seen
him throw you know how utterly mad that could make a person.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Nen was working without a breaking pitch. His slider,
creator of so many of his 53 strikeouts this season, was on a
year-long sabbatical. He doesn't know where it went, only that it
came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're only able to get one pitch over, you're going to get
hit,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It seems everything positive with the Giants eventually funnels
its way back to the manager's office. Nen worked for Jim Leyland in
Florida, and while Leyland's baseball acumen is top-flight, his
nervousness and anxiety often get the best of him. He might not be
the best guy to work for if your livelihood depends on getting his
team out of the tough situations.
</P>
<P>
   So here's what Dusty Baker's calm, confident style has meant to
Nen: ``It's a lot easier to go out there and take the ball when
you've got a guy behind you pulling for you. He makes you want to
say, `Hey, thanks for putting me out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   At his current pace, Nen will throw more than 100 innings this
year. He's never thrown more than 83; he had 74 last year. It isn't
an issue right now. It might become one in August or September, but
for now Nen says the extra workload has helped him. His slider is
nastier and harder than ever, his mechanics are locked in and his
control is so good he's walking certain hitters semi-intentionally,
as he did Tuesday night with Seattle's Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say no, and even harder to say no to Baker. You
can't cash the big checks and shake the hands and do the interviews
and then take the ball only when your world is perfectly aligned.
You do that and teammates start looking at you funny and your
manager starts dropping subtle hints about courage and manhood and
the individual sacrifices that go toward making a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to pitch,'' Nen says, shrugging. ``I get paid a lot
of money to go out there when I'm needed. If he needs me, I'm
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker doesn't harbor the jealousies that reside in the minds of
so many other managers. The career minor-leaguer who rose through
the ranks to get a big-league job often expects too much. He sees
his own job _ all that work and sweat and bus rides _ out there on
the line every time some overpriced prima donna gives up a
game-winning homer.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an incongruous element of Baker's style: He can't
bring himself to let a game go. He can't stand the idea of losing a
game with his best relievers sitting idle.
</P>
<P>
   Most managers draw the line at three straight appearances for
their closer. Baker doesn't have such hard and fast rules. It's
understood that Nen will ask for a day off when he needs one _ he
has done so more than once this season _ but sometimes it's just
too damned hard to tell Baker no.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Nen wants to be out there as much as possible. He wants
to ride this thing out. He's no longer standing out there tensing
every time a runner gets on base. He's no longer looking into the
dugout, trying to read bad thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty doesn't put added pressure on you from the dugout,'' Nen
says. ``I was always trying to be better than I needed to be. On
this team, it's easy to remember there are eight other guys out
there working together to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no fun to go out and pitch like last year, always
wondering what was going to happen. The way things are working this
year makes it a lot more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Nen catches himself. He's a closer, after all. Life goes up and
down with no advance warning. Did he say fun?
</P>
<P>
   `` &LR; More  &LR; fun,'' he says. ``Not easy, just more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
