</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS DEFEAT CAPITALS IN OVERTIME, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Red Wings took a 2 games to 0 lead over the
Washington Capitals in the Stanley Cup finals on Thursday night
with a 5-4 victory in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit won it on a goal by Kris Draper at 15 minutes 24 seconds
of extra time after the Wings' Martin Lapointe stole a pass in the
right corner. He fired the puck across the slot to Draper, who
redirected it past goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   But it is still possible for Detroit to squander its chance at a
second straight championship. After all, the Red Wings squandered
an early lead on Thursday night before coming back.
</P>
<P>
   They could get overconfident as they head to Washington for
Games 3 and 4. Their erratic goaltender, Chris Osgood, could let
them down, as he did on Thursday night. They could suffer one or
more key injuries, as they did on Thursday night when Slava Kozlov,
one of Detroit's best attackers, left the game in the second period
with a leg injury after being hip-checked by Sergei Gonchar, a
Washington defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   And they could lose four games of the next four or five to a
team that finished fourth in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But all of this is not likely. What is more probable is that the
Red Wings will become the first team since the 1992 Pittsburgh
Penguins to repeat as champions, possibly without having to return
to Joe Louis Arena. They put themselves in this position by erasing
two two-goal deficits before prevailing in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   This was a frantic and furious game, with moments of
controversy, sloppy play and brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 4-2 near the midway mark of the third period,
despite two goals by the captain, Steve Yzerman, Detroit rallied
with goals by Lapointe and Doug Brown to tie the score at 4-4 with
just over four minutes remaining. In the final minutes of
regulation, the Wings stormed the net of Kolzig, but he either
stopped their shots or survived them when they whistled wide.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals, who had won their five previous overtime games in
this tournament, got goals from Peter Bondra, Chris Simon, Adam
Oates and Joe Juneau.
</P>
<P>
   The last team to win the cup after losing the first two games of
the championship round was the Montreal Canadiens in 1971 over
Chicago. In the past three seasons, the team winning the first two
games of the finals has gone on to sweep. Detroit did it last
spring over Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in Tuesday night's 2-1 victory, the Red Wings scored
first. This one was by Steve Yzerman, the Detroit captain, who came
into the game with 21 points in the post-season, the most of any
National Hockey League player. Yzerman put his own rebound past
Kolzig at 7 minutes 49 seconds of the first period after Tomas
Holmstrom made the play possible, digging the puck out of the
corner with great effort.
</P>
<P>
   Holmstrom, who came into the game with 16 playoff points, fourth
on the Red Wings, had assisted on both Detroit goals in Game 1.
Getting the other assist on Yzerman's goal was Nicklas Lidstrom,
the defenseman who came into the game with 18 points, second on the
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings outshot the Capitals by 14-8 in the first period and
dominated them. Unlike Game 1, the pace of play didn't stop and go,
with many whistles.
</P>
<P>
   But the wind began blowing in a different direction early in the
second period, and the Capitals scored three consecutive goals on
Osgood to hold a 3-1 lead at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The first was most unusual and will be discussed at length for
some time. It was scored by Bondra at 1:51 on a shot from a sharp
angle in the left-wing circle. He put it past Osgood, who was
standing still, as if he thought play had stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals had cleared the puck from their zone with an
aimless long, hard pass by Jeff Brown. It was the kind of play that
often ends up ruled as icing, as long as the other team touches the
puck behind its own goal line. However, as the puck traveled up the
middle, it was touched by Andrei Nikolishin of Washington, who was
in the neutral zone, between the blue lines. This didn't negate an
offside, but it did take away the possibility of offsides should
the puck be reached first by a Capital.
</P>
<P>
   The puck carried on over the goal line that crosses the pipes of
Osgood's net. And none of his teammates touched the puck. Bondra
got to it first and quickly fired, shocking the Red Wings, who
argued with referee Don Koharski before the faceoff. The gaffe was
another embarrassment for Osgood, an unproven goalie who has given
up three goals this spring on long shots from outside the blue
line, one in each of the previous three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone remained stunned, the Capitals got two more goals
within 10 minutes. Chris Simon made it 2-1 at 6:11 by beating
Osgood on a rebound, high on the glove side. Oates made it 3-1 by
shooting to the same spot after splitting the defense of Larry
Murphy and Lidstrom. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
