</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-JENKINS-SFCHRON-NBAFINALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN IS THE MYTH _ AND PIPPEN'S THE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE JENKINS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; CHICAGO _ They seemed so small and insignificant up there,
answering the media's questions with hollow eyes and a shrug.
Forever in tandem, John Stockton and Karl Malone did their press
conference together, but they could have mailed it in. These were
two superstars who had been stripped of their humor, their patience
and their conviction.
</P>
<P>
   A little earlier, Michael Jordan had been at the podium, talking
about ``taking their heart'' and ``sticking in the knife, then
twisting it a little.'' The words, so tenderly spoken, seemed
chilling in retrospect. That's when you realized that Stockton and
Malone have not really failed. They're just two more faces in the
crowd of Jordan's victims.
</P>
<P>
   It never has mattered whether they're small-town, like Stockton
and Malone,or big-city, like Magic Johnson. Against Jordan and the
city of Chicago, they're all the same. Every series is Rome vs.
Turlock. Magic, Barkley, Drexler, Payton, Malone _ whoever. Makes
no difference. Olajuwon and Shaq would have gone down, too.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday night comes the coronation. Everybody's thinking
Sandy Koufax and Jim Brown just now, the highest standards of
retirement from sports, and if this is Jordan's final bow, he might
play one for the ages, give us something to remember along with the
right-to-left reverse layup against the Lakers, the unconscious
3-point barrage against Portland and the sick-as-a-dog classic
against Utah in last year's Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's all thoroughly understood. Jordan is
basketball's Pele, its Muhammad Ali, a myth among mortals. You
won't accept his retirement until he puts it in writing. You know
Jordan's story by heart because it's part of your soul. Once you
advance to other relevant topics of these NBA Finals, you shoot
right past Stockton and Malone. You go directly to Pippen _ not
only the MVP of this series so far, but also the key to Chicago's
future as an NBA dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tyrannical nature of owner Jerry Reinsdorf and GM
Jerry Krause, this is still a game of options. A champagne-soaked
Phil Jackson could mutter ``bygones'' to Krause, give him a big hug
and come back next year. Jordan has hedged on his feelings so many
times, you can't imagine him actually leaving Chicago. But Pippen
seems thoroughly packed, halfway to the horizon in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   And if he leaves, it's all over. No matter what anyone else
does.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Jordan could have persevered without Pippen.
Such is the magnitude of his power; each teammate becomes 50
percent better. But Jordan is 35 now, incapable of seizing every
single game by the throat. He's been magnificent in this series but
not otherworldly, not as we've seen him before. Imagine Jordan next
fall, at the start of camp, looking at the Longleys and Kerrs and
Harpers and some new free agent in Pippen's slot. Names have been
tossed around: Jayson Williams, Charles Barkley, even Derrick
Coleman. None of them sound right.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else in basketball flows at the power-forward position
like Pippen: canning 3-pointers in bunches, dunking savagely in
traffic, crafting the sweetest long-range bank shots since Julius
Erving, breaking hearts with his offensive rebounds, throwing an
octopus-like defense at the opposition. When they asked Utah coach
Sloan about Dennis Rodman the other night, he gave a disgusted,
deadpan answer. When Pippen's name came up, Sloan called him
``sensational'' and ``terrific'' and generally the answer to any
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jordan nor Jackson has given a hard-and-fast clue about
the future. Pippen seems 100 percent gone, already wandering the
marketplace of free-agent riches. For years he's been the league's
most outrageously underpaid player, and his disgust for Reinsdorf
and Krause stems from pure hatred. ``I'm just trying to get through
one more game, so I can pack that uniform in a trunk,'' he says,
bitterly. ``I don't have any intention of coming back. This is the
last run.''
</P>
<P>
   A few other observations on the eve of a clincher:
</P>
<P>
   _Watching a replay of NBC's Game 4 broadcast, we were struck by
the candor and insights of Isiah Thomas. He's no David Brinkley,
but he flat-out predicted that Rodman would make those two free
throws with 43.8 seconds left, because he knows Rodman has the
stuff of greatness. And he jumped all over Karl Malone, who played
the fourth quarter in a passing and pick-setting haze. ``Right
now,'' said Isiah, ``Karl should be  &LR; demanding  &LR; the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone did nothing of the sort. Everyone else was stepping up;
Howard Eisley, Shandon Anderson, Bryon Russell, even Antoine Carr
and Chris Morris. They all hit big shots. Malone barely attempted
one, let alone put it down.
</P>
<P>
   _You have to laugh at critics suggesting that Rodman's off-court
adventures _ and the fact that he gets away with them _ will set a
dubious standard for impressionable kids. Folks, there's only one
Rodman _ this century and next. Forget the excuses and late-night
cavorting. Start with the rouge, the lipstick, the multicolored
hair. Nobody's ever gone that far. He's beyond ``role model.'' He
comes from Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   _Also kind of amusing: The Utah shuffle of centers: Greg
Ostertag, Greg Foster and, lately, the impossibly earnest Adam
Keefe. Memo to Sloan: New look next year. All of these guys are
horrible.
</P>
<P>
   _No team has come from 3-1 down to win the NBA Finals, and the
Jazz won't reverse the trend. But Bill Russell's Celtics once beat
Wilt Chamberlain's 76ers in that predicament. Larry Bird came back
to beat Erving. It was only the Eastern Conference finals, but in
those days, when real teams roamed the landscape, the task was
infinitely more difficult than anything we've seen in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   _The tributes to Jordan run nonstop. It's too easy to say he's
the greatest of all-time; comments lean more toward the esoteric.
Jayson Williams had a pretty good one the other day. He called
Jordan ``Jesus in tennis shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's scary to think what he might have in store Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
