</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-DICKEY-SFCHRON-A'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM OF A'S IS MISSING THE MARK 
</HEADLINE>
   By GLENN DICKEY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The A's have been getting advice from their media critics
lately. Fortunately for them, they haven't paid attention.
</P>
<P>
   The first bit of advice was to draft J.D. Drew and call the
bluff of Drew's agent, Scott Boras. That would have been wasting a
draft pick because the A's never would have been able to pay what
Drew and Boras are demanding, and they would have been involved in
protracted, rancorous negotiations, which would have sidelined Drew
for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Boras is trying to abolish the baseball draft. In fact, he might
accomplish exactly the opposite because there is sentiment within
baseball to try to negotiate a ``rookie salary cap'' with the
Players Association, as NBA owners have done.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Drew is being used as a pawn, turning down a
$2.6 million bonus and holding out all last season after being
drafted by Philadelphia. The only conclusions to be drawn are that
Drew is (1) stupid; (2) greedy; or (3) both. The A's are better off
without this rockhead.
</P>
<P>
   (Chad Hutchinson has also cost himself money and possibly a
development year by aligning with Boras. He would have been a
first-round pick if he'd had another agent, but clubs don't want to
deal with Boras, understandably, so Hutchinson slipped to the
second round. He won't get the offer he wanted, so he might be
forced to play another season of football, a sport in which he has
no professional future. You'd think a Stanford athlete would be
smarter than that.)
</P>
<P>
   Now the A's are being castigated because they sold Kurt Abbott
to the Colorado Rockies. We're hearing again of their ``bottom-line
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, the A's acquired veterans to shore up their
pitching staff _ Kenny Rogers, Tom Candiotti and Mike Fetters _ and
to keep some positions warm while their prospects were developing.
Mike Blowers, for instance, is playing third base, but Eric Chavez,
hitting well over .300 with 15 homers at Huntsville in Double A,
probably will be there next season.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott was part of that plan, because the A's didn't think
Miguel Tejada was ready. But Abbott had played so poorly at
shortstop that the A's rushed Tejada, injured in the spring, to the
majors as soon as he got healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott is a versatile player and a good hitter. He is valuable
to a contending team, especially one that can afford a $1 million
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Does any of that describe this year's A's team? Of course not.
With or without Abbott, the A's are not going to rise above third
place in their division this year, and he had no part in their
future.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are sticking to their master plan of developing young
players. Though the media emphasis has been on their low
major-league payroll, the more important factor at the moment is
the money they're putting into scouting and the minor-league
system.
</P>
<P>
   This emphasis is not new. The A's had consecutive Rookies of the
Year in Jose Canseco, Mark McGwire and Walt Weiss when the late
Walter Haas owned the team, and most of the players who have been
coming up were signed when Haas still owned the team.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been impressive. Four of the five infielders
are farm products, and Chavez could be the fifth next season. Two
of the three outfielders are recent farm products; Rickey
Henderson, of course, also came out of the A's system _ when
Charles Finley owned the team.
</P>
<P>
   The group has star quality, too, with players like Ben Grieve,
Jason Giambi and Tejada. Ryan Christenson is an outstanding
defensive center fielder.
</P>
<P>
   In their past two drafts, the A's have emphasized pitching,
which will be slower to develop, and they've acquired two
potentially outstanding pitchers in trades, Jimmy Haynes and Blake
Stein.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the A's will come when their young players get to
the arbitration phase of their careers, when their salaries will
jump. Giambi is there now, and the A's made a pre-emptive strike in
April to sign him to an extended contract.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been that the payroll will increase as attendance
does, but I doubt it will work quite that neatly. Fans won't come
out until the team is a contender; the development phase doesn't
interest them. Owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann will have to
boost their payroll to sign the young stars, or the A's will become
another Montreal, developing young players for the richer teams.
</P>
<P>
   If the A's owners allow their team to fall into the Montreal
mode, they'll deserve any criticism they get. But telling them they
should draft J.D. Drew or keep Kurt Abbott at this point makes no
sense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
