<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5911 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVALANCE-RAINIER-SPI &LR;      06-12 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVALANCE-RAINIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE DEAD, FIVE INJURED IN MOUNTAIN AVALANCHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE AND KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGMIRE _ An avalanche rumbled down the eastern side of Mount
Rainier Thursday, striking 12 climbers along the most popular route
to the 14,410-foot summit.
</P>
<P>
   One man was killed, left dangling from a rope until rescuers
were able to reach his body as night fell.
</P>
<P>
   He is believed to have died before sunset, suffering severe
internal injuries, said Maria Gillett, a National Park spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Another man broke a leg, one woman and one man each suffered a
broken hand and another woman suffered from hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 survivors were either rescued or escaped on their own.
But rescuers had to call off their efforts because of darkness as
they tried to reach the man hanging by a rope at about 11,300 feet.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening rangers had gotten close enough to remove the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 8 p.m. Eric Walkinshaw, a spokesman at Mount Rainier
National Park, said the man had been ``moving and conscious,'' but
died sometime later, on the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   The man was at the end of a rope that had included five other
people, said John Krambrink, the park's chief ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers saved the other five, who were probably going to spend
the night on the mountain with rescuers, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries were not considered serious enough for the five to
be sent out by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Of most concern was the woman suffering from severe hypothermia,
which can be life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   A rescue team was digging in for the night out of the line of
avalanches, Krambrink said.
</P>
<P>
   Six climbers escaped uninjured. They stopped their slide by
sticking ice axes in the snow, Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche, which an ice fall may have set off, occurred in
the afternoon as two groups of climbers were coming down from the
mountain summit, Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The slide was most likely a slow-moving, ``point release''
avalanche that loped along at a jog-like pace, said Phil Ohl, an
experienced hiker who has also ascended Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   It was slow-moving but powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The avalanche swept six of them off Disappointment Cleaver,''
Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The man hanging by a rope was at the cleaver, a giant rock
outcropping that separates the Emmons and Ingraham glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   Each group _ made up of six climbers _ was roped together.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of disabled climber Peter Rieke, who is ascending the
mountain by a vehicle he operates with his arms, saw a team of
climbers falling over the cleaver, Krambrink said.
</P>
<P>
   She notified park officials by cellular telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Park rangers, several professional climbing guides and other
mountain rescue crews _ perhaps at least 20 people _ were involved
in rescue attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chinook and Blackhawk helicopters were being used. But
Walkinshaw said a low cloud cover was keeping some helicopters
away.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche occurred on the Camp Muir-Disappointment Cleaver
route, the shortest and most popular of the routes up the mountain.
At least 10,000 people try to climb the mountain every year; about
half succeed, Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of climbers were on the mountain Thursday. Most try to
reach the summit early in the morning and return to Camp Muir by
noon.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems likely that the climbers caught in the avalanche had
reached the summit and were coming down, behind schedule,
Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche site is near that of the worst climbing accident
ever at Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people died on June 11, 1981, when they were caught in a
huge icefall at the 11,000-foot level on the Ingraham Glacier
between Disappointment Cleaver and Gilbraltar Rock.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 93 climbing deaths on the mountain since 1882.
</P>
<P>
   An accident such as Thursday's is somewhat unusual for this time
of year, when attempts to climb the mountain are usually launched
and the avalanche danger is considered low.
</P>
<P>
   ``By June, the snow is relatively stable,'' said Dan Phillips,
an owner and guide for Cascade Alpine Guides, a Bellevue
mountaineering company who had 12 people reach the summit
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts say recent warm temperatures on the mountain
increased the chances for an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Melting snow makes for favorable avalanche conditions because it
changes the stability of the snowpack.
</P>
<P>
   With weekend temperatures in the low 70s _ and more warm weather
Thursday _ parts of Rainier's snowpack had softened significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather on the mountain _ the summit was bathed in sunlight
and the freezing level was at least 11,000 feet Thursday afternoon
_ made the snow sloppy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real concern normally isn't avalanches. It's the soft snow
bridges over crevasses,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for the mountain called for temperatures approaching
40 degrees at Camp Muir, which is at the 10,000-foot level.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
