<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HICKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' NEW OWNER-ELECT NOT TIPPING HIS HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Tom Hicks conducted his first news conference
Thursday as owner-elect of the Texas Rangers. He did not bring Todd
Zeile or Randy Johnson to The Ballpark in Arlington with him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers began a new era when Major League Baseball owners
unanimously approved Hicks' $250 million purchase of the franchise
on Wednesday. However, the early indications are that the new era
will look a lot like the old one, at least for the short term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no trades that were waiting to happen because of
this transaction,'' said Tom Schieffer, who remains as club
president.
</P>
<P>
   That means Zeile, the Florida Marlins third baseman, won't be
coming to town. That was reported by one national publication,
which said the deal would be done as soon as Hicks became owner so
he could approve the bump in payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will Johnson, the disgruntled ace who wants out of
Seattle, be headed here anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, who also owns the Stars, expects to close on the purchase
of the franchise from the group headed by Edward ``Rusty'' Rose on
Tuesday. That's when he officially can begin to make moves.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't, though, envision major changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope not,'' he said. ``We're in first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said he will explore selling the naming rights to the
ballpark. He said he will begin bringing in minority owners,
continue to work on a sports holding company and a TV network for
the Rangers and Stars, and begin developing the land around the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said there will be no immediate bump in payroll, and
no immediate mandate to Schieffer, general manager Doug Melvin and
manager Johnny Oates to do whatever it takes to upgrade the
starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a fan, I've got my own ideas,'' Hicks said. ``But I respect
the organization, so I want to listen to Johnny and Doug and Tom
and get their recommendations. My suspicion is some of their
concerns would be the same as some of the concerns I have. But you
can't just press a button and fix those. The good players you might
want aren't necessarily available. At this point it really is
fine-tuning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks did make sweeping changes when he purchased the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was with the Stars is they were not a healthy
franchise when I bought the team,'' Hicks said. ``We had to make
some immediate changes to restore the fans' trust. We made some
major changes the first year, we had some fine-tuning the second
year, and we may do some fine tuning this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers already are at the ``fine-tuning'' stage. They play
in a state-of-the-art facility before almost 36,000 spectators a
night, and their payroll already is among the top seven in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the fine-tuning includes a move that can
help the first-place Rangers win a championship, Hicks indicated he
won't say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in first place, and we want to stay there,'' Schieffer
said. ``I think he's prepared to do whatever it takes to make that
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he didn't promise to deliver Johnson before the ink
dries on the sales contract, Hicks said the kind of things that are
sure to please Rangers fans still waiting for that first
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take this team to the next level,'' he said.
``That's my commitment to the fans. There are 30 baseball teams,
and only one gets to win the world championship every year. But it
will be our expectation that this franchise should be a team that
each year over the next 10 years will be one of those teams that
plays for a chance to go to the World Series. Over the next 10
years I expect we will have at least one, or more than one, World
Series championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks won't do it the way the Marlins did. Owner H. Wayne
Huizenga spent liberally in the free-agent market before the '97
season, and won the World Series. The club lost money, though, and
began to auction off the best players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very competitive, and I want to win,'' Hicks said. ``But
I'm a businessman. I'm not foolish. I'm not going to win at all
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team in Dallas/Fort Worth realistically shouldn't have the
highest payroll in baseball. It doesn't work from a business
standpoint. There are teams in larger markets that have cable
revenues and other revenues we just don't have. We intend to follow
in the trend that's been set the last few years. We should be a top
five, six, seven, eight, nine payroll, and we can win championships
at that level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
