<HEADER>
A5919 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBAC     06-12 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD DELIVERS  
 YOUNG ANGEL RIPS D-BACKS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever havoc Mark McGwire is planning to wreak when the St.
Louis Cardinals begin a three-game visit to Bank One Ballpark
starting tonight, it probably won't measure up to what Darin Erstad
did to the Diamondbacks the past three days.
</P>
<P>
   For humanity's sake, let us pray it doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad and the Anaheim Angels manhandled pitcher Bob Wolcott,
coming off a brilliant outing in his debut, early and often
Thursday night. The Angels scored five runs in the first inning,
rested, then resumed their assault in the fourth to drive Wolcott
from the game en route to a 10-5 victory at Bank One Ballpark in
front of 41,954.
</P>
<P>
   Acting peeved that the Diamondbacks ended their nine-game
winning streak on Wednesday, the Angels hit a season-high five home
runs, two by Dave Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   If he hadn't already, Erstad this series officially was
registered as a deadly weapon. At 24, he has ventured past the
brink of stardom. He is there. The Diamondbacks tried everything
against the Arizona Fall League alumnus except kryptonite.
</P>
<P>
   Currently playing left field but better as a first baseman,
Erstad had four hits, including a triple and a home run, and drove
in two runs to conclude a remarkable series.
</P>
<P>
   He almost went 5 for 5 for the second time in three games but
lined out to first baseman Travis Lee in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   In the three games against the Diamondbacks, Erstad was 10 for
14 with a double, triple, two homers, four RBI and and six runs
scored. Going back even farther, he is 15 for his past 23. He is
now batting .333 with 15 home runs and 44 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad began the assault on Wolcott by sharply rapping a single.
Then the next hitter, Hollins, who experienced a somewhat scary
diabetic reaction on Tuesday, took a sweet swing and lined a home
run to right field. Two batters, and a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Next was Jim Edmonds, who singled. That brought up Cecil
Fielder, and Wolcott knew better. He walked Fielder. Garret
Anderson fouled out, and it looked as if Wolcott had settled down.
But Matt Walbeck settled into a Wolcott pitch, sending it over the
fence in right for a three-run homer, and the Angels led, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Anaheim outs were well-struck. Norberto Martin lined
out to right for the second out before Wolcott got Gary DiScarcina
to ground out to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like more of the same in the second inning when the
invulnerable Erstad tripled with one out and Hollins walked.
Edmonds, who sat out Wednesday's game because of a sore shoulder
after being hit by a Clint Sodowsky pitch the night before, hit a
bullet to first baseman Travis Lee. The rookie not only gloved the
shot but started a nifty double play that ended the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wolcott held the Angels off in the third inning, but did a silly
thing in the fourth. With two out, he walked pitcher Jason Dickson.
Not only don't you walk the pitcher, not only don't you walk the
pitcher with two outs, you don't walk the pitcher with two outs and
Erstad coming up. Erstad promptly zipped a home run into the
Angels' now-familiar spot in the right field seats.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels led, 7-0, and Wolcott, who pitched eight shutout
innings against Oakland last week after being called up from
Tucson, was gone. Felix Rodriguez came in and gave up a two-run
homer to Anderson in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 9-0, the Diamondbacks got a solo home run from Karim
Garcia in the fifth and a three-run blast from Jay Bell in the
sixth, his second homer in two games and 10th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Andy Fox was hit by a pitch with two out, and
scored on Devon White's double to make the score 9-5. But Greg
Cadaret came in for Dickson and got Travis Lee to fly out to avoid
further damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks loaded the bases with two out in the eighth and
Yamil Benitez pinch-hit, representing the tying run. Bullpen ace
Troy Percival came in for Shigetoshi Hasegawa. Benitez hit his
first career grand slam on Tuesday, and hoped to do it again, or at
least keep the inning going. But he struck out. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0130EDT &QL; 
