<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALICEA STATUS QUESTIONABLE FOR SERIES OPENER WITH ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Reserve infielder Luis Alicea of the Texas
Rangers remains questionable for Friday's game against the Anaheim
Angels at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Alicea, who became the Rangers' second baseman after Mark
McLemore (muscle pull, left hamstring) went on the 15-day disabled
list Sunday, aggravated the area surrounding his left rib cage
during Wednesday's 9-8 loss to the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field.
Alicea departed after the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he did it the other day at home diving for the
pop-up that he didn't catch, and he jammed his elbow into his rib
cage,'' Rangers trainer Danny Wheat said in reference to a
seventh-inning pop-up off the bat of San Diego Padres second
baseman Quilvio Veras during Sunday's 17-8 loss at The Ballpark.
``It hadn't bothered him hitting left-handed, but he felt it
hitting right-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels plan to start right-hander Omar Olivares tonight,
which improves Alicea's chances of playing after receiving
treatment Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother him hitting left-handed,'' Wheat said. ``He
may be fine hitting right-handed by'' tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would be without three of the four middle infielders
on their Opening Day roster should Alicea not be able to play.
Shortstop Kevin Elster (ligament strain, left shoulder) went on the
disabled list June 5, retroactive to June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielders Domingo Cedeno and Scott Sheldon, whom the
Rangers purchased June 5 from Triple-A Oklahoma to replaced Elster,
will likely start at second base and shortstop should Alicea not be
able to play.
`A GREAT SERIES' Right fielder Juan Gonzalez made a prediction
regarding this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a great series,'' Gonzalez said of the Rangers'
four-game set with the Angels. ``It's a battle for the American
League West, and we need a split or go 3-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered Thursday with a three-game lead over the
Angels, whose nine-game winning streak ended Wednesday at the hands
of the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been playing well,'' first baseman Will Clark said.
``We've been playing well, and now we get a chance to play one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels won eight of the 12 games played between the two
during 1997, but this will be their first meeting this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we're the two best teams in the division, so it's
definitely going to be an important series for us,'' designated
hitter Lee Stevens said. ``It's great to play a series that means
something. Guys always talk about taking it to another level, and
you have to do that against teams like New York, Anaheim, Boston
and Cleveland.''
.300 DOESN'T TOP STEVENS' GOALS Stevens, who during 1997 hit .300,
does not view that among his primary objectives this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a goal at all for me,'' said Stevens, who enters
tonight's game hitting .257 with 12 home runs and 34 runs batted
in. ``It became a goal last year toward the end. I'd rather hit
.260 or .270 and drive in more runs than I did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who during 1997 drove in 74 runs, remains on pace for
86 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting .300 once does not make you a .300 hitter in the major
leagues,'' Stevens said. ``Will Clark is a .300 hitter, but it did
prove to me that it can be done _ and I think I can still get hot.
It's not out of reach.'' FARM REPORT
</P>
<P>
   _ Triple-A Oklahoma (Pacific Coast League): The RedHawks (33-24)
beat Memphis, 10-3, Wednesday as left-hander Matt Perisho (7-5)
earned the victory Wednesday by allowing two runs on six hits and
five walks during 51/3 innings. Third baseman Tom Quinlan went
3-for-5 with a home run and five runs batted in. Quinlan leads the
PCL with 53 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   _ Double-A Tulsa (Texas League): The Drillers (27-39) lost both
games of a doubleheader to Shreveport, 4-1 and 3-2. Second baseman
Warren Morris' hitting streak was snapped at 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-A Charlotte (Florida State League): The Rangers (40-21)
beat Clearwater, 9-4, as shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt hit his 13th
home run this season and fifth during the past eight games.
Dransfeldt needs two more to match Charlotte's single-season
record.
</P>
<P>
   _ Class-A Savannah (South Atlantic League): The Sand Gnats
(30-36) lost to Augusta, 8-0, in a game called during the sixth
inning because of rain. Right-hander Aaron Bond allowed eight runs
(seven earned) on 11 hits during 51/3 innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
