<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 01:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5927 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VANPOPPEL-TEX     06-12 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, VAN POPPEL TAKES SLOWER ROUTE TO THE MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
 POPPEL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers have this good-looking pitching prospect down
on the farm. A big guy, standing about 6-foot-5, with a live arm
that can fire a fastball in the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   He has good command of the strike zone, and can throw four
pitches over the plate. Good attitude, too, willing to do whatever
the organization asks.
</P>
<P>
   He's having success at Triple-A Oklahoma, with a 5-2 record and
2.65 earned-run average in his past 10 starts. He leads the Pacific
Coast League in innings pitched (82) and is fourth in strikeouts
(66) and has walked only 22.
</P>
<P>
   He could be first in line to get the call if the Rangers decide
to make a change in their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have to be considered if there was a need for someone, no
doubt about it,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, good-looking prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've heard of him. Goes by the name of Todd Van Poppel.
</P>
<P>
   The same Todd Van Poppel of Arlington who was on the scrap heap
a year ago after being released by his fourth organization in 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a prospect, given that he's having success at the
Triple-A level,'' farm director Reid Nichols said. ``If we need a
starter, it may be a toss-up between him and \RMatt\S Perisho.''
</P>
<P>
   That Van Poppel now is mentioned as a prospect is an indication
of how far he has come in the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real happy with the way I'm throwing the ball,'' Van
Poppel said. ``I know I've still got some things to work on, but
I'm confident right now I could do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little doubt that Van Poppel would do the job when he
left Martin High School in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He was the Kerry Wood of that year, a hard-throwing right-hander
from a local high school _ Wood went to Grand Prairie High _ who
generally was considered the best young pitching prospect in the
land. Van Poppel made his major-league debut with the Oakland
Athletics as a 19-year-old in September 1991, and struck out five
of the first six big-league batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   But he never fulfilled that early promise. He went 20-33 with a
6.22 ERA in 3 1/2 seasons in the majors. Some said an arm injury
sustained in '92 was the problem. Others said he didn't get enough
minor-league seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel himself said information overload was a factor,
especially when he bounced from Oakland to Detroit to the Angels
organization to the Royals organization from August 1996 to April
'97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I basically went through about nine different pitching
coaches,'' he said. ``That doesn't work, because everybody has
their own ideas and everybody has different ways to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   With three strikes against him, last June he received his fourth
in a 10-month period. He was released by the pitching-poor Royals
after going 1-5 with an 8.03 ERA in 11 games at Triple-A Omaha.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers _ his hometown team, the one he dreamed about
pitching for when he was growing up in Arlington _ offered a deal.
But there was a catch. The onetime Boy Wonder had to go back to
Class A and start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel swallowed his pride, and agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the only way for me to get back to the big leagues was
to start at ground zero,'' he said. ``Going back to A ball was
starting from ground zero, and I had no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He went 0-4 with a 4.04 ERA in the Florida State League, and 3-3
with a 5.06 ERA after being moved up to Double-A Tulsa. The numbers
perhaps didn't reflect it, but he was showing progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers coaches helped simplify his pitching motion, and he
was able to work on changing his motion until he felt comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's wanted to say this is your problem, do this, this
is your problem, do that,'' he said. ``I've never had an
opportunity to stay with one thing for a long period of time where
I can get comfortable with it and find my own rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers bullpen coach Larry Hardy did a little tinkering after
the season, and Van Poppel went to Venezuela to pitch winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   He went 3-2 with a 2.27 ERA, fifth in the league. He is
repeating that success at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   And, once again is a prospect, albeit an older one. The former
teen-age sensation is 26. Older, but not too old.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, pitchers don't develop until they're 25 or
26,'' Melvin said. ``You hear scouts talk about him. They say he's
pitching a lot better than they had seen him previously.''
</P>
<P>
   Older, but not in any particular hurry to make it back to the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the farthest thing from my mind,'' he said. ``I just
want to keep improving. That's my main focus. I don't want to rush
back up there until I'm 100 percent ready. When I go back up I want
to be ready and be able to stay for a long time. I know I've got
the ability to go up there and pitch well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers must be sure he is ready to stay for a long time
before making the call. Van Poppel is out of minor-league options,
so he can't be sent back to the minors without going through
waivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That weighs into it, whether your need is for short term or
long term,'' Melvin said. ``You couldn't bring him up for one start
and then send him back out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Poppel is willing to wait. When you're a prospect you
know your time _ even if it's your second time _ is coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0143EDT &QL; 
