<SLUG> BC-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN-SATIONAL RACE IN WORKS IN NL WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Enough about the Los Angeles Dodgers. The Fox bunch and their
underachieving warriors have made enough headlines for one season.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to focus on the National League West race and the
Dodgers have had absolutely nothing to do with that. They may
eventually get their act together, but right now it's between the
San Francisco Giants and the San Diego Padres, and, starting
tonight, those two play each other seven times in the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams are everything the Dodgers aren't: tough, gritty
and resourceful, a bunch of hard-nosed ballplayers who get the most
out of their talent. Just look at their third basemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants may have one of the best players in the game in Barry
Bonds, but their character comes from Bill Mueller, a slow-footed
third baseman with no power who simply hits around .300, makes the
routine play in the field and goes all-out for nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are all about Ken Caminiti, who earned National
League most valuable player honors in 1996 by hitting .326 with 40
homers and 130 runs batted in despite playing much of the second
half with a torn rotator cuff that needed surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres were leading the division for the first two months
until the Giants caught them with an 11-game winning streak. But
injuries have also hurt; Caminiti, Tony Gwynn and Wally Joyner have
missed significant time because of nagging injuries. Gwynn has a
strained calf muscle and is not expected to play this weekend
against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get everybody healthy at the same time,'' Padres
manager Bruce Bochy said.
</P>
<P>
   Three players have saved them. Starter Andy Ashby is 8-4 with a
2.21 earned-run average, closer Trevor Hoffman (18-for-18 on saves
with a 1.63 ERA) has been outstanding and Greg Vaughn has revived
his deteriorating career with 22 home runs and 56 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres could use some help. Like everybody else, they could
use another starting pitcher, plus a catcher and a shortstop. There
was talk of them taking a shot at obtaining Mike Piazza or trading
for a shortstop, either Royce Clayton or Edgar Renteria.
</P>
<P>
   Owner John Moores and general manager Kevin Towers are likely to
do everything they can, because this is a critical year. San Diego
voters will decide in November on funding for a new stadium, and a
division championship would do wonders for the Padres' cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are getting a new downtown stadium in 2000, and
everything points to this franchise becoming a powerhouse by then,
especially if the Athletics finally get out of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants aren't doing too badly right now, mainly because
Dusty Baker remains one of the best managers in the game and Brian
Sabean has proven to be a resourceful, astute general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Last off-season, the Giants couldn't afford to re-sign
free-agent shortstop Jose Vizcaino, who defected to the Dodgers.
Instead, they settled on an inexpensive platoon of Rich Aurilia and
Rey Sanchez, two ex-Rangers minor leaguers who are both hitting
above .300 and playing good defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sabean also improved his bullpen by getting Robb Nen (19 saves,
1.30 ERA) from Florida and Steve Reed (2-0, 1.23 ERA) from the
Rockies, and strengthened his bench by getting Charlie Hayes, who
is hitting .311 as a backup at third and first base. But his best
acquisition was 39-year-old pitcher Orel Hershiser, who went 5-0 in
May and is 6-4 with a 3.19 ERA for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants also benefit from another ex-Rangers player: center
fielder Darryl Hamilton. Not only is he hitting .295, but his
upbeat leadership creates a positive atmosphere in the clubhouse
and provides a counter-balance for the moody Bonds. It's no
coincidence Hamilton has played for division winners in each of his
last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Giants nor the Padres have the Dodgers' immense
talent. But they're the ones who are in a pennant race, and the
next 10 days should be fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
