<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN OVERTIME, WINGS EDGE CLOSER TO TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Their goalie made another critical mistake to allow
another shabby goal that threw his team into a tailspin. Because of
this, they squandered an early lead and fell behind by two goals _
not once but twice. They lost an important attacker with an injury
midway through the game. So what would the Detroit Red Wings do for
the rest of Game 2 of the Stanley Cup finals last night in Joe
Louis Arena?
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by two with less than 12 minutes remaining, the
defending champions resumed their whirlwind attack, scoring two
goals to send the game into overtime. And then they triggered a
long, loud dance of delirium in their sweltering home rink by
winning it at 15 minutes 24 seconds of the extra period on a goal
by Kris Draper.
</P>
<P>
   A checking specialist without a goal in this tournament, Draper
jumped on the ice from the bench, charged unchecked to the net,
took a long pass across the slot from Martin Lapointe and put the
puck behind goalie Olaf Kolzig for a 5-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize it was going to be an overtime goal in the
Stanley Cup finals, but I'll take it,'' Draper said of his first
playoff goal this spring. ``This is what you dream about. I just
one-timed it into the open net. You can tell by my smile how
excited I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The result gave the Red Wings a 2-0 lead in the
four-of-seven-game championship series that will resume on Saturday
night with Game 3 in Washington. They swept the Philadelphia Flyers
last season. Every championship round since 1994 has ended in the
minimum four games.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman, the Detroit captain, scored two of the Detroit
goals, one while shorthanded. Lapointe and Doug Brown scored in the
third period to tie it. Peter Bondra, Chris Simon, Adam Oates and
Joe Juneau scored for the Capitals, who had won five consecutive
overtime games in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   They might have short-circuited a Detroit comeback in the middle
of the third period had Esa Tikkanen finished a scoring chance.
Shortly after Lapointe cut the Washington lead to 4-3, Tikkanen
found himself alone in front of Detroit's Chris Osgood, with the
goalie sprawled out of position. But Tikkanen shot the puck wide,
and Detroit resumed its comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wilson, the Washington coach, said, ``We had the win right
on Esa Tikkanen's stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Tikkanen said: ``I had the open net like, three, four seconds.
Next time, I have to make sure that it is in.''
</P>
<P>
   In the overtime, Detroit had a 12-3 edge in shots on goal. For
the game, the Detroit advantage was 60-33. The Wings began the game
with their dazzling, swirling attack _ skating, passing, shooting
with grace and energy _ and seemed en route to a rout until Osgood
let down his guard on a confusing play at 1:51 of the second
period. When Washington's Jeff Brown cleared the puck from his end
of the ice, it appeared at first that icing would be called against
the Capitals. But no Red Wing got to the puck as it crossed the
Detroit goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Because Washington's Andrei Nikolishin had touched the puck as
it passed through the neutral zone, an off-sides possibility no
longer held. So Peter Bondra raced to the puck and fired it behind
Osgood from a bad angle in the left-wing faceoff circle. In the
three previous rounds, Osgood has given up three goals on long
shots from outside his blue line, one against each opponent. This
time, his gaffe was to relax and to forget about defending his goal
when no whistle sounded to stop play.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from this, the Wings then gave up two goals in the next
10 minutes to Simon and Oates, making it 3-1. Right after this,
Osgood tried to throw a puck at Washington's Craig Berube, after a
whistle. He missed and, instead, hit the referee, Don Koharski, and
got an unsportsmanlike conduct penalty for his efforts. On a team
full of unflappable veterans, Osgood is an inconsistent and
undependable weak link.
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman got one back while shorthanded early in the third
period, but Juneau made it 4-2 less than a minute later, on the
same power play, at 7:05. At this point, the Red Wings were being
taunted by Simon and other Capitals toughies. Instead of getting
mad, the Wings got even.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate Tikkanen missed the open net,'' Yzerman
said. ``That was the break we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   They surged without Slava Kozlov, one of their top attackers,
who left the game in the second period with a charley horse in his
leg after being checked hard and legally by Sergei Gonchar. His
condition is uncertain for the next game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
