<HEADER>
A5935 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX     06-12 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODZILLA'S MONTSROUS DEFENSE LEAVES JAZZ WITH SOUR NOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Deal with it America: Rodzilla is having his Jazz and
eating it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Between absurd antics off the court, freaky forward Dennis
Rodman's aggravating defense, boundless energy and timely scoring
has put a headlock on counterpart Karl Malone and helped give his
Chicago Bulls a stranglehold on their sixth NBA Championship in
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't discount what Dennis is doing,'' Michael Jordan
said. ``There's no understanding him. But as long as he does his
job on the court like this, it's really hard to argue with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely in part to Rodman becoming a most-valuable-player
candidate by going postal on The Mailman, this Finals rematch has
become a mismatch and the Bulls' ``Last Dance'' is likely down to
its final step. Chicago, 33-4 in playoff games at the United
Center, takes a 3-1 lead and the opportunity to clinch its Repeat
Three-Peat into Friday's Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   No team has recovered from a 3-1 deficit to win a Finals series.
With Jordan playing a full season, no team has beaten the Bulls in
a series since they lost to the Detroit Pistons in the 1990 Eastern
Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is, in fact, the end, it's been a great run,'' Bulls
coach Phil Jackson said. ``And Dennis, in his own way, has been a
huge part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman _ who debuted a Godzilla-green-and-black hairdo in Game 1
_ has had a particularly newsworthy series off the court.
</P>
<P>
   He has jetted off to gamble in Las Vegas and wrestle in Detroit,
gotten sued by a casino dealer and a woman in Las Vegas for sexual
harassment, fined by the NBA and dissed by Jazz coach Jerry Sloan,
missed a practice, not sat on the bench for tip-offs and called
Malone ``awkward'' and ``average.''
</P>
<P>
   A night after skipping practice to wrestle in Detroit, Rodman
had drinks with Illinois state Sen. William Marovitz at a Rush
Street tavern before heading to his notorious Crobar Club all-night
lair.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a civil, intellectual side to Dennis that people
rarely get to see,'' Marovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Rodman told his agent, Dwight Manley, to pay for the
funeral of James Byrd, the African-American dragged to his death
near Jasper in East Texas. Three white men have been charged with
murder in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll cost around $20,000 to do it right,'' Manley said. ``But
Dennis was moved by the incident and he wants to do what he can to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodman: ``My heart goes out to the family and it's a shame
when something like this happens.''
</P>
<P>
   He's hung around wrestler Hulk Hogan and Pearl Jam lead singer
Eddie Vedder, and hung all over Malone. The Jazz star, who figured
to average at least 30 points per game against Chicago's inferior
interior, grows hair in his television commercial. In his Finals
nightmare, however, he is growing horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The refs have let me play,'' Rodman said. ``When they do that,
Karl Malone is not effective against me at all. I have too much
heart for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, more popular in Utah than the Osmonds or The Mormon
Tabernacle Choir, has disappeared in key stretches under the
despised Rodman's defensive blanket. Since Malone knocked down late
jumpers to force overtime in Game 1, Rodzilla has destroyed him
and, in turn, Utah's offense. In Game 2, Malone was 0-of-4 in the
second half. In Game 3, he went 2-of-5 the last 39 minutes. In
Wednesday's Game 4, he went 1-of-3 in the final 12 minutes, with
the only basket a meaningless jumper in the final 10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have to prove anything to anybody in this country or
this business,'' Rodman said when asked if his substance has
legitimized his style.
</P>
<P>
   During the regular season, Malone averaged 27 points and the
Jazz 101. In this series, he's been held to 20 per game and his
team to a Finals record-low 78.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know,'' said Malone, who has scored more than
23 points in only one of 10 Finals games against Chicago. ``You
can't pinpoint it. I have chances to score against Dennis. But you
guys are the experts now, so why do you even ask those questions?''
</P>
<P>
   So exactly how has the synchronized, seasoned Jazz been
discombobulated by a head-butting, crotch-kicking, tattooed Worm?
</P>
<P>
   Giving up three inches and 50 pounds to the NBA's second-best
player, the 37-year-old Rodman has successfully climbed inside
Malone's head as well as onto his body. Using a defensive tenacity
developed in the South Oak Cliff neighborhood in Dallas, improved
at tiny Southeastern Oklahoma State and polished to perfection
during a 12-year career that has seen him bedevil offensive stars
from Larry Bird to David Robinson, Rodman has refused to surrender
low-post position to Malone.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Rodman called a heady timeout during a loose-ball
scramble, convincing veteran referee Bill Oakes that his team had
the ball when replays showed a tie possession. A minute before, he
had drilled a foul-line jumper to tie the score and jump-start
Chicago's rally to a five-point victory.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4, he outfought Malone for a loose ball and drew a foul
on the series' most important play. Instead of giving Utah the ball
and a chance to tie the score in the final minute, Rodman earned _
and calmly sank despite being only a 55 percent shooter _ two free
throws to put the Bulls in position to smell Utah's blood and
clearly see their finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's precisely why we put up with Dennis,'' reserve guard
Steve Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Rodman's deep impact has come from neutralizing Malone
and disrupting Utah's pet pick-and-roll. After Malone has hit open
jumpers early in the past two games, Rodman has entered and played
him much more closely and physically than starter Luc Longley.
Rodman's quickness and desire allows him to step out and
momentarily impede Jazz point guard John Stockton, then scurry back
to alter or even altogether prevent a Malone jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's his technique or just his attitude about
playing in crucial situations,'' Jordan said. ``Whatever, you've
got to commend him. Just don't try to dissect him as an individual,
if he is in fact an individual. When time is of the essence, he's
ready to play basketball. He excels in adversity. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Rodman could have only 11 points _ along with 39 rebounds
and 0 technical fouls _ and be such a dominating factor. Given
Malone's anticipated dominance but subsequent disappearance, Rodman
will receive NBA Finals MVP votes should he continue his trend
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He also likely will receive the fifth NBA Championship ring of
his 12-year career for his contributions to a Bulls dynasty that
featured the game's greatest and weirdest players: Air and Airhead.
Where Rodman, who has jewelry in his navel, ears and nose, will
choose to wear the ring remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to back himself into a corner and come out of it with
shining laurels,'' said Jackson. ``He got himself in situation
where he had to prove himself, then he does it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
