<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      06-12 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON'S JOB WITH RODMAN SHEER GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA playoffs have provided more bewilderment than
pork-and-beans underwear:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)For the second year in a row, the regular-season
powerhouse Sonics failed in the second round, playing less
competitively than in the previous season against Houston, despite
having what former coach George Karl believed to be his best, most
enjoyable team, which was free of Shawn Kemp's distractions.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The team that eliminated the Sonics, the Los Angeles
Lakers, appeared to be the greatest new dynasty since the Mings
dominated the old Eastern Conference. Then the Lakers were swept in
the Western finals.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)The team that swept the Lakers, the Utah Jazz, is on the
verge of elimination by Friday's fifth game in the NBA Finals
against the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of this sequence five weeks ago was about the
same as an exchange of Valentines between Karl and Sonic president
Wally Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in terms of the improbable, these outcomes pale compared
with what Bulls coach Phil Jackson has achieved with Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman's brilliant contribution in Game 4 _ superb defense on
Karl Malone, spirit-crushing offensive rebounding and five of six
free throws _ was the unexpected stiletto slicing Utah's title
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman prepared for this moment by cavorting with steroid freaks
in Detroit, joining in a pro rasslin' promotion that was heavy on
dollies, cigars and nationally televised imbecilism.
</P>
<P>
   This adventure was preceded by a Las Vegas sojourn after Game 1
in Salt Lake City that included heavy drinking, gambling and
all-night lasciviousness. The week also was spiced with a lawsuit
by a Vegas craps dealer who claimed that Rodman in October rubbed
the guy's head, stomach and crotch while shooting dice.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet from any animal-protection society on assaults on
farm livestock.
</P>
<P>
   While the history of pro sports is littered with stories of
prodigious bacchanalia by jocks convinced of the myth of their
invulnerability, almost none has included an athlete who was a) 37;
b) an unrepentant irritant to teammates and coaches by breaking
nearly every team rule, and c) eager to have writers and cameras
record his silliness.
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent international circus he has created is normally
anathema to every principle of team sports. Yet somehow Jackson has
kept Rodman and his phony, self-indulgent chaos from compromising
the title pursuit in a season when the Bulls appeared to be their
most vulnerable against an astute challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN analyst and longtime NBA coach Jack Ramsay said it the
other night for many in the league who have shaken their heads
until dizzy:
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Jackson is the only coach in the NBA who could have
handled Rodman. I know I couldn't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker needs no more reason than that to keep open the Sonic
coaching search that will otherwise go to Paul Westphal, all along
the likeliest candidate since Karl began self-destructing before
the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Sonics are about to pursue impending free
agent Rodman, although they could do worse. But the Sonics have
their own curious talent in Gary Payton, the only part remaining
from the Karl-Kemp-Payton triumvirate that has kept the Sonics
among the elites.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has advocated for Paul Silas, someone he knows and trusts
and is fairly certain he could manipulate as he did Karl, who
virtually quit trying to get Payton to conform to team rules. As
with Rodman, Payton almost always delivered on the court, which
gave him leverage to skip practice and skirt other
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Westphal is something of an unknown, although
his indulgence of another my-way-or-the-highway superstar, Charles
Barkley, helped lead to his demise as coach of the Suns. Teammates
such as Kevin Johnson and A.C. Green grew to resent the double
standard for Barkley by Westphal, much as some Sonics resented the
same with Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Managing the double standard is the toughest coaching trick in
the NBA. The treatment expected by top players often is divisive to
the point of destruction. Coaches like Ramsay, Jerry Sloan and most
others in the league have little or no capacity to indulge profound
deviants like Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was aided by Michael Jordan, whose overwhelming
psychological dominance of the Bulls has helped moderate Rodman's
impact. Yet Jackson had to set the attitude and atmosphere so
Jordan could accept Rodman's knotheadedness in order to extract his
valued virtues.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's his attributes derived from Zen or zookeeping,
Jackson has been marvelous in keeping the Bulls directed despite
their disparate personalities and the internal and external forces
arrayed against their continued success.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson says he will not be back with the Bulls, and will take
time off before deciding his future, which could include no
coaching for a year.
</P>
<P>
   It behooves Walker to keep the Sonic door open until Jackson
closes it. Westphal isn't going anywhere _ which could be the Sonic
fate if Payton isn't better directed.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight year, Jackson put a porcupine in a baby's
crib. No cries have been heard. Here is a nanny for the ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALSNOTES-TEX     06-12 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC URGES JORDAN TO CONTINUE PLAYING
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Magic Johnson was one of the first to see up close how
dominant the Chicago Bulls were going to be in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In '91, his Los Angeles Lakers won Game 1 of the NBA Finals in
Chicago before losing the next four games as the Bulls won the
first of their five championships.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bulls on the verge of their sixth title and Michael
Jordan apparently on the verge of retirement, Johnson is as sad as
anyone. How emotional? Asked what he thought of Jordan's departure
earlier this week, Johnson _ obviously practicing for his new talk
show _ offered this unique and insightful filibuster, complete with
a plea for His Airness not to hang up his Nikes:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about ultimate excellence and when you talk
about beautiful basketball, the way the game is supposed to be
played, the way Mr. Naismith drew it up to be played, you're
talking about Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason I'm disappointed at the young people in this
league, and, yes, some veterans, is because they look at Michael
and they don't understand Michael. They see ``the greatest'' but
they don't know why he is so great. They miss the point. They don't
remember or realize that when he first came into the league, he was
a star whose game was confined to driving to the basket, dunking on
everybody and making other fantastic moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you'd try to block his dunk, he'd learn to kill you some
other way. So over the years, people missed out on the fact that he
worked hard to add the jump shot, the 3-point basket, the post-up
moves, the passing and the great defense and team leadership. It
was like he'd say, `OK, now that y'all have seen this part of my
game and adapted a little to it, I'm going to add this to it, too.
Now what y'all going to do?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then later on he'd say, `Now I think I'd post up and shoot the
fade-away J a little.' Other times he'd say, `I think I'll beat you
with my passing this time.' But you see so many guys in this league
who don't understand the progression of his greatness. They don't
realize that he evolved into what he is now through hard work and
tremendous dedication. That's why I love Michael. He worked to
become the complete player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not his last year because I think he has two good
years left. But I don't think Michael knows what he really wants to
do afterward. And it may take him another year just to decide what
he'll do after basketball. Remember, he is already the chairman of
the board with his own shoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Michael _ we need you one more year. Michael, please don't
go. The league needs you and these players sure need you. And I
need you, too, as a fan because I'll tell you the truth: I don't
know how much basketball I'd even want to watch without Michael.
You see _ Michael, Phil Jackson and Pat Riley and very few others
understand the real beauty of five guys playing the game together.
They understand how to compete and get guys going. So I can't see
the league without Michael because we are not ready and there's
nobody ready to take his place.'' RUNNING OF THE BULLS
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls have won their past eight Finals home games. ... Most
of the talk Thursday surrounded closing the series out at home and
avoiding a return trip to Salt Lake City. ``I have no business in
Utah at all,'' Dennis Rodman said. ``Those people are a different
breed.'' Added Jordan, ``If this happens to be our last dance, why
not finish it in front of our fans?'' ALL THAT JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   In a series in which it has been difficult to differentiate
between good defense and bad offense, the Jazz has not surpassed 88
points and are averaging a Finals record-low 78 per game. ... One
reason for that is its 3-point shooting. The Jazz, the fifth-best
team from long range during the regular season, has made only 10 of
45 (22 percent) in the series and missed 13 of 15 in Game 4. ...
Utah's concentration Thursday focused on the series not being over.
``I have both arms and legs and I plan to fight them again
\RFriday\S,'' coach Jerry Sloan said. Added point guard John
Stockton, ``We'll cross that bridge when we come to it. I'm still
kicking, we're still kicking.'' JORDAN WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, facing what will definitely be his last game of
the season at the United Center, said he'll try to approach the
game unemotionally. ``It's going to be hard for me to not think
it's my last game,'' he admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Other than again ruling out a role as player-coach, Jordan shed
no light on his plans for next season. He did however, say he
believes teammate Scottie Pippen has left a crack in the door to
return to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the opportunity to go out on top,'' Pippen
said. ``But I don't have any intention of coming back here next
season.'' Inside the numbers Closer than it looks: Three of the
games have been decided by five or fewer points and in the final 45
seconds. Chicago has won seven of the 10 Finals games against Utah
the past two years, five by five of fewer points. HE SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic because we don't want it to end, yet we can't wait
until it's over.'' _ Bulls guard Steve Kerr, on his team being one
victory away from a championship and a probable breakup. THE FINALS
SCENE
</P>
<P>
   With the possibility that Friday's game will be the last for
Jordan and the Bulls' dynasty, tickets are up to as much as $10,000
for two courtside seats. Film critic Gene Siskel, talk-show host
Jerry Springer, actor Bill Murray, religious leader Louis Farrakhan
and singers Donny Osmond, Eddie Vedder and Brooks &AMP; Dunn are
expected to have good seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
