<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5954 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-SPI &LR;      06-12 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDY CITY PREPARES FOR MEMORABLE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The anticipation is almost a ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's police force is primed to work overtime Friday night.
Local stores are being depleted of plywood stock to cover windows
against potential looters. And some Chicago Bulls players _
especially Michael Jordan _ already are being asked to send a
party-but-don't-tear-up-this-town message to their fans.
</P>
<P>
   No, a tornado is not about to hit outside the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   And no, the NBA Finals are not over.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls own a 3-1 lead over the Utah Jazz, and the history
of never having lost a playoff series with that kind of advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If the five-time NBA champion Bulls finish off Utah in Friday
night's Game 5, or do so later, there will be something different
about what has become a routine party: Chicago will celebrate
winning a sixth ring, but it will come with an emotional end to an
eight-year dynasty because the existing team probably will break
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard for me not to think of it in that way,''
Jordan said Thursday. ``I'm going to try to think of it in a way
that we're finishing off the season. From the beginning we wanted
to play and win our last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to get this thing done here, in Chicago. . . . If
this happens to be the last dance, why not do it in front of our
fans?''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter the outcome of the Finals, the end is near for
this roster of the Bulls, and they know it.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen _ a free agent as of July 1 _ reiterated Thursday
that he has no desire to play with the Bulls past this season.
Jordan does not want to retire. But he is prepared to do so, unlike
when he walked off the court to play baseball after winning the NBA
championship in 1993. Without Pippen, Jordan knows he will be
better off selling cologne and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's Bulls coach Phil Jackson, who said at the start of
this season ``that wild horses couldn't bring me back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This (championship) would mean more to us, especially to
myself and Michael and Phil,'' Pippen said. ``We'd love to have the
opportunity to go out on top. That's been the drive for us the
whole season. We want to prove that we're still the greatest and
we're still champions.''
</P>
<P>
   A sixth championship in eight years makes a compelling argument
for the Bulls being considered the greatest team ever. Only Houston
also won championships this decade, in 1994 and 1995, the two years
Jordan spent in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is an era when the NBA competition is diluted
because of expansion, the individual talent of the league is
arguably at its highest level. The game will lose Jordan, perhaps
the greatest basketball player the game has ever known. It also
means Jordan will loosen his stranglehold on the NBA trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't miss it (the NBA) at all, as much as you may
think,'' Jordan said. ``I've got enough memories to suffice and
overcome that.''
</P>
<P>
   Every Bulls opponent in the NBA Finals has sat like a guy in the
wrong seat during a high-stakes card game. This time, the Jazz are
holding the bad hands while watching Jordan, Pippen and Dennis
Rodman trump them for the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's John Stockton is being rendered invisible. His partner
Karl Malone is groping to come up big. The Jazz won a league-best
62 games this season. But Utah has been hemmed in in this series by
the Bulls' defense and desire to win.
</P>
<P>
   There was a suggestion in the Utah locker room after Game 4
Wednesday night that Stockton and Malone were playing scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel they're scared,'' Pippen said. ``I feel like we
have them off balance from a defensive standpoint. We're sending so
many different defensive schemes at them, they don't know what to
expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls will be remembered for their success, sideshow-like
settings and ability to sell out arenas from Chicago to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Their success has sparked jealousy, as well as adulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans want to see a new champion because they're tired of
Bulls, Bulls, Bulls,'' Jazz veteran Antoine Carr said. ``It's time
for some fresh blood and new faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fan support picked up after we knocked out the Lakers.
Even their fans wished us good luck. They said the Bulls are a
great team, but their soap opera has gotten old. But we can't worry
about that. We've got to win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah must win three straight games to dethrone the Bulls. The
last time the Bulls dropped three straight games was February 1995
before Jordan returned. With Jordan, you would have to go back to
the start of the 1990-91 season when the Bulls lost their first
three games. That was also the Bulls' first title season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls went on to claim three straight titles. They are
poised for another three-peat. Only the 1960s Boston Celtic teams
dominated a decade like the Bulls have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess everybody is talking about our age and the limitations
in terms of what we can do,'' Jordan said. ``That's a great
challenge. I love that. I'm pretty sure we're proving to a lot of
people that they're not great predictors or that they don't know
that much about the game. I think that's fun _ to see people eat
crow.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the Bulls will force everyone to digest the dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
