</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER'S BACK, BUT MARINERS LOSE TO A'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mariner right fielder Jay Buhner waited more
than two months to be in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   He walked to home plate in the eighth inning Thursday night with
two runners on base, two outs and his team three runs behind.
</P>
<P>
   A home run might have been too much to ask, but that didn't keep
the Mariners from dreaming. They envisioned a game-tying homer from
the slugger who hit 40 or more in each of the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to come back from knee surgery?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought he was going to do it,'' M's hitting coach
Jesse Barfield said. ``He had some good cuts, but ... ''
</P>
<P>
   The potential storybook finish had a sour ending. Buhner
grounded out against Oakland's Billy Taylor, and the M's returned
to the American League West basement with a 5-2 loss to the
Athletics before 7,838 fans _ the smallest crowd to watch Seattle
this season.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the triumphant return the Mariners expected. You can
blame Oakland starter Mike Oquist and Taylor for that.
</P>
<P>
   Oquist, winning his fourth straight, made key pitches when he
had to, kept the ball down and left three runners in scoring
position as the Mariners went 0-for-8 with runners on third or
second bases.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle finally broke through in the eighth when Joey Cora
singled with one out and Ken Griffey Jr. slugged his league-leading
26th homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throwing a fastball over the plate to Junior is death,''
Oquist said.
</P>
<P>
   Losing pitcher Jeff Fassero kept everything the A's hit in the
park, but two walks and a wild pitch in the fourth inning led to
the first runs of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walks weren't as damaging as the wild pitch,'' said
Fassero, now 5-3. ``If I don't throw the wild pitch, I might get a
double play and get out of the inning with only one or no runs
being scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Oquist, meanwhile, didn't encounter serious trouble until the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey provided part of it with a 400-plus foot blast to
left-center. And after David Segui and Edgar Martinez singled off
reliever Mike Fetters, Buhner was in position to take care of the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Jay one or two more days and he will hit some of the
pitches (he saw in the eighth inning) out of the ballpark,''
Barfield said. ``He doesn't quite trust his hands yet, but a few
more (batting practice sessions) will level out his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner took treatment on his knee after the game and wasn't
available for comment, but he told team trainer Rick Griffin that
he felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey said he, too, thought Buhner would go deep in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been a good start for the ballclub and for
Jay,'' said Griffey, who shaved off his mustache and goatee
yesterday morning to symbolize a fresh start. ``He had some good
swings. He battled.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's teammates trumpeted his return with a T-shirt that
read: ``Unleash the Dogs'' on the front and ``The Bone is Back'' on
the back.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, sidelined since April 6 with an injured left knee that
required surgery on April 28, went 1-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good for being out so long,'' manager Lou Piniella
said. ``If he keeps that same approach, he will help us out and
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   And, boy, do the M's need help.
</P>
<P>
   On June 11 last season, their Big Three starters _ Randy
Johnson, Jamie Moyer and Fassero _ were a combined 20-5 and Seattle
was in first place by one-half game.
</P>
<P>
   As of today, they are 13-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have pitched that poorly,'' Fassero said,
``but it seems like when we pitch well, we don't get enough run
support. It's something you have to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes prove costly. Walks score. And key hits are too rare.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' 58th error of the season helped the A's score two
runs in the fifth inning and expand their lead to four runs.
Shortstop Alex Rodriguez misfired after fielding Mike Macfarlane's
routine grounder leading off the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Segui, the M's first baseman, attempted to keep his right foot
on the bag as he leaned toward home plate to grab Rodriguez's
slighly errant throw but couldn't quite pull it off. Ryan
Christenson bunted Macfarlane into scoring position and Rickey
Henderson rapped a first-pitch double past third baseman Russ
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Not satisfied with two bases, Henderson quickly stole third, his
24th theft of the season. He was there only long enough to trot
home on Scott Spiezio's single to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero has been victimized the most this season by defensive
leaks. The fifth inning unearned run was the 11th scored off the
left-hander. In all, Seattle opponents have scored 28 unearned runs
this season. Only Kansas City and the Chicago White Sox have
surrendered more freebies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do about unearned runs,'' he said.
``But it kind of epitomizes our season.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without Buhner in the lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 0224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
