A5992 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-SFCHR     06-12 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SWITCHES TACTICS ON CAMPAIGN REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here is how confused the House's debate over
campaign finance reform has become: Republicans brought to the
floor a reform measure they oppose Thursday, while Democrats voted
to kill the legislation, which they not only support but wrote.
</P>
<P>
   After that was settled, GOP leaders _ who had previously tried
to cut off all debate _ embarked on a procedure that could require
lawmakers to cast ballots on at least 258 amendments to 11 separate
reform measures.
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings have grown so convoluted that one lawmaker felt
compelled to reach for words from television's ``X-Files'' to
explain her opponents' legislative tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obfuscate, inveigle and connive,'' Rep. Ellen Tauscher,
D-Walnut Creek, Calif., said of the GOP strategy, using words far
simpler than the rules under which the House will take up the
measures.
</P>
<P>
   As the House began what is expected to be a summer filled with
public posturing and private wrangling on the issue, partisans on
both sides conceded that the prospects of any meaningful reform
being enacted this year are close to zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legislation this year? Oh, the chances are very, very slim,''
said Rep. Sam Farr, D-Carmel, Calif., author of one of the main
proposals. ``This debate is designed to be confusing. It's designed
to go on and on and on. It's designed to never have anyone coalesce
around any one bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders concede that they are opposed to changing the
system, in which they are raising more money than their Democratic
opponents. Yet their attempts to stifle debate earlier this year
backfired when a handful of GOP rebels threatened to join forces
with Democrats and force a vote on one of the most comprehensive
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Republican leaders have apparently settled on a new
strategy to defeat reform _ debate it to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is another way for them to kill campaign finance
reform,'' said Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco. ``They had to be
dragged kicking and screaming into this debate in the first place.
The fact is, they like the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that limits on campaign donations amount to an
intrusion on free speech and are insisting that any overhaul of
campaign finance laws include restrictions on union contributions,
which go mostly to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And they insist that the parliamentary procedure they have
settled on is the only way to let everyone have their say, while at
the same time fulfilling a pledge to conduct a full and open
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine the outcry if they had restricted the debate,'' said
Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., who has offered his own proposal to
prohibit donations from political action committees, unions and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders have agreed to permit the 11 competing measures to
come to the House floor and have employed a legislative gambit
known as ``Queen of the Hill,'' which has left even veteran
lawmakers scratching their heads. The rule says that if more than
one measure receives a majority vote, the one with the highest vote
total prevails.
</P>
<P>
   The leading proposal is a companion to a stalled Senate bill
written by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Russell Feingold, D-Wis.
The House version, introduced by Reps. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.,
and Marty Meehan, D-Mass., would ban unlimited contributions to
political parties, known as ``soft money,'' and create restrictions
on independent groups that advertise during campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   However, under the Queen of the Hill rule, if a competing
proposal _ for example, an uncontroversial measure to simply create
a commission to study campaign rules _ receives more votes, it
would trump the Shays-Meehan bill.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, GOP leaders have called for an open debate that
would allow hundreds of amendments (258 have been filed so far) to
the main proposals, without setting aside a continuous chunk of
time to address them.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., called the rules a
``travesty'' that amounted to a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take until 2025 to finish the bill at this rate,''
Gephardt told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their strategy, Republicans plan to introduce a
series of amendments intended to highlight alleged fund-raising
misconduct by the White House and embarrass Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   That's what occurred Thursday, when Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, brought to the floor a proposed constitutional amendment
that would empower Congress to restrict campaign contributions and
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay opposes the amendment, which was submitted more than a
year ago by Gephardt and other Democrats. DeLay brought it to the
floor to highlight potential First Amendment issues involved in
campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a debate about free speech,'' said DeLay, who voted
against the measure even though he brought it to the floor. ``This
is a debate about the Bill of Rights and the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the proposed amendment was not ready for passage
and needed the scrutiny of a committee, something that Republicans
have thus far refused to permit.
</P>
<P>
   The House rejected the amendment by a 345-to-29 vote in what may
be the first in a long summer of votes.
</P>
<P>
   There are some optimistic supporters in the House who believe
that a majority may coalesce around the Shays-Meehan bill, or a
bipartisan measure advanced by Tauscher and other freshman members.
However, prospects for passage in the Senate are far bleaker, where
it will require at least eight opponents to change their positions
in order to break an almost-certain filibuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
