<SLUG> BC-AVALANCE-RAINIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE DEAD, FIVE INJURED IN MOUNTAIN AVALANCHE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE AND KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGMIRE _ An avalanche rumbled down the eastern side of Mount
Rainier Thursday, striking 12 climbers, including one man who died
after dangling from a rope over the edge of an icy cliff.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who was not identified, survived the avalanche but
suffered severe internal injuries in the fall and then was soaked
by icy, melting snow water for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   Five other climbers sharing the rope with the dead man were
rescued but suffered injuries ranging from broken bones to
hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   At least two were carried on litters and lowered on ropes down
the mountain to an area called Ingraham Flats, about 400 feet down
the mountain from the avalanche site at 11,400 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers said it was a miracle the five climbers were not more
seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be considered lucky. They are very fortunate to
have been rescued considering what happened,'' said David Uberuaga,
a spokesman for the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   One survivor, Doug Wagoner, told reporters as he was carried off
the mountain with a broken leg, ``We were just going up the slope
and ice started coming down about the size of a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Another climber, Kent Swanson, told reporters as he was rolled
into the emergency room at Tacoma General Hospital: ``The rescue
group did a fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   The rescue helicopter landed at Ingraham Flats and took the five
injured and the dead climber to Madigan Army Hospital in Pierce
County last night.
</P>
<P>
   One survivor was admitted to Madigan, while the rest were sent
to area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The climbers who were not injured were reported to be at Camp
Muir, where climbers gather before trudging up popular routes to
the summit of the 14,411-foot mountain, Uberuaga said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened about 2:30 p.m. as two climbing groups
were descending after reaching the summit. The climbers, who were
from several states, were being escorted by Rainier Mountaineering
Inc., a mountain guide service, Uberuaga said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known what caused the avalanche but it
may have been set off by a large block of snow and ice that broke
loose without warning, other climbers said.
</P>
<P>
   The slide was most likely a ``point release'' avalanche that
loped along at a jog-like pace, said Phil Ohl, an experienced hiker
who has also ascended Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   But it was powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of this Hollywood movie-type picture of an avalanche,
picture a two- or three-foot section of snow slowly sloughing down
the mountain, pulling in everything in its path,'' Ohl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions were probably pretty good for an avalanche
because it was so warm.'' The man who died on the climbing rope was
at the edge of Disappointment Cleaver, a giant rock outcropping
that separates the Emmons and Ingraham glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called that because it's usually the spot where most
people who can't make it to the top of the mountain turn back,''
said Gus Bush, operations leader for Tacoma Mountain Rescue, which
was sending a dozen volunteer rescuers to the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Each group, made up of six climbers, was roped together when the
avalanche struck. The wife of disabled climber Peter Rieke, who is
ascending the mountain by a vehicle he operates with his arms, saw
a team of climbers falling over the cleaver and called park
officials on her cell phone, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(She) came out of the tent and saw two teams of hikers being
swept away,'' a park spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Park rangers, several professional climbing guides and other
mountain rescue crews _ perhaps at least 20 people _ were involved
in rescue attempts.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening rangers had gotten close enough to see the
climber who eventually died, but they couldn't immediately reach
him.
</P>
<P>
   Just before 8 p.m. Eric Walkinshaw, a spokesman at Mount Rainier
National Park, said: ``He's moving and conscious. A ranger is now
close enough to observe him. But he's in need of help.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the survivors, rescuers were most concerned with a woman
who suffered from severe hypothermia, which can be
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   A rescue team was digging in for the night out of the line of
avalanches, said John Krambrink, the park's chief ranger.
</P>
<P>
   The six climbers who escaped injuries were able to stop their
slide by sticking ice axes in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chinook and Blackhawk helicopters were being used. But
Walkinshaw said low cloud cover was keeping some helicopters away.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche occurred on the Camp Muir-Disappointment Cleaver
route, the shortest and most popular of the routes up the mountain.
At least 10,000 people try to climb the mountain every year; about
half succeed, Walkinshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of climbers were on the mountain Thursday. Most try to
reach the summit early in the morning and return to Camp Muir by
noon.
</P>
<P>
   Rainier is the state's most challenging, and perhaps the most
dangerous, peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one sense, it's always considered avalanche danger on Mount
Rainier. It's an active glacier. It's always moving. The weather
changes all the time. It's really crumbly rotten rock up there,''
said Mount Rainier National Park spokeswoman Maria Gillett.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche site is near that of the worst climbing accident
ever at Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people died on June 11, 1981, when they were caught in a
huge icefall at the 11,000-foot level on Ingraham Glacier between
Disappointment Cleaver and Gilbraltar Rock.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 93 climbing deaths on the mountain since 1882.
</P>
<P>
   An accident such as Thursday's is somewhat unusual for this time
of year, when attempts to climb the mountain are usually launched
and the avalanche danger is considered low.
</P>
<P>
   ``By June, the snow is relatively stable,'' said Dan Phillips,
an owner and guide for Cascade Alpine Guides, a Bellevue
mountaineering company who had 12 people reach the summit
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But other experts say recent warm temperatures on the mountain
increased the chances for an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Melting snow makes for favorable avalanche conditions because it
changes the stability of the snow-
</P>
<P>
   pack.
</P>
<P>
   With weekend temperatures in the low 70s _ and more warm weather
Thursday _ parts of Rainier's snowpack had softened significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Warm weather on the mountain _ the summit was bathed in sunlight
and the freezing level was at least 11,000 feet Thursday afternoon
_ made the snow sloppy, Phillips
</P>
<P>
   said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real concern normally isn't avalanches. It's the soft snow
bridges over crevasses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for the mountain called for temperatures approaching
40 degrees at Camp Muir, which is at the 10,000-foot level.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
