r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCEANS-CONFERENCE-SFC     06-12 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEANS-CONFERENCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO EXTEND BAN ON DRILLING UNTIL 2012 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BARNUM and MICHAEL MCCABE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    MONTEREY, Calif. _ President Clinton is expected to cap a
historic conference on the state of the world's oceans Friday by
announcing a 10-year extension of the ban on new offshore oil
drilling, a federal official said Thursday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The planned executive order would be part of a package of
initiatives, including $24 million in increased research funding
that the Clinton administration hopes will boost protection of
oceans and marine life in federal waters.
</P>
<P>
   The existing oil drilling ban, imposed in 1990 by President
Bush, expires in two years, although an Interior Department
five-year management plan would extend that to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The president's order, to be delivered in a keynote address in a
park at the foot of Cannery Row, would extend the ban until 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The president's decision drew varied reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be pleased if the White House extends the
moratorium, period,'' said David Sandretti, spokesman for Sen.
Barbara Boxer, D-Calif. ``However, we're not going to be satisfied
until we get an act of Congress for a permanent ban.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for California Gov. Pete Wilson, who called
Wednesday for Clinton to sign a permanent ban on drilling off the
coast of California, said the president has not gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor believes there should be a permanent ban,'' said
Ron Low, Wilson's deputy press secretary. ``We are puzzled and
dismayed that the president doesn't share this view. The governor
has a long commitment to preserving California's majestic coast,
and it's disappointing that the Clinton administration does not
share it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who came to fog-shrouded Monterey for
the first National Ocean Conference, declined earlier Thursday to
confirm reports of the president's order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned, the president will have announcements (Friday) on
that issue,'' Gore said. ``This is going to be looked back upon ...
as a sea change in our attitude to protecting and saving the
oceans.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the Clinton administration's commitment, Gore
brought gifts of new funds and initiatives to increase research and
improve protections of coastal waters.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a Coast Guard pier with sea lions barking in the
background, Gore said the administration would commit $24 million
over three years to map the ocean floor and to improve tracking of
the climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oceans are too often a neglected scientific resource,'' Gore
said after being given a tour of the Western Flyer, a local marine
research vessel. ``We know more about the surface of the moon than
about the ocean floor.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration also will spend $6 million to restore
damaged coral reefs, step up attempts to reduce coastal pollution
and declassify sensitive Navy information that could prove useful
for ocean conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who had called for far more sweeping
measures, were clearly underwhelmed by the funding announcements,
but the initiatives are likely to be only the first installment of
federal action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a good start,'' said Julie Packard, executive
director of the Monterey Bay Aquarium. ``But the funding is very
minimal, compared to what is needed. It won't go far _ ocean
science is very expensive. What is certainly missing is an
overarching strategy such as long-term funding resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Dreyfus, a spokeswoman for the World Wildlife Fund, said:
``The specific steps announced by the vice president fall short of
what is required to deal effectively with an environmental crisis
of global proportions. To paraphrase a famous hamburger commercial:
`Where's the fish?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have proposed establishing an Ocean
Conservation Investment Fund, using royalties from offshore oil
leases. They say the fund should add a minimum of $200 million a
year to the nation's ocean research budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson administration, which is miffed at not being given a
larger role in the conference, also scoffed at the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   State Resources Secretary Douglas Wheeler said that although
more research spending is needed, the administration's initiatives
do not address the need for better federal management of ocean
resources. ``There is nothing that would even approach a larger
mandate here, and that's what everyone was looking for,'' said
Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gore, the Clinton administration will undertake the
following initiatives:
</P>
<P>
   -- Commit $12 million over three years to map the ocean floor
within U.S. coastal waters, which extend 200 miles off the
continent.
</P>
<P>
   -- Commit an additional $12 million over three years to place
hundreds of monitoring buoys in the North Atlantic and North
Pacific to be used to improve research on the world climate and
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sign an executive order to expand research and protection of
coral reefs, which are sometimes described as the marine equivalent
of rain forests because they support a stunning diversity of marine
life.
</P>
<P>
   -- As part of the order, the administration is proposing an
additional $6 million through 2002 to complete restoration of 18
damaged reefs in the Atlantic, the Gulf of Mexico and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   -- Release previously classified data and technology that was
used by the Navy to hunt submarines. This information can be used
to track whale migrations, improve climate predictions and detect
illegal fishing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Start a new web site (www.epa.gov/ost/beaches) to alert the
public of beach closings, similar to one that is being developed to
alert the public of fish advisories.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving at midmorning, Gore and Rep. Sam Farr,
D-Monterey, who conceived of the conference, were given a tour of
the Western Flyer, a 117-foot high-tech research ship operated by
the Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   While aboard the vessel, Gore was in his element, taking the
reins of a remote-control underwater vehicle on the floor of
Monterey Bay and guiding it as it drilled holes, collected samples
and took videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real thrill for me,'' Gore said. He was accompanied
on the tour by Julie Packard, and Marcia McNutt, director of the
Monterey Bay Aquarium Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writers Robert B. Gunnison and Marc Sandalow
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
