<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-PEASANTS-COX- &UR; -     06-12 1365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEASANTS-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV13 
 &HT;     CHINA'S PEASANTS CLIMBING OUT OF POVERTY
 &HT;     With PEASANTS-MAO-$ADV13.
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server and are available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     NOTE: For purposes of a locator map, the village Guo Yuan is
about 20 miles northwest of the city of Changsha.
 &HT;     For Use Saturday, June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUO YUAN, China _ Gazing down over green rice shoots that
forever have been the Chinese peasant's sweaty handhold on life,
Zhan Hanjuin couldn't dismiss the broad grin that had played across
his face all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard for him still to believe he was standing atop his
own new, two-story house with a fish pond on the roof, a Volkswagen
Santana in the garage, and a six-foot-high air-conditioner in the
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   Just 25 years ago, Zhan and his new bride shared a house with
his parents, two brothers and their families. They worked on a
collective farm and didn't have electricity, much less electronics
like the television and stereo ornamenting Zhan's year-old house.
</P>
<P>
   Zhan, 48, is a top-of-the-line ``peasant.''
</P>
<P>
   But millions of Chinese families have pulled themselves out of
exhausting poverty since land reform began handing them control of
China's rice paddies and grain fields in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peasants can arrange their work and living schedule on their
own,'' he told a visitor. ``In their spare time they have the
freedom to look for opportunities to earn a lot of money. It's up
to them to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   About 50 million mostly rural Chinese remain overwhelmed by the
deepest poverty, according to government statistics, but that is
dramatically less than the 250 million registered in 1978. Back
then the Zhan family was among the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The grain farmers of northern China accrue less from reform than
farmers in this south-central rice bowl, where tiny plots of land
give lucrative yields. Yet peasants throughout the country are
seeing lifestyle improvements at the very time urban workers are
suffering from growing unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   An early summer ride through Hunan Province shows what that
means in the rice paddies patchworking the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliantly verdant landscape is flecked everywhere with
two-story homes faced in the same white, brick-sized tiles that
cover Zhan's house, with the same smoked-glass windows battling the
sun. Some tiled roofs make orange-red splashes on the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Many are additions built onto older adobe or concrete slab
buildings, and many are still under construction. The majority of
peasants in Hunan Province, population 62 million, look to be
living in spacious, if rather basic, comfort.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain this agriculture success story, when the other
giant of collective farms _ Russia _ has been almost totally unable
to retreat from the communist style of communal farm work and
continues to experience a draining slump in output?
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is that China eliminated collectives and
divided the land among families. Chinese farmers don't have full
ownership, since they cannot sell, develop or lease the land
allotted them. But the crops are theirs to keep or sell. And they
expect their grandchildren to farm the same fields.
</P>
<P>
   Except at a few experimental sites, Russia did not divide its
farm land. So farmers still assume no individual responsibility for
their work, in either success or failure.
</P>
<P>
   Differences in the nature of soil and crops make independent
farming more difficult in Russia, and so far the nation and its
farmers have been unwilling even to attempt broad-based farming
outside the village-centered group.
</P>
<P>
   In Hunan Province today, 70 percent of the farmers no longer
live in poverty, said Wu Heqing, a province spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today peasants spend 25 percent of the time they used to
(spend) farming the land,'' said Wu. ``Now they have incentives to
work, because they get everything they grow. And now they can
engage in business in their free time. That used to be
prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the collective system, peasants were paid according to the
number of days they spent in the fields. Working slowly was to
their advantage _ the more days worked, the more compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Now farmers get in and out of the fields at full tilt, so they
can make money working in small factories or running their own
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Guo Yuan Township Vehicle and Parts Factory molded itself
seamlessly to the changes. Employing 43 people when it started
producing small tools and plows in 1971, the enterprise now has 700
to 1,400 workers hammering together bright blue farm trucks
increasingly in demand as agriculture prospers.
</P>
<P>
   The primitive factory lacks conveyors or safety gear, but plant
director Jiang Yitian said the factory rolls out about 10,000
trucks a year. He finds the cyclical nature of farm work compatible
with the up-and-down demand for trucks. Both require part-time
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we have orders they come to work. Then when they're free
they go back to the land,'' Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
   His factory hands earn an average of 500 yuan ($60) a month,
about as much as low-end urban workers. This usually supplements a
family's farm income.
</P>
<P>
   It is China's dense, double-crop cultivation of rice that has
enabled farmers here to prosper even with land allotments that seem
incredibly small.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt road leading back to Huang Jianxia's place, for
example, passes a rice paddy so tiny that it looks scarcely big
enough to feed his family a year of dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with three of those small fields called mu -- each mu is
about one-sixth of an acre -- Huang manages harvests totalling more
than four tons of rice every year. Adding the income from the pigs
his wife raises, this becomes another ``peasant'' family that no
longer qualifies for the moniker.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we got only 600 kilograms (1,320 pounds) of rice
for each mu we farmed,'' said Huang, 45.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of seed has improved, machines are available for
land preparation, and chemical fertilizer has replaced the human
and pig manure that farmers used to spread on the paddies, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it took five or six months to work the fields. Now it
only takes two months,'' Huang said. ``The skills have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Huang also is a carpenter, though he said selling his tables and
doors and beds is harder these days since neighbors buy so cheaply
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his family income averages 1,500 to 1,660 yuan a month,
or about $180 to $200. Though low by Western standards, 1,500 yuan
a month is an enviable wage in China.
</P>
<P>
   Recent government statistics show that even in the biggest
cities only 8 percent of the workers earn 1,500 yuan or more.
Workers at Delphi China's Shanghai factory, for example, average
1,000 yuan a month.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials described Huang's household as about median
income for province farmers, and this tallied with observations
during a two-day visit to the Hunan countryside.
</P>
<P>
   His quarters aren't as lavish as those of the Zhan family, but
Huang, his wife and 16-year-old son enjoy a comfortably large house
with spare furniture, a television, refrigerator, ceiling fan and
perhaps most importantly an electric pump that carries well water
to an indoor standpipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't hold much hope to buy a car, but we do hope to have
more household appliances. And more money in the bank,'' Huang
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhan has done better for two reasons: he has six mu of land in
rice and orchards, double Huang's holdings, and off-season he does
lucrative construction work. His family's income averages 2,500 to
4,200 yuan a month. At the upper end, that equal $508 or nearly
$6,100 annually.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy money. Zhan and his wife do all the farm work now
that their two grown sons no longer live at home, but the farmer
said he still has plenty of energy to do construction engineering
in the city between crop demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sure that if the world will stay peaceful,'' Zhan said,
``the life of peasants will become better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
