<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6144 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BRIDES-COX- &UR; -$     06-12 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BRIDES-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV13 
 &HT;     USING INTERNET, VIDEO AND CATALOGS, RUSSIAN WOMEN SEEK `MR.
RIGHT' IN AMERICA
 &HT;     With photos placed in the International and Lifestyle folders
on the Cox Server and are available from the New York Times News
Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Saturday, June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRASNOYARSK, Russia _ In the world of lonely hearts, Tatyana
Denoshova's lament rings loud and often.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to meet a real man here. Good men are already
married and if they are not already married, they are no good,''
said the dark-eyed Denoshova, 25, on her inability to find a
suitable mate.
</P>
<P>
   But in her case, the desperation resonates with urgency.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital nurse in this depressed Siberia city 2,000 miles east
of Moscow, Denoshova earns only $40 a month and hasn't been paid
since March. She says the men she meets are similarly strapped, or
sodden with vodka, or both.
</P>
<P>
   She and thousands of other Russian women have turned to catalog,
video and Internet-based matchmaking services seeking husbands _
preferably American or European men who will love them and take
them far away from the dead-end of today's Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic turmoil following the collapse of the Soviet
Union in 1991 and the ever-expanding World Wide Web have conspired
to make matchmaking a multimillion-dollar industry. Scores of
services also offer similar introductions to women from Asia and
Latin America as potential brides to men in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my clients would prefer an American husband. Times in
our country are very bad and everyone wants a better life,'' said
Nina Kuzmena, a marriage broker in Krasnoyarsk who charges her
clients $20 each to shoot a video in her small living room.
</P>
<P>
   In cosmopolitan Moscow, the same rationale prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Elena Vishnitsev, 31, an accomplished artist, has been searching
for three years through an Internet-based service, Vetsa-Fortune,
which catalogs hundreds of young women searching for husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The agency charges $40 per female client for an unlimited
listing in their published catalog and on the Internet. Men are
charged $50 for each introduction they request after scrutinizing
the catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Vishnitsev's quest hasn't been easy. She divorced her Russian
husband in 1993 when his drinking became chronic. Trying to meet
men in bars or other public places is potentially dangerous and
demeaning, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the introductions via the service, while safer, also can be
degrading.
</P>
<P>
   Often, American and Russian services team up to hold Moscow
``socials'' where hordes of women gather at a Moscow disco to meet
a handful of American men who have paid thousands of dollars each
for a tour package to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competition among women in my age group is very
difficult,'' she said. ``These meetings are terribly unpleasant.
You feel like you are for sale at a slave market.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says, the agency ``gives hope to lonely women'' and
has brought her a number of near misses, though she's still looking
for Mr. Right.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search via Yahoo.com produced 65 separate companies
offering to match American men and Russian women, listing thousands
of personal ads and color photos of women. Some offer a search
function, allowing men to specify age-range, hair color and height
_ and even body measurements _ among the galaxy of women being
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the listings from Russia is Olga, a 23-year-old
English teacher from the northern city of Severodvinsk: ``I seek an
American or Canadian who is well-educated, thoughtful, and
passionate. I want to find someone special from another part of the
world who might value the importance of family values.''
</P>
<P>
   The marriage agencies stress that Russian women are eager
homemakers, yet also well-educated and poised. The sales pitch
plays on a sad Russian reality of soaring alcoholism and
unemployment rates among men, often leaving women as the sole
providers and caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They possess a strength of spirit combined with a delicate
femininity that sets them apart from the so-called `liberated'
women in the West,'' says the Web ad for the Svetlana Agency of St.
Petersburg, Russia's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be surprised to know that these highly educated and
charming women have housekeeping and cooking as their favorite
hobbies,'' says another company, European Introductions.
</P>
<P>
   Another is more blunt: ``Russian ladies are not destroyed by
feminism,'' a headline blares in one ad.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of this generally unregulated international industry
prompted the U.S. Congress to pass a 1996 law that requires
matchmaking companies to give information about marriage fraud,
legal residency and domestic violence to women they recruit or risk
fines up to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which estimated that 2,000 to 3,500 American
men find wives through such agencies every year, was prompted in
part by news accounts of cases of immigration fraud and sexual
offenses associated with such matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a small number of fraudulent, abusive, or
sex-oriented marriages that occur. These are, of course, good
stories, and as such are the only stories that end up in the papers
usually,'' said Beau Brummel, an American software developer who
found his wife Tania through a matchmaking service in St.
Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Brummel, 31, who was living in rural North Carolina, said he
chose to search Russia for a wife because ``it was easier to review
the Russian women interested in Western men from my computer, and
correspond with them, than it was to be out all night dealing with
drunks and such, here in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the women he met tended to be ``barely high-school
educated, usually overweight, and had no interest in or idea about
any of the things that were part of my professional life or
personal hobbies.''
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, he ordered the addresses of 10 Russian women
and sent them letters. Only three wrote back, one of them his
wife-to-be. They corresponded for about four months until he
traveled to Russia and spent a few weeks with her and her family.
</P>
<P>
   They were married last August and now live in Portland, Oregon,
with her eight-year-old daughter from a previous marriage, his
six-year-old son and their baby Jessica, born in April.
</P>
<P>
   However, such success stories are few given the large numbers of
Russian women looking for mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're dealing with very lonely people in this business who
have unrealistic expectations. American men come here and want a
Barbie doll, a slim blonde without children and a woman much, much
younger than they are. Some younger Russian women want the jackpot,
too. A man who's going to sweep them away to the mansion in
America,'' said Nina Rubasheva, a co-owner of the Vesta-Fortune
agency in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   But in faraway Krasnoyarsk, a music teacher and divorced mother
of one, Ludmilla Karielina, 37, is realistic. She has braced
herself for a life alone, despite the hopes she has placed in a
matchmaking service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to be alone,'' she said, ``than to be with a man
who is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
