 &HT;     AIR FORCE ONE DIPLOMACY
 &HT;     With CLINTON-DEVELOPING-$ADV14.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ``INTERNATIONAL'' TRAVELS OF PRESIDENT CLINTON
</P>
<P>
   -- In March, Clinton visited six African nations _ Ghana,
Uganda, Rwanda, South Africa, Botswana and Senegal _ on a journey
scripted to spotlight the promise and hope lying before a
long-tortured continent whose ties to the United States are rooted
in the savage beginnings of American slavery.
</P>
<P>
   -- In April, he visited Santiago, Chile, for a summit of the
leaders of the 34 countries in the Western Hemisphere _ all except
Cuba _ that have embraced open markets and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   -- Still planned, though under review in the wake of the nuclear
tests, is an autumn trip to India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   -- Clinton also plans to visit Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, for the
November summit of the leaders of the nations making up the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
</P>
<P>
   -- And on June 24, Clinton leaves for a state visit to China,
the first such visit by a sitting American president since
Beijing's bloody crackdown nine years ago on democracy advocates
near Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
