<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING THE END OF THE FIRST GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday June 18)  
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We brought chips to the end-of-the-year party at my son's
elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   First-graders, apparently, are a munchy lot, as evidenced by the
list of party supplies the teacher requested: cake, pretzels,
candy, fruit, cookies, juice.
</P>
<P>
   But they're also a delightful age, bridging that 7- to
8-year-old divide like miniature Lewis and Clarks, headed west to
explore uncharted territory.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Erik Erikson calls it the latency stage in
development, where children are learning ``the relationship between
perseverance and the pleasure of a job completed.'' Children in
elementary school, he found, have a need to be productive and to do
work on their own.
</P>
<P>
   First-graders are mastering abstract thought, and are able to go
beyond the here and now to think about concepts like ``forever,''
``justice,'' and ``love.''
</P>
<P>
   I just enjoy the conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know why people get married ... because they want someone to
play with,'' Adam says. ``But does there have to be a wedding? And
do you have to kiss in front of all those people? I would be
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``What if you never existed? You wouldn't know that you
didn't exist. There would just be NOTHING, you wouldn't have ever
been here at all, but I wonder what it would feel like, to not
exist? How does nothing feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``OK, so babies come from seeds and eggs, but how do those
seeds get into those eggs, that's what I want to know.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as we feel like ducking and running for cover during
Adam's heavy question artillery fire, his dad and I stand our
ground and have surprised ourselves by coming up with fairly decent
answers.
</P>
<P>
   But every once in a while _ sometimes the temptation is too
great, even as parents _ we have some fun with young,
impressionable minds.
</P>
<P>
   Take the first-grade party.
</P>
<P>
   My husband showed up straight from the airport, back just in
time from a business trip to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The first-graders gathered around, since Jim had been a big hit
at the teach-in a few months back by demonstrating a few simple
magic tricks. (That's another great thing about first-graders. A
few simple magic tricks are all you need to be cool.)
</P>
<P>
   Johnny, one of my son's best friends in class, asked if he could
come over and play after the class party.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' said Jim, joking with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have $7,'' said Johnny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, in that case, sure,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   The other kids stared in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pay to go to Adam's house?'' one asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' said Jim. ``There's video rental fees, snacks...''
</P>
<P>
   ``You make kids rent your video games?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a bidding war was under way. ``I have $3.'' ``I can get $5
from my brother ....''
</P>
<P>
   Adam was pretty sure this was all a joke. But he still reveled
in having instantly turned into such a hot commodity.
</P>
<P>
   After the kids had their fill of snacks, they gathered their
pencil cases, stubby crayons, treat bags, folders filled with
artwork taken down from the walls, and a few leftover math and
spelling worksheets.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Adams called her students up and said goodbye to each in
turn, giving them a hug.
</P>
<P>
   And Johnny came over to play, free, for the rest of the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   (Mary J. Loftus is a feature writer for The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
