<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plain talk, plain sense
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have good news from Washington for a change. President
Clinton and his cardboard sidekick, Al Gore, have ordered
government bureaucrats to stop writing gobbledygook and use plain
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain language saves the government and private sector time,
effort and money,'' the president explained.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore will be point man in the Plain English
campaign. This is because of his experience in making speeches on
kindergarten level. A typical Gore mouthful is ``see Jane run,'' or
``see Dick jump.'' Al Gore's lectures are easy to follow, if you
can stay awake.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, rambling government sentences will be short and
to the point. ``Short is better than long,'' says Gore. ``Active is
better than passive. Clarity helps advance understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a good start, but they're still wasting words and space.
How about: ``Short beats long. Active beats passive. Clarity helps
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Plain English will be helpful when we start to file income tax
forms. We won't have to worry about lines 9 and 5 and all the stuff
even H&AMP;R Block can't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Instructions for paying income tax will be simple:
</P>
<P>
   1. Go to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   2. Withdraw all your money.
</P>
<P>
   3. Send it to the government.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have at least half a year's earnings in the bank
you can:
</P>
<P>
   a. Sell your car.
</P>
<P>
   b. Sell your home.
</P>
<P>
   c. Get a night job.
</P>
<P>
   d. Make your spouse go to work.
</P>
<P>
   e. Sell your vital organs.
</P>
<P>
   Another battle ahead
</P>
<P>
   Although it will cost around $56 million, plain talk is expected
to save billions in the long run. The bad news is just as we get
one problem solved we run into another that's threatening to
destroy the economy, along with our sanity. That's voice mail and
automated telephone directories.
</P>
<P>
   Where I live we have to get government permission to strike a
match. About half the year we have a burning ban, applying to
leaves, limbs, candy wrappers and, in many places, cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   I had a small pile of tree leaves and several candy wrappers I
needed to burn before the summer burning ban went into effect last
month. In order to stay out of jail and avoid fines, I had to call
the county fire department to get permission to burn a small trash
pile in my back yard.
</P>
<P>
   I looked in the phone book for the number of the fire
department, non-emergencies. I dialed the number. I didn't get the
fire department, non-emergencies. I got a recorded voice: ``You
have reached the Fayette County Administrative Complex. If you wish
to speak to the health department, dial 415; if you wish to speak
to the building department, dial something else, if you wish to
speak to the county agent or extension service, etc., etc.''
</P>
<P>
   The electronic voice droned through a half dozen departments but
never got to the fire department. ``For recorded information, dial
500; otherwise remain on the line for assistance,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to remain on the line for assistance. Another
electronic voice informed me that everyone in the county
administrative office was busy and I'd have to wait. After a
lengthy wait I decided everyone at the county administrative office
was going to be busy until the end of the week when it would be too
late to get a burning permit. I dialed back to ``recorded
information.''
</P>
<P>
   After several tries I made a connection with a fire department
recording. I got an electronic lecture on fire safety. I got
precise measurements required for a legal trash pile. By the time I
got permission to strike a match to it, I was ready to stuff
everything into plastic garbage bags and throw my trash on the side
of the road like some people do.
</P>
<P>
   And that's not all
</P>
<P>
   It's not just the government. Have you tried to call your bank
lately?
</P>
<P>
   I had a simple account question. I looked in the local phone
book, got the local number of my local bank, and dialed. An
electronic voice, obviously located in some other state, or
country, began listing options: home loans, corporate offices,
automobile loans, investments, etc. A laundry list of things that
had nothing to do with what I needed to know.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes of punching on my telephone, listening to
electronic options, and a disconnect, I finally got to customer
service, and eventually to a live human being. I told the live
human who I wanted to speak with at my local bank. ``Let me see if
I can locate her,'' he said. I could hear clicking on computer keys
as he searched files. After several minutes the clicking stopped.
``She's in the Miami office,'' the voice said. ``You'll have to
call her there.''
</P>
<P>
   I hung up the phone and drove to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
