<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HORSE-TRAVEL13-COX     06-12 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORSE-TRAVEL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talk horse sense or whisper to a winner on equine farm tour
 &HT;    By Mary Thurwachter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCALA, Fla. _ I went to Farnsworth Farms to visit some old
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the equine kind. Ones that I had seen when they had
run at Gulfstream or Calder racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   I hoped to get close enough to do some horse whispering _ I
wanted to thank Mecke, a Florida racing legend who once won me
enough cash to buy a CD player.
</P>
<P>
   Mecke, who has since moved to Ocala Stud, never got close enough
to hear a whisper that day, but I got a chance to shout out a few
kind words when he came within 10 feet of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   When you drive through this part of the state, with its rolling
hills, classic farm country board fencing and ancient oaks veiled
in Spanish moss, you'll be tempted to roll down the windows and
breathe in the beauty. And you'll want to visit a horse farm. If
you're lucky, you'll encounter greatness of the four-legged kind.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Kentucky Derby winner, Silver Charm, was foaled in
this area and this year's Derby champ, Real Quiet, was trained
here. Triple Crown winner Affirmed (1978) was bred and raised here,
too. It's no wonder folks call this the ``Lexington of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's horse industry has been at home here since the 1930s.
Ocala and Marion County boast more than 400 thoroughbred farms, and
an additional 300 farms that raise Appaloosas, Paso Finos, paints,
miniatures and quarter horses.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief visit to Ocala, a friend and I toured the
500-acre Farnsworth Farms, owned by Mike Sherman, on Highway 326
west of Interstate 75.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Mecke, we visited a few of the horses that were
still in the barn, some in air-conditioned stalls. Each one, we
learned, has a distinct personality.
</P>
<P>
   Jeblar knocked his hoof against the barn gate, anxious to run
free in the green pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Leon was a royal clown. He made faces, exposing every giant
tooth in his mouth and raising his snoot toward the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Our visit was very informal and the grooms, who were cleaning
the barn as we arrived, seemed to enjoy talking about the horses as
much as we loved seeing them.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when we go to the racetrack, we pay special
attention to horses sired by any of the legends we spent a morning
with at Farnsworth. And it's a sure bet we'll return to visit more
of Ocala's equine celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other farms open to visitors by appointment. Admission
is free. You can pick up a list of farms at the Ocala Chamber of
Commerce, 110 E. Silver Springs Blvd. in downtown Ocala, or call
the Florida Thoroughbred Breeders' and Owners' Association (352)
629-2160. Most farms ask that you call before a visit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abracadabra Farms, 510 E. Highway 484, Ocala. Phone: (352)
347-1115 or (352) 347-1144. 125 acres, 3/4-mile racetrack, 5/8-mile
turf course and European turf gallop.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bonnie Heath Farm, 4450 S.W. College Road, Ocala. Phone: (352)
873-3030. Stallions: Blue Ensign, Swedaus, Way West, Outflanker.
Visitors not encouraged during foaling and breeding season, January
through June.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dudley Farm, 5340 S. W. College Road, Ocala. 180 acres. Phone:
(352) 237-3413.
</P>
<P>
   _ Farnsworth Farms, 15500 W. Highway 326, Morriston. Visiting
hours are from 8 a.m.-4 p.m. Phone: (352) 622-5551.
</P>
<P>
   _ Franks Farms, Southland Division, 11629 S. Highway 475, Ocala.
Phone: (352) 245-2495. 1,100 acres. 5/8-mile training track.
Stallions: All Gone, Gold Alert, Heaven's Wish, Homebuilder, Kissin
Kris, Lost Soldier, Lucky North, Native Regent, Track Rebel.
Visitor hours: 9 a.m.-4 p.m. Monday through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Live Oak Stud, 9275 S.W. 9th St. Road, Ocala. Phone: (352)
854-2691. 3/4-mile training track. Stallions: Dispersal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ocala Stud Farms, P.O. Box 818, Ocala. 500 acres. Phone: (352)
237-2171. 7/8-mile training track. Stallions: Mecke, Alaskan Frost,
Concorde's Tune, Notebook, Prospector's Halo, Ponche, Pentelicus,
Montbrook. Visiting hours: Monday-Saturday: 7-10:30 a.m. and 2-3:30
p.m. There are no visiting hours on holidays.
</P>
<P>
   FOR INSIDE TRAVEL, 5i FOR INSIDE TRAVEL, 5i FOR INSIDE TRAVEL,
5i FOR INSIDE TRAVEL, 5i
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: Think you need to be a rough rider to do a horse
tour? Neigh! Just call one of the tour operators listed below and
let them do the work or hop in the car and drive to the farms
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Fun fact: Horse breeding began in the Ocala area in the late
1950s with the discovery that the area's nutrient-fortified grass
aided strong equine bone development. The grass is the product of
the limestone-rich Florida Aquifer, which stretches across Marion
County.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: From West Palm Beach, Ocala is a three-hour drive
north on the Turnpike to Interstate-75. To get to Farnsworth Farms
at 15500 W. Highway 326, Morriston, from I-75, go 13 miles west on
U.S. 27 (Exit 70) to Blitchton. Turn left at the crossroads on
County Road 326. Continue for 2 1/2 miles to Farnsworth Farms.
Visiting hours are from 8 a.m.-4 p.m. Phone: (352) 622-5551.
</P>
<P>
   Horse tours: Horse fans can tour horse farms with local tour
operators including Tours By Appointment (352) 624-9191, which
tailors excursions to the visitor's interests. For Lorna Hagemeyers
Farm Tours (352) 351-5524, tourists pay $5 per person and follow a
guide through several horse farms in their own vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay:
</P>
<P>
   _ Heritage Country Inn, 14343 W. State Road 40, Ocala, phone
(352) 489-0023, six rooms with fireplaces. A country breakfast is
included. Rates are $79 to $84.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven Sisters Inn, 820 S.E. Fort King St., Ocala, phone: (352)
867-1170, eight rooms in an 1880s Queen Anne Victorian house.
Breakfast and afternoon tea are included. Rates range from $105 to
$165.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ocala Silver Springs Hilton, 3600 S.W. 36th Ave., Ocala,
phone: (352) 854-1400 has 198 rooms, a swimming pool, two tennis
courts, two volleyball courts and a putting green. Rates for rooms
and suites range from $79 to $350.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
