<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6219 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IDEA-HOUSE13-COX     06-12 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDEA-HOUSE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STEAL AWAY FROM DISNEY AND DROP BY SOUTHERN LIVING'S IDEA HOUSE
 &HT;    By AVA VAN de WATER
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Sometimes it's the little, less obvious things
that are most interesting in a house. Like the Honeywell vacuum pan
in the kitchen floor of Southern Living's Idea House in
Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Sweep your crumbs into a pile, tap the switch with your foot and
_ swoosh _ crumbs are sucked into the wall. It's the '90s way to
sweep dirt under the rug.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the crumbs really go into a central vacuum system, but it
is the neatest, most useful conversation piece I've ever seen. Just
don't turn it on if the cat's snoozing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in the market for new decorating or home building
ideas, hop in your car and head for Celebration, Disney's
neo-traditional town just south of Orlando. That's where Southern
Living magazine's latest Idea House just opened (and will remain
open through the end of January).
</P>
<P>
   With easy-to-live-with fabrics, comfy furniture and a soothing
color scheme of cream, sage green, and bricky terra cotta, the
house has a relaxed, comfortable feeling that still evokes gracious
living.
</P>
<P>
   And there are a heck of a lot of places to relax in this house.
There's a den, garden parlor, family room and covered patio
downstairs; a private guest apartment above the garage; and a
master retreat on the third floor _ above the master suite.
</P>
<P>
   There's a computer nook with window seat for the kids, a mudroom
for the kids' stuff, and potting room for the garden enthusiast. In
addition to the two-car garage for vehicles, there's a one-car,
detached garage that's just as easy to envision as a home office,
artist's studio or rec room with pool table.
</P>
<P>
   There is the rather odd fact that you walk into the dining room
from the front porch, but, first impressions aside, there are
plenty of good ideas in this house. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ A nursery doesn't have to be cutesy to be cute. There are no
fussy kids' fabrics or juvenile wallpaper borders. Instead, there
is a Matisse-looking painting of a pot of flowers above the crib,
and whimsical watercolors of teapots and shoes in a bold,
MacKenzie-Childs style. The drapery fabric, which coordinates with
plaid crib set, is a quiet print of nursery rhyme characters, and
walls are a creamy beige, with white christening gowns hung high _
out of a little girl's reach. The washed pine furniture from
Lexington _ a dresser, rocking chair and shelves to display baby
photos and memorabilia _ can go all the way through college,
providing she doesn't spill nail polish on it as a pre-teen.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: If you go, be sure to look up _ criss-crossed ribbons with
bows on the nursery ceiling create an interesting lattice pattern.
It's simple to do, but the bows take time to make. Mary McWilliams,
Southern Living's interior design director, wanted to give the
ceiling extra interest because it's one of the first things you see
as you reach the top of the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Challenging architecture can be overcome. We all, sooner or
later, encounter a room with too many openings. Such is the case
with the garden parlor. The roughly 15- by 14-foot room between the
foyer and kitchen, has six openings _ French doors to the courtyard
patio, two doors into the kitchen, the passage from the front
entry, a door to the study, and the side entry door. That was a
challenge to the decorating team, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? ``You float the furniture the best you can in the
middle of the room,'' said interior designer Marnie Sorensen of
Godfrey &AMP; Associates in Winter Park.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the room, they placed an ottoman between a love
seat and two chairs. Then, to jazz it up a bit, they mixed fabrics
on the love seat, and added beadboard to the walls, giving it a
faux finish. ``When you have a room that's divided up like that,
you have to do something to make it interesting,'' Sorensen said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expand your living space outdoors. A walled-in courtyard has a
soothing fountain and a covered patio for alfresco dining. Don't
miss the potting room with sink plus storage for compost, potting
soil and fertilizer. It can double as a wet bar for parties on the
patio, thanks to a pass-through window above the sink.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Homeowners can create their own potting shed by adding a
lean-to at the side of the house. Or, buy an outdoor workbench from
a store such as Target, and put a couple cans beneath it to hold
compost, Sorensen said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't forget to accessorize the kitchen. The kitchen is the
nerve center of the house _ the place we start and end the day. So
make room for personal family photos and prop small pieces of art
on the backsplash or open shelves. But don't clutter up the tops of
the cabinets, McWilliams warns.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: The kitchen's Armstrong vinyl floor looks like pink slate,
but is easier on feet _ and dropped items _ than tile.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get the computer out of the bedroom. If you have the space,
create a computer nook for the kids. This one has seating for two
at the desk, with plenty of storage for books, games and computer
software, freeing up the bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: A rope secured to a wall by teacup hooks is the perfect
place for kids to hang their artwork with clothespins. (The
children can paint the clothespins if they want.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Reflect children's interests when accessorizing their rooms.
Shelves with pegs beneath hang above twin beds in the boys' room,
giving them space to display trophies and favorite things.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Even window valences can showcase an interest. At the Idea
House, simple window valances are topped with baseball finials
``aged'' with Old English oil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accessorize the bath for children, but make the fixtures
timeless. Simple cream cabinets and gold door pulls are teamed with
hand-painted stool and accessories geared to kids. And cream, sage
and white tiles that blend with the rest of the house color scheme
won't be outgrown.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Add interest to a flat bathroom mirror by ``framing'' it
with molding. Use baseboard molding or casing from Home Depot _
just miter the corners and give it a coat of paint.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clean up the master bedroom. Ever wonder why master bedrooms
look so spacious in decorating magazines? There are no dressers to
clutter the room. Built-in cabinets in huge walk-in closets are one
alternative; or, if you're lucky enough to have the space, in the
master dressing area.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Don't miss the master breakfast bar, with GE
refrigerator/ice maker, sink and cupboard for cups, glasses and
teapot. It's a luxury more and more new homes are including.
</P>
<P>
   _ You don't have to have a sofa and TV in the den. This
14-by-12-foot den off the front entry has four, plump leather
chairs and floor-to-ceiling bookshelves.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: McWilliams hopes those going to the Ideas House will be
inspired by the little touches _ such as the pictures hanging on
the front of the bookshelves. ``I could have filled those bookcases
with just books, but when you do that, you lose the opportunity for
art pieces and accessories,'' McWilliams said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add architectural elements without breaking the bank. The
family room, off the kitchen, features heart pine paneling above
the mantle. It adds architectural interest but is less expensive
than paneling the entire room.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: The sofa is upholstered in chenille fabric _ comfortable
enough to cuddle up in while watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add storage near the family entry. A mudroom by the garage has
a bench for pulling off muddy shoes, and pegs for storing baseball
gloves, backpacks and rain gear.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: Note the mudroom floor _ you don't have to scrimp in small
spaces. The limestone was cut against the grain to emphasize its
texture.
</P>
<P>
   _ And the best idea of all _ a guest apartment. Good for
in-laws, nannies, and guests, this mini-apartment includes a
bathroom, bedroom/living room and kitchen with microwave, oven,
sink, refrigerator and stacked washer/dryer. Everything to give
them _ and you _ a little privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: It's so nice, guests may overstay their welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
