<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BICYCLE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whoosh! Once past the big rigs, the bike tour was a breeze
 &HT;    By Scott Wiseman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get a bicycle. You will not regret it if you live. _ Mark Twain
</P>
<P>
   LAKE WALES _ I have a bicycle, and minutes into my 28-mile ride
in Lake Wales, I thought that I might regret it.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th tractor-trailer rocketed by, seemingly inches away, its
backwash yanking me from the right edge of the white stripe that I
was desperately trying to keep beneath my wheels. This might be the
way the world ends for me, I thought. The fate of so many love bugs
on the grills of trucks might also be mine.
</P>
<P>
   My hands were locked in a death grip around the handlebars. I
wanted to turn around, get in my car and drive on four wheels back
to West Palm Beach. I had been warned by a friend who had cycled in
Polk County that the traffic was fast and the roads were narrow.
</P>
<P>
   But two miles and a right turn later I was alone on Alternate
U.S. 27, a rolling two-lane road, happily pedaling through orderly
lines of orange trees and bright green fields scattered with
grazing cattle. The thundering whooshes of traffic were replaced by
the quiet roar of the wind in my ears, the cicada's buzz and the
low purr of spinning bicycle wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Today I was going to live.
</P>
<P>
   Polk County, southwest of Orlando, is in the shadow of Disney
World. It has no theme parks, but it does have miles of open roads.
Promoting their county as bicycle-friendly, tourism officials have
created a nifty package of maps and information for cyclists. It is
an inventive effort to attract visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The maps have plotted trips and color-coded streets showing road
widths and traffic volume. The routes, all loops, vary from 20 to
100 miles and are generally sparsely traveled.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the roads are in the country, where I found a mix of
shaded lanes lined with moss-draped trees, shallow hills and wide
open spaces of citrus groves and pastures. I often rode miles at a
time without seeing a car, allowing for long moments of quiet
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   The routes also go through small towns, down wide, tidy
neighborhood streets and past businesses such as fruit-picking bag
manufacturers, drive shaft repair shops, feed stores and fertilizer
plants.
</P>
<P>
   I cycled four of the six marked routes during my three-day stay.
I rode 20 miles in Lakeland, 28 miles in Lake Wales, 38 miles in
Winter Haven and the 62 mile Auburndale loop. My favorite was the
Winter Haven ride, which runs along many lakes and has long
stretches of roads canopied by live oaks. My least favorite was the
Lakeland route, which had portions under repair and a road over
Interstate 4 with on and off ramps with very heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   These trips, particularly the longer ones, are best suited for
lightweight road bikes with narrow tires, which provide less
resistance and make for an easier ride. If you plan to try it on a
mountain bike, stick to the shorter routes unless you are sure of
your fitness level.
</P>
<P>
   My companion for this trip was a Colnago, an Italian racing
bike.
</P>
<P>
   There are several bed and breakfasts (you will want a big,
protein-rich breakfast) in Lake Wales. I stayed at Noah's Ark, a
place named after Noah Holton, who owns it with his wife, Louise.
It is decorated with antique furniture and has very accommodating
hosts. It is large enough to fit two of every type of animal, like
the original ark, as well as several bicycles, which are allowed
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the routes can be ridden from Noah's Ark and the others
are a short car ride away.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from my inn were two attractions, Bok Tower Gardens and
Spook Hill. The 205-foot-tall Bok Tower is in the middle of a huge,
beautifully landscaped garden. It houses a carillon, an instrument
of 57 bronze bells. Visit Bok near the end of a ride _ you will
leave too relaxed to be of much use on a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Spook Hill is an incline where it is claimed that gravity is
defied and a vehicle will coast uphill. The sign says to stop on a
marked line, put your car in neutral. You'll roll back, but it will
seem like you're rolling uphill. I pulled up with my bike to the
foot of the hill, pointing up, lifted my feet and I rolled
backward. But it seemed like I was rolling down the hill. No
spooking for me.
</P>
<P>
   On a remote section of the 62-mile Auburndale trip, I had ridden
for many thirsty miles with one last rationed swig of water in my
bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding a corner on Old Polk City Road, an oasis emerged in the
form of an old packing house with a glass-paneled refrigerator
stocked with ice cold fresh-squeezed orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   I bought a quart and gulped it. For a moment I felt that I
wouldn't have to stop when the loop was finished back near Lake
Alfred, that I could stay on my bike and pedal forever.
</P>
<P>
   travel, 9i travel, 9i travel, 9i
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: You have to have nerves _ and thighs _ of steel to
ride the white line on some of these roads. Your competition is
18-wheelers. The rides are for the serious cyclist.
</P>
<P>
   Preparation: Most of the roads are in remote areas, so you
should be able to make minor repairs and be self-sufficient with
food and water. There are places to buy fluids, but they are few
and far between.
</P>
<P>
   What to take: Items to change flats (tubes, air canisters), two
water bottles (you'll need both), map and nutritional bars.
</P>
<P>
   Information: To get your Polk County Cycling Kit call (800)
828-7655 or (941) 298-7565. Write to the Central Florida Visitors
and Convention Bureau, P.O. Box 61, Cypress Gardens, Fla. 33884.
PHOTO CAPTION:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTT WISEMAN/Staff Photographer Bicycles are always welcome at
Noah's Ark, a Lake Wales bed-and-breakfast. For a break from the
bike route, go to nearby Bok Tower and Spook Hill.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-11-98 1051E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
