<HEADER>
A6221 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-OKEECHOBEE13-C     06-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-OKEECHOBEE13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Yorker tours the lake and finds history, harmony and
cocoanut cream pie
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKEECHOBEE, Fla. _ I steered our aging Ford Tempo to the steep
slope of dirt and floored the accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there it was: Lake Okeechobee. And we were about to
plunge into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit the brakes, hit the brakes,'' my wife sputtered in fear. I
thrust the tape of life's greatest moments into my mental VCR as I
imagined the car slowly sinking to the bottom. Only my 6-year-old
son registered the right reaction, giggling in delight at my
vehicular idiocy.
</P>
<P>
   The joke was that we had been driving for miles and miles,
trying to catch a glimmer of water, but the earthen dam stood in
our way. What did I expect to find on the other side? Chopped
liver?
</P>
<P>
   We stopped just inches before the inevitable downward roll.
Maybe this was going to be a memorable vacation after all.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Okeechobee is the second-largest lake in the United States
and a mecca for fishermen, but as Florida tourist destinations go,
it ranks well below Disney et al. Beyond the water, its actual
attractions are few. There are no souvenir stands, no T-shirts
imprinted with the words, ``My grandma went to Lake Okeechobee and
all I got was this lousy T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there's a Florida that lives up to its simple Southern
setting. A Florida that a New York native like me never knew
existed.
</P>
<P>
   We planned our three-day winter trip to be a voyage of
discovery. We wanted to see the lake and the towns around it.
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible to hop from hotel to hotel as you circle the
lake, we preferred working from a single locale. We picked the new
Holiday Inn Express in Okeechobee. It's a no-nonsense chain hotel,
with the customary complimentary breakfast and rooms that
comfortably accommodate a small family.
</P>
<P>
   But the lake became the constant of the trip. Covering more than
730 square miles, it's a thing of immense beauty, its name
literally translating as ``big water'' in the Seminole tongue. So
big that when the 1928 hurricane caused it to flood, 2,500 people
died. The result was the aforementioned dam, otherwise known as the
Herbert Hoover Dike: It nearly surrounds the lake.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves anyone who visits the Okeechobee area playing a
hide-and-seek game with the lake. We saw it from all vantages.
</P>
<P>
   Of the official access points, including a number of parks and
canal locks, I'd pick the piers in Pahokee and Okeechobee as the
best. The structures stretch far into the lake. The crowds dispense
free fishing advice and everyone seems to have their radios tuned
to the same gospel station.
</P>
<P>
   But part of the joy of a lake vacation is venturing into
uncharted territory. Somewhere on the western side of the lake, we
stopped by a desolate patch of green, cast our fishing pole and
watched the world go by.
</P>
<P>
   If the lake is a fixed force, the surrounding towns do manage to
differentiate themselves. Here are some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're driving from West Palm Beach, you'll first encounter
Belle Glade, the lake's largest city. If you make one stop, let it
be the Drawbridge Cafe on a Sunday afternoon. The buffet spread is
country cooking at its finest. Drive a little past the restaurant
and you'll see the drawbridge _ a hand-operated wooden marvel of
engineering that allows cars to pass one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the southern end of the lake, Clewiston has a more stately
feel. It's headquarters of United States Sugar Corp., the nation's
largest sugar cane grower, and home to the Clewiston Inn, the
lake's most elegant hotel.
</P>
<P>
   _ To the west are dot-on-the-map towns like Lakeport and
Buckhead Ridge. This is, by far, the lake's most quiet region.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're willing to make a slight trek, visit Arcadia and
Lake Placid, two towns between the lake and Sarasota. The former
preserves its early 20th-century roots remarkably well, and it
contains a number of fine shops, many within the lovingly restored
Old Opera House Antique Mall and Museum. The latter is famous for
the 270-foot-high Placid Tower and the murals painted on the sides
of many buildings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last, consider an expedition to LaBelle, between the lake and
Fort Myers. There's not much to see, but people come mostly for
Flora and Ella's. The restaurant is everything Cracker Barrel
pretends to be. Have a plate of Lake Okeechobee catfish and finish
the meal with a slice of coconut cream pie. The food is so good,
your arteries will forgive you.
</P>
<P>
   Photos by PAUL J. MILETTE/Staff Photographer
</P>
<P>
   The Okeechobee Pier stretches far into the lake, with visitors
dispensing free fishing advice. Radios are tuned to gospel
stations. The lovingly restored Old Opera House Antique Mall and
Museum in Arcadia boasts a ticket booth and other theatrical
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: The most you'll exert yourself on this trip is when
you reel in a fish from the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Drive time: It takes about an hour to get from West Palm Beach
to Lake Okeechobee. We drove about 400 miles over three days as we
circled the lake and visited towns throughout the region (Belle
Glade, Buckhead Ridge, Clewiston, Lakeport, Okeechobee, Pahokee)
and near the Gulf Coast (Arcadia, LaBelle).
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: The Holiday Inn Express in Okeechobee is a clean,
comfortable chain hotel on the lake's northern point: Summer rates
are $69 per night (holidays slightly higher), includes free
continental breakfast; call (941) 357-3529 or (800) HOLIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   Before you go: You won't find much about Lake Okeechobee in the
traditional travel books. The 1998 Frommer's Florida devotes only
three of its 627 pages to the area. A couple of better sources come
from Sarasota-based Pineapple Press: Bill and Carol Gregware's
Guide to the Lake Okeechobee Area is filled with history going back
to the Ice Age, details about flora and fauna and suggested driving
and biking tours (the maps, though, are somewhat confusing); Bruce
Hunt's Visiting Small-Town Florida provides more colorful
descriptions of some of the area's destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
