<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS13-COX     06-12 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author wrote artist's colony into her will
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patricia Highsmith made a lot of money writing about the
calculating psychopath Tom Ripley, and, before she died, she made
sure that all of it would go to Yaddo, the upstate New York
artist's retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Highsmith wrote ``Strangers on a Train'' at Yaddo in 1948, and,
in her will, left the colony her $3 million estate, the largest
single gift in the colony's history.
</P>
<P>
   COMING SOON . . . David Guterson's follow-up to ``Snow Falling
on Cedars'' will be titled ``East of the Mountains,'' and, like his
first novel, it's set in the Pacific Northwest. It's about a
terminally ill surgeon who reminisces about his life while on a
hunting trip. Harcourt Brace is expected to publish this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Evans, whose ``The Horse Whisperer'' became an enormous
commercial success worldwide, will also publish this fall. ``The
Loop'' involves a pack of wolves that are plaguing a Montana
ranching town, and the biologist who is trying to save them from
being wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Longstreet Press, which has sold 900,000 copies of
``The Millionaire Next Door,'' not counting the paperback that
comes out this fall, has committed what Publisher's Weekly
estimates as $2 million for the follow-up, ``The Millionaire
Mind.'' (Full disclosure: Longstreet is owned by Cox Enterprises,
which also owns The Palm Beach Post.)
</P>
<P>
   Look for ``The Millionaire Mind'' a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   New and noteworthy . . . ``Pulp Culture'' (Collector's Press,
$39.95) is a scrumptious collection of art from the pulp magazines
of the teens through the '50s, when the form died out.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by genre _ horror, western, and so forth _ the editors
are careful to showcase premium magazines. Hammett's ``The Maltese
Falcon,'' for instance, first appeared in the September 1929
``Black Mask'' (20 cents!), with a nice painting of somebody _ not
Brigid O'Shaughnessy _ firing through a newspaper right at the
reader.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the artists are famous (Wyeth, Leyendecker), but most
were worker bees specializing in lurid action and bug-eyed
monsters, but with great dramatic vitality.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of sub-genres covered by the book, such as
Mad Slasher magazines, featuring woman in various stages of
dishevelment about to be ravaged or dismembered. There are some
images here that are unpublishable today, but are considered
perfectly all right for the unfortunate revival in teenage horror
movies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful tour of a publishing universe that no longer
exists. Did you know there was once a magazine called Speakeasy
Stories? How many stories would anybody want to read about
speak-easies?
</P>
<P>
   Quote Unquote . . . ``The dilemma of the critic has always been
that if he knows enough to speak with authority, he knows too much
to speak with detachment.'' _ Raymond Chandler
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
