<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEAR&AMP;-REAGAN13-COX     06-12 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAR&AMP;-REAGAN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pecan logs and cola in Yeehaw junction
 &HT;    A 'trip' up the Reagan Turnpike
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This Ronald Reagan Turnpike name change fiasco has defeated
conventional journalism,'' my editor ranted. ``Wiggins! We need you
to take to the turnpike for a Gonzo journalism perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see,'' I said. ``I like it. You want a desperate and savage
journey up Florida's ulcercated varicose vein. Maybe the trip
itself will reveal what those tapioca brains in Tallahassee had in
mind when they named our turnpike after a California soap
pitchman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't heard the latest?'' my editor blustered.
``Florida's Turnpike is only to be `designated' the Ronald Reagan
Turnpike. Go on the road, Wiggins. Don't stop until you reach the
Stuckey's in Yeehaw Junction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'll need mind-altering substances,'' I replied.
``A case of Jolt Cola, a half-pound of Jelly Bellies and three
pounds of cinnamon Red Hots ought to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine, Wiggins. But just remember: There is nothing more
irresponsible and dangerous than an aging Gonzo journalist in the
throes of a cinnamon Red Hot sugar high.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographer Jennifer Podis and I headed straight for the West
Palm Beach interchange on Okeechobee Boulevard. ``We'll find out
what the toll-takers know,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously under strict orders, the toll takers wouldn't talk. A
quick call to the regional toll office revealed that all turnpike
employees are brain-dead to the press, as a matter of policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if toll booth personnel had an opinion, it would be
inappropriate for them to express it,'' a turnpike spokesman in
Fort Lauderdale explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, really?'' I retorted. ``And I suppose if the governor
wanted to rename the turnpike the
Have-Cards-Ready-and-Tip-Attendant-Fifteen-Percent-Parkway, they
wouldn't have an opinion on that either?'' I hung up and walked
back to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Podis suggested that we get rolling interviews every time we
picked up a card or paid a toll. Sneaky. I liked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few Jelly Bellies might loosen their tongues,'' I agreed.
</P>
<P>
   We exited at Palm Beach Gardens, and I asked the woman who took
my 50 cents, real casual like, ``Why did they change the name?''
</P>
<P>
   She met my gaze steadily and said carefully: ``I have no idea
why they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her co-worker in the other booth said: ``What difference does it
make to Reagan? He's got Alzheimer's and won't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   I saw her point. And what's the deal on ``designating'' a
highway after someone if you're not going to change the name? Isn't
that a little like saying, ``Mr. President, we want to honor you by
naming the bleakest strip of asphalt this side of Death Valley
after you, but we're kidding about the name change part.''
</P>
<P>
   I cracked a can of Jolt and tore open the bag of cinnamon Red
Hots. ``We obviously need more sugar,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   We left the turnpike at Jupiter and swung into the parking lot
of the Palm Beach County Visitors Center on Indiantown Road.
Inside, we met supervisor Alan Bernstein, who only compounded the
mystery of the Name Change that Wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Reagan?'' Bernstein asked. ``If you're going to change the
name of the Florida Turnpike, why not somebody from Florida? Ponce
de Leon? Claude Pepper?
</P>
<P>
   (Not bad, I mused. The Pepper Parkway. ``The beach? Take the
Pepper Parkway to your Burt Reynolds exit ramp in Jupiter, go east
across the Perry Como Causeway, and you're at Sally Beach.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Or,'' Bernstein proposed, ``name it after Lawton Chiles.''
</P>
<P>
   I tried to picture it. The Walkin' Lawton He-Coon Parkway. The
Republicans wouldn't go for it, even if they eight-laned the thing
with tobacco money.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the turnpike, we set course for Yeehaw Junction. The
candy was gone and I was feening for a fix. ``Are you going to be
all right?'' Podis asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as my cavities are aching, I'm OK,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside Stuckey's, I loaded up on pecan logs, Pecan Goo-Goo
Clusters, Pecan Brittle and Tom's Pecan Pies. I sat down at a booth
and ordered a large Coke, easy on the ice, and a bag of
Cajun-boiled peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear about them calling the Turnpike the Ronald Reagan
Turnpike,'' I asked fry cook Dorisene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's stupid,'' she said. ``He didn't do nothing for
nobody _ Lord, don't go putting down my name! OK, just my first
name.''
</P>
<P>
   A male customer in his early 60s, overhearing us, volunteered:
``It's silly naming it after somebody from another state. Chiles is
a good man; name it after him.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked the man his name. ``Carl,'' he said. ``I work over here
on the turnpike.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, Carl, but I can't quote an employee of the Florida
Turnpike Authority. It is inappropriate for you to have an
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my day off,'' he said. ``Just put `Carl.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stuckey's manager Pat Hutto dismissed the name change flap as
``B.S. _ you're just going to confuse everybody. First they call it
the Sunshine Parkway, then the Florida Turnpike, and now the Reagan
Turnpike?''
</P>
<P>
   Cashier Fran LaJoie concurred. ``You get people not knowing
where they're going, asking for the turnpike and there it is 100
feet away.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking mild exception was vacationer George Spivey, on his way
to Key West. ``I think it's pretty neat calling it the Reagan
Turnpike. We have a Ronald Reagan Parkway in Atlanta. Reagan was a
no-nonsense guy. He let you know where he stood.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading back to West Palm Beach, we found one more champion of
the name change (OK, the name ``designation'') in Margarita Ortiz,
cashier at the Fort Drum Plaza. ``President Reagan deserves the
honor,'' she said. ``He was our president for eight years. He
didn't do so well, but he still deserves our respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading back, I let an entire Stuckey's pecan praline dissolve
in my mouth as I tried to synthesize all we had learned into one
incandescent insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny,'' Podis said, as we passed Jupiter, ``how the turnpike
runs right beside I-95 for so many miles.''
</P>
<P>
   I stared at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's it!'' I shrieked, sitting bolt upright and
pointing to the stream of interstate traffic not 200 yards from us.
``Don't designate the turnpike after Reagan. Name Interstate 95
after him all the way up to Canada!''
</P>
<P>
   I pulled over and Podis took the wheel as I ranted. I found some
cinnamon Red Hots that had spilled into the console and shoved them
in my mouth. I chased them with warm soda. My fillings shrieked
from sugar overload. I'd found my answer. And not a minute before
my brain exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
