<HEADER>
A6224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIDDEN-DISNEY13-COX     06-12 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIDDEN-DISNEY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ahhh....It's a whole new world; find bliss at a quiet garden,
spa
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ On a steamy summer day at any jammed
Disney World theme park, you begin to think that peace and quiet
can come only if you pass out.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to black out to bliss out at Disney World. If
you know where to look, there are a few places where the lure is
lazy and laconic and you may even learn something.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid, don't tell Michael Eisner, but there are people
who abhor theme parks and are delivered there by family or fate on
a forced march. Those tortured tourists will discover it's the
quiet, quality stops that give them reason to march on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gardens of the World _ Much of Disney's reputation for
fastidious control begins with its precise and pristine
landscaping. The themed shrubs along with the trees, flowers and
lawns make even some golf courses look like abandoned lots.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a Disney theme park ticket to take the 3 1/2 hour
behind-the-scenes Epcot landscaping tour called Gardens of the
World.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Institute tour costs $45 per person and includes a
walking tour of Epcot's gardens with experts explaining the
landscaping and growing plan. You need to be 15 or older for this
tour. For information and reservations, call (407) 939-8687.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hidden Treasures of the World Showcase _ Not everything at
Disney is a plastic version of the real thing. This tour through
Epcot's 11 countries offers a look at the usually overlooked art,
architecture and costumes. You'll go backstage at France and Canada
while dwelling on the details of the other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Imagineers explain how some of the theme park's illusions
were created and why. The tour is $75 per person with lunch and $60
without the meal. Both prices include a Hidden Treasures booklet.
For information and reservations, call (407) 939-8687.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voodoo Garden at the House of Blues _ Downtown Disney _ The
Cajun/Creole-themed House of Blues offers a quiet, 20-table deck
overlooking Lake Buena Vista. Set in a brick garden and patio, you
can get a limited menu of dinner choices in this quiet setting.
Live music is featured during the summer on Thursday, Friday and
Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discovery Island _ Within site of the always-crowded Magic
Kingdom and the chaos of the Contemporary Hotel is dreamy Discovery
Island. What you discover on this 12-acre island is the quiet of a
self-guided tour through a South Seas jungle home to a wide variety
of animals.
</P>
<P>
   You walk along tree-shaded paths to see 140 species of birds,
mammals and reptiles. The Avian Way is home to 14 bird varieties.
An animal hospital lets you watch vets at work. There are places to
buy food and souvenirs. Daily shows involve birds and reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery Island is a short boat ride across Bay Lake near the
Contemporary Hotel. The price for adults is $11.95 and $6.50 for
kids (ages 3-9).
</P>
<P>
   Disney hotel guests can get Discovery Island information at
guest relations and non-hotel visitors can board the boat to
Discovery Island at the Contemporary Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Victoria &AMP; Albert's restaurant _ Grand Floridian Resort &AMP; Spa
_ If you take a date to Victoria &AMP; Albert's romance-drenched dining
room and hot, monkey love doesn't happen as soon as you get back to
the hotel room, yours is the definition of a dead-end relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 tables make up the exclusive Victoria &AMP; Albert's at the
Grand Floridian. A harp plays as you pace yourself through a
seven-course meal that includes four entrees, served on Royal
Doulton China with Schott-Zweisel crystal and Sambonet silver. An
extensive wine selection is also available.
</P>
<P>
   There are two seatings daily, 5:45-6:30 p.m. and 9-9:45 p.m.,
with reservations a must. This is the only Disney restaurant where
jackets are required.
</P>
<P>
   Diners are pampered by formal service that includes a butler and
a maid for each table. Each customer gets to take home a
handwritten, personalized menu and women are given a long-stemmed
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Prices begin at $80 per person for the seven-course dinner, $110
if you want a different wine with each course.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal menu is American regional with classical
influences. Daily choices include fish, fowl, red meat, veal and
lamb.
</P>
<P>
   For reservations, call: (407) 939-7707.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oak Trail golf course _ Maybe every other golfer wouldn't be
10 or 70 pounds overweight if players routinely walked the course
hauling their own clubs. But they don't, and getting in and out of
golf carts won't make you buff but will create a big duff.
</P>
<P>
   At Disney's nine-hole family Oak Trail course you have to walk
the course and pull your clubs along. The 40-acre quiet course is
par 36 with fairways lined by oak trees and plenty of water
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   The longest hole is the 517-yard No. 5 featuring a double
dog-leg with a green guarded by bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   Nine holes at Oak Trail is $20 for juniors (age 17 and under)
and $32 for adults. You can rent clubs for $15, no charge for
junior clubs. For tee times that can be reserved by resort guests
up to 60 days in advance (or 30 days in advance for non-resort
guests), call (407) 939-4653.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand Floridian Spa &AMP; Health Club _ After a stressed-out day
battling theme park crowds, even a sleazy, fake massage parlor with
gum-chewing, big-hair ``blondes'' named Tawny and Tiffany would be
relaxing. (And they model lingerie for you, too!)
</P>
<P>
   So imagine how relaxing a legit health spa would be while the
rest of the family battles wide-bodies for life-saving shade at the
Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Hours are 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. daily at the Grand Floridian Spa &AMP;
Health Club, where they'll loosen muscles you didn't know you had
in a setting so serene you'll think you're medicated in a
psychiatric ward for rich people.
</P>
<P>
   You can get treatments from around the world including Japan
(Shiatsu Therapy), Germany (The Kur), France (Thalasso Cure),
Mexico (Wild, Wild West Treatment). Massages start with a 25 minute
basic rubdown ($47.20) and run to the exotic along with facials,
manicures, pedicures and every other legal thing you can have done
to you at a spa.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a day at the spa or a day at any theme park, the smart
ones will go to the spa's front desk, hand over a credit card and
plead, ``help meeeee.''
</P>
<P>
   For reservations or information, call (407) 824-2332.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
