<HEADER>
A6227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORLANDO-CITY13-COX     06-12 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORLANDO-CITY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get up, get out, and go downtown
 &HT;    Has sidebars: ORLANDO2, ORLANDO3
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Sidestep the mousetrap.
</P>
<P>
   While most folks assume a trip to Orlando means Disney World,
you can have fun galore in Florida's largest inland city without
ever entering a theme park _ or even driving a car, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   At Church Street Station downtown, you'll find everything from a
Dixieland revue with waitresses who cancan on the bar to a
restaurant with a table that once belonged to gangster Al Capone.
Just down the way is a haunted house, and in between are bars
aplenty (consider having a drink before you meet the ax-wielding
mummy).
</P>
<P>
   Three blocks northeast of this tourist enclave is sidewalk-lined
Lake Eola, complete with swan-shaped paddle boats.
</P>
<P>
   Stroll south for about 25 minutes, and you'll hit the historic
Courtyard at Lake Lucerne, a bed-and-breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   One thing you'll notice about downtown Orlando: It's the kind of
place where people hold hands. Maybe it's because they're relaxed.
After all, it is nice not sweltering in line to board Space
Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   AT THIS `SWAN LAKE,' YOU CAN PEDAL, HIKE OR BIKE _ OR JUST RELAX
</P>
<P>
   Orlando is loaded with lakes, but its downtown landmark is Lake
Eola, encircled by a wide walkway and lush grounds. Take a stroll,
and you'll see soaring skyscrapers on one side and Spanish moss
swinging from trees on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine taking your lunch break at a place like this during the
workweek! Bikes and skates are forbidden, so this is truly a
walker's paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Water gushes down a tiered fountain that resembles a giant
wedding cake (especially at night with the lights). Park benches
are plentiful, and there's even a snack bar, playground and band
shell, home of the Orlando Shakespeare Festival each spring.
</P>
<P>
   Just to say you did it: Rent a swan-shaped paddleboat ($7 per
half hour), and enjoy some fowl play. Locals will warn you how hard
the boats are to maneuver, but they're really not that tough. (If
you get in a bind, a motorboat will tow you in.)
</P>
<P>
   If you'd rather just sit and watch other folks pedal, try Lee's
Lakeside, on the lake's southeast corner. The long-established
restaurant _ at Central Boulevard and Osceola Avenue _ offers prime
viewing, plus an awesome $16.95 Sunday brunch from 11 a.m. to 3
p.m. (Omelettes! Roast beef! Crabmeat stuffed mushrooms!)
</P>
<P>
   Dinner menu items include Florentine pasta Alfredo with pine
nuts, $8.95; fresh fruit salad with cottage cheese and sherbet,
$14.95; and lobster tail with prime rib or filet mignon, $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's is open from 11 a.m. to 10 p.m. daily, and reservations
are recommended: (407) 841-1565
</P>
<P>
   STREET SCENE: HOT DRINKS, CHEAP THRILLS
</P>
<P>
   Here, in a totally subjective analysis, is what's hot, hokey and
hair-raising in downtown Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Best-of-show strawberry daiquiri _ $5.50 at Rosie O'Grady's.
Four berries splayed on the rim, whipped cream and a cherry.
</P>
<P>
   Hottest drink (literally) _ $9.25 Flaming Hurricane hawked in
every bar at Church Street Station. Liquor concoction with lemon
extract set ablaze (really) on top. Extinguish before sippin'.
</P>
<P>
   Least attractive store (again, literally) _ The magnet specialty
shop at Church Street Exchange. Forget finding a treasure.
Everything says Florida. Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Strangest fashion trend _ Pantyhose with shorts. These gals
can't be Floridians.
</P>
<P>
   Cheapest thrill _ $5 Gyronaut ride at Church Street Market.
Strap in, flip around, and turn green in minutes (especially if
you've had a few Flaming Hurricanes).
</P>
<P>
   Goofiest huckster _ A guy sporting inflatable biceps and a
Viking hat (a motorcycle helmet topped with horns) who hands out
fliers for restaurants and bars.
</P>
<P>
   Trendiest name _ Ayme, a clerk at Speedo Authentic Fitness.
``Yes, that's really how it's spelled, but it's pronounced Amy. My
mother's very creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Most flexible pet _ Herbie the boa, wrapped around the
handlebars of Greg Walker's Harley-Davidson. ``I've never measured
him,'' says Walker, an art director.
</P>
<P>
   Sneakiest photo op _ At the end of Terror on Church Street, a
haunted house with actors that lunge at you. Eek! You'll most
likely be screaming or have your head down in this surprise
souvenir picture, which costs $10. (Admission is $12.)
</P>
<P>
   Best spot to meet strangers _ Also at Terror on Church Street,
open Monday through Thursday and Sunday from 7 p.m. to midnight;
Friday and Saturday until 1 a.m. You do a 20-minute walk-through
with your hands on the shoulders or waist of the person in front of
you. (I clutched Dennis Delgado of West Palm Beach, who was there
with his girlfriend, Suzanne Filomia.)
</P>
<P>
   Laziest way to sightsee _ Via horse-drawn carriage (think New
York's Central Park). Carriages run nightly from about 8 till
midnight, and a 30-minute jaunt costs $25 per couple (although
rates may vary depending on which driver you ask). Rides start at
Church Street Market, the newer shopping strip just outside Church
Street Station. It's worth $10 more to go all the way around Lake
Eola.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
