<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLIDE-EXPLODES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fire in the sky ignites fear in Junction
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colorado _ Bobbie Garcia saw it, but didn't
believe it, so she called the fire department to find out what was
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were scared,'' the Orchard Mesa mother said. ``It was like
'Oh my God, it's going to hit. We are dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia got home shortly after 10:30 p.m. Tuesday and called the
fire department to say she thought she, her children and some
friends saw something explode in the sky and fall west toward the
Colorado National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``He explained it was a meteorite and if you are not dead yet,
don't worry,'' she said. ``It would not have taken long.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, according to Western Colorado Astronomy Club President
Mark Goodrich, saw what's referred to as a bolide.
</P>
<P>
   A bolide is a meteor or shooting star that explodes in the sky.
Bolides are rare to witness.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich has never seen one. He's seen the moving objects' heat
until they have a white-hot tail but never what Garcia described.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it heading north up behind the Elks bingo on Orchard
Mesa,'' Garcia recalled. ``We looked up and saw a big ball of fire
out of the clouds. It had a tail and the rear end of it turned
bright red. We saw this. I swear to God on my kids. It exploded and
it shot out like a little red sparkles.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later she heard what sounded like a sonic boom.
Central dispatch said one person called Wednesday morning to report
seeing something explode above the monument.
</P>
<P>
   ``We referred them to the FAA or the UFO hot line,'' a
dispatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich said that, because Garcia heard the boom shortly after
seeing the explosion, he believes the bolide was closer than most.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 tons of space debris enter the earth's atmosphere
annually, Goodrich said. The majority of it burns up in the
atmosphere and never has the chance to touch the surface of the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff enters the atmosphere all the time but to
actually see that is unusual,'' Goodrich said. ``It is kind of
neat.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolides range in size from that of a golf ball to a house,
Goodrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich said typically the best time to see meteorites and
bolides is about 3 a.m. when the earth's rotation is in the right
position to pick out the streaks of light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen shooting stars,'' Garcia said. ``I love the sky. I'm
always watching. I'm always telling my husband to get me a
telescope. He got me a pair of binoculars. Gosh hon, I want a
telescope.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Patrick Cleary writes for The Daily Sentinel (Grand Junction,
Colorado)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
