A6231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-BOOKS13-COX     06-12 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Due this fall: sure things, in the publishing world
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ These days publishers look for the sure thing whenever
possible. The books planned for fall demonstrate that. There's
everything from Sophia Loren to George Bush to Alice Walker, to a
glorious picture book history of the West, to histories of the
journey from slavery, to a book about turning 50 (Prince Charles).
</P>
<P>
   A recent interest in memoirs, the perennial interest in
cookbooks and the public fascination with film stars made ``Sophia
Loren's Recipes &AMP; Memories'' (GT Publishing) a likely project.
Cookbooks always sell, even as diet books do.
</P>
<P>
   Laced with photographs of the star wearing an apron in the
kitchen, ``Recipes &AMP; Memories'' is the most glamorous _ if not the
most literary _ of the many new books due out this fall. (It
doesn't hurt that Loren's cookbook comes on the heels of ``Sophia
Loren,'' Warren Harris' biography of the film star from Simon &AMP;
Schuster.)
</P>
<P>
   At the recent Book Expo in Chicago, where publishers displayed
their fall lists to the nation's booksellers, Loren's cool presence
lent luster. Wearing tiny spectacles, the author/star spoke of
growing up impoverished in Italy during the turmoil of World War
II, but credited her grandmother, Nonna Luisa, with giving her a
love of cooking: soup, pasta, pizza, vegetables, desserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her genius could flavor even a few crumbs of stale bread with
herbs and turn them into an elegant dish. . . . It is to Grandma
Luisa that I wish to dedicate this cookbook. Not only for the many
things I've learned from her, but for her ability to transform even
the most ordinary food into something succulent.''
</P>
<P>
   At 63, with her taut skin and shapely legs that look decades
younger, Loren is a fine advertisement for eating from the
cookbook, to be published in October. It's her first cookbook since
1972, when Doubleday published her ``In the Kitchen With Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a month-by-month summary of some other books to watch for
in the next few months. It's only a sample. You'll notice that
several Austin writers will be among those with upcoming books,
competing with Sophia Loren for your dollars. Upcoming book
releases August ''Irrational Fears,'' by Austin's William Browning
Spencer. An offbeat novel about alcoholism and recovery (White
Wolf). ''Into That Good Night,'' an East Texas memoir by Ron
Rozelle about his father's struggle with Alzheimer's disease
(Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux). ''Farley's Jewel,'' by Jon Ferguson, a
novel about a philosopher of everyday things (Cinco Puntos Press).
''Love is a Racket,'' by John Ridley. A dark farce about a
screenwriter by the author of ``Stray Dogs'' (Knopf.) ''The
Illustrated History of Britain,'' first two volumes, by University
of Texas professor Roger Louis (Oxford). This book has raised
controversy in England because it's being put together by an
American. ''Created Unequal: The Crisis in American Pay,'' by James
K. Galbraith (The Free Press). A professor at UT's LBJ School of
Public Affairs, Galbraith argues that wage inequality is a result
of government policy and is not inevitable because of technological
advances. ''Fax Me a Bagel,'' by Sharon Kahn. A former rabbi's wife
from Austin begins a mystery series with a rabbi's wife as the
protagonist. (Scribner). September ''A World Transformed,'' by
George Bush and Brent Scowcroft. Former President Bush and his
national security adviser give a behind-the-scenes account of
foreign policy during their administration (Knopf). ''Tomcat in
Love,'' a novel by National Book Award winner Tim O'Brien
(Broadway). Instead of Vietnam, O'Brien is writing about an English
teacher and his attempt to find intimacy. ''The Loop,'' a novel by
Nicholas Evans, who wrote ``The Horse Whisperer'' (Delacorte).
''Written in Stone: Public Monuments in Changing Societies'' by UT
law professor Sanford Levinson (Duke). ''The Farming of Bones,'' a
novel by Haitian American writer Edwidge Danticat, one of the
literary magazine Granta's best young novelists. ''The Voyage of
the Narwhal,'' a novel by Andrea Barrett about the exploration of
the Arctic. Her ``Ship Fever'' won the National Book Award. ''The
New Encyclopedia of the American West,'' edited by Howard R. Lamar.
It contains many Texas references (Yale University Press). ''In the
Black,'' by Fran Harris. The African American Parent's Guide to
Raising Financially Responsible Children (Fireside) by an Austin
Entrepreneur of the Year. ''Something to Declare,'' essays by Julia
Alvarez (Algonquin), author of ``How the Garcia Girls Lost Their
Accents.'' These essays deal with her exile from the Dominican
Republic and her split cultural identity. ''Welcome to the World,
Baby Girl,'' a new novel by Fannie Flagg, author of ``Fried Green
Tomatoes'' (Random House). ''Rumble Tumble,'' by Joe R. Lansdale.
The outrageous East Texas writer brings back Hap Collins and
Leonard Pine for a road trip through the Southwest
(Warner/Mysterious Press). ''Rude Behavior'' by Dan Jenkins. This
is the sequel to ``Semi-Tough,'' a classic novel about Texas
football (Doubleday). ''Holes,'' by Louis Sachar. This novel for
age 12 and up by an Austin writer deals with a boy sent by mistake
to a juvenile detention center (Farrar Straus Giroux). October
''Africans in America: America's Journey Through Slavery,'' by
Patricia Smith and Charles Johnson. This book, a companion to a PBS
series, tells the story of American history from the African
American point of view and includes short stories by Johnson
(Harcourt, Brace). ''By the Light of My Father's Smile,'' a new
novel by Alice Walker. It's about a family from the United States
who goes to Mexico and encounters the Mundo, a band of mixed race
blacks and Indians (Random House). ''I Married a Communist,'' a
tragic novel by Philip Roth set in the McCarthy era (Houghton
Mifflin). ''Purple Dots,'' a novel by Jim Lehrer. Set in
Washington, D.C., this political mystery centers on the president's
nominee for CIA director. ''The Ladies of St. Petersburg,'' three
novellas by Nina Berberova translated from Russian by Austin's
Marian Schwartz (New Directions). ''Hill Country,'' a novel by
Janice Woods Windle, author of ``True Women'' (Longstreet). ''Cruel
as the Grave,'' a medieval mystery by Sharon Kay Penman, a UT
graduate (Henry Holt). ''Bech at Bay,'' a quasi-novel by John
Updike. Five new chapters from the life of Jewish American writer
Henry Bech (Knopf). ''A Likely Story,'' by Rosemary Mahoney. The
author of ``Whoredom in Kimmage'' writes about the summer she spent
working for Lillian Hellman (Doubleday). ''Ex Libris: Confessions
of a Common Reader,'' by Anne Fadiman. The award-winning author of
``The Spirit Catches You and You Fall Down'' writes about books and
language. ''Incident at Twenty Mile,'' by Trevanian. Fifteen years
since his last book, this former Austinite writes a Western
thriller (St. Martin's). ''The Oxford History of the Twentieth
Century,'' edited by Michael Howard and William Roger Louis
(Oxford). ''Values of the Game,'' 10 essays on basketball by Bill
Bradley, with a foreword by Phil Jackson (Artisan). ''Dutch'' by
Edmund Morris, a biography of Ronald Reagan (Random House).
November ''A Man in Full,'' a novel by Tom Wolfe (Farrar Straus
Giroux). ''All Too Human: A Political Education,'' by George
Stephanopoulos (Little, Brown). ''The Good Man of Nanking: The
Diaries of John Rabe,'' edited by Erwin Wickert (Knopf). These
diaries deal with the German businessman who saved lives during the
rape of Nanking. ''Final Verdict: The True Account of the Murder of
John F. Kennedy,'' by Vincent Bugliosi. One more account of the
assassination (Norton). ''Baking Across America,'' by Arthur L.
Meyer, the Austin author of ``Texas Tortes'' (UT Press). ''The Love
of a Good Woman,'' stories by Alice Munro. Eight new stories by
this Canadian master (Knopf). ''Oona: Living in the Shadows,'' by
Jane Scovell. This is a biography of Oona O'Neill, daughter of
Eugene O'Neill and wife of Charlie Chaplin (Warner). ''Charles at
Fifty,'' by Anthony Holden. Prince Charles turns 50 on Nov. 14, and
Holden assesses him (Random House). December ''Barbara Jordan: An
American Hero,'' by Austin writer Mary Beth Rogers, who taught with
Jordan (Bantam). ''Distraction,'' by Austin's award-winning science
fiction writer Bruce Sterling (Bantam). ''Careless Love: The
Unmaking of Elvis Presley,'' by Peter Guralnick. This is the
concluding volume in the life of Elvis (Little, Brown). ''Biggie
and the Fricasseed Fat Man,'' by Nancy Bell. This third novel by
the UT sorority house mother is about small-town Texas life.
January
</P>
<P>
   ''The Mother-in-Law Diaries,'' a comic novel about family by
Austin writer Carol Dawson (Algonquin). ''The Tale of a Dog,'' by
Austin poet Lars Gustafsson (New Directions). Anne Morris is a
staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
