<HEADER>
A6232 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-6DAYS13-COX     06-12 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-6DAYS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford, Heche crash on Island: this romantic comedy does too
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harrison Ford and Anne Heche may be stuck on a deserted island
in ``Six Days, Seven Nights,'' but the real problem is they've been
stranded without much of a script.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay, such as it is, doesn't know whether it wants to
be a romantic comedy or an adventure saga. As a compromise, it's
anemic at both. Like Ford's rickety airplane, which is hemorrhaging
oil when we first see it, ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' is about a
quart low. Low on excitement, low on chemistry between its stars,
low on reason for being.
</P>
<P>
   To escape snowy New York, magazine editor Robin Monroe (Heche)
and her puppyish boyfriend (``Friends''' David Schwimmer) head to a
Pacific island resort, chartering a ride from surly
pilot-mechanic-beach bum Quinn Harris (Ford). Before long, though,
an unexpected assignment arises for Robin in Tahiti and she is
flying off again with Quinn, straight into a tropical storm. Before
you can say ``Gilligan,'' they are forced into an emergency landing
on a gorgeous, uninhabited island, far from civilization and
cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   So Robin and Quinn bicker and banter in that Hollywood semaphore
that is code for the imminent outbreak of love. When screenwriter
Michael Browning tires of this _ long after we have _ he brings
ashore a band of pirates that can't shoot straight to chase after
the fun couple. Add a scorpion in Robin's hair and a snake down her
shorts and you have a prototype for a new thrill ride at Disney
World.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't have is a sufficiently interesting movie. In
part, that's because Ford makes a gruff, ham-handed light comedian.
(Didn't anyone at Touchstone see ``Sabrina''?) So halfway through,
the movie makes a course correction, taking a left turn into Ford's
action hero strength. But these days, it is hard to get very worked
up over a handful of cross-eyed pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Since being cast as Robin, Heche has gone public with her
lesbian orientation, which suddenly gave this movie some off-screen
drama. If ``Six Days'' disappoints at the box office, she
undoubtedly will be made the scapegoat. Heche's relationship with
Ford is truly hard to buy, but that's because he is nearly 30 years
older than she is. The age mismatch is so apparent that the movie
jokes about it, but the problem lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Heche gamely does a few comic pratfalls, looking alternately
silly and smashing, changing outfits several times on the desert
island. Maybe she found a Gap outlet hidden among the jungle trees.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is directed by Ivan Reitman (``Ghostbusters,''
``Dave'') with a definite energy deficiency, but a keen eye for
paradise landscapes. The movie looks good, but it fails to grab and
hold our interest. As a hybrid romance-adventure, it seems
calculated to reach a demographically wide audience, but neither
part of this Polynesian stew is very satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
