<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPMAN-COLUMN-COX &UR; $AD     06-12 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPMAN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
   $ADV14  AN AMERICAN-TRAINED JOURNALIST
LANGUISHES IN NIGERIAN PRISON
 &HT;     For release Sunday, June 14.
 &HT;     By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An American-trained journalist has been languishing
in a Nigerian prison since May 1995, her health deteriorating, her
eyesight failing.
</P>
<P>
   What was the crime for which this 46-year-old mother of two was
sentenced to life in prison, later reduced to 15 years?
</P>
<P>
   She did what she had learned to do here in the United States:
she wrote an article critical of the government of Nigerian
dictator Gen. Sani Abacha, who died of a heart attack on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   For that action, Christiana Anyanwu was hauled before a military
tribunal and tried _ without even a lawyer to plead her case _ on
charges of treason.
</P>
<P>
   American journalists write critical articles about the
government every day with little fear that their stories will not
result in harsh reprisals. Around the world, courageous journalists
risk their freedom and their lives when they attempt to write or
broadcast the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The Committee to Protect Journalists recently reported that 20
other journalists are in Nigerian prisons. Mrs. Anyanwu is the only
woman among those prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, Nigeria is far away, and what happens there
barely registers on our conscience. But the United States has a
strong interest in Nigeria. It is one of the world's leading oil
producers, and recent offshore finds suggest petroleum reserves
rivaling those in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   American oil companies deal extensively with Nigeria, and what
America thinks should matter very much to the military strong men
who rule the country with an iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Mrs. Anyanwu was a media star in her native land.
After receiving her bachelor's degree at the University of Missouri
and her masters degree at Florida State University she returned to
Nigeria in 1979 and covered the National Assembly on Nigerian
television. In 1990, she left television to establish a news
magazine, The Sunday Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Things got dicey when the military refused to accept the June
12, 1993, election of Chief Mashood K. Abiola. Although Abiola won
with 58 percent of the vote in an election monitored by more than
1,000 international observers, the military didn't like the
results.
</P>
<P>
   They threw President-elect Abiola in prison where he, too,
remains without medical attention. Mrs. Anyanwu wrote an article
urging recognition of the election and Chief Abiola's installation
as president. For that she was accused of participating in a
military coup to overthrow the military junta.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last week at the National Press Club, Chief
Abiola's daughter, Hafsat, 23, a magna cum laude graduate of
Harvard University, said she could empathize with Mrs. Anyanwu's
22-year-old daughter, Ihuoma, who recently graduated from Rutgers
University.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Abiola said she could understand Miss Anyanwu's anguish in
not being able to see her mother. Miss Abiola's mother was
assassinated, her body riddled with bullets, as she rode in a car
to the Canadian Embassy to seek support for her imprisoned husband.
</P>
<P>
   But Miss Abiola said Miss Anyanwu's anguish has a different
quality. At least Miss Abiola knows what happened to her mother.
Miss Anyanwu doesn't know from day to day how her mother is being
treated; whether she is being properly fed, or _ as Miss Abiola
said _ whether her mother is being assaulted by prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   For Mrs. Anyanwu's daughter, her 16-year-old son, and her
husband, a visiting professor at Howard University, not knowing her
fate is a terrible anguish they endure daily. The family had to
flee Nigeria when Mrs. Anyanwu was arrested because, in Nigeria,
the government often arrests the entire family when persecuting one
member.
</P>
<P>
   The hallmark of a democratic government is freedom of the press.
Clearly, in Nigeria, where reporters are jailed for writing
articles the government doesn't like, there is no freedom of the
press and no democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the National Press Club last week
hand-delivered a letter to the Nigerian Embassy urging its new
leader, Gen. Abdusalam Abubakar, to release Mrs. Anyanwu. Failing
that, the press club urged that she at least be allowed to receive
medical attention, which the club has agreed to sponsor. (A
personal disclosure: I am the vice president of the National Press
Club.)
</P>
<P>
   The death of Gen. Abacha last week gives Nigeria a golden
opportunity to restore democracy. Gen. Abubakar has indicated he
will hold elections this fall, but he did not offer any hope for
the release of Mrs. Anyanwu or Chief Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   If he's serious about restoring democracy, he will release Mrs.
Anyanwu and her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6242 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CROSBY13-COX     06-12 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CROSBY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music reunites Crosby, son he gave away
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a three-decade rock 'n' roll career, David Crosby has
probably supplied enough stories to keep a struggling supermarket
tabloid from going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Tales of heroin and cocaine addictions. A nine-month stint in a
Texas prison. And a down-to-the-wire liver transplant that saved
his life in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But the most remarkable story is just emerging.
</P>
<P>
   While Crosby was preparing for his transplant, he learned a son
he gave up for adoption in the '60s had been searching for him. He
met the man, James Raymond, and discovered that his abandoned child
had grown up to be _ what else? _ a successful keyboardist and
composer.
</P>
<P>
   The two started writing songs together, hooked up with studio
guitarist Jeff Pevar and faster than you can say Crosby, Stills and
Nash, a new trio was born.
</P>
<P>
   Call them Crosby, Pevar and Raymond, or CPR for short. Given
that they started just as Crosby was getting a second lease on
life, the name certainly applies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a song fountain, we have been writing so much,'' the
56-year-old Crosby brags of the new group, which played the
Carefree Theatre in West Palm Beach, Fla., on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, 36, confirms the atmosphere has been electric. ``I
think we both hear things very much the same way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond was born when the future Rock and Roll Hall of Famer was
a young, wayward musician. The child was the result of a fleeting
relationship _ Crosby refuses to identify the mother _ and was put
up for adoption immediately. ``I was still a kid. There was no way
I could have parented anybody, and the girl who was his mom knew
that,'' Crosby recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But he never forgot the son he fathered _ and as he was awaiting
a new liver, his thoughts grew stronger. ``I was in the hospital
dying, and I knew that I had a son out there some place . . . I had
been beating myself for years about not being there for this kid,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Raymond had done well in the intervening three
decades. Growing up in relative comfort in California _ Crosby's
home state _ he pursued music from an early age, studying classical
first, then jazz. After a short stint at California State
University, he went professional and by the time he was 30, he was
musical director for an award-winning Nickelodeon series
(``Roundhouse'') and a busy touring sideman for everyone from Chaka
Khan to Take 6.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond had known he was adopted from the time he was in grade
school. But it was only when he was established personally (he's
married to a screenwriter and producer) and professionally that he
decided to seek out his birth parents. Imagine his shock when he
saw the name David Crosby on his birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was the David Crosby,'' he recalls. But he
checked around and discovered it was true. He contacted Crosby just
before his transplant, and the two met for lunch three months later
in February 1995 at the UCLA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Raymond describes the encounter: ``There are certain
points in life when everything skews in a new direction, and that
was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   And Crosby? ``He was this nice, decent young guy and we became
friends immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and collaborators. The pair, who consider their
relationship more brotherly than father-and-son, compared musical
notes and found out they had similar tastes and sensibilities.
Granted, Raymond didn't own any CSN albums _ ``I'm a keyboard
player. I spent all my money on Elton John and Stevie Wonder
records'' _ but he knew the group well enough to sing along with
the radio as a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered why I blended so well,'' he kids.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby sparked the professional association by giving Raymond a
homework assignment _ the lyrics to a song he was writing inspired
by the tumultuous life of Jim Morrison. ``He was more worried than
I was that it was going to suck,'' Raymond recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But the results spoke otherwise: ``Incredible'' is how Crosby
describes the finished product.
</P>
<P>
   The pair played the piece for Graham Nash at his house _ and it
just so happened that Pevar, a guitarist who's worked with CSN,
also was there. ``He started jamming, and that's when the idea (for
the group) came to David,'' recalls Raymond. By January 1997, CPR
was playing dates.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crosby will slip in reworked versions of some of his
greatest hits in concert, the group is clearly not a CSN clone. If
anything, critics have likened its jazzy sensibility to another
group from the past, Steely Dan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely David's folk influence, but harmonically it
is pretty advanced kind of stuff,'' Raymond explains. ``I don't
know if jazz is the right word to describe the flavor, but it's
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Crosby also struggles to define the band's style and influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's jazz and funk and folk music and Steely Dan and
probably Bruce Hornsby and lots of different people . . . It's
advanced singer-songwriter music,'' he says. ``I haven't been able
to come up with a name for what we are. The only thing I can do is
encourage you to listen and make up your own name. We don't sound
like anybody I know of.''
</P>
<P>
   All the members have limited commercial expectations, even
though they are releasing a debut album in late June. Crosby plans
on touring with CSN again and is putting the finishing touches on a
book and documentary called ``Stand and Be Counted,'' about the
charitable work of entertainers. Raymond, who recently worked as a
keyboardist on a Spice Girls TV special, is scoring a one-hour
drama for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But when Crosby and Raymond are not playing together, they're
often with each other at their California homes. ``We live about a
45-minute flight (away) in a Cessna 182,'' says Crosby. Their wives
have grown close and so have their children. Raymond has a
3-year-old daughter, Grace, and Crosby a 3-year-old son, Django.
(He also has a grown daughter from a previous relationship.)
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell whether the children will also grow up to
become musicians, but the odds are probably with them. As Raymond
says of his musical links to Crosby, ``I think this makes a very
strong case for genetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
