<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, never one to duck
an easy compromise, has declared that 2000 will be known as the
``millennial year.'' (Glass, Cox News Service) MOVED 6/10.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ A far from colorblind criminal justice system is
turning a bad-enough black disproportion in crime into an even
worse disproportion in needless social damage. It is deepening and
perpetuating poverty, undermining family formation and, in the name
of fighting crime, creating crime. A confluence of recent studies
has produced a powerful stream of evidence. (Teepen, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Just prior to a naturalization ceremony in
Miami Beach last week, a Colombian woman who had studied English in
night school for four years made a fatal slip-up with an INS
employee. In a conversation with him about changing her name as a
result of a divorce, her English failed. The INS official seized
upon that and denied her a place among the 2,000 receiving
citizenship that day. It's another example of our illogical
language laws. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ The first thing that struck me on my vacation
return to my old hometown, Mobile, Ala., was the hotel.Not any of
the new commercial places, but Malaga Inn, a small hotel made up of
two 1850 houses linked by a lobby and a walled garden. (Sibley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/11.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ We have good news from Washington for a change.
President Clinton and his cardboard sidekick, Al Gore, have ordered
government bureaucrats to stop writing gobbledygook and use plain
English. (Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
