<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLACK-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUD THREATENS HOME, SWEET HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARY CLACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As a new day unfolds on this neighborhood, a
Batman bedsheet hanging on a clothesline is blowing and billowing
in the wind. The smell of coffee and bacon and tortillas mingle
pleasantly as they float on an aromatic breeze. Sleepily, but
surely, the neighborhood comes alive.
</P>
<P>
   Two women stand on their porches and talk about their children.
Other women are walking their own children to day care.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly man sits on his porch and watches as younger men,
clutching lunch pails or brown bags, head to work. A man jokes with
his son as he opens the car door for him while a pair of teen-agers
walks to a bus stop.
</P>
<P>
   Mornings in this neighborhood are like mornings in other
neighborhoods except for one significant difference. This
neighborhood is Victoria Courts and its mornings are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development is forcing
the San Antonio Housing Authority to demolish the Victoria Courts
housing project and sell its 44 acres. All the residents, 660
families, will have to be relocated by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In the relocation lies the rub.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Courts, which was built in 1942, was never meant to be
a permanent home, just a temporary abode until the residents could
afford something better.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened with public housing projects in the United
States is what has happened in any neighborhood in any country in
any era where there is a high density of poverty and unemployment:
hopelessness sets in and breeds crime, juvenile delinquency, drug
use and other ills.
</P>
<P>
   A key to breaking the cycle of hopelessness is, as sociologist
William Julius Wilson has been writing for years, to disperse the
poor in quality subsidized housing throughout the city, including
the suburbs. The most important thing this does is put the poor in
areas where there are more and better jobs than in their previous
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The solution for Victoria Courts residents is to break up the
concentration of poverty and relocate residents to other
neighborhoods. Even better _ build subsidized single-dwelling homes
on Victoria Courts' 44 acres and allow some residents to return.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Courts has developed a reputation as one of the most
dangerous areas in San Antonio, a city of 1 million people. But its
residents see things others don't.
</P>
<P>
   Two summers ago I wrote an article on a photo project by some of
the children who lived in Victoria Courts. The photographs they
took revealed what they saw in their neighborhood. There were
photos of flowers, trees, pets, family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   They knew about the unpleasant parts of life in the courts, but
they focused their cameras on those things that made them feel
loved and connected to something.
</P>
<P>
   For all its problems and perceptions, Victoria Courts is a
neighborhood where people get up in the morning to go to work,
where neighbors share triumphs and sorrows and where children play
in the grass and dirt courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Few of us would choose to live there and may not understand why
those who do feel so strongly about having to leave. Actually, it's
quite simple: for now, at least, it is their home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cary Clack is a columnist for the San Antonio Express-News,
P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
