<SLUG> BC-FLORES-COLUMN-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER TO THE PEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 14)   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VERONICA FLORES  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ I'm not sure at what point in the middle of this
sure-to-be record-hot summer I decided that buying a mountain bike
was a great idea for outdoor recreation.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly wasn't after biting the dust the other day on one
of the rocky trails in Austin's Green Belt. Nor was it when I and a
friendly mountain biker who wouldn't let me fall behind briefly
lost the pack of bikers we were riding with _ at night, on the same
Green Belt, decidedly a spooky experience.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, I remember now. The great idea must have hit me around the
time I wheeled my shiny new bicycle out of the bike shop earlier
this month. The sales clerks _ enthusiasts all _ had assured me it
would be, in mountain-bikespeak, a bad (expletive) experience.
Sleek black and that new-car smell emanating from the fat rubber
tires, the bicycle was to be my answer to boredom with the gym.
</P>
<P>
   One night ride on the treacherous Green Belt and several scrapes
and bruises later, that boredom is wiped out. Soon to be gone, too,
will be my ignorance about bicycling.
</P>
<P>
   My interest in the sport was piqued last month with San
Antonio's Bike Week. The week of activities was designed to promote
the sport and, more importantly, to encourage use of bicycles as an
alternative to air-dirtying motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The latter has moved to the forefront in recent years as this
South Texas city grapples with the issue of air quality.
</P>
<P>
   The first month in the bike seat has been hard _ literally _ for
someone who hadn't been on a bike in years. (Of course, if I could
back pedal, I probably wouldn't take my first trail ride at night
on the Green Belt. I must have had my helmet on too tight.)
</P>
<P>
   I have, however, gained a new perspective. And what I've seen so
far isn't encouraging for bicycle enthusiasts, particularly those
who dare to take to the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers on the city's main streets navigate their vehicles at
our peril. They don't like to share the road, although it occurs to
me that some appear to do so simply because they don't know how
they should drive around bicyclists. I used to be guilty of that.
</P>
<P>
   Just share the space, that's all we ask. And, for heaven's sake,
signal before you make those turns. We're not mind-readers and we
have no desire to become road kill.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not all bad. I am finding the benefits of bicycling
outweigh the negatives _ namely, the exercise that the pastime can
provide. That's especially so for me as my neighborhood is dotted
with hills (OK, so maybe they're actually just gradual inclines)
that are just the right size for a beginner who wants to get a good
workout, but who doesn't have a death wish.
</P>
<P>
   The slower cruise through my neighborhood also has given me the
opportunity to check out streets and people who are tucked out of
sight and otherwise unseen to drivers in fast-moving cars.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find that in any gym. Besides, I figure I'd look
awfully silly wearing that helmet while sitting on a stationary
bike.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Veronica Flores is a columnist for the San Antonio
Express-News, P.O. Box 2171, San Antonio, TX 78297.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
