<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIX-DAYS-FILM-REVIEW-     06-12 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIX-DAYS-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-FASHIONED FUN IN `SIX DAYS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' is the kind of movie its creators
must have fallen in love with on the late show on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay that Michael Browning wrote for director Ivan
Reitman makes the Harrison Ford character a distillate of John
Wayne and Clark Gable, with a bit of Lee Marvin thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   The Anne Heche character is an amalgam of Irene Dunne, Katharine
Hepburn and Myrna Loy from an heiress-on-the-run story. The heiress
has been updated a bit. She's a ``career woman'' facing the
Rosalind Russell job-vs.-picket-fence dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   The romance of the story is basted to the
lost-on-an-uncharted-South-Seas-island pattern. Writer Browning has
seen 'em all, and he has taken notes.
</P>
<P>
   Robin (Heche) is an assistant editor for a Cosmo-like magazine
called Dazzle. Her boyfriend, Frank (David Schwimmer), whisks her
away to a romantic Polynesian resort, where he proposes marriage
and she accepts.
</P>
<P>
   But their idyll is interrupted. Robin is dispatched to Tahiti to
supervise a photo shoot. She hires a scruffy, hard-drinking charter
pilot named Quinn (Ford) and his scruffier monoplane. Both, Quinn
tells her, are ``old but sturdy.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn runs into the inevitable storm and must crash-land in the
inevitable uncharted island paradise.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the sort of person who thinks, ``Wait a minute, it's
1998 and there's an island that big and that pretty that doesn't
have a La Quinta and a Denny's?'' you may have a problem here.
You'll enjoy it more if you're the type who can extend romantic
license to the filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The process of the film is for the thrown-together twosome to
bicker and clinch, then bicker and clinch some more while avoiding
the island paradise's resident peril. In island movies of the past,
it has been cannibals. I had guessed the updating would make drug
runners the peril. I'll leave the discovery of the compromise to
you.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the emotional process of the narrative in this
sort of thing has been the plug horse (Ford) cutting the
thoroughbred (Heche) down to his size and her eventually liking it.
To that tradition these filmmakers have bowed _ make that
genuflected.
</P>
<P>
   Reitman uses his Hawaiian locations effectively, and his leading
players are certainly appealing. Heche is especially amusing at
slipping Robin back and forth between tough and girlish when she
senses which will be to her advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there is not quite enough narrative to spread over 97
minutes. But the film's utter predictability is offered as charm,
and the dialogue is reasonably happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Days'' offers a coy little exchange between Robin and
Quinn to acknowledge that during the shoot Ford became eligible at
many banks for free checking accounts because of his senior status.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn invites the 29-year-old Robin to guess his age. She starts
at a rosy 45. Quinn smiles crinkily and bids her up to 50.
Fifty?!?! Get out. So how old is he?
</P>
<P>
   And right there, lost on an uncharted island with no one around
but a movie camera, Quinn ...
</P>
<P>
   Go see for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Six Days, Seven Nights is rated PG-13, for language, sensuality
and brief violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
