<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KURT-FILM-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      06-12 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURT-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COBAINS: A TABLOID VIEW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEFF MILLAR 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As ``Kurt &AMP; Courtney'' unfolds, it displays the gap between what
filmmaker Nick Broomfield promises and what he delivers, which is a
film that might more accurately have been titled ``Nick &AMP;
Courtney's Lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Courtney of both titles is Courtney Love, the Widow Cobain,
who was married to Kurt Cobain _ of the music group Nirvana _ when
Cobain was found dead with a gunshot wound to the head in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who are not satisfied with the official
pronouncement that Cobain was a suicide; a cottage industry has
developed to serve these folks. The conspiracy theory with the most
sizzle points to the ambitious Widow Cobain as the holder of the
smoking (hired) gun.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield is a British documentarist whose recent output has
boasted films about New York City sado-masochism clubs, a female
Florida serial killer and call-girl entrepreneur Heidi Fless.
</P>
<P>
   He is not, of course, the first filmmaker to put a
borderline-unethical title to one of his films. The ``Kurt &AMP;
Courtney'' title suggests that he set out to give us a portrait of
what he considers today's First Family of Rock, starting with his
subjects' tough-as-nails childhood years.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that the first thing that Broomfield learned was
this: The principal difference between Courtney Before Kurt Died
and Courtney After Kurt Died is that this unpleasant and obscure
woman became an equally unpleasant but now famous woman with
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Likely because she learned Broomfield was soliciting information
from those who would depict her as a shrike _ her estranged father
entered the Kurt industry with a book concluding that his daughter
was quite capable of calling up a hit on her husband _ the Widow
Cobain began opposing the filmmaker.
</P>
<P>
   With no access to members of Cobain's handlers or band, and
without license to the music controlled by Love, Broomfield was
compelled to make a film about how he was not able to do what he
wanted. In the process, he has been able to show off his First
Amendment stigmata.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield, who carries his own tape recorder and boom mike,
makes himself the protagonist of this venture. He personally
records the corporate weasel who confides on the phone that a
Certain Someone has succeeded in cutting off the corporation's
backing of the film project.
</P>
<P>
   Documentaries like this have a way of turning me into a city
editor (worse: into a school of communications associate
professor), barking phrases like ``attribution'' and
``substantiation.'' I forget that a feature film is not a news
story, and viewers are probably less interested in the quality of
Broomfield's journalism and his ethics than whether the film is
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Provided you can get beyond the whiff of hypocrisy (Broomfield
wants us to think that he's swimming with stinkfish but he's not a
stinkfish himself), ``Kurt &AMP; Courtney'' is entertaining in a
tabloid-TV sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield is aware that in the United States legal protection
from libel decreases roughly in inverse proportion to ascending
fame. He'll put anybody in front of his camera who has something
negative to say about Courtney Love, provided it will grab our
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Love's father seems to revel in delivering enthusiastic payback
for his daughter's making him miserable during her adolescence.
Broomfield also tracks down a grotesquerie named El Duce _ we see a
clip of El Duce's garage video called ``I Want You to Be My Sex
Slave'' _ who says that the pre-Widow Cobain offered him $50K to
whack Cobain and ``I shoulda took it.'' El Duce was later struck
and killed by a train.
</P>
<P>
   But the bits remaining of the film that Broomfield seems to have
intended to make at the outset are more affecting.
</P>
<P>
   There are interviews with the high school principal who gave
Cobain shelter when he could abide neither of his parents; pictures
of the bridge under which Cobain slept; shots of Cobain's
despairing paintings; recordings of him singing at age 2; and
videotapes of him as a teen-ager, taken by his fond Aunt Mary.
</P>
<P>
   These are poignant moments that tend to convince us that,
contrary to everything else in the film, Cobain probably needed no
assistance in deciding to end his melancholy life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
