u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HABITAT-ENERGY-ART-HN     06-12 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-ENERGY-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABITAT VOLUNTEERS TO BUILD ENERGY-EFFICIENT HOMES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Art available on NYT photo service) 
 
By MELANIE COFFEE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Habitat for Humanity is not just making houses
affordable for local families, it's trying to keep them that way.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of the 1998 Jimmy Carter Work Project, the
organization plans to build 100 homes for low-income families next
week _ all to be constructed under strict energy-efficient
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building our homes to be energy-efficient is the right thing
to do,'' said Michael Shirl, executive director of Houston Habitat
for Humanity. ``Our homes will allow our homeowners to save on
their utility bills, and to low-income families, that is additional
money they really need.''
</P>
<P>
   Two programs will join in making sure that Habitat for Humanity
meets its goals for the new houses in the Fifth Ward, a historic
African-American hub that fell on hard times between 1970 and 1990,
and areas in and around Magnolia Park, a neighborhood with a rich
Hispanic tradition that dates to about 1910.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Cents Homes program, offered through Houston Lighting &AMP;
Power Co., has been working with Habitat for Humanity since 1996 to
make its homes energy-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 new houses will also be inspected under the federal
government's EnergySTAR program standards. Devised by the U.S.
Department of Energy and the Environmental Protection Agency, the
program certifies homes and products that help conserve energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Cents program and the EnergySTAR program are very
parallel,'' Shirl said. ``We belong to both because they are geared
towards energy efficiency, but the EnergySTAR takes their program a
little further.''
</P>
<P>
   To become certified under the Good Cents Program, each new house
will be inspected for efficient heating and cooling equipment,
caulking around the windows and air ducts and weather-stripping
around the doors to decrease the amount of wind that can leak into
a house, said Stacy Davis, Good Cents program accounts manager.
</P>
<P>
   Thick insulation will be installed in the walls and even thicker
insulation in the attics to help keep heat outside in the summer
and inside during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, double-paned windows will be tinted to help
deflect sunlight, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The new houses can be certified as energy-efficient after all
reports, including the findings by Good Cents, have been reviewed
by EnergySTAR program representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing about what Houston is doing is that people
will be able to see how successful EnergySTAR is at saving
energy,'' said Sam Rashkin, EnergyStar program director.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA blames household energy use for 20 percent of all carbon
dioxide emissions. If all U.S. households and businesses conformed
to EnergySTAR guidelines _ which include using energy-efficient
equipment and air ducts, high-performance windows and thick
insulation _ the reduction in gas emissions would be equivalent to
removing 21 million cars from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Shirl got the idea to promote energy-conserving houses for
Habitat for Humanity while working on his own home.
</P>
<P>
   Now Houston Habitat for Humanity is known for its high-quality,
energy-conserving homes. Last year, it won the Building Innovation
Award from the National Partners in Homeownership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
