<HEADLINE>
`KILLING THE DREAM' PILES UP EVIDENCE AGAINST RAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the last 30 years, millions of Americans have refused to
believe a racist hillbilly and prison escapee could plot the murder
of a national leader, and successfully spend two months on the lam
before being apprehended in London.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion has been fueled by conspiracy theorists, who in turn
were led on by James Earl Ray, who after pleading guilty to killing
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., would spend nearly three decades
seeking to overturn his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Killing the Dream: James Earl Ray and the Assassination of
Martin Luther King Jr.,'' author and investigative reporter Gerald
Posner presents what is in essence a biography of the assassin.
</P>
<P>
   Posner takes readers on an unsettling journey through the
underbelly of American life. His book recounts the hardscrabble
poverty and brutality of Ray's upbringing, brings us into the
whorehouses where the assassin satisfied his sexual desires, and
visits flophouse after flophouse.
</P>
<P>
   The book shows how an inhabitant of such a world can be
mean-clever, accomplished at using aliases, and able to concoct
stories to cover his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Posner has exhaustively tracked Ray, however. He is convinced it
was this man, perhaps pursuing a bounty offered by rich
segregationists, who murdered King. He piles up the evidence that
the killer acted alone. The perennial loser was just lucky enough
to find King leaning over a balcony at the Lorraine Motel in
Memphis. The apostle of non-violence was a perfect target.
</P>
<P>
   If Ray had not spotted two police cars, when walking briskly
from the scene of the murder, he may never have been caught. He
dropped a bundle containing the murder weapon. His fingerprints
were found on the rifle, its telescopic sight, binoculars and two
other items.
</P>
<P>
   Posner is at his best when debunking conspiracy theorists. He
blows hole after hole in Ray's longstanding alibi about being set
up by a mystery man named ``Raoul.'' The book's climax comes when
Ray's defenders find a retired auto worker in New Jersey whose name
matches one of the fantasy leads.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the poor man, an immigrant from Portugal, had never
been anywhere else in the United States except for a brief
work-related trip to Portland, Ore. Suddenly he finds his home
staked out by ``investigators'' and the trash news media.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theories get mixed. At one point, an investigator
tells Ray's attorney, William Pepper, ``We can tie him (Raoul) into
the Kennedy assassination a lot better than the Martin Luther King
assassination.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' Pepper yells. ``We can't say that. That would ruin
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point, conspiracy buffs charge that King was really
assassinated by Army Special Forces troops. The leader of the
covert team is identified as a Captain Billy R. Eidson. Eidson is
conveniently listed as dead, and hence removed from questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The theory takes off, moving from Montel Williams' TV show to a
Court TV program with Johnnie Cochrane. Quietly, retirees in the
Special Forces Association track down Eidson. He is very much
alive. It turns out he was never in Memphis. On the day of the
assassination, Eidson was on duty with the Birmingham, Ala., fire
department.
</P>
<P>
   The dishonest, duplicitous behavior of Ray's defenders takes the
breath away, as does the gullibility of King's family. The son of
the slain civil rights leader, Dexter King, meets with Ray in
prison and proclaims his innocence. The TV cameras roll.
</P>
<P>
   Ray died recently. He can lie no more. Still, as Posner
relentlessly documents, the business of fabricating and marketing
conspiracies has found quite a market.
</P>
<P>
   In Ray's case, a special House committee on assassinations
probed his alibi in the late 1970s and revealed its multiple
falsehoods. But that did not keep the BBC from producing a sloppy
``documentary'' on British TV that exonerated the killer. Thames TV
of Britain, and Home Box Office, would pay $140,000 to Ray's lawyer
to ``investigate the case,'' and staged a mock trial at which Ray
was found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, incidentally, the role of prosecutor was played by
one Hickman Ewing Jr., a former U.S. attorney from Tennessee. The
same Hickman Ewing is today a top deputy to Whitewater special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr, who has spent four years and consumed $35
million of the taxpayers' money on an investigation that has yet to
prove a single conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Killing the Dream: James Earl Ray and the Assassination of
Martin Luther King Jr. By Gerald Posner. Random House, $25, 446
pages.
</P>
</TEXT>
