<HEADLINE>
PSYCHOLOGIST ASSURES MOMS THAT PARENTING IS NO WALTZ FOR ANYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LYNN STEINBERG  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's true. Misery loves company. So when
``relationship expert'' Harriet Lerner admits to being a
less-than-perfect parent _ acknowledges that ``when I get angry
enough, intense enough, I have the brain of a reptile'' _ we take
comfort in knowing we're not alone, that given the right set of
circumstances, the best of parents can behave like lunatics.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner recounts times when, in the heat of a fight, her younger
son, Ben, would glare at her and say: ``How can you write about
relationships? Just look at you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lerner, a psychologist and author, reminds us in her newest
book that when it comes to raising children, logic often eludes us
and no amount of training can adequately prepare us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mother Dance,'' (HarperCollins, 319 pages, $25) draws on
research, case studies and Lerner's own experience as a parent and
therapist to paint an authentic, engaging and occasionally
hilarious portrait of motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   There are no instructions on how to do it right. Just a
refreshingly real look at the ways in which children change a
woman's life.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, author of the best seller ``The Dance of Anger,''
initially set out to do a book on parenting, but was dissuaded by
the thousands of volumes already written on the subject. As she
combed the bookshelves, she said, she noticed ``a conspicuous
silence on the mother's experience of having kids and how her life
and relationships are transformed when children enter the
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   She welcomed the opportunity to revisit her own experiences, now
that her two sons are grown, and to take a stab at what she calls
``the false sentimentality'' surrounding the institution of
motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Raising children can bring a woman untold joy and happiness. But
it can also evoke in us a dark side we never knew we had.
</P>
<P>
   At times like those, Lerner likes to remember the words of
novelist Fay Weldon, who observed that ``the greatest advantage of
not having children must be that you can go on believing that you
are a nice person: Once you have children, you realize how wars
start.''
</P>
<P>
   That Lerner's book contains ample evidence of her own blundering
is part of its charm. Here is a therapist, a woman who has spent
her entire career writing about and counseling people in
dysfunctional families, feeling her way along and occasionally
foundering, just like the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   At first Lerner's editor questioned whether it was wise to
reveal too much about her own relationships, whether sharing openly
about her vulnerability and bad-mother days might undermine her
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my other books,'' she explained, ``I come across as a
highly evolved, clear-thinking mature person who would sail through
every phase of her child's development with perfect clarity and
calm, like a saint or a highly evolved Buddhist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lerner felt strongly that mothers need to hear other mothers
talking openly and honestly about the good, the bad and the
unspeakable. ``We need this even more than expert advice,'' she
said, ``though we need that too. When kids come along, we need all
the help we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   So early on in the book, we meet Lerner in the middle of the
night, in the seventh month of a complicated and potentially
disastrous first pregnancy, looking for some way to explain the wet
bedsheets, not wanting to believe that her water could have broken,
that her baby could be this early.
</P>
<P>
   She describes she and her husband, Steve, also a therapist,
``crouched like dogs on our bed, noses to the sheet, coming up for
air only long enough to fight with each other about whether we were
or were not smelling pee.''
</P>
<P>
   When they finally agreed that Lerner had indeed gone into labor,
they rushed to the hospital where their son Matthew was born,
premature but healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner said it was during this first and difficult pregnancy
that she learned the basic lessons of motherhood: ``That we are not
in control of what happens to our children, but that this fact
needn't stop us from feeling totally guilty and responsible; that
matters of life and death turn on a dime; and that most of what we
worry about doesn't happen, although bad things happen that we fail
to anticipate.''
</P>
<P>
   As her children grew, she also learned humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I had kids,'' she said, ``I was amazed at the improper
behavior of other mothers and I knew I would never do any of those
things. I would never yell at the kids, I would never fight with
Steve within earshot of my children, I would never feed them at
McDonald's and I wasn't going to be a worrier. My mother was a
worrier and I wasn't going to be that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I did all those things _ and more.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, she and her husband never fly together because she
fears the plane will crash and her grown boys will be left without
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' she writes, ``we mothers need to honor our
worries even when we can't justify them.''
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, the issue Lerner wrestled with most was setting
clear rules for her children and imposing consequences when they
were broken. It seemed like such a simple thing _ before she became
a mother.
</P>
<P>
   But when her boys fought with each other in the car or refused
to pick up their dishes from the living-room, she was rendered
helpless.
</P>
<P>
   She describes hitting rock bottom during a protracted struggle
with her son Ben, when he was a teenager oblivious to the mess in
his midst.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if a fog descended on her brain, she said, and
dissolved her thinking center. Her inability to function well in
those situations was in stark contrast to the clarity she
experienced with adults when she was in conflict, and she remains
at a loss to explain the difference.
</P>
<P>
   A chapter in the book on worrying, titled ``Will Your Child
Become a Serial Killer,'' has an eerie ring in an age when armed
children burst into schools, killing other children.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner recognizes that bringing a child into the world is an
enormous leap of faith, but she cautions that there are ``no good
old days to return to, even if we could.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each generation has its own particular crises and its own
particular strengths,'' she said. ``I would not have wanted to
raise a child when my mother did, when divorce was not an option no
matter how empty or conflictual a marriage, when there was so much
solitude and secrecy, when no one knew the terrible things going on
in other people's homes or their own for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   She describes in her book a couple she saw in therapy, beginning
when their only child was 6 and suddenly adverse to going to
school. The little girl had long been the focal point of conflicts
between her parents over how best to raise her, and those arguments
fed into a destructive cycle. The more the parents fought over her
care, the more troubled she became. The more problems she
exhibited, the more her parents fought.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most important to know about this family is how
ordinary it is,'' Lerner writes. ``... In the life cycle of a
normal family, something will get terribly screwed up with at least
one of your kids. If this doesn't happen to you, well, you're just
some kind of weird exception to the rule, or very lucky, or in
denial, or your time hasn't come yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lerner sat down to write the last chapter of her book, the
one on the empty nest, her younger son was leaving home for
college.
</P>
<P>
   She missed him terribly, far more than she imagined she would.
She ached for the feel of him, for the smell of him. So she dug out
a dirty old T-shirt from the bottom of his closet and wore it every
morning while she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, her house in Topeka, Kan., still feels empty without
her boys. ``But the paradox is, as much as I miss them, I wouldn't
want them to move back,'' Lerner said. ``I'm ready for this new
stage of development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
