<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-SHANIA-TWAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANIA TWAIN SHALL MEET HER LEGIONS OF FANS ON FIRST NATIONAL
TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been more than three years since Shania Twain launched her
career with the feisty singles ``Who's Bed Have Your Boots Been
Under?'' and ``Any Man of Mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Twain says she isn't even a teeny bit worried about the
start of her first national concert tour, a milestone that could
make any performer weak in the knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling great and I'm ready,'' Twain said by phone from
her home in Lake Placid, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people may not understand is that I've been
performing in front of audiences for a long, long time, but on a
smaller scale. So I'm actually getting back into my comfort zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain, a native of Ontario, Canada, began singing at about age
6. She made her nightclub debut at 8 when her father pulled her out
of bed one night to sing at a local club after the nightly liquor
curfew.
</P>
<P>
   Before she was 21, Twain opened a concert by Bernadette Peters
and the Toronto Symphony. In 1993, she recorded her first album,
which included the single ``God Ain't Gonna Getcha for That.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain's career has been on fire ever since she met her husband,
rock producer Robert John ``Mutt'' Lange, in 1993. Lange has worked
with Def Leppard, Michael Bolton, AC/DC, Foreigner and Bryan Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things I've been most successful with over the last four
years have been the television appearances and the studio stuff,
like my records,'' Twain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the irony of that is that those are the things I'm the
most awkward with and that I had no experience with at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The first leg of Twain's tour, which opened May 29 in Sudbury,
Ontario, includes a concert with fellow Canadian group Saturday
night at the Tacoma (Wash.) Dome. The tour continues through the
summer of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Twain said the biggest challenge in launching a first-time tour
was living up to her fans' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to ask myself, `Is the show spectacular enough and
exciting enough and entertaining enough for my fans?' And I'm
confident that it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked on it for several months now and I've been very
hands-on since day one with the lighting, staging, the musicians
and every little thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rehearsals for the tour, which will feature a nine-piece band,
began last month in Lake Placid. Fans recently snapped up tickets
to a warmup show at the Lake Placid Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tickets sold out the first morning,'' Twain said, sounding
surprised. ``I was expecting to at least fill the floor, but we
were way beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals in recording her current album, ``Come On
Over,'' was to come up with additional songs suitable for her tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I aimed for the kind of stuff that fans enjoyed the most on
the last album, like `I'm Outta Here' and `Any Man of Mine,' ''
Twain said.
</P>
<P>
   The songs on ``Come Over Over'' are also a lot more personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a natural thing to do. These days, I feel more
comfortable and confident writing about my own personality and my
own perspective on things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Come On Over'' includes two message songs _ ``If You Want to
Touch Her, Ask,'' a song about adolescent awkwardness and respect;
and ``Black Eyes, Blue Tears,'' about regaining one's self-esteem
after leaving an abusive relationship.
</P>
<P>
   `` `If You Want to Touch Her, Ask' really comes from my early
teen years, a time when the boundaries really hadn't been set
between boy and girl,'' Twain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through a stage that probably most girls do. When
you're developing physically, you feel very awkward. And guys
either find those things funny or are really embarrassed if they're
caught looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the song based on that, but turned it into something
far more positive. It's a song about mutual respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for her feisty, fist-pumping songs, Twain longs for the
hard-hitting messages of many older country songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think I'm bringing to country isn't something that's
new to country but something that's left country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to write songs with more direct lyrics, like
Johnny Paycheck's `Take This Job and Shove It.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Country music used to be much more controversial than it is
now. We've gone into this serious, politically correct stage that
artistically I find very, very restrictive.''
</P>
<P>
   Twain and Lange are one of modern country's most successful
husband-and-wife teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship kind of intertwines naturally,'' she said.
``When you're in love and have an intimate relationship you can be
open about your thoughts and that translates into creative things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid to share our stupid ideas with each other.
You have of allow yourself to be vulnerable to truly expose
something that could be brilliant. That happens with us a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
