A6354 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMIT     06-12 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONE MARROW REGISTRY: IT'S A CANCER SURVIVOR'S WISH LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Customer service trainer Jack Chandler of AirTouch Cellular in
Bellevue, Wash., was 34 when he discovered, by accident, that he
had an 8-inch tumor wedged between his heart and lungs.
</P>
<P>
   He'd just finished a touch football game with friends and
thought he had broken a rib. When he went in for X-rays, he came
out with a grim diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The cancer, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, was advanced and spreading
fast. Until that point, he didn't even know he was sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lymphoma is one of the least curable forms of cancer,''
Chandler said. ``My doctor didn't say, `You don't have much of a
chance,' but I could tell by the way he was going through the
motions he didn't think I'd last much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in November 1994. In May 1996, after chemotherapy and
radiation failed to keep him in remission, he discovered that a
bone marrow transplant was his only hope for survival.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. ``I wouldn't be alive if I had not had a bone marrow
transplant,'' Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chandler and his wife, Lisa, also an AirTouch employee, are
trying to make sure that more people get the life-saving
opportunity of a bone marrow transplant. Yesterday, they
spearheaded a bone marrow drive at the company's regional
headquarters in Bellevue.
</P>
<P>
   They would have been pleased if 30 people had showed up.
Instead, the response was overwhelming and they had to extend the
drive. When everyone is finally registered, they expect to have
added more than 150 names to the registry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pair hope to challenge other AirTouch offices around the
country to take part.
</P>
<P>
   There are already 3.2 million potential marrow donors in the
nation, including about 36,000 in Washington. But more donors are
needed, especially members of minorities, who are underrepresented
in the registry.
</P>
<P>
   The registry is critical because only about 30 percent of cancer
patients can find bone marrow matches within their own families.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler was one of the lucky ones. Three of his siblings
matched, which is almost unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   But he knows that not everyone has that same chance. The odds of
two unrelated people finding a match on the registry are about 80
percent overall, but only 30 percent to 40 percent for
African-American patients, and less for some other minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 8 percent of registered donors are African
American, about 1 percent are Native American, and the balance are
Hispanic and Asian American.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow transplants are often the last hope for cancer
patients with lymphoma, breast cancer, leukemia and other diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate drives can be a huge help in building the registry.
Yet, while many companies sponsor corporate blood drives, bone
marrow drives are less common. The Puget Sound Blood Center and
Program, which maintains the registry in Western Washington, does
about 1,000 corporate blood drives a year, but only five or six
corporate bone marrow drives a year, spokesman Keith Warnack said.
</P>
<P>
   Bone marrow drives are less frequent in part because people have
the misconception that signing up for the registry involves a
painful bone marrow procedure, Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't. Registering only involves giving a small sample of
blood, no more of an ordeal than a normal blood donation.
</P>
<P>
   The uncomfortable part, actually donating the marrow, only
happens if a patient happens to match.
</P>
<P>
   Most people, given the chance to save someone's life, don't mind
the little bit of pain involved, Chandler said. He likened it to
the soreness you get if you fall on your tailbone.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate drives help educate people about the need for bone
marrow donors, Warnack said. They're also helpful for building the
registry, because the companies usually pay the $40 registration
fee for each non-minority donor who signs up. (The cost of
registering minority donors is covered by federal grants.)
</P>
<P>
   Warnack also encourages companies to consider paying an extra
$30 a person to have each donor's tissue typed completely. The $40
pays for an initial level of testing, called A-B matching, that
allows for a rough match of patients and donors. For $70, the
tissue will be typed to the D-R level, which enables a match to be
made much more quickly, Warnack said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of which way they go, Chandler hopes more companies
will do drives of their own.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to take a sick employee to get people involved,
he said. ``I can't think of a more worthwhile drive than one that
so directly affects whether someone lives or dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
