<P>
   NIGERIA (Abidjan, Ivory Coast) _ Nigerian police use tear gas
and fire shots into the air to disperse a group of about 200
protesters in the capital, Lagos. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Pursuing reports on Bruce Lindsey's
behind-the-scenes efforts after the Lewinsky story broke. Other
developments in Kenneth Starr's investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OCEANS (Monterey, Calif.) _ The president speaks to the
National Oceans conference, called to address the ``perilous
state'' of the world's oceans from pollution and overfishing. By
John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Under pressure from farmers,
Congress is poised to skirt the nation's sanctions on India and
Pakistan by allowing the sale of wheat to those countries. This
would seem to undermine the administration's moral outrage against
India and Pakistan. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MASS-CHILD-ABUSE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ A judge today ordered a
new trial for the woman who was convicted more than 10 years ago of
abusing children at her family's Fells Acres Day Care Center. In a
decision that could have implications for hundreds of child abuse
cases around the nation, Superior Court Judge Isaac A. Borenstein
said that the child abuse trial of Cheryl Amirault LeFave was
tainted by flawed interviews of children. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-INTERNEES (Los Angeles) _ The federal government will
pay $5,000 settlements and issue an apology to Japanese who were
taken from their homes in Latin America and held in U.S. internment
camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly Religion Column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE (Houston) _ The space shuttle Discovery is scheduled to
land at 2 P.M. today, wrapping up NASA's final mission to Mir and
bringing home the last American tenant on the Russian outpost. By
Bill Dicke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Removing any lingering doubts that Japan is
in a full-blown recession, the Finance Ministry said that the
economy contracted at a 5.3 percent annual rate in the year's first
quarter. Compared with the prior three months, the decline in gross
domestic product was 1.3 percent, faster than the contraction in
1997's final three months. It was the first time in six years that
Japan had recorded two consecutive quarterly declines. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Tokyo) _ South Korean stocks tumble a record 8.1
percent. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., the industrial average was
down 113 points, and, at midday, the long bond was off 5/32, with
the yield at 5.67 percent. In Asia, share prices were flat in Tokyo
and up 0.4 of 1 percent in Hong Kong. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds, no separate CREDIT.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Detroit) _ Developments in the strikes against
General Motors. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-SACHS (New York) _ Partners at Goldman, Sachs begin a
meeting at which they will consider whether to take the firm
public. A decision is not expected until Sunday. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDED-DRUGS (Undated) _ For years, generic drug makers have
eked out profits by selling only cheap knockoffs of name brands
that had lost their patents. Now they are producing their own
patented brands. Branded drugs _ either patented original formulas
or renamed generics _ boast profit margins of 75 percent, twice
those of regular generic drugs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENATARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Friedman's ``Foreign Affairs'' and Frank Rich's ``Journal'';
details to come.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moving later:  &LR;
</P>
