San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ideas Page &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIXTIES-REVISITED (Undated) _ Historians are beginning to
rewrite the history of the 1960s, saying that the culture wars have
distorted our understanding of the period. By Patti Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-MULES (Undated) _ They die by asphhyxiation, rabies,
drowning and falling off cliffs. They are hit by railroad trains,
worked to death, hanged, stabbed, shot and, in one Cormac McCarthy
novel, decapitated by an irate opera singer. Such is the fate of
the mules of the South as recounted in a minor classic of mock
scholarship entitled ``Equine Gothic: The Dead Mule as Generic
Signifier in Southern Literature in the Twentieth Century'' that
asked a simple question, ``What makes Southern literature
Southern?'' and came up with a simpler answer. You can tell it's
Southern if it has a dead mule in it. But, if the dead mule is the
signifier for Southern literature, what is the element that makes
French literature French or Irish literature Irish or film noir
noir? By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-LIBRARIES (Undated) _ Over the last five years, efforts
on behalf of Bosnia's cultural institutions have steadily sharpened
into a book drive and the creation of the Bosnian Manuscript
Ingathering Project, an Internet-based effort to track down copies
of records, manuscripts and unique historical documents that were
destroyed in the war. By Len A. Costa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other culture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-QUIZ (Undated) _ The radio quiz is alive and well on WMCA.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Dirty Work'': Bob Saget,
director; with Chevy Chase, Jack Warden, Don Rickles, Christopher
MacDonald, Artie Lange, Traylor Howard, Norm Macdonald. Reviewed by
Lawrence Van Gelder.
</P>
