A6478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-HARDLY-BOS &LR;      06-12 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HARDLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEENAGERS THE INTENDED AUDIENCE FOR TALE OF HIGH SCHOOL LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL SAUNDERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAN'T HARDLY WAIT &QC; 
Directed and written by: Harry Elfont and Deborah Kaplan &QC; 
Starring: Ethan Embry, Jennifer Love Hewitt, Peter Facinelli,
Lauren Ambrose &QC; 
Running time: 98 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Playing at: Copley Place; suburbs
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a film doesn't have to be classically good, just good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   This is the case with ``Can't Hardly Wait,'' a breezy summer
teen flick that will never be mistaken for a Merchant-Ivory epic.
It should earn, deservedly, the love of its intended audience, the
millions of young people with surplus leisure time over summer
vacation: It respects that audience by avoiding the contrived
situations and lame dialogue that torpedo most teen movies.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, ``Can't Hardly Wait'' will solidify the position of
Jennifer Love Hewitt as the Ally Sheedy of her generation (the
``Breakfast Club,'' ``St. Elmo's Fire,'' pre-``High Art'' Sheedy).
Hewitt is a marginally interesting young actress from TV's ``Party
of Five'' and last year's slasher flick ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer'' who, depite acting that's as flat as her subdued Texas
twang, seems to cause testosterone spikes in young men.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those lads were looking more at the external package,
which must have been what first drove Preston Meyers (Ethan Embry)
to swoon so heavily when Hewitt's Amanda Beckett sat next to him in
freshman English. Meyers is leaving town the day after high school
graduation and has finally worked up the courage to profess his
enduring love to prom queen Beckett, who ignored him in class and
went out with the school's uberstud, Mike Dexter (Peter Facinelli).
</P>
<P>
   It's typical byzantine high-school social intrigue, its
participants a collection of stereotypical cliques (jocks, geeks,
stoners, the cool kids), but writer/directors Harry Elfont and
Deborah Kaplan make the situation play out over a single day in the
lives of these teens. As in the ``Peanuts'' comic strip, parents
are intentionally reduced to off-screen ciphers who have little
direct contact with their children. ``Can't Hardly Wait'' opens
with a graduation ceremony where there's much hat tossing and
hugging but no adults.
</P>
<P>
   Once the scene is set _ a big party attended by most of the
school _ the film moves well, its stories woven in a series of
fast-moving anecdotal scenes that evoke the feel of the innovative
television show ``Parker Lewis Can't Lose.'' Pacing helps ease the
film over its scattered rough spots, and occasional laugh-out-loud
dialogue keeps the energy level high. The story takes several
unexpected twists, especially a wonderful cameo by Jenna Elfman
(``Dharma and Greg'') as a wayward angel, but opts for the typical
feel-good Hollywood ending. It's one of the few bad moves in an
otherwise fine film that, among today's teens, should resonate as
strongly as ``The Breakfast Club'' did for their older siblings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1502EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-SLAYING-BOS &LR;      06-12 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN TRIES TO COPE WITH VICIOUS RACIAL CRIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The horror began with an act of kindness.
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd Jr., a disabled musician with big dreams of putting
this dusty, East Texas town on the map with his songs, was walking
home from a family party Saturday night when a man with a familiar
face stopped on a dark highway to offer him a ride. It was the last
of Byrd's life.
</P>
<P>
   In the nightmare that followed, Byrd was brutally beaten,
chained by his ankles to the back of a pickup truck and torn to
pieces as his body was dragged along a country road in a vicious
hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   The killing ripped the scab off Jasper, a community like
thousands of others where racial tensions quietly simmer. The
tragedy emblazoned the small timber town on the national map,
cruelly fulfilling Byrd's dream.
</P>
<P>
   As Byrd's family prepared Thursday for his funeral, the slaying
of the 49-year-old grandfather revived images of bygone racial
violence and confronted national leaders and ordinary citizens with
a question none could answer: Why do people continue to commit such
horrible acts?
</P>
<P>
   Three white ex-convicts, who police say were members of a white
supremacist group, were charged Tuesday with murdering Byrd, who
was black.
</P>
<P>
   ``As small as James seemed in life, he is powerful in death,''
said Ethel Parks, a lifelong friend. ``Maybe it took this to force
us all to find a way to heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper, a town of 8,000 about 120 miles northeast of Houston, is
big enough for a Wal-Mart but small enough that the Cotton Patch
Cafe still sells a plate of chicken-fried steak and fries for
$2.99.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, black and white, said race relations generally
have been positive in recent years, although they said problems
remain.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Byrd's death stretches from a craggy, red-clay
road, where the attack began, along 2 miles of pocked asphalt to a
white clapboard church and cemetery, where the last of his remains
and effects were found. All 81 spots on the road where pieces of
Byrd were discovered are marked wth bright orange spray paint.
</P>
<P>
   The crime was so jarring that the county sheriff, Billy Rowles,
wept when he arrived at the Jasper home of Byrd's parents to
deliver the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are killed every day,'' said James Byrd Sr., a deacon
at the New Bethel Baptist Church, as he sat in his parlor eating a
lunch provided by neighbors. ``But the brutality of what they did
to James, that's what's really hard to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Police laid out a chilling account of the killing in a
probable-cause affidavit charging the three Jasper men _ Robert
Russell Brewer, 31, John William King, and Shawn Berry, both 23 _
with murder. Police based their account on a statement from Berry.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a night of drinking, Berry said, the men were riding in his
1982 gray pickup down a main highway in Jasper sometime after
midnight when Berry, the driver, spotted Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who had served time for burglary, recognized Byrd from
his parole office. Byrd had been in prison for theft and forgery.
</P>
<P>
   But when Berry pulled over to offer Byrd a ride, King balked.
``You don't need to be picking up a (racial slur),'' King told
Berry, according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   King's and Brewer's arms are covered with tattoos linking them
to the Aryan Nation, a white supremacist group that all three
suspects allegedly joined in prison.
</P>
<P>
   With Byrd seated in the bed of the truck, the four rode to a
nearby convenience store, where King began to drive. Berry said
King drove several miles east of Jasper to a dirt road near a
winding creek, then stopped. ``I'm fixin' to scare'' Byrd, King
allegedly said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said King and Brewer then beat and kicked Byrd and chained
him to the truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to start `The Turner Diaries' early,'' King was
quoted as saying as he drove off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Turner Diaries'' is a novel that depicts the slaughter of
blacks and is popular among antigovernment militia groups and white
supremacists.
</P>
<P>
   As the truck pulled Byrd along the winding, hilly asphalt road,
his belongings _ keys, dentures, wallet, tennis shoes, and clothing
_ fell in his wake, as did parts of his body. Hundreds of yards
separated the spots where police found Byrd's head, neck, right
arm, and torso the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   M.L. Traylor Jr., who describes himself and other residents of
the road as distant relatives of Byrd, was watching a Western movie
on television when the truck pulling Byrd roared by his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard something coming and looked out and saw the truck
going by,'' Tyler said, ``but I never saw James.''
</P>
<P>
   The police trail to the suspects began when a witness said he
saw Byrd in the pickup truck, which they traced to Berry. At the
scene of the beating, authorities also found tools inscribed with
Berry's name, beer cans, a compact disc by the group Kiss, and a
cigarette lighter inscribed with the name ``Possum'' and a symbol
for Aryan Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses later said Possum was King's nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they have found no motive for the slaying other
than racial hatred. The FBI has joined the investigation to pursue
possible hate-crimes charges that could carry the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Texas law makes capital punishment available only if prosecutors
can prove the murder was committed in association with another
felony, such as kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's preference, mine included, is for this to be a
capital murder case,'' said the district attorney, Guy James Gray.
``We have to have evidence to prove that in court, and that's what
we're working on right now,''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has offered condolences to Byrd's family, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson has flown in to call for peace and progress, and
aides to Vice President Al Gore were calling local officials to
arrange a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's family said Chicago Bulls basketball player Dennis Rodman
had offered to pay the funeral expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there was fear among many residents of a nasty
aftermath. The imperial wizard of a Ku Klux Klan faction in Vidor,
55 miles away, said the Klan would remain active in Jasper, despite
assertions by law enforcment officials that no white supremacist
group operates in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing is, we don't who they are,'' said Gwen Carter,
a longtime friend of Byrd. ``They're not wearing white sheets
anymore. Some of them might be wearing three-piece suits. And none
of wants to see this happen to anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Many white residents joined the call for healing. Some hung
banners in storefront windows that read ``Pray for Jasper and the
Byrd Family,'' and ``Let's All Pray For Unity.''
</P>
<P>
   A teenage brother and sister, Chris and Melissa Bush, handed out
yellow ribbons and drove stakes into the ground with ribbons
fluttering from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to show that all people of Jasper are not racists,''
Chris Bush said, his face glistening with sweat in the 90-degree
heat. ``We do care what happened to Mr. Byrd.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
