A6483 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SIXDAY-BOS &LR;      06-12 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SIXDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILM EQUIVALENT OF BEACH-BLANKET READING, AIRY AND FLUFFY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIX DAYS, SEVEN NIGHTS &QC; 
Directed by: Ivan Reitman &QC; 
Screenplay by: Michael Browning &QC; 
Starring: Harrison Ford, Anne Heche, David Schwimmer, Jacqueline
Obradors, Temuera Morrison, Allison Janney &QC; 
Running time: 101 minutes &QC; 
Rated: PG-13 (language, sensuality and brief violence) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' is film's equivalent of beach blanket
reading. Light, breezy, pleasant, no surprises, in one eye and out
the other, no aftertaste, perfectly serviceable escapism as it
throws Harrison Ford together with Anne Heche on a desert island.
It's no ``African Queen'' or even ``Romancing the Stone,'' but it
at least frees Ford from heavy lifting, like, say, carrying Air
Force One on his back. Here, he's a pilot whose roughed-up cargo
plane is forced down by a squall after Heche's high-powered New
York magazine editor (is there any other kind?) hires him to fly
her to Tahiti when an assignment suddenly looms. There's always
been comic potential in the mix of dread and grumpiness Ford wears
so naturally, and Heche gives him plenty to be grumpy about.
</P>
<P>
   The career-agenda-driven editor's pushy disdain is the very sort
of thing that made Ford's throttle jockey opt for the beachcombing
life. She gripes, he grumbles. Naturally, they're made for each
other, but just need a little time to discover it. In other words,
first they crash, then they fall. The flying scenes are the film's
funniest, the only times, in fact, that ``Six Days, Seven Nights''
really takes off and regenerates the comic fizz of the madcap
romantic comedies it otherwise meekly and predictably follows. You
can feel Heche's acting career leaping forward when her character
starts swallowing Zanax and spacing out in giggly fashion as the
storm intensifies. After the plane winds up on a beach with its
landing gear ruined, her zany life-raft scene confirms her comic
gifts. Ford's pilot sometimes plays wary and distanced. Heche's
peppery workaholic is always right there in his face, a funny,
sassy little atomic reactor.
</P>
<P>
   Just when they begin to get the hang of survivalism, the search
party they think is about to rescue them turns out to be a band of
murderous pirates. Thus, survival skills yield to fleeing skills
and romantic comedy yields to romantic adventure. Two less
resourceful actors would be in big trouble, given the script's
dropoff in wit and absence of surprise. Luckily, something else
takes over with Ford and Heche. At about the time you stop
believing in them as characters, you become intrigued, then
absorbed, by the way each persuades us they're taking us inside
their heads. They let us see the wheels turning as they find ways
to put fresh spin on material that grows more humdrum as the film
proceeds, divert us from the fact that sizzle is less than
abundant.
</P>
<P>
   Ford makes the film face up to the fact that he's nearly twice
Heche's age when he mumbles, after their mutual attraction becomes
too obvious not to acknowledge, that she deserves someone fresher.
But, of course, he then gets to make the case that he's got what it
takes, especially after he removes a snake that invades her shorts
when she's bathing in a river before they literally take the plunge
from a cliff into the sea to escape the pirates. The film's sex
scenes go to David Schwimmer, as the shallow fiance left back at
the resort by Heche's workaholic. Amusing despite the one-note
shallowness of his character, he says all the right things about
loving his fiancee, then gets drunk and beds the easygoing island
beauty (Jacqueline Obradors) with whom Ford's pilot had been
sleeping. ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' never seems freshly minted,
but Ford and Heche keep us watching it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
