<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAPER ELEVATES RED WINGS IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ There was a frown across Hockey Town for much of the
night. But chagrin almost magically turned to elation when the Red
Wings capped one of the most dramatic comebacks in recent Stanley
Cup history as Kris Draper nailed in a slapper 15:24 into overtime
for a 5-4 victory over the Washington Capitals Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Set up by Martin Lapointe in the slot, Draper belted in his
first goal of the postseason, a one-time slapper that handed the
reigning Cup champions a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven finals. Game
3 will be Saturday night at the MCI Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called anticipation,'' said a laughing Draper, asked what
he was doing in the slot, prepared to strike, when he's known as
one of Detroit's more reliable checking forwards. ``The truth was,
I kind of sneaked in there on a line change. We play a left wing
long (defensive scheme), but that by no means has to take away from
scoring chances. If I'd missed the shot, it just meant I would have
been the first guy digging back into the defensive zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings fell into what appeared a hopeless 3-1 hole in the
second period. Peter Bondra, Chris Simon, and former Bruin Adam
Oates beat Chris Osgood in a span of under 10 minutes, and it
seemed the Caps would go home with a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made too many soft plays in front of a very hungry team,''
said Caps coach Ron Wilson. ``We were stick-checking out there
instead of getting in their way.''
</P>
<P>
   In their four-game sweep of the Flyers in last year's finals,
the Wings trailed for a total of two minutes in the series. Here
they were against the Caps, down by two goals when the third period
began. Osgood was again looking shaky in the Detroit net. Slava
Kozlov was out with a charley horse. The Caps, without a doubt the
luckiest team in the playoffs this season, were threatening to make
a real series out of what most felt would be a fourth consecutive
sweep in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the Caps got out, 3-1,'' said Wings captain Steve
Yzerman. ``We really started to open up and take chances. The game
opened up for us because we got down. What caused it to open up was
the fact that we had to catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wing return came amid a wild seesaw display of offense
by the two clubs. First, with 6:37 gone in the third, Yzerman cut
the gap to 3-2 when he knocked in a shorthanded goal _ the
league-leading sixth by the Wings this postseason. The Caps struck
right back, though, when ex-Bruin Joe Juneau drilled one in for the
4-2 lead only 28 seconds later, connecting on a steaming slapper
from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Safe again with a two-goal lead? Hardly. Only 63 seconds after
it was on the board, Lapointe cut the deficit back to one. Caps,
4-3, with 8:08 gone.
</P>
<P>
   What may have been the Capitals' last best chance to make a
series of this went wide right at 10:08 when Esa Tikkanen slipped
behind the defense and had 24 square feet of open net to shoot for
with Osgood still down from a save. But the crafty Tikkanen, no
more than 5 feet out in front of the net, inexplicably slid his
shot wide of the right post.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the win right on Esa Tikkanen's stick, for God's
sake,'' said an exasperated Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time and math after that. With 4:14 left
in regulation, the Bay State's Doug Brown knocked in the equalizer,
unassisted, after taking possession on a turnover in the right
faceoff circle. The Wings were buzzing. The Caps were wheezing. The
Wings finished with a 20-7 shot lead for the period, and it only
got worse in the OT, when Detroit rolled up a 12-3 shot edge,
finishing the night with a 60-33 advantage. Emotionally, the Caps
were crushed, and their legs buckled in lockstep with their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Off the bench jumped Draper. In possession in the right circle,
Lapointe saw Draper racing in from the side and feathered his pass
into the slot. Olaf Kolzig didn't have a chance. In a flash, the
sellout crowd of 19,983 would be shaking down the memories of Howe,
Delvecchio, and Sawchuk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoring goals is all about confidence,'' said Draper, stymied
for some six weeks. ``When you go without a goal, you doubt
yourself. But I felt if I kept shooting, it would go in. I just
didn't expect it would be the OT winner in the finals _ but I'll
take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
