<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BENFICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENFICA RALLY OVERTAKES REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution lost. The crowd loved it.
</P>
<P>
   The 35,136 fans _ most of them wearing red and white to support
Benfica of the Portuguese first division _ whooped it up when their
team came from behind to stop the Revolution, 2-1, in Thursday
night's exhibition match at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't so much cheering against the Revolution as cheering
for Benfica. And they cheered for the show _ especially the two
late goals, both on free kicks, that decided the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we scored, there was a pretty good roar. When they
scored, it was even bigger,'' said Revolution goalkeeper Jeff
Causey.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a Revolution win. And after losing five straight Major
League Soccer games, they could have used one, even if it wouldn't
have counted in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Revolution gave Benfica, coming off a 3-1 victory
over the New York-New Jersey Metro-Stars Tuesday, all it could
handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that American mentality, always fighting,'' said Benfica
keeper Michel Preud'Homme, who started for Belgium in the 1994
World Cup. ``I like it. We are at the end of our season. We are
tired. For us, it's a friendly, but it was not a friendly at the
end of the game. It was serious out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It became decidedly more so when Carlos Rocha put back the
rebound of an Edwin Gorter shot that hit the post, breaking a
scoreless tie in the 53d minute. It was Rocha's first goal with the
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   And it riled up Benfica, which already had been getting its
share of shots on Causey, who had seven saves to Preud'Homme's two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely did turn it on,'' said Causey. ``We knew they
were kind of tired. They had played a couple of nights before and
were traveling. They weren't going to be chasing our guys around.
But once we scored, it reminded them we were for real.''
</P>
<P>
   Benfica turned up the heat. Causey, making his first start since
the preseason, held his ground.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the ground to stop a header, denied a bid by Karel
Poborsky, and smothered a shot by Sergiy Kandaurov. Then he went up
high to get the ball with Joao Pinto charging in.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 76th minute, Benfica had a free kick from 40 yards
out. Midfielder Edwin Sanchez, who had entered the game in the 55th
minute, lined it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he's known for whacking a pretty good ball,'' said
Causey.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez got all of this one. It got by the wall of defenders and
beat Causey for the tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just hit one that eluded the wall and swerved as it came
toward me,'' Causey said. ``It was just a great hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was not done yet. In the 87th minute, the Revolution
were called for another foul when Ulf Pringle went down just
outside the 18-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez set up again and fired again. The shot went off the
Revolution's Brian Dunseth and deflected into the corner of the net
to Causey's left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second one was pure luckiness,'' Causey said. ``Our guy
was standing there and it hit his foot and caught me moving the
wrong way. He may be known as a guy who can whack it, but if he's
known as a guy who can hit it into the middle and have it hit
someone and go in the near post, he's pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   While Benfica players packed up and signed autographs before
hitting the road for home, Revolution assistant coach Renato
Capobianco talked about having a light practice  &UR; today &LR;  with a home
game against Chicago coming up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about being able to take positives out of this loss.
He liked the way his team did some things _ like getting the ball
out wide and finding space behind defenders _ that it had worked on
in recent days. And he liked the way Causey played, plus the
overall attacking, aggressive approach his team took.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went after them,'' he said. ``That's a positive sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Revolution will try to build on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Pereja, a midfielder out of Colombia who was still
clearing up visa problems Wednesday, made his debut for the
Revolution and played the first 59 minutes ... Revolution head
coach Thomas Rongen is due back from his US World Cup team duties
for Sunday's afternoon game here. Rongen's plane is supposed to
land at 12:30 p.m. at Logan Airport. The game is at 3, and he flies
back to France at 6. He is expected to return for the Revolution's
game at New York-New Jersey June 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
