<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-ELECTIONS-BOS &LR;      06-12 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-ELECTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESSIONAL VICTORIES MAY NOT LEAD TO SUCCESS AT THE POLLS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By stalling or diluting a succession of bills, from
stiff tobacco regulations to patients' rights to campaign finance
reform, Republicans on Capitol Hill have compiled an impressive
string of victories.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, analysts, and some GOP rank and file believe that
these warm-weather victories may spell doom for Republicans in the
autumn elections. Republicans, many say, are increasingly
projecting themselves as members of the party of inaction,
obstacles to popular proposals rather than agents of change.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leadership has tried repeatedly to quash campaign
finance legislation in the House, even after conducting extensive
hearings last year into President Clinton's fund-raising practices.
Republicans have bogged down the tobacco legislation, and a final
vote remains elusive. And Republicans across Capitol Hill are
reticent about an overhaul of managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``One nightmare scenario is to go out there as a majority party
and take the sides of big tobacco against kids, health care
companies against patients, and with big-money interests against
reformers,'' said Norman Ornstein, a congressional scholar for the
American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   An influential Republican strategist said: ``The Democrats want
to position our guys as anti-minimum wage, pro-tobacco,
pro-insurance, and anti-campaign reform, and our side isn't doing a
lot to dispute this.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, facing a string of legislative defeats, have vowed
revenge in the fall. Initial strategy plans call for Democratic
congressional candidates to lump the issues together as they tag
Republican incumbents as part of a so-called ``do-nothing''
Congress wedded to large corporate interests like the tobacco and
health care industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have embarked on an agenda that is so narrow and so out
of sync with the rest of the country that they run a real risk of
not doing anything by the fall,'' said Laura Nichols, spokeswoman
for the House minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt. ``We intend to
make these issues part of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a slim 11-seat advantage in the House and a
55-45 majority in the Senate. History is against the Democrats.
Only once since the Civil War has the president's party gained
seats in a midterm election, in 1934, amid the Great Depression,
when Franklin D. Roosevelt was in office.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Republicans said they do not believe the public is
engaged in such issues as overhauling the campaign finance system
or regulating the tobacco industry _ not like education and crime,
the traditional areas of voter interest. Aides said Representative
John Linder of Georgia, head of the Republican National
Congressional Committee, held a series of forums over the Memorial
Day weekend and not one voter raised a point about campaign finance
or tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have been trying to say we're evil on finance
reform since I can remember, and I can't find a single seat in the
last five cycles where anyone can say it made one percentage point
of difference in the outcome,'' said Ron Kaufman, a Republican
consultant and former political director in the Bush White House.
``I just don't see those being a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   The RNCC communications director, Mary Crawford, &UR;  &LR; said, ``If you
ask members where those issues pop up, they will pretty unanimously
tell you they don't pop up at all.''
</P>
<P>
   On tobacco, Republicans in the House and Senate believe they
have effectively painted the issue as one of a tax increase, given
the $1.10 extra proposed for a pack of cigarettes. With that
perception firmly planted, they believe they are safe in opposing
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is whether it's a tax matter or a health
matter, and the Republicans are trying to drive home the tax
implications,'' said Dave Mason, a congressional analyst with the
Heritage Foundation, a right-leaning think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Even many Democratic candidates appear loath, at least at this
early stage, to focus on tobacco and campaign finance as key issues
in their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all talking about the Patient Bill of Rights and HMO
reform, education and more money for teachers and school
construction and maybe hitting a Republican for a voucher vote or
more student aid,'' said Amy Walter of the Cook Report, a political
newsletter in Washington. ``And they talk about Social Security,
and that's really it.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans privately concede that they may be most vulnerable
on patients' rights, given the widespread disdain of health
maintenance organizations. Some members of the rank and file have
signaled to their leadership that Republicans must soften their
opposition and work through a compromise. In the meantime, senior
Republicans are accusing Democrats of wanting to return to
Clinton's 1994 concept of nationalized health care.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is the impact of Clinton's ethical, legal, and
moral difficulties on the fall elections. House Speaker Newt
Gingrich has toned down his attacks on Clinton, and others appear
hesitant at lining up behind other chief Republican Clinton
antagonists like House majority leader Richard Armey of Texas and
Representative Dan Burton of Indiana, chairman of the House
Government Reform and Oversight Committee, especially at a time
when voters are indicating dwindling concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how that's going to play out,'' Crawford said of
Clinton's legal troubles. ``None of us do, because we don't know
what's there. From a political standpoint, we don't bank on it for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Some strategists believe that Gingrich, far more than the
individual issues, might be the GOP's most significant liability in
the autumn elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6500 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-POPULARITY-BOS &LR;      06-12 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-POPULARITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOROUGHBRED RACING MOVES TO GAIN POPULARITY FOR THE SPORT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For five weeks every spring, thoroughbred racing dominates
television and press reports as the best 3-year-olds in the country
compete for the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   But the peaked, national interest is ephemeral. After the
Belmont Stakes in the first week of June, it largely evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   If thoroughbred racing is to capture a significant piece of the
national spotlight, many of its most devoted participants
increasingly say it must market itself to a much broader, younger
audience than the traditional handicapper, the stereotypical
railbird. And for the ``Sport of Kings'' to generate the excitement
of the pretelevision days when Citation and Whirlaway vied with
Williams and DiMaggio for space in the sports sections, many
believe it needs a storyline that the greater public can follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can develop some heroes in racing, if we get an
organization together that is going to push these heroes on a
national stage so that people have something in the sport they can
more readily identify with, then we would really be on to something
big from my point of view,'' said Don Little, of Centennial Farms,
a local owner and developer of racing syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   Such a national organization for thoroughbred racing may be at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   A product of two years of research the National Thoroughbred
Racing Association was officially established on April 1 to bring
to thoroughbred racing what NASCAR brought to stock car racing 50
years ago and what the NFL brought to professional football in the
1920s: structure and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally what we are doing is creating a national
structure and a brand for the sport, which it really has not had
before,'' said Tim Smith, the newly appointed commissioner and
chief economic officer of the NTRA.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred racing officials say the NTRA is the first national
organization in their sport that has united its diverse groups:
horse owners, track owners, trainers, jockeys, and breeders. Dues
have financed a $15 million advertising budget and a $500,000
public relations budget.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the NTRA launched the sport's first-ever national
advertising campaign. Like the NBA, with ``I love this game,'' and
the NHL, with ``Coolest game on earth,'' the NTRA has a slogan:
``Go baby go!'' The ads have appeared on television, largely
coordinated with the Triple Crown, and in USA Today, Sports
Illustrated, ESPN The Magazine, Rolling Stone, Swing, and Buzz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cl10.5 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Having largely ignored the television boom in sports coverage
and battered by other betting outlets for the gambling public like
state lotteries and casinos, thoroughbred racing is in need of new
marketing tools. In appointing a top gun like Smith, many in the
sport hope it has finally established a ``league office,'' a united
voice for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly this has been tried before, but never with the
amount of support across the board that we have already received,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is a lawyer who worked in various posts in the Carter
administration, where he befriended Hamilton Jordan, who is now
chief executive of the Association of Tennis Professionals. Smith,
49, has worked with the organizing committee for the 1996 Summer
Olympic Games in Atlanta, the Professional Golfers' Association
Tour, and the ATP Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk Downs is among 41 tracks nationwide _ including
Churchill Downs, Saratoga, Aqueduct and Santa Anita _ that have
signed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``What encourages us that this will be successful,'' said Bob
O'Malley, chief operating officer of Suffolk Downs, ``is that
industry groups that we have had before, for a long time, have been
more social clubs than bringing everyone together for business.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and O'Malley are working to make the major thoroughbred
racing attraction in Massachusetts, the MassCap, part of a
season-long racing schedule that generates significant interest and
significant national television exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fan is going to see something that looks a lot more like
NASCAR and the PGA tour,'' Smith said. ``It is going to be
something that is easier to follow, something that generates a
story line, with horses that fans can follow from race to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says the NTRA hopes to have the new circuit up and running
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Even without the new entity, things are looking up, a bit, at
Suffolk Downs, as attempts to turn the MassCap into a festival with
musical groups and boat cruises from Boston Harbor have drawn more
attention to the track. The average daily handle for this year's
spring dates, which ended June 6, was up 4 percent to $998,473, and
the average attendance increased by 2 percent to 4,455.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Malley says he is noticing somewhat of a younger crowd,
especially on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benefiting from an age of technology, younger people seem to
be caught up in the statistical analysis of racing,'' O'Malley
said. ``There was a time when people used to come to the track with
binoculars, and now they come in with laptops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
