<HEADLINE>
NATIVES REFLECT ON WASHINGTON'S TOP RANKING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has often been said that the nation's capital is
a city of Southern efficiency and Northern charm. And that, it has
also been said, is putting it nicely.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia has long gotten poor grades for high
crime, low-quality schools, and a high cost of living. Yet Money
magazine rates Washington the No. 1 place to live in the Northeast.
Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scratched our heads a bit, too, when we first saw that
Washington came out as No. 1,'' Doug Dundas, a Money magazine
editor, said Thursday. ``But what pushed it over the top was the
vast number of museums and other cultural institutions that are in
the area.''
</P>
<P>
   That's still quite a rise, since Washington ranked at 162 out of
300 cities last year. But Dundas said the magazine's survey showed
that concern about crime had dropped, helping Washington skyrocket
to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who participated in our survey just weren't that
interested in crime this year as they have been in the past, so
crime had less weight this year,'' he said, adding that air quality
and clean water also had helped the district.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the magazine changed its format for rating the
cities, a switch that helped bump up Washington, Dundas said.
Rather than judge cities against one another, Money divided the
list into regions and population size for similar comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this new method is more useful,'' Dundas said. ``It
helps us compare like cities. Otherwise, we might get more big
cities on the top of the list and smaller cities at the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Another surprise: Many Washingtonians said Thursday that they
agree with the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aside from the museums that always give you something to do,
you have the protection of the federal government here,'' said
Richard Q. Lewis, who lives in Capitol Heights and works in a
subway information booth. ``Also, this is a good area for
minorities. There is not as much racism, sexism or homophobia here.
Those things are not tolerated here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis added that the city's only major problem is ``the big gap
between the extremely poor and the extremely rich. But that's
something you deal with everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's high crime rate is not much different from those of
other cities, said Tawanna Jenkins, a domestic cleaner and a
Washington native from Capitol Hill. ``There's crime everywhere.
You can't get away from it in the big cities,'' she said. ``You
have to look at the whole picture, and DC is great. There's just so
much here.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Monroe, a store clerk from Adams Morgan, agreed that the
city's highlights outweigh its problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something good and bad about every city, but overall
it is an interesting place to live.'' Monroe said.
</P>
<P>
   However, not everyone thought Washington is No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Nebinski, an insurance broker who lives across the Potomac
River in Great Falls, Va., and works in Washington, said he didn't
understand what the magazine sees in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think services in this city have a lot to be desired,
especially for the public school system,'' he said. ``As for
museums and cultural institutions, yes, that part is attractive,
but these museums were here long ago. The city hasn't really built
anything worthwhile as of late.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have a point. But then, the magazine survey wasn't
confined to just the District of Columbia, but also included nearby
``posh'' suburbs in Virginia and Maryland, certainly a boost for
the city, Dundas explained.
</P>
<P>
   Washington beat Boston, which Money says is No. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
