<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE'S INDEPENDENT GOVERNOR PROFITS FROM GOOD TIMES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH HARPSWELL, Maine _ The rising economic tide may not lift
all the boats, but it is swamping challengers who aim to dump
incumbents overboard.
</P>
<P>
   As the only independent among the nation's 50 governors, Angus
King was assured of challengers from two sides after his first
four-year term. But the remarkable surge of prosperity that has
lifted much of New England elevated King as well.
</P>
<P>
   And the laid-back, auburn-haired governor enjoys a level of
popularity that makes his defeat seem practically impossible. That
does not daunt Thomas Connolly, Scarborough lawyer, or James
Longley, a former 1st District congressman. Connolly won Tuesday's
Democratic primary by a 4-1 margin over Joseph Ricci. Longley,
whose father was a popular independent governor who left office 20
years ago, defeated Henry Joy and Leo Martin by taking two-thirds
of the GOP vote. But neither Connolly nor Longley got more than
about 30,000 votes statewide, which substantially dims their
prospects for November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bored Maine voters stay away in droves,'' admitted a Portland
Press Herald headline's assessment. If anger is the most powerful
motivating force in politics, it seems to be in short supply in
Maine. King's moderate, thrifty, probusiness approach seems to
mirror Maine's mood of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   He is liberal on social issues, conservative on fiscal affairs,
and worships, like almost all Maine politicians, at the feet of the
green god of environmentalism. What's not to like? seems to be the
attitude of most of the 1-million-plus Mainers.
</P>
<P>
   King's challengers set manfully to their task on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to be one of the most heavily taxed states in the
US, even as our citizens continue to be among the lowest-earning,''
complained Longley. Running as a traditional conservative, Longley
bids to cut taxes by 20 percent and vows to drop the sales tax down
from 6 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly is a mainstream Democrat, appealing to the party's
traditional constituencies, and amplifies Longley's lament that
prosperity has not visited each Maine household equally. The Pine
Tree state lags 35 other states in per capita income. Six of
Maine's 16 counties ``are poorer than the poorest counties in the
poorest state in the country, Mississippi,'' Connolly claims.
</P>
<P>
   But Governor King seems to have spread his tent in the middle
ground of both parties, and his easygoing, mediagenic personality
helped smoothe out the inevitable rough spots he encountered during
his first four years in office.
</P>
<P>
   Maine likes its politicians polite, presentable, and respectful
of other points of view. From Ed Muskie to George Mitchell to Bill
Cohen, the voters have expressed a preference for pols who were
low-key, low-maintenance, and industrious. They don't like scandal,
harrumping, or highly charged rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   They know that winter comes after summer, that skies are cloudy
or stormy at least 43 percent of the time, on average, in this
latitude, and they know that trees fall, fish vanish, and the power
fails just when you wish it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Creation and retention of jobs is a big deal in Maine, where the
traditional industries _ paper-making, shoes, fishing _ have
suffered losses. The newer industries _ in tourism, catalogue
sales, telephone call-centers, high tech _ have taken hold or
flourished under King's light-hand-on-the-tiller approach to
business regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Longley has needled King about the governor's reluctant backing
for a $60 million state tax abatement scheme approved to entice
Bath Iron Works to expand its shipbuilding facility. King argues
that he plays the role of a balance-wheel, trying to measure how
much tax money to give up against how many more jobs and tax-paying
salaries are involved in the trade-off.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of economics is hard to predict and harder still to
justify if the numbers get screwy, as in the type of swift, sharp
recessions that have periodically blitzed this rural,
high-energy-cost state at the end of the nation's industrial and
transportation pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   King won a narrow victory four years ago as the third candidate
in a field that was nearly evenly split. The topic then was how to
contain a big budget shortfall, and King's experience as a
businessman stood him in good stead with voters worried about
maintaining their family income in a lean time.
</P>
<P>
   Now the much more agreeable problem is what to do with a comfy
surplus in the state budget. Republicans prefer cutting taxes.
Democrats tend to want to expand services and spend tax money for
this group or that. King sits astride the debate in a position of
considerable leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Were he facing a large and unified majority in either branch of
the Legislature, as is the case of the Democrats' 4-1 margin over
Republican legislators in Massachusetts, King would have a much
tougher job. But Maine's Legislature is more evenly divided, and he
enjoys approval ratings only slightly below the astronomical.
</P>
<P>
   King says the idea of going to Washington as congressman or
senator holds no appeal for him, and so he limits his aspirations
to running the state, period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
