</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-UNDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMANTHA MORTON MAKES STUNNING DEBUT BY PURGING DEATH WITH SEX
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDER THE SKIN &QC; 
Directed and written by: Carine Adler &QC; 
Starring: Samantha Morton, Rita Tushingham, Claire Rushbrooke,
Stuart Townsend, Christine Tremarco, Matthew Delamere &QC; 
Running time: 85 minutes &QC; 
Unrated &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   British writer-director Carine Adler's ``Under the Skin''
emblazons the screen with the most startling and gripping film
debut by an actress since Emily Watson took our breath away with
her emotional nakedness in ``Breaking the Waves.'' Samantha
Morton's alternatingly keening and convulsive portrayal of a
daughter grieving for her mother in loose-cannon fashion is the
year's most powerful performance so far, overwhelming in its raw,
touching, invigorating immediacy. Yet while profound, the death of
a mother from a brain tumor isn't simple. It only complicates the
lifelong sibling rivalry between Morton's Iris and Claire
Rushbrook's Rose, her older sister.
</P>
<P>
   First the film breaks our heart with the muted stoicism of Rita
Tushingham as their suffering mother in her boxy little row house
in Liverpool. When she dies, Rose steals her mother's ring. Iris
steals her mother's ashes. It's their futile way of trying to keep
her around a little longer. Rose is at a crossroads, pregnant with
her first child, about to usher a new life into the world as she
ushers her mother out. Iris, a single woman, has no such
consolation or call to duty, and is under no obligation to hold
things together. And so she doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   When she reacts, it's with rage and heedlessness. She claps on
her mother's blond wig, envelops herself in her mother's coat, and
tries to drive out her grief with nonstop casual sex with an
intensity that borders on the grotesque. Between them, Adler and
Morton convince us that there's nothing histrionic and everything
primal about Iris's frenzied hurling of her body against the same
natural order that took her mother. She's so far inside her own
torment that she seems unaware of the details of her flailings,
even when one man abuses her horribly and she becomes the victim of
a mugging. Even then, the furies driving her aren't quite tamed.
</P>
<P>
   But dropping her dependable boyfriend, as she does when she
picks up a man at the movies and begins her headlong attempt to
purge grief with sex, isn't enough. She realizes this when her
feelings reach their peak in embittered exchanges with her sister.
As played by Rushbrook, who will be remembered from ``Secrets &AMP;
Lies,'' Rose finds something jarred loose in herself by the
spectacle of Iris's self-lacerating odyssey. It's clear that
neither will arrive at anything resembling consolation until and
unless they can do so with each other. Few _ if any _ films will
hit you with the raw emotional urgency Morton delivers in ``Under
the Skin.'' It's an extraordinary evocation of pain and catharsis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1515EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
