<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-KURT-BOS &LR;      06-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-KURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUNDGE LADY MACBETH THE RELUCTANT PARTICIPANT IN LOVE STORY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KURT AND COURTNEY
</P>
<P>
   A documetary by Nick Broomfield
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Unrated
</P>
<P>
   If Courtney Love had her druthers, no one would be reading this
review of ``Kurt and Courtney.''
</P>
<P>
   If the singer-actress had her way, there would be no review
because there never would have been a movie about her tumultuous
marriage to Kurt Cobain, lead singer and guitarist of the seminal
band Nirvana, or the insidious theories that have sprung up since
his death in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   So much of Nick Broomfield's documentary, ``Kurt and Courtney''
concerns Love's efforts to block the film's completion and
distribution _ she got it booted off the bill at this year's
Sundance Film Festival _ that it's a wonder he didn't call the
movie, ``Courtney and Me.'' The rest of the film, an arresting,
darkly comic horror show of junkies, irate ex-lovers, and freaks,
portrays Love as a bullying, manipulative fame-hungry shrew, a
malevolent grunge-girl Lady Macbeth who may have played a role in
her husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   On April 8, 1994, an electrician discovered the body of the
27-year-old Cobain in his Seattle home. Found next to his body was
drug paraphernalia, a rambling note, and the shotgun police believe
Cobain used to take his own life. Cobain's death was jarring and
tragic, but hardly seemed unexpected. Suicide was a recurring theme
in his songs _ ``Milk It'' from 1993's ``In Utero,'' featured the
line ``Look on the bright side is suicide'' _ and Cobain often
complained about the dual pressures of his sudden, worldwide
success, and a drug problem he couldn't seem to shake.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had the last candles flicked out at makeshift
memorials than conspiracy theorists came out of the woodwork with
Web sites and books devoted to uncovering nefarious plots
supposedly hatched by Love to do away with Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Cobain's death, Love was seen as the Yoko Ono of the
grunge generation, another attention-seeking viper sinking her
teeth into the rock god of the day. Love already fronted her own
band, Hole (which released an acclaimed album ``Live Through
This,'' days after Cobain's death), but marrying the Nirvana
frontman instantly made her more than just another guitar-slinging
musician waiting for her big break.
</P>
<P>
   For Broomfield, finding Love's enemies proves as easy as finding
a double mocha latte in Seattle. There's the ex-boyfriend, an
especially bitter failed musician, who says of Love, ``a kinder,
gentler Charlie Manson is still (expletive) Charlie Manson,''
referring to Love's slinky designer makeover. There's a former
nanny to the couple's daughter Frances, who claims Love constantly
nagged Cobain about the contents of his will in the weeks before
his death.
</P>
<P>
   Others maintain the Cobain-Love marriage was on the rocks, and
that Cobain intended to file for divorce, giving Love some motive
for having her husband murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield doesn't believe Love arranged Cobain's murder. He
doesn't need to _ there are enough others, including Tom Grant, a
private investigator originally hired to find Cobain after he
skipped out of a Los Angeles drug treatment facility days before
his death. Grant is now one of the leading murder conspiracy
theorists. There's El Duce, who looks like an extra from
``Deliverance,'' and was, before his death shortly after talking to
Broomfield, the leader of some sort of S&AMP;M thrash band, who says
Love offered him $50,000 to ``whack'' Cobain.
</P>
<P>
   But none are as terrifying or unsettling as Hank Harrison,
Love's father. A former Grateful Dead roadie who once used pit
bulls to discipline his daughter, Harrison has found a career in
writing books branding Love a murderer. He screams into the camera
exactly what he will do to Love if she tries any legal tricks to
stop him, and once you stop laughing, your mouth will be slack with
horror. In another life, Love and Harrison would be duking it out
on the ``Jerry Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's gentler moments are ephemeral, such as an interview
with Cobain's aunt who gave her nephew his first guitar, and still
treasures recordings of his earliest musical efforts. That's almost
all that's heard of Cobain's music since Love wouldn't allow any
Nirvana music in the film. Never a woman to be trifled with, Love
pulls out every diva trick short of biblical plagues to keep
Broomfield from completing his film. Somehow, Broomfield, who seems
smarmyhimself, never elicits much sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Broomfield's sources are hardly the most reliable people, and
there are no conversations with those who spent a great deal of
time with Cobain, including his former Nirvana bandmates Dave
Grohl, now of Foo Fighters, and Krist Novoselic. He tries to hijack
an interview fromLove at an American Civil Liberties Union dinner,
but she's just not having it.
</P>
<P>
   Is Love ill-tempered and difficult? Without a doubt. But in all
likelihood, Kurt Cobain was a tremendously talented, but deeply
troubled man, who, under the strain of his career, perhaps a
failing marriage, and the influence of drugs, blew his head off one
April day. For all the dust it kicks up, ``Kurt and Courtney''
doesn't uncover any dark truths about Cobain's sad end. Mainly,
it's a nightmarish tour, guided by bottom-feeders, through the
sleazy underbelly of fame. It's as grisly as a multi-car pileup,
and just as luridly fascinating to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6513 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BREAK-BOS &LR;      06-12 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BREAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN TAUGHT TO KILL FOR A CAUSE LOSES HIS CONVICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE BREAK
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Dornhelm
</P>
<P>
   Written by Ronan Bennett, based on an idea by Stephen Rea
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Stephen Rea, Alfred Molina, Rosana Pastor, and Brendan
Gleeson
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 96 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Rea has a face like an emotional weather map, on which
every crag, every angle, every furrow is etched with indelible
sorrow. The eyes brood and mourn; the gaze is funereal. And that's
a good thing in ``The Break,'' because the best parts of this
political thriller unfold on the actor's face, which subtly and
stoically communicates more about the conflicted soul of an IRA
terrorist than the thin plot and clipped dialogue of Ronan
Bennett's screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   The film starts with an intriguing notion: What happens when a
man who was raised to hate and taught to kill loses his conviction
for the cause? Can he make the psychological break after he has
made his literal escape from prison, in this case the notorious
H-Block in Northern Ireland's Maze Prison? Certainly, he can get a
fake passport and cross the Atlantic, but can he vanquish memory,
unlearn old habits, build a new life? He can break out, but can he
break free?
</P>
<P>
   Rea is best known for his intense performance as the inscrutable
gunman in ``The Crying Game,'' and ``The Break'' is based on his
original idea. It opens within the drab, concrete walls of the
prison, where Rea's character, Sean Dowd, joins a group of inmates
who overcome the prison guards. The escape from the high-security
jail is pulled off with unlikely ease, and the film overall has a
breezy naivete about the complex world of political terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Dowd flees to New York, where he is befriended by a family of
Guatemalan refugees harboring secrets of their own. Alfred Molina
plays a salt-of-the-earth dishwasher who saves Dowd's life, and
Rosana Pastor is his sultry sister Monica, who falls in love with
Dowd in about two seconds. They are plotting to assassinate a
vicious killer from their native land, and Dowd is faced with a
choice: Should he use his covert skill to help these earnest
amateurs or should he come clean for good?
</P>
<P>
   It's an intriguing dilemma that never achieves its promise,
though. Director Robert Dornhelm shoots two equally claustrophobic
worlds, from the drab, bleak shots of Ireland to dark, shabby
interiors of an utterly unromantic New York. There is no air, no
light in either environment, perhaps because the characters are
suffocated by the shadows of the past. The dialogue is clipped,
terse, economical to a fault, as if language threatens to reveal
too much. Apart from the assassination plot, the conflict here is
interior, played out in Dowd's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Rea is perfectly cast, and he is absolutely
fascinating to watch. In one scene, he lies alone in a bare
rent-by-the-night hotel room, drinking from a cheap bottle of
whiskey; he pulls the bottle to his lips, and you know instantly
this is a haunted soul, the ultimate outcast. When he connects with
Monica, he cringes at the mere suggestion of feeling. As outcasts
from another culture, Molina and Pastor are earthy types, but
they're more like outlines than full-bodied characters. Plus, their
``political'' situation is vague and absurd, like an un- &QC; 
schooled novelist's version of upheaval in an unfamiliar territory.
</P>
<P>
   There is very little political detail in this purportedly
political story, and the lack of research weakens its premise. The
machinations of age-old conflicts are far too complex to be brushed
off with sketchy plot devices, instant romances, and crimes that
are made too simple. When the inevitable happens, a law officer
brushes it off as ``some Irish thing,'' with the same inexplicable
nonchalance that permeates ``The Break.'' There is an opportunity
lost with this film, especially when the recent peace agreement in
Ireland leaves many wondering what happens when the cause ceases to
exist, on paper or in the mind. No doubt, that dilemma is fodder
for future films, but in ``The Break'' we get only a glimmer of
that conflict, seen in the shadows of Rea's changing face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
