<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKER LEGEND OF 1988 BECOMES NEWEST INTERNET MILLIONAIRE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; An intriguing social note arises from this week's $49 million
takeover of Cambridge's Viaweb by Internet search engine giant
Yahoo! Inc. One of Viaweb's three co-founders _ and doubtless one
of Viaweb's newly minted paper millionaires _ is convicted computer
felon Robert Tappan Morris.
</P>
<P>
   You don't remember Robert Morris? The Justice Department does.
He was the 24-year-old programming genius who unleashed the famous
Internet ``worm'' of 1988, a virus launched from an MIT computer
that crippled an estimated 6,000 computers, includin sensitive
hardware owned by NASA and the Department of Defense. His defense
lawyers argued that an error caused the rogue program to go
berserk. Government prosecutors told the court that Morris had
stolen hundreds of computer passwords and tried to disguise the
program's origins so it could not be traced to him at Cornell
University, where he was then a graduate student.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Morris was convicted of computer fraud, fined $10,000,
and sentenced to three years' probation and 400 hours of community
service. Ironically, Morris is credited with putting the Internet
on the map. ``Not a lot of people on the street had heard that word
before the trial,'' says Viaweb cofounder Paul Graham. At the time
of Morris's prank, the outside world had virtually zero knowledge
or understanding of the communications system that linked
practically all of the country's major computing centers. Now we
know.
</P>
<P>
   Graham says that Morris, now finishing up his PhD in computer
science at Harvard, ``is the most upstanding guy I know.'' Morris
is hardly the only computer miscreant to have become a productive
member of society. Former MIT student David LaMacchia, whom the
government accused of computer piracy when he posted copyrighted
software programs on his electronic bulletin board, had the charges
against him dismissed in 1994 and now works for Oracle. Two other
members of the hacker elite, Kevin Poulsen and Randal Schwartz,
have sought the ultimate refuge of the congenital sociopath _
they've become columnists.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, widely hailed as a genius in the Perl programming
language, writes a column for a publication called Web
Techniques. &UR;  &LR; His Internet home page
(www.lightlink.com/spacenka/fors/) has all the details of his 1995
felony conviction under Oregon's computer crime law, and provides
an opportunity to contribute to his legal defense fund. Poulsen
became a fugitive from justice _ and a hacker legend _ after he
managed to gain access to records of sensitive FBI investigations
in the mid-1980s. While fleeing the feds, Poulsen, widely known by
his log-on ``Dark Dante,'' supported himself by successfully
rigging radio phone-in contests, winning a vacation to Hawaii and a
Porsche in the process. He was eventually caught and imprisoned for
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Poulsen's web site (www.catalog.com/kevin/) has an entry,
``Kevin Sells Out to Corporate America,'' which allows visitors to
access his weekly column at ZDTV.com, appropriately titled, ``Chaos
Theory.'' In his most recent outing, Poulsen warns readers that his
``normally unassailable objectivity should be suspect this week.''
That's because he's writing about another famous computer felon,
the still-imprisoned Kevin Mitnick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Classicists everywhere were shocked and appalled to see
Bloomingdale's hyping Master of the Universe cuff links for
Father's Day ... with an astonishing Latin error. The $50
chatchkas, advertised in The New York Times, display the phrase,
``Veni, Vedi, Vici.'' The Bloomies ad copy states that this is
Julius Caesar's famous line, ``I came, I saw, I conquered,'' which
is actually spelled, ``Veni, Vidi, Vici.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloomingdale's executive Anne Keating says the vendor, Swank, is
``very embarrassed'' by the spelling gaffe and that the store is
removing the cuff links from the sales floor. Corrected links will
be available next week. But what do the cuff links say? We called
in TGIF's Special Dead Languages Consultant, Caroline Caswell of
Latin Academy, to translate the bungled quote. ``Vedi' could be the
vocative for the Etruscan god of the underworld, Vedius,'' Ms.
Caswell explained. ``So the phrase could read, `I came, Vedius, I
conquered' ... but why? Somebody didn't do their homework.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(AT)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
