<HEADER>
A6523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-JEALOSY-BOS &LR;      06-12 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-JEALOSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMEDY OF INSECURITY IN THE BIG CITY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MR. JEALOUSY &QC; 
Written and directed by: Noah Baumbach &QC; 
Starring: Eric Stoltz, Annabella Sciorra, Chris Eigeman, Carlos
Jacott, Marianne Jean-Baptiste, Berian Kerwin, Peter Bogdanovich,
Bridget Fonda, John Lehr &QC; 
Running time: 105 minutes &QC; 
Rated: R (language) &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Until it thins out and is beached on the increasingly
unrewarding self-absorption of its characters, Noah Baumbach's
``Mr. Jealousy'' provides ample evidence that his debut feature,
``Kicking and Screaming,'' was no fluke. He fills the screen with
bright Manhattan neurotics led by Eric Stoltz's romantically
blundering title-roleist and Annabella Sciorra's incandescent art
historian working as a tour guide in the Brooklyn Museum. For the
film's first half at least, he keeps us hooked as he traces their
rocky relationships, past and present. It's the past that makes
trouble for Stoltz's insecure would-be writer. His obsession with
the ex-lovers of Sciorra's less-messed-up love interest keeps
getting in his way.
</P>
<P>
   He knows it, knows he needs help, but when he goes after it,
it's because he wants to get inside the head of Sciorra's ex-lover,
whose presence in her history is all the more galling to Stoltz
because the guy happens to be a best-selling writer. To feed his
obsession with spying on her, he joins the ex-boyfriend's therapy
group, assuming the name and history of his buddy, Carlos Jacott's
Vince, who's filled with enough of his own qualms about marrying
his own girlfriend. Sciorra's insecure but emotionally tough and
honest Brooklyn girl is easier to take than Stoltz's hapless dope,
whose one-note narrowness provides a real test of the actor's
ability to divert us with soft charm.
</P>
<P>
   As the deceptions escalate, the comedy of insecurity quickly
hits a point of diminishing returns before deflating in a farcical
climax outside the therapist's office when everyone confronts
everyone else. One of the surprises that keeps the deflation at
bay, however, is the way Stoltz's drolly named Lester Grimm becomes
friends, against his better judgment, with the quarry he hates. But
his rival, astutely and alertly played by Whit Stillman regular
Chris Eigeman, convinces us he's smarter and more sensitive than
Lester cares to admit, but finally does. He's the film's most
unpredictable element, but the ensemble quality is high and
likable, even if Baumbach's inventiveness as a writer falters after
the film's sweet, savvy beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Names, by the way, are only one of the forms of homage Baumbach
works into ``Mr. Jealousy.'' Baumbach, son of critics and scholars
Jonathan Baumbach and Georgia Brown, cut his teeth on films, loves
them, and has worked into this film a number of salutes. These
range from such stylistic flourishes as wipes and irises, a snatch
of music from ``Jules and Jim,'' a voice-over by Baumbach, a
genuflection to his parents, a nicely gauged performance by Peter
Bogdanovich as the therapist, and a plot turn that hinges on
knowing whether ``The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance'' was shot in
color or black and white. He has also appropriated and rendered
into contemporary New Yorkese the French New Wave's rueful sense of
the messy overlaps of love lives, which it in turn learned from the
great Jean Renoir, to whose benevolence and embrace of his
characters Baumbach is winningly attuned. May his next film arrive
soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
