<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKAKIS-LEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIA DUKAKIS ASSESSES TITLE ROLE IN ALL-WOMEN ``LEAR''
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympia Dukakis has played plenty of mothers in her 40 years of
acting, from her Oscar-winning performance as the matriarch in
``Moonstruck'' to Amanda Wingfield in ``The Glass Menagerie.'' She
raised three children of her own and nursed her mother when she was
confined to a home for senior citizens. So motherhood is familiar
territory. But at 66, the actress never expected to be appearing as
parent to the likes of Regan, Goneril, and Cordelia, the trio of
sisters in Shakespeare's tragedy ``King Lear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' she says, ``I'm not someone who has been running
around all of my life saying I wanted to play this role.'' But
protests aside, she is, in fact, playing the aging monarch in ``The
Lear Project,'' a joint production of Shakespeare and Company and
the Orpheum Theatre-Foxborough. Dukakis isn't doing the role in
drag: Her Lear is every inch a queen, a mother and ruler who
decides to give up her kingdom in her declining years. Lear is one
of the most captivating roles in dramatic literature, and it
resonates for Dukakis in more ways than one. ``Aging is a big part
of it,'' she says. ``I had a mother who passed away a few years ago
at 93, and I was very present during her aging process. I saw her
struggle to find a place of peace. It's very interesting what
happens. There is an accumulation of a lifetime, the evaluation of
a life, the accounting one takes.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as her mother used to say, Dukakis is ``no spring
chicken,'' which makes this project ``a mountain to climb, complex
and profound, but terribly moving.'' This particular expedition
began a year ago, when Dukakis agreed to try the gender-bending
role at the suggestion of Shakespeare and Company's cofounder
Dennis Krausnick. Dukakis's daughter, Christina Zorich, is in
training with the company in Lenox, and she plays Cordelia to her
mother's Lear. The troupe is exploring the play through a female
point of view, probing a woman's struggle with power and dynasty as
well as her complex relationship with her daughters and with the
Fool (played by another woman, the estimable Tina Packer).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very dangerous: We're really courting fear and
humiliation here,'' Dukakis says, without a trace of fear in her
deep, throaty voice. This is a woman who has played contemporary
roles and classics on Broadway and in regional theaters nationwide
(she opens in the title role of Euripides's ``Hecuba'' at the
Williamstown Theatre Festival later this summer) and who has
garnered considerable credits on both the small and large screens.
You don't expect fear and humiliation from Dukakis. Intensity, yes.
Passion, yes. Fear? Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   But ``The Lear Project'' comes when Dukakis is taking stock of
her life. A child of Greek immigrants (and cousin of former
governor Michael Dukakis) who was raised in Lowell, she's at that
point in her career when she's long past ingenues but not quite
ready for doting grandmothers. The no-spring-chicken dilemma. Men
get to look forward to Lear, to Prospero, to Vanya. With women,
it's another story. ``In contemporary drama, most of the roles for
older women don't have complexity, don't have challenges,'' she
says. ``As a matter of fact, most commercial parts are trivialized
or ridiculed. Older women don't get a chance to see themselves up
there, and younger women don't get a chance to see what's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, she finds it thrilling to work so closely with
her daughter, who has never performed Shakespeare before. ``It's
great to watch her, and everything is easier,'' she notes. The
real-life link enhances the relationship onstage: ``It's easier to
be offended by her, to be moved by her, to love her. The
mother-daughter relationship is very different from the
father-daughter relationship. At times, it can be more fierce and
more vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The role raises never-ending questions. ``What happens to a
woman in order to rule and to succeed in her world? What kind of
skills does she have to learn? What does that do to her as a
woman?'' Dukakis keeps the questions coming. ``What happens to a
woman in a world dominated by men?''
</P>
<P>
   By extension, what happens to ordinary women of a certain age in
contemporary society? Dukakis doesn't ask that one herself, but she
answers it. ``I'm interested in ways women are trying to figure out
how to function in a world that is seen through a male lens,'' she
says. ``Often, they're not needed or respected, but they're also
complicit in silencing themselves. It's too easy to say, `Oh, well,
we live in a patriarchal world. They did this, or they did that.'
But the truth is, we're very complicit in it. More and more, women
_ especially someone like me, who has raised two sons and a
daughter _ are saying, `How do I really want to live and be known?'
as opposed to how the world tells me I should be known or how I
should please others.''
</P>
<P>
   But for 40 years, she has worked in a business that is all about
... ``about pleasing!'' she says, finishing the thought. ``I don't
have the answers, but I'm beginning to find the questions. That's
pretty good. First we gotta get the questions.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the questions are rooted in the mother she is and
the mothers she has played. ``The end of nurturing is not the end
of growing,'' she says. ``Your children leaving the house is not
the end of all things that will transform you and change you.'' A
pause. ``As my husband says, the dog barks and the caravan moves
on. It's not over. The caravan just keeps going.'' In this case, it
moves up that mountain to the world of Lear.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lear Project'' is at the Orpheum Theatre-Foxborough June
16-21 and at Shakespeare and Company in Lenox June 23-28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
