   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-THORNBIRDS-CHAMBERLAIN (Undated) _ Richard Chamberlain talks
about the series that captivated a country in 1983 on the eve of
its revival. By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES-WODEHOUSE (Undated) _ In 1927, when James H. Heineman
was 10, he demonstrated a bibliographic bent: he began buying first
editions of the novels of his favorite author, the British writer
P.G. Wodehouse, whose works poked fun at bumbling English
aristocrats. Over the next 60 years, Heineman continued to buy the
works of Wodehouse, amassing a collection of some 6,300 items. Next
Sunday, Heineman's entire Wodehouse collection goes on view for the
first time at Sotheby's in New York, where it will be auctioned in
150 lots on June 26. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   FLAMENCO-DANCE (New York) _ It was not a dream. Late one night
last month, at Tunnel, a club in lower Manhattan, the deejay threw
a curve. For several hours a group of young men and women had been
gyrating to hip-hop, house and techno music when, out of the blue,
a passionate song sung by Alejandro Sanz filled the room. Without
missing a beat, the dancers' posture changed. They lifted their
chests, placed their hands on their waists and prepared for a fiery
flamenco. Then, fingers clicking, hips swiveling, feet pounding,
they had a go at it. They sizzled. And why not? Flamenco is hot. By
Valerie Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   MANZE-MUSIC (Undated) _ If two new CDs by the English violinist
Andrew Manze are any indication, early music may finally be
shedding one of classical music's most venerable but useless
assumptions. To wit, the funny notion abroad among classical-music
reviewers that the best thing a performer can do is disappear. By
Richard Taruskin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-CASTLES (Undated) _ Exploring the cobblestone
streets and medieval castles of Portugal's hilltop towns. By
Mitchel Levitas.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PORTUGAL-EXPO (Lisbon) _ Lisbon looks to the future as
well as to its glorious maritime past with Expo '98. By Alan
Riding.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ How can you get anywhere if you
won't fly and can't drive? Very slowly. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRAZIL (Salvador, Brazil) _ Bahia makes room for a
Candomble Pantheon. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Travel notes and news: U.S tour
companies venture to Iran; Denmark town celebrates 1,000 years;
Pacific Aquarium opens in Long Beach; a wetter, wilder Dollywood.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ The Czar's burial; Tudor events in
England; the pope in St. Louis.
