<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS FLOCK TO HABITAT PROJECT IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Art available on NYT photo service) 
 
By LISA M. CHMIOLA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Newlyweds Ken and Gretchen Kirkpatrick are about to
put their marriage to a real test by building a house together.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not even for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Kirkpatricks are among the 6,000 volunteers who will work
next week building affordable housing for low-income families on
Habitat for Humanity's Jimmy Carter Work Project. The project began
in 1984 when Carter worked at a Habitat site in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Each year the project visits a different city, and Carter and
his wife, Rosalynn, join volunteers to help build homes and raise
awareness of the need for low-cost housing. This year, volunteers
will build 100 homes in one week in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the largest Habitat project ever conducted in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without them, we couldn't do it. It physically couldn't be
done,'' said Rev. Michael Shirl, executive director of Houston
Habitat for Humanity. Shirl added that hiring subcontractors to do
the work would add $12,000 to $15,000 to each home's cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens (during construction) is friendships are built,
relationships are built, and everyone begins to learn about each
other. Before you know it, people are having a good time, and they
walk out of it with relationships that last a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Kirkpatricks, family ties will be renewed when Gretchen
Kirkpatrick's mother, Carol Gregory, and aunt, Dixie Conner, take
time off work to help out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Gregory, director of Habitat affiliates in the
Atlanta area, who persuaded Gretchen to get involved in the
project. When she called and said she would be working on the
Houston project, Kirkpatrick decided to pitch in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been the kind of person who would give a dollar
... but I've never gone out and volunteered,'' Kirkpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her mom, who has spent 13 years with Habitat, told her
to anticipate 12-hour workdays in the Houston heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we won't suffer any sunburn,'' Kirkpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   The heat also concerns project planner Becky Neuhaus, who is in
charge of coordinating transportation, housing, hospitality and
food _ especially the more than 40,000 gallons of water volunteers
will drink during the week. Also lined up are air-conditioned
first-aid trailers at each site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the goodie bags, we have tips to stay healthy during this
(heat),'' Neuhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   The project actually began about two years ago, when Milby Hart
and other volunteers canvassed inner-city areas looking for land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inner-city development requires an inordinate amount of
work,'' said Hart, a Houston attorney who has volunteered with
Habitat for 11 years. ``It requires patience, planning and
perseverance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart said he has cut back his hours at his practice during
recent months as the project week neared.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't trade it for the world,'' Hart said. ``You feel
good. You feel productive. You feel valuable. You feel like you're
making a bona fide effort to improve the quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick said she felt privileged to participate. ``When I
walk away, I can say, `I helped build that house, and this family
is going to have a comfortable place to live.' That, in and of
itself, is a privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus echoed that thought. ``It's something you don't get to
do every day. It's getting out there in the fresh air and being
with your friends. It's a really great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
