<P>
   CIR-WEB-FILTERS-NYT (Undated) _ The American Family Association,
a conservative Christian group, has strongly supported filtering
products, software meant to cordon off X-rated and other nasty
corners of the Internet from users, especially children. So it was
with some surprise that AFA officials discovered that their group's
own Web pages were being lumped together with skinhead, white
supremacist and other ``intolerant'' sites blocked by a popular
filter called Cyber Patrol. By Pamela Mendels. Moved 6-10. WITH
PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-JEWS-ART-HNS (Havana) _ Before the 1959 revolution, some
15,000 Jews lived in Cuba. Thousands fled when Castro took over,
and those who remained faced the near-extinction of their faith and
culture. But in recent years there has been a growing renewal of
Cuba's small, impoverished Jewish community. That renaissance
continues, thanks in large measure to tireless assistance from
American Jews. By Cecile S. Holmes. Moved 6-9. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CANTORS-CONCERT-REVIEW-NYT (New York) _ To commemorate the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the Cantors Assembly, nearly two
dozen cantors from synagogues across the country took to the stage
of Carnegie Hall on Monday evening and performed classic settings
of prayers from the Sabbath and holiday services. By Allan Kozinn.
Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-CASAROLI-NYT (Rome) _ Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the
former Vatican secretary of state, died June 9 at 83. Casaroli was
second-in-command to Pope John Paul II during the most active and
turbulent times of his pontificate and the architect of
rapprochement with the communist world. By Alessandra Stanley.
Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   ISLAM-BOMB-REVIEW-NYT (Washington) _ For more than two decades,
the prospect that a Muslim country could possess nuclear weapons
has often been summed up in two words _ ``Islamic bomb'' _ a phrase
that captured the imagination of some and terrified others. But is
there such a thing as a bomb that exists for the sake of Islam and
for the destruction of Israel? Or do the phrase and the oratory
about it reveal other things instead _ a hunger and rivalry for
greatness by major Islamic countries, and the depth of Israel's
anxieties? By Elaine Sciolino. Moved 6-6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTHERN BAPTIST CONVENTION  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-COX (Salt Lake City) _ By only 66 votes of more than
2,000 cast, the Southern Baptist Convention on Thursday refused to
call on President Clinton's home church in Arkansas to consider
disciplining the president for his stand on civil rights protection
for homosexual federal employees. By Gayle White. Moved 6-11.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-SIDE-COX (Salt Lake City) _ The Southern Baptist
Convention continued the process of gender definition begun earlier
in the week by coming out Thursday against women in combat, calling
the practice ''a foolish social experiment.'' By Gayle White. Moved
6-12.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-DOBSON-NYT (Salt Lake City) _ The 8,500 representatives
from Southern Baptist churches in 36 states were encouraged in
their views stands by James Dobson, president and founder of Focus
on the Family, an independent evangelical organization based in
Colorado Springs, Colo. Dobson gave the convention's keynote
address Thursday and received a standing ovation from the Southern
Baptists. His books and daily radio program on child-rearing and
family issues are popular among evangelical Christians. By Cary
McMullen. Moved 6-11. with photo.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-BAPTISTS-HNS (Salt Lake City) _ Southern Baptists
concluded their annual meeting Thursday by continuing criticism of
the policies of the nation's foremost Southern Baptist public
official _ President Clinton. Delegates approved a resolution
urging Congress to overturn Clinton's executive order banning
discrimination in the federal civilian workforce based on sexual
orientation. By Richard Vara. Moved 6-11.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-COX (Salt Lake City) _ Southern Baptists urged
Americans to consider character when evaluating the performance of
public officials, but defeated an attempt to single out President
Clinton, a fellow Southern Baptist, in the resolution they adopted
at their annual convention. By Gayle White. Moved 6-10.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-NYT (Salt Lake City) _ The Southern Baptist Convention,
the nation's largest Protestant denomination and an increasingly
conservative force among American religious organizations, amended
its essential statement of beliefs Tuesday to include a declaration
that God expects a woman to ``submit graciously'' to her husband's
leadership, and for a husband to ``provide for, to protect and to
lead his family.'' By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-CONVERT-SFCHRON (Salt Lake City) _ The Southern Baptist
effort to convert Jews is in full swing. James Sibley, hired by the
Southern Baptists as their national consultant on Jewish
evangelism, says says secularism, not Christianity, is the main
threat to Judaism. Maybe so, but the Southern Baptist move has
enraged American Jewish leaders, who call it an insult and major
setback for interfaith relations. By Don Lattin. Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-C0NVERT-COX (Undated) _ The Southern Baptist blitz is
on in the home of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.
Southern Baptists from across the nation, meeting for their
national convention in Salt Lake City, are taking part in an effort
to persuade Mormons to change their beliefs, to reach the
unchurched with the gospel of Jesus and maybe to win back some
Southern Baptists who converted to Mormonism. By Kim Sue Lia
Perkes. Moved 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-MORMONS-NYT (Salt Lake City) _ Call it a confrontation
between the confident and the convinced. For the past week,
Southern Baptists have been gathering here in the capital of the
Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, observing, listening
to seminars on Mormon beliefs, and evangelizing a people who say
they are already Christian. By Cary McMullen. Moved 6-8. WITH
PHOTOS AND GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-TEX (Salt Lake City) _ Conservatives hammered home
another spike in their domination of the Southern Baptist
Convention on Tuesday by adopting a statement affirming a biblical
hierarchy for the family stating that ``a wife is to submit
graciously to the servant leadership of her husband.'' By Jim
Jones. Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-WOMAN-HNS (Undated) _ A Sunday sidewalk protest by
dozens of followers of the ultra-conservative Rev. W.N. Otwell will
not keep a Baptist church in Waco, Texas, from hiring its first
female senior pastor, church leaders said Monday. By Allan Turner.
Moved 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTIST-WIVES-HNS (Salt Lake City) _ Southern Baptist Convention
leaders Tuesday defended a new doctrinal statement on the family
that defines the role of husbands as providers and leaders and asks
that wives ``submit graciously to the servant leadership of her
husband.'' By Richard Vara and Cecile S. Holme. Moved 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ Can competition's benefits for
sports, business and government be similarly realized in organized
religion? Yes, replies Rodney Stark, a professor of sociology and
comparative religion at the University of Washington, who recently
published the results of a study making that case. Among Stark's
findings was that the areas of the country that had recently
produced the highest number of Roman Catholic priests, seminarians
and conversions, relative to the size of the Catholic population,
were also areas where Catholics were a small minority. By Gustav
Niebuhr. Moved 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ About three dozen attorneys and
law students gathered last week for a conference entitled, ``Beyond
the Code of Professional Responsibility: Can Spiritual Values Be
Our Compass?'' Religious and spiritual values, the lawyers argued,
give meaning to every aspect of personal and professional life,
even in such a seemingly secular vocation as law. By Diego
Ribadeneira. Moved 6-11.
</P>
