<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SHAKERS-BOS &LR;      06-12 1500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SHAKERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTEMPORARY ARTISTS GAIN INSPIRATION FROM SHAKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``THE QUIET IN THE LAND: Everyday Life, Contemporary Art and the
Shakers''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by France Morin.
</P>
<P>
   At: Institute of Contemporary Art, through Sept. 27.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Shaker sect dwindles in numbers _ only seven members
remain in the last active community, in Sabbathday Lake, Maine _
Shaker influence in design and art increases. Most people, in fact,
know the Shakers only through those signature oval boxes and
rocking chairs that seem so in tune with contemporary minimalist
style. ``When I die,'' mused the late Sister R. Mildred Barker, ``I
fairly expect to be remembered as a piece of Shaker furniture.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the strengths of the new show at the Institute of
Contemporary Art, ``The Quiet in the Land: Everyday Life,
Contemporary Art and the Shakers,'' is that it goes beyond the
furniture. The premise of the show is both simple and surprising.
Smitten by all things Shaker, New York-based independent curator
France Morin proposed a collaboration between the Sabbathday Lake
community and a group of contemporary artists. The Shakers
declined. Morin persisted and eventually prevailed. She invited 10
international artists to spend about a month at Sabbathday Lake in
the summer of 1996. Morin, the artists, and the Shakers lived,
worked, and worshiped together. The artists kept journals and drew
on them to make work they first exhibited at the Maine College of
Art in Portland last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Medvedow, the ICA's new director, saw the show in Portland
and went after it with as much determination as Morin had
displayed. One theme that attracted Medvedow was the stability of
the Shaker community vs. the mobility of modern life. Most of the
artists in the show, she notes, no longer live in the countries
where they were born. Some of the artists speak wistfully about the
Shakers' roots, but there was never any intention of Shakers
recruiting artists or vice versa. A respectful sharing was Morin's
idea.
</P>
<P>
   You might expect a certain superficiality in the show: A month
of living a vastly different life is mere toe in water. Morin knew
this and wisely chose artists who would avoid cliche and bring
their own experiences to the project rather than try to be
temporary Shakers. The success of this meeting of two groups who
are ostensibly as different as two groups could be is movingly
documented in a 45-minute video by Branka Bogdanov, the ICA's
senior video producer-curator, which should be your first stop at
the show. It reminds you that the Shakers broke down orthodoxy,
that they were _ and still are _ radicals, that equality of the
sexes was a tenet for them long before the feminist movement.
Artist Janine Antoni used this separate-but-equal status of Shaker
men and women as the basis for color photographs of the different
doors, staircases, and dining tables the men and women use, which
Antoni cropped and seamed to look like mirror images.
</P>
<P>
   When artist Domenico de Clario wanted to move a grand piano into
the Sabbathday Lake meetinghouse so he could play all through the
night of the summer solstice, the Shakers, after initial
hesitation, not only let him do it but sat through the performance
and later pronounced it powerfully beautiful. Bogdanov's video
shows how these unworldly people came to appreciate some of the
farthest shores of contemporary art because they came to it with
open minds and hearts. Sabbathday Lake Brother Wayne Smith
summarized it with Shaker economy: ``You do art, we do praying.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound of the improvised piano pieces de Clario made at
Sabbathday Lake wafts through the ICA. Contemplative and unhurried,
the music seems to slow the space down. Its phrases are short, some
questioning, some comforting. De Clario's work involves a ceding of
control: He made both the music and the monochromatic paintings in
the ICA show while ``blindfolded'' by a Shaker basket inverted over
his head. The results seem as connected to Zen, John Cage, and the
automatic writing of the Surrealists as to the Shaker faith.
</P>
<P>
   Antoni, too, got permission to use the meetinghouse, for the
kind of spinning dance that once was a part of the community's
rites. Holding a video camera, she spun until she fell to the
floor. The blurry, vertiginous result reads like an abstraction of
Doris Humphrey's 1930 dance ``The Shakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The fragmentation of de Clario's work is complemented by Sam
Samore's. He has outlined the ICA's zigzagging staircase with a
stream-of-consciousness text drawn in part from Shaker songs he
found in the Sabbathday Lake library. While the phrases are as
choppy as the staircase itself, they also pull the place together.
A line like ``making the anxiety sit still'' can stop you in your
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   This show somehow makes the ICA look even whiter than usual,
nowhere more so than in the mezzanine gallery where Adam Fuss's
silk and mylar ladders are affixed to the wall. They're silhouettes
without the contrasts, white on white, lit so they almost disappear
at the top. They start a couple of inches off the floor, which
gives them an otherworldly, gravity-free quality.
</P>
<P>
   Shakers seek the sublime in the everyday; so do many
contemporary artists. Jana Sterbak's search involved an ordinary
metal stool whose seat she replaced with a sponge cake. A
juxtaposition of two utilitarian objects, ``Cake Stool'' also
offers the show's only whiff of humor. Mona Hatoum took mundane
objects from a Shaker kitchen _ graters, colanders, strainers _ and
pressed them into ghostly white waxed paper. The regularity of the
resulting dots is contradicted by the intricate veining caused by
handling of the fragile surface. Hatoum's ``First Step'' is an
infant's crib that has left in its wake a powdered sugar stencil of
the diamond pattern of the crib's springs. It is literally
sweetness and innocence _ and makes you think of the Shakers'
celibacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese-born artist Kazumi Tanaka commemorates the silent
grace before Shaker meals in her installation ``Communion,'' a pair
of tables with shallow basins set in them. The basins are filled
with water on which the plainest of white dinner plates float. Food
would both sink and soil them: This is a meal of the mind. Between
the two tables stands a tall clock, ticking away the seconds, the
sound Tanaka remembers from the silent grace. The clock has no
face: It measures no time in particular. Tanaka's installation is
reminiscent of the 1996 show ``Kindred Spirits,'' a juxtaposition
of Shaker and Japanese arts. ``Kindred Spirits,'' which visited the
Art Complex Museum in Duxbury, demonstrated that the yearning for
the plain transcends geography.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Tillmans and Chen Zhen include images and artifacts
from non-Shaker cultures in their work. Tillmans's huge collage of
color photographs features skyscrapers, suburbs, train tracks, and
freeways, symbols of a frenetic contemporary life, along with
photographs of Sabbathday Lake, which looks removed from time. But
his most jarring inclusions are photos of Baroque churches whose
more-is-more aesthetic wars with Shaker modesty. Zhen made an altar
of Chinese wooden vessels, Asian counterparts to Shaker boxes,
along with a 10-sided Shaker chair, and wrapped both in an airy
framework of Chinese latticework windows. Zhen also made realist
portraits of all seven Shakers. On Bogdanov's video, Sister Frances
A. Carr reacts to hers, first with an ``I don't look like that!''
response, then by acknowledging that we don't see ourselves as
others do.
</P>
<P>
   Bogdanov's video also describes how artists and Shakers
collaborated on the restoration of an old fence, picket by picket.
Manual labor is, like love of the everyday, common to both. Manual
labor is much evident in Nari Ward's ``Threshold,'' which recycles
discards from Sabbathday Lake and a Baptist church in Harlem, where
Ward lives. Among the several elements in this muscular sculpture
are two Harlem preachers' pulpits, which face each other as Shaker
men and women face each other in the meetinghouse. The work is
surrounded by a burlap-wrapped fence from the porch of the
Sabbathday Lake Sisters' Shop. This fence, which was rotting, has
been replaced, and Ward smiles as he explains with what, because it
illustrates that Shakers are not trying to preserve some quaint
antique lifestyle. ``They wanted pressure-treated,'' Ward says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The first of the public events in conjunction with the ICA show
will be a lecture June 25 by Gerald C. Wertkin, director of the
Museum of American Folk Art in New York. He is to speak on the
history of the Shaker faith at 7:30 p.m. in the ICA theater. At 2
p.m. on June 26, Medvedow is scheduled to give a tour of the show.
And at 7:30 p.m. on July 16, Boston artist Michael Dowling is
slated to tell stories based on myth and spirituality, suitable for
all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
