   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Removing any lingering doubts that Japan is
in a full-blown recession, the Finance Ministry said that the
economy contracted at a 5.3 percent annual rate in the year's first
quarter. Compared with the prior three months, the decline in gross
domestic product was 1.3 percent, faster than the contraction in
1997's final three months. It was the first time in six years that
Japan had recorded two consecutive quarterly declines. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-ECON (Tokyo) _ South Korean stocks tumble a record 8.1
percent. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., the industrial average was
down 113 points, and, at midday, the long bond was off 5/32, with
the yield at 5.67 percent. In Asia, share prices were flat in Tokyo
and up 0.4 of 1 percent in Hong Kong. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SIXTIES-REVISITED (Undated) _ Historians are beginning to
rewrite the history of the 1960s, saying that the culture wars have
distorted our understanding of the period. By Patti Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-MULES (Undated) _ They die by asphyxiation, rabies,
drowning and falling off cliffs. They are hit by railroad trains,
worked to death, hanged, stabbed, shot and, in one Cormac McCarthy
novel, decapitated by an irate opera singer. Such is the fate of
the mules of the South as recounted in a minor classic of mock
scholarship entitled ``Equine Gothic: The Dead Mule as Generic
Signifier in Southern Literature in the Twentieth Century'' that
asked a simple question, ``What makes Southern literature
Southern?'' and came up with a simpler answer. You can tell it's
Southern if it has a dead mule in it. But, if the dead mule is the
signifier for Southern literature, what is the element that makes
French literature French or Irish literature Irish or film noir
noir? By Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-THEATER (New York) _ New York City's last
Chinese-language theater, the Music Palace, will soon take its
final bow, its faded three-story structure to be demolished and
replaced by a gleaming office building. The growing popularity of
videotapes is partly to blame, along with Chinese cable TV programs
and other options for staying in touch with the homeland. But the
theater's passing is also a small milestone in the story of the
Chinese in America, a shift toward the mainstream that recalls the
experience of Italians, Jews, Puerto Ricans, and other newcomers
who once had thriving theaters, too. By David Chen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORLD CUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports Column on players on the
U.S. World Cup team who played in Germany. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLDCUP (Marseilles) _ France opens World Cup play in its
own country with a game against South Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
