<HEADLINE>
SOME JOBS REQUIRE A BIT MORE TASTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Carol Husfeld surveys the cart in front of her and
dips her spoon into a half-gallon tub of Peaches and Homemade
Vanilla ice cream. She nods her approval and then moves on to
sample a half-gallon of Homemade Vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Husfeld has what is perhaps the best job in the world _ she
spends her days tasting ice cream at Blue Bell Creameries in
Brenham, Texas. In the name of quality control, Husfeld is the
final check to assure that when a customer opens a carton of
chocolate ice cream, it's everything he is expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Folks such as Husfeld, who taste for a living, have golden
tongues. After years of experience, they know when the product
tastes good and when something is a bit off. Sometimes, Husfeld
said, production workers may have forgotten to add the peaches to
the Peaches and Homemade Vanilla or the nuts to the Buttered Pecan.
That careful attention to detail makes the difference between a
great product and a mediocre one.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes after the production line starts each day, Husfeld
tests the ice cream that rolls off the line. She samples everything
_ half-gallons, pints and novelties _ as well as all the raw
ingredients, such as fruit and nuts, and the syrups, such as
marshmallow and chocolate swirls for flavor, texture and color.
</P>
<P>
   Husfeld figures she eats about a half-gallon of ice cream each
day. Amazingly, after 10 years of professional eating, Husfeld is
thin. ``I used to weigh 50 pounds,'' she said modestly.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the plant, the safety director, marketing
director, assistant production manager and the controller sit in
cubicles and at the signal _ it's very scientific _ the four men
put their spoons into bowls of Honey Cinnamon Graham Ice Cream.
</P>
<P>
   The research department developed the new flavor the previous
day and the four men, who sit on one of many tasting panels at the
plant, gave it a whirl at their monthly tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Safety director Howard Zuch complained that the cinnamon flavor
was too strong and the whole effect was too sweet. Zuch, an avid
ice cream eater whose favorite flavor is coffee, said he loves
serving on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Valera, research and development director, said the
testers are trained to look for key factors such as consistency _
but other than that, she wants tasters who just love ice cream and
are brutally honest.
</P>
<P>
   There is a dark side to tasting for a living, experts say. When
something is bad, you have to taste more of it, said Teresa
Byrne-Dodge, publisher and editor of My Table magazine, a
bi-monthly guide to dining out in Houston. Byrne-Dodge requires her
reviewers to visit a restaurant three times if the review is
negative. If the review is a good one, the reviewer only goes
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting is a critical job in a company and it's common for the
chief executive to get in on the action _ especially if the food is
caviar and duckling.
</P>
<P>
   At Houston-based Continental Airlines, Chief Executive Officer
Gordon Bethune and President Greg Brenneman participate in the
tastings of the fine wines and the new dishes that are scheduled to
be served in business first on its international flights.
</P>
<P>
   For beer lovers, there probably isn't a sweeter sight than the
tasting room at the Anheuser-Busch Brewery in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the industrial plant is a richly paneled room with long
counters on three sides. Twice a day, the brewmaster and his
assistants gather to taste all the beer brewed that day along with
the waters that are used to rinse the bottles.
</P>
<P>
   One recent afternoon, about 75 glasses of beer were laid out
from end to end, and brewmaster Kirk Norris took a drink of every
third beer after swirling and sniffing it.
</P>
<P>
   Norris said he's looking for balance _ a full flavor that
shouldn't linger too long yet goes down easily. Swallowing is a key
part of the taste test, said Norris, who doesn't have the girth
most people would associate with a brewmaster.
</P>
<P>
   Tasters drink between one and two beers during a session. There
are about nine testers and they rotate so they don't have to taste
each day. It works out to about a six-pack a week, according to
Norris, who said he never tires of beer and often has one at home
with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Norris and his assistants have gone through extensive training
to pick out imperfections that are typically caught early in the
brewing cycle. When a slight problem is spotted _ a bit too sweet
or harsh _ it's blended with another tank.
</P>
<P>
   If the job sounds good, don't get a college degree in beer
drinking. Study chemistry, food production and engineering because
you'll need to fix the problems when they come up, Norris said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
