<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SMITH-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      MARGARET CHASE SMITH HONORED FOR MILITARY ROLES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Sarah Stebbins  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 12 -- America's most influential female and
military leaders, including first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, paid
tribute this week to the late Sen. Margaret Chase Smith for her
legendary efforts in promoting women's positions in the military.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton presented the first annual Margaret Chase Smith award
Thursday night to former Defense Secretary William Perry,
commemorating the 50th anniversary of the Women's Armed Services
Integration Act.
</P>
<P>
   This act, which Smith wrote and was signed into law by President
Truman in 1948, established permanent professional status for women
in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have always been willing to do our part for our
country,'' Clinton said at a ceremony at the Women in Military
Service for America Memorial in Arlington National Cemetery. On
Friday, military leaders held panel discussions at the memorial
spotlighting women leaders in military, aerospace and medical
research.
</P>
<P>
   The Margaret Chase Smith Leadership Award was created by the
women's memorial foundation to honor leaders who follow in the
footsteps of the legendary Maine senator.
</P>
<P>
   Perry was recognized for his life-time dedication to promoting
meaningful roles for women in America's military, ``not because it
was the right thing to do,'' said Mrs. Clinton, ``but because it
was the smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The words `leadership' and `Margaret Chase Smith' naturally go
together. ... Senator Smith bolstered American national interests
and the active participation of women in all facets of American
life,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Both Collins and Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, were scheduled to
speak at the event but were detained with a vote in the Senate and
unable to attend.
</P>
<P>
   A second, ``surprise'' award was given to Major General Jeanne
M. Holm, who spent 33 years in the Armed Forces, rising from
private to two-star general.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Chase Smith was elected to the U.S. House of
Representatives in 1940 and the Senate in 1948, where she held a
seat on the Senate Armed Services Committee, with oversight of the
military. She was the first woman in American history to be elected
to both Houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, Smith was appointed a Lt. Colonel in the U.S. Air Force
Reserve where she served until 1957.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 196,173 American women serving on active duty
in the armed forces, 8,400 of which are from Maine. Women make up
14 percent of the force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
