<SLUG> BC-KOHL-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOHL DISCOVERS HE IS MORE GERMAN THAN EUROPEAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: News Analysis) 
 
By BERNARD D. KAPLAN 
c.1998 Hearst Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has decided that being a
fervent supporter of European unity doesn't win many votes. So he
is pushing his credentials as a champion of his own country's
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl is trailing in the polls against Gerhard Schroeder, his
Social Democrat rival, in September's national elections. Opinion
surveys show that among his biggest handicaps is the perception
that he has given too much of his time to pushing European
integration and not enough to Germany's economic woes, including
record unemployment since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor's response has been to go on the attack against
the European Union's executive commission in Brussels, Belgium,
accusing it of highhandedness, and to denounce the idea of a
``centralized Europe'' in any form. He told his Christian
Democratic Union party congress last month that he would
``counterattack a new wave of bureaucracy by the European
institutions.``
</P>
<P>
   Kohl also began a campaign to slash Germany's contribution to
the European Union budget as ``excessive'' and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   At the next EU summit in July, he is expected to demand a large
cut in Germany's $11 billion contribution to the EU budget, the
largest of any of the 15 member nations. ``We want our money
back,'' Finance Minister Theo Waigel told a political meeting
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor's advisers reportedly regard the
budget-contribution issue as politically potent at a time when
average Germans are feeling the economic pinch more than they have
in years. A widespread popular view, as reflected in some German
newspapers, is that Germany is subsidizing other EU countries, even
those as wealthy as France and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl is suspected by some analysts of veering toward the more
nationalist stance of the Bavarian wing of his party, known as the
Christian Social Union, which has always been skeptical of moving
too fast toward European integration. Bavaria's vote is crucial if
he is to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he and French President Jacques Chirac signed a joint
declaration calling for the safeguarding of national interests
within the EU.
</P>
<P>
   All this is strange talk coming from the man that his own
compatriots have dubbed ``Herr Europe.'' During the 16 years that
he has headed the Bonn government, he gained a reputation as
probably the most ardent champion of a united Europe. As recently
as two years ago, he declared that only the continent's integration
could ``solve the question of war or peace'' in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   His critics accuse Kohl of sheer cynicism in suddenly turning
into an opponent of developments he previously espoused because
German voters have shown clear signs of tiring of him and wanting a
new face at the head of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kohl is wrong to count on a show of anti-Europeanism to win
him re-election,'' according to analyst Lutz Kreeger, who writes
for Berlin's Morganpost newspaper. ``His supposed change of heart
comes far too late to get the votes of the real anti-Europeans and
strikes most other Germans as blatant opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kohl's real problem is that much of the country finds him worn
out and lacking in new ideas while it regards his aides as
incompetent,'' Kreeger said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
