<HEADER>
A6742 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINGLE-CLUBS-ART-2TAK     06-12 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGLE-CLUBS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE SINGLE BOOMERS ARE STAYIN' ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl)  
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first time Hara Teicher ventured out to a
nightclub on Manhattan's Upper East Side, she met Jerry Steinberg.
No one wants to rush anything, but it appears to be love.
</P>
<P>
   That happy tale would not be so unusual, except for the ages of
the people involved. As romantic and social venues, nightclubs
these days are generally the province of 20-something hipsters
sporting tattoos and black miniskirts. But Ms. Teicher, a
therapist, is 43, while Dr. Steinberg, an internist from Israel, is
49.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-month-old club where they met, Decade, would never be
confused with Balthazar, Spy, Moomba or any of the other night
spots of the moment, where gatekeepers barely acknowledge a suit
with a comb-over or a skirt with, well, gray roots.
</P>
<P>
   With its elegant menu, wine cellar and late-'70s dance music
like ``Shame'' by Evelyn (Champagne) King and ``I Will Survive'' by
Gloria Gaynor pulsating from the sound system, Decade is geared to
baby boomers looking to meet the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``This relationship is a place I've been really looking to get
to for a long time,'' Ms. Teicher said. ``Before I heard about
Decade, I would never have gone to a club.''
</P>
<P>
   With growing ranks of people over 35 finding themselves single
in a social world not set up for them, a niche is arising for clubs
that cater to those with more years, more money and more
unapologetically discriminate taste.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that baby boomers _ the original inventors of the New
York singles scene back in the 1960s and '70s _ would seemingly
have outgrown meeting people at bars. Some, no doubt, have. But
plenty of others have been tempted back out again _ sometimes after
a divorce, sometimes after years of frustration with less
adventurous ways of meeting mates _ by nightclubs specially
designed to put them at ease.
</P>
<P>
   Decade is reminiscent of the Stork Club, where cocktails, dining
and dancing all came under one roof. Beneath a flattering amber
glow, patrons can enjoy a dinner of pan-seared salmon or braised
lamb shank in an upstairs dining room that overlooks the dance
floor. There is a private dining room in a 4,000-bottle wine
cellar, and a room with private humidors for regular customers, at
the top of the winding staircase.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been in a 20-something singles bar, you know that's
no place for a grown-up,'' said Pepper Schwartz, a professor of
sociology at the University of Washington in Seattle. ``Quite
honestly, you wouldn't want to compete in visual attractiveness
with people in their 20s and 30s, who are arguably at the height of
good looks and good bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, besides Decade, on First Avenue, in the shadow
of the Queensboro Bridge, the over-35 crowd is hanging out at the
popular Rhythm Revue Dance Party at the Roseland Ballroom in
midtown, a giant monthly high school reunion of sorts that plays
'50s, '60s and '70s music for some 2,000 enthusiasts, who remember
the words from the first time around. The racially diverse,
sold-out crowd likes to get its groove on until the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday, disk jockey Felix Hernandez _ spinning
songs like ``Mickey's Monkey'' by Smokey Robinson and the Miracles,
``Cold Sweat'' by James Brown, and ``Heatwave'' by Martha and the
Vandellas _ received raves from the crowd that was jolted back to
adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   On the dance floor, crunchy granola met bargain basement chic as
the partygoers danced the night away, including those who were
emulating the look of Barry White and Chaka Khan. Some people even
dug out their '60s radical clothes, including a man in a dashiki,
who spent most of the evening cruising the periphery of the dance
floor, giving off vibes that were too powerful for the women.
</P>
<P>
   Those who prefer a more staid setting can nurse a glass of
champagne at a growing number of revolving singles parties at
private homes and upscale restaurants like Tavern on the Green and
Maxine's, said Marion Smith, a New York City party planner, who has
been in business for more than 20 years. In New York magazine, ads
for baby boomer dating parties have doubled to about 30 in the last
five years, Nancy Fedder, vice president of the magazine's
classifieds, said.
</P>
<P>
   Women are more likely to attend these kinds of soirees than men,
which makes sense: women over 38 are more likely to be single than
men in New York City. In 1996, the latest year for which figures
are available from the U.S. Census Bureau, almost 59 percent of the
single baby boomers (born between 1946 and 1961) in the city were
women, and just 41 percent men. That's partly because the mortality
rate of men in this age group is higher than for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows why women in this age group would be nervous about
their chances of getting married,'' said Andrew Beveridge, a
sociology professor at Queens College. ``And some of the men who
are left are likely to be gay, especially in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Brody considered this phenomenon when she conceived
Decade. ``I designed this place with women in mind. I know what
it's like to be a single, divorced mother,'' said Ms. Brody, who
has since remarried. ``I want women who come here to feel
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Through its music, Decade allows boomers to recapture the heady,
free-love days of the '60s and '70s that evolved into the ``disco
inferno'' nights of the '80s before the AIDS scare _ which
essentially erased the singles scene. Studio 54 died. Dinner became
the social thing to do in the '80s. Then after the stock market
crash in 1987, which marked the beginning of a recession, people
started to stay home and rent videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Studio 54,'' Ms. Brody said. ``I'm typical of that
era. I have created that environment for people to come with their
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   While a sexual undercurrent permeates the air, the over-35
patrons who frequent Decade are certainly more cautious about
dating than they were in their youth.
</P>
<P>
   Take Alan Stone, for example, a smartly dressed 51-year-old
businessman, who has been divorced for seven years and has two
grown children. He should know better than to try to meet Mrs.
Right at a bar, but he says Decade is different. It draws people
who are interested in long-term relationships, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a Woodstock kid,'' he said. ``It was always bell-bottom
jeans and crazy shoes. I was down in the Village all spaced out.
But you grow up. You get more mature. You have your children. You
want a career. So, you tend to mellow out, not rush things.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Bell, 52, an investment banker and real estate
investor, who lives on the Upper East Side, is a regular at Decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decade has filled a void, created a niche for people 35 and
older on the Upper East Side,'' he said. ``By the time you reach
35, you are somewhat mature. Manners are somewhat expected. People
aren't necessarily shy about saying exactly what they're looking
for in a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Zarin, 51, a real estate investor and owner of Zarin
Fabrics in downtown Manhattan, who is separated, said supper clubs
like the Rainbow Room satisfy the refined tastes of some boomers,
but it plays big band, not disco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most clubs are like Life in the Village, which has a very
crowded dance floor,'' he said. ``They have VIP rooms for stars and
actresses, and you just sit back on a sofa and have drinks. At
Decade, you have food, plenty of people in my age bracket that now
have money to spend. This club is not dealing with kids who have no
money. You have the music of my generation in a nice atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Glynn, 43, a real estate broker from Staten Island, was at
Decade with three friends on a recent Saturday evening to celebrate
her sale of a $335,000 house on Todt Hill. She said the atmosphere
at Decade was female-friendly, meaning men who were looking for
dates were not sizing them up like morsels of meat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Glynn, who has been divorced for 12 years and has a
16-year-old daughter, said she planned to return to the club in the
hopes of meeting a mate. ``My friend met a man there six months
ago,'' she said. ``Now they're engaged. Why not come back? Where
else would I go?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
