<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6765 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-VIAGRA-$ADV14     06-12 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-VIAGRA-$ADV14-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WON'T BE YOUR STANDARD VIAGRA COLUMN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I take some pride in the fact that I seem to be the only
newspaper columnist between San Diego and Mattawamkeag, Maine, who
has not written what I would call my ``Viagra column.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't know, by the way, whether there IS a columnist in
Mattawamkeag, but I know columnist Margery Eliscu, who lives in
Poland, Maine, and I'm betting she's either been to or written
about Mattawamkeag. Besides, I didn't say ``in'' Mattawamkeag. I
said ``between'' San Diego and there. Sheesh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't know whether Marge has written a Viagra column, but
I expect to see her this week in San Diego, and if you insist on
knowing, I'll ask her. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I was thinking about a Viagra column and Marge the other day
(they have no connection, so let it go) after I got my latest
newsletter from the National Society of Newspaper Columnists. I
read a line there from our group's treasurer, Roberta de Boer of
Toledo, who owes me money but promises to pay, so leave her alone,
too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberta said no columnists should be allowed to attend our
upcoming 1998 convention ``until they first send their Viagra
column.'' Her assumption, of course, is that all columnists have
written a Viagra column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drug company Pfizer introduced its drug to combat male
impotency on tax-filing deadline day, April 15. (Speaking of that
inter-uh-mingling of events, what was up with that?) Since then
some story or comment about Viagra has been in most newspapers
almost every day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, the story has everything _ sex, money and happiness
(pronounced with an emphasis on the second syllable). You get a
story like that and columnists will flock to it like flies to the
Clinton administration. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But not me. It seems to me there are a few subjects on which I'm
not required to have an opinion. A good example: Not only have I
not done a Viagra column, but I have said nothing about Jerry
Seinfeld's final show, either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, my reasons for avoiding both subjects were
similar. Neither is of any interest to me. I have never seen
Seinfeld's show and have neither personal nor professional interest
in male impotency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you end up writing about things you don't care about, readers
soon detect your emotional flatness and abandon you in favor of
something more exciting, like the obituaries or the list of grains
and soybeans prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You have to be passionate about your topics. That's why, in the
past year or so, I have written about Alexander von Humboldt, the
National Assessment Governing Board, Wake Island, Fritz Zwicky,
cranberry-vodka punch, house-sized ice comets, C-SPAN, Helen Herron
Taft, the ``Vermont Weather Calendar,'' the Cornish-Windsor Covered
Bridge, WIN buttons and Antiphanes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because I think columnists have to care _ and care deeply _ I
have just this year tackled these hot-button subjects: Miguel de
Cervantes, Calvin Coolidge, the Manuscript Division of the Library
of Congress, Canadian wheat, Vesto Slipher, Aesop and National Car
Care Month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clearly these engaging topics, which actually matter to most of
our lives, are more worthy of my (and your) limited time and space
than Jerry Seinfeld and Viagra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I do not, by the way, wish to imply anything about Seinfeld by
tossing him into the same sentence with Viagra. I don't know Jerry
Seinfeld. I already have told you I've never watched his
now-defunct show. And whether he takes Viagra is of even less
interest to me than the fact that Pfizer chose the name Viagra to
suggest virility and vigor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And even that's a fact about which I simply don't care. Which is
why I'm not going to write a Viagra column. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, unless I need one to get into the columnists' convention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
