A6769 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-DAD-$ADV15-KA     06-12 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-DAD-$ADV15-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S DAY GREW BECAUSE OF ONE SMART GUY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1997 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Father's Day approaches each year, I become grateful that my
children may remember me but a little annoyed that children
everywhere will feel a sense of oppressive, culturally contrived
obligation about all of this because of one Sonora Smart Dodd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And yet how could anyone harbor ill feelings toward someone with
so sonorous a name as Sonora Smart Dodd? It seems to fill the air
with clear, lilting music. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonora, it turns out, was sitting in church on Mother's Day of
1909 in Spokane, Wash., listening to a sermon in praise of
motherhood. (Isn't it reassuring to learn that even back then many
preachers apparently were courageous enough to risk praising
motherhood on Mother's Day?) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonora, that day, could not have known that later that same year
my own father would be born, but she did know that her father, one
Henry J. Smart, was a pretty good guy, having reared his daughter
by himself after Sonora's mother suffered an untimely demise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonora's gratefulness led her to suggest that there should be a
day to honor fathers as well as mothers. (See? You probably thought
a man dreamed up Father's Day _ perhaps even a man in need of some
new ties.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonora obviously knew how to get things done. Indeed, the very
next year the mayor of Spokane proclaimed June 19 Father's Day.
Before long the idea spread and in 1924 President Calvin Coolidge
declared his support of the concept. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (By the way, it recently occurred to me what Silent Cal Coolidge
looks like in most of his photos. Do you know what a screen saver
on a computer is? It's a program that makes your screen go
essentially blank when it's left unattended. The computer is on,
but, aside from some randomly blinking lights, it looks like no one
is home. Coolidge looked as if he had a screen saver running on his
face most of the time. Kind of like Al Gore today.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it took until 1972 for Congress _ usually quick to rush
into such easy pickings _ to pass a law recognizing the third
Sunday in June as a day to honor Dad. By then, as surely you know,
Richard Nixon was president. There were days when the shadowy Nixon
could have used a screen saver running on his foreboding face. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am, if you insist on knowing, both a father and a step-father.
(One difference between them is that to achieve the former office
one usually wears fewer clothes.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And as I've already indicated, I had a father, too. He lived 82
years, most of it in Illinois, without ever seeing the Chicago Cubs
win a World Series. In turn, I have lived 53 years without seeing
that happen. What a life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Dad was alive, I recall feeling a forced sense of duty
whenever Father's Day rolled around. I knew I would be expected to
come up with some sort of clever gift and card, and each year it
seemed as if the list of things he would either need or appreciate
got smaller and smaller. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure my children feel the same way now, though I do my best
to leave hints for them about the denomination of currency I would
find most useful. This helpfulness on my part, I figure, saves them
from wasting time searching for just the right screen saver or
something for me. Well, not for me but for my computer. My stare is
blank enough without adding new software. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When my children were younger, I was ambivalent about receiving
Father's Day gifts from them because I knew that most of the money
they spent could be traced back to my pocket. But I've recovered
from that. Besides, my collection doesn't yet include the Sonora
Smart Dodd Beanie Baby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
