A6779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPENSIVE-SOAPS-ART-$     06-12 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPENSIVE-SOAPS-ART-$ADV14-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A SOAP SNOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Advance for Sunday, June 14) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)
(ja) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After putting the finishing touches on a recent
makeover of my bathroom, I stepped back and marveled at the
spanking white tiles, sparkling fixtures and plush, cream-colored
towels. Suddenly, the sight of a bar of pink Dove in my new
porcelain soap dish jarred me. The supermarket staple was
dreadfully out of place in my new sanctum of personal hygiene.
</P>
<P>
   I rushed to L'Occitane on Madison Avenue at 80th Street, a
luxury outpost of a venerable French soap maker, whose
manufacturing processes originate in Provence. Browsing among 15
soaps in 60 scents, I picked Linden Wood, a blond, oval-shaped bar
that looked like a smooth beach stone. Its subtle, woodsy fragrance
was seductive. It hardly mattered that it cost $7, more than twice
the price of a Dove twin-pack.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time I had splurged on luxury soap for myself,
but it would not be the last. At the cash register, announcing my
embarrassment at paying so much _ money that would literally go
down the drain _ Terris Krueger, the store manager, told me,
``You'll get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to use Dial,'' he said. ``But three years ago when I
worked at the bed and bath shop at Takashimaya, I got some samples
from the vendors. I was amazed how my skin felt and smelled. I'm a
soap snob now. I guarantee you'll become one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He turned out to be right. Ever since, I have been a convert to
luxury soaps _ to linden tree extract and African shea butter, to
triple-milling and palm oil, all the persnickety hallmarks of
premium soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of evaluation processes as to what makes
soap appeal to a soap snob,'' said Robert Cantor, a clothing
importer who is a longtime devotee of designer suds. His obsession
dates from the 1970s, when he discovered Erno Lazlo soap, and
continues today with Floris, Pears and Issey Miyake, rotating the
bars each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask myself, Does the soap feel good in my hand?'' Cantor
said. ``Does it feel good rolling in a washcloth or on my skin?
Does my skin feel fresh afterward, or does the soap cling to my
skin? You also have to know the water in the area you live in,
because if it's soft, you need less soap. If it's hard, you need a
lot of soap to generate suds. You may feel you need a stronger soap
in the winter, and in the spring, you need something light and
floral.''
</P>
<P>
   Jiminy, so many subtleties for those who dedicate themselves to
soap connoisseurship. But Cantor is hardly alone. As the
proliferation of luxury bath boutiques indicates, soap snobbery is
on the rise. The L'Occitane chain, originally from Europe, landed
in Manhattan two years ago, has added two other New York locations
and plans to open shops this summer in New Jersey, Connecticut and
Washington, D.C. Portico Bed and Bath opened its first store in
SoHo in 1992, selling an egg-size soap for $2.50 and a ``toning''
soap for $21 _ and has since expanded to nine stores in the New
York region.
</P>
<P>
   Soap snobbery has even trickled down to the mass market. Since
1990, the Bath and Body Works chain, which is owned by Intimate
Brands, the same company that controls Victoria's Secret, has grown
to 900 stores, many in malls. Its fruit-scented liquid and bar
soaps, from $2.50 to $8.50, are booming, accounting for $210
million in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even Wal-Mart is in a lather over fancy soaps. Although it
sounds like an oxymoron, the discount chain has introduced a
``luxury'' bath line, the Regatta Clothing Company Bath and Body
Collection, which includes scented soaps enriched with natural
luffa extracts that sell for $1.50 each. (Luxury is clearly
relative _ $1.50 qualifies because Wal-Mart sells Ivory three-packs
for 97 cents.)
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At Portico stores there are body washes, body balsams, body
shampoos, bath salts, bath oils and basic bath bars. There are also
exfoliating, energizing and stress-reducing soaps. Some are made
with tea, milk, honey or oatmeal, all ingredients for a healthy
breakfast. Other soaps are perfumed with garden flowers, ocean
waters or alpine forests. Once the soap foams, releasing its
fragrance, the cleanser acts like a magic carpet, transporting you
mentally to the natural wonder of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Recreating natural wonders is often a soap maker's inspiration.
``I had a background in geology, and one day I was in the shower
and there were soap remains that looked like little pebbles,'' said
Tod Pink of Oneonta, N.Y., recalling the moment when he conceived
of Soaprocks. They are soaps that resemble the faceted shapes and
colors of quartz crystals, minerals and semiprecious stones.
Fellismo sells them for $13.50 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   These days, soaps that emphasize ``all natural'' ingredients _
meaning they are not based on traditional tallow, or animal fat _
often command premium prices, thanks to the craze for healthy
living and the corollary that non-animal products are somehow
better suited to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better soaps are 100 percent vegetable,'' Krueger, the
L'Occitane manager, maintained, adding that soaps based on olive or
palm oils are less dehydrating.
</P>
<P>
   L'Occitane also uses the Marseilles process of triple-milling, a
traditional technique whereby the soap is pressed three times to
eliminate any air. The company says this produces a harder bar than
more commercial varieties, one that lathers better, lasts longer
and is more moisturizing.
</P>
<P>
   Not all experts in saponification _ the science of soap making _
agree. ``A Marseilles bar is like any regular soap, but it has
higher moisture and glycerin and ingredients that improve the
feeling of the soap on the skin,'' said Armando San Juan, director
of technology at Colgate-Palmolive, the maker of Palmolive and
Irish Spring soaps. ``A lot of special ingredients are put in for
marketing purposes,'' he added. ``But it's really a regular
palm-coconut oil soap with glycerin, preservatives and little
goodies. The way it is described makes it seem special. And they're
able to sell it at a higher price.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, consumers seem to know no bounds in their taste for
luxuries, especially if the luxuries are low-key ones like fancy
soap. In March, when Bergdorf Goodman introduced sandalwood soaps
by Jo Malone of London at $40 for three bars, it nearly sold out in
two weeks. And Takashimaya regularly sells out a $35 Vellutina, or
velvet soap, from Florence.
</P>
<P>
   For the truly indulgent, those who cannot get enough of
specialty soaps, there is L'Occitane's Eco Museum of Soaps in Volx,
a village in Provence. There, cleanser zealots can witness the
miracle of soap making and ogle antique bars displayed like
reliquary objects. The pilgrimage, which approximately 80,000 have
made since 1992, takes a bubbling desire to be immersed in the
realm of rarefied suds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
