<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 216.
WASHINGTON, June 12 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments this week.
A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N'' means the
member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the member did not
vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted ``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: DRUG
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Tuesday, 52-46, to approve an amendment to the
tobacco settlement bill. The measure would set aside $3 billion per
year to boost the nation's drug interdiction efforts and encourage
the states' schools and businesses to crack down on drug users.
Supporters said the bill should do more than just go after
tobacco-related problems. Opponents said the amendment might help
drug fighting efforts but hurt efforts to stop teen smoking, the
``real gateway'' to drugs. A ``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
(Vote no. 151)
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) ?
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The House on Friday passed, 216-204, a 1999 budget plan that
would cut domestic spending and provide $101 billion in tax relief
over five years for married couples. Supporters said the bill would
provide needed tax relief. Opponents said that it violated last
year's balanced budget agreement and that it would cut funding for
education, the environment and health care. A ``yes'' vote favors
the bill. (Vote no. 210)
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Tuesday, 392-22 to implement legislation geared
toward forcing Russia to stop exporting missile technology to Iran.
The legislation will impose sanctions on Russian companies that
have a history of helping Iran develop missiles. Both the House and
Senate passed the bill and President Clinton is expected to veto
it. Supporters said the legislation challenges the Russians to stop
trading with rogue countries. Opponents said sanctions could
backfire by discouraging Russia's cooperation. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill. (Roll no. 211)
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: BANKRUPT
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Wednesday, 306-118, to reform the nation's
bankruptcy laws. The measure would make it harder for debtors to
escape payment of debts through declaring bankruptcy. Supporters
say that the bill will hold debtors accountable for paying as much
of their debt as possible. Opponents say that the bill puts too
many restrictions on bankruptcy filers. A ``yes'' vote favors the
bill. (Roll no. 225)
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
