A6782 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV14-     06-12 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING: A SUMMER VINE YIELDS A SWEET REWARD IN FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (bl)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I lived in an apartment with a balcony, friends used to
admire the vine I had growing there each summer in an old apple
crate. Its shiny leaves cascaded over the balcony's edge, and it
always looked fresh, healthy and a little bit tropical.
</P>
<P>
   What I liked best about that vine was that after the first frost
had blackened its foliage, I would dump it out of the crate and
harvest a nice crop of sweet potatoes from its roots.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potato vines are pretty. They even make decorative
houseplants, which are easily grown by putting a whole sweet potato
into a vase half-filled with water, so that the top of the potato
is high and dry. It will sprout within a couple of days. Eventually
the potato will rot, at which point you discard the plant and start
a new one.
</P>
<P>
   But the vines are best in the garden, because that is where they
will produce an abundance of sweet potatoes, erroneously thought of
by some people as yams.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes are Ipomoea batatas, a relative of the morning
glory. Yams are in the genus Dioscorea and are an important food
source in the tropics but are seldom grown in the United States.
The confusion is compounded by the fact that canned sweet potatoes
are usually labeled ``yams.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two main types of sweet potatoes. The most commonly
available type has moist, orange flesh; the other has drier, mealy
flesh that is usually off-white or yellowish.
</P>
<P>
   Where I live, in south-central Pennsylvania, most local
gardeners prefer the dry, white sweet potato, which they call sweet
potato. The orange one they call yam. Both, however, are sweet
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes are generally thought of as a Southern vegetable.
About 60 percent of the commercial crop comes from North Carolina
and Louisiana. But they can be grown successfully in the North,
provided that the growing season is at least 120 days long.
</P>
<P>
   Most modern varieties mature in just 90 days, but sweet potatoes
do not grow well in the cool soil of early spring, even if frost
danger is past. Although my last average frost date is May 10, I
don't plant sweet potatoes until late May, sometimes as late as
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are grown from slips, which are rooted sprouts from a
sweet potato. Slips are available by mail order or in garden
centers, or you can produce your own by burying a sweet potato in a
pot of soil and keeping it in a warm spot. Each potato will produce
from eight to 12 rooted sprouts in about three weeks. When they are
roughly 6 inches tall, detach them carefully from the surface of
the mother potato's skin, keeping as many roots attached as
possible. If you like, that mother potato can then produce another
crop of slips.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes won't appreciate your finest garden soil, so
don't waste it on them. Poor, dry, slightly acidic soil suits them
fine, and I never add fertilizer to the sweet potato bed. If grown
in fertile loam, the potatoes may develop skin lesions similar to
the scab disease that afflicts white potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Raised beds are good for sweet potatoes, because the mounded
soil will warm up faster in the spring and drain quickly after a
heavy rain. If possible, use black plastic mulch on the sweet
potato bed. Not only will this help warm the soil, but it will also
prevent the vines from sending down additional roots as they sprawl
across the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Letting the vines root along their length will greatly reduce
the harvest. If you don't use plastic, you will need to lift the
vines off the ground every week or so to keep them from rooting.
</P>
<P>
   Plant the slips from 12 to 18 inches apart, and if you're
growing a standard variety, allow at least three feet for the vines
to sprawl. (I like the red-skinned standard varieties Georgia Jet,
which produces large, round potatoes, and Beauregard, which
produces more elongated potatoes.) If space is at a premium, grow a
bush variety like Vineless Porto Rico or Vardaman, which send out
vines only 18 inches long, about half the length of a standard
vine.
</P>
<P>
   All these varieties are orange-fleshed. Finding slips of
white-fleshed sweet potatoes is difficult. The best course might be
to buy a white sweet potato at a specialty store or farmers' market
and to grow your own slips.
</P>
<P>
   If planted in plastic mulch, sweet potatoes require virtually no
further attention until harvest time. When the first frost has
nipped the foliage (or before, if you just can't wait to sample the
crop), cut off the vines and dig up the potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   This is best done cautiously, with a garden fork, starting a
foot or more away from the main stem. If you accidentally spear a
potato, put it on the dinner menu within a few days. It will not
keep for long.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet potatoes need to be cured for long storage. Brush off
loose soil, but don't wash the potatoes. Spread them out in a warm,
dry area for at least a couple of weeks. A curing temperature of 80
to 85 degrees is ideal, which for many gardeners is right next to
the furnace.
</P>
<P>
   Once cured, sweet potatoes will keep for months in a cool, dry
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Save two or three of the best potatoes to provide slips for next
year's garden. If your garden can't hold that many sweet potato
plants, there's always the option of lining up apple crates on the
balcony or patio. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
