<SLUG> BC-WOMEN'S-SUMMER-HATS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMS ARE DOWN, SO HATS ARE UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As hemlines flutter below the knee this spring, the
stock market may not be falling with them, despite Wall Street
lore, but another leading indicator associated with plunging
hemlines has taken effect: the return of hats.
</P>
<P>
   Hat departments of big stores and small boutiques are full of
customers, since nothing complements the silhouette of a flowing
calf-length skirt or dress like a charming chapeau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time skirts get longer, hats go crazy,'' said Judy
Collinson, the general merchandise manager for women's
ready-to-wear and accessories at Barneys New York. ``It really
works. Long skirts make for a really good hat season.''
</P>
<P>
   At Barneys, Andrew Wilke's $175 wide-brimmed ivory-colored sun
hats, reminiscent of English gardening hats, are perfect for
frizzy-hair days. The crowns are cool linen fabrics in pastel
shades, including blue and gray, reminiscent of men's oxford
shirts.
</P>
<P>
   For $325, Nafi di Luca's flights of fancy include an iridescent
organza-covered pink straw sun hat adorned with straw strips _ a
kind of upscale scarecrow look, more suited to the Connecticut
countryside than Iowa cornfields.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Treacy, one of the most original modern milliners, offers
fashionable hats that are not overtly fussy at Bergdorf Goodman.
His Mad Hatter style in fuchsia-colored straw has a brim covered
with wisps of straw woven into a scallop shell pattern. It is $359.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Bergdorf's are Lola's imaginative and whimsical
concoctions, including a pagoda-style hat in natural straw dotted
with black raffia daisies, for $265. ``It's inspired by '50s
chinoiserie with Bermuda souvenir decoration,'' said the designer,
who uses only her first name. ``That's a great beach look.''
</P>
<P>
   British milliner Patricia Underwood created the Isabella this
season, a picture hat with a wide, flexible brim that can be turned
up or down. It is $415 at Bergdorf's. Made of tightly woven straw
with a slight sheen, the hat comes in colors to match eye shadows
like violet, lilac and pistachio. The brim is broad enough to
protect against the sun and adds a romantic touch to a summer
frock.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hat must set off your silhouette,'' Ms. Underwood said,
giving tips on how to choose one. ``The whole thing has to work in
terms of proportion. It helps if you are wearing the outfit you
will be wearing with the hat, or you should have a vision of how it
will look in total. You put a lot of thought into the height of
your heel and cut of the shoe. The hat has to marry with that. The
color of the hat should be flattering to the eyes. The other thing
that is important is the neckline. If you show more neck, you can
wear more brim.''
</P>
<P>
   To look as if you've just stepped out of an Impressionist
painting, there are classic boaters trimmed in colored grosgrain
bands and bows ranging from $300 to $375 at Tracey Tooker,
Lexington Avenue and 82nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   And if the South Pacific is more your style than the Seine, the
Hat Shop, at 120 Thompson Street (Prince Street), has black or
natural hats by Sheenan Huxham inspired by the roofs of beach huts
in the tropics. Shaped like Dior's classic upside-down dish hat,
they are edged with raffia fringe and cost $220. All you need is a
pair of Capri pants to complete the castaway look.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
