<SLUG> BC-DEAD-MULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY LITERATURE HAS ITS SIGN, OR DEAD MULE, IN THE SOUTH'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They die from asphyxiation, rabies, drowning and falling off
cliffs. They are hit by trains, worked to death, hanged, stabbed,
shot and, in one Cormac McCarthy novel, decapitated by an irate
opera singer.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the fate of the mules of the South as recounted in a
minor classic of mock scholarship entitled ``Equine Gothic: The
Dead Mule as Generic Signifier in Southern Literature in the 20th
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   It asked a simple question, ``What makes Southern literature
Southern?'' and came up with a simpler answer. You can tell it's
Southern if it has a dead mule in it.
</P>
<P>
   The paper, written by Jerry Leath Mills, a retired Renaissance
scholar at the University of North Carolina, and published a year
ago in The Southern Literary Journal, is a parody of both academic
literature and obsessive scholarship. But beyond its own question
and answer, it presented an intriguing thought for reflection: If
the dead mule is the signifier for Southern literature, what is the
element that makes French literature French or Irish literature
Irish or film noir noir?
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who began collecting dead mule references when he was a
graduate student at Harvard in 1964, unearthed more than 200
examples of Equus caballus x asinus (defunctus), as he refers to
them, in Southern literature. His citations include William
Faulkner, Richard Wright, Erskine Caldwell, Truman Capote, Thomas
Wolfe and Zora Neale Hurston _ including Doris Betts' seminal ``The
Dead Mule'' _ to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   They are all arranged ``coroner-wise'' by cause of death, and
McCarthy, who killed off 59 specific mules in ``Blood Meridien''
alone, emerges as the king of Southern letters, mulewise at least,
even though he's best known for his novels about West Texas and the
border.
</P>
<P>
   The search for other signifiers in a completely unscientific
survey of professors and literary types wasn't quite so simple,
often descending to snippy lectures on what constitutes a genre (a
big topic in its own right) and the depravity of cultural
oversimplification. But since the generic signifier for academic
literature is inscrutable terms like ``generic signifier,'' maybe
that's not surprising. Still, more than a few worthwhile
contributions turned up.
</P>
<P>
   Sanford Pinsker, an English professor and expert in Jewish
American literature at Franklin and Marshall College had a
similarly pithy signifier for modern Jewish novels _ ``Portnoy's
Complaint'' being the ultimate example _ with their persistent
concern about intermarriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signifier isn't a dead mule,'' he said. ``It's a live,
blond shiksa.'' (For those unfamiliar with the technical term
``shiksa,'' it describes a non-Jewish woman.)
</P>
<P>
   Jack O'Connell, a novelist who edits the alumni magazine and
teaches expository writing at the College of the Holy Cross in
Worcester, Mass., is a serial signifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It it's got a sweating amnesiac in a predatory city, it's film
noir,'' he said. ``If it's got adultery with a chamber maid in a
haze of Gitanes smoke, it's French lit, and if it's got mother
love, xenophobic ballads and cirrhosis, it's Irish lit.''
</P>
<P>
   Most signifiers _ even the dead mule _ are open to debate. But
some cases are pretty strong. Sam Coale, an English professor at
Wheaton College in Norton, Mass., and a Hawthorne scholar, said the
presence of a minister in heat was essential for a New England
novel. Lisa Hoagland, an English professor at the University of
Cincinnati, said you could not have popular feminist fiction in the
1970s without a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
