A6826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIXTIES-REVISITED-900     06-12 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIXTIES-REVISITED-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYTHS OF THE SIXTIES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the wallet-size version of the sixties:
</P>
<P>
   Before, there were the fifties, a placid decade of consensus,
when Americans watched ``Father Knows Best,'' pursued the same
grassy suburban dreams and shared the same values.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was a volcanic rupture, a cultural big bang that
severed the era from the past. Student rebels, civil rights
marchers and antiwar protesters challenged the authority of the
family, the police, the military, the government and the
university. The New Left eventually fell apart, but set the stage
for a rights revolution that extended to women and homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Neither liberals nor conservatives dispute the basic
before-and-after storyline. Both concur it blasted away the
existing order and led to undreamed-of personal license. What they
can't agree on is whether this represented a fulfillment of
American values or their betrayal, a disaster or a deliverance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, historians are beginning to veer clear of the
familiar good-sixties, bad-sixties debate as if it were a
bumper-to-bumper feud over a single parking spot. Instead, they are
challenging the traditional before-and-after narrative, arguing
that the sixties do not represent as cataclysmic a break as
portrayed or as exceptional a decade as the proliferation of
college courses on the period would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Pivotal developments like the civil rights movement, urban
decline and consumerism began years earlier, they say. Meanwhile,
other crucial developments _ the religious revival, for instance,
or the change in immigration patterns _ have unappreciated links to
the sixties. Scholars are finally exploring just how much things
changed and how much they stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's my livelihood, I make an argument against
sixties exceptionalism,'' says Thomas Sugrue, who has taught a
course on the sixties for seven years at the University of
Pennsylvania. ``It was a moment when many of the conflicts burst
into the surface, but we misread other decades if we focus on the
sixties as this moment of rupture or apocalypse.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, much did change in the sixties : Hair was longer, sex
was freer, protests were larger, soldiers were dying in Vietnam.
Yet both left- and right-wing partisans have a motive to exaggerate
the degree of radical change _ either to score ideological points
or to justify or atone for their pasts. Bickering over the culture
wars has in general helped drown out interpretations that emphasize
links with the previous decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has his or her own sixties, and it means a lot to
them,'' says Allen Matusow, author of ``The Unraveling of America:
A History of Liberalism in the Sixties.'' ``The reason the sixties
still evoke such vehement reactions is because we're still fighting
over what kind of a country and what kind of a culture we're going
to have. But do people have a full understanding of what
happened?''
</P>
<P>
   Sugrue has probably gone the furthest in trying to replace the
before-and-after narrative with the-same-only-more-so. ``I believe
that in my lifetime there will no longer be courses on the
sixties,'' he said. ``We'll teach the whole postwar period as a
whole.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he points to the series of race riots that
convulsed cities across America in the sixties, arguing that the
ruinous decline of booming industrial cities was the product not of
sixties racial violence, white flight and backlash, as some have
argued, but rather of housing patterns, job discrimination and the
deindustrialization that occurred in the forties and fifties.
</P>
<P>
   The New Deal created a ``newfound sense of entitlement'' for all
Americans, while wartime military service lodged the expectation of
equal treatment in the minds of African-Americans, he writes in
``The Origins of the Urban Crisis: Race and Inequality in Postwar
Detroit,'' (Princeton, 1998). Yet during the late forties and
fifties, discrimination kept blacks in the lowest paying jobs and
the worst neighborhoods. Meanwhile, hundreds of thousands of
entry-level manufacturing jobs disappeared in the Midwest and
Northeast. (In 1957, one in five black Americans was unemployed.)
Detroit may not have burned until 1967, but Sugrue points out that
a decade earlier, unemployed blacks warned of ``widespread riots''
if confronted with another depression.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Tischler, who edited the series ``Perspectives on the
Sixties,'' wouldn't go quite as far as Sugrue. Still, she notes,
``I try not to say that the sixties are so different from any other
time. There are many periods of dramatic political and social
change. Is it more important than the period 1935 to 1945? I'm not
sure I can make that case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tischler, who has taught courses on the sixties at both
Barnard College and Columbia University, starts her students off
with the notion that President John F. Kennedy continued the Cold
War policies of the Eisenhower administration. If the United States
was going to strut the superiority of capitalist democracies over
Communist regimes around the world, then it was going to have to
prove it at home. ``That's why civil rights could become an
important issue in terms of the Cold War,'' she said: it was used
as part of ``the arsenal'' against Communism, as was the war on
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would really focus on continuity, particularly in the period
up to about 1968,'' she says. ``There was tremendous faith in the
ability of people to change their own system.'' Peaceful protesters
were drawing on traditions of American thought as old as the
Revolution. They ``took Locke and Jefferson very seriously,'' she
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
