<P>
   OHIO -- KYOTO. A new report, sponsored by the American Petroleum
Institute, says Ohio will lose more than 100,000 jobs if the U.S.
ratifies the Kyoto treaty on global warming. The White House, Ohio
EPA and environmental groups dispute those findings with their own
studies. Ohio ranks third in production of greenhouse gases after
California and Texas, and will face tougher emissions regulations
if the treaty is ratified. This story looks into that debate.
Barton and Herard
</P>
<P>
   -- DISCLOSURE. Financial Disclosure reports for members of
Congress were released Friday. Will write up summaries for OXLEY
(including REGULA), HOBSON, BOEHNER (including PORTMAN and
STRICKLAND), NEY (including KASICH) and DEWINE. Sen. John Glenn's
report is not yet in. Eckstein/Egbert
</P>
<P>
   -- NEWARK. (For Monday.) Looking into the revitalization of a
city ... what federal resources are available? what have other
cities done? Eckstein.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA -- WIRED. At least one school district -- Northern
Cambria -- stands to gain an 80 percent discount on Internet rates
if the Federal Communications Commission approves a $2 billion plan
to help hook up classrooms to the Web. Kane
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN ISLANDS -- GREEN. While many members of Congress have
investment holdings worth far more than their salaries, V.I.
Delegate Donna Christian-Green -- for the most part -- is living on
what she earns as a lawmaker. Williams
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
