<SLUG> BC-RADIO-QUIZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD QUESTION': YOU'RE ON THE AIR, SMARTY-PANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Wis., Mass., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By ANDREA HIGBIE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are not many places where you can win a gift
set of Torah cards or a teeth cleaning just for knowing a few
things about Benjamin Franklin. ``Good Question,'' a new call-in
radio quiz program on historical figures, is just such a place.
</P>
<P>
   Created by WMCA (570 AM) and broadcast from 8 to 9 on Saturday
nights, the program is one of the few listener-call-in game shows
in New York City. On ``Good Question,'' the 37-year-old creator,
producer and writer Philip Suraci, under the name Cuthbert Powell,
announces biographical information about the figure of the week,
which sets up but usually has little to do with the questions that
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Was Benjamin Franklin's father a butcher, a baker or a
candlestick maker? Sura, a teacher from Brooklyn's Crown Heights,
wins a camera for her answer: candlestick maker.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions are a little off the subject, which opens the way
for specialists on other topics. What is the meaning of the name
Philip (of Macedon), father of Alexander the Great? ``Lover of
birds?'' ventures Yhoeved, a researcher from Manhattan. ``Word
up!'' says host Ritch Duncan, 25, a stand-up comic who has
performed his routine about having parents who pride themselves on
being liberals (``They're disappointed that I'm not gay,'' he says)
at Gotham, Rebar and the Monkey's Paw in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher hangs up happy, with a gift set of Torah cards
for her efforts. Other prizes, all from sponsors, include cameras,
film tickets, pizza, massages and those teeth cleanings.
</P>
<P>
   On another evening, Ruchel from the Kensington section of
Brooklyn is asked which car Leonardo da Vinci would buy if he were
in the market for an Italian model: Fiat, Volvo or Linda
Evangelista. She picks No. 3. Sorry, Ruchel. The answer is Fiat.
But Leo, a retired archivist from Manhattan, scores when he is
asked whether Walt Whitman served as a nurse during the Civil War.
(He did.) ``Torah cards!'' Leo shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Goldie, a 10-year-old from Crown Heights, is asked by Duncan if
she has read any poems by Whitman. ``No,'' she confesses. He
reassures her, ``I think you're going to do well.'' (But she
doesn't: Whitman was an editor for The Daily Eagle in Brooklyn, not
The Brooklyn Herald or The Alaminer Journal.)
</P>
<P>
   By turns educational and cheesy, ``Good Question'' is introduced
each week as ``the answer to all your problems'' as well as ``one
day America's most-listened-to talk show.''
</P>
<P>
   While audience figures for ``Good Question,'' which began in
mid-December, are not yet available, WMCA _ former home of the Good
Guys Top 40 team of the 1960s _ is heard by 21,100 people from 7
p.m. to midnight on Saturdays, according to Arbitron, the radio
ratings service.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers can also listen to WNYC (820 AM) to hear ``Whad' Ya
Know?,'' a quiz, comedy and interview show produced in Madison,
Wis., and broadcast on Saturday afternoons from 1 to 3 and replayed
at 2 a.m., and ``Says You!,'' a wordplay game show based in Boston
that is broadcast on Saturday nights from 7 to 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Question'' has recently been picked up by WAXY (790 AM),
a station in Miami that reaches the Caribbean. A Web site
(www.netreaction.com/goodquestion) has been set up with news on the
program: George Washington will be the topic next Saturday. The
show's phone number is (201) 460-WMCA; it is broadcast from
Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   WMCA is owned by Salem Communications of Camarillo, Calif., a
Christian broadcasting company; Talkline Communications Network,
based in New York, buys 10 hours of programming on Saturday nights
for Jewish-oriented shows. Suraci presented ``Good Question'' to
Talkline, which wanted a secular program to offer after Shabbat,
which is from sundown Friday to nightfall Saturday, when many
observant Jews do not drive or turn on electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian programs on WMCA include ``Focus on the Family
With James Dobson'' (weekdays at 7:30 a.m. and 4:30 p.m.) and ``The
Bible Answer Man'' (weekdays at 6 p.m.); the Jewish programs
include ``The Top 10 Jewish Music Countdown'' (Sundays at 4 a.m.)
and ``Talkline With Zev Brenner'' (Saturdays at 11:30 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   ``So read up,'' Duncan tells his listeners about the program on
Napoleon. ``It's always a short show when you talk about
Napoleon.'' Janet from Manhattan, who with her Midwestern accent is
among the few callers clearly not a native of New York City or
Eastern Europe, proves to be a comedian herself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Napoleon owed his leadership capabilities to his
mother, his father or Morey Amsterdam, Janet goes for Mom. ``Do I
win the Beatles tickets?'' she asks breathlessly. ``They're playing
at Shea! I read about it in The World-Telegram.'' Janet settles for
a massage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
