<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVE-DEMOCRATS-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS BANK ON CONSERVATIVES TO RETAKE HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 14) 
 
By DAN FREEDMAN 
c.1998 Hearst Newspapers 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pat Casey, Ken Lucas and Loy Sneary, who are
running for Congress this year, are all conservatives on certain
issues, including abortion and gun control. And they are all
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   They and at least six others represent a key element of
Democratic Party strategy for taking the House of Representatives
back from the Republicans. They are the only hope the party has of
winning in many rural districts in states such as Alabama, Idaho,
Kentucky, Pennsylvania and Texas _ fertile ground for the
Republicans in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   On divisive social issues such as late-term abortions and
waiting periods for handgun purchases, they fall outside Democratic
Party orthodoxy and march in lockstep with Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which is
coordinating House races this November, actively recruited them.
Doing so, DCCC officials admit, was a calculated risk. But running
conservative Democrats in these increasingly Republican districts
might prove crucial in helping the party recoup the 11 seats it
needs to recapture the House after four years of GOP rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to impose any kind of liberal agenda on
anyone,'' said Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, chairman of the DCCC.
``Our attitude is the candidate should fit the district.''
</P>
<P>
   But some Democrats worry that by recruiting such conservatives,
the party is devaluing its bedrock beliefs and alienating many
moderates and liberals who comprise its base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take you any place and it erases your identity as a
party,'' said Bob Borosage, codirector of the liberal
Washington-based Campaign for America's Future. ``It should bother
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Some women's groups are particularly horrified. ``It's a concern
to us to see Democrats recruiting candidates who would take away a
woman's right to choose after we've made so much progress,'' said
Stephanie Cohen, spokeswoman for Emily's List, which raises money
for female Democratic candidates who support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats involved in the nitty-gritty of restoring their
party's leadership in the House insist there is no other way to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gersh, a consultant who has advised the DCCC on candidate
recruitment, said, ``In certain districts it would be suicidal to
have a liberal run.``
</P>
<P>
   The main criterion for selecting candidates is a promise to vote
for a Democrat to be House speaker. ``Voting in a Democrat as
speaker means Democrats control committees, legislation, the entire
agenda,'' Gersh said. ``Anyone who doesn't understand the
difference between (House Speaker Newt) Gingrich and (House
Minority Leader Richard) Gephardt doesn't understand politics.``
</P>
<P>
   Gersh and other Democrats also say that while the nine
candidates are conservative on some issues, they support the
mainstream of the party on others and are rarely as conservative as
their Republican opponents.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Republicans are amused by what they view as yet
another effort by Democrats to gain favor by aping GOP positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an acknowledgment by the Democratic leaders that their
ideas are the wrong ideas and the people who espouse them are not
electable,'' said Mary Crawford, spokeswoman for the National
Republican Congressional Committee, which coordinates GOP House
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Democrats are hardly a new phenomenon in Congress.
From at least the end of World War II to the early 1960s, Congress
was dominated by conservative Southern Democrats who favored
military spending and opposed civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the Blue Dog Coalition, with 24 House members,
represents the interests of the conservative Democratic
minority-within-a-minority. Coalition members have worked with the
DCCC to recruit conservative Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Dogs focus on economic issues such as balancing the
budget and reducing the size of government. ``We're all over the
map on social issues,`` said Rep. Allen Boyd, a coalition member.
''We don't involve ourselves in them.``
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, this year's conservative Democrats are out front on
some social issues. Among those on the ballot are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ken Lucas, judge-executive in Boone County, Ky. Although
anti-abortion and pro-gun, he supports federal spending on Head
Start, school lunches and education loans. The Kentucky AFL-CIO
endorsed him. His opponent is state Sen. Gex ``Jay'' Williams, a
religious conservative supported by the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pat Casey, a lawyer and son of former Pennsylvania Gov. Bob
Casey, who was denied a chance to speak before the 1992 Democratic
National Convention because of his anti-abortion stance. Pat Casey
shares his father's views on abortion and opposes gun control. He
has the backing of the Pennsylvania AFL-CIO in the Scranton-area
district. His GOP opponent is Don Sherwood, a car dealer who also
opposes abortion and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   _ Loy Sneary, a cattle rancher, rice farmer and former judge in
Matagorda County southwest of Houston. Fitting the anti-abortion
and pro-gun profile of the district, Sneary is running against Rep.
Ron Paul, R-Texas, a colorful politician who opposes abortion, gun
control, foreign aid and federal aid to education. He is the
Democrats' top target in Texas this November.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Turnham, former chairman of the Alabama Democratic Party
who steered the party organization away from support of gun control
and abortion rights. But he has supported civil rights, an
important factor for black voters in the east central Alabama
district. His GOP opponent is Rep. Bob Riley, who won his first
term in 1996 with a bare 51 percent majority.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ronnie Shows, the regional transportation commissioner in
southern Mississippi, who opposes gun control, abortion and gay
rights. On the GOP side are two conservatives, tax lawyer Delbert
Hosemann and banker Phil Davis, who will compete June 23 for the
GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chris Gorman, former Kentucky state attorney general. He is
anti-abortion and pro-gun, as is the Republican he is challenging,
first-term incumbent Rep. Anne Northrup of Louisville. In 1996 she
campaigned for cuts in taxes, the size of government and the amount
of regulation of small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Phelps, a state representative and gospel singer running
for a vacant seat in southeast Illinois. Besides opposing abortion
rights and gun control, he favors school prayer, positions that his
Republican opponent, Brent Winters, a lawyer and farmer, agrees
with.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marjorie McKeithen, granddaughter of former Louisiana Gov.
John McKeithen. Running in Baton Rouge, she opposes abortion and
gun control and advocates a ``flatter'' tax system. But she
supports raising the minimum wage. Her GOP opponent, Rep. Richard
Baker, also anti-abortion and gun control, opposed raising the
minimum wage in 1996 but ultimately voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Stallings, who left the House in 1992 after four terms
to make an unsuccessful Senate bid. Stallings is conservative on
abortion and gun control but moderate to liberal on many other
issues. The Republican nominee, Idaho state House Speaker Mike
Simpson, is pro-gun but has been attacked by anti-abortion
advocates as insufficiently committed to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
