<HEADLINE>
SINATRA STYLE STILL RESONATES IN FASHION WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; He had the voice and the Rat Pack fame, but more
than that, Frank Sinatra had style.
</P>
<P>
   You thought Kramer's bowling shirts were pure ``Kramer''?
According to Elena Hart of the Fashion Association in New York,
that ensemble, accented with pointy shoes and a cigar, were part of
Sinatra's signature wardrobe long before ``Seinfeld'' made TV
fashion history.
</P>
<P>
   And what about all those pinstripe suits he wore in ``Guys and
Dolls''? Hart says you can find similar looks today in the latest
Claiborne for Men collection, while Members Only still produces the
very same golf jacket Sinatra wore on the links.
</P>
<P>
   To see more of Sinatra's personal style, cruise over to Concours
on Rodeo at 10 a.m. June 21. The crooner's car _ a 1956 Thunderbird
_ will be among the 75 vintage and classic celebrity-owned
automobiles displayed on Rodeo Drive in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The free Father's Day event is sponsored by Chrysler Corp.,
Beverly Hills Motoring and the Rodeo Drive Committee. The Concours
on Rodeo is part of the California Classic Weekend that begins
Friday with the Cars and Stars gala at Petersen Automotive Museum,
6060 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles. For more information, call (310)
858-6100.
</P>
<P>
   BEAUTY BIZ: Hard Candy, maker of that nifty nail polish with the
little ring, now has compacts for the galaxy girl on the go. The
silver cases are filled with creamy blusher and metallic
highlighter and tucked into a holographic compact pouch, priced at
$26 at Macy's and other department stores.
</P>
<P>
   To get that perfect fake tan without orange hands, the Beach
Self-Tanning Kit now includes a pair of Beach Mitz. The palm-shaped
mitts stick to the palms of your hands so you can apply the
quick-tanning cream everywhere, even the tops of your hands. Then
peel off and throw away.
</P>
<P>
   The kit is $22, and extra packages of Beach Mitz are $6. You can
find them at Nordstrom at Topanga Plaza in Canoga Park; or call
(800) 648-9729 to place an order.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE KIDS: The latest bandage for children is soooo cute,
your darlings will probably start faking injuries. Why, even Miz
Hot Tips covered her paper cut with the pink-eyed frog, which is
one of several tattoolike designs from 3M Nexcare Waterproof
Bandages. Other designs on the clear plastic strips are happy
faces, teddy bears, peace signs and tigers, priced at $3.49 a box
at Target and numerous drug stores.
</P>
<P>
   UNDER HER SPELL: Celeste Mills counts to three, snaps her
fingers, and you no longer need a ciggie. Magic? Nah, it's
hypnotherapy, now endorsed by the American Cancer Society as an
effective tool to stop smoking.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, this Magic Castle magician has used hypnosis
to help cancer patients endure chemotherapy, and now she's working
her spell on smokers.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer with the Valley branch of the American Cancer
Society, Mills will be conducting classes June 22 at the Holiday
Inn in Burbank; June 24 at the Holiday Inn in Woodland Hills; and
June 25 at the Holiday Inn in Palmdale. Show up at 7 p.m. with
$59.95, and she'll send you home smoke-free, with a reinforcement
tape plus a ``Kiss me, I quit'' badge. For more information, call
Mills at (818) 783-8209.
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS ON THE LOOSE: Do you sit home alone, wishing for an
adventure but too scared to go solo? Miz Hot Tips has the ticket _
a group tour of Asia with a bunch of over-60 folks for $1,299
(includes round-trip air fare, hotels, food and travel guides). To
hear more about it, attend the meeting 1:30 p.m. July 10 at Valley
Senior Services, 18255 Victory Blvd., Reseda. For more information,
call the Organization for the Needs of the Elderly at (818)
705-2345.
</P>
</TEXT>
