<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6945 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIRDRESSERS-PARTIES-     06-12 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRDRESSERS-PARTIES-ART-2TAKES-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HAIRSTYLIST TO SOCIALITE, INVITED VIRTUALLY EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 14)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By RUTH LA FERLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Dillon, a hairstylist at the high-end Brad
Johns salon on Fifth Avenue, who tends to the manes of Natasha
Richardson and young society swans like Carolina Herrera Jr., has
found himself at the center of a social whirl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe the number of things I get invited to every
week,'' Dillon said. He was Ms. Richardson's guest at the opening
night of ``Cabaret,'' in which she stars as Sally Bowles. He was
also asked to be a co-chairman of a benefit for Lou Gehrig's
disease and was invited to a Chuck Close retrospective at the
Museum of Modern Art _ never mind that, as he put it, ``I didn't
know anything about Chuck Close until the invitation arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Sally Hershberger, a Los Angeles hairstylist who created Meg
Ryan's artfully mussed bob in ``City of Angels,'' attended the
Academy Awards in March with Ms. Ryan and Dennis Quaid and landed a
coveted invitation to Vanity Fair's post-Oscar party. More recently
she turned up in New York, invited by Madonna to attend a birthday
celebration for Ingrid Cesares, a nightclub owner, at the Kit Kat
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lately, it seems we're going out more than usual,'' Ms.
Hershberger said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it does. Hairstylists and makeup artists who cater to
celebrities and socialites are as likely to turn up at A-list
parties these days as their clients _ feted, befriended and fussed
over. The people who clip, snip and apply streaks of buttery blond
coloring _ once viewed as members of a service class _ are emerging
as new social lions in an era that is increasingly image-obsessed.
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Fekkai, the leading celebrity hairdresser of the 1990s,
is routinely invited to mingle with the bon ton by such formidable,
nationally prominent hostesses as Betsy Bloomingdale in California
and Lynn Wyatt in Texas. ``He's a businessman and an artist, the
Christian Dior of his generation,'' said Mrs. Wyatt, who introduced
him to a gathering of her friends in Houston last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wyatt, bred in the old school of social proprieties, is not
unaware of the irony: the gates of the social elite swung open to
admit, first, fashion designers like Geoffrey Beene and, now,
hairstylists and other beauty professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten or 15 years ago, you might not have asked a dress designer
to your party,'' she said. ``And inviting your hairdresser, well,
that would have been unthinkable. But lots of things used to be
unthinkable. All I can say is, times have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fekkai, who operated the beauty salon at Bergdorf Goodman from
1989 to 1996, when he opened Beaute de Provence on East 57th
Street, recalls his admission to Los Angeles' gilded inner circle
with a mixture of awe and amusement. Invited by the producer Steve
Tisch to a dinner preceding a Rolling Stones concert last fall, he
found himself seated with Tom Freston, the chairman of MTV
Networks, and Sheryl Crow, the singer. ``If I told the friends that
I grew up with in the south of France where I had been and who I
had seen, they would say, `Wow, he's hallucinating,''' Fekkai said.
</P>
<P>
   Such spectacular evenings only top the list of perks enjoyed by
the grooming world's fabulous few: limousines furnished by generous
clients to speed them to appointments, tickets to movie premieres
and, not least, friendships cemented in the stylists' chair. Philip
Berkovitz, the Beverly Hills hair treatment specialist known
professionally as Philip B., often serves tea in his garden to his
friend and longtime client, Lynda Obst, the producer of films like
``Hope Floats.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Ms. Hershberger is in New York, she says she likes to
have dinner with pals like Richard Gere at Da Silvano, a favorite
downtown haunt of actors, artists and high-profile magazine
editors.
</P>
<P>
   Hair and makeup artists haven't always basked in such glamour.
In the more formal climate of the early 1960s, Kenneth Battelle,
who created Jacqueline Kennedy's bouffant hairstyle, felt compelled
to keep a low social profile.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as half a dozen years ago, Battelle fretted that his
friendship with Joan Rivers, who had recently moved to New York,
might hamper her ambitions. ``Joan is not going to make it in New
York in the social swing of things if she's out with her
hairdresser all the time,'' he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   At photo shoots just a decade ago, ``we used to be on the low
end of the totem pole, a notch above the caterer,'' recalled Kevyn
Aucoin, the makeup artist and best-selling author, who is at least
as famous as some of his clients. By contrast, ``socially, these
days it's wild,'' said Aucoin, who whiles away his leisure hours
with Cher and Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Aucoin still can't get over his newfound social cachet. ``I feel
like I'm one of these people who has somehow snuck in to a secret
society,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He needn't have been so modest. Aucoin's climb up the ladder
comes at a time when hair and makeup artists have never wielded
more influence as image makers, attaching their names to cosmetics
lines, drawing crowds at store appearances, and writing makeover
books that climb best-seller lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hair and makeup artists are the newest style gurus,'' said
Jennifer Josephy, the editor of ``Making Faces,'' Aucoin's
coffee-table book (Little Brown, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   But if that is true, they owe much of their stardom to an
elevated definition of their craft. ``These people are in what used
to be known as a service industry,'' said Linda Wells, the editor
in chief of Allure, the beauty magazine, ``but now they are thought
of as creative types, as important as artists and trendsetters as
some of the better-known clients.''
</P>
<P>
   By promoting stylists as celebrities, Allure has played a
significant role in raising their profile, a development Ms. Wells
has come to rue. ``Lately,'' she joked, ``it's a lot harder to book
Kevyn for a sitting than to get Jewel to play at your bat
mitzvah.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
