<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      06-12 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 13, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1997 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, temperatures at Charleston, S.C., soared to a
record-tying 95 degrees as a warm ridge of high pressure centered
over the eastern Gulf of Mexico extended its canopy of sizzling
heat northward.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, temperatures will soar to 100 degrees in parts of east
South Carolina and east Georgia as breezes from the west warm on
descent from the mountains and boost afternoon heat. Isolated
thunderstorms will provide spotty relief, given the lack of
high-altitude cooling needed to extensively destabilize the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Over eastern North Carolina and eastern Virginia, however, where
ample cooling aloft associated with an approaching disturbance is
juxtaposed over surface temperatures in the 90s, thunderstorms,
possibly severe, are more likely to erupt. Storms are possible as
far north as Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will douse parts of the northern Middle Atlantic and
southeast New England seaboards as steady onshore winds import
Atlantic moisture. Ocean winds, whose persistence will be
guaranteed by low pressure developing farther south along the
Middle Atlantic coast, will average 20 to 30 mph from eastern Long
Island to Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, powerful thunderstorms will erupt later Saturday
across the western Plains from northwest Texas to the Dakotas as an
expanse of cold air aloft moves over gathering warmth and moisture
at the surface. The greatest threat of severe weather will come
over Nebraska and Kansas, where a compact disturbance vigorously
lifts increasingly humid air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WARM FRONT BLOCKADE
</P>
<P>
   In a struggle between a warm front and the Atlantic Ocean in
June, the ``Big Pond'' usually wins when the battle takes place in
eastern New England. A warm front is an opportunist, only staking
claim to battleground from which cool air has already retreated. In
spring and early summer, when ocean waters off New England are
still cool, a pattern that promotes steady onshore winds can keep
reinforcing cool air, thereby thwarting the advance of a warm
front. Saturday, a warm front attached to a low in Canada will
stall in the Northeast as cool ocean winds persist. Protracted
rains are likely. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAIRDRESSERS-PARTIES-     06-12 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIRDRESSERS-PARTIES-ART-$ADV14-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: bat mitzvah.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aware of their new clout, the savviest hair and makeup stylists
have positioned themselves as advisers on everything from the
texture of clients' lipstick to the color of their shoes.
``Hairstylists are really the designers of the '90s,'' said Dillon,
who added that his clients seek his advice on everything from where
to vacation to what to wear to a premiere. ``And if I tell them, `I
want you in this dress' or `those mules,' you can believe that
they'll do what I say.''
</P>
<P>
   Fekkai, who still finds time eight or 10 days each month to cut
clients' hair, recently placed his logo on a collection of canvas
handbags, sunglasses and candles. ``Today, the business is not just
hair,'' he said. ``It's about life style and creating a total
look.''
</P>
<P>
   But though a handful of hairstylists now compete with designers
as taste makers, few show signs of taking themselves as seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have hairstylists at your party because they are
unintimidating and refreshingly accessible,'' said Jean
Godfrey-June, the beauty and fitness director of Elle magazine.
``Unlike designers, who are all so corporate now, these people
don't have to be so careful about what they say. They are plugged
in to a more fun kind of world, a surface world where fashion
begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The most socially savvy of the lot have parlayed their
popularity into sidelines as party hosts in their own right. Art
Luna, a high-octane hairstylist in West Hollywood, arranges
frequent dinners for 10 or 12, for favored clients like Anjelica
Huston and Sally Fields, who begin the evening with wine in his
garden, a miniature Eden replete with ferns, jasmine, bamboo and a
fountain brimming with seashells and quartz.
</P>
<P>
   The ebullient Luna views his newest hobby as a natural extension
of his work. ``I'm already a glorified host,'' he said. ``I see
myself as entertaining clients in their chairs all day.''
</P>
<P>
   At night, those very clients are inclined to make a fuss over
him. Ms. Wells, who recently attended one of Luna's palmy,
candlelighted dinners, found him surrounded by fawning members of
the Hollywood elite, including Kelly Lynch, Daryl Hannah, Jeanne
Tripplehorn and Gina Gershon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were crowding around him, but that was
understandable,'' Ms. Wells mused. ``In a city like L.A., where
your beauty is your currency, everyone wanted to get in with Art,
just to make sure that when the moment arrived, they'd be able to
get an appointment.''
</P>
<P>
   It's light years from the day when to be seen on the arm of your
hairdresser was to court social ruin. ``These days, one of the
smartest things you can do for your looks is to party with a
hairdresser,'' Ms. Wells said. ``And the best thing you can do for
your social life is to marry one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
