<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALAND GIANT SHOWS NEW INTEREST IN U.S. MARKET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With even some of the smallest New Zealand wineries entering the
U.S. market, it seemed strange last January when I visited the
largest Kiwi winery _ Montana _ only to be told it didn't export to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's changed.
</P>
<P>
   Montana, the 500-pound gorilla of New Zealand, makes several
separate tiers of estate-bottled wines under different vineyard
designations, and now it's launching its Brancott Vineyards wines
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Montana's Brancott Estate, at 570 acres, is the single largest
vineyard in New Zealand, located in the Marlborough region at the
north end of New Zealand's South Island. Indeed, Montana was the
pioneer in Marlborough, traditionally a sheep-farming region, when
it established the Brancott Estate in 1973. Other winery ventures
have followed suit, of course, the best known being Cloudy Bay,
just down the road from Brancott.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are a number of Brancott wines being made, this
first venture, marketed nationally by Seagram's, consists of five
white wines. Since wines show best (generally) when paired with
food, I tasted the Brancott wines at the chef's table in DeVille
Restaurant, where chef Tim Keating prepared a special lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Keating, not afraid to mix and match, changed the order of
serving the wines to go with his dishes _ and it worked.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Brancott wines is the 1996 Patutahi Vineyard
Gewrztraminer ($23.99) _ 4 stars _ a spicy white wine with a hint
of sweetness. I would've expected this wine to be served with
dessert, but instead Keating served it with the first course, which
was an ``Asian Cocktail of Crabmeat and Shrimp'' with what he
called ``piquant spices.'' Excellent match, the spiciness of the
seafood going hand-in-glove with the slight sweetness of the wine.
</P>
<P>
   (Note to Keating: Should you opt for a French wine next time
with that Asian dish, try the 1996 Marc Brdif Vouvray, an off-dry
Loire white that goes really well with spicy crawfish, among other
dishes ...
</P>
<P>
   Montana's too smart to send questionable wines into a new
market, so all the Brancott wines showed well. My favorite, because
of its pungent, grassy style, was the 1996 Brancott Sauvignon Blanc
($25.99) _ 4 1/2 stars _ which illustrated why the Marlborough
region is so fertile for sauvignon blanc. The 1997 Reserve
Sauvignon Blanc ($16.99) _ 4 stars _ with its crisp but somewhat
rounded citrusy taste was a good aperitif.
</P>
<P>
   Keating literally turned the tables on us. The gewrztraminer was
served first (not last), so naturally the sauvignon blanc was
served last (not first), with a selection of three mild cheeses.
And again, it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Although all three chardonnays were barrel-fermented, they
remained a contrast, ranging from the 1997 Gisborne Reserve
Chardonnay ($16.99) _ 3 1/2 stars _ with its ripe, tropical-fruit
profile, to the 1996 Ormond Vineyard Chardonnay ($23.99) _ 4 stars
_ with more butter and toast. The 1996 Renwick Vineyard Chardonnay
($23.99) _ 4 1/2 stars _ tasted more like a white burgundy, with a
touch of ``terroir,'' or taste of the soil, married with the
butterscotch and vanilla nuances.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line on Brancott Vineyards from New Zealand: not
inexpensive, but well-made wines. Hopefully not too long from now,
more Montana wines will wind their way here, including some of the
less expensive ones. Those that I tasted in New Zealand were
bargains.
</P>
<P>
   Wine rating: 5 stars, outstanding; 4 stars, fine; 3 stars, good;
2 stars, fair, 1 star, poor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael Lonsford can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and question to
michael.lonsford(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
