<HEADLINE>
WHEAT FUTURES CLOSE HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA SIZEMORE LONG  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City wheat futures and Chicago wheat, corn and soybean
futures prices closed higher Friday, following early losses that
came after government crop reports.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Value Line stock-index futures closed down only
slightly after sharp early losses.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sold off sharply early after the Producer Price Index was
released and further pressure came from bonds, said Kansas City
trader Mark Grismore.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after bonds closed, the market came rip-roaring back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Western Natural Gas futures closed up sharply on talk of warmer
weather linked to the La Nina phenomenon, which causes hotter
temperatures and less precipitation in summer.
</P>
<P>
   In grains, wheat futures were helped by short-covering after
recent declines. Prices also rose after the Agriculture Department
lowered its estimate for 1998 soft red winter wheat production. The
USDA did, however, increase its winter wheat estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures closed higher on concern about the potential for
hot and dry weather soon in growing regions. Meanwhile, the crop
estimate for 1998 corn remained unchanged from last month at 9.6
billion bushels.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures closed up as much as 9 cents a bushel on growing
concern about the potential for hot and dry weather this summer.
Prices also rose on signs of strong demand for soybean products
such as oil and meal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government's soybean projection was steady at a
record 2.8 billion bushels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
