A6972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTINS-DANCE-REVIEW-     06-12 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: A 3-WAY ADVENTURE IN PARTNERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Martins has had a long fascination with ballet
partnering. In his ``River of Light,'' presented by the New York
City Ballet in its world premiere Thursday night at the New York
State Theater, Martins continues his exploration of what partnering
can mean in ballet of the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Martins also continues his exploration of new music with ``River
of Light,'' which was choreographed in celebration of the 60th
birthday of Charles Wuorinen. Wuorinen conducted this first
performance of the ballet and will conduct the work through the
City Ballet season. Set to a commissioned score with the same
title, the new ballet is the fourth collaboration between Martins
and Wuorinen.
</P>
<P>
   Martins touched on the subject of partnering in ``Calcium Light
Night,'' his first choreography for the company that he now heads.
That ballet, created in 1977, was set to pieces by Charles Ives, a
composer who, like Wuorinen, is thought of as uncompromisingly
modern. The quirky astringency of ``Calcium Light Night'' came in
part from the distinctive stage personality of Heather Watts, who
danced the earliest performances with Daniel Duell.
</P>
<P>
   Even then Martins, himself an accomplished partner schooled in
the traditions of 19th-century classical ballet, was enlarging on
the experimentation of George Balanchine with partnering that
reflected changing music and society.
</P>
<P>
   For Martins, such experimentation could push the boundaries of
the traditional challenges inherent in two people dancing as one,
enhancing the sense of a ``play of forces which gives a sense of
drama,'' as he later wrote in his autobiography, in partnering that
nakedly revealed ``dynamic interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   There are glimpses of ``Calcium Light Night'' _ and of
Balanchine's ``Episodes'' and ``Ivesiana'' _ in ``River of Light.''
And no startlingly new points are being made in the Wuorinen
ballet. Martins seems to be settling into old ideas and imagery in
the new piece, allowing the dance to luxuriate in its jagged,
biting excesses.
</P>
<P>
   The choreography embodies the music's rising and waning tension.
And there are moments of unexpected texture and color comparable to
pools of tonal color in the music. A good deal of the physical
texture comes from the distinctive differences in the ways Martins'
three couples dance together at first. Each couple seems designated
to express a different facet of partnering in the three duets that
open the ballet, though the dancers soon change partners and blend
to some extent in this tightly knit work.
</P>
<P>
   It falls to Monique Meunier and Jock Soto, who are dressed in
black unitards and are the first couple out onstage, to represent
partnering in its most angular, urgent joining and pulling apart of
tightly wrapped bodies. Alexandra Ansanelli and Charles Askegard
are a more lyrical and innocent-seeming pair of partners, qualities
suggested, perhaps, not only by the comparative lyricism of their
dancing but also by their white unitards and the gentle impetuosity
of Ms. Ansanelli's long body.
</P>
<P>
   There is a suggestion of maturity in the relative languor and
the slight distance of Darci Kistler and Sebastien Marcovici in the
third duet. Dressed in red, they seem to represent a seasoned
variation on the romantic relationship inherent in all ballet
partnering.
</P>
<P>
   Each couple's dancers enter individually and proceed along a
rectangular path of white light that dissolves into a small, soft
pool. The effect enhances the choreographic shifts and the staging
of those opening duets.
</P>
<P>
   But lighting designer Mark Stanley undercuts Martins with the
hard, geometric patterns that follow, looking, distractingly, like
a Futurist design for a Broadway show. And the mixing and matching
of costume colors is eventually a little too neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``River of Light'' does not seem destined to become a signature
or even major Martins work with time. But Martins sends his six
dancers into some interesting adventures, delineated in a
performance of impressive clarity and commitment. And he ends on a
mystical note suggested by the ballet's title, as the women spin
slowly within their partners' arms first on the ground and then in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   The program also included a performance by Nichol Hlinka and
Damian Woetzel of Balanchine's ``Tchaikovsky Pas de Deux'' that was
breath-stopping in its musical and pyrotechnical daring.
Balanchine's ``Stars and Stripes,'' danced to Sousa marches
arranged by Hershy Kay, received a properly saucy performance from
a cast led by Jennie Somogyi, Aura Dixon, Tom Gold and Ms. Meunier
and Askegard. Darius Crenshaw stood out in the corps for the extra
snap and sparkle of his dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Martins and Wuorinen paid homage to Balanchine and Stravinsky
respectively in ``Reliquary,'' which completed the program. The
1996 ballet was performed ably enough by a cast headed by Samantha
Allen, Peter Boal, Wendy Whelan and Nila Martins, with the
demi-soloist roles taken by Ms. Dixon, Michele Gifford, Kathleen
Tracey, James Fayette, Peter Hansen and Arch Higgins. But Martins
failed to animate his quotations from Balanchine with any new life
of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Wuorinen conducted his score for ``Reliquary.'' Maurice Kaplow
was the conductor for the Balanchine works. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
