<HEADLINE>
LETTERS TO THE COLUMNIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's this? The mailbag is overflowing. No wonder, though. It's
been three months since this space was set aside for Valued
Contributors. So, let's rummage around in the pile and snare a few
of the most interesting missives.
</P>
<P>
   Well, well. Here's one concerning, of all things, Social
Security. Can you imagine anybody being interested in Social
Security?
</P>
<P>
   ``Regarding Social Security recipients receiving more back than
they invested. No one ever mentions the millions who died and never
received a cent back...Let's be fair. Whenever (you) mention SS
recipients getting more back, mention the millions who paid in and
received nothing.'' {Dear Mentioner:
</P>
<P>
   OK. How about those millions who paid into Social Security and
died before they could collect a penny in benefits? There! They've
been mentioned. While we're at it, how about those millions who
paid little or nothing into the system and nevertheless hit the
jackpot for a lifetime? Don't they also deserve a mention? Having
mentioned all this, what's the point? Social Security remains a
terribly flawed concept. It needs reforming to reflect the fact
that fewer and fewer workers are supporting more and more
beneficiaries. The past is irrelevant to the future.}
</P>
<P>
   Smoking is almost as hot a button these days as Social Security,
and the following view is one of the most frequently expressed:
</P>
<P>
   ``If people choose to smoke, that certainly is their right.
However, I don't think I should have to pay for their medical bills
when they're dying of lung cancer as a direct result of a (really
pretty stupid) decision they made with full information (it says
right on the package what the risks are).'' {Dear Stone-Heart:
</P>
<P>
   The great myth of the tobacco debate is that smokers' health
problems impose an economic cost on society. Several studies,
however, show just the opposite. Kip Viscusi, a Harvard Law School
professor, has done extensive research on this subject, for
instance. He found that smokers more than cover the external costs
of their habit. They die sooner and thus don't live long enough to
consume as much health care as the non-smoking elderly; moreover,
their tax burden as tobacco consumers is relatively higher than
non-users when they're alive.}
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of counterintuitive economic truisms, the trade
situation also confuses many readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think that trade (deficits) were a positive thing,''
says one, ``like money in the bank that would eventually be
returned to the USA to buy U.S. goods from us. Now I am beginning
to think this money is being used to turn us into some sort of
colony for foreign investors to exploit.'' {Dear Confused:
</P>
<P>
   If this is colonialism, then let's have more of it. Japan has a
humongous trade surplus and has been living an economic nightmare
for all of the 1990s. Some of the Asian ``tigers'' currently
experiencing the worst economic crises have been noteworthy for
their trade surpluses. The longer protectionists keep arguing that
trade deficits are the way to perdition, the better things keep
getting for a U.S. economy with growing trade deficits. Meanwhile,
the worse things keep getting for our trading partners with
substantial trade surpluses. Theory is one thing, but reality keeps
telling us something entirely different. Maybe the world has
changed and traditional economics hasn't caught up with these
changes.}
</P>
<P>
   Keep them cards and letters comin', hear?
</P>
<P>
