<HEADER>
A6991 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-BEATING-KAN &LR;      06-12 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-BEATING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY CONVICTS KANSAS CITY MAN WHO WHIPPED HIS SON TO DEATH WITH A
BELT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Jackson County Circuit Court jury on
Thursday convicted a Kansas City man who whipped his son to death
with a frayed belt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John J. Williams Jr., 30, could be sentenced later to up to life
in prison for felony second-degree murder and endangering a child. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His attorney will appeal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams' defense attorney argued that his client never intended
to kill 2-year-old Michael Scott when he disciplined the boy with a
braided, split belt. Prosecutors compared the beating to a flogging
with a cat-o'-nine-tails. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jackson County Prosecutor Claire McCaskill said the verdict
showed a public shift away from too much emphasis on parental
rights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't want to be convicted of murder for killing
their children they shouldn't beat them in the first place,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael attended the Operation Breakthrough day-care center. The
assistant director of the center, Sister Berta Sailer, testified at
the trial and applauded the verdict. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get the message across this will not be
tolerated,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jurors heard testimony that Williams beat Michael on May 29 last
year because the boy wet his pants. Minutes after the beating,
Michael stopped breathing, and Williams rushed him to a fire
station. Michael was dead, and the police investigated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams told police about the beating in a videotaped statement
played for the jury. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I stripped him from the waist down; I wanted him to feel it,''
Williams told police. As the boy screamed, Williams told him, ``If
you're going to make that noise at least drop a tear.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He called it ``a normal whipping'' _ about five blows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The beating caused a rare condition usually seen in industrial
accidents or car wrecks, a medical expert said. His flesh was
struck so hard that the fat turned to liquid and blocked his blood
vessels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The expert added that Michael would have died from internal
bleeding the beating caused in his thigh. The flesh was beaten off
Michael's thigh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jurors also heard testimony from Michael's 12-year-old half
brother. He testified that he heard the smack of blows mixed with
Michael's screams for about 15 minutes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said Williams had been beating Michael about every two
weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During closing argument's Wednesday, Dan Miller, assistant
prosecutor, popped the belt taut as he held it before jurors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you beat a dog with this?'' he asked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller showed jurors pictures of Michael's injuries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They look like tire tracks going over that little boy,'' he
said. ``No man would do that unless it was his purpose.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Horton Lance countered that his client did not
take into account that one blow with the belt struck in many
places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could have foreseen that his fat would liquefy,'' Lance
said. ``This was a tragic, unintentional accidental death.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fact that his client disciplined Michael before with the
belt also showed it was an accident, Lance said. ``This day, for
whatever reason, he went too far _ it was reckless.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lance argued that his client was guilty of no more than
involuntary manslaughter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jury went out at 3:50 p.m. Wednesday. As in many child
deaths, its verdict hinged largely on whether the defendant
intended to seriously injure or kill. Those elements are needed for
conventional second-degree murder, which carries a sentence of 10
years to life in prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers often argue for involuntary manslaughter, saying
the accused did not intend to kill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Involuntary manslaughter carries a top sentence of seven years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a rare legal move, Miller also charged Williams with felony
murder. That allows a murder verdict whenever someone dies during a
serious crime. Miller argued that Michael's death was felony murder
during child endangerment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only one appeals court has upheld that approach in one case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jury reached a verdict at 11:30 a.m. Thursday. It did not
believe Williams intended to seriously injure or kill, jurors said
afterward, so they rejected the charge of conventional
second-degree murder and convicted him of felony second-degree
murder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri, Kansas and 26 other states have passed recent laws
that allow sentences of up to life whenever a child dies by abuse,
intentional or not. But the Missouri law went into effect in August
1997, three months after Michael died. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charges of endangering the welfare of a child are pending
against Michael's mother, Deborah Blake. She allegedly did nothing
to stop the beating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael's half brother is in the care of an aunt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sailer, the assistant day care director, said Michael was a
happy boy who loved the Barney show and often sang its song. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The message he got from that show was so different from what
he got at home,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
