<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6994 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLAST-MOURNERS-KAN &LR;      06-12 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAST-MOURNERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNERS SAY GOODBYE TO FIRST OF BLAST VICTIMS TO BE BURIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JOHN PETTERSON AND RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA, Kan. _ While rescue crews struggled to find the final
worker still missing after Monday's massive grain-elevator
explosion, mourners gathered to say goodbye to the first of the
blast victims to be buried. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people filled the chapel of the Resthaven Mortuary in
Wichita on Thursday afternoon for the funeral of Jose Luis Duarte,
40. Duarte, a Cuban immigrant who had worked at the elevator for
more than three years, was found dead Monday, shortly after the
explosion at the DeBruce Grain elevator complex southwest of
Wichita. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Father Leopoldo Gonzales told the mourners that no one can
understand why God takes people when he does, and why he takes some
who've lived a relatively short time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conducting the service in Spanish, Gonzales said, ``We are in
God's hands.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mourners streamed behind the hearse that carried Duarte's body
to the cemetery. His four small children _ Andy, Manual, Jaime and
Javelin _ walked at the front of the procession. Jaime carried a
cross of flowers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The death toll in the blast stands at five, and Duarte was the
first to be buried. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Duarte was laid to rest, rescue crews continued the difficult
search through the grain- and rubble-filled tunnel seeking the last
missing victim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon Thursday, a spokesman for the Sedgwick County
Fire Department said the rescue work appeared to be nearing an
end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that we're getting close,'' said Ken Cox,
the department's division chief. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Occupational Health and Safety Administration
was investigating the DeBruce Grain elevator for possible
violations of federal law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Marple, OSHA's Kansas director, said he and three other
inspectors had been conducting interviews with survivors and
examining pieces of equipment blown from the structure by the
explosion that was believed to have been caused by an accumulation
of grain dust. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The elevator had not undergone an OSHA examination since 1983,
Marple said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got elevators in Kansas that have never been
inspected,'' he said, estimating that there could be as many as
1,500 of them in the state. ``They are like trees in the forest.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the elevator, purchased by DeBruce in 1996, had not been
the subject of complaints against the current owners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marple emphasized that his inspectors were taking a back seat to
the rescue teams that continued to focus their efforts on a
1,200-foot tunnel, one of four that run beneath the half-mile-long
grain storage facility southwest of Wichita. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Three bodies already have been removed from the tunnel. They
have not been identified, although Cox said the county coroner was
making good progress toward identification. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Workers cut a hole through the thick ceiling of the concrete
tunnel to provide new access for a huge grain vacuum that will
speed the recovery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a rescue mode,'' Deputy fire chief Curtis
Wilson reported. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, Cox said, three crews were at work in the
section of the tunnel where the man was believed to be trapped. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The crews are very optimistic now that we're making such good
progress,'' Cox said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The tunnel is clogged with grain, concrete chunks from the
storage bins above and twisted pieces of the conveyor belt system
that transported grain through the complex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the rescuers who worked to remove a 4-by-7-foot section
of the 15-inch thick ceiling was Jeff Gottbreht, a member of a
specially trained urban search and rescue team organized by the
Federal Emergency Management Agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's based in Lincoln, Neb., where Gottbreht is a city
firefighter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His three-member team spent six hours cutting through the slab
with a water-cooled saw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By about noon, it was loose, and Gottbreht and other crew
members rotated out for a 12-hour rest as they had since they
arrived early Tuesday morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he squeezed water from his heavy clothing, Gottbreht talked
about what they might find. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of morbid, but even if we don't find and rescue a
live body, you are giving some closure to a family,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rescue teams were being housed in a nearby school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A large bus, chartered from a company called ``Good Life
Coaches,'' brought the crew members back to the school for their
rest period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping accommodations were arranged in the school's
multipurpose room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They make me sleep on the stage,'' Gottbreht said. ``I
snore.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The team also has dogs trained to detect human scent and they
have been working all week in the tunnel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One crew member sat on the school steps petting a mixed-breed
dog named Ditto. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the best in the country,'' the crew member said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five men still are hospitalized from blast injuries and their
conditions remained unchanged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those hospitalized: Lanny Owen, critical condition; Scott
Mosteller, serious; Johnny Sutton, upgraded to serious from
critical; Daryl Williams, critical; and Carlos Amador, fair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Authorities identified the men missing in the tunnel as Howard
Goin, Noel Najera, Victor M. Castaneda and Raymundo Diaz-Vela. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of the dead, only the two victims found Monday _ Duarte and Jose
Prajedes Ortiz, 24 _ had been identified.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early on in the disaster, local hospitals had feared they would
face a shortage of blood. But donors crowded the American Red Cross
Wichita office this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials asked people to send cards to survivors, rescuers and
families who are mourning those who died. Cards can be sent to
``Families and victims of DeBruce Grain Elevator explosion, c//o
American Red Cross, 707 N. Main St., Wichita, Kan. 67203. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
