<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLIGHT-TWA-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flight attendants of Trans World Airlines may stop working on
the carrier's Boeing 757s next month if the two sides fail to reach
an agreement on staffing and safety issues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The head of Machinists Local 1997, which represents TWA's 4,900
flight attendants, said talks to establish staffing guidelines
regarding the 190-seat jet so far had failed. The Boeing 757 was
introduced into TWA's fleet about 18 months ago, and management and
the union must incorporate any new aircraft into its current
bargaining agreement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As of July 1, you will no longer be obligated to fly the
757,'' said Sherry Cooper, president of Local 1997, in a recorded
phone message to members. ``Our primary concern is safety.
Additional issues include understaffing penalty pay and the type of
service to be performed on the 757.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said the union was continuing to hold talks with TWA on
the 757. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWA has 15 of the 757s in its fleet of 185 aircraft. The company
said it thought an agreement would be reached with the flight
attendants before next month. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, we don't anticipate a service disruption,''
said TWA spokesman Jim Brown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the talks about the 757 are separate from the main
negotiations occurring now between TWA and all of its unionized
work force on a new contract. The latest contract expired last
August but remains in effect during negotiations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TWA's discussions with the Machinists union and Air Line Pilots
Association have dragged along, frustrating many in the work force.
Last month, many TWA workers engaged in a work slowdown for two
hours at TWA's St. Louis hub, causing flight delays and
cancellations. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
