<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'LL NEVER LOOK AT COWS THE SAME WAY AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If only we could have had this book on those long family trips
in the station wagon instead of that boring magnetic tack-toe
board!
</P>
<P>
   ``A Field Guide to Cows: How to Identify and Appreciate
America's 52 Breeds,'' by John Pukite, is modeled humorously on
birding guides. But instead of classifying herons, the book takes
on heifers _ offering comprehensive profiles on breeds, clothing
and equipment suggestions, viewing tips, glossary, charts, and
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Pukite, a biologist, wrote the book almost on a whim. ``I didn't
really have a strong opinion about cows before,'' he says, by phone
from Minnesota. ``I just mooed at them like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he was struck by the number and variety of cows he
encountered as he drove from Minnesota to Seattle on a trip.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The book has caught on so well _ with close to a whopping
50,000 &UR;  &LR; in print _ that Pukite laughs when he recalls he initially
thought he'd have to pay to have it self-published. &UR;  &LR; In fact, ``A
Field Guide to Cows'' is so hot that his publisher, Penguin (of
course), wants more &UR;  &LR; guides like it. And naturally, pigs, sheep,
and goats are next for this barnyard Roger Tory Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Packed with facts both serious and silly, the cow guide can keep
travelers busy long past that first whiff of manure.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine yourself driving along. ``What are those black-and-white
cows out there?'' someone asks.
</P>
<P>
   With your handy guide, you can be a bovine Einstein. You'll see
that the animal's wedge-shaped outline tells you it's a dairy cow
(beef cows are more rectangular). And the conformation of the spots
reveals that these cows are Holsteins _ the No. 1 dairy cow (most
numerous and produces the most milk) in America.
</P>
<P>
   What if you encounter something more exotic? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   That huge cow with the massive horns? Is it a Texas Longhorn?
No! Pukite tells us it is the Watusi from Africa, the cow that has
the biggest horns of any breed (often 8 feet long and 8 inches
around at the base).
</P>
<P>
   If you have to stop the car for a better look in identifying a
breed, Pukite has a few cautionary words, listed under ``Cow
Etiquette'': ``Cows have almost total 360-degree panoramic vision,
making them tough to sneak up on.'' Approach them slowly, without
sudden movements or loud noises. Also, try to keep your own mooing
in check. Mooing is a reflexive human reaction to cows, but since
it can signal distress or the ``feed me'' lament of a calf, you
shouldn't overdo it.
</P>
<P>
   How serious is Pukite about all this? The book is a
pungent &UR;  &LR; mixture of parody and information. And so is the author's
general view of cows. On a recent trip to Hawaii, Pukite realized
he may have a secondary profession as a leader not of birding, but
cowing, trips in paradise. No kidding. ``There are cows all around
the island!'' he exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Pukite's enthusiasm for cows ensures that you will never look at
them in the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   He can make cows sound wholesome: The Jersey has a ``cute
appearance,'' ``a gentle nature,'' ``intelligence,'' and it makes a
great ``family cow.''
</P>
<P>
   He can make cows sound sexy: The Chianina, he says, is
``shapely.'' The breed Blonde d'Aquitaine, the full-figure girl of
bovines, is described as having ``curving horns'' and ``a long,
straight topline,'' and it is ``the largest and heaviest of the
French breeds.'' The British White has, quite bluntly, ``big
udders.'' And the Piedmont sports a ``big, beefy butt.''
</P>
<P>
   And he can be downright racy: American farmers, he writes, take
advantage of the Simmental's ``latent dairy traits in
crossbreeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Cows can be macho, according to Pukite: The breed Salers (for
this breed, the cows don't moo, they coo ``Hey there, Salers, new
in town?'') is described as ``a big, burly, cherry red cow.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pukite's world, cows can even be dignified: The Charolais is
``one of the oldest and most respected of the French breeds.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Limousin, ``the long, sleek cow'' from France, sounds as
if it should be called a ``stretch Limousin,'' since it is noted
for both power and speed. (The Limousin may very well be the cow
depicted in the famous Lascaux cave drawings.)
</P>
<P>
   Cows are everywhere _ there are 100 million of them in the
United States alone _ and it's a shame that so many of us pass them
by without appreciating their bovine beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Let John Pukite show you the whey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
