<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7002 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-12 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDDLING IS TO BLAME IN ASIAN ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent analysis of Asia's woe suggests that its economic
miracle and its subsequent crisis are opposite sides of the same
coin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arthur J. Alexander, president of the Japan Economic Institute,
points out that the countries with the biggest problems share
significant economic development philosophies. The most significant
of these is an emphasis on government intervention in banking and
credit activities designed to mobilize savings and channel them
into favored investment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexander says such intervention on a modest scale doesn't
appear to hurt growth. If, however, the favored projects aren't
pursued strictly for profitability, the stage is set for future
troubles. When an investment's soundness is questionable, the usual
practice is for governments to protect investors from risk with
guarantees against loss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This creates what economists call ``moral hazard,'' which is
what Alexander says has been ``the primary cause of today's crises
in East Asia.'' Moral hazard is basically an insurance term used to
explain how imprudent or dishonest behavior is encouraged when
people are protected from the adverse consequences of their
actions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aggressive government involvement in capital formation and
allocation was obviously an early dynamic spur to economic growth
in such countries as Japan, South Korea, Thailand and Malaysia.
Over time, though, moral hazard led to questionable policies and
unsound investments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As is usually the case, government socialized the losses and
privatized the profits. If loans weren't repaid, government rescued
lenders and depositors. If the loans proved profitable, bank owners
pocketed the profits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that not all the Asia ``tigers'' have
come to grief. Hong Kong, Taiwan and Singapore remain stable,
Alexander points out, most likely because they are subject to
rigorous bank supervision and have capital markets providing access
to long-term financing through other means than bank loans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's analysis is useful in the debate over what many
perceive as inadequate savings by Americans. The Asian countries in
the most trouble all shared remarkably high savings rates. Much of
the savings was wasted, however, because ill-advised government
policies encouraged unsound investment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Asian debacle thus proves that savings in and of itself
can't ensure prosperity. What's needed is sound accompanying policy
directing savings toward their highest and best use when
transformed into the wealth-creating investments necessary for
prosperous growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the Japanese, for instance, are renowned for their thrift,
their rewards are the most humongous banking problem in history, an
anti-consumer economy, and political and economic systems in
tightening gridlock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the problem, beyond bad resource-allocation
policies, is the anti-consumer nature of economic policy. In trying
to build economies on exports, the workers making the prosperity
possible are denied the full fruit of their labor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Asia is to regain its dynamism, market-disciplined financial
systems must be complemented by consumption-oriented economies. The
U.S. miracle is the enduring real deal it is because it creates
ample rewards for the working-class folk who make it possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Asia miracle is vaporizing because economic policy has been
geared to reward the ruling elite while shortchanging the masses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-DIARY-REACT-$AD     06-12 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-DIARY-REACT-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR `BRIDGET JONES' DIARY': GET REAL! 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 14) 
(jt) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bridget Jones makes me ill. She gives me a headache; she makes
my stomach hurt and my heart heavy.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't heard of ``Bridget Jones' Diary'' ... well, good
for you. The novel, a best seller in England, tells the story of a
single woman in her 30s who works in publishing with a degree of
passion that can best be described as dead-eyed apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones tells her tale in the form of a diary, noting at each
entry her weight, the number of aborted phone calls made to former
and potential lovers, cigarettes smoked, calories and snack foods
and alcoholic drinks consumed. She agonizes over why men mistreat
her, how they're self-absorbed and emotionally stunted, then spends
hours gazing wistfully at the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly normal behavior, if you're a 13-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   The book transformed its author, Helen Fielding, into a
celebrity in England, and almost every women's magazine in America,
from Vogue to Mirabella to Jane, praised it upon its publication
here by Viking. Many women are apparently laughing as they
recognize parts of themselves in Bridget's jumble of insecurities
(just as they smile knowingly along with Ally McBeal).
</P>
<P>
   Bridget's universe is populated by couples she calls Smug
Marrieds and single friends she calls Singletons. Ambivalent as
Bridget is about marriage _ those who achieve it immediately turn
into self-satisfied boors _ she leaves no doubt about the single
state: the unattached woman is a simpleton, a spinster, someone
worthy of a derogatory label. The plot is simple: she is on a quest
for a man who returns her phone calls, and she'd like to lose eight
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   After a member of the publicity brigade that is trumpeting the
book called and urged me to read it, I decided to see what the fuss
was about. It doesn't take a Freudian analyst to know that the
cover is a tip-off that something is terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of enthusiastically mascaraed eyes look up expectantly; a
mouth frosted in lipstick is poised into the open ``o'' that
appears in sexually suggestive advertising. (There's no nose. Who
needs a nose?) Most disturbing is the foundation upon which this
disembodied woman's face is presented: blank pages, the red and
blue lines of a child's notebook, unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And through it all,'' the jacket reads, ``Bridget will have
you helpless with laughter and shouting, `Bridget Jones is me!'''
</P>
<P>
   Nah. I started reading and couldn't stop, through all 271
stomach-churning pages. It was like stumbling across open-heart
surgery on the Learning Channel _ appalling, but hard to turn away
from.
</P>
<P>
   The thing reads like a novelization of the Calvin Klein perfume
commercial for Contradiction, in which the model Christy Turlington
talks about what a mess of conflicting emotions she is as she
stares stormily into the camera, then laughs a shade too
hysterically, then weeps a little, then smiles coyly, then averts
her gaze moodily.
</P>
<P>
   That's what ``Bridget Jones' Diary'' is about: the learned
helplessness thrust upon women by advertisers, popular
entertainment and, yes, women's magazines. Ms. Fielding constructs
her heroine out of every myth that has ever sprung from the ground
of Cosmopolitan and television sitcoms. To wit, that men are, in
the words of one character, ``stupid, smug, arrogant, manipulative
and self-indulgent''; that women are obsessed with boyfriends,
diets and body hair, and that every emotional reversal is cause for
a chocolate binge.
</P>
<P>
   It makes humor out of the premise that being neurotic is cute.
That women eat too much. That we succumb to the lure of too many
cocktails. That if we don't enjoy our jobs, we just stick around
and, heck, sleep with the boss (who never calls us back).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was taking the whole thing way too seriously. I decided
to survey some female acquaintances, to see if I was, in fact, a
harridan with no sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   But I wasn't alone. Others, smart New Yorkers all, shared my
antipathy for Bridget. ``She's a self-contained, one-woman mental
institution,'' said Joanie McDonell, a writer. Candace Bushnell,
whose sometimes lonely but mostly confident female characters
inspired the new HBO series ``Sex and the City,'' said she thought
``Bridget Jones' Diary'' was fun to read, but 10 years out of date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the kind of thing that would have been written
here in the '80s,'' she said. ``Now, in Manhattan, if you're over
35 and you're not married, frankly it's not a big deal. People say
you're lucky and don't bother. But in England if you're 30 and
you're not married, it's totally weird. It says more about the
state of feminism in England.''
</P>
<P>
   Giulia Melucci, who handles book publicity for Scribner, was one
of the few I surveyed who argued that the novel was a realistic
look at single female life. ``Haven't you ever had a day where you
spent two hours looking for pantyhose and couldn't find any?'' she
asked. Sure, but a new pair of pantyhose costs $5 at the corner
drugstore. That shouldn't be the price of self-respect.
</P>
<P>
   I called an author who has written extensively on the status of
single women today, Marcelle Clements, who wrote ``The Improvised
Woman: Single Women Reinventing Single Life.'' She said the book
disturbed her on so many levels she couldn't begin to count. ``It's
the humor of the pathetic,'' she said. ``It's as if as women become
more successful and powerful, they need to be punished for defying
the old laws. They have to be with their nose in the Haagen-Dazs;
they have to be made to look ridiculous and pitiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Overheated, perhaps, but I see her point.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes, I know ``Bridget Jones'' is satire, a sassy spoof of
urban manners. But Bridget is such a sorry spectacle, wallowing in
her man-crazed helplessness, that her foolishness cannot be
excused.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend _ a Smug Married _ noted that although men suffer
from similar, and maybe even more toxic, neuroses and fears, ``men
always burnish their images.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their images are always much glossier and better than
reality,'' she said. ``Women don't do that. Society wants the woman
to be self-deprecating.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the book, Bridget is carried away by an
inscrutable character who has magically metamorphosed from the dull
boor he was for the first 250 pages into a dashing knight, sweeping
her out of her family's dysfunctional home on Christmas Day. The
pair have never even been on a date, but she gamely joins him in a
hotel suite where he makes love to her on _ someone call Barbara
Cartland! Her material is being ripped off! _ a four-poster bed.
She is surrounded by the trappings of long-sought material comfort,
secure in the arms of the faceless Prince Charming who has saved
her day.
</P>
<P>
   But not mine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
