<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7009 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS     06-12 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEED ORWELL'S WARNING ON THE DEGENERATION OF LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fascinating exhibit about Boston is in Cambridge at the
Compton Gallery of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Norman B. Leventhal of MIT's class of 1938 is displaying, until
July 31, ``Mapping Boston: Delineating the City and its Region.''
Leventhal, who has collected Boston maps for years, has displayed
these elegant parchments chronologically, from the 17th to the 20th
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Perusing a 19th-century map at the exhibit's opening was John R.
Silber, former president of Boston University, former gubernatorial
candidate, and full-time contrarian. With a mischievous gleam in
his eye, Silber muttered, ``My, my, these are wetlands. If we had
saved the wetlands, there would be no Back Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ``nature'' became ``the environment,'' its dominant
language has elided from euphemism to propaganda to Holy Writ. In
the 19th century, city builders called it a noxious swamp, a
malarious marsh, or a fetid fens (adios, Fenway Park, if today's
bureaucrats had made the call). ``Wetlands'' conjures up Rousseau's
peaceable-kingdom purity, which is why it soberly infests state and
federal statutes.
</P>
<P>
   When language evolves into propaganda, George Orwell warned, the
result is totalitarianism. After he issued that warning in 1946,
Soviet Russia created ``The People's Republics'' of Poland,
Czechoslovakia, Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria, Estonia, Latvia,
Lithuania, and so on. Winston Churchill's skill at the English
language properly described this conquest as imposing ``an iron
curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement of ``swamp'' by ``wetlands'' is a more benign
evolution of language, just as ``jungle'' has been eclipsed by
``rainforest,'' although Edgar Rice Burroughs did not write a novel
about, nor did Johnny Weismuller portray in movies, ``Tarzan, Lord
of the Rainforest.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell pointed out that most degradations of grammar and
language have political motives. Thus, in self-defense, people now
study words and consult language mavens, a concise Yiddishism in
itself. Jesse Sheidlower has been studying language at Random House
for years and has published ``Jesse's Word of the Day,'' an
alphabetized compilation of answers to inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   The American language, H.L. Mencken declared more than 60 years
ago, is constantly evolving, but many regionalisms resist
homogenizing. Sheidlower notes that ``moxie,'' for instance,
appeared in a 1930 Damon Runyon short story, and asserts that the
phrase derives from ``Moxie, the trademark name of a popular soft
drink marketed especially in New England. Moxie is thus a sort of
`Pepsi spirit' of the 1930s, if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   No, we won't, because ``if you will'' is a stalling-tactic
phrase, a tangle of overbearing linguistic kudzu. Sheidlower is
more useful in rolling out a ``juggernaut,'' determining the
ancestry of ``nerd'' (Dr. Seuss), and giving due deference to the
Dutch phrases, ``booze'' and ``kit and caboodle.'' He also
forthrightly admits defeat: ``The ultimate origin of `eighty-six'
is unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   He details the Greek and Latin origins of ``onomatopoeia,'' a
favorite linguistic tool of today's bureaucrats, who know that
``wetlands'' sounds better than ``swamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Leventhal's marvelous maps narrate the saga of how
civilization arrived in Boston and how the city subdued its
environment, which included weather, a nonsacred shoreline, and
fetid swamps. The manmade beauty of today's cities might not have
survived a multi-volume environmental impact report.
</P>
<P>
   Much of today's enviro-bureaucratic language caters to
air-conditioned troglodytes who have their pie and refuse to share
it. The first, not last, refuge of litigious scoundrels is often
``traffic and parking.'' But a city without ``traffic and parking''
problems is a dead city. Those who can't handle the byproducts of
density should move far away, perhaps to a quiet, peaceful spot
amid federally protected ``wetlands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-COX- &UR; -     06-12 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-COX- </SLUG>
   -(ANALYSIS) 
 &HT;     FEAR MOUNTING THAT MEXICO READY TO PURSUE WAR, NOT PEACE WITH
REBELS
 &HT;     ED: This is an Analysis.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Saturday, June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After hundreds of troops and police marched into a
Zapatista rebel village Wednesday and sparked a deadly gun battle,
Mexican human rights groups fear the government will provoke an
all-out war now against the Maya Indian dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's violence marked the first time Zapatistas and the
Mexican military have directly exchanged gunfire in more than four
years of uneasy truce and mounting tension in Chiapas, a state on
Mexico's southern border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are back where this all started in January 1994,'' said
Pablo Romo of Chiapas' Fray Bartolome de las Casas Human Rights
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the government is trying to pave the way for a
direct confrontation with the Zapatista Army,'' Romo said, calling
``peace the loser.''
</P>
<P>
   He joined a chorus of voices that are criticizing the government
for failing to promote peace talks in Chiapas and adopting an
aggressive military policy toward the Zapatistas, with whom the
government officially has a truce.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative and left-wing opposition parties also attacked the
government this week, calling for an investigation into how the
military's attempt to enter El Bosque, a village sympathetic to the
Zapatistas, flared into a deadly confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government had better be absolutely open,'' said Felipe
Calderon, president of the conservative National Action Party
(PAN). ``If its intention is to end the truce that has held since
1994, considering it to be useless and not viable, then it must say
so and bear the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   The military's attempt to occupy El Bosque came less than a week
after Catholic Bishop Samuel Ruiz _ a key figure in Chiapas _
resigned in frustration from a mediation commission that helped
forge the truce between the government and the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican troops and police were sent into El Bosque after a
reported ambush on Tuesday killed a sympathizer of Mexico's
dominant political party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party
(PRI). On Wednesday a column of 500 heavily armed troops and state
police were sent marching into the village in an attempt to occupy
it by force.
</P>
<P>
   The troops said they were fired on and then lobbed tear gas, and
began firing their weapons, killing eight Zapatista sympathizers
and sending other villagers fleeing into thickly forested hills.
Survivors of the confrontation said the military fired on the
village first.
</P>
<P>
   For several months now, the Mexican military has been marching
into Zapatista villages in an aggressive law-and-order campaign,
dismantling some of the more than 30 parallel or so-called
``autonomous'' governments that Zapatistas have set up in villages
scattered about the state.
</P>
<P>
   The policy began around the same time that the government began
expelling foreign human rights observers it charged were violating
Mexican immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Critics see the policy as a concerted effort to break the truce,
roust the Zapatistas and undermine rebel support among Indian
towns. Human rights groups, including the government's own National
Human Rights Commission, have urged that the military be withdrawn
from areas of conflict because they are hindering peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negotiations now seem to be completely blocked on the national
level,'' said Jose del Val of the Inter-American Indigenous
Institute in Mexico City. He suggested that only international
pressure could help push the government and the Zapatistas back to
the table to talk peace.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's gun battle in Chiapas was significant enough to
prompt Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo to comment publicly on the
incident during a trip to Chiapas, where he met with presidents of
local municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks Friday, Zedillo lamented the violence in El Bosque,
but said ``the best protection against violence is to comply with
the law, respect each other, whether we agree with each other or
not, and practice tolerance as we pursue dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to resolve the conflict in Chiapas, Zedillo has
been pushing for the passage of reforms in Mexico's Congress that
are designed to expand Indian rights.
</P>
<P>
   An administration source said Zedillo is ``dedicated to
dialogue,'' but the government must enforce ``the rule of law'' and
use the military to stop arms trafficking in the region and
violence from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was not a strike against the Zapatista Army,''
the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas, who enjoy sympathy among many Mexicans, staged
their first attack on the government in January 1994, claiming that
native Maya Indians were suffering from crushing poverty, disease
and brutal treatment by a corrupt government.
</P>
<P>
   Although peace accords were eventually signed, talks between the
government and the rebels broke down and the accords were never
implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Zapatistas have set up their own village
governments and pursued their cause mostly by seeking support from
sympathizers in the rest of Mexico and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The shoot-out between Zapatistas and the military in Chiapas
Wednesday occurred on the heels of another event this week that
shocked Mexicans _ a military assault last Sunday on the Popular
Revolutionary Army (EPR), a second rebel group that has attracted
sympathy among impoverished Mixteco Indians living in Mexico's
Guerrero state.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes in Chiapas and Guerrero this week are unrelated, but
have contributed to a climate of fear that more violent
confrontations between the military and underground rebel groups
are likely to occur in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The EPR, for its part, has issued a communique stating that for
each of the 12 sympathizers killed in Guerrero last Sunday it will
kill 10 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Chiapas, human rights observers and analysts
believe the government has opened a new chapter this week in its
relationship with the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an `Internet war' anymore,'' political analyst Sergio
Sarmiento wrote in the Mexico City newspaper Reforma, referring to
the peaceful, almost playful way Zapatista rebels and sympathizers
have used the Internet to boost international support for their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Sarmiento castigated the government and rebel leadership for
failing to negotiate an end to the crisis in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this conflict, as in all, the victims are not the
protagonists,'' he said. ``Neither Subcommander Marcos (spokesman
for the Zapatistas) nor high government officials lose anything
because peace has not been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who offer their lives are the soldiers and the
guerrillas,'' he said, ``and those who pay are the peasants, with
their deteriorating standard of living and the economic and
physical insecurity that today rules Chiapas.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-COX- &UR; -     06-12 1189
