each of the 12 sympathizers killed in Guerrero last Sunday it will
kill 10 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Chiapas, human rights observers and analysts
believe the government has opened a new chapter this week in its
relationship with the Zapatistas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an `Internet war' anymore,'' political analyst Sergio
Sarmiento wrote in the Mexico City newspaper Reforma, referring to
the peaceful, almost playful way Zapatista rebels and sympathizers
have used the Internet to boost international support for their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Sarmiento castigated the government and rebel leadership for
failing to negotiate an end to the crisis in Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this conflict, as in all, the victims are not the
protagonists,'' he said. ``Neither Subcommander Marcos (spokesman
for the Zapatistas) nor high government officials lose anything
because peace has not been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who offer their lives are the soldiers and the
guerrillas,'' he said, ``and those who pay are the peasants, with
their deteriorating standard of living and the economic and
physical insecurity that today rules Chiapas.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
