A7015 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-CONTAINERS-COX     06-12 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-CONTAINERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No space to garden? Can't stand the work? Want to dress up your
porch or patio? Hey,...contain yourself
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your idea of gardening is planting a couple of nice-looking
pots on the porch, give yourself a gold star. You've become a true
gardener.
</P>
<P>
   That's because there's a real science to designing and
assembling an attractive and effective container garden. Don't let
anyone tell you it's just potluck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like baking a cake,'' said Alison Dembo, assistant
retail manager for Habersham Gardens. Leave out a key ingredient or
forget a crucial step, and you risk a real flop.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never experimented with pots, consider what more and
more garden addicts are discovering: Containers allow you to create
a low-maintenance garden in a small space, to move the color of a
garden close to the house or into the shade, and to experiment with
a wide variety of plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're especially nice for people who live in the city,''
Dembo said.
</P>
<P>
   The planting options, including shrubs and even small trees, are
endless. ``Basically, any plant can be grown in a container if
you're willing to water, fertilize and acclimate the pot to a
location,'' Dembo said.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're willing to pay the price, you can create an
established garden from the get-go by packing it with mature
plants. ``The goal is to do something that looks pretty from the
beginning and will grow into something beautiful over the course of
the summer,'' said Sylvia Attkisson, an Atlanta garden designer.
</P>
<P>
   Before stirring up a pot, here are the main ingredients you'll
need:
</P>
<P>
   -- Proper container material. ``There are so many whimsical
things out now, you can use almost anything for a container,''
Dembo said, from rustic troughs to old boots.
</P>
<P>
   Terra cotta, by far, is the most popular material. Because it's
porous, it can absorb water, maintaining moisture longer, and
assume the mossy look so popular today. For year-round containers,
avoid Mexican terra cotta, Dembo said, because it's prone to
cracking during freezes. French or Italian terra cotta, concrete,
fiberglass and plastic are wiser choices.
</P>
<P>
   -- Location, location, location. The amount of sun or shade in
the place where you plan to put the pot will determine your plant
choices.
</P>
<P>
   -- A variety of plants _ verticals, trailers and fillers. Also
aim for a mix of heights; leaf sizes, shapes and textures; and
complementary colors in blooms and foliage.
</P>
<P>
   For height, consider cannas; ornamental grasses; shrubs,
including roses; and small trees, such as cherry laurels and
Japanese magnolias. Edge the pot with trailing plants such as
verbena, petunias, lantana, plectranthus, ivy, variegated vinca or
trailing zinnia (Zinnia angustifolia). Then fill in with
medium-size plants _ penta, plumbago, caladiums, coleus, impatiens,
ferns, hostas, small roses, hydrangeas.
</P>
<P>
   -- Decoration. Accent the pot as you would a garden. Add an
ornament, such as metal sculpture, an obelisk or even a trellis for
growing clematis, roses or Carolina jessamine.
</P>
<P>
   You were planning to decorate that cake, weren't you?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
