<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To become a priest: Four Roman Catholic men take holy orders in
a solemn ceremony
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--Below an immense white stone image of the crucified
Christ, four men lay prostrate on the cool hard floor of the
Cathedral of Christ the King last Saturday to dedicate their lives
to the Roman Catholic priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   Their prostration symbolized their unworthiness for office and
their dependence upon God.
</P>
<P>
   Each had been called by name:
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Barona.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael A. Castano-Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Victor A. Galier.
</P>
<P>
   Richard K. Tibbetts.
</P>
<P>
   All had been proclaimed worthy of the office by the Rev. David
Talley, the archdiocese's director of vocations.
</P>
<P>
   For Atlanta Archbishop John F. Donoghue, the ordination brought
back memories of his own on June 4, 1955. ``The ceremony in many
ways is the same as the ceremony I had,'' said Donoghue. ``I think
of my ordination every time I place hands on these young men.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Catholic ordination rite symbolizes the continuity
of the church. The hands of each new priest were anointed with oil
to signify the authority to handle the sacred vessels and
substances of the sacraments. And, each priest in attendance laid
hands on the heads of the ordination candidates, continuing the
unbroken chain of the priesthood going back hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-July, 11 new priests will have joined the ranks of the
Archdiocese of Atlanta, and 54 more men slated for service in the
archdiocese are in seminary. The number is significant at a time
when many dioceses suffer from a shortage of clergy.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Saturday's ordination reflected trends nationwide
in the priesthood _ increasing numbers of Hispanic priests and a
growing number of second-career priests. Of the four, only Galier
is under 30. Tibbetts, 55, has worked as a special education
teacher in high school, and Barona, 52, was vice president of an
import fashion company and worked in the finance department of
Grady Memorial Hospital. Castano, 34, who is from Colombia, worked
with Colombian Boy Scouts and the Red Cross, served a year in the
army and led missions to rural parts of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
