<HEADER>
A7020 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NASCARCAFE-COX     06-12 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NASCARCAFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nashville's NASCAR Cafe sets blood to racin'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 14: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go to Talladega or Daytona to wallow in the
sights and sounds of NASCAR racing. The mother of all venues is
sitting here on Lower Broadway, in the heart of the country music
district. And like a beer-drenched Hank Williams Jr. show, it's
loud, it's garish, and pure heaven for fans of the
Southern-born-and-bred motor sport.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's new NASCAR Cafe (the second of several planned
across the country) is the latest entry in the world of theme
restaurants. Like Planet Hollywood or the Hard Rock, it's a
combination restaurant-museum-arcade dedicated to one subject _ in
this case, NASCAR racing. Found in an old warehouse just a stone's
throw from Ryman Auditorium, historic home of the Grand Ole Opry,
this place is as subtle as the roar of a fuel-injected engine. From
the garish neon facade to the orange pimento cheese spilling out of
the Thunder Road Burger ($7.99), the spot is the same exercise in
excess that makes stock car racing so appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Out front, Jeff Gordon's orange and blue Monte Carlo, dressed up
in DuPont decals, sits on the sidewalk beckoning tourists to pull
out their wallets and come inside. If that wasn't enough, a
loudspeaker spits out announcements like a carnival barker:
``Remember _ life's a race. The best times win.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, the race begins. Literally. The three-story
restaurant is designed like a track, with huge open lobby
surrounded by tiered balconies of dining tables, arcade racing
games and glass cases enclosing NASCAR memorabilia. In the center
of it all, a huge bar serves as the main pit stop, built on bright
blue, green and yellow oil drums. The whole thing is illuminated by
lights made out of racing helmets, suspended from the ceiling on
black cables that look like the bell cords at gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of this monument to motor sports sits Darrell
Waltrip's Budweiser Chevrolet. At the top of each hour, one of the
wait staff (dressed in a black and white official's uniform with a
microphone headset), climbs on a platform overlooking the scene and
waves a flag, unleashing a rumble not unlike seeing a movie in
Sensurround. TV monitors overhead light up with video of an actual
NASCAR race, with a thunderous noise that nearly shakes the salt
off your fries. Then the big moment: Waltrip's car starts rising on
a hydraulic lift, soaring higher and higher above the bar like a
carnival ride. Whew.
</P>
<P>
   In between races, there's plenty of food straight out of the
grandstand. Specialties include the Pit Pig Sandwich (pulled pork
barbecue for $7.99), Superclash Catfish (with fries and coleslaw
for $8.99), and Collision Chicken ($9.99). You can top off your
meal with dessert, such as Chocolate Fudge Tire cake, or one of a
dozen ``high octane'' drink concoctions, such as the Spark Plug
(Crown Royal and Pepsi) or the Kahluadega 500 (Kahlua and
cappuccino). When the race isn't on, you can dine to nonstop
country music videos, including Lee Greenwood's flag-saluting ``God
Bless the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   For the hard-core NASCAR enthusiast, there's plenty to gawk at.
One wall is dedicated to the first family of NASCAR, Mr. and Mrs.
Bill France Sr. You can check out racing outfits worn by Michael
Waltrip, Davey Allison, Rusty Waller and Bill Elliott. The Winston
Cup trophy is on display. You can have your picture made sitting in
Gordon's car. If that's not enough, $5 will get you a ride in the
Virtual Reality Race Simulator, a big metal box that tosses fans
around like they were strapped to the hood of a souped up Monte
Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the NASCAR Cafe is designed to appeal to the racing
crowd. If you're not into motor sports, you might find yourself a
bit lost as to what the ruckus is all about. And if you don't like
boisterous crowds or burgers, you might want to avoid it
altogether. But if you're into NASCAR, this can be one wild ride.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
