<P>
   BULLS-ANALYSIS _ CHICAGO _ The last dance? No chance. Don't
believe Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen and Phil Jackson when
they start talking about the Chicago Bulls breaking up after The
NBA Finals. That trio has been all over the road when addressing
this subject. (D'Angelo, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH-JAZZ _ CHICAGO _ The Utah Jazz are trying to remain upbeat
despite being one game from elimination. But even the Jazz must
believe overcoming something nobody has in the Finals, a 3-1
deficit, and doing it against the greatest dynasty in sports in the
past 30 years, the Chicago Bulls, is almost impossible. (D'Angelo,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STODA-COLUMN _ Rodman has folded, spindled and mutilated the
Chicago Bulls' trust. He has twisted it, ripped it and mangled it.
He has mocked the Bulls from front office to head coach to
teammates. He is a narcissist and a clown. He is dangerous. But he
has not consumed the Bulls. In fact, Rodman has elevated them.
(Stoda, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-COLUMN _ BOYNTON BEACH _ It's been a week since Maynard
Trudeau scored a basketful of money at the NBA Finals. A quarter of
a million dollars, that's what they said. So what exactly has
changed in the life of Palm Beach County's most sudden sports
celebrity? ``Nothing,'' says Maynard. (George, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY-NOTES _ The first two games of the Stanley Cup finals at
Joe Louis Arena marked a homecoming of sorts for Washington's Adam
Oates. (Biggane, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-SUPERSTITIONS _ Not all baseball superstitions are as
obvious as the Florida Marlins' high black socks. Most of them, you
don't even notice. (Graziano, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
