</HEADLINE>
 0613 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June 13,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June
13, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. ET
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. ET, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS _ MEXICO CITY _ With hundreds of soldiers and
police marching into villages sympathetic to Zapatista rebels _
sparking deadly firefights _ fear is mounting that the Mexican
government has given up on peaceful solutions to political violence
in Chiapas state. (Ferriss, Cox News Service). ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PEASANTS _ GUO YUAN, China _ Gazing down over green rice
shoots that forever have been the Chinese peasant's sweaty handhold
on life, Zhan Hanjuin couldn't dismiss the broad grin that had
played across his face all afternoon. It was hard for him still to
believe he was standing atop his own new, two-story house with a
fish pond on the roof, a Volkswagen Santana in the garage, and a
six-foot-high air conditioner in the parlor. Just 25 years ago,
Zhan and his new bride shared a house with his parents, two
brothers and their families. They worked on a collective farm and
didn't have electricity, much less electronics like the television
and stereo ornamenting Zhan's year-old house. Zhan, 48, is a
top-of-the-line ``peasant.'' But millions of Chinese families have
pulled themselves out of exhausting poverty since land reform began
handing them control of China's rice paddies and grain fields in
the early 1980s. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With PEASANTS-MAO _ SHAOSHAN, China _ The adobe house where Mao
Tse-tung grew up is a shrine not just to the father of communist
China, but to the spirit of the peasants who inspired and helped
him fight a revolution. Tan Ruiren's parents were among them, early
members of the Shaoshan peasants' movement that Mao was said to
have started in a small loft of that house in 1925 to help
burdened, dirt-poor peasants shape a new life. She still proudly
shows the photograph of herself and fellow workers meeting with
Chairman Mao when he returned to visit in 1959, after the
revolution had put the communists in power. Then, she was a young
mother and the cook of the collective farm where Mao ate. Now, Tan
runs her own hectic restaurant across the pond from Mao's house,
where she also sells Mao trinkets and gladly distributes every day
hundreds of copies of that 1959 photo that has brought her
celebrity. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Tuesday, June 9, for use Saturday, June 14.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BRIDES _ KRASNOYARSK, Russia _ In the world of lonely
hearts, Tatyana Denoshova's lament rings loud and often: ``It's
difficult to meet a real man here. Good men are already married and
if they are not already married, they are no good.'' In her case,
though, the desperation resonates with urgency. A 25-year-old
hospital nurse in this depressed Siberia city, Denoshova earns only
$40 a month and hasn't been paid since March. She says the men she
meets are similarly strapped, or sodden with vodka, or both. She
and thousands of other Russian women have turned to mail-order,
video and Internet-based matchmaking services seeking husbands _
preferably American or European men who will love them and take
them far away from the dead-end of today's Russia. (Holmes) MOVED
TUESDAY. (i, l)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is a CoxNet layout available on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   ARAB-RENO _ WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno delivers a
12:15 p.m. speech on hate crimes and discrimination Friday to the
American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee's national convention.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-BARR _ CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., addresses
Iowa's ``first in the nation'' gathering of GOP presidential
hopefuls. (Carr, Cox News Service). EDs: Event begins at 8 p.m.
EDT.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY _ Members of Congress and candidates for Congress disclose
their personal financial data in disclosure statements made public
June 15. (Foskett/Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RACE _ WASHINGTON _ Throughout his presidency, Bill
Clinton has been at his eloquent best when talking about race in
America. But in the year since he asked Americans to begin talking
about the bitter legacy of racism and the country's multicultural
future, his voice has been largely silent. (Shepard, Cox News
Service 1000). Moved Thursday for release Saturday, June 13.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-BIZ _ WASHINGTON _ About 500 small-business owners from
around the country will draft a two-year agenda for federal
lobbying goals at an unprecedented summit here June 17-19.
Following up on an ``electronic town hall meeting'' conducted via
satellite May 29 at 250 sites in all 50 states, the summit is
partly a show of strength and partly a method of coalition-building
by the southern-dominated National Federation of Independent
Business and more narrowly focused national associations of
florists, furniture manufacturers, printers and restaurant owners.
(Mollison).
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-BIZ-DATA _ Data for graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Both moved Thursday in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Saturday, June 13.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-KILLING-VICTIM _ JASPER, Texas _ The man dragged to his
death was an unlikely martyr. With a talent for singing, friends
said he would put Jasper on the map. But not like this. (Mitchell,
Lufkin Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-KILLING-SUSPECTS _ JASPER, Texas _ Checking with B'Nai
Brith and Southern Poverty Law Center for information about the
suspects and the group they reportedly were associated with.
(Mitchell, Lufkin Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   KINGS _ Coretta King announces she and three of her children
will be meeting with Clinton next Tuesday to discuss setting up a
reconciliation commission. (Brice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CARNIVAL _ The carnival ride from which a 16-year-old was thrown
to her death had faulty latches on safety bars and was capable of
running more than 50 percent beyond its speed limit, according to
documents. (Phillips, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
