<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-ECON-514&AMP;ADD-NY     06-12 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ECON-514&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREAN STOCKS TUMBLE A RECORD 8.1 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Investors stampeded out of the Korean stock market
Friday, sending it back down to the 11-year lows hit late last
month on worries about the pace of economic changes and potential
labor unrest.
</P>
<P>
   This time, fears that the Japanese yen's free fall would put
pressure on China to devalue its currency, the yuan, unnerved both
foreign and local owners of Korean stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The key market index fell 8.1 percent, to 302.09, the largest
plunge on record. The closing figure was the lowest since January
1987. Many investors pulled their money out of the market on rumors
that Tiger Management LLC, a New York investment fund headed by the
well-known manager Julian Robertson, had sold large quantities of
South Korean shares.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Robertson has built up his fund's holdings in
companies like SK Telecom, South Korea's largest mobile-phone
company, and he has led a group of foreign investors pushing for
greater shareholder rights in the country. Those efforts had
bolstered the confidence of local investors.
</P>
<P>
   But those investors apparently ignored Robertson's other recent
statements that the problems of several Asian countries are not yet
close to being resolved. In fact, Tiger Management has been selling
some, but not all, of its South Korean holdings recently, including
Friday, according to an executive in the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Fraser Seitel, a spokesman for Tiger
Management, declined to comment on the firm's trading activities or
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding force driving down the market was the yen's
inability to regain its footing against the dollar after remarks
Thursday by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that were
interpreted by currency traders to mean Japan would get no help in
defending the yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major concern is no longer restructuring but currency,''
said Yoon Doo-young, chief strategist at Daewoo Securities in
Seoul. ``The yen has been depreciating far more rapidly than the
market anticipated recently, and that gives China more reason to
consider devaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   A weaker yen and a weaker yuan make Japanese and Chinese exports
cheaper and increase competition over the long run for the exports
of other Asian countries like South Korea, particularly since the
Korean currency, the won, has remained relatively stable.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Marvin, head of research at Jardine Fleming in
Seoul, said there was little reason for the won to fall. He pointed
to $35 billion held in reserve at the Bank of Korea, evidence of
the country's comeback from severe financial pressures and
indebtedness late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin also said concerns over the effects of the falling yen
were premature because it took considerable time for currency
fluctuations to have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Marvin said, while South Korea and Japan sell many of
the same products, they often cater to different segments of the
same market. Korean computer-chip manufacturers, for instance,
largely make basic chips, while their Japanese counterparts have
branched into specialized memory chips and the like.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Additionally, according to Japan's Ministry of Trade and
Industry, only 35 percent of Japan's exports are denominated in
yen, and most of those products go to Asia. The rest are largely
denominated in dollars, German marks and British pounds and, thus,
their prices are not adjusted unless the yen moves substantially
and over a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, however, the yen's weakness means some South
Korean industries are verging on losing their edge against Japanese
competitors, if they have not already done so.
</P>
<P>
   Korean steel companies lose their currency competitiveness
against Japanese steelmakers when the yen weakens to 9.5 won, and
South Korean electronics makers lose their currency edge when the
yen weakens to 10.5 won. The yen fell as low as 9 won Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having a very hard time,'' Yoon of Daewoo Securities
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
