<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7065 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLS-ANALYSIS13-COX     06-12 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLS-ANALYSIS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breaking up the Bulls? Not so fast
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The last dance?
</P>
<P>
   No chance.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen and Phil Jackson
when they start talking about the Chicago Bulls breaking up after
The NBA Finals. That trio has been all over the road when
addressing this subject.
</P>
<P>
   Every word has been calculated to set up two men to take the
fall if something does happen and they don't return _ Owner Jerry
Reinsdorf and Vice President Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Pippen and Co. will end this surprisingly easy series
tonight against the Jazz for one reason: to see The Jerrys squirm
when they are presented with their sixth NBA championship trophy in
the '90s. That's why Jordan, when asked Thursday if this is the
final run, said: ``A lot of things can happen, and management has
to choose a direction in terms of where they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Now who's wearing the Bull's-eye?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and Pippen will be back next year. The biggest question
marks are Jackson and Dennis Rodman. Jackson started the whole
``Bulls Are Breaking Up'' phenomenon by saying this would be his
last contract. Then it was Pippen, who said he would never play for
the Bulls again, before he came back from his injury and played for
the Bulls again.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Jordan, who twisted the entire soap opera and said
if The Jerrys don't want Jackson back (something neither of them
said), then he'd never play for another coach.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Rodman who said ... nothing that's made any sense.
</P>
<P>
   The only one who can be believed is Jackson. At this time next
season, he'll be sitting cross-legged on a rock in North Dakota
meditating.
</P>
<P>
   But don't buy Pippen's latest threat. ``I don't have any
intention of coming back here next season, even though I stated a
couple of days ago that I would look to come back, but I think that
this is the last run for this club.''
</P>
<P>
   How's the vise feel now, Jerrys?
</P>
<P>
   Here's what will happen:
</P>
<P>
   Pippen will explore his options and find he can receive about
$15million a year for three years from the Suns or the Rockets. He
will sit on the best offer and talk to Jordan, who said about
Pippen on Thursday, ``The harmony between the two of us is
incomparable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will ride off to his ranch and the Bulls will appease
Jordan by allowing him to hand pick Jackson's successor. Forget
Iowa State coach and Krause buddy Tim Floyd. That would assure a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan will tell the Bulls he'll stay if somebody like current
assistant Jimmy Rodgers is given the job and he's offered another
$30 to $40million.
</P>
<P>
   Management goes back to Pippen and makes a one-year offer for
$20 to $25million. Pippen may or may not sign. Being the
front-runner for the Finals MVP, Pippen now holds the hammer. He's
looking for his big payday, despite being 32. He probably asks for
three years in the $60million range.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan and Pippen back, the next decision is what to do
with Rodman. At times, the Bulls appear fed up with his act, but
then he comes back and dominates the fourth quarter of the most
important game of the season Wednesday and puts the Bulls on the
brink of another championship. He turns the second- best player of
the decade _ Karl Malone _ into a whimpering, whining crybaby who
is looking for every excuse not to take the ball to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Does Rodman's incredible resiliency on the floor make up for his
bizarre behavior? Perhaps. But the Bulls have another option to
fill the subordinate role of power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, a free agent, comes and plays for his golfing/gambling
buddy Jordan, takes whatever the rules allow, which will be
$1million at the most or about $327,000 and finally gets his ring,
something Barkley cherishes more than a late-night bar rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago would be the perfect fit for Barkley. The Rockets are
looking to dump their older players (they started with the Kevin
Willis trade) and Barkley could fill Rodman's role as the
rebellious rebounder. And Jordan would find another reason for
motivation: To win a ring for Barkley. After all, Jordan has been
saying all week his pet project this year was to win one for Scott
Burrell. Scott Burrell?
</P>
<P>
   And why would the Two Jerrys commit another $100 million to win
another title?
</P>
<P>
   How about a stay of execution?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
