<HEADER>
A7066 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZACH-WATKINS13-COX     06-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZACH-WATKINS13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitcher Watkins heading to West Point after state tournament
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Wangrin
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DRIPPING SPRINGS, Texas _ In two weeks Zach Watkins will ship
out, bound for the banks of the Hudson River and ``Beast
Barracks,'' basic training for the plebes of the U.S. Military
Academy at West Point's bicentennial class of 2002. For the next
four years he'll play baseball and work his way through an
education worth an estimated $280,000 and toward the goal of
leaving as the type of strong-willed, hard-working success-driven
man he has seen West Point produce.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Watkins, a trim 49-year-old entrepreneur, was Class of '71.
He played guard on Army's football team _ former Texas Coach John
Mackovic was one of his freshman coaches _ and became an Airborne
Ranger and served his commitment in Germany and Italy. Then he
successfully started, and ultimately sold, a string of business so
now he can comfortably afford to do what he did Wednesday. That is
to sit in the visitors dugout at the Dripping Springs High School
baseball field and watch his son and teammates work out in
preparation for tonight's Class 3A state tournament game against
Iowa Park at Nelson Field.
</P>
<P>
   Zach, one of four members of the school's 156-member senior
class to earn an appointment to a military academy, plans to be an
airborne ranger, serve his commitment and start a business, just as
his father did. He'd love to fly. His vision isn't good enough to
be a military aviator, but he will major in aeronautical
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Already he does have a pretty fair knowledge of the physics of
flight, particularly one involving a horseshoe-stitched ball.
Velocity. Control. Movement. He has it all, as his 15-3 record
(nine straight wins), 1.30 earned run average and 1.6
strikeouts-per-innings-pitched ratio will attest, and he'll have
the ball in his hand to start tonight's semifinal game for the 24-6
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hits spots. If I call for a breaking ball in the dirt, he
puts it there,'' junior catcher Mark Bomar said.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins has emerged as the ace for the senior-dominate Tigers,
whose six losses have been to playoff teams, including
Halletsville, which they could meet in the final if the Brahmas get
by Atlanta in the other semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom Hancock, effusive in his praise of assistants Rick
Eickenloff and Mark Schroeder and trainer ``Doc'' Ohnheiser in
keeping the Tigers consistent and injury free, has done something
he's never done in 29 years as a coach, including 12 at Austin High
and 14 at Travis _ keep the same lineup since the third game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Hancock took over a Dripping Springs program that
was a 12-time district champion and had reached the state
tournament in 1984 (runner-up) and '96 (semifinal loser). Going on
what people had told him, he figured Watkins would be his No. 2
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron Beauford was No. 1 last year, but when you take him out of
center field it really hurts us defensively,'' Hancock said. ``And
the more I was around (Watkins), the more I saw his easygoing
attitude you need in a pitcher and the attitude that he always
wants the ball in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins has been amply backed by the Tigers, who have averaged
7.5 runs per game in the playoffs. This season all nine batters in
the starting lineup hit at least .321, led by Rhett Eickenloff's
.483, and eight of them have an on- base percentage of .510 or
better. Defense has been a question, though. The Tigers average 2.1
errors per game.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a bad pitch or timely error will unhinge Watkins, whose
unflappability is as big an asset as a fastball that's reputed to
have been clocked in the high 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably my biggest attribute,'' the 6-foot-2-inch,
195-pounder said. ``If things don't go my way 100 percent, I can
just shrug it off. I used to want to strike everyone out, do
everything in a game. But I've grown up a bit. At each higher
level, more and more you're not able to do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not unusual to see him smile when he makes a bad pitch,''
Paul Watkins said. ``He'll smile _ and he'll know what to do next
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Father knows his son well, the seeds of which can be traced back
to one Friday night when Zach was about 5, when Paul Watkins came
home from a business trip at 10 p.m., suitcase in hand, and
encountered his son in the kitchen. ``He asked me, `Have you been
gone, Dad?' I'd been gone a week and he hadn't noticed. So I
decided I needed to spend more time at home,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   They began to do more things together. Father and son took
frequent trips back to West Point or wherever the Cadets were
playing on the road, and Zach got to go into the locker room and
meet the players and coaches. At the end of his sophomore year, he
told his father _ whom along with his mother, Judy, he considers
his best friends _ that he wanted to go to West Point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a surprise to me he decided to go there,'' said
Paul, wearing an Army hat and an Army football T-shirt. ``I tried
to be careful not to push the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't press the issue,'' said Zach, who shares the same
cropped red hair and freckles as his father. (His teammates call
him `Sausage' because his freckled cheeks look like, well,
sausage.) ``I'd grown up hearing about it all my life, the prestige
of it and the success West Point men have all their life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1826EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7068 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-5DAYS-5JOBS13-COX     06-12 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-5DAYS-5JOBS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five days, five jobs
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After working five jobs in five days to
see how the other half earn their daily bread, I thought of the old
joke about the eager college grad's first day on the job when his
boss shoves a broom into his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I just spent four years in college,'' the young man
protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, that's right,'' apologizes the boss. ``Here, I'll
show you how.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to be shown everything. Even the one job I had some
experience at had changed. But even if I wasn't worth the powder to
blow me out the door, my brief stints at other jobs might help you
decide whether to try a different hamster wheel:
</P>
<P>
   Winn Dixie Bag Boy
</P>
<P>
   As a former Publix bag boy, I felt ready to hit the floor
running. Just to be on the safe side, George Okell, sales manager
of the Winn Dixie in Palm Beach Gardens, suggested I watch a
12-minute instructional tape. I did. And I learned that as a
``service associate,'' my job was to provide friendly service, bag
groceries and offer to take them to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Could anything be easier?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Bagging groceries in large paper bags would be much easier.
The big brown bags are certainly more convenient for the customer
than plastic bags, which have the thickness of butterfly wings. But
plastic bags are cheaper ($20 for 2,000) than paper bags ($20 for
500) and that's the way it is unless the customer requests paper
bags.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the 50-lb paper bags of yore. A good bag boy _ and I was
good _ could size up a customer's package-carrying capacity at a
glance and pack accordingly. If the customer were robust, I would
whip two layers of cans into a double bag, toss in cereal, Kleenex,
macaroni, tomatoes, bread and _ thwock _ toss in a stalk of celery
for the perfect bag.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a service clerk has no choice but to tediously fill
plastic bag after plastic bag, a most unsatisfying task because
these bags have no side support. If you try to consolidate, you
risk bag breakage. Gone are the days when you could develop a
rhythm, slapping cans and baby food jars from counter to hand to
bag in a fluid blur of motion.
</P>
<P>
   The customers, bless them, are reconciled to annoying plastic
bag overload. What's more, when you smile and make eye contact and
offer to carry their groceries, they seem momentarily taken aback _
and then charmed by the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of my Saturday afternoon shift was a Royal Palm
Beach customer with a small pickup truck who had strung an elastic
cord across the bed, just aft the cab. ``Watch this,'' she smiled,
unhooking the cord and then stringing a dozen bags by their loops
across the truck. ``That was my daughter Jennifer's idea.''
</P>
<P>
   My Humble Recommendation (MHR): A good job for a youngster to
showcase a helpful attitude and move up. Only retirees with strong
lower backs need apply. For more satisfying stashing, encourage
customers to choose paper over plastic. _ _ VETERINARY ASSISTANT
</P>
<P>
   I might have been a little more helpful at Dr. Joan McMindes'
Native Palm Animal Hospital in Jupiter if I had stood around with
my thumb in my ear and simply watched.
</P>
<P>
   But no, I had to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is different,'' said veterinary assistant Monique
Pierpont, doing 17 things at once. When a patient comes in, its
record is pulled up on computer, the animal is weighed, petted,
talked to and treated as if it is the center of the universe, which
is usually the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``China,'' a 15-year-old female boxer, came in with a pinkish
growth bulging through the pad on her left hind paw. Blood was
drawn and it was Pierpont who detected the signs of a malignancy. A
swollen lymph node on the leg all but cinched it. Cancer. The
growth would be removed by laser surgery that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Assistants know just how to grasp a foreleg to facilitate
drawing a blood sample. They make stains, analyze blood, look at a
mysterious skin rashes on the tummy of a tabby and say, ``hmmmm,''
as sagely as any physician.
</P>
<P>
   Pierpont began preparation of a rambunctious 5-month old German
shepherd for spaying. Together we hoisted the animal onto a table
and in a trice the pup was anesthetized and flat on its back, its
paws restrained by soft straps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' said Pierpont, handing me electric shears. ``Shave her
belly and prep the incision site.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, tummy fur falls away like lamb's wool under the
shears. I used several pads of soap and alcohol to swab the
incision site. And then I watched McMindes perform the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start feeling faint, you don't have to stay,'' said the
vet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that you mention it, I could use some fresh air,'' I said,
hurrying for the door.
</P>
<P>
   MHR: As a veterinary assistant, I'd make a good cage cleaner. _
_ SCHOOL CAFETERIA FOOD SERVER
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't considered this line of work, it may be because
you thought only surly middle-aged women with the forearms of a
Swedish masseuse were eligible.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the servers still sweat. That's because they work between a
steam table and a pizza oven. But they're cheerful.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The kids are cute as Beanie Babies and they knew
what they wanted for lunch when they got up this morning: Pizza. I
exaggerate, but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   The day I served at Wynnebrook Elementary in West Palm Beach,
students had a choice (can you believe it?): Turkey and dressing
with cornbread and peas, pizza, a sub, a hot dog or a hamburger. It
was like dealing blackjack. One out of seven kids wanted the
regular meal, three opted for pizza, two chose hot dogs, one chose
hamburger, and subs were wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day starts early _ 6:30 a.m.,'' explains Theresa Graham,
cafeteria manager. ``It helps to know food preparation, smile, and
be willing to pitch in and help your co-workers.''
</P>
<P>
   And the No. 1 job requirement? ``To understand that we are here
to make the kids happy.''
</P>
<P>
   MHR: If you're an early riser who can stand the heat in the
kitchen, this would be one of those jobs that makes the day fly. A
head that looks good in a hair net is entirely optional. _ _
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH FOOD SALES
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Maureen Miller and Judy Williams have 28 years
behind the counter at Mother Nature's Pantry in Palm Beach. What
they don't know about what's good for what ails you would probably
fit into a sassafras tea bag.
</P>
<P>
   So when I took my place behind the counter it was to listen and
learn. (What I know _ ``Dairy products cause mucous'' _ not
everybody wants to hear.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't even on computer,'' Miller says. ``Our inventory
control is our customer who says, `I just got your last bottle of
whatever.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the latest trend?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carbs are out. Fats are out. The Adkins Diet is in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you pushing?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miracle Water, it's the greatest for athletes,'' Miller said.
``Replaces your electrolytes with no calories, no sugar or
sodium.'' Just bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   And Judy? ``Liquid chlorophyl,'' she said. ``It's a great blood
cleanser.''
</P>
<P>
   A customer brought a bag of millet to the counter. Why? Who eats
millet? ``It tastes like rice,'' the customer explained, ``but I
have a staph infection, and millet helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   Flax oil, so they say, is good for the brain and reducing
cholesterol. Rice milk _ a product called Rice Dream _ replaces
milk but takes getting used to. There are probably 100 varieties of
teas, some merely for sipping, others said to be sovereign for
every ailment from eczema to gout.
</P>
<P>
   A supplement called Ginkgo Biloba is taken for short-term memory
problems, and capsules of something called chondroitin sulfate
seems to help some cases of arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like to see our laxative section?'' Miller asked,
directing me to shelves of remedies. ``We call it Corner a-Go-Go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take me there,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   MHR: Not for the bashful. Be prepared to hear complete medical
histories and get constant feedback on what works and what doesn't
work. _ _ Palm Beach County Library Reference Clerk
</P>
<P>
   Ah _ my career after my career! If after retirement my wife
needs to keep me out of the house, I can think of no happier
employment than fielding reference desk questions at the library. I
tried it for two hours. I liked it, even if I had to hand off the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take about 2,000 calls a month,'' said reference manager
Jane Craig at the Summit library. ``We get questions ranging from
side effects of medicines to grammar to finding a company that
certifies nuclear power plants.''
</P>
<P>
   One of my first callers wanted books on wolfhounds. With clerk
Janalee Garwood doing the computer search, we quickly found one
book on hand, and where others in the country could be located.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of humor can help when a child calls and asks an overly
general question:
</P>
<P>
   Child: ``Do you have information on elephants?''
</P>
<P>
   Librarian (with twinkle in voice): ``Certainly. Would you want
to know how to grow an elephant or cook one?''
</P>
<P>
   MHR: If you can't be a newspaper columnist, be a reference
librarian.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
