<HEADER>
A7069 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DORM-PRICES13-COX     06-12 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORM-PRICES13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Property values rising at private dorms near UT
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Private dorms near the University of Texas are among
the hottest properties in Austin, with some more than doubling in
value since last year, according to 1998 property appraisals.
</P>
<P>
   This could be bad news for students because higher appraisals
usually translate into higher taxes, and managers could raise rents
to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   The appraised value of Dobie Center, a high-rise dorm at 2021
Guadalupe St., more than doubled from $14.9 million last year to
$33 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   University Towers on 24th Street jumped from $13.6 million to
$23.1 million. The Castilian, at 2323 San Antonio St., increased 80
percent in value to $17.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the increase-- , according to Travis Central
Appraisal District officials who calculate property values for tax
purposes, is that several dorms have sold recently, drawing much
more than their value on the tax rolls. The Castilian, for example,
sold for about $17 million last year, while its appraised value was
$9.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the fact that the dorms have been notoriously full
in the past year, and property appraisers said it was more than
enough reason to take a second look at high-rise dorms near campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a resurgence in the dormitory market,'' said
appraiser Mary Kieke. ``Apartments have gotten so expensive,
students have come back to dorms. Many dorms have been full in the
past year, and operating incomes have been up.''
</P>
<P>
   The private dorms near UT haven't seen a significant increase in
value since the 1980s, before the recession and the bottoming-out
of the real estate market, Kieke said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorm managers and owners, shocked by the sharp rise in
appraisals, all say they will protest them. ``I just don't
understand how they came up with their figures,'' said Ugene Olson,
manager of the University Towers, which saw a 70 percent increase
in value over last year. ``I've been here since 1991, and there's
no way our income has doubled, yet they say we've increased more
than double in value.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, many students have signed leases for the fall and most
dorms have waiting lists. Rental rates at private dorms vary by the
kind of room and meal plan requested. The average starting rate for
next fall at large private dorms is about $6,500 per academic year.
</P>
<P>
   Students could face higher rents next year, if managers and
owners must pay more in taxes, which will happen if the tax rate
stays the same or increases for 1998. Olson said students have
already signed contracts locking in prices for next fall, but by
fall 1999, his rates could jump to make up the additional taxes. If
the tax rates stay the same, University Towers would be liable for
an additional $904 a day in taxes based on its new appraisal, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Dobie, starting rents for next fall have been set tentatively
at $6,200, but managers say they could raise them before classes
start. At the Castilian, managers say it's too early to tell
whether or not the dorm would have to raise its rent.
</P>
<P>
   Dabo Horsfall, a junior who is living at the Castilian this
summer, said students shouldn't be burdened with higher rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a college town, so I see why everything is high,'' he
said. ``But students are already paying enough. Many have to work
to pay their rent and go to school. They can't afford to pay
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Appraisal district officials say that dorm values have
fluctuated wildly over the years, depending on the boom and bust
cycle of real estate and the flow of students through UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the Dobie Center appraised anywhere from $6 million
to $26 million just over a few years,'' Kieke said. ``I think it's
safe to say the market is very cyclical.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
