<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7072 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTAH-JAZZ13-COX     06-12 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTAH-JAZZ13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't look to Jazz for sign of champion
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Utah Jazz are trying to remain upbeat despite
being one game from elimination.
</P>
<P>
   But even the Jazz must believe overcoming something nobody has
in the Finals, a 3-1 deficit, and doing it against the greatest
dynasty in sports in the past 30 years, the Chicago Bulls, is
almost impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought all season to be where we wanted to be and now we
get here and tend to slack off a little bit,'' center Greg Foster
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the sign of a true championship team.''.
</P>
<P>
   The sign of a true champion is burying an opponent when the time
is right, which is what the Bulls intend to do in Game 5 tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still see belief in their eyes, and we've got to take that
belief away from them,'' Michael Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to ... don't just stab them, but turn it once you
stick it in them.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest wound came during Game 3, the Bulls' record-breaking
42-point win.
</P>
<P>
   But trailing 2-1, Utah had one chance to recover in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Bulls all but put the champagne on ice with an 86-82
victory Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz are making excuses, saying they had chances to win
Games 2 and 4 and they could be the ones ahead 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   But those are excuses teams make when they see hope fading.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Utah had chances to win both games, but it was Jordan and
Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman who made the plays. Not John
Stockton and Karl Malone and Jeff Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, specifically, has failed to live up to his personal
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series, Malone said the outcome would depend on how
well the Jazz's big men performed. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   They have been awful.
</P>
<P>
   Malone refuses to give Rodman credit, but the fact is Rodman has
shut down Malone during the most crucial stages.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has a combined two points in the fourth quarters of Games
2 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is we can't be making our summer plans, this is
not over yet,'' Malone said. ``And then, second of all, you don't
want to make history.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Drawing the line: The Jazz, who led the league in free throws
made with 24.9 per game in the regular season, are averaging 13
during the Finals. Malone made 7.7 during the year and has 16 in
four Finals games.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who clearly has evaded taking the ball to the basket
when being guarded by Rodman, evaded the question Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about it, really,'' he said. When asked
specifically if it was a matter of him not driving, he said:
``Let's just say it's a matter of not going to the basket and leave
it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ No center lane: Adam Keefe started at center for the Jazz on
Wednesday, marking the third starter in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Foster started Games 1 and 2 and Greg Ostertag started Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our centers were really slow in reacting with what's happening
offensively and that's one of our main problems,'' Jazz coach Jerry
Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe was the most effective. Entering Game 4, Ostertag and
Foster had 12 fouls and six field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe had six points and seven rebounds in 20 minutes in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   _ Out of reach: OK, die-hard Bulls fans: How badly to you want
to see what could be Jordan's last game for Chicago's NBA
champions?
</P>
<P>
   Enough to take out a second mortgage?
</P>
<P>
   Enough to cancel your vacation?
</P>
<P>
   Enough to dip into the kids' college funds?
</P>
<P>
   A check with Chicago-area ticketbrokers found that what are
usually the cheap seats _ $40 each in the regular season _ are now
selling for $700. Moving down to the $90 seats will cost from
$1,200 to $1,600. Tickets for courtside seats _ with face values
ranging from $120 to $425 _ are going for $4,000 on average, but as
much as a whopping $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Easy to spot: Hairstyles and off-the-court interests aren't
the only things that set apart Jordan and Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Jud Buechler said you can look outside the team bus and
immediately tell which fans have turned out to see Jordan and which
are Rodman fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is the Elvis of the Underground. He brings some
creatures out from the night. That's his fan club,'' Buechler said,
laughing. ``Michael just has the regular All-American kids. You
never really see a good, clean-cut kid wearing a 91 jersey. And if
you do, you kind of shake your head on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, actress-director Penny Marshall was
sporting a Rodman jersey for Game 4 Wednesday at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
