<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: SKATEBOARDING, FLOWERS, NEWLYWED DATA, DESIGNER APRONS,
TRUFFLE SAUCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 14) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SALES ROLL ON
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hey dude, skateboarding's back. The National Sporting
Goods Association says skateboarding eclipsed mountain biking and
golf last year to become this country's fastest growing activity
for which you need sports equipment. Hurt in recent years by
in-line skating, skateboarding recovered strongly, with 6.3 million
skaters lurching through streets and parks last year, a 35.8
percent increase over the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The question is, why? Scott Kelliher, the director of marketing
for the New York-based Blades, Board and Skate shops, said that the
style and fashion associated with skateboarding has enhanced its
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are tons of small companies producing everything from
clothing, sneakers and watches to the boards themselves, which are
amazing,'' he said. He also attributed the resurgence to wider
exposure of the pastime (it doesn't sound right to call it a sport)
on television in ESPN's X-Games and in MTV Sports. ``Skateboarding
is beginning to show up everywhere, even in the Gap ads,'' Kelliher
added.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KIMBERLY STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   Flowery Greeters
</P>
<P>
   When Steven Spielberg and Donna Karan arrive at their East
Hampton, N.Y., retreats, after a long week in the film and fashion
trenches, they want to relax in rooms made welcoming by fresh-cut
flowers. But they're not in the mood to stop first at the village
florist, then mess with vases and unwieldy delphiniums.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Paul Goerz, who precedes them home on Friday afternoons
and fills rooms with delicate and romantic floral arrangements.
(Spielberg likes all white; Ms. Karan prefers colorful, theatrical
displays.)
</P>
<P>
   Goerz's business, A New Leaf, (516) 329-2646, charges $150 a
room. He's one of the new florists making house calls in the
Hamptons, where the notion of flowers used to be limited to
telegraphed carnations or zinnias from a farm stand.
</P>
<P>
   Mecox Gardens, (516) 287-5015, in Southampton, the most
elaborate service, charges about $1,500 a week to dress up a home
with fancy blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Potted Gardens, (516) 537-6235, which operates out of an
old-fashioned, ivy-covered shed in Bridgehampton, is known for its
countrified arrangements like roses with a few stalks of celery.
For about $250, weekly Potted Gardens customers get five vases of
flowers delivered _ plus coffee and the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ELENA KORNBLUTH
</P>
<P>
   Bridal Statistics
</P>
<P>
   Just in time for the June onslaught of dyed-to-match shoes, a
paperback of frank statistics on how people meet, marry and survive
the first year of nuptial bliss is arriving in bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a survey of 3,876 Americans who have been married an
average of 9.6 months, ``Just Married'' (Andrews McMeel Publishing,
$8.95) by Barry Sinrod and Marlo Grey offers amusing and sometimes
surprising data.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the belief that holding out on the sexual front
guarantees a mate, 17 percent of the respondents chose to
consummate their marriage on the first date. The spouses who say
``I love you'' least often to their partners are over 40 and
married for the first time. Those who say it the most are on their
third marriage, or more.
</P>
<P>
   In those rare unions in which the wife commands the television
remote control (15 percent), she has been previously married and
has an income of her own of at least $75,000. Of the men surveyed,
86 percent said they fell in love with their wives at first sight;
only 41 percent of the women said the same. Finally, if you believe
it's just as easy to marry a rich spouse as a poor one, keep in
mind that those who earn more than $75,000 took an average of two
years to make a commitment after the first meeting. That's bad news
for the 1 percent who said they married for a single reason: money.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Wear It or Frame It
</P>
<P>
   Richard Karnatz is an artist who may not have made it into the
Whitney Museum of American Art, but at least his barbecue aprons
are in the Whitney Museum's Store. Printed with 1950s images of
what he calls ``fashion girls,'' his four cotton-duck aprons cost
$40 each at the Whitney, Madison Avenue at 74th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started the business by making a new apron for myself to
wear in my print shop,'' said Karnatz, a fine-arts printer who owns
Bent Fish Editions in Manhattan. ``All my clients wanted them, so I
started giving them out as promotional gifts _ even to potential
clients like Chuck Close.'' Karnatz's own silk-screened artworks
are on show at Bendix Diner (First Avenue at 10th Street).
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks he'll be huge someday might want to collect
the apron series.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MARIANNE ROHRLICH
</P>
<P>
   Molten Delirium
</P>
<P>
   On the hunt for a special and much-appreciated house gift, one
that will keep the invitations rolling in?
</P>
<P>
   Consider a jar of truffle sauce from Charbonnel et Walker, the
London chocolatier established in 1875 and a fixture of the luxury
row of Bond Street. Until recently, only those jetting back and
forth to Britain could enjoy the decadent chocolate sauces in
flavors like Cognac and Grand Marnier. But since September,
Bergdorf Goodman has carried them in its specialty-foods department
for $20 a jar.
</P>
<P>
   Drambo Villar, a sales associate, said they are hard to keep on
the shelves. ``We've had great success with Europeans and the
traveling types who know the brand,'' he said. ``It's an insider
thing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy them with ice cream, fruit or sorbet, preferably on a
summer-house patio.
</P>
<P>
   _ By KIMBERLY STEVENS &QL;
</P>
