<HEADLINE>
JAPAN HAS SLID INTO RECESSION, NEW DATA CONFIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.)  
 (bl)  
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The world's second-largest economy sank at a stunning
annual rate of 5.3 percent in the first quarter of this year,
according to official figures released Friday that painted an even
bleaker picture than many economists had expected.
</P>
<P>
   While Japan's economy has been troubled for many months, the
latest official numbers confirmed that economic output has declined
for two consecutive quarters _ the definition generally accepted by
economists for a recession. In addition, they showed that for the
first time since the oil shock of 1974, the economy actually
declined for a full year _ falling by 0.7 percent for the fiscal
year ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Such dismal numbers contributed to a further fall in the yen,
sent shock waves throughout Asia and heightened fears that the
economic crisis could spread from Asia to the United States and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials took care to release Friday's news after the
stock market had closed for the day. Earlier, driven largely by the
declining yen, South Korea's stock market fell by 8 percent Friday,
while the Nikkei 225 benchmark index dipped below 15,000 in the
morning, before closing at 15,022.33, up 8.29 points.
</P>
<P>
   The weaker yen makes Japanese products cheaper and more
competitive, further damaging the economies of its East Asian
neighbors, triggering a relentless spiral of currency devaluations,
and destabilizing financial markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the United States thus far has been mixed, with
consumers benefiting from cheaper imports and lower interest rates
made possible, in part, by the slowdown in Asia. But U.S. corporate
profits have declined recently, in part because of the contraction
in Asian markets. There is fear as well that continued financial
decline in Japan and East Asia could trigger a panic that would
spread to the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials again warned Friday that the yen is falling
too far and too fast. It now takes about 144 yen to buy one dollar,
meaning that the yen has fallen 80 percent since its peak in 1995.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will cause a minus effect on the Japanese
economy, `` Koji Omi, head of the Economic Planning Agency, said of
the weak yen Friday, according to Kyodo News Service. But it poses
problems, he added, ``for the whole of the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Mobile, Ala., on Friday, U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin characterized the economic data as ``worse than
expected.'' He reiterated his view that Japan needs to embrace
fundamental reforms of its financial structure and to vigorously
stimulate its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Economies are slumping throughout Asia as well as in Russia and
Eastern Europe, he said, adding that ``the center of the problem is
in Japan, and it's a very serious problem for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Li Zhaoxing, China's ambassador to the United States, called
upon the Group of Seven industrialized nations and Japan to take
action to bolster the yen. ``They know their situation, they know
they have means available,'' Li said. ``If there's a will, there's
a way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists believe that Japan's economy may recover in the
short term, in part because of a huge fiscal stimulus package that
will begin to be felt in the next few weeks. But others warn that
Japan is itself teetering on the edge of a much greater tumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things could fall apart very quickly here and Japan could go
like other countries in Asia _ completely fall apart, or it could
linger on,'' said Brian Rose, an economist at LTCB Warburg
Securities Ltd., a joint venture between Long-Term Credit Bank and
SBC Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Rose cautioned that Japan is now in the throes of an
unpredictable transition to more of a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Eastern Europe, if you introduce shock therapy and go
from a non-market to a market, the short term disruption is
enormous,'' Rose said. He added, however, that once the transition
is made, Japan could be poised for strong growth again.
</P>
<P>
   Shimpei Nukaya, vice minister of the Economic Planning Agency,
which released the economic numbers, said that the negative impact
on Japan's economy from the Asian economic crisis was bigger than
the government had expected and that the figures ``underline the
gloomy situation of the national's real economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sluggish for several years, Japan's economy fell into a
recessionary spiral on the impetus of a tax increase last year,
imposed at a moment when the economy instead required a stimulus,
in the view of many economists, who believe that no adequate fiscal
stimulus has yet been applied.
</P>
<P>
   Sales are down at many medium-sized businesses, and Mom-and-Pop
shops are particularly feeling the pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no customers, even at this hour,'' said Yasuhiko Sato,
a 30-year-old vendor selling tuna fish during lunchtime. ``I see
shops closing down in this area. My bonus is very low. It's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Teikoku Databank, a private credit research agency, said Friday
that the number of corporate failures in May rose 37.5 percent from
a year ago to 1,791. It was the highest total for the month of May
since 1984.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
