<P>
   GM _ By this time next week, a labor dispute may shut down the
vast North American operations of the world's No. 1 automaker. As
the body count swells from the United Auto Workers strikes in
Flint, Mich., the local economic fallout has begun. If the strike
continues and more local plants shut down, look for retail,
restaurants and other sectors of our economy to suffer. (Drummond,
Dayton Daily News) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DOWDOW _ Wall Street's rediscovery of Asia's problems,
exacerbated by confirmation that Japan was in a recession last
year, drags stocks down again. The Dow is off 11 points, while the
Nasdaq is down more sharply percentage wise, at 1.7 percent. When
the correction will end is anybody's guess. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   5DAYS-5JOBS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ After working five jobs in
five days to see how the other half earn their daily bread, I
thought of the old joke about the eager college grad's first day on
the job when his boss shoves a broom into his hands. ``But I just
spent four years in college,'' the young man protests. ``Oh, yeah,
that's right,'' apologizes the boss. ``Here, I'll show you how.''
(Wiggins, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DORM-PRICES _ AUSTIN _ Private dorms near the University of
Texas are among the hottest properties in Austin, with some more
than doubling in value since last year, according to 1998 property
appraisals. This could be bad news for students because higher
appraisals usually translate into higher taxes, and managers could
raise rents to compensate. (Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
