<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-ARAB-COX </SLUG>
     RENO URGES LOWERING HURDLES TO FEDERAL
PROSECUTION OF HATE CRIMES
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Friday urged the
federal government to respond when ``hate speaks out'' by
eliminating ``hurdles'' that prevent the prosecution of hate crimes
to the fullest degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen in Jasper, Texas, an example that hate and
bigotry in its worst and most tragic form is still with us,'' Reno
told the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee's national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   In what has been labeled a hate crime, James Byrd Jr. was
dragged, dismembered, and decapitated by three white men near
Jasper last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us can relax when that happens,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno blamed current federal law for preventing ``the most
heinous crimes'' from being prosecuted. The federal civil rights
statute deals with hate crimes only if they involve the use of
force based on a person's race, color, religion or national origin
and if they interfere with certain federally protected activities,
such as attending a school that receives federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Reno said, the federal government can prosecute a
racially motivated crime ``if it occurs in the parking lot of a
public school but not if it occurs across the street in the private
yard of a family home.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno endorsed legislation sponsored by Sens. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass. and Arlen Specter, R-Pa. that would punish any attack that
caused injury and was based on race, ethnicity or religion,
regardless of whether federally protected activities were involved.
The bill would also add sexual orientation, gender and disability
to the list of motivations that define hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hate Crime Act of 1998 was also endorsed Friday by Kweisi
Mfume, president of the National Association for Advancement of
Colored People, who said that ``Congress should waste no time in
passing this much-needed legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate is still a destructive force in America and requires the
strongest sanctions and penalties that the law can provide,'' Mfume
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she is forming a task force that would bring nearly
federal 100 attorneys nationwide to work with state enforcement
agencies to address the issue of hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, 8,759 hate crimes were reported to federal
agencies in 1996, with 5,396 of the incidents based on race.
</P>
<P>
   Reno speech also addressed the topics of diversity and Arab
American concerns of being ``targeted'' by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer period dominated by the subject of
alleged ``targeting'' of Arabs and Muslims by the Justice
Department, Reno said she would review concerns involving an
Immigration and Naturalization Service practice of deporting
immigrants it deems has political affiliations based on secret
evidence. Reno is facing a lawsuit pending before the Supreme Court
on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are losing their lives while they're
incarcerated,'' said Sarah Alfadl, a Pennsylvania attorney who said
that her client _ detained in Florida on the basis of secret
evidence _ suffers from post-traumatic stress disorder and ``may
die in custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who said she recognized that the Justice Department
relationship with Arabs and Muslims may have been ``troubled'' in
the past, said her office was ``committed to a new and better
understanding'' of the Arab American community.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
