<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, June 13. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (London) _ Group of Eight meet to discuss the
Balkans and the South Asia nuclear crisis. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Removing any lingering doubts that Japan is
in a full-blown recession, the Finance Ministry said that the
economy contracted at a 5.3 percent annual rate in the year's first
quarter. Compared with the prior three months, the decline in gross
domestic product was 1.3 percent, faster than the contraction in
1997's final three months. It was the first time in six years that
Japan had recorded two consecutive quarterly declines. By Sheryl
WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-THEATER (New York) _ New York City's last
Chinese-language theater, the Music Palace, will soon take its
final bow, its faded three-story structure to be demolished and
replaced by a gleaming office building. The growing popularity of
videotapes is partly to blame, along with Chinese cable TV programs
and other options for staying in touch with the homeland. But the
theater's passing is also a small milestone in the story of the
Chinese in America, a shift toward the mainstream that recalls the
experience of Italians, Jews, Puerto Ricans, and other newcomers
who once had thriving theaters, too. By David Chen.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OCEANS (Monterey, Calif.) _ Clinton, navigating a narrow
course between environmentalists and oil companies, announced on
Friday a 10-year extension on the current moratorium on oil
drilling off virtually all American coastlines. Clinton also placed
several existing marine sanctuaries permanently off-limits to oil
exploration. The moratorium does not, however, affect the extensive
drilling activity off the Texas and Louisiana Coast, nor does it
protect any new areas not already covered by the drilling ban first
imposed by President Bush in 1990. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-MOMS (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ As more mothers of young
children run for office, they are finding that the issue of
motherhood cuts both ways with voters. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TECHNOLOGY (Washington) _ Powerful evidence emerges that
China has been using American technology for military purposes,
taking advantage of the Bush and Clinton Administrations' decisions
to encourage high technology sales in Asia and apparently in
contradiction to the U.S. ban on sales of military equipment to
China. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-JUDGE-DELAY (Washington) _ Republicans explain their
strategy in delaying a Federal judgeship, providing a peek inside
the intense and often byzantine politics that occur unseen behind
judicial nominations. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
