<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES 3 MANAGERS ARE BETTER THAN 1  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (af) 
 By CAROLE GOULD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One hot industry trend _ some would say fad _ is the
concentrated fund: an offering that holds 30 or so stocks instead
of the typical 100 or more. Another is the so-called all-star fund,
in which several high-profile managers each run a slice of a
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the two and _ bingo _ you start another trend, funds in
which two or more star managers run a concentrated portfolio. Sun
America Asset Management and Prudential Securities just unveiled
two such funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sun America's Style Select Series Focus Portfolio combines the
top 10 stock picks of three high-powered fund managers: Elizabeth
Bramwell of Bramwell Capital Management, Thomas Marsico of Marsico
Capital Management and Spiros Segalas of Jennison Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential's 20/20 Focus fund drafts Segalas to pick his
favorite 20 growth stocks and combines those picks with 20 value
stocks selected by Thomas R. Jackson, who manages the Prudential
Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   Such combination funds would appear to address two pressing
shortages in today's markets: a dwindling supply of smart
investment ideas and a dearth of management talent.
</P>
<P>
   Fund companies are putting the same handful of people on an
ever-growing number of dance cards. Sun America Style Select Focus,
for example, brings the number of offerings that Marsico has a hand
in running to five. Segalas has his fingers in Masters Select
Equity, an all-star fund, and runs Harbor Capital Appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   Will such managers be overworked? In the case of Segalas, Tim
Biggs, a spokesman for Prudential Securities, said: ``Absolutely
not. His firm is built on running multiple portfolios, first for
institutions and then for individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Independent analysts champion the trend, too _ with a caveat.
``I think they're a great idea because there are a lot of very
talented portfolio managers being forced to invest only in their
best ideas,'' said Susan Dziubinski, who edits the newsletter
Morningstar Fund Investor. ``The downside is that most of these
funds are very concentrated, which can produce outsized gains but
also very large losses.''
</P>
<P>
   But J. Steven Neamtz, executive vice president of Sun America
Asset Management, said the multimanager approach reduced the risk
of concentrated portfolios. ``Usually, you'd get one mind-set in 30
picks. Here, you get three points of view, which provide a certain
amount of diversification in a focused fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bramwell's eponymous fund, Bramwell Growth, returned an
annual average of 25.6 percent, compared with 24.4 percent for its
large-growth peers, from its August 1994 inception through June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Segalas' Harbor Capital Appreciation rose 20.7 percent a year,
on average, from its December 1987 inception through June 5, versus
16.5 percent for its large-growth peers.
</P>
<P>
   Marsico ran Janus 20 from its March 1988 inception through July
1997, when he left Janus Capital to start his own firm. In that
time, the fund returned 22.5 percent, annualized, versus 16.2
percent for its large-growth group, Morningstar said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jackson started at Prudential Equity in April 1990, it
returned 16.8 percent a year, on average, through June 5, compared
with 15.4 percent for the average large-cap value fund.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will pay for this stock-picking expertise. Sun
America's fund carries a maximum initial sales charge of 5.75
percent. Prudential's fund charges a like load of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Here's a different kind of price tag for a no-load mutual fund.
To buy the new Waterhouse Investors Dow 30 fund, investors are
required to open a brokerage account at Waterhouse Securities, a
discount brokerage firm based in Manhattan, although the account
can be as little as the fund's $1,000 minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``People generally do more than one type of investment,'' said
Frank Petrilli, chief executive of the brokerage's parent,
Waterhouse Investor Services, in explaining the firm's strategy.
``Eventually, they will buy or sell stocks or options and have a
relationship with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which became available to investors last month, now
has $14.5 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Why open a brokerage account to buy shares of a no-load fund?
One reason is that there aren't too many Dow funds out there. The
only pure Dow index fund tracked by Morningstar is ASM Index 30,
whose performance has lagged significantly behind the index since
its March 1991 inception. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
