<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-MOMS-(1,000)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT NEW ISSUE ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL: MOTHERHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Maine, Mass., N.Y., Calif., La., Wash., Ohio)  (mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ Even in the friendly crowd at an afternoon
coffee, where three generations of women were gathered around a
silver punch bowl, talking politics in between bites of ham roll,
the Senate candidate Blanche Lambert Lincoln heard the usual
question: ``Do you see hubby and the babies at all?''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate smiled and explained, again, how her husband is
really supportive and her 2-year-old twins, Bennett and Reece, are
doing fine. In 1996, just after learning she was having twins, Mrs.
Lincoln announced she would leave the House of Representatives to
be at home full time. Now that she wants to go back to Washington
with a promotion, her mothering has become an issue in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who think she should stay home,'' especially
because she once said that was the plan, said Stephanie Cohen, of
Emily's List, a Democratic group that promotes and finances female
candidates. But as more mothers of young children run for office,
they are finding that the issue cuts both ways with voters, many
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln campaign has done no polling on the motherhood
factor, but the candidate and her staff say they sense a concern
among many voters over how she will juggle her roles. A moderate
Democrat who talks about fraud and waste in government, Mrs.
Lincoln is constantly asked to explain herself as a mother, and
even to provide the details of her child-care arrangements, in a
way that male candidates with young families are not.
</P>
<P>
   But voters seem satisfied once they hear the specifics of her
plans, which involves moving her family en masse to Washington,
where her physician-husband will relocate his practice, she said.
And the fact that she has children seems to be helping her more
than it is hurting, according to political handicappers.
</P>
<P>
   She easily beat Winston Bryant, the Arkansas attorney general,
winning 63 percent of the vote in a Tuesday runoff, and is widely
expected to win in the fall over the Republican candidate, Fay
Boozman. At the same recent party where she was asked when she sees
her family, another woman gave Mrs. Lincoln a hug and said: ``From
one mother to another, I'm so glad you're running. That's why I
want you there.''
</P>
<P>
   While much of the criticism of Mrs. Lincoln's candidacy seems to
come from older women, younger women tend to identify with Mrs.
Lincoln _ and love the idea that she could spend a couple of years
at home and then go back to work as a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   She has made her children a focal point of the campaign. She
carries her brag book of snapshots with her at all times. A
television commercial shows her in various maternal poses,
overseeing mealtime, balancing one child on her hip, bouncing one
on her knee, and then, perhaps in need of rest, laying her head on
the shoulder of her husband, Steve Lincoln, a fertility doctor.
(``Daughter, wife, mother, congresswoman,'' the voice-over says.
``Living our rock-solid Arkansas values.'') On a recent day spent
campaigning, Mrs. Lincoln received dozens of neighborly queries
about her children, and few other questions.
</P>
<P>
   Her hostess at the coffee, Martha Wall, an elegant 79-year-old
whom Mrs. Lincoln described in a whisper as `a quintessential steel
magnolia,'' said that she, for one, did not question Mrs. Lincoln's
ambitions. ``I never liked housekeeping that much myself,'' Mrs.
Wall said with a small smile.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, women have entered politics relatively late in
life, as did former Rep. Millicent Fenwick of New Jersey and former
Sen. Margaret Chase Smith of Maine. Only in about the last five
years have significant numbers of women like Mrs. Lincoln, who is
37, begun running for office while still of childbearing age, said
Elizabeth Sherman, director of the Center for Women in Politics and
Public Policy at the McCormack Institute at the University of
Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While the hot-button topic of a mother's place in the workplace
is being played out in every profession, politics is the only one
in which the general public gets to vote on the outcome. And though
no race can be seen as a direct referendum on the issue, recent
elections do suggest that mothers on the stump often stir intense
interest and debate, yet motherhood in itself appears to be no
barrier to a political career, even when the candidate's children
are small. ``So many women with young kids are working,'' Ms.
Sherman said, ``that voters can relate.''
</P>
<P>
   When the late Sonny Bono's mother said her 7- and 10-year-old
grandchildren ``would essentially become orphans open to abuse by
strangers'' if her daughter-in-law, Mary Bono, was elected to fill
his congressional seat, the uproar that followed ultimately created
a backlash that worked in Mary Bono's favor. She won an April
special election with 64 percent of the vote over the Democrat,
Ralph Waite, the actor who once played the patriarch on TV's ``The
Waltons.''
</P>
<P>
   After former Rep. Susan Molinari, a New York Republican turned
television commentator, gave birth in 1996, she was accused of
using her daughter, Susan Ruby, as a family-friendly prop, and
criticized for keeping her up late to hear mother speak at the
Republican convention. (And what was that clear liquid Grandpa was
feeding her when the cameras cut to him?) But the premise of the
criticism is that voters respond favorably to seeing an elected
official with her baby. And Ms. Molinari's seat, even in a
conservative district, was presumably hers for life until she gave
it up for television.
</P>
<P>
   There are 15 mothers with children who are school-age or younger
in Congress, compared with just one as recently as six years ago.
In 1974, Yvonne Braithwaite Burke of California became the first
member of Congress to give birth while in office. But in the last
few years, there has been something of a congressional baby
boomlet, beginning in 1995, with Enid Greene, a Utah Republican who
was only the second congresswoman to give birth. Molinari and Mrs.
Lincoln had children in 1996, and last year, Sen. Mary Landrieu,
D-La., adopted a baby.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Patricia Schroeder, the Colorado Democrat, said that
when she was elected to the House in 1972, when her children were
ages 2 and 6, ``Even Bella Abzug called me when I won and said, `I
don't know how you're going to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., was elected
after campaigning as ``a mom in tennis shoes.'' She ignored
advisers who warned her to soft-pedal the fact that she had
children, arguing that she was running because of her 12- and
15-year-old children, not in spite of them. Female candidates now
routinely play up their domestic experience.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Tubbs Jones, a Democrat running for Congress in Ohio,
says she talks about her eighth-grade son every chance she gets.
``It seems to be a plus that here's a working mother,'' Mrs. Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day spent campaigning, Mrs. Lincoln prompted those
few who did not ask about her boys: ``Have y'all seen my babies?''
</P>
<P>
   At the Randolph County Courthouse, Mrs. Lincoln received the
star treatment from the mostly female employees, who obviously
liked her _ and seemed to appreciate the Hollywood-style storyline
of her life: A farmer's daughter, Mrs. Lincoln worked at
secretarial jobs and later became a Washington lobbyist before
beating Rep. Bill Alexander, for whom she had worked as a
receptionist, in her first race at age 31. (She recalls that when
she told her old boss she was running, he laughed and said, ``Why
not run for the Senate?'')
</P>
<P>
   The female clerks repeatedly told her they were ``so proud'' of
her, and she more than returned the favor, thanking them for
keeping the machinery of local government cranking.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Mrs. Lincoln said, she is a traditional woman, a
wife who ``always just expected to take my husband's name.'' But
she says she felt isolated at home, and quit Congress two years ago
mostly because she worried about campaigning in the heat of an
Arkansas summer during a high-risk pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   None of her opponents has been critical of her comeback, though
she suggests that a fellow Democrat, Scott Ferguson, a West Memphis
radiologist, had raised the issue obliquely by saying that, of all
his titles, ``Dad'' means the most. (Ferguson said he would not
dare. ``My wife is a dentist and we've got a family,'' he said,
adding that he had, however, heard such complaints from voters.)
</P>
<P>
   Her Republican opponent, Dr. Boozman, a 51-year-old eye surgeon
and state senator, best known as the lead sponsor of last year's
state legislation banning the procedure known as partial birth
abortion, does not plan to make her motherhood an issue. Boozman is
a religious conservative who attends the same church as his friend,
Sen. Tim Hutchinson, in their hometown of Rogers, and is generally
considered a long shot in the race.
</P>
<P>
   John Brummett, a columnist for The Arkansas Democrat Gazette,
said, ``You hear people say, `What kind of baloney is this, running
as a family candidate two years after you said you had to leave
Congress because you were having twins?' But generally, having two
gorgeous babies in your TV advertisements works to your benefit.''
Brummett has criticized Mrs. Lincoln for other reasons, saying she
is not on a par with the retiring Democratic senator, Dale Bumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to believe that John doesn't like women,'' Mrs.
Lincoln said of Brummett.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate herself is not completely uncritical of other
women's decisions on balancing parenting and politics. When asked
about Jane Swift, the pregnant candidate for lieutenant governor in
Massachusetts, Mrs. Lincoln was quiet for a moment, then asked
whether hers was a planned pregnancy. And she assailed Ms.
Molinari's decision to take her baby to a political convention: ``I
don't like to put them in situations that frighten them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Lincoln said she figures the debate about whether women
can simultaneously focus on potty-training and NATO expansion will
go on for some time. ``It's going to be hard for a while,'' she
said, ``until more women begin to support each other in the
different ways we do things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
