u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOFFA-HNS &LR;      06-12 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFA CONTINUES TO BUILD COALITION IN QUEST TO LEAD THE TEAMSTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC BRAZIL 
c.1998 San Francisco Examiner 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ With his adversaries in disarray, James P.
Hoffa looks vastly more relaxed and confident these days than
during his first fractious run for the Teamsters Union presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of attacking Ron Carey, who edged him in a tainted 1996
election that has since been voided, Hoffa is talking unity as he
stumps the country in an effort to win the office his father, James
R. Hoffa, held for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This union can never be great again as long as it's totally
divided,'' Hoffa said Thursday between bites of a bran muffin at a
diner in Berkeley. ``People everywhere want to end the infighting
so that we can rededicate ourselves to delivering for our
members.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 campaign for the presidency of the 1.4 million-member
Teamsters was memorably nasty. Carey defeated Hoffa by 4 percentage
points, but his victory was overturned by federal oversight
officials, who said Carey participated in a plan to divert union
funds to his campaign treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, a lawyer, has been campaigning nonstop for the Teamsters
presidency for the better part of four years. ``I've shaken more
hands than my father ever did,'' he said. Hoffa claims to have won
over the leaders of more than a dozen Teamsters locals who
supported Carey for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have switched is Mike McLaughlin, secretary
treasurer of Local 856 in San Francisco. ``Hoffa wants to end the
divisions that have really hurt us,'' McLaughlin said. ``He will
recognize the fact that we've made reforms here, and he's given us
his assurance that he supports us. We've just got to end the
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa continues to hammer the Carey administration for draining
the treasury of the nation's biggest private-sector union. Carey's
reformers ``give reform a bad name ... They were deficit spending
for five years, and that's why we're in a financial shambles, on
the verge of bankruptcy, at rock bottom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots will be mailed to Teamsters members Sept. 14 and voting
will begin Oct. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa is seen as the front-runner against Tom Leedham, who is
head of a Teamsters local in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZWEEK-ART-$ADV14-NY     06-12 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZWEEK-ART-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14) 
(af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Charging Into Reverse
</P>
<P>
   No one else has had the power to move markets in recent years
the way Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, has. With the
merest hint that the central bank might need to take aim at
inflation, the markets ducked for cover.
</P>
<P>
   But last week he signaled to investors that he saw no immediate
need to strike against inflation by raising interest rates, telling
the Joint Economic Committee of Congress that ``the current
economic performance, with its combination of strong growth and low
inflation, is as impressive as any I have witnessed in my near
half-century of daily observation of the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happened on Wall Street? The stock market ducked for
cover. The Dow Jones industrial average ended the week at 8,834.94,
down 202.77 points. But the bond market surged, sending government
bond yields to their lowest levels in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Retail Sales Climb &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department said its Producer Price Index rose 0.2
percent in May, reflecting higher prices for energy and
prescription drugs. That followed an identical increase in April.
... With an assist from the strongest new-car sales in 15 months,
retail sales rose a stronger-than-expected 0.9 percent last month,
to a seasonally adjusted $224.62 billion, the Commerce Department
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The gain, the seventh in a row, exceeded private economists'
forecasts of a rise of 0.7 percent. ... If a bill passed by the
House becomes law, retailers may even be paid for all those sales.
The bankruptcy laws would be tightened, making it far more
difficult to buy now and escape paying later.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO
</P>
<P>
   A Bill (and Its Largess) Advance
</P>
<P>
   If a middle-income husband and wife both smoke, their outlook is
win some, lose some, financially at least. Employing a certain
inside-the-Beltway logic, the Senate voted to use part of the money
that would be raised from higher cigarette prices to give an
income-tax break to married couples with annual incomes below
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was billed as fighting the income tax code's
marriage penalty; the vote gave additional strength to anti-smoking
legislation that has been before the Senate for three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also voted to use some of the cigarette money on
drug-abuse programs. ... In a setback to the tobacco industry, a
Florida jury found Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco liable for a smoker's
death and ordered the company to pay $1 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS
</P>
<P>
   At GM, Strikes and Layoffs
</P>
<P>
   Angry over what they called unmet demands for job security,
hundreds of striking workers chanted ``U.A.W.!'' and toted red
placards at the gate of a General Motors spark-plug factory in
Flint, Mich., joining striking workers from a metal-stamping
factory.
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly bitter fight could lead GM, the world's largest
auto maker, to close most of its North American assembly plants
within days. GM has already closed seven assembly plants and
temporarily laid off 18,600 workers for lack of parts, and it could
temporarily lay off up to 200,000 more workers. ... Honda and Ford
endured a multimillion-dollar embarrassment, agreeing to pay
millions of dollars in federal fines for selling cars that were
designed to pass emissions tests but were certain to run
substantially dirtier on the road.
</P>
<P>
   THE FDA
</P>
<P>
   Taking Aim at Supplements
</P>
<P>
   In a case to be heard Monday in federal court in Salt Lake City,
the Food and Drug Administration is waging a pivotal battle against
the fast-growing dietary supplement industry, which is not subject
to the same rigorous requirements for scientific testing as the
drug industry.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is Chinese red yeast sold in this country by Pharmanex
under the name Cholestin to lower cholesterol. The FDA calls the
product, which is sold in both health food outlets and the giant
Wal-Mart chain, an illegal, unapproved drug because it contains an
ingredient, lovastatin, that is the key component of the
cholesterol-lowering drug Mevacor, made by Merck.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sues Intel
</P>
<P>
   The FTC filed antitrust charges against the chip maker, accusing
it of threatening and injuring three computer makers, including
Compaq, the leading maker of personal computers, to coerce them to
turn over rights to patented technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Intel disagreed. ... Boeing said it would cut production of its
wide-body 747 aircraft next year because of slow growth in Asia.
And the company said that starting this year it would eliminate
more jobs than the 12,000 previously announced. ... Nabisco
announced a $524 million reorganization plan that will include
factory closings and the layoffs of more than 3,000 of its 53,000
employees. ... Controversy swirled around a $42 million golden
parachute that William Catacosinos received as New York state
partly took over Long Island Lighting Co., the troubled utility he
led. He is now chief executive of Marketspan, the successor
company.
</P>
<P>
   BANKS
</P>
<P>
   Deal After Deal
</P>
<P>
   Norwest and Wells Fargo agreed to a $34 billion merger, the
latest in a string of blockbuster unions that have created a cadre
of giants and a few dozen also-rans in the once-sleepy banking
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The banks' merger frenzy has been driven by stalled revenue
growth and heightened competition from mutual funds, brokerage
firms and credit card companies. ... Credit Suisse First Boston
bought Brazil's leading investment bank, Garantia SA, for $675
million, making the Swiss-American group the largest underwriter
and stock trader in that hotly competitive emerging market.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   A Warning From the IMF
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has told the Russian government that it needs to slash
its budget deficit and overhaul its antiquated tax system if it is
to qualify for billions of dollars in extra loans, senior Russian
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fund officials also want Russia to strengthen its banking system
and have suggested that the operations of Gazprom, the huge natural
gas monopoly, be split up. In one move aimed at improving its tax
picture, the Russian government arrested the head of the state
committee for statistics, Yuri Yurkov, and his top deputies and
accused them of manipulating data to help Russian companies avoid
taxes. Adding to the unrest, miners from the Vorkuta region, who
have not been paid in four months, protested in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   A Pervasive Gloom
</P>
<P>
   Asia's financial crisis appears to be turning into the most
serious region-wide recession since the end of World War II,
leaving investors throughout Asia as deflated as these two Tokyo
currency traders.
</P>
<P>
   Japan announced its first year of economic contraction since
1974, confirming that it is in a severe recession. Gross domestic
product for the fiscal year ended March 31 shrank by 0.7 percent;
for the January-March quarter the shrinkage was 1.3 percent,
following a 0.4 percent drop in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong, Malaysia and Indonesia have all confirmed that their
economies shrank in the first quarter and are likely to keep
contracting, and South Korea and Thailand are also in retreat. The
culprit in the latest slide is the Japanese yen, which has fallen
to an eight-year low against the American dollar, ending the week
at 144.72, with predictions it could drop further. Stock markets
throughout Asia have plunged along with the yen, with Bangkok's
market at its lowest level in 10 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
