<SLUG> BC-RAC-COMEBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM RETURNS TO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One week after the Triple Crown series ended in a classic finish
in the Belmont Stakes, older horses will follow the 3-year-olds
into the spotlight Saturday: Silver Charm returns to action at
Churchill Downs in the $750,000 Stephen Foster Handicap, and Ordway
and Behrens are among a full field of 13 in the $300,000 Brooklyn
Handicap at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, who won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness last
year, returns at age 4 with a three-race winning streak that he
capped in March with the $4 million Dubai World Cup. In the Stephen
Foster, he will face six rivals, including his stablemate Semoran
and Awesome Again, who won the Jim Dandy Stakes at Saratoga last
August.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, who has finished first or second in all 13 of his
starts, has been made the 3-5 favorite even though he is giving
away 12 to 18 pounds for the mile and an eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have him cranked up full steam,'' said his
trainer, Bob Baffert, speaking from his barn at Churchill Downs in
Louisville, Ky. ``But win, lose or draw, he's going to get a good
race out of it. I don't expect him to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   At Belmont Park, two comeback campaigns and a purse of $300,000
will be riding on the outcome of the Brooklyn Handicap, the middle
race in New York's Handicap Triple for older horses. The series
opened on May 25 with the Metropolitan Mile, which was won by Wild
Rush, who was not nominated for the Brooklyn. The third and final
event is the Suburban Handicap on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback horses are Ordway and Behrens, a pair of
4-year-olds whose careers have taken detours. Ordway looked like a
Kentucky Derby contender last year, running second in the Gotham
and fourth in the Wood Memorial. But he came down with an infection
and missed most of the summer. Last month, he raced for the first
time in six months and won an allowance race on Belmont Park's
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to go out looking for Skip Away or Silver Charm
because Ordway isn't up to that,'' said his trainer, David Donk.
``But this could be another good step on his road back.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens is not looking for Skip Away or Silver Charm, either; in
his last four starts, he has been outrun by one champion or the
other. After winning the Pegasus last September, he ran seventh to
Skip Away in the Breeders' Cup Classic, seventh to Skip Away in the
Donn, third to Skip Away in the Gulfstream Park Handicap and fifth
to Silver Charm in the Dubai World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But Behrens and Ordway should get plenty of action from Frisk Me
Now, the favorite, and Acceptable, Sir Bear and Subordination. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
