u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-REVIEW-BLOO-N     06-12 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-BLOO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLOO REVIEW': A MERRY RETURN TO MUSIC HALL
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By PETER MARKS     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That husky warble, those hairy legs! He absolutely is
Lady Bracknell.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Bette Bourne, the gentle heart and soul of Bloolips, the
illustrious British drag troupe, rides the Oscar Wilde popularity
wave in ``Bloo Review,'' the company's charmingly ditzy new show at
Theater for the New City. Rigidly upright in a chair, as imperious
an actress as one of those grandes dames of yore, Bette performs a
scene from ``The Importance of Being Earnest'' with an almost
terrifying technical dexterity.
</P>
<P>
   Bette is, in fact, Edith Evans on a male hormone regimen. ``Do
you smoke? I'm glad to hear it,'' Bette says, the consonants
enunciated so crisply each sounds as if it could snap. ``A man
should have an occupation of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bloo Review,'' the scene from ``Earnest'' counts as
highbrow theater. In inimitable Bloolips fashion, the show is a
merry return to the music hall, albeit a daintier music hall than
the one in which Archie Rice gallivanted in ``The Entertainer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you normally work in shifts?'' Bette purrs to the evening's
co-star, Precious Pearl (the actor Paul Shaw).
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I usually find them more comfortable,'' hisses Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a return to material Bloolips has performed before.
(Thus the evening's subtitle, ``A Bloolips Retrospectacle.'') The
comedy, intermingled with musical numbers evoking Noel Coward's
London of the 1940s and '50s, is all in an extremely loopy vein.
That Bette and Precious Pearl begin and end the show as chickens
and eggs (hatchlings for the opening; sunny side up for the finale)
should give some sense of the silliness quotient.
</P>
<P>
   You can see in the harmless lampoons by Bloolips, which over the
years has developed a loyal following in New York, the inspiration
for Howard Crabtree's drag productions. Irony is kept to a blessed
minimum. Some of the best gags fly on the flimsiest premises, as,
for instance, when Bette, with the help of his dressers, suits up
as Marie Antoinette to the strains of the 1812 Overture.
</P>
<P>
   A spoof of ``Brief Encounter'' in which a problem in a nasal
passage leads to romance, is a high point, as is the rendition of a
signature Bloolips song, ``Why Must the Frock Go On?,'' which
features Bette in a batwing-sleeved dress fringed with tea
strainers.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few lulls in the evening; occasional jokes and skits
targeting Prime Minister Tony Blair don't have much oomph. Still,
few troupes make playing dress-up such an agreeable cabaret.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Bloo Review, a Bloolips Retrospectacle''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Willis; designed by Cecile Thunder; musical
direction by Simon Deacon; costumes by Chance; lyrics and sketches
by Neil Bartlett, Jimmy Camicia, Ray Dobbin, Paul Shaw, Oscar Wilde
and others; music by Nicholas Bloomfield, Tchaikovsky, Wagner and
others. Presented by Theater for the New City, Crystal Field,
executive director. At 155 First Ave., at 10th Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   With: Bette Bourne, Precious Pearl and Simon Deacon. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
