<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT &LR;      06-12 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTAN REJECTS INDIA'S CALL FOR TALKS, BUT CRISIS APPEARS TO
SUBSIDE  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ An Indian proposal for talks with Pakistan
later this month on ways of lessening tensions in the Indian
subcontinent was quickly rejected by Pakistan Friday, but the
exchange appeared to have moved both governments closer to direct
negotiations over the crisis set off by the nuclear tests that both
conducted last month.
</P>
<P>
   While New Delhi and Islamabad were testing each other out over
possible talks, a new sense of urgency developed as a result of
decisions made Friday in London at a meeting of foreign ministers
of the United States and seven other industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of the eight nations announced that they
would act together to postpone loans for everything but ``basic
human needs'' by major international financial institutions,
including the International Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the
Asian Development Bank. ``We agree to support postponement of
consideration of other loans by the international financial
institutions,'' the foreign ministers said in a statement. They did
not say how long a postponement they had in mind, however. The
length of any delay has been the subject of disagreement by the
Europeans on one hand and the United States, Japan and Canada on
the other. United States law sets no limits on postponement.
</P>
<P>
   India and Pakistan had both hoped the United States would be
isolated in its bid to cut off loans to the two nations by the
international institutions, a step President Clinton included in
the package of sanctions he imposed on India after its first series
of nuclear tests on May 11, and in the identical sanctions on
Pakistan he announced after Islamabad's initial test series on May
28.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the United States has the power to delay, but not to
halt, billions of dollars of loans that are crucial to development
in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's decision in London, Indian and Pakistani analysts
noted that the eight countries represented at the meeting have more
than 50 per cent of the voting power at the IMF and the World Bank,
enough to block loans and inflict major damage on the economies of
both countries. But there are few people in either country who
believe that economic pressure, however severe, is likely to
achieve the ultimate objective stated by the nations that met in
London: forcing India and Pakistan to sign existing nuclear
limitation treaties and to abandon plans to develop arsenals of
nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, the prime ministers of the two countries,
Atal Bihari Vajpayee of India and Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan, have
both said that they favored negotiations on nuclear weapons and
other issues. But when India made a formal proposal Friday that
senior officials open a dialogue on June 22 in New Delhi, India's
capital, Pakistan promptly rejected the proposal, calling it ``the
traditional gimmickry of Indian diplomacy.'' Instead, Pakistan
suggested the talks begin in Islamabad, Pakistan's capital, on June
20.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection reflected differences between the two governments
over the agenda for the negotiations, in particular over the
procedures for discussing the highly-charged issue of Kashmir. But
western diplomats and officials in both capitals said the
significance of the day's exchanges lay less in that maneuvering
than in the fact that both governments had signaled that they
wanted talks to begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all that's happened, you'd have to expect that they'd
play cat-and-mouse,'' a western envoy in New Delhi said. ``But it's
clear that both sides recognize the need to start talking about
nuclear weapons, and to do it soon, for their own sake and to show
the world they understand the seriousness of the issues involved.''
</P>
<P>
   A clearer indication of how far New Delhi and Islamabad are
prepared to go in restraining a nuclear arms race is likely to
emerge when they begin talks. Although Friday's efforts to schedule
talks proved abortive, there were signs that Vajpayee and Sharif
were already looking beyond talks at the level of officials to a
possible summit meeting in early July, when government leaders of
seven South Asian nations are to gather for an annual summit
meeting in Colombo, the Sri Lankan capital.
</P>
<P>
   Dates for the regional meeting have been up in the air since the
nuclear tests, with doubts whether the Indian and Pakistani leaders
would attend, and if they did, whether they would meet. But western
diplomats said they were told by the Indian foreign ministry Friday
that the Colombo meeting was likely to take place between July 9
and 12, and that Vajpayee and Sharif were likely to meet during
that period.
</P>
<P>
   The talks that the two governments jockeyed over in public
Friday would be held at the level of their foreign secretaries, the
top diplomats in their respective foreign ministries. Talks at this
level were resumed last year after a gap of several years, but
lapsed in September when the two sides were unable to agree on a
formula for discussing Kashmir, the disputed territory that has
been at the core of enmities between them since the partition of
the sub-continent in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   In its proposal for talks Friday, India suggested that the talks
resume in New Delhi on the basis of proposals put forward by India,
and rejected by Pakistan, in January. Although the Indian proposals
provided for discussions on Kashmir, as demanded by Pakistan, India
wanted these to be subsumed in broader talks on peace and security
in the subcontinent, and not in a separate working group as favored
by Pakistan. It was this difference that Pakistan cited Friday in
rejecting the Indian proposal for resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
   When the two nations do meet, their discussions on nuclear
weapons are likely to focus on several proposals including a formal
agreement not to conduct any further tests, a step both governments
have said they are ready to take; a non-aggression pact, a proposal
put forward by Pakistan that India has said it will consider; and a
commitment by both nations not to be the the first to use nuclear
weapons, an idea favored by India but not by Pakistan, which has
said that it regards a nuclear arsenal as a counterweight to
India's large advantage in conventional forces.
</P>
<P>
   But Pakistan has said that it will not abandon plans to develop
a nuclear arsenal, as demanded by the United States and the other
nations that met Friday in London, unless India abandons its
arsenal; and India has said that the only circumstance under which
it will forgo the development of nuclear arms is if the established
nuclear powers, Britain, China, France, Russia and the United
States, agree to eliminate their own arsenals, something all five
have rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
