<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TRASH THE IMF! 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Precede should be italicized) 
(bl) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recently several prominent former officials and economists have
called for abolishing the International Monetary Fund. Congress is
also holding back its next deposit to the fund, $18 billion,
because a Republican congressman, Chris Smith, won't allow the U.S.
contribution to be made unless the Clinton administration drops
support for any worldwide family-planning program that includes
abortions. Since all these smart people seem to think the world
doesn't need the IMF, I say junk the place. Here's what the world
would look like a year later.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 13, 1999 _ On the first anniversary of the
closing of the IMF, the Russian ruble hit a new low today of 50,000
to the dollar. Russia's president, the former army general
Alexander Lebed, who ousted Boris Yeltsin in a coup after the
Russian economy collapsed six months ago, announced a new export
program for getting Russia's economy back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``From today forward,'' said President Lebed, ``any Russian
company capable of exporting any device, technology, weapons system
or natural resource _ including highly enriched uranium _ is
encouraged to do so to anyone who can pay hard currency. The U.S.
Congress says it will sanction us for selling nuclear technology to
Iran or India. Hah! What more can they do? Since they closed the
IMF, 35 percent of Russia is unemployed. The Russian army has not
been paid in six months. How's that for a moral hazard!''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the former U.S. allies Korea and Thailand, with their
economies in a tailspin from the lack of IMF support, decided to go
to the only other potential lender of last resort _ the U.S.
Congress. Korea's president, Kim Dae-jung, told Congress: ``We have
been loyal U.S. allies for 40 years. I am the first liberal
democrat elected President of Korea. All my years as a political
exile, America was my model. You're not going to abandon me now?
With 30,000 U.S. troops in my country and North Korea up there with
a bomb in the basement?''
</P>
<P>
   The Koreans have enlisted two former U.S. Treasury secretaries,
George Shultz and William Simon, along with the former Citibank
chief Walter Wriston, to lobby Congress for an emergency $10
billion aid package for Seoul. Unlike IMF bailouts _ where the
burden is shared by many countries _ this Korean bailout will have
to be a direct loan from the United States to Korea, with America
bearing all the risks and costs alone.
</P>
<P>
   That loan was jeopardized yesterday, though, when the U.S.
Embassy in Seoul was ransacked, along with the Coke and Pepsi
bottling plants, by an angry Korean mob. The mob was outraged by
the conditions that the U.S. Congress wanted to impose on Korea in
exchange for U.S. help: an end to all birth control in Korea and
the right for any U.S. company to buy 100 percent of any Korean
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad we don't have the IMF around to impose these
conditions, so everyone could blame it instead of us,'' mused House
Speaker Newt Gingrich, in a rare moment of candor.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Asia, human rights activists were appalled as
Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia all declared martial law so their
governments could close down newspapers and stop rioting against
businesses owned by ethnic Chinese, who tend to dominate Southeast
Asia's economies. China warned that if the anti-Chinese rioting was
not halted, China's navy would ``not stand idle.``
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad denounced
the IMF's closure as yet another conspiracy to weaken Southeast
Asia, mounted by ``the global Merchants of Venice _ and you know
who I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   America's trade deficit hit an all-time high of $400 billion, as
cheap exports from all over Asia's battered economies flooded the
United States. The Dow fell again today, to 6,660, as the dollar
hit 300 yen.
</P>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS Poll showed two
nativist-protectionists, Patrick Buchanan and Ross Perot, running
neck and neck in the year 2000 presidential race, after Al Gore and
George W. Bush both dropped out because of lack of support.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the United States called for an emergency meeting of
the world's leading industrial nations to try to establish some
sort of international monetary fund to deal with the crisis.
America offered to hold the meeting in a quiet estate in New
Hampshire called Bretton Woods, but the other world powers, showing
contempt for weak U.S. leadership, insisted on Shanghai. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1921EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-12 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CLASS OF '98 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last term of high school, as I remember it from the first
time around, is one steady flooring of the accelerator pedal.
Grades don't count, exams don't count, the college that's accepted
you can't change its mind.
</P>
<P>
   In my particular senior year, ``Sgt. Pepper'' had just hit town,
the drinking age was 18 and everyone had a driver's license. By
both shaking and stirring these ingredients, my friends and I were
able to float for weeks, it seemed, from one backyard party to
another until finally we stayed still just long enough to slip into
our rented tuxedos, pick up our corsages and find our way to our
dates and the prom.
</P>
<P>
   After that we drove all night to the beach, though how we then
crept back to our Washington graduation from Ocean City, tired and
sunburned but no wiser, I don't precisely recall. Lucy was always
in the sky with diamonds that endless June, and she was blinding.
</P>
<P>
   The second time around, high school graduation has a different
effect. As I have watched my first son float through his spring
term of senior year, I don't begrudge him his dawning recognition
that school is out even before it officially is; he's earned the
right to coast. And I would have hated myself in the morning if I
had hypocritically applied a curfew to his late spring nights. But
graduation, which could not come fast enough when I was 18, arrives
far too quickly now that he's 18. Instead of accelerating, a father
wants to slam on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Friends talk about the horror of turning 50, an indignity that
apparently requires you to crawl into a dark psychic cave for
several months and then emerge reading Gail Sheehy books, but I
can't imagine how it could be worse than a first child's
leave-taking. After those years of secretly fantasizing that it
might be a breather to have at least one child out of the house,
especially an adolescent male child, I want to bar the door.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the end of the so-called ``college-application
process'' _ a misnomer for ``college-application torture'' _ that I
realized why it had filled me with such anxiety. My fear wasn't
that my son would fail to get into whatever school he wanted (not
that he was going to choose what school he wanted until the last
possible minute anyway, thank you very much), but that he WOULD get
into that school. The moment the admissions letters went out was
the moment he was truly out the door _ not to an indeterminate
friend's house from which he'd certainly return (however tardily),
but to the humbling realm of adulthood that will be his permanent
new home.
</P>
<P>
   Unselfishly as well as selfishly, I wanted him to cling to
senior year forever. He was safe and happy there, and I, as I now
realize, was safe and happy there too.
</P>
<P>
   My friends John and Nan have tried to cheer me up. Their
daughter, a year older than my son, is at the same college he'll be
going to in the fall. It's not that far, they keep reminding me,
and we can all drive up together on a weekend and take our kids out
to dinner. Having only boys, I can't speak about daughters, but I
remember what I was like in college; dinner with my parents if they
happened to drop into town was not much higher on my list of
priorities than folding laundry. I had my own life now.
</P>
<P>
   These June mornings I wake up to the radio, on which my favorite
talk-show monologuist, a few years older than I am, talks about the
joys of incipient second fatherhood: he has a new baby due any
minute. I fantasize: Could I start at the beginning again and
simply fill the empty place in my nest? Then I get out of bed, and
flash back to the hospital where my son was born, to the nights of
formula, the days of strollers. I face reality: I'm just not one of
those people who can turn back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   So I anticipate instead the world that's going to open wide for
my son in the fall, and imagine it excitedly through his eyes. I
take the pictures of him in his rented prom tux _ far slicker than
his Dad's _ to the drug store to be developed. I dote on my younger
boy, still with all of high school ahead of him and too much the
forgotten soldier of his brother's graduation week. I remind myself
as well that it's still only June, and that there's a whole summer
to come before my son decamps to college.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if I've learned anything at all in those many years
between my high school graduation and his, it's that the summer
goes by so fast. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
