<HEADER>
A7164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CENTRALPARK-LAWN-5     06-12 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CENTRALPARK-LAWN-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTRAL PARK'S GREAT LAWN HAS A KEEPER WHO'S NOT BAD EITHER
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Kasoundra Kasoundra is cq.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Earlier this week, a well-dressed couple stood on the
edge of the newly restored Great Lawn in Central Park, the lush
bluegrass tickling their ankles. They had rolled aside the
four-foot-high fence to enter.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Hernandez brought her golf cart to a halt, smiled broadly,
and announced: ``Excuse me, the lawn is closed right now. It opens
at 11.''
</P>
<P>
   What? The man fumed that this was ludicrous. The woman said the
golf cart, the fence and the grass fetish made one of the world's
greatest urban parks seem hopelessly suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hernandez, 45, who has calloused hands and a lot of silver
bracelets, nodded cheerfully and began her spiel. ``You have to
understand this is a brand new landscape,'' she said, explaining
how the city had just spent more than $18 million on the
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see,'' said the woman, slightly mollified. ``You have to
baby-sit.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. The Central Park Conservancy, the private group now
responsible for day-to-day management of the park, is determined to
protect the investment in the Great Lawn _ everything from 250
computer-controlled, pop-up sprinklers to more than 2,000 new trees
and shrubs to the centerpiece, 1 million square feet of amazingly
weedless grass _ composed of five different strains of bluegrass.
So it has created a new position with a broad mandate and a
grandiose title: Keeper of the Great Lawn. Ms. Hernandez is the
keeper, and make no mistake, she takes the job very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting the new Great Lawn is particularly important to the
conservancy as a way to demonstrate that it is up to the new
responsibilities it took on in February under a contract with the
city. ``The spotlight is on us to perform _ big-time,'' said Karen
Putnam, the conservancy's president.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hernandez's responsibilities include everything that goes on
in the 55-acre Great Lawn area, including the 14-acre Great Oval
that is home to some of the most heavily used ballfields in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   With a staff of five full-time employees, three summer seasonal
workers and a dozen volunteers, she monitors soil and grass stems,
prunes trees, shovels fertilizer, decides which entrances to open,
oversees restroom repairs, coordinates cultural events like park
appearances by the Metropolitan Opera and New York Philharmonic,
rolls up hundreds of feet of hoses _ and performs at least a
hundred other chores, most daily.
</P>
<P>
   But her most urgent mission is working to educate people on how
to behave in their new emerald paradise: no dogs, no impromptu
ballgames, no bikes, no Rollerblading, no frisbee-throwing by more
than two people. It is thus Ms. Hernandez's job to sell the notion
that the way to enhance and preserve a renewed play space is to
curb the more destructive of people's fun-loving instincts.
</P>
<P>
   The conservancy's philosophy is that by providing a familiar
worker in the same space _ 49 gardeners have been assigned to the
park's 49 specific areas _ it can give maintenance and good
behavior a recognizable human face. ``Otherwise it's like an
invisible hand is taking care of the public space,'' Ms. Putnam
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Putnam lauds Ms. Hernandez's ``spectacular integrity'' and
``mythic passion for the park,'' but pays her just $36,000 a year
for what are usually 50-hour weeks. Ms. Hernandez is not in it for
the money. She calls herself ``a Central Park baby,'' having grown
up on the Upper West Side, where she still lives. She studied to
become a chiropractor but went on to work in a variety of jobs from
real-estate management to art restoration to fashion buying.
</P>
<P>
   But gardening became her love. She named her now 21-year-old
daughter Fern, likes to pull weeds in her friends' yards, takes
horticultural courses and volunteers with gardeners at the
Cathedral of St. John the Divine.
</P>
<P>
   One day seven years ago when she was walking her two dogs
(leashed, of course) in Central Park, she became fascinated
watching a pruner. She applied and was hired as a summer worker.
This led to a job as the gardener for Cedar Hill, a section on the
east side of the park that has long been known as Dog Hill because
of all the unleashed canines.
</P>
<P>
   Partly by bringing her own dogs on a leash, but mostly through
patient explanations of landscape improvements at the hill, she
succeeded in both reclaiming the hill for humans and keeping the
dog people reasonably happy. She also came up with the idea of
displaying red flags when the grass was too soggy for walking _ a
system she has taken to the Great Lawn. And she smiled, sometimes
cajoled, but always smiled again.
</P>
<P>
   One result was an anonymous donation of $5,000 for a bench in
her name at Cedar Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maria's work goes beyond a mere job,'' Parks Commissioner
Henry Stern said. ``It's a calling.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the keeper cannot be tough. Her governing
philosophy: rule with a pot of honey and an iron fist. ``Sometimes
I feel like judge, attorney and hangman, all in one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kasoundra Kasoundra, a volunteer who works in the Great Lawn
three days a week, having followed Ms. Hernandez from Cedar Hill,
said, ``She gets cantankerous when she sees somebody doing
something he shouldn't be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hernandez's joy is helping someone understand the need
to behave differently. She recalls a woman who was walking next to
Turtle Pond when red flags were up. Her dog was paddling in the
water, also a no-no. They talked. ``I went through the whole nine
yards,'' Ms. Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, the woman told the keeper that she had seen
someone doing the same thing. ``I gave her your whole story,'' she
eagerly told Ms. Hernandez. ``I feel so proud of myself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
