<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-DREMAN-$ADV4-     06-12 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-DREMAN-$ADV4-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH DAVID N. DREMAN: KEMPER-DREMAN HIGH RETURN EQUITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Canada)  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
Contrarian fund facts and figures; Charts of 3 stocks from
Contrarian fund will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14) 
(af) 
 By NOELLE KNOX    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ugly, the down and out, the beaten up _ these are the stocks
that David N. Dreman, the value investor, loves.
</P>
<P>
   And as you might expect in a rampaging bull market, Dreman's
flagship fund, Kemper-Dreman High Return Equity, has seemed a bit,
well, downtrodden itself lately.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 12 months, the fund has returned 24.1 percent,
compared with 24.6 percent for the average large-value fund,
according to Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher, and
31.9 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Is Dreman, 62, disheartened? Not at all. He is the grand master
of a simple yet psychologically challenging investment strategy:
consummate contrarianism.
</P>
<P>
   Consider tobacco stocks, which fell some 20 percent when the
Clinton administration started negotiating an industry liability
settlement last spring. That is when Dreman started buying Philip
Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   He has also waded into oil, buying shares of Amoco and Texaco
despite a selloff caused by the current oil glut and tapering
growth in demand. His bet is that the new oil coming from Iraq and
the warmer temperatures created by El Nino are temporary setbacks
for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking a major play, and as always, the value manager
is early,'' Dreman said.
</P>
<P>
   If history is any guide, he may well be right. For the three
years ended June 5, the fund returned an average of 31.9 percent a
year, compared with 24.5 percent for the average large-value fund
and 30.8 percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   For the 10-year period, the return was 19.6 percent, compared
with 14.5 percent for peer funds and 18.5 percent for the index.
</P>
<P>
   With a record like that, what's a couple of bad quarters?
</P>
<P>
   Dreman is the chairman and chief investment officer of Dreman
Value Management in Red Bank, N.J.. In addition to the High Return
fund, his firm manages the Kemper-Dreman Financial Services fund,
which opened in March and has $184 million in assets. He also
manages about $2 billion in private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview aboard his yacht, Contrarian, moored near
New York's World Financial Center, Dreman recalled how he was born
to doubt. He was raised in Winnipeg, Manitoba, the son of a
commodities trader who at 87 is still the patriarch of the Winnipeg
Commodities Exchange. Dreman remembers that his father ``talked a
lot about the research not being right.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreman now makes a lot of money betting against the experts. He
starts with companies with an average capitalization of $15
billion, thus insuring better reporting standards and trading
liquidity. Then he looks at four key measures.
</P>
<P>
   First, he wants a low price-to-earnings ratio _ at least 30
percent lower than the market average, which is currently about 26.
He also compares the ratios with those of other companies in the
same industry to make sure he is not overpaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to have stocks that are really badly sold out,''
Dreman said. The average p/e ratio in his portfolio is 18.7.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he looks for a price-to-book ratio that, again, is at
least 30 percent lower than the market's, which he currently pegs
at 6.1.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Dreman compares the company's stock price with its cash
flow, typically defined as after-tax earnings, adding back
depreciation and other noncash charges. This should also be 30
percent lower than the market's ratio of about 20, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he looks for something that has become an afterthought
for most investors _ high dividends. Before he buys, he wants a a
stock to have a yield at least 50 basis points, or hundredths of a
percentage point, higher than the market's 1.42 percent. And he
looks for a history of rising payouts. Over all, Dreman's fund has
a yield of about 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One of his longest-held stocks is Fannie Mae, the federal
underwriter of home mortgages that has been a standard-bearer of
this bull market. Dreman says that it still fits his model, though
``it's kind of the higher end of our range.''
</P>
<P>
   He started building his position in Fannie Mae in October 1990,
toward the end of the savings and loan crisis, at about $6 a share.
The stock, which closed on Friday at $61.4375, now has a
price-to-earnings ratio of 20.6 and a price-to-book ratio of 4.9.
(Price-to-cash-flow ratios are less meaningful for financial
companies because their capital costs are different from those of
most companies.) The stock yields 1.56 percent, more than 10 basis
points above the market.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent contrarian call is Philip Morris, which the fund
started buying last June at an average price of $40 a share. The
stock closed on Friday at $37.3125, but Dreman likes the company's
price-to-earnings ratio of 15.1, its price-to-book ratio of 5.9,
its price-to-cash-flow ratio of 10.8 and its yield of 4.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He does not set price targets, but predicts that if the market
keeps rising over the next 12 months, Philip Morris will outperform
it by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   His other big contrarian play is oil. His largest holding in the
sector, Amoco, traded as low as $35 when he started buying it in
August 1995. The shares closed on Friday at $41.6875. Amoco has a
price-to-earnings ratio of 16.6, a price-to-book ratio of 2.5, a
price-to-cash-flow ratio of 8.8 and a yield of 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He also declined to set a price target for Amoco but said that
he expected all of the stocks in his portfolio to increase 50
percent to 100 percent over three years.
</P>
<P>
   The fund holds just 52 stocks. And surprisingly for a
contrarian, Dreman has about 30 percent of the portfolio exposed to
the price of the S&AMP;P 500 through futures contracts.
</P>
<P>
   He holds onto these futures until a stock he is considering
sinks to his target levels. (His current list includes technology
stocks and oil service companies, like the Noble Drilling Corp. and
Tidewater Inc.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather get an S&AMP;P return, and then, at the right time,
buy the stock I want rather than get into that stock early or buy a
second or a third choice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Dreman has a fairly strict ``sell'' discipline _ any stock
that does not perform within three and a half years is out _ the
fund's turnover is a remarkably low 10 percent. He cautions,
however, that buying stocks purely on valuations can lead investors
astray. He spends a lot of time poring over a company's quarterly
reports and balance sheets and talking with management before he
buys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the companies we buy are going to be
survivors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many other investors fear the prospect of a market
selloff, Dreman looks forward to one. He searches for breaks to go
against the market grain and take advantage of investor fears.
``We've always been opportunistic,'' he said, ``and that would give
us a chance to take advantage of these corrections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
