<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      06-12 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS SEEN IN GM TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Strikes at two General Motors parts factories forced
the automaker to close some of its most profitable assembly plants
Friday, increasing the number of temporarily laid-off workers to
50,900. But tensions started to ease in the dispute, as negotiators
began making slow progress.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the talks said that the tenor had changed
following a pledge by GM officials late Thursday to return
parts-making equipment to a Flint, Mich., plant. The equipment was
removed over Memorial Day weekend from one of two auto parts
factories in Flint, Mich., that have since gone on strike.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders at the United Automobile Workers union, who had been
treating the confrontation in Flint as an emotional showdown over
what they described as strike-breaking tactics by the automaker,
began settling down Friday to discuss with the automaker how many
jobs would be preserved at the two factories. Talks recessed at the
factories late Friday afternoon, but negotiators agreed to return
on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the negotiations continued, GM was closing five more
assembly plants, bringing the total to 13 of GM's 29 assembly
plants in North America. The factories closed Friday included two
in Fort Wayne, Ind., and Pontiac, Mich., that make full-size pickup
trucks and another factory in Janesville, Wis., that produces
full-size sport utility vehicles. Full-size light trucks account
for a tiny share of GM's worldwide sales but close to half of its
profits, according to Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these factories going down, it starts to cost GM real
money,'' said Stephen Girsky, an auto analyst with Morgan Stanley,
who predicted that the strike would be settled by the middle of
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution of the equipment-removal issue now makes the
strike very similar to eight others that GM has faced over the last
three years. In most of these factory-level strikes, the union has
tried to insist that GM replace every worker who retires. GM has
tried to eliminate jobs gradually through attrition while
installing more automated equipment or buying more auto parts from
outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   In each strike, negotiators have ended up splitting the
difference, with the UAW slowing but not stopping GM's steady push
to cut costs and become more competitive by producing ever more
cars and components with ever fewer workers.
</P>
<P>
   But in some cases, negotiators have taken a long time to split
the difference. A 17-day strike in 1996 at two brake factories in
Dayton, Ohio, forced GM to close briefly all but two of its 29
North American assembly plants, while temporarily laying off
178,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   GM has tried in each strike to allocate as many parts as
possible to the production of the most profitable light trucks,
while shutting unprofitable car factories first, and has done so
again this week.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 strike, GM agreed to a compromise several days
after it finally ran out of brakes and shut down its Janesville
factory, its sole source then of full-size sport utility vehicles,
which earn profits of $10,000 apiece. But GM has since converted a
factory in Arlington Heights, Texas, to production of the same
models, and that factory remained open Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The current labor dispute is complicated because it involves two
different strikes. The first strike, which began on June 5, shut
down a factory that stamps sheets of steel into hoods, fenders and
other parts for full-size pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles.
The second strike, which began on Thursday evening, closed down
GM's main source of spark plugs and various dashboard instruments,
like speedometers.
</P>
<P>
   At the stamping factory, GM contends that some workers have been
trying to collect a full day's pay for half a day of work, while
the UAW wants GM to promise that it will replace 200 workers as
they retire. At the second factory, the UAW is trying to slow a
long decline in employment that has already shrunk the factory's
work force from 13,000 a decade ago to about 5,800 now.
</P>
<P>
   GM has been building new assembly plants and parts factories
overseas to reduce costs, even as it allows its American work force
to shrink gradually. But GM's overall international strategy is not
part of the talks at either factory, which involve specific
provisions of factory-level labor contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at several other GM factories have asked the UAW's
permission to strike but have not received it and are unlikely to
do so soon. The UAW has to pay $150 a week in strike benefits to
workers who walk out. But workers temporarily laid off by GM are
usually eligible for unemployment compensation from state
governments _ which could later demand the money back from GM
through higher unemployment insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   GM tried with little success during the Dayton strike to block
the unemployment benefits on the grounds that the temporarily
laid-off workers were members of the same union that was on strike
elsewhere. The automaker has not decided whether to try to block
benefits this time, said Gerald Holmes, a GM spokesman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
