<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROCERIES-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      06-12 1925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROCERIES-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER, BIGGER SUPERMARKET CHAINS MAY BE WHAT FUTURE OFFERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it looked for the right recipe for its house brand of
salsa, Shaw's Supermarkets Inc. relied on customer focus groups and
blind taste tests. After much trial and error, Shaw's came up with
a mild sauce that passed muster.
</P>
<P>
   Red-hot salsa may be prized in Texas, but in the land of the
bean and the cod, consumers prefer bland dips for their snack
foods. And the peanut butter had better be just right, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't spread thick on white bread, New Englanders
don't want it,'' says Shaw's spokesman Bernie Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   Picky regional food tastes may partly explain why there isn't a
national supermarket chain. In this land of plenty, tastes can vary
widely, even from neighborhood to neighborhood. As a result, the
food industry has tended to be regionally fragmented, with
supermarket chains succeeding by becoming experts in the food
preferences of local consumers. Get too big, and grocers can lose
sight of what customers want.
</P>
<P>
   All that may be changing. In an industry in which profit margins
are razor thin, market forces are pushing chains to bulk up and get
more efficient. Within a few years, national grocers could emerge,
and that could have major implications for everyone, from consumers
to mom-and-pop stores. Such changes could also rearrange a local
landscape where the three biggest players are Quincy-based Stop &AMP;
Shop Supermarket Co., East Bridgewater-based Shaw's, and
Cambridge-based Star Markets Co.
</P>
<P>
   One force for change may be Wal-Mart Stores Inc. In the last
decade, Wal-Mart has charged its way into the grocery aisle. In
1997, Wal-Mart sold about $20 billion worth of food, about $6
billion behind America's largest grocer, Ohio-based Kroger Co. With
Arkansas-based Wal-Mart becoming a big food presence in the South
and Midwest, many supermarket chains want the buying clout and
efficiencies that acquisitions can bring.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, supermarkets are waging war on a second front.
Consumers now spend about half of every food dollar on takeout and
restaurant meals. A good acquisition can also help supermarkets as
they compete with these rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, the $436 billion US grocery industry has
been consolidating rapidly, with more than 100 mergers or
acquisitions, says the Food Institute, an industry group. The
latest big deal: an agreement by Stop &AMP; Shop's Dutch parent, Royal
Ahold NV, to buy Giant Foods Inc., a 176-store chain based near
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   If this consolidation pace continues, America could soon look a
lot like Europe, where a few big chains rule, says Stop &AMP; Shop
chief executive William J. Grize.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a relatively short time, there will be five or six
retailers dominating our industry,'' Grize predicts. ``You're going
to see things that will make your head spin.''
</P>
<P>
   With population growth stagnant in Europe, big European players
like Ahold see US chains as good investments, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Putting together a national grocery chain may not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   For other retailers, national expansion can be a relatively
straightforward exercise, though not always easy to execute.
</P>
<P>
   A Home Depot can take its formula for a big hardware store and
replicate it from Maine to Oregon. A Staples can open big office
supply stores from coast to coast and thrive. But a cookie-cutter,
one-size-fits-all strategy may not work as well for a business that
lives and dies on knowing the salsa tastes of its local customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sell the same legal pad in Los Angeles that you can in
New York,'' says Staples Inc. founder Thomas G. Stemberg, who once
worked at Star Market. ``But regional food tastes vary widely.
People even have different names for things. In Boston, it's tonic.
In New Jersey, it's soda. In Chicago, it's pop.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to food, consumers are reluctant to buy from
strangers, which may explain why chains think an acquisition is a
better, and often cheaper, way to move into an unfamiliar market
than simply building new stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have a warm and fuzzy feeling about their grocer,''
says Steve Griffin, president of the Griffin Report of Food
Marketing, an industry newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing makes a food lover more warm and fuzzy than a grocer
who meticulously studies their eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   That's something A&AMP;P may have lost sight of. Thirty years ago,
the Great Atlantic &AMP; Pacific Tea Co. had 4,600 supermarkets and was
about the closest thing America had to a national chain. Now that
total is about 900. A lack of decentralization, an indifference to
customers' tastes, and an unwillingess to use new technologies were
among the reasons cited for A&AMP;P's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ahold and others are using a different strategy. Seeking
to combine the best of both worlds, Ahold lets its chains keep
their identities, names, and management teams while getting more
buying clout and added efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   By creating a network of cooperating chains rather than one big
chain with one name and store format, Ahold hopes to enjoy the
advantages of size without losing sight of local food preferences.
</P>
<P>
   When the Giant acquisition is completed, Ahold will operate US
supermarkets under seven nameplates, including Stop &AMP; Shop, Bi-Lo,
and Tops.
</P>
<P>
   Its East Coast food empire will stretch from Gloucester to the
Florida-Georgia border. And with Stop &AMP; Shop likely to contribute
more than $5.5 billion to the total, Ahold expects its US sales
could account for nearly $20 billion of its roughly $30 billion in
annual worldwide revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Look for Ahold to make more acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we need to be $100 billion in worldwide sales in a few
years,'' says Stop &AMP; Shop's Grize of Ahold's plans.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Ahold's home turf, the food business is different.
Stores stock fewer items and rely less on brand names.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, you won't find nine kinds of yogurt in a
supermarket,'' says Shaw's Rogan.
</P>
<P>
   And in Europe, you won't find the pervasive American-style
television advertising that stimulates brand loyalty for everything
from Cheerios to Coca-Cola, he suggests.
</P>
<P>
   In this vacuum of brand loyalty, European food stores load their
shelves with house brand items. By cutting out brokers and
middlemen, these house brands can mean lower prices for customers _
and higher profit margins for grocers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rogan, house brands account for about half of a
European grocer's sales; in the United States, that number may be
only 20 to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, British food operator J Sainsbury plc brought some
of its house-brand grocery strategy to the United States when it
bought Shaw's.Yet in 1998, some observers still wonder if this
house-brand strategy can work on a grand scale in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's top job has been vacant for a few months; operating
profits have dipped. And earlier this year, Shaw's scaled back on
Connecticut expansion plans, says Griffin, the industry newsletter
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's worked as well as they had hoped,'' Griffin
says of the chain's house-brand strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Rogan counters that the numbers show otherwise. In 1997, he
says, house brands at Shaw's accounted for about 40 percent of the
chain's $2.8 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the envy of the industry,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As a smaller chain with just over $1 billion in annual sales,
Star Market may face some different challenges.
</P>
<P>
   With so much consolidation in the US grocery industry, the best
way for a small independent chain to survive may be to carve out
its own special niche, says Kurt Funderburg, a supermarket analyst
with Ferris, Baker, Watts in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the strategy of Star Market, a 53-store chain.
Star's hope is that it can become a publicly owned company someday,
says Star chief executive Henry Nasella.
</P>
<P>
   By Nasella's lights, creating a niche means designing each store
to fit an individual neighborhood &UR; , &LR;  with the same care a tailor
uses to fashion a custom-made suit.
</P>
<P>
   Star's newest store, which just opened between Kendall and
Central squares in Cambridge, is a case in point, Nasella says.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Stop &AMP; Shop once had a store nearby, but neighborhood
residents and the company couldn't reach an agreement when Stop &AMP;
Shop wanted to convert and expand the location into its highly
efficient and profitable superstore format.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than continue to operate at a small, antiquated store
that no longer meshed with its superstore formula, Stop &AMP; Shop left
the neighborhood, and Star moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted by the higher costs of operating in urban areas not
ideally suited to supermarket logistics, Star's new store is
located on two levels of a hotel, something Nasella says has never
been done before.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, Star is competing as much with restaurants as with
other supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter believes a good meal comes from a menu, not a
recipe,'' Nasella says.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter might approve of the new Star, which is full of
meals-to-go and ethnic cuisines carefully matched to the
demographic breakdown of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to ride the popularity of high-profit natural foods, the
store features a Wild Harvest section. Star has also opened four
free-standing stores under the Wild Harvest name.
</P>
<P>
   Like most new supermarkets, the Star in Cambridge aims to
provide one-stop &UR;  &LR; shopping for its customers. Many new stores, in
fact, include a bank branch, a dry cleaners, a pharmacy, and a
flower section.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, one-stop &UR;  &LR; shopping has evolved to an even higher
level. In so-called ``hyper-stores,'' customers can buy everything
from duck pate to snow tires.
</P>
<P>
   About a decade ago, Arkansas-based Wal-Mart debuted its own
variation, called a Supercenter. In stores as large as 220,000
square feet, grocery aisles have been added to a traditional
Wal-Mart discount store.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Wal-Mart's 469 Supercenters are in the South and
Midwest, says spokesman Keith Morris. In searching for new store
sites, Wal-Mart looks for places where real estate is readily
available and the local population is growing.
</P>
<P>
   That would rule out most of New England for the moment, but
Wal-Mart has just announced plans to open a 40,000-square-foot
``convenience store'' that will sell groceries in its hometown of
Bentonville, Ark. Meanwhile, Wal-Mart rivals such as Kmart and
Target are also experimenting with groceries.
</P>
<P>
   These food forays may not be instantly felt in New England, but
they're fueling supermarket consolidation elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Threatened by the discount stores, small independent chains are
selling out to larger supermarket rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The planned Giant sale to Ahold may prompt more acquisitions.
Shaw's parent, Sainsbury, owned a stake in Giant. Will it still
make sense for Sainsbury to keep Shaw's as its only US chain?
</P>
<P>
   Safeway Inc. faces a similar dilemma. Far from its California
base, it operates stores on Giant's Washington-Baltimore turf.
</P>
<P>
   Safeway may either have to make an East Coast acquisition or
sell the East Coast stores it has now, analyst Funderburg says.
</P>
<P>
   With all this jockeying, is a national supermarket chain
possible? Some observers thinks so. Thanks to scanning devices and
shopper loyalty cards, grocers know more about their customers'
food preferences than ever before. With such technology, it may be
possible for a grocery giant to please salsa lovers in places as
diverse as Texas and Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1935EDT &QL; 
