<HEADLINE>
TEXAN TAKES ON POLICE OVER HIS GRANDMOTHER'S REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACQUE CROUSE   c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ She took care of him, helped him sort out his
problems and loved hi m like no one else ever has.
</P>
<P>
   So when June Hewitt died at age 63 and was cremated in 1995, her
grandson, Michael Horne, took some of her ashes, put them in a
plastic, zip-up bag and carried them with him at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Horne, 21, kept her ashes and memory close, never dreaming that
the police in San Antonio would some day arrest him on drug charges
because of the bag of remains he carried with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carried them because I missed her, and she's the one person
in my life I ever cared about,'' he said Thursday in his lawyer's
office. ``When she passed away, I was alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Horne and his lawyer, Luis Vera, have filed a lawsuit against
the city and plan to amend it to add the county and the
manufacturer of a field-test kit that police officers use to detect
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint in the Army, Horne moved to San Antonio and worked
for about six mo nths as a security guard. After working a 12-hour
shift on July 30, 1997, he head ed home at 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Too tired to drive, he pulled his Chevy Blazer into a parking
lot for a nap.
</P>
<P>
   Then he saw a police car stop and an officer with a spotlight
approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it here in San Antonio until then,'' he said. ``But
what happened next made my whole point of view on Texas go
downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers searched his vehicle and found his large, tri-fold
wallet. In it was the baggie, folded neatly around Hewitt's driving
license. The officer used a field-test kit and found the contents
of the bag tested positive for methamphetamine. Horne was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was telling everyone it was his grandmother's remains, and
when he told the magistrate, the magistrate's reaction was to ask
the police if they wanted him to set the bond even higher,'' Vera
said.
</P>
<P>
   Horne couldn't post the $7,500 bond. He spent the next 30 days
in the Bexar County Jail, the first half wearing a mask and in
isolation because another test false ly showed he had tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   All the while Horne kept asking to see a lawyer, to talk to the
judge, to get som eone to listen to the truth. He got no help, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even find out when my court date would be,'' he
said. ``I found out when the jail guards woke me up two hours
before and said to get up, I was going to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Two laboratory tests showed the bag contained human remains.
Prosecutors eventually dropped all charges against the man and a
judge ordered him released on Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Horne walked out of jail and straight to Vera's office, where he
had been
</P>
<P>
   referred by another inmate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had lost my truck _ they repo'd it while I was in jail,'' he
said. ``The secu rity service firm didn't want me back because of
the drug charge. And I was kicked out of my apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera had to get a court order to get the grandmother's remains
back _ it took unt il January. He has been unable to get Hewitt's
driving license and Horne's wallet returned.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what remains of his grandmother's confiscated ashes are
in his lawyer's office. But Horne has a tiny amount he still
carries with him in a plastic bag.
</P>
<P>
   His grandmother would have been upset at his being jailed in the
first place, but Horne believes she would be happy about the course
he has taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because she knows in the end I'll be OK,'' Horne said.
``In a way, I feel like she's still taking care of me, watching
over me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
