<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADOWY BANK IN BASEL DESERVES CERTAIN AMOUNT OF CREDIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the institutions of international finance, none is more
shadowy than the Bank for International Settlements, which conducts
its business from a bland glass office tower in Basel, overlooking
the spot along the Rhine where Switzerland gives way to the border
of France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund gets beat up regularly for its
role in the Asian financial crisis. The Federal Reserve Board gets
credit for keeping the American economy strong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a certain amount of credit and blame for each must be
assigned to the BIS, which ordinarily escapes notice altogether.
The central bankers' central bank held its 68th annual meeting last
week, and issued an annual report that offers the best available
synopsis of the view from the quarterdeck of the world financial
system. (It can be found on the Web at http://www.bis.org)
</P>
<P>
   Its verdict on the conduct of institutional investors last year:
that pension fund managers sensed the developing problems in Asia
and lightened up appropriately starting in 1996, while the big
commercial banks continued to plunge in with loans. Whether the
banks' heedlessness arose from a wish to please their high-rolling
customers, or was influenced by the expectation that a bailout
would be forthcoming, would require further investigation, said the
BIS.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing seemed clear: The hedge funds, with their
aggressive investment strategies and exceedingly private ways, were
not the villains of the piece. No very extensive short positions
against Asian currencies _ bets that the currencies would fall _ in
the summer of 1997 and thereafter could be demonstrated
statistically among the hedge funds as a group, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   The BIS wasn't created to be the global cockpit and lender of
last resort that it has become. Chartered in 1930 under the terms
of the agreements that ended World War I, it was supposed to go out
of business in 1990, after sixty years of overseeing German
reparation payments to the nations of Triple Entente.
</P>
<P>
   As with so much else, fate took a hand. For the BIS, that meant
a gradual evolution under the terms of the post-World War II
Bretton Woods agreements into the manager of the global currency
system. Today it holds around 7 percent of the world's currency
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Though it seldom makes a loan, its readiness to lend freely to
governments in crisis makes it the last line of defense against
panic. An often crackerjack analytic capability equips it to serve
as an early-warning system against financial excess.
</P>
<P>
   (The BIS has been criticized for being slow to sound the alarm
in Asia, but last year's report did warn firmly about heavy
investment in Asian projects with ``questionable profitability
prospects.'')
</P>
<P>
   It also oversees the ultimate soundness of the international
banking system, negotiating in 1988, for example, the accord that
eventually guided banks around the world to new standards for
capital adequecy.
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which new instruments and financial institutions
appear and grow at lightning speed, the BIS fulfills a crucial
mission. It serves as the absolute top of the heap, the pinnacle to
which responsibility-takers of a certain sort can aspire. Central
bank governors gather once a month in its serene dining rooms to
rub elbows and talk shop. Committees of blue-chip staffers labor
nightly in its conference rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers are creating financial institutions of breathtaking
reach. Bankers are richer and more powerful than ever. Even so, BIS
regulators still cultivate the immunity to temptation that is the
essence of successful banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Its personnel fly first class, retire to generous pensions
(instead of working the revolving door with the private sector),
and in general convey the aura of worldly perpendicularity that is
necessary in order to persuade the best bankers to confide
one-anothers' secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the perpendicularity of the central bankers in the
glass tower is too great. The recent decision to convene a working
group of high-ranking central bankers and treasury officials from
22 nations to deal with the Asian crisis has been construed as a
rebuke to the central bankers' efforts to take the lead in
prescribing to the politicians. And the steady expansion of the
bank's membership has not ameliorated the impression that the BIS
hasn't yet become truly multinational.
</P>
<P>
   But the quiet old city on the Rhine is likely to continue to be
the rendezvous of choice for the world's most powerful civil
servants, as governments pursue their efforts to keep control of
the world`s increasingly complex financial system. The
international association of insurance regulators recently
relocated to Basel; efforts are underway to persuade the securities
commissioners to join them (they are currently headquartered in
Montreal.)
</P>
<P>
   But all the sunshine in the world, in the form of more timely
disclosure, won't eliminate the problem of the business cycle. As
the BIS pointed out in this year's annual report, transparency is
not enough. ``What is also needed is the vision to imagine crises,
and the will to act pre-emptively.''
</P>
<P>
   So even after the European Bank replaces the various national
central banks over the next few years and so reconfigures its
geometry decisively, the Bank for International Settlements is
likely to be preferred location for quietly hashing out the thorny
problems of central banking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
