<HEADLINE>
WOMEN CONTROLLERS SUE TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMELYN CRUZ LAT   c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO Five female air traffic controllers have filed a
class-action law suit against the U.S. Department of
Transportation, alleging job discrimination a nd sexual harassment
so severe that it distracted them from
</P>
<P>
   their duties and thre atened the safety of airline passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in San Francisco federal court earlier this
month and served on the government Thursday, claims that the women
were subjected to years of lewd jokes, demeaning comments, physical
and verbal intimidation and retaliation for complaints. The women
also allege discrimination in job assignments, pay and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harassment ranged from men yelling at women in their face
and upsetting them to exposing their private parts to offensive
jokes,'' said Brad Yamauchi, the l awyer for the women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shenanigans and insults were done to distract women from
their jobs, to force them to fail. ... Imagine the incredible
strain on these women
</P>
<P>
   responsible for the safety of passengers and crews, the pressure
put on them to slip up. The reality is there is a very small margin
of error. If you lose concentration, if you' re distracted, that's
going to impact safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names as defendants Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater and the Transportation Department, which is the parent
agency of the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Williams, chief counsel with the Department of
Transportation in Washington, did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks ``a complete overhaul of the male-dominated
`good ol' boy' culture that dictates every aspect of the air
traffic control work environment.'' According to the lawsuit, one
woman from Sacramento, Calif., alleged that a male supervisor
unzipped her sweater and exposed her bra to a male co-worker. The
supe rvisor was fired but later reinstated while the female
employee was transferred and demoted.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman claimed in the suit that a male supervisor in
Santa Barbara, Calif. , had a habit of creeping up on women air
traffic controllers, exposing to them and exclaiming, ``Look what
you've done!''
</P>
<P>
   Some women claimed they were denied necessary training given to
their male counterparts, assigned menial tasks and were subjected
to verbal and physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed on behalf of the more than 1,400 female
air traffic controllers, about 10 percent of the 14,000 controllers
in hundreds of towers across the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
