A7189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV14-A     06-12 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-$ADV14-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WITH THE HOUSE'S MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Will investors buy on stock market dips?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question market watchers ask nervously whenever
equities start to look a little wan. And the averages have looked
wan for something over a month now. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed Friday at 8,834.94, down 2.2 percent for the week.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, dip-buying, the strategy that has served
investors so well since the October 1987 crash, continues apace.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence that small investors are jumping into falling
markets comes courtesy of AMG Data Services, which tracks mutual
fund inflows. For the week ending Wednesday, more than half the
$4.9 billion that investors put into equity mutual funds went into
large-capitalization stock funds and index funds, according to AMG.
</P>
<P>
   But a surprising 26 percent of the money _ $1.3 billion _ was
earmarked for small-cap, aggressive growth and technology funds,
areas that have been decidedly weak.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had been sellers of small-cap and technology funds
during the last two weeks of May. But with the NASDAQ composite _ a
proxy for aggressive-growth and small-cap shares _ down around 9
percent from its April high, they came back with a vengeance.
Technology issues, measured by the Standard &AMP; Poor's High
Technology Composite, were down 10 percent when the buyers roared
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speculator is alive and well, despite market conditions,''
said Robert Adler, president of AMG. ``If this market stalls, it's
not because of an abatement in positive investor sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, investors seem to be increasingly impervious to what can
only be called serious internal bleeding in individual stocks.
While market averages like the S&AMP;P 500-stock and the NASDAQ
composite indexes are both up 24 percent in the last 12 months, the
performance of those weighted indexes is exaggerated by the gains
of big stocks. Declines in many individual stocks are getting
scary.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the findings of a study by John Manley Jr., an equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney. As of June 2, the average
NASDAQ stock had fallen 30 percent from its 52-week high. Some 60
percent of all NASDAQ stocks are down 20 percent or more. And 84
percent are off more than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in larger stocks have been luckier; the average
decline for an S&AMP;P 500 stock is 15 percent. But more than 10
percent of the stocks in the index are down 30 percent or more;
more than half have fallen at least 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through, internally, one of the most grueling
market periods,'' Manley said. ``Only once in the last eight years
has the damage been notably greater for the NASDAQ. Even among the
bigger stocks, the average decline has been fairly substantial by
recent standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet investors seem to take these body blows with aplomb. Does
this mean they have a new, increased tolerance for market pain?
That the market could fall 30 percent and investors would simply
shrug? In the not-so-distant past, a 15 percent drop in a stock was
something to be concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that one of the wealth effects of this great bull
market is that the poverty effect of a bear move no longer
registers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a gambler who's won so much, now he's playing
with the house's money,'' said Ted Aronson, a money manager in
Philadelphia. ``Wouldn't you be more willing to take a risk and
play again if you'd just won 10 games of blackjack in a row?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
