<SLUG> BC-DRIVEUP-BOOZE-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO BANS DRIVE-IN LIQUOR SALES, BUT THE FIGHT ISN'T OVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For Release Sunday, June 14) 
(Eds.: a tilde goes over n in Munoz) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying liquor in New Mexico for decades has been as easy as
rolling through McDonald's, but the state's 234 drive-in liquor
windows will be illegal by early August.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the ban, recently enacted by the state's
Legislature, believe that closing the windows will reduce New
Mexico's historically high rate of alcohol-related traffic deaths,
partly by slowing sales to minors and drivers who already are
intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the new law will only put people out of business,
although owners of the drive-ins, commonly called ``drive-ups'' in
New Mexico, will be allowed to convert their businesses to walk-in
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from at least six different business owners who say
there's no way (they can stay in business),'' said Lisa Ulibari,
president of the state association of bar and liquor store owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is because a lot of these drive-up windows are in
small communities who have an Albertsons or a Walgreens (which are
allowed to sell liquor in New Mexico) with easy access. So what
happens is the drive-up window is really their only advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the smaller operators live day-to-day and don't have the
money for remodeling, Ulibari said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the affected businesses are mulling a lawsuit
challenging the constitutionality of closing the drive-ins without
compensation, Ulibari said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Nathan, special counsel to the state attorney general, said
he expects a lawsuit to be filed a day or two before the law goes
into effect Aug. 2, on the theory that there's money to be made
while a legal challenge delays the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls have shown that a majority of New Mexico
voters have supported closing the drive-ins for some time, Nathan
said, but the liquor industry opponents are vocal and powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hot issue in New Mexico,'' Nathan said. ``Those of us
in favor of reform are labeled prohibitionists.''
</P>
<P>
   For years New Mexico was No. 1 in the nation for alcohol-related
traffic fatalities per capita. The state's Traffic Safety Bureau
notes that the state's rates ``steadily declined'' for 15 years,
but the trend was reversed in 1996 when New Mexico returned to the
top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Johnson has changed his position on the drive-ins
since being elected in 1995. He took office saying drinking and
driving was a matter of personal responsibility and didn't believe
closing the windows would affect DWI rates.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson later said he would sign a local option election bill
that would have allowed voters to decide the issue in individual
communities. But by this year, he indicated he would consider
signing a statewide ban.
</P>
<P>
   The New Mexico Legislature sent Johnson three bills at the end
of its special session in May: a local option bill, a statewide ban
on window sales, and a third approach also banning the windows but
granting liquor store owners the sole right to liquor sales after 9
p.m., supposedly to help recoup the anticipated business losses to
groceries and drug stores.
</P>
<P>
   Often the debate over banning drive-in windows turned a
spotlight on McKinley County, where window sales have been banned
by special legislation since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had this name, `Drunk City,' for 30 years,'' said Ed Munoz,
the former mayor of Gallup, the McKinley county seat.
</P>
<P>
   Munoz said his years as a tow truck operator had shown him some
pretty gruesome alcohol-related traffic accidents, but the deaths
of a young mother, her 3-month-old baby and another family member
at the hands of a drunken driver in 1989 galvanized the community
to organize against the alcohol problem.
</P>
<P>
   A protest march while the Legislature was in session drew 4,000
people who walked nearly 200 miles to Santa Fe in the dead of
winter, Munoz said.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature agreed to pass a law allowing McKinley County to
outlaw the drive-in windows as a local option. The community also
built a large detoxification center, and levied an excise tax on
the sale of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Donna Goodrich with the McKinley County Sheriff's office
said the county's DWI rate has not changed significantly since the
windows were closed, but alcohol-related fatalities have dropped.
``Whether they are connected, I don't know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the year before the march on Santa Fe, 17 percent of
McKinley County's auto accidents were alcohol-related, compared to
a 9.5 percent statewide rate. In 1996, McKinley County's rate was
still 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1988, 33 people died in alcohol-related accidents in
McKinley County, and by 1996 that number had dropped slightly to 31
deaths (despite an increase in licensed drivers). In 1997,
preliminary state figures show only 17 people died in
alcohol-related traffic accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Atkinson, director of the state's DWI Resource Center, is
encouraged by McKinley County's apparent progress, though she
concedes the results cannot be attributed to closing the drive-ins
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Special counsel Nathan said he recognizes that statistics can be
misleading, but several studies revealed multiple problems
associated with drive-in windows _ from the ease with which minors
obtained alcohol with fake IDs at dimly lit windows to the
difficulties vendors had in determining the sobriety of the
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
