A7195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-12 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME ELECTION-YEAR ISSUES FACING THE MASSACHUSETTS HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlton Heston, go get your gun. Because the Massachusetts
House of Representatives is finally getting off the dime on
limiting the availability of assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Heston, the National Rifle Association's Moses-with-an-M-1,
is the public face of the gun lobby, but the backbone of the NRA is
the obdurate refusal of many gun owners to acknowledge that any law
to curb the use of guns by criminals, the deranged, or the
temporarily discombobulated is ipso facto a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Having worn for many months what he acknowledges is ''the
bullseye on my back'' for being the Bad Guy who croaked the assault
weapon ban in his first big test as speaker of the House, Rep. Tom
Finneran (D-Dorchester) jumps into the shark tank Thursday for a
modified, pared-down package of limits on high-powered,
rapid-firing guns.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Ways and Means panel will usher out the 90-page
bill crafted in compromise by Rep. Paul Casey (D-Winchester), House
chair of the Public Safety Committee. Advocates of an outright ban
on the controversial assault weapons, like Sen. Cheryl Jacques
(D-Needham), say the bill is flawed because it still allows
existing assault weapons to be exchanged under slightly stricter
laws requiring a special new license from the owner's local police.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, vows Finneran, the House will begin voting.
In the past, rural and suburban legislators have tended to vote
with gun owners, and city reps to be for tighter restrictions.
Finneran has reached an understanding with Rep. John Slattery
(D-Peabody), an outright-ban advocate, who, the speaker says,
acknowledges the outright-ban forces are shy between six and ten
votes on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Since Slattery's vote was criticial to defeating the capital
punishment bill pushed unsuccessfully by Acting Gov. Cellucci, the
Peabody rep has become a high-profile liberal, and his making
common cause with Finneran and Casey probably enhances chances of
passage Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Finneran argued the bill he's pushing is
aimed at ''weapons of high-capacity -- ten rounds or more to an
ammunition clip -- that can level a restaurant, a schoolyard, or a
train car.'' Notorious shootouts in all those sorts of gathering
places in recent years have fueled a national campaign to cut down
on high-powered, rapid firing pieces that can slay dozens in a
matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''A gun vote has never been easy,'' said Finneran, harder for
some rural reps than a vote to raise taxes, which is the usual
high-water mark for degree of difficulty in this era. A number of
other restrictions aimed at prodding owners to separate ammunition
from the firearm, and new penalties for overly casual storage in
households with children, plus refusal to provide licenses to
owners with outstanding warrants, will be debated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran was excoriated by gun-control advocates in the initial
go-round, because he named to a conference committee on the assault
weapon ban passed in the Senate a legislator, now departed, who
effectively sabotaged the effort. John Rosenthal of Stop Handgun
Violence claimed Finneran caved in to the gun lobby as a payoff to
the 32 (out of 33) Republicans who, in an astonishing manuever,
voted to make him speaker over the front-running Democrat at the
time, Richard Voke.
</P>
<P>
   Having worn the Black Hat as the guy who did in the assault
weapon ban, Finneran makes another foray into the field, this time
expressing cautious hope he can deliver a slim majority of
Democrats for the slimmed-down ban. Finneran points to Slattery's
own head count: ''He can say with more credibility than I that the
Senate version (outright ban) does not have the votes (in the
House).''
</P>
<P>
   If the sort of bill Finneran backs survives the Senate and the
House-Senate horsetrading of a conference committee and reaches the
desk of Gov. Cellucci, predicts Casey, ''He (the governor) will
sign this,'' because it's an election year, and Cellucci presumably
does not want to appear to be in Charlton Heston's satchel.
</P>
<P>
   After a relatively quiet election-year run-up, Finneran's House
seems poised to dispose of a number of issues. Finneran is being
asked by the Roman Catholic Church to facilitate the marshaling of
$4 million in state funds to close a deal to create a 140-unit
family housing project in the South End at the Cathedral of the
Holy Cross under the Archdiocese's Planning Office of Monsignor
Michael Groden.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved a $3 million item that would
enable homeless parents who now are denied access to state-run
shelters if they hold a job earning $6.18 an hour to keep working
for as much as $8.50 an hour and still be eligible for staying in a
shelter. Finneran says he's inclined to go for that.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker is resolutely on the sidelines in the Democratic
gubernatorial primary, and will stay there. And he is definitely
sitting on his hands when it comes to crafting legislation to
benefit the New England Patriots and their unending schemes to get
state money for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As a 155-pound center and linebacker in high school, Finneran
has a taste for the game. But Patriots owner, Bob Kraft, he howls,
``wants the taxpayers to buy the land -- and give it back to him!
Hello?'' The huge TV contract the NFL signed makes state aid all
the less likely, Finneran affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Of much more interest to him, he said, is a looming debate on a
major restructuring of the mandatory sentencing framework which
many lawyers and judges claim has created disparities in sentencing
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   With 10,000 prisoners in state cells, and 12,000 more in county
facilities, the burden of confining inmates at the rate of up to
$35,000 per prisoner per year is escalating out of control, he
said. Finneran's legal adviser, Bill Kennedy, has brokered a series
of meetings with judges, district attorneys, public defenders and
others to come up with a compromise set of reforms that will give
judges more leeway, in certain cases, to adjust levels of
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1.6 million Americans currently behind bars in
this country, and another 400,000 or so paid to guard, feed, doctor
and transport them, the 2 million-man American prison Army is too
costly a solution to America's criminality problems. If Finneran
can manage a sensible start at restraining the lock-'em-up
mentality, that legacy will endure long after his machinations on
the assault weapon ban.
</P>
<P>
   One irony of the departure of Bill Weld from the governor's
office, said Finneran, is that Weld came into power boasting of his
hostility to the convicted. But he turned around some in six years
to the point where ``Weld was prepared to do it (approve sentencing
restructuring). His mind had shifted.'' Where Cellucci's mind will
shift in an election year on the controversial issues of criminal
sentencing is another matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
