<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-OCEANS-ART-60     06-12 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OCEANS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON EXTENDS COASTAL OIL-DRILLING BAN BY 10 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ga., Wash., Hawaii, Puerto Rico)  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ President Clinton, navigating a middle course
between environmentalists and oil companies, announced Friday a
ten-year extension of the current moratorium on oil drilling off
virtually all American ocean coastlines.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also placed several existing marine sanctuaries
permanently off-limits to oil exploration. The areas include the
Channel Islands and Monterey Bay sanctuaries in California, the
Florida Keys, Gray's Reef in Georgia and the Olympic Coast
sanctuary off Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium does not, however, affect areas off the Texas and
Louisiana coasts, where extensive drilling has been going on for
years, nor does it protect any new areas not already covered by the
drilling ban first imposed by President Bush in 1990, including the
coastlines of the Southeastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, calling the oceans ``the world's last great frontier,''
also signed an executive order Friday to expand programs to
preserve and restore coral reefs in U.S. waters. He proposed new
spending of $6 million to restore 18 damaged reefs in Florida, the
Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, Guam and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking against a sparkling backdrop of Monterey Bay, the
nation's largest marine sanctuary, the president said that offshore
oil activity threatens fish populations and fragile coastal
ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
   Although there have been relatively few drilling-related oil
spills in American waters, Clinton said, ``Even under the best of
circumstances, is it really worth the risk?''
</P>
<P>
   With worldwide oil supplies plentiful and domestic gasoline
prices at near-historic lows, extending the moratorium carries
little political risk for the president.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry, always interested in finding new petroleum
sources, reacted harshly to the president's announcement, saying
that banning further offshore exploration worsens the nation's
dependence on imported oil.
</P>
<P>
   The ban, issued under the Outer Continental Shelf Lands Act,
covers virtually all of the coasts of the North Atlantic,
California, Washington, Oregon, southwest Florida, New England, the
Mid-Atlantic and the North Aleutian Basin of Alaska, according to
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling in these waters is currently banned through 2002; the
president's action would extend that period to 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists would have preferred a permanent ban on all
drilling, but gave Clinton credit for using his executive authority
to halt the activity for an additional 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's commitment is impressive and heartening,''
Mark Massara, director of the Sierra Club's coastal programs, said
in an interview Friday, ``but it doesn't go far enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton used an executive order to extend the ban,
Friday's action could be rescinded by a future president or revoked
in a national oil emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need legislation from Congress to ensure permanent
protection,'' Massara said.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Steiner of the Earth Island Institute was less generous in
his assessment, calling Clinton's action ``a drop in the ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's giving us what we already had - a moratorium on
drilling,'' Steiner added. ``It's a politically popular thing to do
but it doesn't really take us anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, the industry's largest trade
group, reacted more bitterly. ``The moratoria's extension is
unfortunate because it ignores the near-perfect performance of the
American petroleum industry in operating offshore in a safe and
environmentally sensitive manner,'' said Chris Kelley, a spokesman
for the Institute.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This regrettable decision which is not in the long-term
interests of American consumers is particularly bad policy at a
time of record U.S. energy imports,''he continued, reading a
prepared statement. ``Ultimately, the extension means a smaller
future supply of domestically produced oil and natural gas and a
lost opportunity to create American jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie McGinty, chairman of the White House Council on Economic
Quality, said that criticism from environmentalists and the
industry was a sign that the president had found a workable
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has charted the most prudent course here,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his appearance here, at the first National Oceans
Conference, to announce a number of other proposals, including an
$800 million fund to repair and expand the nation's seaports and a
ban on the sale or import of Atlantic swordfish weighing less than
33 pounds to help sustain swordfish stocks.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced the administration's intention to build two
new deep-sea observatories and to develop two high-technology
undersea probes to explore exotic sea life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We propose to provide new submersibles and other advanced
tools for mapping and exploring the world's last great frontier,''
Clinton said as a sailboat drifted across the bay behind him. ``I'd
kind of like to go down there myself someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
