<HEADLINE>
IN SOME MERGERS, BUYER AND SELLER EMPLOY SAME ADVISER
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the cozy world of corporate finance, bankers and
lawyers are finding themselves straddling both sides of merger
negotiations these days in what some critics say is a risky move
for companies and their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every large Wall Street firm has found itself
representing the interests of both buyers and sellers at one time
or another. It is not illegal, but industry observers question
whether corporate boards should allow the practice to occur at all.
(Bankers typically help negotiate a fair price. Lawyers ensure the
terms of the contract are upheld.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a director, and I would never let someone be on both sides
of the table,'' said Samuel Hayes, a professor of finance at the
Harvard Business School. ``I find that so contrary to my perception
about the way things should work.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Wachtell Lipton Rosen &AMP; Katz provided legal
advice for both Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD Corp. in their
$30 billion merger; Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.advised both Italy's Credito
Italiano and Unicredito in their $10 billion combination; and just
this week, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. advised both Norwest Corp.and Wells
Fargo &AMP; Co.on their $34 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and lawyers who specialize in merger negotiations say
dual representation is rare _ more common in the late 1980s than
today _ and only done if a deal is friendly. Wachtell was not
called until after Banc One and First Chicago negotiated most of
the details themselves, including price, bank executives have said.
And in the case of the Italian deal, a Merrill Lynch banker came up
with the idea and pitched it to both companies, so no other bankers
were needed except to give the fairness opinion _ a third-party
assessment of whether an offer appears fair to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Wells Fargo and Norwest, Goldman dispatched two
separate teams, one for each company, and Credit Suisse First
Boston, a unit of CS Holdings, was hired by Wells Fargo to give a
fairness opinion, for some added assurance. Reatha Clark King, a
member of the Norwest board, said the decision to allow Goldman to
represent dual interests was among many issues presented to the
board, including use of the same auditor. ``I felt comfortable it
was an appropriate arrangement,'' she said. A Goldman
representative would not comment on pending transactions.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Securities and Exchange Commission said
working for both sides does not pose a conflict if all
relationships are disclosed to investors. Still, said Joseph
Auerbach, a Boston-based merger lawyer, ``It may be legal, but it's
very bad business.''
</P>
<P>
   It is especially troublesome if a third bidder shows up or if a
dispute erupts over the contract. Wells Fargo shareholders, for
instance, have already filed a lawsuit seeking to stop the merger
with Norwest, saying Wells Fargo spurned other potential bidders
and did not shop for the best price, according to news reports.
(Shareholder suits disputing the price of a proposed merger are
common.) U.S. Bancorp, which had its own banker, had expressed
interest early on in buying Wells Fargo, said people close to the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rogers, manager of T. Rowe Price's Equity Income fund,
which as of December owned 225,000 shares of Wells Fargo, said
directors should be mindful of the appearance of a conflict,
whether there is one or not. ``Just because it starts out friendly,
doesn't mean it ends up that way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And even more companies could become the subject of lawsuits if
investors believe the current wave of merger negotiations have been
mishandled in any way. ``I can't conceive of any person serving my
interests, and the man I'm doing business with,'' said Auerbach.
``There are shareholder lawyers out there who are just looking for
these kinds of cases.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
