<HEADER>
A7215 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGHTINGALES-REVIEW-H     06-12 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHTINGALES-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES' MAKES AN IMPRESSIVE DEBUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``Not About Nightingales'' burns up the stage at the
Aerial Theater, where the rediscovered early Tennessee Williams
prison drama is making its U.S. debut.
</P>
<P>
   That holds true in the most incendiary moments, particularly the
pivotal sequence in which prisoners on a hunger strike are roasted
alive in a hellhole nicknamed ``Klondike.'' Director Trevor Nunn's
riveting production conveys the scene's visceral horror in
unflinching detail, while Richard Hoover's fantastically effective
setting heightens the impact, its gridwork floor allowing searing
light and geysers of steam to burst from below. Who could argue
with one con's description of this torture chamber as ``a little
suburb of hell?''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Nightingales'' blazes with theatricality throughout.
Despite some uneven passages and the overfamiliarity of certain
prison drama archetypes, this long-lost effort by the 27-year-old
Williams is fired with the indignation and raw talent of a young
artist finding his passion and beginning to find his distinctive
voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am at last becoming sincerely aroused in my social
consciousness,'' Williams wrote in his journal at roughly the time
of ``Nightingales''' inception. Little wonder that newspaper
reports of real-life atrocities at a Pennsylvania prison inspired
Williams to write this wild yet powerful rant. It resonates chiefly
on the plight of the incarcerated, but also echoes other
Depression-era concerns, from the dearth of jobs on the outside to
the rise of fascism in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Williams centered his play on the titanic struggle between
hardened prisoner Butch O'Fallon, who leads the hunger strike
seeking decent food, and the monstrous warden Boss Whalen, who
resolves to whip his charges into line with increasingly harsh
punishments, culminating in their trip to Klondike. Butch reflects
Boss Whalen's own thinking in his line, ``a con ain't a human
being.'' Both thuggish power mongers are repeatedly compared to
Mussolini and Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing center stage are two other protagonists, more rounded,
human figures who give the audience an entry into this nightmarish
realm.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Crane arrives at the prison in the opening scene, desperate
to win a job as the warden's stenographer. At the start, she
naively parrots the prison's publicity (``It's supposed to be a
model institution'') to the pitiable mother of a prisoner who has
been driven to a mental breakdown. She gradually awakens to the
terrible truth about Boss Whalen and his operation. Yet she
resolves to ``keep her mouth shut,'' at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Eva falls in love with Canary Jim, a model trusty who is just a
month away from possible parole after 10 years of biting his tongue
and kowtowing to Boss Whalen (for which the other prisoners despise
him). Like Eva, he is caught in the bind between principle and
self-preservation as the prison revolt gathers steam.
</P>
<P>
   Jim is the most frequent outlet for the author's voice _ whether
in his desire to incorporate new words and ideas he has discovered
in his writings for the prison newspaper, or in his musing on the
human condition. When Jim describes ``the wall around every person,
the cage you carry with you, wherever you go,'' one hears early
indications of the Williams who would win fame for works from ``The
Glass Menagerie'' to ``Night of the Iguana.''
</P>
<P>
   One recognizes Williams' sure dramatic instincts at other
points. In one scene, he shrewdly juxtaposes Boss Whalen's most
innocent and most monstrous moments _ baby-talking with his little
girl over the phone, then moments later, recalling how his beatings
broke Jim's spirit and scarred him for life. Elsewhere, in Butch's
dream of seeing his dance-hall girlfriend again, or Eva's final,
breathless plea that she and Jim get a chance at a life together,
flashes of brilliance leap from the surrounding purple.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time, however, ``Nightingales'' has less in common
with the mature Williams than with the agitprop Depression-era
dramas of Clifford Odets and 1930s prison flicks. The rising cry of
``Don't eat it'' that launches the hunger strike recalls the
rabble-rousing ``Strike!'' that climaxes Odets' ``Waiting for
Lefty.'' Jim's speech about how the dictionary is ``no good anymore
because we need a new one with a new set of definitions'' echoes
the inevitable moment in Odets plays when an idealist calls for a
new social order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nightingales'' also is informed by such movies as ``The Big
House'' and ``The Last Mile.'' Williams sketches the requisite
prison types: black, Jewish, Hispanic, newly arrived well-to-do kid
who is overly optimistic about his lawyer springing him soon (he is
doomed, of course). The traditional prison-flick touches also are
present: the riot with inmates clanging tin dishes against the
bars, the searchlights seeking out figures hiding in the prison
yard.
</P>
<P>
   Williams jotted onto the news clippings that inspired the play:
``And they say my play is melodramatic!'' Point taken. Even life
sometimes is melodramatic. But somewhere amid this play's melodrama
is a real indictment of an inhumane system and genuine sympathy for
the underdog.
</P>
<P>
   Hoover's setting underscores the prison movie connection by
depicting a monochromatic world of black, white and gray. The
Aerial Theater has been reconfigured to re-create the Royal
National Theater's Cottesloe Theater in London, where
``Nightingales'' premiered earlier this year. It impresses from the
moment one enters. At one end stands a two-tier block of prison
cells. At the other is the warden's office, backed by a towering
wall of file drawers, the prisoners' lives reduced to statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Within this space, Nunn creates a taut drama, whipping Williams'
sometimes unwieldy saga into shape as decisively as Boss Whalen
controls his cons. His secure grasp of visual and dramatic style,
and deft editing, has made this potentially problematic play into a
coherent whole. The air of anxious anticipation, punctuated by
outbursts of violence, is sustained throughout. Nunn makes
evocative use of the tantalizing hints of the outside world, like
the voices and music from an excursion boat that passes the island
prison.
</P>
<P>
   A strong cast gives its all to this rugged enterprise. Corin
Redgrave's reptilian Boss Whalen is a piece of work, a monstrous
monument to insensitivity. Yet he has just the right touch of
robust bravado to make it believable that Whalen could fool
visitors with his slap-on-the-back posturing.
</P>
<P>
   James Black acts Butch O'Fallon with a rough-hewn vitality and
determination. Brash and cocky, he is plainly in the
Cagney/Robinson tough guy tradition. You believe this guy would
brave the horrors of Klondike in an effort to best Boss Whalen.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Parker Lee makes a Depression heroine of Eva _ desperate,
plucky, increasingly committed to standing up to injustice. Her
portrayal is warm, sympathetic and totally persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   As Canary Jim, Finbar Lynch strikes the right balance between
earthly need and idealistic impulse to make this multifaceted
figure come to life. He makes palpable the character's torment at
being considered a traitor by his fellow cons.
</P>
<P>
   There is vivid work throughout the company. Jude Akuwudike
brings battered dignity to The Queen, the gay inmate lamenting a
lifetime of persecution. Mark Dexter's Swifty deftly illustrates
the newcomer's horrible destruction. Sandra Dickinson contributes
two sharply etched characterizations, as the careworn mother, and
later as Butch's remembered kewpie doll girlfriend, with a
distinctive Shirley Booth voice. Dion Graham is warm and affable as
the well-liked Ollie (doomed, of course). And Tom Hodgkins and
Noble Shropshire register neatly as contrasting chaplains, a
crusader that Whalen fires and the malleable dupe he uses.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Nightingales'' will seem obvious to contemporary
sensibilities _ as in the Jewish prisoner's speech about being born
to persecution. Yet in this potent production, most of it is
undeniably effective.
</P>
<P>
   Williams must have had fire on the brain early in his career.
His first Broadway bound-play, ``Battle of Angels'' (which would
close in Boston in 1941), involved a climactic fire onstage and was
at one point called ``Figures in Flame.'' In ``Not About
Nightingales,'' despite imperfections, the fire of something urgent
to say never dies out.
</P>
<P>
   The play runs through July 3.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
