<HEADLINE>
A SCHOOL BUS RIDE TO AVOID 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Forget about daredevils. Forget about
thrill-seekers who skydive or bungee jump or tame lions for
jollies. And forget about people who don't actually live with their
kids, day by day, sweating out each perilous second of those
childhood years.
</P>
<P>
   Every custodial parent knows that if you really want a real
scare, just kiss your kid goodbye and send that kid out the door. I
raised two. Believe me, those parental terrors gnaw at your gut.
It's the dirty little secret about parenthood that you never find
out about until it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I listened the other day with such sympathy to
Theresa Carrasquillo's story.
</P>
<P>
   She works for the State of New York. She has three kids _ one
11, another 8 and a 5-year-old. Her kids go to the Albany School
for the Humanities. They ride a bus operated by Albany Yellow
Communications, a troubled company that holds the district's bus
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Yellow has had all kinds of problems _ drivers who drink
and drive, kids left on buses. A neighboring district just went to
a judge and got permission to break its contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, she put her kids on the school bus the other day
and went to work with that familiar sinking feeling in her middle.
Her kids are supposed to call her when they get home from school.
That day Theresa Carrasquillo received no call. Panic set in.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she called Albany Yellow Communications. Where aPe]d
</P>
</TEXT>
