<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION RALLY IN NIGERIA IS ANSWERED WITH TEAR GAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ In the first showdown between Nigeria's
new military leadership and promoters of democracy, hundreds of
protesters braved a powerful deployment of police and soldiers in
Lagos on Friday to mount a demonstration at a downtown market.
</P>
<P>
   After a morning of wary quiet in which schools remained closed
and few people ventured outside, chanting protesters suddenly
turned out in the afternoon near the Yaba market, and witnesses
said the security forces responded with tear gas and shots in the
air.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd dispersed, but gathered again, local journalists said,
and the organizer of the demonstration, Chief Gani Fawehinmi, began
to speak. His speech was interrupted by tear gas and he was
arrested, along with Dupe Abiola, wife of Moshood K.O. Abiola, the
presumed winner of Nigeria's last multiparty elections. The
elections, held five years ago Friday, were annulled by the
Nigerian army, and Abiola has been in jail almost ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was planned weeks ago to commemorate that
election. But the rally took on dramatically increased importance
after the sudden death of the country's dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha,
on Monday, reportedly of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha's death has emboldened the opponents of military rule,
many of whom demand that the military make way for Abiola.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha's successor, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, has sent mixed
messages about his intentions since being sworn in as president
early Tuesday. A career military man who has never held political
office, he immediately pledged to hand over power to an elected
government by Oct. 1, a promise already made by Abacha.
</P>
<P>
   But the new leader also disappointed those who were hoping for a
departure in the country's policies, when he said he would follow
his predecessor's ``socio-economic program'' in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Nigerian military officers and former political
advisers say Abubakar has no interest in holding power for himself
and has little regard for the political program of Abacha. They
contend that he is desperately trying to buy time to shore up his
base in the Byzantine military structure and work out a transition
on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Abubakar, who has made no public appearances since his short
speech to the nation on Tuesday, was reported Friday to be meeting
with other senior officers and with members of the national
electoral commission in order to revive plans for elections before
October.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the five approved parties have reportedly been
summoned to Abuja, the capital, for meetings with the general this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Many people in the army, as well as retired officers and
civilian leaders, began urging Abubakar to scrap his predecessor's
transition plans, either by holding fresh elections, free of
military control, or by bringing Abiola into a transitional
government of ``national unity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody killed Abacha, so nobody should have to carry his
water,'' said Omo Omoruyi, a senior civilian adviser to past
Nigerian leaders. ``Abubakar is going to have to decide if he is
willing to go to the grave known as the man who tried to solve this
country's problems, or as the man who simply tried to fill the seat
until he was carried to his grave.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of Abubakar's first measures was to declare a seven-day
mourning period, perhaps to give himself some breathing space. But
there has been no respite, either from the promoters of democracy,
who see their moment in Abacha's death, or from lobbies within the
military. Some army factions are committed to keeping power; others
would like to see the army return to its barracks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition there are regional rifts in the military:
Northerners have dominated the military regimes and southerners
resent what they say has been their exclusion from executive office
or positions of command.
</P>
<P>
   The rifts are mirrored in civilian politics. While most of the
southern-based opposition groups profess some allegiance to Abiola,
leaders of the Ibo, who fought for secession during the bloody
civil war in the late 1960s, seem to have foreclosed any hope of
common cause.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Abiola should head a government now, Chukwumeka Ojukwu,
a leading Ibo politician and leader of the self-declared Biafran
republic during the civil war, told the BBC: ``Absolutely not.
Adversity is not a qualification for the presidency. There have
been so many wrongs since 1960 that Nigerians must turn the page
and look forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Nigerians express the fear that, as in the past, elements
in the military will exploit the regional and ethnic rifts among
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is whether the civilian politicians have
learned the lessons of the hard years of dictatorship,'' said
Richard Joseph, an expert in Nigerian affairs at Emory University
in Atlanta, who says a united front is critical. ``If not, they'll
just re-open the door for the military.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
