<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN, SACHS PARTNERS HUDDLE TO STUDY PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The partners of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. met at a
suburban New York conference center Friday to consider a proposal
to turn the firm, Wall Street's last major private partnership,
into a public company.
</P>
<P>
   The 190 partners are debating strategy, including the
possibility of a public sale of shares. Half a dozen times in
recent years they have considered the same question and elected to
stay private. Some partners have indicated that they do not favor a
public offering at this time.
</P>
<P>
   But some Goldman bankers have said that the stock market's high
level and Goldman's own rich profits _ it is expected to earn more
than $2 billion in this year's first half compared with $3 billion
for all of last year _ make this the best time in recent history to
sell shares.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Goldman faces intense competitive pressures from many
of its rivals, which are already public firms.
</P>
<P>
   The partners have often held their annual retreat at the Doral
Arrowwood resort in Rye Brook, N.Y.. This year, however, the firm
selected a more secluded site, the Palisades Executive Conference
Center, in Palisades, N.Y. A receptionist at the conference center
confirmed that several Goldman partners were there, but said that
she had instructions to block all telephone calls to the rooms.
</P>
<P>
   A Goldman spokesman said the firm would probably announce on
Sunday whether or not the partners backed the plan to go public. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
