<HEADER>
A7231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACAO-CHINA-BOS &LR;      06-12 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACAO-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME WAVE THREATENS COLONY'S HANDOVER TO CHINA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACAO _ Not long ago, this Portuguese enclave on the south China
coast was considered a sleepy tourist destination, as famous for
its cobblestone alleys and European-style churches as its neon-lit
casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Macao is better known as a modern-day Casablanca, a mecca
for organized crime, loan-sharking, prostitution, and money
laundering, and the picturesque backdrop for gangland killings.
</P>
<P>
   With just 18 months before Macao returns to Chinese rule, a
high-profile crime wave is threatening a smooth handover. Led by
gangs that skim profits from the legal gambling industry, the
violence could undermine good relations between China and Portugal,
the economic and social future of this 450-year-old port town and
the image of a happily reunified China.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Macao's hit men targeted rival gangsters and spared
law-abiding citizens. But the recent executions in broad daylight
of three security officials _ a top gambling inspector, a marine
policeman, and the driver for the secretary for security _ have
frightened away tourists and investors and rocked the tight-knit
community. And for the first time in otherwise harmonious
negotiations over the transfer of power, recriminations have flown
between Beijing and Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing views Macao's return on Dec. 20, 1999, as the next step
in the reunification of China after the handover last year of Hong
Kong, its richer neighbor 38 miles to the east. The example of
Macao running its own affairs, Beijing believes, might persuade
Taiwan to rejoin China with promises of self-rule. But if
disintegrating order in Macao forces Beijing to renounce its
hands-off vow, both Macao's autonomy and Taiwanese unification
sentiment will suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong residents feared that Chinese rule would erode their
civil rights. Ironically, the crime wave in Macao has made many
residents eager for a speedier return to China or for Chinese
intervention before the handover. They consider Beijing to be tough
on crime and Lisbon overly concerned with the rights of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management of this territory is laid-back, and it
shouldn't be. People do (crime) because they know they are not
going to get caught,'' said Edmund Ho, a prominent banker and vice
president of Macao's legislative assembly, who is the front-runner
to become Macao's first Chinese leader after the handover.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, he said, ``The whole framework for the handover
was `no change,' because Hong Kong was considered so successful.
Unfortunately, we don't have a `successful Macao experience.' The
transition is an opportunity to make change and make things right.
... After 1999, Macao will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the famous debates in Hong Kong over the preservation of
democracy, Ho said Macao people ``are more concerned about economic
issues and security.''
</P>
<P>
   Leong Heng-kao, a pro-Beijing legislator, has called on China to
send troops to Macao after the handover, and many average citizens
agree. ``The Chinese government is strict and they have the death
penalty. I want China to come now,'' said Lao Kin-chang, a
43-year-old security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Portuguese officials defend Macao's record by pointing out that
crime here is still low relative to major cities, and residents
should be thankful that human rights are not compromised. Macao
will retain its criminal code after the handover. The death penalty
will remain outlawed, although it exists in China. Similarly,
gambling will remain legal here, though banned in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Colonel Manuel Geraldes, adviser to the Secretary for
Security, notes that even with 29 homicides last year, a 40 percent
rise over 1996, the murder rate in this territory of 450,000 people
ranks significantly lower than those of Washington or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a false image of Macao,'' Geraldes complained. ``We
have problems in Portugal too, and we feel safer here than in
Lisbon.'' Overall crime here fell 2.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But many residents say the perception of Macao as a lawless city
of sin stems from the willingness of ``triad'' gangsters to carry
out their vendettas in public.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 11 murders and some 100 firebombings this year,
including attacks on police property. On March 24, a top gambling
inspector was assassinated on the city's busiest avenue at
lunchtime, a block from the main casino where police cars were
stationed. Two days later, a police officer was shot to death in
morning rush hour traffic with his wife and daughter in the car
with him.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of disdain for authorities, the man believed to be
the boss of Macao's biggest triad gave media interviews a few
months ago to promote ``Casino,'' a movie he financed that
glorifies his life as a gangster. He even managed to shoot key
scenes in Macao, despite the government's rejection of his
application for a filming permit.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, Wan Kuok-koi, or ``Broken Tooth Koi,'' was
arrested at the LisboaCQ Hotel, home to the city's most famous
casino, 12 hours after the Judicial Police Director narrowly
escaped death when a bomb destroyed his car. Wan remains in
custody, thanks to anti-triad laws that took effect last year.
</P>
<P>
   More than 135 people have been arrested under the new laws,
including three charged this week. The new code allows video and
audiotapes as evidence and punishes triad membership with up to 10
years in prison. Since the law went into effect, police say they
have arrested twice as many suspects as during the same period a
year ago. And since the bombing of the police director's car, the
campaign has intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Many Macao residents accustomed to the leniency of the
Portuguese _ or the corruption and intimidation of authorities _
are stunned by these statistics. They are used to sagas like the
trial last year of Wan for triad membership. A judge found him
innocent and then retired unexpectedly the next day to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police have been corrupted since the early days of
gambling here,'' alleged one well-connected native who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``If they want to put someone in jail, they
should start with the top echelons of government and go on down.''
</P>
<P>
   Geraldes admits the police force is ``not pure,'' noting that 34
officers were dismissed last year. But the majority, he said, are
simply outnumbered in the battle against crime. Wan's triad, 14K,
has 10,000 local members _ compared with 4,300 police officials.
Police say the problem is compounded by additional criminals from
China.
</P>
<P>
   Some frustrated Chinese officials have criticized Portugal
publically for trying to pass the crime problem on to them. But
this week, Chinese police arrested several hundred suspected drug
traffickers and prostitutes in Zhuhai, the Chinese city that
borders Macao. Portugal has dispatched intelligence agents here and
promised to send extra crimefighters from Lisbon within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet crime has already taken its toll on Macao's economy, which
is heavily dependent on gambling and tourism. More than a quarter
of the territory's gross domestic product comes from gaming, and
the government earns half its revenue from gambling taxes, which
fell in April to a three-year low, according to the Macao Daily
News.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist arrivals, which consist mostly of casino visitors, fell
14 percent from 1996, and one hotel executive said her business was
down 30 percent. On a recent afternoon, Chinese and Russian
prostitutes and loansharks trolling for customers outnumbered
tourists in the LisboaCQ Hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   While neighboring Hong Kong is an international financial
center, Macao has few big enterprises apart from casinos, and city
officials worry that Macao's failure to diversify will eventually
render it a seedy backwater.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities here say the crime wave stems from Asia's economic
downturn, which has thrown triads into battle for diminishing
gambling-related profits. The more painful truth is that Macao's
recession and turf battles predated the downturn. Efforts to lure
investors with a new airport and modern offices have been
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But the self-rule promised by Beijing after the handover will
force the residents here to find solutions for the crime wave and
the depressed economy behind it, according to Domingo Fezaz Vital,
diplomatic adviser to the Governor of Macao.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macao people are learning from Hong Kong next door the price
of autonomy and what it means. They are conducting their business,
and we'll have to do the same,'' said Vital. ``Dad and Mom will not
come. They will help as best they can, but Macao will have to solve
its own problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
