<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA EVENT POINTS TO WIDE-OPEN RACE FOR GOP NOMINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ It was billed as the first major meeting of
Republican presidential prospects, and the ``First in the Nation
Gala'' had all the trimmings: a dozen candidates, 2,500 Iowa's GOP
activists, a C-Span television broadcast, and a national press
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   But last night's gathering was most notable for what was
missing. There was no self-proclaimed moderate, no elder statesman,
no front-runner _ and no obvious signal about who will become the
GOP nominee in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The message from Iowa, which traditionally holds the first major
presidential caucus, is that the Republican Party is about to
embark on one of the most wide open races for the presidential
nomination in decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no one ahead right now,'' said Iowa
Republican Party chairman Steve Grubbs. ``It is completely up in
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The most visible prospects here were two men who lost out in
1996, Lamar Alexander and Steve Forbes, as well as Senator John
Ashcroft of Missouri and Representative John Kasich of Ohio. But
several possible key players such as Texas Governor George W. Bush
and former Vice President Dan Quayle didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the state's Republican convention provided insights that
will be studied by those who are considering entering the contest.
The pre-campaign is focused on a two-pronged strategy, with most of
the prospects vowing to cut taxes and seeking to woo religious
conservatives, especially those affiliated with groups such as the
Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to winning elections on the Republican side is
to energize both of the currents in the Republican river,''
Ashcroft said. ``There is both the economic current and the social
current.''
</P>
<P>
   While Iowa is a relatively moderate state, voting for Clinton in
the last two elections, the Republican caucuses are well known for
being dominated by religious conservatives. According to 1996 exit
polls, 40 percent of those who participated in the GOP caucuses
considered themselves religious conservatives. The conventional
wisdom is that any candidate who can gain the support of about
15,000 such activists has a good shot at winning the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grubbs said, that leaves plenty of room for a more
moderate, establishment-oriented candidate to show up and stake a
claim on the remaining 60 percent of the caucus-goers. But so far,
no one has emerged to claim that ground, perhaps because of the
abysmal showing of 1996's moderate candidates, Senator Richard
Lugar of Indiana and Senator Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania. Grubbs
said he invited New Jersey Governor Christine Todd Whitman, one of
the party's leading moderates, but she declined to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the prospects came here hoping to sign up activists for
possible campaigns, while some came simply to float their names.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Marc Racicot of Montana, who prompted no quarrel when
he introduced himself as nationally unknown, fell into the latter
category. With his slightly bemused manner and telegenic looks, the
49-year-old governor evoked comparisons with the way a little-known
Arkansas governor ran for president. Racicot, the only candidate
who sat through a news conference of his colleagues, prompted
laughter when he said, ``This is a very unusual culture I have been
introduced to.'' He declined to attack anyone, saying, ``I don't
have no particular ax to grind.'' Asked to cite a major issue, he
said he favored the reauthorization of the Endangered Species Act
and a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk here centered on three men who didn't show up:
Bush, Senator John McCain of Arizona, and House Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia. Bush and McCain have said they won't get
involved in presidential politics until they win reelection this
November, while Gingrich has expressed interest in the race but
declined to participate in early cattle shows.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Alexander may have the best organization in Iowa, with
plenty of money to spread around from his political action
committee, which is chaired by Iowa Governor Terry Branstad.
Alexander, thanks partly to the residual effect of his 1996 race,
also has the support of Iowa's House speaker and numerous other
high-profile politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander is portraying himself as a different candidate
than the one who placed third here in 1996. In the last campaign,
Alexander was known mostly for his red plaid shirt and his call for
cutting Congress' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday Alexander switched tactics by proposing a new tax
code, including a doubled deduction for charitable contributions
and an increase in the child exemption to 8,000 from $2,650 for
preschool children.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will see from me is less red-and-black shirt and more
talk about character,'' Alexander said in an interview. ``Not just
Mr. Clinton's character, but the character of the country. There
will be less talk about `cut their pay and send them home,' and
more talk about taking responsibility for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, a millionaire publisher who was widely perceived as
trying to buy his way to victory in Iowa in 1996, this time is
combining an aggressive media campaign with old-fashioned tactics
such as visiting as many Kiwanis clubs as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Forbes's strategy is trying to remold himself as a
social conservative instead of simply being known for his flat-tax
plan. Forbes recently took the unusual step of endorsing two
Christian Coalition leaders who ran for the state legislature
against incumbent Republicans in a primary earlier this month. Both
candidates lost, but his endorsements were, as he hoped, popular
among religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're facing a moral crisis in this country,'' Forbes said.
``I've endorsed a number of kindred souls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes faces a lot of competition for the religious
conservative vote. Alan Keyes, the radio talk-show host who ran for
president in 1996, lashed out at Forbes as a ``phony.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes's professed interest in the moral agenda is totally
false,'' Keyes said at a candidate news conference, noting that
Forbes has supported Republicans such as New Jersey's Whitman, who
favors abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, the House Budget Committee chairman whose hopes rely
partly on his image as a hip conservative who balances budgets and
listens to the Grateful Dead, got a taste of the kind of questions
that await him as a presidential candidate. Asked how he would deal
with a widely discussed computer bug that could devastate many
computers on Jan. 1, 2000, Kasich said, ``First, I need to learn
how to get on the Web myself,'' referring to the Internet's World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, the former vice president, citing a scheduling conflict,
sent his wife Marilyn to the gala. The other prospects who attended
included: Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire, Representative Bob
Barr of Georgia, former Reagan White House aide and talk-show host
Oliver North, and former Reagan aide and Family Research Council
head Gary Bauer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
