<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCHOOL BUS RIDE TO AVOID 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Forget about daredevils. Forget about
thrill-seekers who skydive or bungee jump or tame lions for
jollies. And forget about people who don't actually live with their
kids, day by day, sweating out each perilous second of those
childhood years.
</P>
<P>
   Every custodial parent knows that if you really want a real
scare, just kiss your kid goodbye and send that kid out the door. I
raised two. Believe me, those parental terrors gnaw at your gut.
It's the dirty little secret about parenthood that you never find
out about until it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I listened the other day with such sympathy to
Theresa Carrasquillo's story.
</P>
<P>
   She works for the State of New York. She has three kids _ one
11, another 8 and a 5-year-old. Her kids go to the Albany School
for the Humanities. They ride a bus operated by Albany Yellow
Communications, a troubled company that holds the district's bus
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Yellow has had all kinds of problems _ drivers who drink
and drive, kids left on buses. A neighboring district just went to
a judge and got permission to break its contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, she put her kids on the school bus the other day
and went to work with that familiar sinking feeling in her middle.
Her kids are supposed to call her when they get home from school.
That day Theresa Carrasquillo received no call. Panic set in.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she called Albany Yellow Communications. Where are my
kids, she wanted to know?
</P>
<P>
   ``They told me, `We've been trying to call you.' Well, I'd been
at my desk for like an hour and a half, waiting for my kids to
call, which I usually do. Then they told me, `Well, all your kids
are at St. Peter's Hospital. One is complaining of her ankle
hurting, and the other two seem OK.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I get over there, and a police officer told me what
happened. He said the bus driver got distracted. She got on the
wrong side of the road, and she hit a truck. And that's how my
daughter got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter has my work number. When I got to the hospital, it
was right there on her paperwork ... So whoever was at the scene of
the accident, they had my number. They could have called
immediately. No one called.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How's her ankle?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's broken. It's fractured in the growth plate, and she
dislocated her fibia.''
</P>
<P>
   So this was no minor accident, and Theresa Carrasquillo is badly
bent out of shape that she had to find out on her own that her kid
had been seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   What does the bus company have to say about this? They say they
called Theresa Carrasquillo at work and were told she wasn't there.
And then she called them.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said that they hold off contacting parents
until paramedics have an assessment of an injured child's
condition. The district said Theresa Carrasquillo's phone was busy,
and nobody thought to ask an operator to break in.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Carrasquillo says, by the way, that when she's on her
work phone any incoming call rolls over to a secretary's line. And,
she says, she was there, all right.
</P>
<P>
   So believe whomever you please. But the incident points up
broader problems.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, most student records are kept in the schools, not
in the Albany district's central offices. If a kid gets hurt on a
bus after school closes, getting a parent's phone number can be a
chore.
</P>
<P>
   The district hopes to have a central computer operation going by
the end of next year. But this is stone-age stuff for a district
that spends 99 million bucks a year and serves 10,000 kids.
</P>
<P>
   It'll now have three fewer children to transport, however. For
the rest of this school year, Theresa Carrasquillo has decided,
she'll find some other way to get her kids to and from school.
</P>
<P>
   She figures that'll be easier on her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
