<HEADER>
A7236 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-TICKETS-HNS &LR;      06-12 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TICKETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF U.S. OPEN TICKETS STOLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than 6,000 tickets to the U.S. Open were
reported stolen from an office at the Olympic Club's golf course,
where next week's tournament will be held, the San Francisco police
said. The tickets are worth as much as $360,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime between 7 p.m. Tuesday and 8 a.m. Wednesday, at least
one burglar entered an unlocked window in the second story
clubhouse of the Olympic Club, taking two boxes of tickets, police
Lt. Dirk Beijen said. The burglar apparently got easy access to the
window from a low roof nearby, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   No other items were reported missing. The police said they had
no suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't have a lot to go on,'' Beijen said. ``What we
do have we're not talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities fear the stolen passes will flood the scalper
market and cause confusion next week if unwitting fans buy bad
tickets and are refused admission.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Golf Association said Thursday everyone who
has paid for a ticket or is entitled to a pass from sponsors will
receive a legitimate pass.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said the stolen tickets included a mix of day passes
and weekly packages for the event, including many set aside for
corporate sponsors, players and other VIPs.
</P>
<P>
   The event, one of golf's most prestigious tournaments, sold out
in less than 10 hours almost a year ago. Tickets were $30 for a day
for each of the three practice rounds and $60 for each of the four
tournament days. A weeklong pass sold for $225, but in the past
week scalpers have been offering them for as high as $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   The spectator gallery is expected to include about 25,000 paying
fans each day of the tournament. In addition, there also will be
more than 5,000 other people there, including volunteers,
employees, players and guests of sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   A USGA spokesman said security officials would not admit anyone
bearing a ticket with the serial numbers of stolen passes. Police
said all the missing tickets had either a two-inch ``W'' or ``O''
on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be taking more precautions than normal,'' said Mike
Butz, USGA deputy executive director. ``Anybody who tries to access
the golf course (with a stolen pass) during the open will not be
admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The field for this year's event includes 156 of golf's best
players competing for a purse of $3 million with the winner getting
$535,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
