<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS CALL FOR DEATH PENALTY IN TEXAS SLAYING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A call for retribution echoed Friday through
this town where a native son fell victim to an atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance is mine, said the Lord,'' said the father of James
Byrd Jr., who died early last Sunday when he was beaten, chained by
his ankles to the back of a truck, and dragged two miles along a
rutted asphalt road in what police called a racially-motivated hate
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want is justice,'' James Byrd Sr. said, ``and fair
justice is the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   In his call for capital punishment, Byrd voiced the sentiment of
much of the black community in this east Texas town 90 miles from
the prison that houses the state's oft-used execution chamber. But
the Baptist deacon's view also reflects growing support among
blacks nationwide for the death penalty, a trend that collides with
the views of leading civil rights groups and leaders, including the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, who is scheduled to speak today at Byrd's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   After opposing capital punishment for decades, a majority of
blacks _ 57 percent _ support the penalty, according to a poll last
year by the National Opinion Center at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged by senseless slayings and searching for stronger
sanctions, increasing numbers of blacks have put their faith in
legal executions despite statistics that show it has long been a
penalty enforced disproportionately against blacks, even as it is
rarely used _ particularly in Texas _ to punish those who murder
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, two top officers in the Texas chapter of the National
Association for Colored People, an organization resolutely opposed
to capital punishment, have called for the death penalty for Byrd's
killers.
</P>
<P>
   Three Jasper parolees identified by police as white supremacists
are charged with the slaying: Robert Russell Brewer, 31, John
William King, 23, and Shawn Berry, 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP is on record against the death penalty for a number
of good reasons,'' said Lee Alcorn, president of the group's Dallas
branch as he stood outside the jail where the three suspects are
being held without bail. ``But this case is just so gruesome that
if they get the death penalty, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, the NAACP's national president, issued a statement
that did not directly address the issue, though his tone was harsh.
``These cowards,'' Mfume said, ``should never walk the streets
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's murder has changed the beliefs of many in Jasper, where
he was known as an affable amateur musician who had been down on
his luck in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, 49, who had served prison time for theft and forgery, was
walking home from a family party late Saturday night when the three
suspects, including one who recognized Byrd from the parole office,
offered him a ride.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the three drove Byrd to a remote dirt road,
where they beat and kicked him before they chained him to the
pickup truck and dragged him along the road, tearing his body to
pieces. Byrd's head, neck, right arm and torso were scattered along
the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many will say it, but this incident has caused a lot of
people in the community to look differently at the death penalty,''
said Gloria Mays, editor and publisher of the East Texas
Communicator, the region's black newspaper. ``A lot more people are
for it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mays said the incident, the cruelest act she has encountered
since she was a child and saw her father's horse abused, hardened
her support for capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should die for what they did because no human being
should be treated that way,'' Mays said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas prosecutors, rarely hesitant about seeking the death
penalty, said they must be able to prove the three men
intentionally kidnapped Byrd before killing him, to satisfy state
standards for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Since capital punishment was reinstated in 1982, Texas has led
the nation in executions, with more than 150.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper District Attorney Guy James Gray made it clear he wants
to seeks the death penalty in Byrd's case. And as backup, an FBI
task force is investigating the incident as a federal hate crime,
which also can be punishable by death.
</P>
<P>
   When Byrd is buried tomorrow, few mourners are likely to share
Jackson's opposition to the death penalty, which he reiterated in a
visit to Jasper earlier this week. Several other members of Byrd's
family said they favor the death penalty, as did the Rev. Kenneth
Lyons, pastor of the New Bethel Baptist Church, where the funeral
will be held.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said Jackson ``has to speak for political reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't,'' Lyons said. ``I have to speak for the truth,
and that's God's word: He who shall take a life shall also have to
give up his life.''
</P>
<P>
   From the parish house to the paved road where Byrd suffered his
fatal indignity, revulsion at the crime was so prevalent it was
hard to find black residents of Jasper who opposed the death
penalty in this case.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few foes was M.L. Traylor Jr., a distant relative of
Byrd who lives on the road where he died. ``I'm sorry, but I don't
believe in the death penalty,'' Traylor said. ``I don't think
anyone should take anyone else's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
