<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EUROPE-HOW-$ADV14-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLD WORLD GETS A NEW MARKET MAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic showing stock market performance of 10 European
nations leading companies in each nation on map will be sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14) 
(af) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the birth of Euroland less than seven months away, it's
high time for a deep rethinking of how American investors approach
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Euroland is popular shorthand for the one-currency, 11-country
monetary union and financial market area that will come into being
on Jan. 1. It brings with it many promising opportunities for
companies and investors alike.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it threatens to make some familiar investing
strategies obsolete, and it raises the question of whether betting
on just this single-currency market is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have shown a surging interest recently in Europe, with
record flows of cash into European stock mutual funds. But the
American financial services industry does not appear to be in a
rush to change what it is now offering its investors and seems to
be ignoring products like a Euroland index fund or a broad choice
of actively managed Euroland mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some argue that focusing on just the 10 active Euroland
stock markets (Luxembourg has none) would mean missing good returns
elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Euroland concept, from a narrow perspective of creating
funds, is a flawed one,'' said Nicholas Bratt, the head of the
global equity group at Scudder Kemper Investments. ``We would
simply buy the best company we could find in Europe regardless of
is specific domicile.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors face more questions than just geography. The role that
indexes and index funds will play in the new region's markets is
far from certain. And perhaps most important is the developing
shift to a new investing style that selects stocks by sector rather
than by country. Here is how these themes may play out in the new
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Before Euroland, European equity strategists began by picking a
country, based on the forecast for interest rates, growth, earnings
and inflation. Then they chose stocks in countries with the best
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   That system, analysts argue, will not be as effective now,
because the new European Central Bank will try to keep interest
rates and economic performance more in line for all Euroland
countries.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean there will not be differences within
Euroland, but it does mean that the era of making millions by
exploiting them is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it will be what sectors are most promising and what are
the best stocks in that sector,'' said William P. Sterling, global
strategist at BEA Associates, an investment management firm.
</P>
<P>
   This new style spells trouble for popular closed-end
single-country funds which, unless they adapt, will struggle to
produce attractive returns, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It slams the lid down on single-country funds,'' said Michael
T. Porter, a country fund analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Exchange-listed American depository receipts, another familiar
way for Americans to invest in Europe, should remain attractive.
Because they are priced in dollars, trade on American exchanges and
conform to American accounting rules, they are easy for Americans
to follow. (Unlisted ADRs trade over the counter and need not meet
American standards.)
</P>
<P>
   As always, an ADR's dollar value depends on movements in both
the price of the underlying European stock and the value of the
currency. Monetary union will eliminate the currency fluctuations
among member nations, but their shared currency, the euro, will
still rise and fall relative to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Only a minority of top European companies trade as ADRs,
however, and for some investors, the exposure they offer may not be
broad enough.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Bank of New York compiles an index of 107
exchange-listed ADRs for Euroland, but many of the top 10 stocks in
market capitalization for each country are missing. The bank is
designing a product that would allow American investors to buy the
ADR index, but there are no details yet.
</P>
<P>
   American investors love index funds, which simply buy all the
stocks in a widely followed index like the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500.
No Euroland analogue yet exists, and creating one will not be easy.
One obstacle will be distinguishing for Americans between Europe
and Euroland.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones Indexes, along with the French, German and Swiss stock
markets, has started a family of indexes for Europe and for
Euroland collectively called Stoxx.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Capital International introduced a 335-stock
index for Euroland on April 30. Standard &AMP; Poor's, The Financial
Times of London and Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. have a 351-stock Eurobloc
index, and The Financial Times and the London Stock Exchange have a
100-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   But these companies have been more successful in selling their
indexes to fund managers and institutional investors as benchmarks
for performance than in bringing index trading to American
investors. None has a retail product ready to see daylight, though
Dow Jones is promising one.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Crosby, director of global marketing at Morgan Stanley,
said, ``Marketing Europe from a U.S. perspective is not a big
revenue opportunity now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Vanguard Group, the index fund leader, has plans
for a Euroland fund. ``We take a long-term view of things,'' said
Brian S. Mattes, Vanguard's spokesman. ``It must be a durable
investment need, and it must go on for years.'' The company doesn't
think Euroland passes the test.
</P>
<P>
   Index investing by country can be done through the World Equity
Benchmark Shares, or Webs, traded on the American Stock Exchange;
they are based on Morgan Stanley country indexes. But no
pan-European or Euroland Webs are planned.
</P>
<P>
   While there is hardly a rush to offer Euroland plays directly to
American investors, plenty of analysts in the United States and
Europe are trying to anticipate Euroland's effects and to spot ways
to profit.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
