 Friday, June 12, 1998 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Editors: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ENGLISH-ONLY (San Francisco) will not move tonight on The Hearst
News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst News Service\Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7242 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EUROPE-HOW-$AD     06-12 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EUROPE-HOW-$ADV14-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: to profit.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One is the index effect. The new indexes that aspire to become
benchmarks include stocks that received scant attention in the
country-picking era but will now be bought simply because of index
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visibility gainers are the ones in the smaller countries
like Ireland, Austria, Portugal and Belgium,'' said Mark Howdle,
European equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
<P>
   Euroland will also provoke major shifts in existing portfolios,
analysts argue. Money managers in specific European countries who
view Euroland as a single market will de-emphasize domestic stocks
and buy across borders. This shift, which seems to have begun, will
move prices of many issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Scott, the European equity strategist at Lehman Brothers in
London, noted in a recent report that the weighting for German
stocks in a Euroland index would be around 27 percent, but by his
estimate, German institutions and money managers now have 70
percent of their assets in German equities.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this evidence, there is plenty of scope for German
institutions to diversify their portfolios,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts argue that smaller-company stocks will be hurt
most, as they are sold by money managers to make room for bigger
stocks from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Murali Ramaswami, global head of equities derivative research at
Lehman Brothers, said that while European stocks in general were
becoming more sensitive to industry factors than to country
factors, some companies and sectors would continue to be
country-sensitive. He found commercial banks in France, Germany,
Italy and Spain to be in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, he said, the most industry-sensitive stocks varied
from country to country: property and casualty insurance in France;
mining, metals and minerals in Germany, and automobiles and
utilities in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in cross-border mergers within Euroland will also
buoy some stocks, analysts predict, as consolidation picks up speed
in oil, construction and _ especially in Italy _ in financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers taking advantage of monetary union to travel and to
buy second homes may help some Euroland companies. On the other
hand, the simplification of cross-border comparison shopping may
hurt profits of airlines, retailers and brand-name goods makers
accustomed to tailoring their prices from country to country.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts point out that these factors do not add up to a
night-and-day difference between investment opportunities inside
and outside Euroland. American mutual fund managers seem to prefer
Europe to Euroland as a playing field in both stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agree that the unified Euroland government bond market
will be larger and more liquid than the present array of national
markets. But many say it is not an attractive bet right now, while
potentially more enticing markets for corporate bonds and junk
bonds will take time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Askew, executive vice president of Rowe Price-Fleming
International in London, said fixed-income investors would do best
in a broader European or international bond fund that can take
advantage of European opportunities outside Euroland.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are betting on Greece, which hopes to join the
union in the second round a few years from now. The required sharp
cuts in Greek interest rates would mean big capital gains for
bondholders, in the kind of ``convergence play'' that paid off
handsomely as Italy and others prepared for Euroland's birth.
</P>
<P>
   N. Graham Allen, the managing director for global fixed-income
at Wells Capital Management in Los Angeles, likes Britain, the
biggest European player not in Euroland, for the same reason; he
thinks Britain will decide to join before too long.
</P>
<P>
   Equity analysts also say it is difficult to ignore Britain. A
Euroland stock fund, Bratt of Scudder Kemper said, ``omits the
largest stock market in Europe, and that seems undesirable to me.''
He said his company's closed-end New Europe fund also includes
emerging markets like Poland and Hungary that he would be loath to
exclude by investing solely in Euroland.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets are performing well across Europe, so for American
investors, the question of Euroland versus all of Europe may seem
academic. The important choice is whether to invest in Europe, by
any definition, or not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
