<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTRO-GLENN-ART-NYT &LR;      06-12 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRO-GLENN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN EAGERLY AWAITS ASCENT FROM POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John Glenn, the merriest commuter on Capitol
Hill, was talking of the spaceship he will soon be riding and the
joy of weightlessness _ which for him is rivaled by the delight of
never again having to engage in political fund raising, the bane of
his earthly existence these past 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather wrestle a gorilla than ask anybody for another 50
cents,'' the senator growled rather happily amid busy days of
commuting between space travel training in Houston and the
astronaut's requisite renunciation of the earthly baggage called
politics.
</P>
<P>
   When he rockets up in October for a nine-day ride at the age of
77, Glenn, who 36 years ago became the first American to orbit the
earth, will once more be a space pioneer, running a myriad of
geriatric medical experiments on himself as the oldest space
traveler ever.
</P>
<P>
   But as a retrofitted astronaut, once more wholesomely
nonpartisan, the Democrat from Ohio will also be ending his Senate
career in a bang and a rush that he tacitly acknowledges with a
sparkle-eyed smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not done here by a long shot,'' insisted the senator in
his Capitol office, tracking the debate on the tobacco bill, not
wanting to get ahead of himself as he flies his own plane to the
Houston space center on every available Capitol recess and long
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There, for the past five months, he has been practicing his role
in the mid-deck crew of the spaceship Discovery and bonding with
the other six members of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''They call me John; I straightened that out when I first went
down,'' he said. ``I told them that at the other end of the line I
may be a senator, but down there I'm John, a working crew member.
They liked that.''
</P>
<P>
   As liftoff nears, Glenn tries to minimize the unscientific fun
of returning to space for a far longer ride than his historic
five-hour, three-orbit trip on Feb. 20, 1962, which galvanized the
nation's pride in the depths of the Cold War space race with the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
   His nature is to regale Capitol acquaintances with the sheer
detail of his next mission, speaking of the voluminous engineering
tasks he obviously loves. He celebrates the pleasure of following a
firm schedule, as opposed to the free fall of Senate politics. As
he talks, the lack of pretension that marked his initial celebrity
remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the greatest bunch of guys you ever saw in your
life,'' Glenn said of his crewmates, his heartland twang ready to
resound once more from space.
</P>
<P>
   He openly worries that once he is beyond the pull of Senate and
launch pad, he may foul up some experiments as he labors with 21
different electronic leads attached to his scalp and chest _ a
weightless geezer injected with protein-tracking isotopes, running
the spacecraft centrifuge, juggling assorted deckhand tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I worry about is lousing things up and not
doing a good job up there,'' said the senator, whose duties,
already time-lined to the minute in his nine-day travel plan,
include gathering data on muscle, blood and bone chemistry and on
sleeplessness and other conditions of the aging process. He became
curious about these problems two years ago when he realized how
many of them are also experienced temporarily by young astronauts
in space.
</P>
<P>
   As fervidly as House Republicans used to carry the Contract With
America in their pockets, Glenn carries a terse checklist of 10
problems that he found in his own research to be common to the
basic medicine of space and geriatrics. He used this array of
problems, ranging from nutrition to equilibrium, in lobbying space
officials to rocket him back up to begin fresh research in behalf
of earthbound humanity, noting that the over-65 population will
triple in the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the luxury of going for a free ride, John Glenn
or anybody else,'' the senator insisted. ``I'm into this thing on a
science basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In his eighth decade of life, the senator has been power-walking
two miles a day for years and found no problem in passing the
physical for astronauts, who in the past have been ruled out by
around age 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a letter that says I have been through the most
rigorous physical of any astronaut that's ever been selected,'' he
proudly noted. ``The target heart rate for everybody is 220 minus
your age and, no problem, I did that,'' he added, smiling boyishly,
as if that target can only get mathematically easier the older he
gets.
</P>
<P>
   He talks soberly of how his staff will attend to constituent
needs once he goes aloft, his political career winding down without
him. But ask him about space flight and his hands, the confident
hands of a pilot, rise and shape the dynamics and his eyes gleam as
he offers detailed narrative on such emergency contingencies as
``the RTLS'' _ return to launch site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solids have come off,'' he said of the initial shedding of
rockets, plunging forth imaginatively from his Senate perch. ``And
you're up over the Atlantic accelerating rapidly toward Africa,
8,000 miles an hour, say. And something happens. And you have only
a three-and-a-half-minute chance to get back down.''
</P>
<P>
   Listeners can only grip the arms of their Capitol chairs as the
senator describes an ingenious reversal of the ship, her heated
plunge back toward Florida waters, the blowing of an escape hatch,
and the crew member called John bailing out with his mates at the
age of 77. ``We were practicing for this in the training pool the
other day,'' he noted, grinning. ``You hit the water just like a
fighter pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   Summoned back to earth by the Senate roll-call buzzer, John
Glenn talked of his political career as an adventure of a different
order, one where gravity can dictate the slogger's pace and
navigation is not often by the stars. ``I had a chance to do some
things I think were good,'' he said gently, noting such victories
as the enactment of his 1994 nuclear nonproliferation sanction law,
which is currently being directed at India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of it I'll miss,'' he said of politics. ``But I
never got my wildest enjoyment out of campaigning anyway, and
particularly fund raising. That's the most miserable part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   His hands idle atop his desk, the senator made it seem as if the
saddest part of leaving is his discovery that the right stuff in
politics has become great amounts of money. ``This is the most
stinking mess in government, the favored treatment from campaign
finance,'' he said, preparing to leave this place far behind,
although not without a certain smile at parting.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see an election coming up and not be raising money,'' he
exulted, as if already looking down from above. ``That's a joy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
