<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENDORSES TREATY ON CHILD LABOR ABUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Labor Secretary Alexis Herman gave the Clinton
administration's support this week to a proposed treaty to outlaw
the most exploitative forms of child labor.
</P>
<P>
   Herman said she hoped that a mechanism to be included in the
treaty calling for follow-up reporting of abuses would encourage
countries to abide by their pledges to end economic exploitation of
children.
</P>
<P>
   The new initiative, at the International Labor Organization,
comes 25 years after the body first tried to curb such abuses. But
nearly two-thirds of the ILO's 174 member nations, particularly
developing countries, chose not to sign it. The United States
itself did not sign.
</P>
<P>
   That convention barred children under 15 from working, except in
the poorest countries where the age was set at 13. And no child
under 18 could work in heavy industry.
</P>
<P>
   The new convention takes a more limited approach, focusing on
such extreme forms of child labor as working in mines and
prostitution. The proposal could be ready for nations to sign next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys indicate that about 250 million children between the
ages of 5 and 14 work worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Herman announced that the administration planned to ask Congress
for $30 million _ a large increase over the current $3 million
contribution _ for the ILO's project to help countries cope with
child-labor abuses. More than 20 countries have applied for help in
eliminating dangerous child labor. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
