<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-OFFSHORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON IMPOSES 10-YEAR BAN ON OFFSHORE DRILLING OF OCEANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ Calling offshore oil drilling an
environmental risk, President Clinton signed a directive Friday
banning exploration off the East and West Coasts through 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced an extension on the current moratorium to a
standing ovation at the National Oceans Conference. Joined by Vice
President Al Gore and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, the
president outlined a series of steps to protect the beaches and
marine life.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it is clear we must save these shores from oil
drilling. Here in California, you know all too well how oil spills
from offshore drilling can spoil our coasts, causing not just the
death of marine life, but the destruction of fragile ecosystems.
Even under the best of circumstances, is it really worth the
risk?,'' Clinton asked 300 scientists and experts.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also proposed a new user fee on shippers to
provide $800 million over five years to repair the nation's ports;
banned the catching or import of Atlantic swordfish weighing less
than 33 pounds; proposed $6 million through 2002 to restore 18
damaged coral reefs and proposed $12 million through 2002 to expand
and develop deep-sea observatories. He also called on the Senate to
ratify the Law of the Seas Convention that provides a legal
framework for activities in international waters.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-year ban on offshore drilling applies to the entire West
Coast, most of New England and the Mid-Atlantic, southwest Florida
and the North Aleutian Basin in southern Alaska. The administration
placed a five-year moratorium on drilling on the outer continental
shelf in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Drilling would still be allowed in the Gulf of Mexico off the
coasts of Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The president's directive also permanently bans drilling leases
within 12 existing marine sanctuaries off California, Florida,
Georgia and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``By standing firm against offshore oil drilling here in
California and around the nation, these people have helped to
protect the most beautiful shores anywhere in the world and we can
continue to do that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry, however, said the administration's ban would
only harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, the Washington-based trade
group that represents the major oil companies, called the decision
``unfortunate because it ignores the near-perfect performance of
the American petroleum industry in operating offshore in a safe and
environmentally sensitive manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. government statistics show that natural seeps from the
ocean floor introduce 100 times more crude oil into U.S. marine
waters than do the petroleum industry's offshore activities,'' API
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in California the issue of banning offshore drilling is
supported by a bipartisan coalition of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. Pete Wilson even wrote a letter to Clinton
calling on the president to make the ban permanent. Clinton aides
said the governor, who was invited to the oceans conference but did
not attend, was grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Katie McGinty, Clinton`s top adviser on the environment, said
the president backed a 10-year extension because it was ``the most
prudent course here.'' She said the administration has maintained
``a very effective dialogue'' with the oil industry and the
administration has ``equaled or surpassed'' previous
administrations in the number of oil and gas leases granted.
</P>
<P>
   McGinty said the western Gulf of Mexico was not included in the
drilling ban because it is not as ecologically sensitive as the
other areas.
</P>
<P>
   While environmentalists cheered Clinton's action, they
criticized the president for failing to take further steps to stop
ocean pollution immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mixed message,'' said Clifton Curtis, the ocean adviser
for the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened the two-day National Oceans Conference, which
was opened by Gore on Thursday, as part of an international effort
to focus world attention on the problems faced by the Earth's last
frontier. The conference was hosted by the U.S. Navy and the
Department of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Earle, a scientist who holds the title of
explorer-in-residence at National Geographic, noted experts know
more about the moon's surface than the ocean's geography.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have neglected the oceans and it has cost us dearly,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the ocean waters are at their warmest in centuries,
thanks to greenhouse gas emissions that warm the water temperatures
and create the El Nino phenomenon that causes weather extremes
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   He ran through a series of problems including pollution from the
land running into the seas, overfishing which has devastated
two-thirds of fish habitats, and conditions that could destroy 30
percent of the world's coral reefs within 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also charged his Cabinet with developing a long-range
oceans strategy with in a year and called on Congress to create an
oceans commission to help forge the new strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to do this right, we're going to have to do it
together. We have to make this an American issue that transcends
party and other philosophical differences,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's address here began a three-day visit to the West
Coast. Clinton was to be the main speaker at fund raising events
for California Sen. Barbara Boxer in San Francisco and for Oregon
Rep. Darlene Hooley in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
