<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-JUDGE-DELAY-     06-12 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-JUDGE-DELAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SENATORS DELAY HISPANIC JUDGE'S ELEVATION TO APPEALS COURT  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Judge Sonia Sotomayor seemed like a trouble-free
choice when President Clinton first nominated her to an appeals
court post a year ago. Hers was an appealing story: a child from
the Bronx housing projects who went on to graduate summa cum laude
from Princeton and become editor of the Yale Law Journal and then a
federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she had been a trial judge since 1992 when she was
named to the bench by George Bush, the last Republican president.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican senators have been blocking Judge Sotomayor's
elevation to the appeals court for a highly unusual reason; to make
her less likely to be picked by Clinton for the Supreme Court,
senior Republican congressional aides said in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The delay of a confirmation vote on Judge Sotomayor to the 2nd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New York, is an example of
the intense and often byzantine politics that take place unseen in
many judicial nominations. Several elements of the Sotomayor case
are odd, White House officials and Democrats in Congress say, but
the chief one is the fact that there is no current vacancy on the
Supreme Court, and no firm indication that there will be one soon.
Nor is there any evidence of a campaign to put Judge Sotomayor
under consideration for a seat if there were a vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sotomayor's nomination was approved overwhelmingly by the
Senate Judiciary Committee in March, making her one of the judicial
nominees who have cleared the committee and waited the longest for
a final vote on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican staff aides in the Senate said that Trent Lott
of Mississippi, the Senate majority leader, has agreed to hold up a
vote on Judge Sotomayor's nomination as part of an elaborate and
complex political calculus; if she were easily confirmed to the
appeals court, they said, that would put her in a position to be
named by President Clinton to the Supreme Court. And Senate
Republicans think that they would then have a difficult time
opposing a Hispanic woman who had just been confirmed by the full
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we think that putting her on the appeals court puts
her in the batter's box to be nominated to the Supreme Court,''
said one senior Republican staff aide who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``If Clinton nominated her it would put several of our
senators in a real difficult position.'' Lott declined through a
spokeswoman to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The aides said some senators believed that Judge Sotomayor's
record on the bench could fit the profile of an ``activist judge'',
a description that has been used by conservatives to question a
jurist's ability to construe the law strictly. It is a description
that Judge Sotomayor's supporters, including some conservative New
York lawyers, hotly dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont who is the senior Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee was blunt in his criticism of the Republicans
who are blocking a confirmation vote: ``Their reasons are stupid at
best and cowardly at worst,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they are saying is that they have a brilliant judge who
also happens to be a woman and Hispanic and they haven't the guts
to stand up and argue publicly against her on the floor,'' Leahy
said. ``They just want to hide in their cloakrooms and do her in
quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   The models for putting a candidate on an appeals court to
enhance his or her stature as a Supreme Court nominee are Judge
Robert Bork and Judge Clarence Thomas both of whom were placed on
the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in part to
be poised to be nominated to the Supreme Court. Bork was denied
confirmation to the Supreme Court in 1987 and Thomas was confirmed
in 1991, both after bruising political battles.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation for the Republicans' strategy is based on two
highly speculative aspects: that President Clinton is eager to name
the first Hispanic to the Supreme Court and that he will have such
an opportunity as one of the current justices, perhaps John Paul
Stevens, will retire at the end of the current Supreme Court term
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings about the possibility of Judge Sotomayor filling
Stevens' seat was raised by the Wall Street Journal editorial pages
this month, both in an editorial and in an op-ed column by Paul
Gigot who often reflects conservative thinking in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Although justices often announce their retirements at the end of
a term Justice Stevens has not given a clue he will do so. He has,
in fact, hired law clerks for next year's term. The Journal's
commentary criticized Judge Sotomayor's record, particularly a 1997
case in which she ruled that a New York business coalition, the
Grand Central Partnership, trying to give work experience to the
homeless had violated federal law by not paying the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Walpin, a former federal prosecutor who is widely known
in New York legal circles as a staunch conservative, disagreed
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had read the case they would see that she said she
personally approved of the homeless program but that as a judge she
was required to apply the law as it exists,'' he said. ``She wrote
that the law does not permit an exception in this case. That's
exactly what conservatives want: a non-activist judge who does not
apply her own views but is bound by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   It also remains unclear who first believed that Judge Sotomayor
was a hidden Clinton candidate for the Supreme Court. Hispanic bar
groups have pressed the Clinton administration to name the first
Hispanic justice but White House officials said they are not
committed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic National Bar Association has submitted a list of
six candidates to the White House as possible Supreme Court
nominees. But Martin Castro, a Chicago lawyer and official of the
group, said Judge Sotomayor's name is not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of her confirmation hearing, Sept. 30. 1997, Rush
Limbaugh, the conservative radio talk-show host, warned the Senate
that Judge Sotomayor was an ultraliberal who was on a ``rocket
ship'' to the Supreme Court. That day, Judge Sotomayor was
questioned closely by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the only Republicans to vote against her were Sen.
John Kyl of Arizona and Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri. The
committee's other conservative members voted in her favor. Both Kyl
and Ashcroft declined comment on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The delay on Judge Sotomayor comes as Ralph Winter, the chief
judge of the 2d Circuit, has complained of terrible delays because
of unfilled vacancies. In his annual report, Winter, a conservative
Republican, lamented that he had to declare judicial emergencies on
several occasions to allow retired judges and trial judges to sit
on appeals panels to deal with the court's largest backlog in
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2033EDT &QL; 
