<HEADER>
A7264 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC--WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      06-12 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC--WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
MARSEILLE, France _ One team was just happy to be here. The other
was at home and on stage in the biggest soccer event to pass its
way in nearly 60 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guess which team dominated?
</P>
<P>
   The French, who considered it an outrage that it had been more
than a decade since it last competed in the World Cup finals but an
honor to be hosting the 1998 tournament, thrilled the wild home
masses Friday night with an all-around thrashing of overmatched
South Africa. The score was 3-0, and it wasn't that close.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of game of which French dreams were made.
</P>
<P>
   No contest. A thrashing. French toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have put another one into the net in the first
half, so we would be comfortable all night,'' France coach Aime
Jacquet said. ``But I was happy with the way we kept the ball on
their end. We stayed in control.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a captivating display of ball possession by the French,
who controlled nearly 60 minutes of the clock and threw in just
enough thrilling plays to keep the chilly, wind-blown Marseille
crowd roaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there is pressure playing at home, but this is what we
have been waiting for for years,'' said Jacquet, who saw the French
team miss World Cup qualification in 1990 and 1994. ``We wanted to
be in this game, and I think we took advantage of the
opportunities. We played a great game. But it was one game, and
there is a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the winning goal came on a terrific header by
striker Christophe Dugarry, who definitely took advantage of an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Normally a starter for France, Dugarry was relegated to the
bench for the opener. He came on in the 27th minute after starting
forward Stephane Guivarc'h hurt his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after taking the field, Dugarry fired a
rocket that barely missed. Moments later, he would trigger one of
the more productive nights of his career with the sharp goal midway
through the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, Dugarry took four shots and was involved in the
second goal, laying off a ball for Youri Djorkaeff, who hit a
falling, slow roller at South Africa goalkeeper Hans Vonk from
inside the penalty area. Vonk appeared to have the shot covered,
but a sliding attempt to clear the ball by defender Pierre Issa
caused it to bounce over Vonk and land softly in the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be a fabulous challenge playing in front of
our nation, but it was an unforgettable night,'' Djorkaeff said.
``We have a lot of bullets in the gun, and we have not unloaded
them all. We're happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the ``Bafana Bafana'' _ the Boys, as the South
Africans are called _ could only keep trying to get their feet
under them in South Africa's first World Cup appearance. During
apartheid, the South Africans never were invited.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, they hardly got the ball out of their end, firing
a mere six shots, none of which could have been considered a
realistic scoring opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was so much excitement in the air, a wonderful
atmosphere for us, I'm sure it was difficult for South Africa,''
said Thierry Henry, who scored France's final goal on a chip-in
during injury time. ``It was a victory, and we could not ask for
more than victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will keep playing like this and the crowd will
keep cheering. We have to applaud the French people as much as they
applauded us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
