<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHUTTLE-NYT &LR;      06-12 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The space shuttle completed its final
mission to the Russian space station Friday, bringing Mir's seventh
and last American tenant home from his stay of 4 and a half months
in Earth orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank you all for bringing me home and giving me a
great ride,'' the long-duration astronaut, Andrew Thomas, said
minutes after a bumpy but safe landing aboard the shuttle
Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown, at the Kennedy Space Center here at 2 p.m.,
capped a 10-day, 3.8-million-mile flight that included four days in
which Discovery was docked at Mir to deliver supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a 46-year-old mechanical engineer enduring his first
sensations of gravity in 141 days, needed help getting out of the
shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to that first meal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lasagna and Oreo cookie ice cream awaited him at Kennedy's
astronaut crew quarters, where he was taken for detailed medical
tests. But doctors said he might be too woozy to stomach the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' homecoming brought to a close a series of 10 shuttle
encounters with Mir: one fly-around to perfect rendezvous
techniques and nine subsequent dockings, which together made up the
first phase of NASA's cooperative effort with Russia and 15 other
countries to build a $40 billion space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end, it's just the beginning of a new phase,''
said NASA administrator Daniel Goldin in a runway ceremony Friday.
That new phase begins in November, when the first piece of the
space station is to be lofted into orbit by a Russian rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke from numerous Central Florida wildfires wafted in the
shuttle's path during its computer-guided descent, but the haze
posed no visibility problems for the flight commander, Charles
Precourt, an Air Force colonel, who was at Discovery's controls for
the final approach.
</P>
<P>
   The winged ship announced its presence with a double sonic boom
and swooped out of a cloud-dotted sky to touch down and bounce once
on the three-mile-long Shuttle Landing Facility. Moderate
crosswinds picked the 100-ton spacecraft up briefly and set it back
down with no harm done.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made the trip home with feet up and head down in a
reclining chair to alleviate his risk of fainting as body fluids,
which had floated in his head and chest in space, were inclined to
rush into his lower torso and legs under the influence of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said he would fight nausea for several days and face
months of aches and pains as his weakened bones and muscles grew
used to being on Earth again.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour after Discovery touched down, Thomas was taken
into a rolling emergency room of sorts that pulled up to the
shuttle's hatch. After a quick checkup, he was transported to the
astronaut crew quarters for a brief reunion with friends, a hot
shower and several hours of detailed medical exams.
</P>
<P>
   He was to spend the night at Kennedy with a doctor at his
bedside, then go home to Houston with his crewmates on Saturday.
Tom Marshburn, a NASA flight surgeon at the Johnson Space Center in
Houston, said Thomas would spend up to six hours a day with doctors
and physical therapists in the early stages of a formal six-week
rehabilitation period. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
