<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7273 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FELLS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      06-12 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRIAL ORDERED IN FELLS ACRE CHILD ABUSE CASE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY   AND JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ A Superior Court judge voided the child
sexual abuse conviction of Cheryl Amirault LeFave yesterday, saying
her alleged victims were manipulated by ``overzealous''
investigators who succumbed to a ``climate of panic, if not
hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   The scathing, 140-page decision, by Middlesex Superior Court
Judge Isaac Borenstein, also barred the alleged victims, now in
their teens, from testifying in any future retrial of LeFave _
effectively gutting the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein wrote that the alleged victims' accounts in the
14-year-old case were tainted by suggestive interviewing
techniques. The judge said the children were coerced by
interviewers who ``would not take `no' for an answer ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Because there is no independent evidence to corroborate these
allegations of abuse, their testimony is unreliable; its admission
at trial was a violation of the most fundamental rules of evidence
and due process.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Lynn Rooney immediately appealed the
ruling. She called Borenstein's opinion ``outrageous'' and deemed
it a ``final insult to the children and their parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney said Borenstein usurped the authority of the trial judge,
the jury and the appellate court, and decided on his own that the
children were not telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is simply not appropriate,'' she said. ``He disbelieved
the parents.''
</P>
<P>
   When Borenstein announced his ruling, LeFave broke into a broad
smile and was congratulated by her lawyers. She was embraced by
supporters in the gallery as she left the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   LeFave said she was ``gratified'' by the decision, but ``very
fearful'' the Supreme Judicial Court could rule against her. LeFave
has lost several other appeals since she was convicted in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   She also was mindful of her brother, Gerald Amirault. Convicted
of similar charges, he is serving 30 to 40 years in prison, but
could benefit from Borenstein's ruling. The same child witnesses
who Borenstein said were tainted also testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' LeFave said. &UR;  &LR; ``My brother is still
languishing in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mothers of two children who testified against
Gerald Amirault were incensed. Both women asked that their names be
withheld to protect the identities of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you think the kids feel? They are being called liars,''
said one woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened,'' said the other. ``The victims are the ones who
have to live with this for the rest of their lives, knowing that
these people are going to be left off free because the law didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense of Judge Borenstein is that he is a smart judge,''
said Laurence Hardoon, who prosecuted all three defendants in three
trials. ``But it seems to me he has crossed the line between being
a judge and being an advocate in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Borenstein had ordered a new trial for LeFave on
different grounds, involving ineffective assistance of counsel. A
ruling on that issue is pending before the SJC.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues probably will be argued before the SJC in the fall,
but yesterday's ruling is considered much more significant.
Prosecutors said they will not be able to retry the case without
the child witnesses.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  The Fells Acres case has raised questions about whether
testimony by preschool children is reliable. Convictions in many of
those cases have been overturned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, LeFave and her mother, the late Violet Amirault, were
granted a new trial because their rights to confront their accusers
may have been violated. Though they were released, the new trial
has never been held, and Violet Amirault, 74, died of cancer in
September.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Yesterday, at the request of defense lawyer James Sultan,
Borenstein formally dismissed the charges against Violet Amirault.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing four months ago, defense lawyers argued that LeFave
deserves a retrial because of new evidence: recent psychological
studies which indicate that preschool children can make up and
believe stories suggested to them through questioning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Maggie Bruck, a psychologist from McGill University in
Montreal, testified that there were no spontaneous disclosures by
children in the case. The allegations, she said, came only after
repeated, suggestive questioning from parents and investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein agreed. In the case against Cheryl LeFave, he wrote,
physicial evidence of abuse was at best inconclusive, and almost
nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of one child, the minimal amount of such
evidence only surfaced months after the children were improperly
questioned, the judge said. He also noted that the child's symptoms
were evident before she enrolled at Fells Acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``These alleged symptoms were only discussed after the families
were overwhelmed by the panic, hysteria, and media attention,''
Borenstein wrote. From the outset, he wrote, investigators were out
to get the Amiraults, and ignored the children's ``incredible''
claims of talking robots, the torture of animals in public, and
children being tied naked to a tree in front of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein noted that the child witnesses at first withstood the
interrogations and denied any abuse. ``Eventually,'' he said,
``they were broken down.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that Susan Kelley, a pediatric nurse who
interviewed all four child witnesses against LeFave, and police
also turned a deaf ear to other teachers and students who supported
the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Borenstein said the case has resulted in two tragedies: that
LeFave was wrongly convicted and ``no one will ever know for
certain if these children were sexually abused.''
</P>
<P>
   In a May ruling, Borenstein granted LeFave a new trial on the
grounds that her former lawyers were negligent. He said the lawyers
failed to object to the seating arrangement for the child witnesses
at the trial. The children were seated at an angle so they did not
face the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Before ruling on that motion, the SJC asked Borenstein to hear
the defense claim that the children's testimony was tainted.
</P>
<P>
   But the mothers of two of the victims stand by their children's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Both women said they believed the Amiraults were winning a
public relations battle, one that depicts the trials as ``witch
hunts'' and ignores the medical evidence, the children's sexually
provocative behavior and the common sense of jurors who convicted
LeFave, her mother, and brother more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you picture telling your child to say sexually explicit
things?'' said one woman. ``All these parents told their children
to say these things? At that age, they don't know anything about
sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it didn't happen, but it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
