A7275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-TEEN-DEATHS-NY     06-12 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-TEEN-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BOYS INTO MEN AS DEATH HITS CLASS OF 1998 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Above the bronze entrance doors of a gracefully
curved Art Deco building on the Grand Concourse are the words
``Cardinal Hayes Memorial High School for Boys.'' They are a
reminder that although the students graduate as Hayesmen, a group
as proud and persistent as the Marines, they enter as children.
</P>
<P>
   Since the school opened in 1941 as the flagship of the Catholic
Archdiocese of New York, that transformation has happened through
all the usual rites of passage understood best by teen-age boys.
Football rallies each November at which heart-pounding,
raspy-voiced vengeance was vowed on its archrival, Mount Saint
Michael Academy. Penance by the hour in ``jug,'' where students
stood through detention. Countless teams and clubs, like the school
paper The Challenger (where this byline first appeared).
</P>
<P>
   Like the priests used to say, to enter this place is to join a
family that includes Martin Scorsese, Regis Philbin and enough
priests and police officers to bless and protect a small city. At
Hayes, kids began to feel they finally belonged to something larger
than the few blocks in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The adolescent rituals of past years were nothing compared to
the way the class of 1998 came of age. In the final weeks before
graduation, Hector Camilo and Aaron Jason Fenton, two funny and
popular seniors, died weeks apart. Hector died in March when his
car struck a tree on the West Side Highway. Aaron was killed six
weeks later, shot in the head while trying to settle an argument in
his neighborhood. Their classmates, fearful of the future,
ultimately became men through mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who didn't even like each other were giving each other
love, showing each other love,'' said Joseph Dickenson, a senior
who was close to Aaron. ``That shows how people grew. You had
respect to show your concern. Hector and Jason. You can't believe
it. I still can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   People who study these things for a living churn out reports
that show how schools like Hayes provide a community and common
purpose for young people whose homes and neighborhoods have
neither. Monsignor John Graham, the school's principal, said the
best way the students were able to weather the successive deaths
was by making real the lessons taught in religion classes, lessons
of forgiveness and support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking anymore about how to play an instrument,'' he
said. ``Here's the instrument, play it. Here's this terrible
experience, we've got to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Aaron's murder, the school provided crisis counseling and
called off classes. Most students came in anyway. They didn't want
to be alone, because you think odd thoughts in the solitude of your
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like school meant nothing anymore,'' said Joseph Rosa,
who was driving behind Hector's car the night of the accident. ``It
was pointless. The goal was always to finish off together. As one.
It was supposed to be our best year.''
</P>
<P>
   What it became was their best moment, coming together in a way
that made them the talk of other schools. They set out yearbooks
for the two boys in the marble-walled lobby, where friends wrote
messages to them and their families. They filled up two boxes with
everything from mortarboards and senior caps to pictures from
outings and private notes. It all allowed them to bond like
brothers, to laugh and cry without shame. Rather than give up in
the face of random death, they rededicated themselves to each other
and their school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I do is in honor of them,'' said Luis Mangual.
``Anything of meaning to me is for them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a gentleness you feel in the hallways, a tenderness
that dispels any idea of tough teachers and boastful boys. It was
felt last weekend, when the class of 1998 marched into St.
Patrick's Cathedral for graduation. Hector and Aaron had their
names called out with the rest of their class, and their parents
walked up the aisle to receive their diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a shiver go up my spine when I heard their names,''
said Leonardo Blackman, who was close to both boys. ``I felt like
they were inside of me. It felt good. It felt sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo came to Hayes from a public school, where he hit the
basketball courts more often than the books. Like most of his
classmates, he now plans to go to college. He's scared, but not
about the academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always tried to help each other,'' he said. ``That's my
fear about going to college. I'll miss these guys. They're my
brothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
