<SLUG> BC-SKIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Advanced Tissue Falls After FDA Rejection   By Carl T. Hall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Advanced Tissue Sciences Inc. lost nearly half its stock value
yesterday after the FDA rejected the company's application to
market artificial skin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Diego-based company's stock closed at $3.94, down $3.13
for a 44 percent decline. The plunge was triggered when Advanced
Tissue revealed that the Food and Drug Administration would not
approve ``Dermagraft,'' a bioengineered skin-replacement product,
without a new clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   That could take at least a year and perhaps as long as two
years. Arthur Benvenuto, chairman and chief executive, said the
company and its collaborator, Smith &AMP; Nephew, are discussing with
the FDA issues concerning the scope of the new trial.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA rejection runs counter to the recommendations of its own
expert advisory panel, which in January voted 7 to 2 in favor of
Advanced Tissue's application to sell Dermagraft for treating
diabetic foot wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked away from the panel meeting thinking we were moving
along on the right path toward approval,'' Benvenuto said.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection left a clear field for another manufacturer,
Organogenesis Inc., whose skin-replacement product, Apligraf, won
FDA approval last month for patching hard-to-treat leg ulcers and
is being studied for diabetic complications. Its shares gained
$2.13 yesterday, or 9.2 percent, to close at $25.13.
</P>
<P>
   Perceptions of the FDA have softened dramatically in recent
months after Congress forced the agency to streamline the
new-product review process.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's developments showed that the agency still can pack a
wallop even if evidence backing up a new product seems marginal.
Nor was anyone surprised by Advanced Tissue's setback.
</P>
<P>
   The company issued warnings in March that the FDA was raising
concerns about the Dermagraft application. Outright rejection
wasn't forewarned, but some analysts have been leery of the stock
for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been negative on it,'' noted Alan Jacobs at Avalon
Research Group in Boca Raton, Fla., adding that the stock ``could
go lower than this'' if the upcoming clinical trial stretches out
much more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Benvenuto said he has a ``solid financing strategy,'' including
a $50 million line of credit and money due from Smith &AMP; Nephew, to
see past the crisis and prove that the product meets FDA standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we are going forward,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
