<HEADLINE>
BELIEFS: CHRISTIANS DEBATE PAUL'S TEXT ON WIFELY SUBMISSION
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By PETER STEINFELS    
 By c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Criticism was quick in coming after the Southern Baptist
Convention, at its annual meeting in Salt Lake City this week,
added to the denomination's basic statement of beliefs a
declaration that ``a wife is to submit herself graciously to the
servant leadership of her husband.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Lois Powell of the liberal United Church of Christ, for
example, called the declaration ``a reaction and an affront to the
social movement for women's rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders would surely reply that the statement
also exhorts husbands to love their wives ``as Christ loved the
church'' and ``to provide for, to protect and to lead'' their
families. The declaration also states that ``husband and wife are
of equal worth before God.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the denomination's leaders maintain, the notion of
differing roles in marriage and the family is firmly rooted in the
Bible. Admonitions that wives ``submit'' or, in recent
translations, ``be subject'' to their husbands are found in several
passages of the New Testament, most eloquently in the fifth chapter
of the Letter to the Ephesians, which develops the analogy between
Christ as head of the church and the husband as ``head of the
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, most Christians embraced those passages in much
the same way as the Southern Baptists now do. But that is hardly
the case today. Ms. Powell, executive director of the United Church
of Christ's Coordinating Center for Women in Church and Society,
said ``very few'' of her church's members, who number more than 1
million, ``would utilize those passages as the guide for modern
relationships.'' She described the passage in Ephesians as ``a
statement of the early church, not of Jesus,'' and one that had
been written and then later interpreted ``in situations of sexism
and patriarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   If that view, from one of the nation's most consistently liberal
denominations, could have been expected, perhaps more striking were
the reactions of two professors at Fuller Theological Seminary in
Pasadena, Calif., an evangelical institution that emphasizes the
authority of the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   David Scholer, a professor of New Testament at Fuller, called
the Southern Baptist declaration one more instance of ``selective
literalism.'' Most Christians claiming to be literal readers of the
Bible, he said, are in fact swayed by their tradition when it comes
to choosing what is significant. Southern Baptists do not take
literally Jesus' command that His followers wash one another's
feet, he noted, although some other Baptists do.
</P>
<P>
   Scholer also said the crucial passage in Ephesians was
introduced by the general instruction that Christians ``be subject
to one another,'' thus making mutual submission more fundamental
than any differentiating of responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Gundry-Volf, who also teaches New Testament at Fuller,
explained that New Testament passages like the one in Ephesians
were Christian adaptations of the ``household codes'' that
Greco-Roman moralists had developed to instruct the heads of
families in running their affairs. She suggested that these adapted
codes _ which also addressed the relations between parents and
children, slaves and masters, people and government _ could be seen
as a retreat from an earlier, more egalitarian ethos among Jesus'
followers. Paul had earlier declared that ``there is no longer male
and female; for all of you are one in Christ Jesus'' (Galatians
3:28), and had also referred to female leaders in the early church.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant view, Ms. Gundry-Volf said, is that this retreat
was a response to suspicions that Christians were upsetting a
social order based on patriarchal authority. But the Christian
household codes were not simply an accommodation to the patriarchal
system, she added; they rejected many of its abuses, filtering the
society's understanding of the relations between superiors and
inferiors through the Christian ethic of love. Many scholars call
the result a kind of ``love patriarchalism,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And where these Christian household codes were meant ``to ensure
that Christians could live out their faith in ways that did not
raise suspicions that they would disrupt the social order,'' the
Southern Baptist position does the opposite, she said: ``It is seen
to be antiquarian and disruptive of Western egalitarian values.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, an even more emphatic challenge to the kind of
interpretation favored by the Southern Baptists came 10 years ago
from Pope John Paul II. In ``Mulieris Dignitatem'' (``On the
Dignity of Women''), a papal letter generally viewed as
conservative, the pope argued that absolutely nothing in Ephesians
about wives' being subject to husbands could be understood apart
from the demand, introducing the whole passage, for ``mutual
subjection out of reverence for Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   The special subjection of wives, the pope said, is the ``old''
reality that the biblical author recognized as ``profoundly rooted
in the customs and religious tradition of the time.'' By contrast,
the call to mutual subjection is the ``something new,'' an
``innovation of the Gospel.''
</P>
<P>
   Implicitly recognizing that the same New Testament passage
called on slaves to obey their masters, the pope compared the
struggle to recognize mutual subjection of the spouses _ ``and not
just that of the wife to the husband'' _ to the historical struggle
against slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders are not apt to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a scholar to be able to interpret what is
clearly laid out in God's blueprint for the family,'' Mary Mohler,
who helped draft the declaration, told the Southern Baptists' press
service this week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what all these Christians, from the Southern Baptists
to the pope, might agree upon is that in contemporary society,
nobody wants to be subject to anyone, mutually or not. But that is
another story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
