<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TRUTH DOES MATTER _ AND SO DO THE CHILDREN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMATA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The only people for whom nothing changes with the latest ruling
in the Fells Acres sexual abuse case are the children.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant is vindicated; the prosecutor is aggrieved. But
what of the children at the heart of this case, children who put
their trust in adults, first in the schoolroom and then in the
courtroom, only to be cruelly betrayed in one or both places?
</P>
<P>
   Beyond describing their testimony of rape and sexual assault as
``forever tainted'' by the leading questions of ``overzealous''
investigators, Judge Isaac Borenstein does not have much to say
about those children in a 140-page decision that overturns the
11-year-old conviction of the late Violet Amirault and grants a new
trial to her daughter, Cheryl LeFave.
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers now, these boys and girls have been since preschool
the phantoms of the Fells Acres case, their anonymous pain merely
theoretical alongside the tear-stained tableaux of an elderly woman
and her two adult children insisting on their innocence.
(Amirault's son, Gerald, remains in prison, convicted of similar
charges during a separate trial in 1986.)
</P>
<P>
   The zeal of ``biased'' prosecutors produced ``dual tragedies''
in the Fells Acres case, according to the judge: The rights of the
defendants and the opportunity to uncover the truth about the
children's allegations were both irreparably compromised. But,
curiously, Judge Borenstein addresses only one of those
``tragedies'' in a decision that focuses on the legitimate need to
protect the liberty of the falsely accused but ignores the equally
compelling need to insure the safety of the truly abused.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that it is ``not the responsibility of this court to
decide the ultimate question of Cheryl Amirault LeFave's guilt or
innocence,'' Judge Borenstein makes it clear that he thinks
Amirault and LeFave, respectively the owner and a teacher at the
Fells Acres day care center in Malden, were victims of public
``panic, if not hysteria'' about child abuse in the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   But his is not the universal view. The Massachusetts Supreme
Judicial Court reviewed this case three times and concluded that
there was independent evidence to support the children's claims.
Justice Charles Fried, writing for the majority in March 1997,
found the children's testimony bolstered by ``the evidence of
physical injury, and the parents' testimony regarding the bizarre,
disturbed, and inappropriately sexualized behavior of their
children and the extent to which these factors corroborated each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent research on the suggestibility of children constitutes
``new evidence,'' according to Judge Borenstein, supporting the
defense contention that the children were made to believe that
horrors happened to them that never actually occurred. Because of
the ``grave errors'' made in the pre-trial questioning of the
children, ``their testimony has been forever rendered unreliable.
Although honest, the overwhelming evidence shows that there is a
grave risk the child witnesses were mistaken, through no fault of
their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does that leave these children? Sexually abused by
ill-intentioned caregivers? Manipulated by well-intentioned crime
fighters? The judge says it does not matter: The children's
perceptions were so distorted by suggestive interviewing techniques
that their testimony would be inadmissible in a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth does matter, if not in court, then surely in the
lives of these children. It matters not just for them, but for all
children who find themselves at the center of such a storm. There
is little likelihood the Fells Acres case will ever be retried _
even if Judge Borenstein's decision is overturned, why would these
families subject themselves to another trial? _ but it is just as
unlikely that we have seen the last case of child sexual abuse in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Judge Borenstein's ruling might serve as public
notice that the criminal justice system is the wrong venue for the
resolution of child abuse cases. There are just too many
adult-sized hurdles for a pint-sized person to clear. If the courts
find children, with their malleable memories and their suggestible
minds, such unreliable witnesses, how can they ever be found to be
real victims? &UR;  &LR; The sexual abuse of children happens in secret,
after all; there are rarely adult witnesses. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Judge Borenstein spends 140 &UR;  &LR; pages addressing the rights of the
accused and not a line considering the plight of children. They
can't trust their parents not to twist their words. They can't
trust their therapists not to mold their memories. They can't trust
prosecutors not to reshape events according to their own biases.
</P>
<P>
   Who then should children trust?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
