<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-WAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SEEKS JUSTICE, PLANS PRIVATE FUNERAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ In the midst of worldwide media attention, the
family of James Byrd Jr. prepared for a private funeral and burial
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 49-year-old father of three and grandfather, was slain
almost a week ago when he was chained to the bumper of a pickup
truck and dragged for almost three miles along a back country road
east of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   His funeral will be at the Greater New Bethel Baptist Church a
block from the home where he grew up, a church where he spent much
of his time as a child and where his father and namesake is still a
deacon.
</P>
<P>
   Although more famous preachers, like the Rev. Jesse Jackson, are
expected to be in attendance and may participate, the eulogy will
be presented by the Rev. Kenneth Lyons, pastor of the little
church, Byrd's family said.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Taylor, a Houston schoolteacher who is one of Byrd's six
sisters, asked news reporters to let the family have some time to
themselves. She said her family has no hate for the three white men
being held in the Jasper County jail charged with her brother's
brutal death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use the world hate here,'' she said, motioning toward
the front door of her parents' modest home. ``We just want justice
done.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother, a one-time vacuum cleaner salesman, who
was known for his gift of gab and fine singing voice, would be
amused by all the attention his death has attracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `All this for James Byrd? Well, well,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As she stood on the front porch a string of neighbors, white and
black, came through the door bringing food, in the tradition of
small towns. Across Jasper flags stood at half-staff. Many street
corners, doors on businesses, trees and coat lapels featured yellow
ribbons distributed as a symbol of the town's support.
</P>
<P>
   The crime has touched other places as well. President Clinton
telephoned Byrd's mother Thursday to express his condolences,
Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family is grateful for all of the support, but
worries that some would use her brother's murder as a reason to
hate. ``We hope it doesn't cause any kind of violence and
division,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps her brother's death can help some people realize that
ignorance and hate is a great evil, she said. ``We need to get at
the cause,'' she said. ``We're dealing with the symptoms.''
</P>
<P>
   An eighth-grade science teacher at Burbank Middle School in
Houston, Taylor said only education can help curb racism. ``These
boys did not get that way overnight,'' she said of the three
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read about atrocities in other places and never here,''
she said. ``People say, `Something needs to be done,' and that's
how it always ends,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper, about 130 miles northeast of Houston, is planning a
communitywide prayer service at the courthouse square Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's funeral, Taylor said, ``will be a time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon and evening more than 200 people paid their
respects by visiting the funeral home where Byrd's body lay in a
dark gray casket. While Byrd's family was grieving, some who came
to Jasper seemed to be less interested in peace than in their
version of justice for a horrible crime.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting the Koran's dictate that murderers should be put to
death in the same manner in which they kill, Houston Black Muslim
minister Quanell X said the three defendants ``should be tied to
the very same bumper Brother Byrd was tied to and dragged down
Interstate 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by black-uniformed bodyguards, he said his entourage
brought a cache of weapons to be distributed to the black residents
of Jasper. The weapons would be used, he said, to defend blacks
against any threat posed by Ku Klux Klan or other white hate
groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give them the same hell they give us,'' said the
former Nation of Islam youth minister.
</P>
<P>
   Several other groups are expected to appear Saturday in Jasper,
including a delegation from Dallas representing the New Black
Panthers, as well as spokesmen for the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
