</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FELLS-CASES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FELLS ACRES IS THE LATEST OF PUBLICIZED ABUSE CASES TO BE
OVERTURNED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names symbolized an era: Virginia McMartin, Kelly Michaels,
Little Rascals, Fells Acres, Amirault.
</P>
<P>
   Each belonged to a daycare center or its operators, and over the
course of two decades each became shorthand for cases of sexual
abuse of young children _ and the trials which unfolded amid a
highly charged, national campaign against sexual abuse that many
said was long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   But in time, each sensational case crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Convictions, built on the sometimes outlandish testimony of
small children, collapsed, one by one, in appeals courts. Of the
dozens of daycare center operators jailed for child molestation in
the 1980s, only a handful _ including Gerald Amirault, a defendant
in the Fells Acres case _ remain behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   For supporters of defendants' rights, the ruling by Judge Isaac
Borenstein in favor of Cheryl Amirault LeFave, Gerald's sister,
marked a clear victory in the war against so-called ``abuse
movement zealots,'' whose efforts created unprecedented national
concern for child molestation and led to an increase of reported
incidents in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And according to one of LeFave's supporters, Borenstein's
decision pounded ``another nail in the coffin, and a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``There is never going to be another one of these massive
abuse cases again,'' said writer Dorothy Rabinowitz, a longtime
opponent of the national wave of child sexual abuse cases.
</P>
<P>
   To victims' rights supporters, the decision represented another
symbolic blow against the movement to punish offenders. Yet they
acknowlege the process of prosecuting child molesters has changed
since its inception, as the public has become ``highly skeptical''
of children's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Over the years, we have become much more cautious about
allegations. The protocol has changed,'' said Kathleen Faller, a
professor of social work at the University of Michigan. ``But a lot
of it is merely a response to the legal system, and is not
necessarily good for kids. It's an uphill battle now.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest and by far most notorious battle began in
California with a mother's phone call to police in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The woman reported her son had been abused while in the care
of the Virginia McMartin Preschool, a daycare center in the wealthy
community of Manhattan Beach. The claim led to a massive
investigation involving more than 200 current and former families
and children who attended the school, and, ultimately, a case that
cost $15 million to prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   McMartin, her son and five others were ultimately indicted for
abusing several dozen children in their care. &UR;  &LR; The charges ranged
from horrifying to bizarre; more than 20 children told police about
not only incidents of rape and sodomy, but also rituals of animal
sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   Before it ended seven years later, the McMartin defendants were
dragged through two lengthy trials. Two of them _ Peggy Ann Buckey,
the founder's daughter, and Raymond Buckey, the founder's grandson
_ each spent time in jail before a jury deadlocked in 1990 and the
case was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, another landmark case fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Kelly Michaels, convicted in 1988 of abusing 19 children in
the New Jersey daycare center where she worked, walked out of jail
after serving five years of her sentence. An appeals court found
the case against her so outrageous it overturned the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And just last year, prosecutors in North Carolina abandoned
their pursuit of the operators of the Little Rascals day care
center, where 29 children had alleged incidents of sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In what was reportedly the longest and most expensive case in
the state, owner Robert F. Kelly Jr. and Kathryn Dawn Wilson, the
cook, were both convicted and spent time behind bars. Their
convictions were ultimately overturned, but in the aftermath one
local columnist compared the ordeal to the 1692 Salem witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As in the witch trials, good and decent citizens were falsely
accused of the most horrendous crimes and some were convicted based
solely on the evidence of children,'' columnist Perry Young wrote
in the Chapel Hill, N.C. Herald. ``If an adult talked of space
ships or shooting babies, it would rightly be discounted or
impeached.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Effectively echoing that sentiment, Judge Borenstein Friday
forbade the testimony of children who testified in the original
Amirault trial, labeling their comments ``forever tainted'' by
investigators' leading, repetitive questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Amirault case broke in September 1984, when Gerald Amirault
was arrested after a five-year-old told his mother he was molested
at the school. Within weeks, the school was closed as other
children came forward with similar allegations.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1985, LeFave, her mother and brother were indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Amirault was convicted in 1986 and sentenced to 30 to 40
years; his mother and sister were found guilty the following year,
and sent away for 8 to 20 years. The case their lawyers had begun
the first in a series of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   But Borenstein's decision placed the Amirault case into the
realm of similar prosecutions that ultimately disintegrated. And it
heartened opponents who for years had perceived Massachusetts as
out of step with the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said defense attorney Harvey Silverglate,
``somebody had to start saying the emperor had no no clothes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
