A7305 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-TRUCKS-HNS &LR;      06-12 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-TRUCKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON FIRM UNDER THE GUN TO FIX ARMY TRUCKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A design flaw in trucks built by Houston-based
Stewart &AMP; Stevenson Services for the U.S. Army causes vehicles to
tip or roll over when driven at higher speeds, military and company
officials confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While company officials hope to unveil a solution to the problem
as early as Monday, the Army has ordered drivers operating more
than 6,000 Stewart &AMP; Stevenson trucks to slow down to 30 mph.
</P>
<P>
   And the Pentagon has decided not to award Stewart &AMP; Stevenson a
new $1.4 billion contract to build additional trucks until the flaw
is corrected.
</P>
<P>
   The Army sounded the alarm about the 2.5-ton trucks in March,
after the vehicles were involved in three separate highway
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators blame the mishaps on severe engine vibration,
which became most pronounced when empty vehicles were driven at
speeds above 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   That vibration caused the trucks' drive shafts to break lose.
And in two of the accidents, those flailing drive shafts struck the
trucks' air brake lines, which set off the vehicles' emergency
braking systems.
</P>
<P>
   Caught unaware, the drivers lost control of their vehicles. One
truck rolled over on its top, while another fell over on its side.
</P>
<P>
   In a third incident, the drive shaft missed the brake line, and
the operator was able to bring the vehicle safely to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers in these mishaps suffered only minor injuries. But
when Army officials identified potential problems in at least 170
vehicles, the Army set a lower speed limit, not only for the
company's 2.5-ton trucks but for a 5-ton class as well.
</P>
<P>
   LaRoy Hammer, Stewart &AMP; Stevenson's senior vice president, said
the vibration problem was not identified, despite more than a
million miles worth of testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't replicate this incident,'' Hammer said. ``Were we
stupid, or was it a situation where we should have known? I guess
we could beat each other to death over that.''
</P>
<P>
   To fix the flaw, Stewart &AMP; Stevenson _ working in conjunction
with engine-maker Caterpillar, General Motors' Allison Transmission
division and drivetrain maker Meritor _ has designed a new bracket
that company officials expect will eliminate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Hammer said he expects the company to finish testing the bracket
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This coming Monday, we will have sufficient data for me to
publicly announce the fix is in place,'' Hammer predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials plan to install the brackets on both the
2.5-ton and 5-ton vehicles. Both Stewart &AMP; Stevenson and its
contractors plan to share the cost of the repair work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost is not that significant,'' Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Army has experienced 13 accidents with the Stewart
&AMP; Stevenson trucks, but only three have been attributed to the
mechanical trouble. The others have all been blamed on driver
error.
</P>
<P>
   Better known as a maker and distributor of diesel and gas
turbine engines, Stewart &AMP; Stevenson has agreed to build nearly
11,000 trucks for the Army under a multiyear, $1.4 billion
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The company has only delivered about 6,000 of those trucks so
far, to be used both on the road as well as on unpaved terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Stewart &AMP; Stevenson contract is just one phase of the Army's
30-year, $15.9 billion effort to replace its aging truck fleet with
more than 85,000 new vehicles, an Army spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart &AMP; Stevenson already has negotiated a contract with the
Army to build another 8,500 trucks, ranging in price from $100,000
to $260,000 apiece, Hammer said. Like the initial contract, that
work order could be worth $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the military is holding off on that contract until the
vibration issue is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes back to basic consumerism,'' a Defense Department
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the military is of critical import for Stewart &AMP;
Stevenson. The company's Tactical Vehicle Systems unit accounted
for about 36 percent of the company's sales last year. And the U.S.
government is the unit's primary customer.
</P>
<P>
   As the company noted in a recent filing with the U.S. Securities
&AMP; Exchange Commission: ``The loss of this customer would have a
material adverse effect on the company's consolidated future
financial condition and results of operation.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gaspar, an analyst with Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co. in
Milwaukee, doesn't believe the Army will turn to some other
competitor to build the next batch of trucks. Gaspar figures the
military would have to delay the program by another two to three
years to certify another supplier to provide the new trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be able to solve this problem,'' Baird said. ``I
don't think this is insurmountable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
