<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FALCON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD DEFEAT IS BACK TO HAUNT THE SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-DIPLO, KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's coming show of strength in Albania and
Macedonia is clearly meant to represent its resolve to stop the
Yugoslav crackdown on separatists in Kosovo. Then there is the
military exercise's code name, announced Friday: ``Operation
Determined Falcon.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing a name for the military exercise, which could begin
as early as Sunday, NATO's military commanders passed over the
usual workaday choices like ``Operation Deliberate Force,'' the
name for the air strikes in Bosnia in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they invoked the falcon, a symbol that is at the heart
of Serbian history and lore and will almost certainly be recognized
by the Serbs who dominate the Yugoslav state but are a minority in
the predominantly ethnic Albanian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1389 the Serbian leader Prince Lazar is said to have dreamed
of a falcon on the eve of the Battle of Kosovo, the epic engagement
in which Turkish forces defeated the Serbs. In the dream, the
legend goes, the falcon offered Prince Lazar the choice between an
earthly kingdom and a celestial one.
</P>
<P>
   Lazar dies in the battle, having chosen the celestial kingdom,
but the defeat of the Serbs near Pristina, the modern capital of
Kosovo, has been a rallying cry for Serbian nationalists and a
historic root of Serbian animosity toward Kosovo's ethnic Albanians
and Bosnia's Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for NATO's military commanders, Col. Konrad Freytag,
said he did not know exactly how the planners had settled on the
name, but he said it was not, in itself, meant to convey any
significant political or symbolic meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Code names, he said, are chosen by military planners for clarity
and ease of communication, although he conceded that they sometimes
come to have symbolic significance.
</P>
<P>
   NATO will complete the details of the exercise Saturday. It is
expected to include 20 to 30 combat aircraft from eight NATO
nations, including the United States. The aircraft, based at
Aviano, Italy, will conduct mock bombing raids in Albania and
Macedonia, close to Kosovo's border. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
