<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT &LR;      06-12 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATES OF SCHOOL VOUCHERS HEARTENED BY RULING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis., Conn., N.J.)   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Emboldened by a Wisconsin Supreme Court decision this
week permitting the use of taxpayer money to pay religious school
tuition, advocates for the use of school vouchers in the New York
area say they believe they now have fresh ammunition to press their
cause.
</P>
<P>
   The proponents said they were encouraged by the Wisconsin
justices' ruling that a Milwaukee voucher program giving tuition
money to parents, rather than directly to parochial schools, did
not violate the First Amendment's separation of church and state.
That, the justices said, is because the program's primary purpose
was not to advance religion.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal scholars believe the issue will become a test case
before the U.S. Supreme Court, and if the Wisconsin decision is
ultimately upheld, the advocates say, then the restrictions of
individual state constitutions would govern the use of vouchers. In
the aftermath of the ruling, they have begun assessing the hurdles
in their own state constitutions and the political prospects,
however difficult, within their legislatures.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the organizers of a privately financed voucher
program said that the Wisconsin decision had provided them with
grist to lobby for taxpayer-supported vouchers as a solution to the
grave problems in the Hartford public schools; this in a state in
which the Republican governor, John Rowland, and one U.S. senator,
Joseph Lieberman, a Democrat, have expressed at least some support
for experimenting with vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the founders of a program that has awarded
privately financed vouchers to 2,200 public-school children during
the last two years said the Wisconsin decision could lead to an
intermediate step on the road to public vouchers: the awarding of
tax credits for parents who send their children to parochial and
other private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler, a Republican who has been a
leading voucher advocate in New Jersey, said that he was hastily
planning a lobbying blitz in support of already proposed
legislation, heretofore given little chance of enactment, that
would permit pilot voucher programs in every county.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have had a Supreme Court rule in Wisconsin that there is
no church-state problem with vouchers,'' said Schundler. ``That
suggests you will also see other state supreme courts rule in a
similar vein.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not necessarily true, even some advocates say. New
York, for instance, is one of 37 states that amended their state
constitutions in the late 19th and early 20th centuries to restrict
the spending of public money on parochial schools, according to the
Becket Fund for Religious Liberty, a public-interest law firm that
defends voucher programs. Most of those states acted after James G.
Blaine, a Republican presidential hopeful, failed in his bid in
1876 to attach such an amendment, widely described by scholars as
virulently anti-Catholic, to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the state constitution stipulates that no ``public
money,'' used ``directly or indirectly,'' may aid ``any school or
institution of learning wholly or in part under the control or
direction of any religious denomination or in which any
denominational tenet or doctrine is taught.''
</P>
<P>
   While New Jersey and Connecticut, like Wisconsin, have no such
provisions in their constitutions, the laws in each are ambiguous
enough to give advocates on both sides cause for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the Legislature is not permitted, under the
constitution, to ``borrow, appropriate or use'' the ``fund for the
support of free public schools'' for ``any other purpose.'' But the
state constitution stops short of an outright ban on using taxpayer
money to aid religious schools. The Connecticut constitution
declares that ``no law shall ever be made'' authorizing that the
``school fund'' be ``diverted to any other use than the
encouragement and support of public schools.'' But as in New
Jersey, it does not bar spending other public money on religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the courts in those states were to give their
blessing to the concept of spending taxpayer money on religious
schools, the political opposition would be strong.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, for example, has perhaps the most powerful
teachers union in the country _ indeed, it has been the
legislators' most generous campaign patron _ and its leaders have
been adamant in their opposition to vouchers, which they say would
threaten to siphon children, and the money spent on them, away from
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the lifeblood of public schools,'' said Randi
Weingarten, the president of the United Federation of Teachers, the
New York City teachers' union. ``Either you believe in public
education or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the union's opposition, and the strong wording of the
constitution, proponents of vouchers within New York state hold out
little hope for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Flanigan, a Wall Street executive who helped organize the
privately financed voucher program in New York City last year, said
he believed that tax credits for parents who pay parochial or
private school tuition might pass constitutional muster.
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Sanders, a Manhattan Democrat who is the chairman of
the State Assembly's Education Committee, said the Assembly would
resist. ``If you were to allow tax credits,'' Sanders said, ``it
would merely be a circumvention around using tax dollars and state
aid as it exists now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, Lewis Andrews, the chairman and executive
director of the Children's Educational Opportunity Foundation of
America, has established private voucher programs for 125 public
school students in Bridgeport and 200 in Hartford. He said he would
lobby for a publicly financed voucher program for Hartford, whose
troubled school system is under the control of a state panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wisconsin decision gets people to realize it's maybe not a
religious issue, but an education issue,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the Democratic-controlled state House of
Representatives deadlocked, 71-71, on a bill that would have
permitted publicly financed vouchers, sending it to defeat.
Subsequent measures did not pass out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think it is not a good place to put taxpayer
dollars into private and religious schools when there is no public
accountability for how those funds are spent,'' said Cameron
Staples, a Democrat who is the co-chairman of the state Assembly's
joint House-Senate Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman, a Republican, is a
supporter of publicly financed vouchers, but the Legislature
blocked a pilot voucher program in 1994. Now, the Legislature is
considering several similar bills, and Schundler said he was
confident that the Wisconsin justices' reasoning would change some
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question has always been,'' Schundler said, ``when do we
want to get our grass-roots supporters cranking to put pressure on
the Legislature? I think it's time to start cranking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
