<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP HOST TEAM IMPRESSIVE IN 3-0 WIN OVER SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ Though the French were the driving force
behind the creation of soccer's World Cup, they never have managed
to reach the final of the event that Jules Rimet and Henri Delaunay
essentially launched in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   That streak may not end this summer, but anyone who watched the
French convincingly defeat South Africa, 3-0, Friday night in their
first World Cup match in 12 years knows that this team is a
legitimate threat to change its nation's luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the French public understands, because it has been
fooled lately by the press,'' said French coach Aime Jacquet.
``This is a very good, very poised, very unselfish team. The door
is wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   The player most capable of holding it open throughout this
tournament is Jacquet's playmaker, Zinedine Zidane, a 25-year-old
midfielder who was born in Marseille and grew up in a public
housing development in one of its hardscrabble neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The son of Algerian immigrants, Zidane has long been a symbol to
France's many residents of North African descent, but since leaving
Bordeaux to join Juventus of Turin in the Italian first division in
the summer of 1996, he has broadened his appeal and horizons
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   With Zidane at the controls, Juventus has won the last two
Italian league titles and reached two consecutive finals of the
Champion's League: Europe's most prestigious competition for clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A genius,'' Jacquet said recently of Zidane. ``Since going to
Italy, he's had to be at his best every weekend and has taken on a
new dimension. He is the one who can lift our level. With him, we
can win the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen, but with Zidane's remarkable
ball-control skills and unnerving knack for finding gaps with his
passes, the French were certainly able to win their opening match
in Group C despite a vicious and unseasonable Mistral wind that
played nasty tricks on the ball and made June in Marseille feel
more like March in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   People in the crowd of 60,000 in Marseille, which included
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, were chanting Zidane's
nickname ``Zizou'' before the game and in the early going, but
despite producing plenty several chances, it wasn't until the 34th
minute that Zizou produced a goal.
</P>
<P>
   It came off a corner kick, which he struck cleanly in the
direction of his close friend Christophe Dugarry, whose header
brushed the inside of the far goalpost and careened into the South
African net. Dugarry immediately embarked on a joyful, wide-eyed
sprint. It was a form of release for a young striker who was widely
considered a poor choice for the French national team after
struggling the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He did not start Friday night, but after Stephane Guivarch
strained ligaments in his left knee in the 26th minute, Dugarry
came off the bench. Three minutes later, he squandered the first
golden opportunity Zidane gave him, but he capitalized on the
second. He and Zidane own a bar called ``Nulle Part Ailleurs''
(Nowhere Else) in Bordeaux, and now they will have a good story to
tell their clients. ``I'm so happy for him,'' Zidane said later.
``He needed that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   France would get two more in the second half. In the 77th
minute, Dugarry passed to teammate Youri Djorkaeff who shot on goal
from 15 yards out. Goalkeeper Hans Vonk dove to his right and
appeared to be in good position to stop it, but before the ball
reached him, South African defender Pierre Issa lashed out with his
left foot and redirected the ball into his own goal. Issa, who
plays for Marseille's club team, was suddenly a very popular man
for the wrong reason.
</P>
<P>
   French striker Thierry Henry added a final goal in extra time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A perfect evening,'' said Henry, who like every member of the
French and South African teams was playing in his first World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   France last appeared in 1986 in Mexico, when Michel Platini was
its star and it finished third. Platini has since made the leap
from playmaker to deal-maker; he is co-president of France's World
Cup organizing committee and is expected to be the right-foot man
of Joseph Blatter, who on Monday was elected president of the
sport's international governing body FIFA. But France's national
team would struggle more than Platini.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to qualify in 1990, France was considered certain
to take part in 1994 in the United States. With two qualifying
matches remaining, both at home, it needed only to defeat
relatively weak Israel or draw with Bulgaria. But the French
proceeded to surrender a 2-1 lead against Israel in the final 10
minutes and lose. Against Bulgaria, the score was tied at 1 when,
with only seconds remaining, Bulgaria's Emil Kostadinov scored off
a counterattack. The next morning, the French newspaper
``Liberation'' ran the memorable headline: ''France Qualifies! For
1998!''
</P>
<P>
   As the home team, France was indeed guaranteed a spot, but its
new and enormously gifted generation of players, most of whom play
for clubs outside of the country, is certainly deserving. France's
fullbacks and midfielders are among the world's best. The problem
before this World Cup was up front, where France lacked a proven
striker. That missing element and Jacquet's inherently conservative
approach helped foster pessimism in recent months. But three goals
in 90 minutes should be enough to convert most skeptics into
believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me, they're the favorites,'' said South African
coach Philippe Troussier, who might be even more objective if he
weren't French. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
