<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A blip in the Dow's dip
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Falling stock prices lured investors back into the
market on Friday, triggering a rally that wiped out what had been a
127-point loss for the Dow Jones industrial average. Still, the
buying isn't expected to continue, given the fundamental market
worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying on the dips has been a good strategy for individual
investors,'' Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist for Edward
Jones, said of the rally. ``We saw some bargain hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's turnaround gave the benchmark Dow its first gain in
four sessions but left it with a loss of almost 203 points for the
week.
</P>
<P>
   The late-session buying also boosted the secondary and broader
markets, which have declined even more than the blue chips since
the end of the first quarter. The Nasdaq composite and Russell 2000
indexes of technology and smaller stocks closed above their lows,
but with small loses for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Energy and energy-service sectors led the turnaround as oil
stocks rebounded from sharp selling earlier in the week. Technology
and blue chip stocks that have been under pressure also gained.
</P>
<P>
   Investors easily digested the government's report that producer,
or wholesale, prices rose only 0.2 percent in May, although it was
the second straight monthly gain.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome was official news that Japan's economy _ second
only to the United States' _ has fallen into the second recession
in six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is the key to an Asian recovery,'' said Skrainka. ``If
it deteriorates, the Asian region will remain under pressure. The
problems are serious and will not go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrainka contends that Asia's problems will not have a major
impact on the U.S. economy, since total U.S. trade represents only
about 12 percent of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts worry that Japan's reluctance to reform its
economy threatens to spread Asia's problems to other world markets,
and that would affect the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Investors will find out Thursday how much worse the Asian impact
has become, when the United States releases its April trade
figures.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the trade deficit rose to a six-year high of $13
billion. A Bloomberg News survey of analysts looks for the April
deficit to increase to $13.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Deepening concern about Asia comes just ahead of the next round
of corporate profit reports. Companies that may have second-quarter
problems are expected to issue advance warnings over the next few
weeks, prior to the release of final reports in July.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter corporate profits declined 2.2 percent
year-over-year, according to the Commerce Department. That followed
the 2.3 percent decline in fourth-quarter 1997 profits, for the
first instance of back-to-back profit declines since the 1990-92
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
