</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand gardenia perfumes gardens and memories
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Gardenia. I love the sound of the word. Some lyricist
did too, as I recall, writing of a ``blue gardenia.'' Never have I
seen any but white ones. White, like the color of snow, like the
color of whiteouts and killer glaciers. Deathly, ghostly white. But
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   And sad, somehow. Why sad, I don't know for sure. I do think
that Billie Holiday is one reason. She, with her gardenia behind
her ear, she of the sadly beautiful songs _ ``... ain't nobody's
business if I do ... strange fruit hanging from the poplar trees
... lover man, where can you beeeeee ...'' _ she of the tragic
life, she has to be one of the reasons the gardenia for some evokes
tragedy, she of the wasted death.
</P>
<P>
   Death, yes, that sweetness associated with funeral flowers. That
makes some dislike _ fear? _ gardenia. These are those who have sat
too many times without air conditioning in country churches,
fanning themselves during hot afternoon funerals, listening to the
haunting songs _ ``... swing low, sweet chariot ...'' _ staring at
the casket up front seemingly afloat in sweet lilies and tuberoses
and ... gardenias.
</P>
<P>
   I have sat in too many of those churches, but I am not in that
number. I still love the flower. Always have. Always will.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the gardenia is in its high bloom season, I am in
high cotton, enjoying its fragrance as it transports me back, back
in time to sweet, hot Southern nights when the flower perfumed the
air of Meridian, Miss., and infused my youth with its richness.
Enjoying its fragrance takes me forward, too, forward to the time
when my small gardenia bushes, scattered around my gardens in
Atlanta and McCaysville, will reach the enviable heights that I see
in so many older spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Even with my smallish bushes, I coax enough blooms to keep one
in the house throughout the season. My best producer is one I
brought inside for the winter, one that now blooms more than all
the rest combined. Together, my several gardenias may have a
half-dozen blossoms at any given time.
</P>
<P>
   But how many do you need? Just one of these lovelies lights a
home _ even after it begins to brown and dry. If I have just two
blooms, one comes inside.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Wallace, friend and neighbor, understands. Sitting in her
garden the other day, her gardenia showing off with more than a
dozen perfect blossoms, we talked about our love for this sweet
thing.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the gardenia is a metaphor for the garden that Kay
is lovingly building. A frequent traveler, she lingers at her
gardenia on each return. And while away, she telephones her sister,
Alexis Barrett, to ask about its condition. ``She gives me the blow
by blow. She'll say, `You've got lots of buds.'''
</P>
<P>
   That sustains Kay until she returns to see and smell and touch
and cut.
</P>
<P>
   Her gardenia love began in childhood back in her native
Tuscaloosa, Ala., where she recalls smelling the blossoms in the
gardens of older women.
</P>
<P>
   She loves gardenia more now than yesteryear, associating them
with Billie, of course, ``and with anticipation,'' noting the
pregnant elegance of the about-to-open bud, white, tinged with
green, noting too that it recalls ``a past that we won't ever have
again.''
</P>
<P>
   What else, I ask, does this flower mean? What does it evoke?
</P>
<P>
   ``That you can write about?'' she said, meaningfully.
</P>
<P>
   Ain't nobody's business ...
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
