<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-POLE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weather change puts Ward Burton on pole
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ It was payback time for Ward Burton Friday as
he won the pole for Sunday's Miller Lite 400 at Michigan Speedway
with a speed of 181.561 miles per hour, his second pole of the year
and fourth of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Burton was the 20th car out, catching a sudden cloud cover that
cooled the track and enhanced his time of 39.656 seconds. Earlier
this year, in qualifying for the Coca-Cola 600, he seemed a lock to
win the pole, but a sudden burst of sun broke through the clouds,
denying him that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win some, lose some,'' said Burton, who became the 13th
different pole-winner in the 13 NASCAR Winston Cup races at
Michigan since June 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett, in his Ford Taurus, joins Burton on the front row,
running 181.210 mph in 39.733 seconds. Rusty Wallace, 181.082, was
third, and Jeff Gordon fourth at 180.918 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Pontiacs are good, and the guys are doing a good job of
adjusting them for me,'' Burton said. ``But the biggest difference
is what's under the hood. We were really good in the 600 and didn't
get to show it at the end. We were probably a 15th-place car there
(instead, winding up 34th). It's time we get it turned back
around.''
</P>
<P>
   It was pretty much another Ford show, with nine qualifying in
the top 15. The Chevy teams placed five, and Burton's was the lone
Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that's over,'' Gordon said. ``We were so off all day.
We weren't hiding anything. We were just flat-out struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   In somewhat of a turnaround, Dale Earnhardt, who was next to
last in the final practice session, came back to take the 25th
spot, his first in the top 25 since Talladega nearly two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I made it the first day (of qualifying),'' Earnhardt
said. ``We've fought this for race after race. I know 25th isn't
first, but it's a hell of an improvement from 43rd. Getting in the
first day makes a big difference. Now, we can come out here
Saturday and concentrate on getting our car ready to go race.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen others are in danger. John Andretti wrecked his car in
practice; Todd Bodine, Kyle Petty, Dave Marcis, Morgan Shepherd and
Chad Little are looking at provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
