<SLUG> BC-NBA-NOTEBOOK12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Busy offseason lies ahead for Jordan
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO -- Whether his basketball career ends with the
conclusion of the NBA Finals or the coming months bring a
well-deserved vacation, Michael Jordan has plenty of offseason
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's love for golf is well-known, and an offhand remark in a
magazine garnered him an exemption to play in this year's Illinois
Open, Aug. 6-8 in nearby Aurora. Jordan has not responded to the
Illinois Professional Golf Association yet.
</P>
<P>
   IPGA executive director Mike Miller said: ``Our contact with
Michael was the result of a Golf Digest article in which he said
after he retired he had an interest in competitive golf. He
mentioned the Illinois Open. Based on that, we sent a letter to him
offering an exemption. I'm anticipating a yes or no after the NBA
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also learned that Jordan and wife Juanita have leased a
palatial home in Vancouver for the month of July. The luxury home
rents for $25,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   West Vancouver Mayor Pat Boname said the family could expect the
people there to be ``not only friendly, but less intrusive'' than
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would respect his privacy,'' she said. ``We would just be
grateful that he is here and say, `Have a good time and we'll see
you around.'''
</P>
<P>
   Riding the wave
</P>
<P>
   Many players have ridden on Jordan's and Scottie Pippen's
coattails to NBA championship rings. Many of them were present
during this year's NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey King, an underachieving big man, was one of them. King is
thankful for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty percent of me wishes I could have gone to a team where
I could have played 40 minutes a game and scored a lot of points,
but taken my lumps,'' said King, who played in Turkey this year.
``It's a tradeoff. With the Bulls, I was just a piece of a puzzle.
Eighty percent of me, though, wouldn't trade those three
championships for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl denies report
</P>
<P>
   Former Seattle coach George Karl denied a report in the Chicago
Tribune this week that he was on the Bulls' list of candidates to
replace Phil Jackson, who is not expected to be re-signed after the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Karl said he has not been contacted by Bulls general manager
Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't talk to any team that already has a coach,'' Karl
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Karl said he probably would not coach at all next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a betting man, I'd bet that I sit out.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing with Rodman
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz's Jeff Hornacek said he'd take the wild Dennis Rodman
as a teammate anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys sometimes, when they go to set a pick, they put their
hands inside of them and stand up straight and don't really set a
good pick,'' Hornacek said. ``But Dennis does, and it opens things
up. You need guys like that to make a team go. I'd take him in a
heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
