<SLUG> BC-RELIGION12-MUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran band takes care of details (4HIM, ``Obvious'')
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The pleasures of 4HIM's ``Obvious'' are indeed
obvious. There are rich vocal harmonies and hook-laden songs, but
they shouldn't be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Much of contemporary Christian music has been taken over by a
youth movement, post-adolescent musicians who favor hyper-driven
tunes that yield more energy than actual musical skill.
</P>
<P>
   That's why ``Obvious'' is so refreshing. This veteran Christian
band takes care of the small details: well-written songs and smooth
harmonizing that makes a listener want to hum along. The approach
has netted the Daphne, Ala.-based group 21 No. 1 songs on Christian
radio, six Dove Awards and a Grammy Award nomination.
</P>
<P>
   4HIM is known for its blend of voices. The group combines the
vocal stylings of '70s supergroups such as Ambrosia and Chicago.
Those influences are obvious on songs such as the uptempo ``Voice
In The Wilderness'' and the bouncy ``Can't Get Past the Evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The album's music is a perfect complement to 4HIM's harmonizing.
The group has abandoned the ``wall of sound'' approach used on its
previous album for a more sparse, organic sound on ``Obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   The new style works. From the shimmering acoustic guitar opening
of ``Let the Lion Run Free'' to the muscular drumming throughout,
the sound of ``Obvious'' is sparkling, full of clever hooks and
tasteful musical touches.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong suit for ``Obvious'' is its variety. Most of the
songs are straight-ahead pop/rock, but on ``Who's at the Wheel,''
4HIM employs an urban R&AMP;B approach that works surprisingly well.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
