<SLUG> BC-THRASHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers' GM search winds down
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As the Stanley Cup finals wind down, so does the
Atlanta Thrashers' search for a general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL expansion team might select its general manager as early
as next week, and the job is expected to be filled by one of four
candidates: NHL director of operations Brian Burke, Detroit
assistant general manager Don Waddell, hockey agent Mike Gillis or
Dallas assistant general manager Les Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Gillis, 39, was interviewed by Thrashers president Harvey
Schiller recently and is considered one of the hot candidates in
NHL circles. He also is a candidate for the GM vacancy in
Vancouver, which contacted him during the all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   Gillis, who is based in Kingston, Ontario, declined to comment
on his candidacy or whether he is seeking any job.
</P>
<P>
   A former player with Boston and Colorado, Gillis is the only one
of the GM prospects with no management experience. But teams hiring
agents for the front office has become a league trend. The best
example is Pierre Lacroix, who made the transition from a player
representative to a management role with the Quebec Nordiques
before the franchise was moved to Colorado. Gillis, who attended
law school in Ontario, has about 20 NHL clients, including Canucks
star forward Pavel Bure.
</P>
<P>
   Burke also is a possibility in Vancouver. He is the only
Thrasher candidate with general manager experience.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller and Thrashers vice president Dave Maggard, who have
acknowledged publicly only that Burke is a candidate, plan to
attend Games 3 and 4 of the Cup finals in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
