<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rains, wildflowers _ and butterflies
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The recent rains have revived wildflowers, which in
turn have perked up butterflies. ``We've definitely got more
butterflies since the last big rain a week or so ago,'' says
naturalist Jerry Payne, who lives in Musella near Macon. Native
verbenas, buttonbush, butterfly weed and other wildflower favorites
of butterflies are sporting their blooms now. ``All the butterflies
that are supposed to be here this time of year are here,'' says
Payne. ``We're seeing lots of tiger swallowtails (Georgia's state
butterfly), buckeyes, pearl crescents, American painted ladies, red
spotted purples, red admirals and a few monarchs; and we're
beginning to get the skippers common for this time of year, such as
cloudy wings and whirlabouts.''
</P>
<P>
   FIELD NOTES: The color white dominates the blooms at the
Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area right now, says
naturalist Jerry Hightower. Sporting white flowers are Southern
magnolias, silky dogwoods, Virginia willows, yucca, New Jersey tea
and elder-
</P>
<P>
   berry. However, yellow-flowered loosestrife, purple-flowered
curly milkweed and the brilliant orange-flowered butterfly weed are
adding dashes of color to the park.
</P>
<P>
   Many turtle species also are moving about, Hightower says.
During the past week, he has saved several box turtles and some
snapping turtles, painted turtles and musk turtles from being run
over by cars on streets in or near the park. Remember, if you
rescue a road-crossing turtle, always place it to the side to which
it was headed. If you place it on the side from which it crawled,
it will simply try to cross the road again. Also, be extremely
careful around snapping turtles. They can stretch their necks
longer than you think, and they can bite with bone-crunching power.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southern Nantahala Wilderness Area in mountainous Towns
and Rabun counties along the Georgia-North Carolina border,
naturalist Glenn Barnett says the blooms of purplish-flowered
spiderwort, fire pink and fawn's breath (aptly named because of its
soft, delicate, off-white flowers) are impressive now. Sheep
laurel, a miniature mountain laurel that also has clusters of
pinkish, cup-shaped flowers, is blooming in sunny, rocky, open
areas on ridgetops. Also at high elevations, Carolina rhododendron
is in flower. ``And there are larger-than-usual colonies this year
of my favorite wild edible, the Indian cucumber root,'' which has a
cucumberlike taste, says Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also seeing lots of insect galls on trees and other
plants.'' The galls, which resemble cancerlike growths, are caused
by tiny wasps or other insects, whose larvae live in the galls and
later bore their way out and feed on the plants.
</P>
<P>
   BEAR NOTES: Want to know more about Georgia's black bears? Then
go to Brasstown Bald _ at 4,784 feet Georgia's highest peak _ on
June 20, 11 a.m.-4 p.m. The Chattahoochee/
</P>
<P>
   Oconee Heritage Association, a nonprofit group that works with
the Forest Service to help visitors enjoy Georgia's national
forests, is holding its first Black Bear Day. Experts will be there
to provide information and answer questions about the bears. For
more information: 706-896-3471.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE SKY: The moon will be at last-quarter phase on Wednesday
evening, rising out of the east about midnight, says Fernbank
Science Center astronomer David Dundee. Jupiter rises out of the
east four hours before sunrise; it can be seen near the moon
Wednesday evening. Saturn comes up in the east three hours before
sunrise and appears near the moon on Friday morning. Venus also is
in the east, rising just before sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
