<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King family to meet with Clinton on MLK slaying
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coretta Scott King and three of her children will
meet with President Clinton next week, as the slain civil rights
leader's family presses for a federal investigation into King's
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Citing new evidence in the 30-year-old case, Mrs. King called
for the investigation in April and requested the meeting with
Clinton. The White House confirmed Tuesday's meeting and said
Clinton is glad to talk with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that the president will give serious consideration to
our request for a federal panel to examine all the evidence
surrounding the death of my husband,'' Mrs. King said in a
statement Friday. ``The majority of Americans want to know the
truth behind the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. I firmly
believe that this can best be done through the appointment of a
federal commission composed of individuals of unassailable
character and integrity. I feel this is the only way we can achieve
a sense of closure, not only for my family, but for the entire
nation and move forward to fulfill Martin's dream of a nation
united in justice and brotherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The national panel that King's widow envisions would be
patterned after the Truth and Reconciliation Commission in South
Africa, which is holding hearings on racial atrocities during the
apartheid era and offers immunity to participants who give honest
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying Mrs. King will be Martin Luther King III, Dexter
Scott King and the Rev. Bernice King.
</P>
<P>
   James Earl Ray, who died in April at age 70, pleaded guilty in
1969 to the April 4, 1968, assassination but recanted within days.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
