</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- June 12, 1998 -- CLINTON-STARR, 6-12 --
Monica Lewinsky leaving the offices of her lawyers Friday
afternoon. Prosecutors looking into President Clinton's
relationship with the former White House intern are investigating
contacts between one of his senior aides and potential witnesses
shortly after the investigation began, according to lawyers who
have read a sealed legal opinion describing the contacts. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) CORONA, Calif. -- June 12, 1998 -- BRANDED-DRUGS, 6-12
-- Companies that primarily sell generic drugs are increasingly
replacing the identically drab scientific labels on their products
with brand names of their own, raising prices in step with a higher
profile. ``We decided the only way to deliver consistent earnings,
quarter after quarter, was to go into the branded drug business,''
says Allen Chao, chief executive of Watson Pharmaceuticals, at the
company headquarters in Corona. (Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MOSCOW -- June 12, 1998 -- MOSCOW-ILLEGAL-LABOR, 6-12 --
Moscow's exuberent prosperity attracts illegal workers from
depressed regions of Russia, countries once part of the Soviet
Union and beyond. Men departing a train from the Ukraine crowd a
railroad platform recently. (James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- June 12, 1998 -- ASTRO-GLENN, 6-12 -- When
he rockets up in October for a nine-day ride at the age of 77, Sen.
John Glenn, the first American to orbit the earth 36 years ago,
will once more be a space pioneer, running a myriad of geriatric
medical experiments on himself as the oldest space traveller ever.
``I told them that at the other end of the line I may be a senator,
but down there I'm John, a working crew member,'' he says of
dealing with the other six members of the flight. ``They liked
that.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- NY-PARK-LAWN, 6-12 -- The
Central Park Conservancy has created a new position with a broad
mandate and a grandiose title: Keeper of the Great Lawn. Maria
Hernandez, 45, is the keeper, and although she enjoys her work, she
takes the job very seriously. ``If you're working in such a
magnificently beautiful place, you should have a good time,'' says
Ms. Hernandez, who patrols the 55-acre Great Lawn area with a golf
cart. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
WOMEN'S-SUMMER-HATS, 6-12 -- As hemlines flutter below the knee
this spring, the stock market may not be falling with them, despite
Wall Street lore, but another leading indicator associated with
plunging hemlines has taken effect: the return of hats. Clockwise
from upper left, Sheenan Huxham roof hat, $220; Mad Hatter style
from Philip Treacy, $359; Patricia Underwood's Isabella, $415. (Don
Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
SINGLE-CLUBS-2, 6-12 -- Cigars for sale at Decade, an Upper East
Side club. With growing ranks of people over 35 finding themselves
single in a social world not set up for them, a niche is arising
for clubs that cater to those with more years, more money and more
unapologetically discriminate taste. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
SINGLE-CLUBS-2, 6-12 -- Mingling en masse at Decade, an Upper East
Side club. With growing ranks of people over 35 finding themselves
single in a social world not set up for them, a niche is arising
for clubs that cater to those with more years, more money and more
unapologetically discriminate taste. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
EXPENSIVE-SOAPS, 6-12 -- No, it is not edible, but Portico does
call this fancy soap bar Milk Chocolate. As the proliferation of
luxury bath boutiques indicates, soap snobbery is on the rise.
(David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
ABOUT-CARS-PORSCHE, 6-12 -- Porsche 911's have always been superior
sports cars despite their quirks, with capable handling and
rocket-like speed. This year, as Porsche marks the 50th anniversary
of its first car, it has reinvented itself by remaking its
34-year-old flagship. The sleeker, all-new 911 Carrera Coupe, top;
the 911 Carrera Cabriolet. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) INDIAN WELLS, Calif. -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 14 -- CLUBCORP-DISPUTE-3, 6-12 -- Club Corp. International
claims it is dedicated to ``the genuine care and comfort of our
members,'' but Fred Sardella, an outspoken member of the club's
advisory board, complains that Clubcorp ``just didn't do what they
said they would Q this is not a private club, as they promised it
would be.'' (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) CHARLOTTE, N.C. -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE
14 -- CLUBCORP-DISPUTE-2, 6-12 -- When Clubcorp tried to build a
phone tower at the edge of a Raintree Country Club fairway in North
Carolina, Elizabeth Smith, president of the Raintree homeowners'
group, took action. ``My friends tell me that it is just not as
much of a warm and friendly place,'' she says of the effects of the
long battle, which has left its scars on the club's atmosphere.
With her is Syl Bartos, a resident. (Nancy Pierce/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DALLAS -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
CLUBCORP-DISPUTE-1, 6-12 -- Robert Dedman Sr., right, who founded
Club Corp. International, and his son, Bob, who became chief
executive last year. What makes a perfect country club? It should
be ``a haven of refuge'' dedicated to ``the genuine care and
comfort of our members,'' says the elder Dedman. But a surprising
number of the company's clubs have, instead, been the scenes of
litigation filed by members, homeowners and, in one case, a club's
co-owner. (Mark Graham/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
SPEND-SHARES-YACHTS, 7-12 -- Irwin Jacobs aboard one of the luxury
yachts available for partial ownership through his new company,
Yachtscape. Access to a super-luxe, fully equipped Hatteras yacht
is divided into thirds, while a management company handles
everything from providing the crews to catering the cocktail
parties to finding the perfect beach for sunbathing. Each pay $1
million apiece, plus annual fees of $259,000, for the privilege to
share yachts. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
MUTFUND-DREMAN, 6-11 -- David Dreman relaxes aboard his boat, the
Contrarian, docked at the World Financial Center in Manhattan.
Known for his investment success with downtrodden stocks, Dreman
recently began buying oil and tobacco shares. (Linda Rosier/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- June 12, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 14 --
MUTFUND-HANSPETER, 6-12 -- Hanspeter Ackermann the chief investment
officer of Deutsche Bank, in his office. As portfolio manager of
the bank's closed-end New Germany fund, a $665 million growth fund
invested primarily in midsize German companies, Ackermann is
deploying money to pursue some of those opportunities. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
