<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7341 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Wash.-Detroit-HNS &LR;      06-12 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Wash.-Detroit </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caps lean on big guy &QL; 
to pull them through
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig fills net so that Red Wings won't
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ To say that Olaf Kolzig has come up big in goal for
the Washington Capitals during the Stanley Cup playoffs might be
redundant.
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig
</P>
<P>
   But even though Kolzig stands 6-3 and weighs 235 pounds _ a
behemoth compared to the average NHL goaltender _ he's going to
have to come up even bigger if the Caps intend to make a series of
the Stanley Cup finals against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig has been the linchpin throughout the Capitals' first-ever
run to the finals. Despite making 55 saves in a 5-4 overtime loss
to Detroit on Thursday night, Kolzig allowed four goals in the
final 28 minutes, 47 seconds of the third period and overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings bounced back from 3-1 and 4-2 deficits in the
third period and won in overtime to take a commanding 2-0 lead in
the best-of-seven series. Detroit appears poised for its second
straight Stanley Cup sweep as the series resumes tonight at MCI
Center. The biggest question Friday for the Caps was whether the
disheartening loss will bother them in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no choice but to come back,'' said Kolzig, who had not
allowed more than four goals in any of the Caps' previous 18
playoff games before Thursday. ``We could sit here and sulk, and it
would be a quicker series than what we had planned it to be. But we
have to learn from what we did and get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of offense. We've got to respect their
ability but not respect them. I think we gave them a little too
much respect. We had our foot on the head of the snake. We let it
up, and it bit us.''
</P>
<P>
   In no way was Kolzig solely to blame for the Caps' collapse in
Game 2. On most nights, 55 saves should get the job done. The
Washington defense corps, which wearied as the game grew longer,
left Kolzig on his own time after time in the third period and
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was making some great saves,'' Capitals coach Ron Wilson
said. ``I think our defense looked like it was tired. Olie was
fine. You couldn't fault him for any of them (goals by Detroit).''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case Thursday, it's obvious the Caps would not have
come this far into the playoffs without Kolzig. He has been the
best goal-tender the last two months, a surprising development
considering Kolzig started the season as the backup to Bill
Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   But Ranford suffered a groin injury in the first game of the
season, and Kolzig's vast potential finally kicked in. In 64
regular-season games, Kolzig was 33-18-10 with a 2.20 goals-against
average. Before this year, the 28-year-old Kolzig had been a career
minor-leaguer and backup whose legendary temper had held him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first couple years of my career, I wasn't tough
mentally, and I had to work on that,'' Kolzig said. ``I used to
break sticks or threaten guys if they shot too high or threaten
them if they came near me in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was given the opportunity before, I fell flat on my
face. When I got it this year, I wanted to make sure I took
advantage of it. I had been labeled a career backup goaltender, and
I didn't know if I'd get many more chances to become a No. 1 guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig's background might begin to explain why he is a
self-described late bloomer. He was born in Johannesburg, South
Africa, to German parents and never was able to put down roots
throughout his childhood. His father worked for an international
hotel chain and was transferred throughout the world as Olaf was
growing up. Ask Kolzig where he has lived, and his answer is:
``Where haven't I lived? That would probably be easier.''
</P>
<P>
   His father was transferred to Canada when Kolzig was in grammar
school, and that's when Olaf started playing hockey. After a
successful junior hockey career in Western Canada, Kolzig was the
Caps' No. 1 pick in the 1989 draft.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until nearly 10 years later that Kolzig was able
to put everything together. Taming his emotions was the key, since
his goaltending ability has always been rated above average. His
bulk makes it hard for shooters to find an open target up high, but
Kolzig also can handle low shots as well as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olie has a ton of talent,'' Wilson said. ``He's very athletic.
He's huge, and he's got the style that I really like in a goalie.
He's a classic butterfly goaltender. He makes himself big in the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig does not try to downplay his size. He seems to relish the
``Godzilla'' nickname that was hung on him when he played in the
minors and would lose his temper and thrash around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty aggressive,'' Kolzig said. ``I'm pretty big and
would play with a lot of fire. So they gave me the nickname
Godzilla, and it just stuck. With my equipment on and with the way
I play, I fill the net pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that intimidates shooters to maybe not shoot, instead to
look for the perfect pass. If that happens, I've already won the
psychological battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest battle facing Kolzig and the Caps tonight is to post
the franchise's first Stanley Cup finals victory and take some of
the gathering momentum away from the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the best-of-seven format was introduced in 1939, only
three teams have won the Stanley Cup after trailing 2-0. The last
time it happened was 1971, when Montreal beat Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll bounce back at home,'' Wilson said. ``If it takes four
tries to win a game here in Detroit, we'll get one. We lost two
games, both of them by one goal, one of them in overtime. I don't
feel like we're out of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
