<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DRAGGING-DEATH-     06-12 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DRAGGING-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE MARKED BY TROUBLES, BUT NOT BY HATRED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ From the shade of his porch across the street,
Grover Thomas could watch the steady stream of people, black and
white, bearing casseroles and baked chicken and other peace
offerings Friday to the family of James Byrd Jr., who was killed
last week in one of the South's most grotesque racial murders in
many years.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere in his 81-year-old imagination, Thomas _ known as
Pete in the quietly disheveled, mostly black neighborhood of East
Jasper _ still held out hope that Byrd would somehow walk up to his
porch, as he did every morning, with a friendly word and a few
sausages or a cardboard box of dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he didn't come over Sunday, I knew that he was gone, not
coming back,'' Thomas, a retired sawmill hand, said as a rooster
strutted about the dirt lawn and an old dog scratched. ``He had cut
my lawn the day before, and he was supposed to take me to church.
He had his problems, but he never forgot.''
</P>
<P>
   James Byrd never seemed to have made full use of a broad
intelligence and a renowned musical ability, relatives and
neighbors said Thursday. But those who knew him described something
solid within him, a reliability that drove him to take care of
Thomas, an elderly neighbor he had known since boyhood, and a deep
affection for three children of his failed marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his personal problems _ alcoholism, petty thievery,
an inability to hold a job _ he was well-liked and had apparently
never been involved in any kind of racial incident.
</P>
<P>
   Family members, gathered from across Texas for the funeral
Saturday, said they cannot fathom the kind of random racial hatred
that authorities say led three white men to drag him by his ankles
from a pickup truck early Sunday morning, tearing his body to
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the children that this was just an isolated act of
people who were sick and twisted,'' said Clara Taylor, one of
Byrd's sisters, standing on the front lawn of the brown wooden
house where they both grew up and where Byrd's mother and father
still live. ``To do this, you have to believe that someone is just
not worth living to begin with. It had nothing to do with him. It
could have been anyone walking down the street. If they were black,
that is.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's high school class of 1967 was the last segregated class
in this southeast Texas town of 8,000, but even before full
integration began, neither Byrd nor most other residents had any
significant run-ins with white residents, neighbors and relatives
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd often sold vacuum cleaners to make money, said another
sister, Mary Verrett, and had success with both white and black
customers. He would often be seen walking the streets of town,
accepting rides from friends or acquaintances, and never with any
consequences, until this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of racial problems we had here were the kinds of
things where you wouldn't get the promotion or the right jobs,''
said Mrs. Verrett. ``In all the time I grew up, there was never any
outright bigotry, and none of us were afraid to walk the street. In
fact, you could say we were pretty happy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Byrd, who was 49, was the third of eight children of Stella
Byrd, a Sunday school teacher, and James Byrd Sr., a dry cleaner.
The family's life revolved around the Greater New Bethel Baptist
Church, a few blocks away from their home, where Mrs. Byrd taught
and her husband was a deacon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the church doors opened on Sunday, we were there,'' said
Mrs. Taylor, 50, who teaches eighth-grade science in the Houston
public schools. ``There was school in the morning, then services,
then Baptist Training Unit, then church again at night. You knew
what you'd be doing on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Byrd was known in church more for the passion of his
piano playing and singing than his faith. He could pick out any
tune on the keyboard before he was 10, and was particularly adept
at belting out spirituals and hymns, especially ``Walk With Me,
Lord,'' and more recently the pop hit ``I Believe I Can Fly.'' He
was the lead trumpeter in the band at Rowe Elementary School, and
also did a more-than-passable imitation of Al Green.
</P>
<P>
   But despite an excellent academic record at Jasper High School,
he decided not to follow his two sisters into college, even though
he was encouraged to do so by his parents. His friends and
relatives speak vaguely and sadly of an aimless, drifting element
to his life, an unwillingness to commit himself to a career or a
passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so very intelligent, and as his family we always
regretted that he never used his intellectual potential to the
highest capacity,'' said Mrs. Verrett, 47, a medical
transcriptionist who lives in Houston. ``He wasn't the type of
person who liked a 9-to-5 job. He would get in a rut, and then his
personal difficulties would begin.''
</P>
<P>
   The drinking started in high school, friends say, and was
exacerbated by medical problems such as arthritis. (He had also
injured his foot in a bicycle accident in his youth, leading to his
neighborhood nickname of ``Toe.'') At some point, said the Rev.
Kenneth O. Lyons, pastor of Greater New Bethel and a boyhood
friend, Byrd lost his religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to remind him that he was brought up in a Christian
home, and that one day something like this could happen, and he
would need an eternal life,'' Lyons said Friday, after a condolence
call on the family. ``But James, he would challenge me. He would
say, if he came, he would have to be right, completely right, and
he would have to be sincere. I would say, no one's perfect, James.
And he would just look at me with that old look of his.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was married a few years out of high school and stayed with
his wife, on and off, for about 23 years, fathering three children:
Renee Mullins, 27, who until recently served in the Army; Ross, 20,
an Army private stationed at Fort. Benning, Ga., who is scheduled
to serve in South Korea in a few months; and Jamie, 16, who lives
with her mother in Lufkin, Texas, about 50 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage broke up in 1993, three years after Byrd was
convicted of theft and sentenced to seven years in prison. He was
paroled a few years later but sent back to prison for a violation,
returning to Jasper in 1996. At that point, things seemed to begin
to improve. Byrd entered Alcoholics Anonymous and began coming back
to the church, Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   Using his disability money, Byrd got his own one-bedroom
apartment in a housing project in Jasper, and his sisters came over
to help decorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me not to sit on the roll-away bed, because his son
was coming to see him and would be sleeping there,'' said Mrs.
Verrett, who had recently bought him a dinette set she was planning
to give him. ``He was so proud of his children and wanted to
protect them. He always told his daughters it was a jungle out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But he never seemed to view his hometown that way. Many people
in Jasper who didn't know Byrd _ hundreds of whom were wearing
yellow ribbons on their shirts Thursday _ remembered seeing him
meander through town, never putting together enough disability
money to buy a used car, perfectly happy to walk if a friend didn't
pass by offering a ride.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows why he got in that pickup truck on Sunday while
walking home from a friend's house, although police have put
forward the theory that he knew one of the three men accused of the
crime because they had the same parole officer.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours earlier, Byrd had stopped by to cut Thomas'
lawn and see two of his children at a bridal shower for a niece at
his parents' house. It was the last time he was seen by anyone who
loved him, the last time the neighborhood was intact. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
