<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-ATTORNE     06-12 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-ATTACK-ATTORNEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER ATTORNEYS PORTRAY MURDER SUSPECTS AS SHOCKED, REMORSEFUL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
and T.J. MILLING 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ One of the suspects denies he had any role in
last weekend's slaying of a black man and a second suspect is
remorseful and ``not a member of any racial hate group,'' attorneys
for two of the three white men accused in the racially charged
crime said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He denies any involvement,'' Jasper attorney Randy Walker said
of John William ``Bill'' King, 23, of Jasper. King denies even
being in the pickup that investigators said was used to drag James
Byrd Jr., 49, for almost three miles up and down a back country
road east of Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks it's horrible,'' Walker said his client said of the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was one of three local attorneys appointed by a judge
Friday to represent King and his co-defendants Shawn Berry, 23, of
Jasper and Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31 of Sulphur Springs.
Charged with murder, all three have previously served prison
sentences for burglary and other non-violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal authorities consider the slaying of Byrd Jr.,
49, a racial ``hate crime.'' Byrd was beaten and chained by the
ankles to a pickup and dragged over a blacktopped road, ripping his
right arm and his head from his mangled body.
</P>
<P>
   State prison officials say that King and Brewer were monitored
for possible affiliation with extremist white groups while serving
sentences in the Beto I unit at Tennessee Colony in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's lawyer, meanwhile, portrayed his client as a remorseful
young man in the wrong place at the wrong time. It was Berry who
was first arrested in the Byrd slaying because Berry's pickup was
used.
</P>
<P>
   He has given a detailed statement to investigators, saying it
was King, a former high school classmate and prison buddy, who
drove the pickup pulling Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``My client is not a member of any racial hate group,'' said
attorney Steve Hollis. ``He doesn't have any sort of hatred for
black people ... The Shawn Berry you think you know as a racist, as
a member of the Aryan Brotherhood or the Klan doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shaken up. He's sad. He's remorseful. He's confused. Take
your pick. He's all of those things,'' Hollis said. ``Whatever
happened out there that night, he's been able to reflect on ...
He's had time to reflect.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Morian Jr., appointed to represent Russell Brewer Jr.,
refused to discuss details of the case.
</P>
<P>
   He described Brewer as quiet, shy and ``very shocked'' when he
learned of the worldwide media attention Byrd's slaying has
received. Like the other two defendants, Brewer was being kept
alone in an isolation cell Friday, Morian said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very scared man in the Jasper County jail and he's
aware of all the media attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three Jasper attorneys expect to be replaced if their
clients' charges of murder are upgraded to capital murder, which
could mean the death penalty upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Although at least two of them have handled previous capital
cases, they are not currently certified to handle those cases now.
Certification requires additional courses.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis said he met briefly with the district attorney Thursday
but did not discuss a plea bargain for Berry, the only suspect
cooperating with authorities. He said he wants the case to stay in
state district court, but ``my gut on it is it'll go federal.''
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal officials are trying to determine whether the
case can be handled as one of federal civil rights violations in
connection with a hate crime, so that the federal death penalty
could be sought.
</P>
<P>
   Berry has had no contact with his co-defendants in jail,
according to Hollis. He said King was Berry's ``old friend from the
pen'' and that Brewer was ``just a bum who showed up on the
porch.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim was an acquaintance of Berry's from around town and
the suspect had talked to him before, Hollis said. He said Berry
sincerely meant to help Byrd when he stopped to give him a ride
early Sunday, but he was intimidated by Brewer and King.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis, 34, is a graduate of the Texas Tech University law
school and has practiced law since November 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other lawyers, Hollis is a Jasper native. He has been
defense counsel in one capital murder case, although prosecutors
sought life in prison rather than the death penalty. Hollis said
his client was convicted and sentenced to a lengthy term in state
prison.
</P>
<P>
   He also was lead counsel in a non-capital murder case, which
ended in conviction for his client.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, King's attorney, is a former assistant county attorney
in Montgomery and Travis counties who has practiced general law in
Jasper since 1981.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, he has defended two accused capital murderers.
One case ended in a plea bargain; the other in a conviction and
death sentence. The second case was retried on appeal and ended in
a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Walker is a graduate of the University of Texas law school and
also holds a degree in business administration from Louisiana State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's attorney, Morian, 30, has practiced law in Jasper with
the firm of Seale, Stover, Coffield &AMP; Bisbey since obtaining his
law license in November 1991. He is a graduate of the University of
Tulsa law school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reporter Allan Turner in Houston contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
