<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-U.S.-LAWYER     06-12 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-U.S.-LAWYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READYING THE SLINGSHOT FOR A MODERN GOLIATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (bl) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Boies is the former Cravath, Swaine &AMP; Moore superstar
tral lawyer in the cheap suits and stretch limousines who has
defended some of the biggest legal game of the last 30 years: IBM
in its 13-year fight with the government, CBS in the libel suit
brought by Gen. William Westmoreland, and the nation's failed
savings-and-loans against Michael Milken.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is the government's chief lawyer in the snazziest
antitrust lawsuit of the 1990s: United States vs. Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Tough case? ``Not really,'' he said. ``To be honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies (pronounced BOYZ) has been called an eccentric genius, a
prima donna, wry and amusing _ but never modest. He said in an
interview on Wednesday that the Microsoft case would be over by
October (the trial is set to start Sept. 8 in Washington), and that
he was pleased with the judge's decision Tuesday to limit each side
to six to 12 witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the government's best evidence against Microsoft
was Microsoft's own documents, used in the government's complaint.
``We didn't sort of hold back the best,'' Boies said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft responded to Boies' maneuverings with its own.
``That's useful information for us,'' William Neukom, Microsoft's
senior vice president for law and corporate affairs, said about the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Murray, a Microsoft spokesman, said Thursday that the
Justice Department was deliberately withholding the documents it
was using against Microsoft to ``hamstring'' the defense. And so
forth.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the case is this: The government says Microsoft
used its monopoly in its Windows software to illegally crush
competitors in another market _ Internet browsers _ in favor of
Microsoft's own browser, called Internet Explorer. Microsoft
counters that Internet Explorer is an ``integrated product'' with
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Things were sunnier three days ago, when Boies talked in the
study of his very large red-brick house on 10 acres in Armonk,
N.Y., north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   There was a pool, a tennis court, a few dogs, the noises of
children (Boies has six from three wives). It might have been a
pleasant scene from the life of a country squire, were this country
squire not distracted by five phone lines and clients like actor
Garry Shandling, who is suing his manager in what is Boies' most
time-consuming case right now.
</P>
<P>
   Boies, 57, had the body language of a harried man who was just
passing through his home en route from Washington to the office in
Armonk. But he sat still for an hour, in black sneakers and a $160
suit from Macy's, and dismissed the idea that as a onetime IBM
lawyer against the government he can now bring tricks to the
government side.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be sure you don't fight the last war,'' Boies
said. Naturally, he said that he was on the right side both times,
and that ``IBM did not engage in the kind of practices'' that
Microsoft did.
</P>
<P>
   His main lesson from IBM?
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed,'' he said. It took the IBM case five years to get to
trial; eight years after that the Justice Department dropped the
case because it was technologically irrelevant. In May, Boies
pushed for the early Microsoft trial date.
</P>
<P>
   He grew most engaged when he talked about the Sherman Act, the
1890 law passed to control the robber barons, being used against
Microsoft. ``You're applying antitrust principles to software,''
Boies said. ``It's interesting, and it's important. But it's not
that difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   He sees a re-emergence of antitrust enforcement in the 1990s,
after a trough during the Reagan administration, and says antitrust
laws ``are what make free markets possible.''
</P>
<P>
   It is probably impolite to point out that Boies has grown rich
from the antitrust laws _ he was making about $2 million a year
when he left Cravath in 1997 _ especially since he is charging the
Justice Department a bargain-rate $250 an hour for his services.
</P>
<P>
   Boies' usual fee is $600 an hour. He expects his total bill to
the Justice Department will be $100,000, although if it were a
corporate client, he said, ``I would have added at least a zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies was hired by Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general in
charge of the department's antitrust division. Klein said Thursday
that his division had not handled major antitrust cases for several
years, and he needed a lawyer with long-term experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for that many years of orchestrating
litigation,'' he said. ``It's a high art form.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies was asked what inspired his career choice. ``Perry
Mason,'' he said. ``Seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies grew up in Orange County, Calif. His father was a high
school history teacher; Boies thought for a time about getting a
doctorate in American history. Instead he married his girlfriend
right after high school, and worked on a construction crew and as a
bookkeeper before graduating from Northwestern University and then
Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Cravath in 1966, made partner in 1972 and left last
year to represent clients like George Steinbrenner, whose interests
collided with some of the companies the firm represents. (Law firms
may not represent competing clients.)
</P>
<P>
   He now has his own firm, Boies &AMP; Schiller, with 23 lawyers and
clients that include CBS and the French government. He has been
married to his third wife, Mary, since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He has a famous fly-paper memory, and loves to gamble in Las
Vegas. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
