<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUT IMPOSTOR INCOMPETENT, ATTORNEY SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Alabama) 
 
By DEBORAH TEDFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Texas man accused of falsely claiming to be an
astronaut, war hero and secret agent is not competent to stand
trial, his attorney said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During a court hearing, public defender Marjorine Meyers said a
local psychiatrist has determined that Jerry Allen Whittredge of
Galveston is mentally incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers told U.S. Magistrate Judge Calvin Botley that Whittredge
is incapable of assisting in his defense against charges that he
impersonated a federal officer and lied to federal agents _ or even
hiring his own attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Whittredge identified his attorney as William J.
Clinton _ a lawyer whose practice is unknown in the Southern
District of Texas, but who shares the same name as the president of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whittredge is accused of using false credentials to gain access
to Mission Control at Marshall Space Center in Alabama. He
allegedly told authorities that he was scheduled to fly on a
shuttle mission and was interested in payload operations.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Whittredge toured the space center Nov. 21-22,
1997, and had access to Mission Control. Whittredge also sat at the
console of NASA Mission Control (NASA's most secure area) at
Marshall Space Flight Center during a shuttle mission, court
documents indicate.
</P>
<P>
   On March 16, 1998, Whittredge allegedly gained access to
technical data on a space shuttle thrust propulsion system that is
not available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   And in May, Whittredge allegedly lied his way into a meeting
with senior pilots and the executive officer of the Kingsville
Naval Air Station in Texas. He was ultimately given training on a
T-45 Aircraft Flight Simulator, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Besides claiming to be an astronaut, prosecutors said Whittredge
has claimed to be a Medal of Honor recipient and a CIA official,
according to the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   But Whittredge was never an astronaut, never received the Medal
of Honor and never worked for the CIA, said prosecutor Mike
Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   Schultz has asked Botley to hold Whittredge in the Harris County
Jail until he can be sent to the federal medical center for the
U.S. Bureau of Prisons in Fort Worth for evaluation by government
psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
   Because such a move would result in extended incarceration for
Whittredge, Botley ordered a probable cause and detention hearing
for Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
