<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Got Soup?   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Ever notice those little milk cartons sitting next to the spinach
fettuccine in the cold-food section of the supermarket?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever wonder why milk cartons were sitting next to the spinach
fettuccine in the cold-food section of the supermarket?
</P>
<P>
   If so, you can understand the challenge faced by Glencoe Foods
Inc., a company with British roots that plans a major U.S. roll-out
of fresh-prepared soups sold in pint-sized, white cartons.
</P>
<P>
   With flavors like wild mushroom, carrot-coriander and Thai green
curry, the soups, sold under the New Covent Garden label, probably
will never match mass-appeal brands such as Campbell's.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have the potential for widespread acceptance among
people who tend to buy premium food, said food industry
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Because New Covent Garden soups are prepared with techniques
similar to those used by home cooks, their flavors and textures
stand out from the dried ramen packs and mushy, highly processed
canned products that dominate supermarket shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The cartons are microwaveable, an appealing feature in this
convenience-crazed society. And at $2.99 to $3.69 per pint, they
make an affordable light meal or appetizer for one or two people.
</P>
<P>
   If the company can replicate the 7 percent market share of its
United Kingdom affiliate, New Covent Garden Soups Co. Ltd., it
would ring up $260 million a year in the United States, where
consumers spend $3.7 billion annually on packaged soups.
</P>
<P>
   But the cartons' close resemblance to the stuff Americans pour
over their Cheerios every morning is just one hurdle Glencoe must
overcome to make a dent in the world's largest consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are creatures of habit, and Americans are not used
to buying soup in cardboard cartons. Nor are they accustomed to
looking in the refrigerator section for soup, so simply finding the
product and recognizing it will be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   New Covent Garden, an unknown name among U.S. consumers, is
fighting such mega-brands as Campbell's and Progresso _ not to
mention pasta, carry-out sandwiches and other foods people look for
in light meals.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the soup's fat and sodium contents, which don't
phase Brits, are unacceptably high for many health-conscious U.S.
eaters. And some of the popular British flavors, such as fresh
haddock, and Brussels sprouts with chestnuts, are not likely to sit
well with Americans. (In fact, the company isn't even considering
bringing those flavors here).
</P>
<P>
   Glencoe, a licensee of its United Kingdom affiliate, has spent
three years testing and honing its products in this country and
outfitting a $5 million processing plant in Modesto.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1995, the company has been flying the soup in from the
United Kingdom to about 45 Bay Area supermarkets for consumer
testing. It is planning a roll-out in August to the rest of
Northern California as well as Portland, Seattle, Denver and Salt
Lake City, and hopes to sign up some major supermarket chains as
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Glencoe, which is funded by two private investors and
a venture capital firm, intends to sell soup throughout the United
States. Alastair Dorward, president of the company, said about $8
million has been invested to date.
</P>
<P>
   The soups that will roll out of Modesto in August will have a
very different look than those now being imported from the United
Kingdom, which were designed to stand in tasteful contrast to the
``gaudy and photographic'' packaging of United Kingdom products,
said Dorward.
</P>
<P>
   The new cartons, designed by the San Francisco firm Deutsch
Design, have a colorful, Mediterranean look. Fresh-looking
vegetables are artfully painted, and the word ``soup'' is written
in eye-catching large script.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the packaging to scream `soup,''' said Steve
Goldman, general manager of Deutsch Design.
</P>
<P>
   Glencoe is also reformulating its recipes for the American
palette. This summer it will introduce two New World flavors, spicy
corn chowder and black bean-green chile. And the U.S.-made soups
will have lower salt and fat contents than their British
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Glencoe can't afford to advertise, so it relies on in-store
sampling and word of mouth to raise awareness for its products,
said Dorward.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its modest marketing efforts, sales have been growing 50
percent annually in local test stores, which include Whole Foods,
Cala Foods, Mollie Stone's and Andronico's, he said. Seven New
Covent Garden soup flavors rank among the top 15 packaged soups in
stores where they are sold, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The soups may get some lift from a new popularity of fresh soup
in the United States, a trend that so far has manifested itself
more in new soup-oriented restaurants than in supermarket products,
said Marcia Schurer, president of Culinary Connections, a food
consulting firm in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Schurer believes there is enough pent-up demand for quality
soups to virtually ensure Glenco's success in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have always had a taste for fresh, home-made tasting
soup and the problem has always been the supply,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mattson, a processed-food consultant and developer, also
expects New Covent Garden soups to do well here.
</P>
<P>
   The soup tastes good because it is cooked at relatively low
temperatures _ about 160 degrees Fahrenheit, or about the same as
soup made in a home kitchen or restaurant, said Mattson, chairman
of Mattson &AMP; Co. in Foster City.
</P>
<P>
   After cooking, the New Covent Garden soups are quickly cooled,
packaged and sealed in a sterile environment so they last on
supermarket shelves for two to three weeks, said Mattson.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's soup, by contrast, is cooked under pressure, in the
can, at about 245 degrees Fahrenheit, said Mattson. With heating
and cooling times, ``it might be above boiling for half an hour,
which is why if you close your eyes and eat a carrot, you might
think you're eating a potato,'' he said. ``It's mush.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell Soup Co., based in Camden, N.J., did not respond to
requests for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
