<SLUG> BC-NY-HOTEL-BOOM-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANHATTAN HOTEL RATES AND DEMAND GO SKY HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also sent with `t' and `a' codes) 
(bl) 
 By NICK RAVO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Looking for a hotel room in Manhattan? You have
plenty of options.
</P>
<P>
   You could book weeks in advance and pay $300 or so a night for a
room at a modern midtown high-rise like the Crowne Plaza. If you're
willing to pay a bit more _ say, $500 a night on average _ you
could probably get something with less of a hassle at the Four
Seasons or the Pierre. Or you could do what a growing number of
visitors are forced to do: stay in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel market in Manhattan, the most expensive in the nation
and fresh off a record year in 1997, continued to tighten in thia
year's first quarter, compared with the first three months of last
year, with the average cost of a night's stay creeping closer to
$200.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the highest first-quarter average daily rate in
Manhattan's history,'' said Dexter Wood, a hotel consultant with
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand.
</P>
<P>
   The market has become so expensive that in the last 18 months,
five hotels _ the Lowell, the St. Regis and the Carlyle, as well as
the Pierre and the Four Seasons _ began charging an average rate of
$500, with some suites running into four figures. No other city in
the nation has even a single hotel with an average rate so high,
industry experts said.
</P>
<P>
   And even as prices rise, it is still difficult to find a room in
New York unless it is booked far in advance. That fact has forced
some visitors to stay in New Jersey or not come to the city at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot find a decent hotel room anywhere on Manhattan, it
seems, for less than a fortune,'' said Alan Bennett of Sydney,
Australia, who was planning to come to the city in August. ``We
have searched database after database and rung hotel chains'
reservations centers, all to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has got to the stage where we are about to scrap our plans
to go to New York and instead split our four or five days there
between an extra day or two in Washington and Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who do find a room are often in for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred bucks!'' said Susan Jeans of Bayport, Minn., who
booked her room at the Crowne Plaza in mid-Manhattan two weeks in
advance. ``We were expecting like $200.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price of a room in Manhattan rose to $189.70 for the
first quarter of the year, according to preliminary figures from
the Coopers &AMP; Lybrand Lodging Research Network. That is a 13.9
percent leap over the $166.58 average room price for the first
quarter of 1997 and a smaller jump over the $187.91 rate for all of
1997. By the end of the year, Coopers &AMP; Lybrand expects average
room rates to rise an additional 10 to 12 percent, surpassing $200,
a figure reached briefly for the first time last fall and
Christmas, the busiest months of the year for many New York hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Occupancy rates are nearing records, too. For the first three
months of the year, which are among the slowest for the industry in
New York, hotels were 80.5 percent filled, according to Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand. That's an increase of 5.4 percent over the first quarter
of 1997, and only slightly down from 82 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1997, which was the highest since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand is unprecedented here,'' said Steven Pipes, general
manager of Le Parker Meridien, a hotel in mid-Manhattan. ``People
wanting a room in the fall, if they don't starting making
reservations now, in the early summertime, they will be missing
out.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. Fox, a senior vice president with PKF Consulting, a
hotel and real estate consulting company in Manhattan, said that
business was good for many reasons: the strong local and national
economies; a continuing shortage of rooms; the city's improved
image, and a cheap dollar in many parts of the world, which makes
it affordable for foreign tourists to come to the city and
expensive for Americans to travel abroad. ``The market has been on
a steady upward climb since 1992,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's decision in 1994 to cut its hotel tax to 15 percent
from 21 percent, along with the state's elimination of its 5
percent hotel tax, may have had some impact as well. ``When taxes
are cut, demand usually rises,'' said Adam Brachet, a spokesman for
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand. ``It's not the whole potato, but it's part of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Zawadzk from Bayport, Minn., was hoping to stay at the
Millennium in mid-Manhattan this month, where a conference he was
attending was being held. He could not get a room, though. Instead,
he, like Ms. Jeans, a colleague, stayed at the Crowne Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do lot more planning next time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bjorn Hanson, chairman of Coopers &AMP; Lybrand's hotel and casino
division, said, ``It's a hotelier's dream, rates rising at three to
four times inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   The increased business has led not only to the planned
construction in Manhattan of more than 31 hotels, with more than
11,593 rooms, but also to a slight increase in hotel jobs.
According to the state's Labor Department, hotel employment in New
York City rose by 700 jobs, to 36,200, in April from a year
earlier.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is the fastest growth spurt I've ever experienced in the
hotel industry,'' said Kevin Murphy, regional manager for New
Boston Select Staffing, which provides hotels with personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are filling job requests including housekeeping-cooks-wait
staff, and it's not just body-pushing anymore. Hotel skills are in
great demand. The hotel business is searching for skilled labor,
similar to the information technology industry. With the right
experience, you can write your own ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanson also said that hotels were curtailing discounts and
weekend packages because the markets were so strong. ``Everything
is priced premium,'' he said. ``And we are also finding that guests
are spending more money in the hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's hotel space squeeze has sent many corporate travel
managers scrambling. J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. now often books people into
the relatively spartan Club Quarters hotel in downtown Manhattan,
which lacks amenities like in-room faxes and room service.
</P>
<P>
   And with the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau projecting
32.5 million out-of-towners coming to the city this year, including
5.9 million from abroad, many business travelers and tourists may
find that accommodations in New Jersey are their only affordable or
available alternative. But even there, the overflow from Manhattan
is making it difficult to find a room.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Eismeier, the treasurer of Colgate University, could
not get a room two weeks ago. ``We tried a dozen or more hotels,
plus a AAA travel agent, plus the Williams Club,'' she said.
``Friends checked the Cornell Club and the Yale Club _ no soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, the agent suggested the Marriott at Newark Airport. ``It
was just fine. It made me want to see if any of our real estate
investment managers were investing in hotel development in New York
City. Seems like the city needs that.''
</P>
<P>
   The visitors bureau advises people trying to find a room to call
the Peak Season Hotel Hot Line at (800) 846-7666, which makes
reservations for more than 80 hotels in various price ranges and
can give availability information. A person really stuck, the
bureau says, should try contacting hotels after 6 p.m. to check on
canceled reservations the hotels have canceled that have not been
guaranteed with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the new hotels going up, it is probable, according
to Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, that only 4,000 to 5,000 of the approximately
12,000 rooms that are planned will be built; there are now about
54,600 rooms in Manhattan and 6,000 in the rest of the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
