<SLUG> BC-RACE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Black Leaders Ask For Clamp On Hiring Foreigners  
   
 By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
A coalition of black leaders asked the U.S. Department of Labor
yesterday to consider prohibiting Silicon Valley companies that
fail to hire enough blacks and Latinos from bringing in temporary
foreign workers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The novel idea was part of a package of suggestions presented by
the newly formed Coalition for Fair Employment in the Silicon
Valley during a meeting with Department of Labor officials. The
coalition met with the San Jose regional office that is responsible
for enforcing affirmative action among government contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The &UR;  &LR; meeting was sparked by a Chronicle investigation last month
that showed blacks and Latinos are significantly underrepresented
in Silicon Valley's leading firms, as compared with the Bay Area
workforce overall.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also found that many of the top technology
firms had been cited by the Department of Labor for failing to
actively recruit blacks and Latinos _ but most were not fined or
penalized in any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeared to us (from The Chronicle articles) that the Labor
Department wasn't aggressively dealing with the issue,'' said Henry
Hutchins, president of the Bay Area Black MBAs and a member of the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department officials worked to dispel that notion during a
three-hour meeting with the coalition yesterday but made no
promises about future actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an exploratory meeting, and we listened very
carefully,'' said Woody Gilliland, deputy regional director of the
Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliland said his office does not have the authority to choose
which companies receive work permits for overseas workers, but that
he would refer the coalition to an appropriate contact in the
federal government. His office does not have the power to fine
contractors unless they owe back pay to an employee who was
unfairly denied a job.
</P>
<P>
   Denying work vias to Silicon Valley companies would be a strong
blow because many firms rely on foreign workers to fill skilled
positions that they claim cannot be filled with U.S. workers. Even
with foreign workers, industry leaders estimate that there are
hundreds of thousands of unfilled technology jobs nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But the black leaders in this group said they told the
Department of Labor about many instances when qualified black
candidates had been overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is, if you are not hiring blacks and Latinos locally,
then how can you go outside the country to hire workers?'' said
Hutchins of the Black MBAs.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition member George Whaley, a San Jose State University
professor, said he plans to crunch some numbers showing the
availability of qualified blacks and Latinos for high-tech jobs.
The coalition hopes to provide these numbers to the Department of
Labor to use as ammunition for turning down work permits requested
by companies that have lagged in minority hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to point out that there are (minority) people out
there who can do these jobs,'' said San Francisco resident John
Templeton, the leader of the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition was formed by the Bay Area Black MBAs, Bay Area
Black Data Processing Associates and the Peninsula Area Black
Personnel Administrators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
