<HEADER>
A7363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT &LR;      06-12 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: ENDGAME IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 13:
</P>
<P>
   The pre-election stupor that has afflicted New York's state
Legislature in recent months now means that Albany has only a few
days left to wrestle with some of the most crucial issues on this
year's agenda. Here is an abbreviated list of important matters
that need immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC SCHOOL AID: Gov. George Pataki's recent budget vetoes
spell real trouble for New York City's public schools. He
eliminated $202 million to repair deterioriating schoolrooms. He
also cut funds that would help the city compete for 30,000 new
teachers over the next four years _ just when the state is
tightening standards, launching a pre-kindergarten program and
ordering cuts in class size. The extra money for teachers is
apparently being held hostage to Pataki's charter school proposal,
a program that would benefit only a small percentage of the state's
students. The Legislature should ignore the governor's agenda and
restore these cuts.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Pataki could muster a timely show of support for
the efforts by New York City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew to end
tenure for school principals. Tenure provides job protection for
mediocrities who cannot currently be held accountable for the
failure of their students.
</P>
<P>
   THE HUDSON RIVER PARK: After months of sparring, Pataki and New
Y(CT)ork City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are now in agreement on most
of the troublesome issues surrounding the creation of a riverside
park on Manhattan's West Side. Both have pledged $100 million
toward the project, which would replace the rotting piers and
industrial detritus between 59th Street and the Battery with an
inviting mix of open space and modest commercial development. The
dream will move even closer to reality if the Legislature approves
a bill governing the design, management and financing of the park.
The bill's provisions dealing with open space protection and the
amount of allowable development may require tightening. But this
can be done in less than a day if Pataki and Sheldon Silver, the
Democratic leader of the state Assembly, apply themselves to the
task. Future generations of New Yorkers will be greatly in their
debt if they do so.
</P>
<P>
   COURT REFORM: Chief Judge Judith Kaye's user-friendly plan to
streamline New York's convoluted court system deserves legislative
agreement this session. Unfortunately, Silver has proposed a
narrower alternative that would leave much of the system intact and
would link court restructuring to permanent funding for legal
services _ a non-starter in the Republican Senate. The underfunding
of legal services is a pressing concern, but it should not be used
as political cover to stop court reform.
</P>
<P>
   THE INSURANCE BOONDOGGLE: Some mutual insurance companies _
companies owned by their policyholders but in reality run by
self-perpetuating boards of directors _ have persuaded Pataki to
back a bill that serves management alone. In simplest terms, the
bill would allow companies to sell stock without compensating the
policyholders. It would also shield the companies from takeover
threats, making it hard for shareholders to change management. The
Assembly should stop this self-serving legislation in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   There are other unresolved issues. This could be the year, for
example, when Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno finally allows
the Senate to vote on a long-overdue change in the state's civil
rights laws that would bar discrimination on the basis of sexual
orientation. Should common sense prevail, the Assembly's strong
measure aimed at keeping guns out of the hands of children by
requiring safe storage of weapons may carry the day against an
insulting Senate version that can only please the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   As a final gesture, Albany could astonish its critics by
revamping a campaign financing system that imposes no limits on
``soft-money'' donations to party slush funds and tolerates
obscenely high donations to individual candidates. That, of course,
may be asking too much. But there is enough time left for the
Legislature to redeem what has been an oddly disoriented and
passive year. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
