<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE RETURN MARKS END FOR MIR MISSIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Hang out the vacancy sign.
</P>
<P>
   An unprecedented 812 days of continuous U.S. presence in space
drew to a close Friday as the shuttle Discovery returned to Earth
carrying marathon astronaut Andy Thomas, the final American
assigned to live and work aboard Russia's Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's return after a 10-day round trip to Mir wrapped up a
three-year series of docking missions to the Russian orbital
outpost. The operation enabled seven Americans to make extended
stays on the Russian station to help prepare for the challenge of
assembling a new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery touched down at NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida
at 1 p.m. CDT, with commander Charles Precourt and pilot Dominic
Gorie at the controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greetings,'' chirped Thomas, 46, minutes after Discovery
rolled to a stop. ``I want to thank you all for bringing me home
and giving me a great ride,'' he radioed colleagues in mission
control in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smiling, giving a thumbs-up,'' said astronaut Franklin
Chang-Diaz, who was strapped in next to Thomas during the descent.
``He was in real good spirits.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Thomas, who logged 141 days aloft, received a thorough medical
exam immediately after landing. Like his U.S. predecessors on Mir,
he will embark on an intensive 45-day rehabilitation program
designed to rebuild the skeletal and muscle strength lost during
his long exposure to weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before his return to Earth, Thomas told NASA he wanted a
meal of lasagna and Oreo Cookie ice cream when he landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really looking forward to that first meal,'' he joked
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, Precourt, Gorie, Chang-Diaz and crewmates Janet Kavand,
Wendy Lawrence and Valery Ryumin are scheduled to return to Houston
on Saturday night. NASA planned a brief public welcoming ceremony
at Ellington Field.
</P>
<P>
   With Discovery's landing, the Russians regained the distinction
of being Earth's sole permanent occupants of space. Cosmonauts
Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin will remain aboard Mir until
August.
</P>
<P>
   America's 812-day run began March 22, 1996, with the shuttle
Atlantis bringing Shannon Lucid to Mir. Her 188 days in space, the
current U.S. record, initiated the relay that was continued by
astronauts John Blaha, Jerry Linenger, Mike Foale, David Wolf and
finally Thomas. Mir's first U.S. visitor, astronaut Norman Thagard,
logged 115 days in the spring and summer of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As NASA's Mir collaboration began three years ago, it appeared
that the end of that program would overlap the initial staffing of
the new station. At the time, construction of the new station was
to have begun in late 1997, with a three-man crew led by astronaut
Bill Shepherd slated to arrive in May of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But chronic funding problems in Russia have delayed the new
station's first habitable component, the Russian-furnished service
module. Plans to start construction have been postponed until
November.
</P>
<P>
   With the service module now essentially constructed and its
mission to Mir drawn to a successful close on Friday, NASA was
eager to look on the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   Agency administrator Dan Goldin, one of the principle architects
of the U.S.-Russian collaboration, greeted Thomas in Florida with
flowers. Normally a stern figure, Goldin embraced Frank Culbertson,
the astronaut who successfully steered the program through a series
of crises last year as Mir was rocked by fire, a near-disastrous
collision and failing life support systems.
</P>
<P>
   In response, support in Congress eroded. The White House offered
little public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started out, we didn't know each other,'' said Goldin.
``Now, we know the Russians, and we know with certainty we're going
to open up the universe to benefit life on this planet. This is not
the end, it's just the start of a new phase.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
