<HEADLINE>
AZTEC TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By BARBARA BELEJACK 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ It was a very good year, especially for the Grupo
Elektra employees, their spouses and business partners who gathered
at the MGM Hotel in Las Vegas for the annual company convention.
 &HT;    Between lectures on neuro-linguistics and trips to the slot
machines, they gawked at TV Azteca actress Lucia Mendez, listened
to TV Aztec talk show host Paty Chapoy, and Armando Manzanero, the
singer composer of the theme song to a TV Azteca telenovela. And
above all, they listened to the star of the show, the man with the
trademark wire-rim glasses, perfectly trimmed, graying beard, and
headset mike.
 &HT;    Flanked by Las Vegas chorus girls and an oversized yellow smiley
button (the Elektra logo), and acting every bit the motivational
guru, Ricardo Salinas Pliego told them what they already knew: 1997
was a very good year; things were going to get even better. At
Grupo Elektra si se puede!
 &HT;    At 42, the president and CEO of Grupo Elektra (Mexico's largest
retail chain), and TV Azteca, has been described as an upstart
maverick, a brilliant visionary, just plain arrogant and more than
a bit cynical.
 &HT;    What else can you say about a billionaire who figured out how to
sell things to people with minimal purchasing power? Who described
a US$29 million loan as ``irrelevant''? Who is currently enmeshed
in a nasty business divorce, a closely watched legal battle with
U.S. TV giant NBC? You could say he is a man who knows how to turn
a company around and make money. Threeyeas ago, who would have
believed that TV Azteca would take over one-third of the television
market in Mexico, asks Leonardo Simpser, an analyst with Deutsche
Morgan Grenfell in Mexico City. With his combination of retail
stores, distribution network, credit and technology, Salinas could
introduce almost any new business and make it his. He could be the
next Carlos Slim, says Simpser; he could be ``The Big Kahuna.''
 &HT;    Even his staunchest critics grudgingly admit that Salinas has
managed to dramatically turn around both Elektra and TV Azteca, the
former state-run television network he bought five years ago. Now
he's turned his sights toward the rest of Latin America, as well as
to the lucrative Spanish-language market in the United States.
 &HT;    Salinas did not grant an interview for this article despite
several requests.
 &HT;    ``When we talk about our group of companies, we talk about
outgrowing Mexico,'' he told a group of analysts, fund managers and
potential investors last February at the Four Seasons in New York's
World Trade Center. ``That's not because we think we've gotten too
big for Mexico, but because our group's sales and cash flow have
tripled the growth of the Mexican economy.'' As performances, go,
Salinas's New York presentation, was only a slightly more subdued
version of his message in Las Vegas.
 &HT;    Hoopla and hype aside, these are the facts: Last year, total net
revenue of Elektra, TV Azteca, and a paging service called Biper
reached $1.3 billion. Net income totalled more than $220 million.
TV Azteca had the number one-ranked nightly news program in Mexico
and the number one telenovela (soap opera).
 &HT;    The network beat Mexican media giant Televisa at its own game
with Mirada de Mujer, featuring a 50-year-old woman who turns the
tables on her unfaithful husband and finds happiness with a much
younger man.
 &HT;    With just two channels compared with Televisa's four, TV Azteca
managed to capture 35 percent of the television audienceand nearly
as much of the advertising market. By the end of the year the
network was producing 85 percent of its prime time programming, up
from 36 percent in December 1995. Azteca officials insist that
they'll reach 100 percent in-house prime time production this year
and produce 10 novelas. Meanwhile, Salinas has opened stores in
Chile, Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras and the Dominican Republic.
 &HT;    As he travels south, Salinas pushes the total package-Elektra,
TV Azteca and Biper. So far, he has managed to buy two small
networks in Chile and El Salvador and a UHF channel in Guatemala, a
relatively modest expense compared with the production costs of
those 10 telenovelas.
 &HT;    In 1997, TV Azteca entered the world financial markets, raising
US$425 million in bonds and $605 million in its August IPO, the
largest public offering of a Mexican company since the December
1994 peso devaluation. Along with his international expansion,
Salinas has announced plans to create a holding company that would
combine TV Azteca with Elektra and its subsidiaries, the clothing
chain Hecali, Biper and credit and money-wire services. At the
outset, Salinas will hold about 40 percent of the shares, but
analysts predict he will soon buy out his relatives, just as he
bought out his Azteca partners, Alberto and Moises Saba Raffoul,
last year.
 &HT;    In addition, Salinas bid almost $300 million in a government
auction of radio-frequency licenses. He's betting that a ``fixed
wireless,'' low-cost phone service will be a sure winner in a
country with a teledensity of less than 10 percent. Finally, in
contrast to rival Televisa, pay network Multivision and their
global partners, Salinas is making a high-stakes bet on digital
television rather than DTH.
 &HT;    Just five years ago, when Salinas bought TV Azteca, ``people saw
him as a refrigerator or microwave salesman,'' says CFO Adrian
Steckel, who left an investment banking career at Dillon Reed to
join Azteca in 1994. Finance writers and analysts weren't paying
attention to a family of regiomontanos (men from business city
Monterrey in Northern Mexico) they considered second- or
third-tier, compared with the better known powers behind Mexican
companies such as Alfa, Visa and Vitro. (Salinas was born in Mexico
City in October 1955, but is usually referred to as a
regiomontano.)
 &HT;    What they weren't following was the criss-cross of Monterrey
business and family relationships, which can be as complicated as
those in a Russian novel-or Mexican telenovela.
 &HT;    His family got its start in business when Benjamin Salinas
teamed up with his brother-in-law Joel Rocha in 1907 to found what
would eventually become the department store chain of Salinas y
Rocha. In the 1950s, Benjamin's only son, Hugo, founded a company
called Elektra that manufactured televisions and radios. When the
Rochas ousted him from the department stores, he retaliated by
turning Elektra into a rival retail business. In 1981, Hugo's
grandson joined Elektra after graduating from the Monterrey Tec and
Tulane, and brief stints at Arthur Anderson and Grupo Visa. Ricardo
Salinas Pliego arrived just in time for the debt crisis that
devastated Elektra. He responded with the same formula he would
apply at TV Azteca: Cut costs and revamp technology. He also
changed the company's customer and merchandise base. Instead of
trying to be an all-purpose department store catering to the middle
class, it began to focus on low-income customers, people with
negligible purchasing power, who were able to buy basic household
appliances and furniture on extended - and hefty -credit plans.
 &HT;    In 1991, Salinas was named president and CEO of Elektra, which
went public two years later.
 &HT;    ``[Ricardo] is a more polished version of my brother, Hugo,''
says Ricardo's great-aunt Irma Salinas Rocha, a keen observer of
the social and business scene in Monterrey.
 &HT;    ``Hugo was a big risk taker,'' Salinas says of her only brother.
 &HT;    ``And so is Ricardo; he's building an empire ... I wouldn't want
to have to compete with him.''
 &HT;    Although he was considered a lightweight during the 1993
privatization process, his original partner was not. Francisco
Aguirre Gomez came from a family that owned and operated a
profitable group of radio stations. They also had experience with
the Azcarraga family and Televisa. After nearly 20 years of
petitioning, they were finally granted a television broadcast
concession in 1968, only to have President Luis Echeverria
orchestrate its nationalization several years later. With the 1993
sale, Francisco Aguirre had a chance at vindication, by bidding on
a media package that included the same television station his
family had lost. But just weeks before the bid was to be awarded,
he parted ways with Salinas Pliego for reasons that were never
explained except for cryptic references to ``differences in
temperament.'' At the last minute, Salinas replaced Francisco
Aguirre with two brothers, Alberto and Moises Saba Raffoul, whose
fortune derived from investments in the textile and petrochemical
industries.
 &HT;    When the bids were opened, their $640 million bid was 30 percent
higher than the next-highest bid. The man whose family had started
off manufacturing and later selling television sets was on his way
to becoming a media mogul.
 &HT;    Salinas told the newsmagazine Proceso that if Mexican viewers
were looking for an alternative to the pro-government stance of
Televisa, they would have to wait a little bit longer.
 &HT;    ``I didn't buy these channels to criticize the government,'' he
said. ``Besides, Mexico is not ready for democracy * Television is
mainly for entertainment and for women who stay at home.'' But
Salinas had big ideas and talked about negotiations with Brazil's
TV Globo, NBC, and with Silvio Berlusconi of Italy. He invested in
technology and extended the penetration of his two channels, 7 and
13, throughout Mexico. He hired a youthful, folksy anchor, Javier
Alatorre, for the nightly news program Hechos-another generation
and another style, compared with Jacobo Zabludovsky, the longtime
anchor of Televisa's 24 Horas. He hired the head of the
Encyclopedia Britannica, Sergio Sarmiento, also known for his
conservative economic commentary in print and radio journalism, to
direct Azteca's news division, and hired away other young
``talent'' in finance and accounting. (Steckel is 31) Azteca had
little to offer in the way of original programming, but managed to
attract attention by importing shows like The Simpsons and The
Wonder Years, considered unique at the time in Mexico. In 1994,
Azteca signed a highly publicized deal with NBC, described
glowingly by executives in Rockefeller Center as the network's
first post-NAFTA deal, ``a growth, growth, growth story.'' NBC
bought an option to purchase 10 percent of TV Azteca, and also
promised to provide technical advice. That summer, Mexican soccer
fans had an alternative to Televisa coverage of the World Cup, and
an estimated 40 percent of them tuned in to TV Azteca.
 &HT;    Elektra weathered the 1995 economic crisis with a boost from its
Western Union money transfer service that turned dollars earned by
Mexican workers in the United States into pesos for their relatives
at home-at a hefty exchange rate differential. TV Azteca continued
to experience a modest growth in the ratings, until it hit on a
seemingly unbeatable combination: sex and violence-with an emphasis
on the violence-and political corruption.
 &HT;    And Salinas made a shrewd alliance with Argos Productions, a
company founded by a team of journalists, including Epigmenio
Ibarra, who reported the Central American wars, produced the first
lengthy televised interview with Subcomandante Marcos in January
1994, and whose independent production company was all over Chiapas
that summer directing videos of the Zapatistas.
 &HT;    Their first project, Nada Personal, changed the telenovela
formula. Instead of the traditional
poor-girl-falls-in-love-with-rich-man-and-lives-happily-ever-after,
story, Nada Personal started off with an unusual twist: Rich girl
meets handsome TV reporter when her father, the Attorney General,
and sister are murdered in a high-level narcopolitical conspiracy.
The fact that life is full of paradoxes and contradictions, lights
and shadows, may have been nothing new in Brazil and Colombia,
where novela writers have been borrowing from the seamier side of
reality for years, but in Mexico it was news. Nada Personal was an
instant hit, particularly since the writers and producers seemed to
be scrambling to include each morning's headlines in the evening's
show. Mexico's political life had turned into one giant telenovela,
in which the characters from one story kept getting mixed up in
another.
 &HT;    Fact and fiction really started to tumble together in July of
1996 , when The Miami Herald published a story linking Ricardo
Salinas to Raul (no relation) Salinas. Salinas Pliego first denied
that he had accepted money from the jailed brother of former
president, then later admitted that he had accepted a $29 million
loan, channeled through Panama and the Cayman Islands, that was
used to help pay for TV Azteca.
 &HT;    Salinas later explained the loan as ``irrelevant,'' and one that
he could hardly have questioned: ``If Raul Salinas] appeared and
said, 'I have this money and I want you to invest it for me, well,
very few people were going to say no to him,'' he told Proceso in
an interview.
 &HT;    Both networks engaged in a war of mutual allegations; TV Azteca
disclosed that Zabludovsky's son Abraham, a Televisa anchor, had
engaged in business dealings with Raul Salinas. Eventually, the
mutual accusations came to an end. But Ricardo Salinas remained on
the offensive. He has the unique distinction of having filed more
libel suits than anyone else in Mexico. According to the annual
report of the New York-based Committee to Protect Journalists, he
``used lawsuits to squelch reporting linking him to a
money-laundering scheme.'' While a congressional investigation into
the privatization of TV Azteca was still pending, Salinas took out
newspaper advertisements announcing that the privatization of TV
Azteca was the most successful in Mexican history.
 &HT;    At a business forum sponsored by the Mexico City newspaper El
Economista, he gave a particularly upbeat performance, telling the
audience that the economic crisis was a matter of ``attitude.'' It
was up to each and every Mexican to look into his soul and
determine what he had done to cause the crisis. Elektra and TV
Azteca had succeeded because, unlike others, he didn't waste his
time brooding that ``Everything went down the tubes because of
Carlos Salinas.'' Less than a month later, congress concluded that
Salinas had won the 1993 bid because he made the best offer, and
the case was closed.
 &HT;    ``I'm not really sure that [Ricardo Salinas] could be
button-holed as the guy who had the most to gain from Raul
Salinas,'' says Robert Hulme, an analyst with Interacciones Casa de
Bolsa in New York. ``Raul ran with a bunch of Mexican businessmen.
I don't think investors perceive political intrigue as something
that comes to mind when they talk about Azteca ... it's not
something that investors are focusing on.'' ``It's a fact that
nobody talks about,'' explains another analyst, who asked not to be
named. ``The bottom line is he is a very good businessman, he is
defending shareholders' interest. That's really all you care
about.''
 &HT;    While analysts disagree about where Ricardo Salinas, TV Azteca
and Elektra are going next, they tend to agree about one thing.
Part of his success last year was due to the turmoil and change at
Televisa.
 &HT;    In April 1997, Televisa magnate Emilio Azcarraga Milmo died of
cancer, less than two months after stepping down and leaving the
world's largest Spanish-language media conglomerate in the hands of
his son, Emilio Azcarraga Jean, then 29. Azcarraga Jean was
considered a privileged ``junior'' and the company was plagued with
financial problems and personal squabbles that led to the defection
of two veteran executives who joined TV Azteca. Among them:
Guillermo Canedo White, Televisa's widely respected former CFO. But
Azcarraga Jean began to follow through with an ambitious
cost-cutting program and analysts and investors began to take
notice.
 &HT;    Despite the success of Mirada de Mujer, the telenovela that
broke even more taboos and presented a new image of contemporary
Mexican women, Televisa produced far more telenovelas than TV
Azteca. After veteran news anchor Jacobo Zabladovsky stepped down
in January and was replaced with Guillermo Ortega, Televisa's
nightly news program drew mixed reviews. But soon it was beating
Hechos in the ratings, and TV Azteca was forced to change the
timing of the news program, moving it up a half hour.
 &HT;    TV Azteca has a considerable dollar debt, drawing skepticism
from analysts such as Brian Barish with Cambiar Investments in
Denver. Barish isn't convinced by the the ``synergy'' message that
Salinas is pushing throughout the hemisphere.
 &HT;    ``It's been a higher-risk, higher-reward proposition,'' he says
of Azteca stock. ``They've gone a decent job operationally, but so
far, the market hasn't rewarded it one way or the other.'' And
while Salinas may say that he's outgrown Mexico, his companies very
much depend on what happens in the Mexican economy and market. If
concerns over a shrinking peso, falling oil prices and a
less-spectacular growth rate than originally predicted continue,
Azteca may feel the crunch. Unlike last year, broadcast networks
can't count on lavish spending for a federal electoral campaign or
a campaign to promote Afores, the privatized pension system that
debuted in 1997.
 &HT;    Then there's also the matter of the messy ``divorce'' with NBC
that is still clouding the picture.
 &HT;    NBCdid not return several phone calls asking for a comment for
this article, but according to Mexican media reports, NBC claims
that TV Azteca failed to disclose its intentions to go public and
therefore it was deprived of adequate knowledge of whether to
exercise its 10 percent option on time.
 &HT;    TV Azteca says that NBC never came through with the technical
and programming advice it had promised. NBC ``wasn't paying
attention,'' Steckel insists. ``They didn't read the contract ...
they ought to know how much the company is worth better than
anyone.'' Steckel says the Mexican network had no plans to carry
out an IPO when it did, but was forced to do so once the Sabas
decided to exercise their options and cash out their shares.
 &HT;    Currently before international arbitration, the case may
eventually depend on something as esoteric as the colors of the TV
Azteca-and NBC-logos.''That's not the NBC peacock,'' Steckel says
of his company's logo. ``That's an eagle, a soaring Mexican
eagle.'' TV Azteca hasn't set aside reserves for a potential
adverse ruling, claiming that the worst-case scenario may cost the
company $12 million and 2 percent of equity.
 &HT;    Now 77 and concerned primarily with the charitable foundation
named after her father, Irma Salinas observes the disputes about
peacocks and eagles, southern campaigns and northern divisions from
the distance in Monterrey. There were three things her brother Hugo
said he wanted to accomplish before he died, she says. And his
grandson has already accomplished two of them. And the third? Irma
Salinas can't remember. Or maybe she's just not saying.
 &HT;     
