<HEADER>
A7397 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARN-MACARTHUR-PROFIL     06-12 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARN-MACARTHUR-PROFILES-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 MACARTHUR FELLOWS ARE ADDING VALUE TO THE WORLD OF MONEY  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 14)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Calif., Mass.)  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year since 1981, it has been a cross between a Pulitzer
and a lottery: the fellowship program of the John D. and Catherine
T. MacArthur Foundation, which awards sizable, no-strings-attached
grants to a diverse group of creative thinkers.
</P>
<P>
   To choose recipients, the foundation uses a confidential group
of nominators and a selection committee. Earlier this month, the
foundation announced 29 such fellows _ receiving grants to be paid
out over five years that ranged from $220,000 to $375,000,
depending on the recipient's age.
</P>
<P>
   Among the winners were three whose work involves innovative
perspectives on money matters: a rancher who has taken steps to
preserve his Southwestern way of life; a geographer who studies how
labor and political issues help mold a cultural landscape, and an
economist who aims to apply the ideals of feminism and the left to
calculations of productivity.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth-generation cattle rancher in the Southwestern border
town of Douglas, Ariz., William McDonald is still recovering from
the shock of being recognized by the MacArthur Foundation, let
alone being awarded $285,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Malpai Borderlands Group, an organization he helped found in
1992, was intended, he said, to find common ground among ranchers,
environmentalists, government and just about anyone else with an
interest in Western lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see the handwriting on the wall,'' said McDonald, 46,
who has 350 head of cattle on 21,000 acres in and around Douglas,
in the southeastern part of the state, near both the Mexico border
and the New Mexico state line. ``We are concerned about what our
children would deal with as ranchers. Western ranchers who lease
land were seen as environmental `despoilers.' We're also dealing
with an increasingly harsh regulatory atmosphere. Development was
gobbling up areas where open space was and is.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald and his group of 20 other landowners in Arizona and New
Mexico saw everything they held dear as equally threatened _ from
the region's jaguars, an endangered species, to the area's ranching
community and the open space and grasslands on which it depends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to work through the tough issues that tend to
divide us in the West _ grazing fees, endangered species, growth,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members say that to maintain their way of life,
ranchers must join with environmentalists, onetime adversaries, to
protect the area from development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cattle market has been depressed for some time, and the
cost of land is such that you can't buy a ranch and pay for it with
the cattle, so you have to get another job,'' McDonald said. ``Or
sometimes people get stuck with inheritance taxes they can't afford
or younger generations lose interest in ranching. These things
cause the owners to sell and subdivide their land, and that raises
the value of the surrounding land, and it just feeds on itself from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In one initiative, some members of the group have signed on for
``grassbanking.'' The arrangement permits one rancher's cattle to
graze on a nearby range so that the grasses do not become
overgrazed and the land can regain its natural state. In return,
the rancher signs a ``conservation easement,'' held by the Malpai
board, prohibiting subdivision of his land in perpetuity.
</P>
<P>
   Members have also moved cattle around to maintain vegetation in
certain areas, and avoided ranching in areas where there are
endangered species. And members have helped the Nature Conservancy
buy land to remove it from the reach of development.
</P>
<P>
   In another initiative, the Malpai group is trying to develop a
``unique product that people would like to eat,'' McDonald said.
``There will be some reward to the producer who tries to do it
right _ by using animals raised in a friendly manner, and that
would then lift the economic situation for some of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, such a venture is not essential to the group's
mission. ``Ranchers don't need to be wealthy,'' he said. ``They
just love the way of life. It's enough to make a living with
assurances that they can make one in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   ``Mansfield Park,'' by Jane Austen, contains a passage of
special significance to Don Mitchell, 36, a cultural geographer at
Syracuse University who has just won a $235,000 grant for his work
on how human activity influences the natural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, when Rushworth vows to improve his home at
Southerton Court but wonders who will help, Miss Bertram chimes in:
``Your best friend upon such an occasion would be Repton, I
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Repton was Humphrey Repton, a famous English landscape gardener
who lived at the turn of the 18th century and laid out the gardens
and parks surrounding many great country houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Repton is a fascinating figure who illustrates how human
aesthetic sense and wealth can be part of the process of
constructing the space we live in,'' Mitchell said last week in a
phone conversation from Scotland where he was visiting the parents
of his wife, Susan Millar, who is also a geography professor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's specialty is the influence of political conflict on
the landscape. In ``The Lie of the Land: Migrant Workers and the
Californian Landscape'' (University of Minnesota Press, 1996), he
explored how the endless struggles between big farming interests
and migrant workers shaped the state's agricultural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the land looks today is the result of these debates
and arguments,'' he said in the phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he pointed to the labor camps built for migrant
workers in California's central valley after the strikes of 1933
and 1934 because authorities feared a social explosion if the
farmers failed to improve conditions for their help. ``You only
find decent living and washing facilities where the workers were
militant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As other examples of the way social or political conflicts can
shape a landscape, Mitchell cites Tompkins Square Park in
Manhattan's East Village and the People's Park near the campus of
the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Both parks, he said, are products of long political battles
among various interests, including city and university bureaucrats,
local residents, environmentalists and advocates of the rights of
homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a result has been a space that now serves the needs
of local residents, while in Berkeley the university constructed a
park where it had originally planned to build dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, born in Walnut Creek, Calif., came to Syracuse
University in 1997 from the University of Colorado in Boulder,
where he had taught since gaining a doctorate in geography from
Rutgers University in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had no firm idea yet how he would spend his award:
``I'm not an entrepreneur. I like teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   But he would like to assemble a team of geographers and
historians to write what he calls ``a people's geography of the
United States,'' which would chart the development of Americans'
``social relationship with their landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Folbre has made a career as a feminist and an economist _
and of showing that the two titles are not mutually exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Since earning her doctorate in economics at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst in 1979, Ms. Folbre, 45, has focused much
of her research on nonmarket work, like child-rearing and caring
for elderly relatives. She contends that these unpaid roles, often
filled by women, should be included when determining a nation's
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Folbre, now a professor at the university, defines this and
other ``care work'' _ like teaching and nursing _ as largely
``first-name-basis'' jobs that involve helping others in a close
way. Because such work is not valued economically, ``care is being
driven out of business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What results is more than just a scarcity of people to fill
those unpaid and underpaid roles, but, she argues, a reduction in
the quality of the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a lot of progress in getting people to recognize
the worth of quantitative work,'' she said. ``But also, what is the
quality of it? Is it rich, is it careful, is it high quality?
Economists should care about quality as much as quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurses, for example, say they have so many patients that ``they
no longer have time on their job to hold people's hands,'' she
said. She likens this ``public good'' to a clean environment:
``Everyone enjoys and benefits from it, but it's hard to get people
to actually pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   News of the $280,000 award came while she was in Europe
attending a conference of the International Association for
Feminist Economics, a group she helped found. The European Union
and other nations already have plans to survey the worth of
nonmarket work; in that regard, she said, ``the United States is
lagging behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Folbre said she would use some of the grant to support the
Center for Popular Economics, a nonprofit group where she is a
staff economist that runs workshops for advocates of social change.
Its mission of economic literacy is in accord with her conviction
that an economy can be changed at the grass-roots level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't believe that, I wouldn't bother,'' she said. In
fact, her first project with the windfall will not be a scholarly
work but a revision of her popular book, ``The New Field Guide to
the U.S. Economy'' (New Press, 1995) a cartoon-enhanced review
meant to provide intellectual ammunition for people with a liberal
bent.
</P>
<P>
   Such individuals, she said wryly, need to be able to refute
comments like `` `That's very nice and very sweet but that's not
efficient; we can't compete in a global economy if we spend money
on health care and education and welfare.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Folbre said: ``It's important to give people a vocabulary of
economics to be able to engage in debate.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
