<SLUG> BC-NY-FERRARO-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO ACCEPTED $20,000 FEE FROM PHILIP MORRIS, DOCUMENTS SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Rep. Geraldine Ferraro, who is seeking the
Democratic nomination for the U.S. Senate from New York, accepted a
$20,000 speaking honorarium from Philip Morris Cos. last year,
according to financial disclosure forms made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The payment was for a debate in February 1997 between Ferraro
and Robert Novak, one of her regular opponents on CNN's
``Crossfire'' program, before Philip Morris executives in Palm
Beach, Fla. Ferraro provided the liberal commentary on
``Crossfire'' until stepping down in January to campaign full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro's disclosure, which she was required to make under
congressional ethics rules, could harm her among Democratic primary
voters who many politicians believe are angry with the tobacco
industry. It could also make it harder for her to attack Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, the Republican incumbent, over the $56,200 in
contributions he has received from the tobacco industry since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Public Advocate Mark Green, who is also seeking
the Democratic nomination, seized on the honorarium to assert that
it was wrong for Ferraro ``to profit politically or personally from
tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to ask yourself what she was thinking to take
$20,000 in tobacco money at a time when Democrats from President
Clinton to congressman Waxman to me locally were trying to crack
down on the industry for addicting children,'' Green said in a
statement, referring to Rep. Henry Waxman of California, a
proponent of anti-tobacco legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro campaign manager David Eichenbaum responded by saying:
``Gerry is staunchly in favor of the anti-tobacco legislation now
in Congress. She is strongly for raising the tax on cigarettes. If
her position were different from that, it would be one thing. But
the fact that she has taken such a strong position against the
interests of the tobacco industry makes this a nonissue.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's attack represented the latest bit of sniping among the
Democratic Senate candidates, a trend Democratic Party leaders
worry will escalate into full-fledged intraparty strife before the
primary season ends, even though the candidates have pledged to
avoid personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The third Democratic candidate, Rep. Charles Schumer, who
represents Brooklyn and Queens, declined to comment on Ferraro's
honorarium, as did D'Amato. Still, Green's attack could clearly
benefit both Schumer and D'Amato by undermining Ferraro, who is
widely considered the Democratic front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also showed that Ferraro's personal finances are
likely to be major issues throughout the campaign. That was also
the case when she lost the Democratic Senate primary in 1992; her
opponents then focused on the real estate dealings of her husband,
John Zaccaro.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro helped rekindle the debate over her finances by
restricting public review of her 1997 tax returns earlier this
year, allowing reporters just three hours to study the complex
documents and refusing to make copies available. Green and Schumer
handed out copies of their returns, though D'Amato did not.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro accepted the Philip Morris honorarium at a time when
Democrats across the country, as well as some Republicans, had
begun attacking the tobacco industry's marketing practices and
demanding that it pay for health costs relating to smoking. Many
Democrats are expected to campaign against the tobacco industry
this fall; indeed, Ferraro, Green and Schumer have all pledged not
to accept any contributions from the industry's political action
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic strategists said the payment would hurt Ferraro
among traditionally liberal Democratic primary voters. ``They are
anti-tobacco,'' said Philip Friedman, a strategist who works for
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The honorarium was listed in financial disclosure forms that all
incumbents and candidates for Congress are required to file
annually. Schumer's report showed that he had assets worth $238,000
to $560,000 and received no honorariums last year. Green received
an extension on his report, saying he needed extra time because he
had just filed his city disclosure report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
