<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 14, will move Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   RAPE-REVIEW _ They strike without warning, bringing terror to an
Algerian apartment, a Chinese shophouse in Indonesia, a squalid
refugee encampment in Africa or a Balkans farming village under
siege. They are shadowy men with a cause so blinding and a hatred
so deep that they have transformed modern warfare into orgies of
primordial savagery _ raping, brutalizing, humiliating, slashing
and hacking women and girls to death. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-REVIEW _ More than two years before Election Day, polls say
a Republican front-runner in the 2000 presidential race has already
emerged. He is a one-term governor, George W. Bush, who has never
run for national office but has, according to one recent poll,
already overtaken Vice President Al Gore, the popular Democrat who
has been running for the White House for 20 years. By Adam
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD-CONSERVATIVES-REVIEW _ If you want to know what is
wrong with the movie business, just ask Lionel Chetwynd. Chetwynd
has written the scripts for more than a dozen successful movies and
says he has been frustrated in his efforts to take his career a
step higher. The problem is not quality, he argued _ his films like
``The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz'' and ``Kissinger and Nixon''
have won widespread praise. No, he insisted, the barrier is his
beliefs: Chetwynd is a conservative. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-REVIEW _ Nigeria's new general-in-charge, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar, in his first speech since the sudden death on
Monday of iron-fisted Gen. Sani Abacha, hammered away at the theme
of unshaken adherence to his country's ``international
commitments'' as he sought to comfort allies and serve notice of
his country's resolve to potential foes. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-REVIEW _ President Clinton's visit to China,
scheduled to begin June 25, is likely to be about appearances more
than anything else. No real diplomatic breakthrough looks possible,
since the United States and China remain far apart on key issues
like Taiwan and human rights. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-REVIEW _ The conspiracy theorists have it all wrong.
The U.S. government is not run by Freemasons. Or by the pope or
Jewish bankers. The American people are entitled to the truth: the
government is run by Southern Baptists, who were recently in the
news for boycotting Disney, proselytizing Jews and, just last week,
declaring that wives should submit to their husbands. By Laurie
Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-POLLS-REVIEW _ They do not have the academic cachet of a
Harvard, nor will they forever be identified with winning one for
the Gipper like Notre Dame. But many unsung schools, including
those with tongue-curling names like Quinnipiac College, have
discovered a sly way to get themselves better known. They poll. By
Joseph Berger.
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSE-REVIEW _ Cosmologists intent on understanding the
origin of the universe are faced with an insurmountable problem:
there is no way to do a controlled experiment. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   TALENTED-IMMIGRANTS-REVIEW _ Yoko Ono is one and so was John
Lennon. Alan Cumming, the Scottish star of Broadway's ``Cabaret''
and a Tony award winner, is one, too. Orlando Hernandez, the
Cuban-born pitching ace for the Yankees known as ``El Duque,''
became one just recently. All are or were ``aliens with
extraordinary ability.'' Despite its sound of chest-out,
fists-on-the-hip braggadocio, the phrase is not a description of an
especially poised visitor from another planet, but a government
classification of a distinguished, and human, immigrant. By Anthony
Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-STATION-REVIEW _ In the history of bad decisions, the
Shoreham Nuclear Power Station stands out, a single project that
has polarized the politics of Long Island, N.Y., for a generation,
boosted electric rates high enough to repel industry for miles
around, uselessly monopolized the talents of hundreds of engineers
and thousands of skilled craftsmen for more than a decade and
sucked more than $5.5 billion out of the economy. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MARATHON-MAN-HNS &LR;      06-12 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MARATHON-MAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON RUNNER ON THE FAST TRACK TO A WORLD RECORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ala., Fla., Ind.) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By NEAL FARMER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rick Worley of Houston broke a world record for
marathon racing last weekend, and all he got was a medal for
finishing the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Worley said, ``it was a medal and a lot of
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   When Worley finished the South Bend, Ind., Sunburst Marathon on
June 6, it marked the 75th consecutive weekend he had finished at
least one race of 26 miles, 385 yards. He has run two marathons in
the same weekend on 12 occasions, meaning he has run better than
2,200 miles since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But that number pales in comparison to the travel time it has
taken Worley to get from race to race. His 75-week string includes
at least one race in each of the 50 states plus the District of
Columbia. And he isn't stopping now.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the year's end, I will have run 104 straight weeks and in
126 marathons,'' he said. ``I haven't been home for a weekend since
Dec. 28, 1996. If President Clinton were to drive by my lawn, he'd
declare it a national disaster area.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not like Worley, 51, is setting the world on fire with his
times; he generally finishes in more than four hours in an effort
to avoid injuries. He runs not only for himself but for the Worley
Marathon Scholarship Fund, which thus far has raised $6,000 for Cal
Farley Boys Ranch near Amarillo, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if I was going to do this, it might as well mean
something,'' Worley said. ``We've funded three-plus scholarships
there, which are $1,800 each.''
</P>
<P>
   Worley, an executive with Houston's Mieco Oil Co., ran nine
marathons from 1982 through 1984 before suffering a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   He set a goal of getting back into shape to run the Houston
Marathon at age 40, in 1987. He planned to run another marathon
when he was 50 and another when he was 60 ``for something to tell
the grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 50, as he prepared to run the 1997 Houston Marathon, he
saw an article about someone who celebrated turning 50 by running
50 marathons in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that made me only wanting to run my one marathon
when I turned 50 look kind of cheesy,'' he said. ``In baseball,
they have the 40-40 club. I thought, `What about a 50-50 club?'''
</P>
<P>
   So on Jan. 5, 1997, one week before the Houston Marathon, he ran
in the Disney World Marathon at Orlando, Fla. Then during the
Houston race, he saw people wearing T-shirts from the 50 &AMP; D.C.
Marathon Group USA Club. Its members set a goal to run a marathon
in each state as well as the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Worley then modified his goal to run a marathon in each of the
50 states and Washington, D.C., in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times, he had to run two marathons in the same weekend
because some states had only one race a year. But on Dec. 13, 1997,
he ran in the Rocket City Marathon in Huntsville, Ala., to complete
his goal, which was certified by the 50 &AMP; D.C. Marathon Group USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took only 47 weeks and a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he finished the South Bend race for his 75th consecutive
weekend marathon, he broke the world record of 74 held by Gordon
Hartshorn of The Colony, a Denton County suburb of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Worley's fastest time in the 75-weekend streak was 4:01 in South
Bend. His career best is 3:29 at Houston in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of his most interesting moments came last year on a cruise
ship to Alaska, when Worley was traveling to participate in the
Mayor's Midnight Sun Marathon in Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   During the trip, Worley and his girlfriend, Dee Stone, met Jim
Thompson, a vice president with Atlanta Freight Liner in Georgia.
Thompson was mesmerized by Worley's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had participated in 23 or 24 marathons at that time, and I
told him that when I had run in enough marathons to become
credible, I would want to seek money for the Cal Farley Boys
Ranch,'' Worley said. ``He said, `You don't have to wait until your
first 30. You have a sponsor now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Worley is a native of Canadian in the Texas Panhandle, and he
moved to Amarillo at an early age. He graduated from Tascosa High
School and West Texas State before the oil business brought him to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   While at Tascosa, he was on the high school wrestling team.
There was only one school against whose wrestlers he never won _
the Boys Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   So he decided to go the distance for his old rivals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How long will the string continue? The end is in sight, Worley
said. But not before he performs his own version of the North
American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to run in all 50 states plus the District of Columbia,
all 12 Canadian provinces and territories, as well as a November
run in Cozumel, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he will choose the time to hang up the sneakers. After
December, he said he will pick a race and retire with the same
hoopla he had when he broke the world marathon record _ just a
medal for finishing the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there will still be a lot of satisfaction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
