<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; tab-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEREGULATED-SKIES-LAT     06-12 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEREGULATED-SKIES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN SEASON
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By CHARLES W. THURSTON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Being the big fish in a small pond has its pleasures.
That so far has been the experience of U.S. airlines opening routes
in recently deregulated skies over Latin America.
 &HT;    In Central America _ the first region to agree to ``open
skies,'' which allows carriers from member countries to freely set
frequencies and aircraft capacity on international routes _ U.S.
carriers American, Continental and United are blanketing the region
with flights. Now Delta Air Lines is expanding in Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala and Panama, thanks to the ease of entry.
 &HT;    Delta CEO Leo Mullin crows the common logic among U.S. airline
executives: ``Passengers pursuing business and leisure
opportunities ... won't accept artificial barriers to their travel.
This unrelenting pressure ... for access and ease ... at
competitive prices will propel nations towards liberalized air
treaties.'' However, the rhetoric of open skies has gone from a
shiny truth to a fuzzy semi-reality, even as regional air traffic
takes off. Some 26 million passengers traveled between the United
States and Latin America in 1990; by 2001, U.S. consultants
Aviation Management Services projects that number will double.
 &HT;    Open skies are aviation's answer to free markets. The agreements
essentially permit any safety-certified carrier from one signing
country to set schedules and routes to meet market demand in the
other country, without government interference. The United States
has nine such treaties in Latin America, but the largest market
open to unfettered access is Chile, the latest country to sign on.
``Until some more big players sign up, the characteristically
restrictive regulatory environment is still essentially intact,''
says Lee Hibbets, the research director for Air Cargo Management
Group, the U.S. aviation consultants.
 &HT;    The equation makes less sense for many Latin Americans concerned
about the future of the regional aviation industry. While small
markets have opened up to the United States' push for free-market
flying, larger countries with marginally competitive carriers have
bulked at the prospect of U.S. multinational carriers blitzing
their home markets.
 &HT;    Intraregional open skies within Latin America are likely to
become a reality sooner than interregional open skies with the
United States, says Bob Booth, president of Aviation Management
Services. The Andean Pact has had a full open-skies agreement in
place among its members since 1992 that has opened up markets,
particularly on routes between capital cities. The Mercosur bloc
has also finally reached an accord, allowing carriers to provide
international service to cities that are not currently
international destinations. Even with such limitations, that market
alone is expected to generate US$1 billion a year. The first
intra-Mercosur routes have been approved and service should begin
soon.
 &HT;    One significant barrier to U.S. bilateral open-skies agreements
in the region is inadequate safety. Latin American carriers' safety
levels must be endorsed by the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration
before they may serve U.S. airports. Although many countries in the
region are ranked in the top Category I, seven important country
markets-including Colombia and Venezuela-are ranked Category II,
meaning safety is lax.
 &HT;    And eight nations are ranked lowest as Category III, meaning
levels are unacceptable.
 &HT;    Similarly, insufficient airport infrastructure and lax
maintenance practices by many Latin American airlines leave
statute-bound U.S.
 &HT;    officials unable to sign deals. Aging infrastructure and
insufficient technology is a problem common to many regional
airports unable handle the growing volume of commercial traffic.
 &HT;    Latin American aviation executives are lukewarm to the idea of
allowing powerhouse U.S. carriers to romp freely. Many fear that if
they don't team up with a bigger partner, the end may be in sight.
``If we don't get an alliance in our region ... we're going to be
very weak,'' LAN Chile CEO Enrique Cueto said, speaking at a
conference of Latin American aviation CEOs in April. ``In the end,
probably someone will buy us up or we will disappear or we will be
very small companies.'' These fears are driving a growing trend
known as pooling, or code-sharing agreements between airlines
within Latin American trade blocs. Several airlines from the Andean
Pact met earlier this year to discuss pooling arrangements, like
the 1996 TACA alliance formed in Central America. And alliances
between Latin American and other airlines-a trend led by American
Airlines-is growing in importance.
 &HT;    Such alliances will grow faster than open-skies agreements,
given the bureaucracy and built-in resistance to what U.S. carriers
see as the logical and just conclusion of free-market flying. Says
Gus Nordelo, vice president of sales for U.S.-based Challenge Air
Cargo's. ``It's the law of survival. The strong will become
stronger and the weaker will disappear.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
</BODY>
