<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ISLAND-REDEVELOP-N     06-12 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ISLAND-REDEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSALS TO REDEVELOP HISTORIC ISLAND IN N.Y. HARBOR TO BE
UNVEILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration plans to release two
reports next week sketching out redevelopment proposals for
Governors Island, including housing, schools, parks, a new hotel _
and a casino that would provide millions of dollars to finance the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The reports come as civic groups, preservationists, and others
have sharply criticized the city and state for failing to move
quickly to develop the historic island in New York Harbor. They
worry that officials are squandering President Clinton's offer to
give the federally-owned island to New York City, provided the city
and state come up with an acceptable public purpose for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Governors Island, a 172-acre military installation for 300
years, was closed last year and is now virtually a ghost town. Its
last inhabitants, the Coast Guard, left the island in pristine
shape, but preservationists worry that the historic buildings could
quickly slide into decrepitude.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, park and playground proponents hunger for the
island's recreational potential, and New York University and
Columbia are looking at it as a possible home for classrooms and
students.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has suggested several times that casino
gambling could provide a windfall to finance other desirable
development on the island, as well to preserve such historic
treasures as Castle William, one of two forts that long guarded the
harbor. But that plan has run into criticism from preservationists
and some politicians, who have argued that a casino is an
inappropriate use for the site and politically unrealistic as well.
</P>
<P>
   The reports by independent consultants that the city will
release next week will outline the economic pluses and minuses of
various developments, as well as suggest changes to the buildings
needed to achieve them, Deputy Mayor Randy Levine said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The state, which has not taken a position on the island, said it
would follow the city's lead. ``We're looking forward to seeing
what they come up with,'' said Michael McKeon, press secretary to
Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the island's fate remains in limbo, the National
Trust for Historic Preservation plans to include the site in its
new list of the nation's 11 most endangered historic places,
officials of the organization said. The designation, to be
announced on Monday, will group Governors Island with such
imperiled treasures as a Civil War battlefield in Virginia and an
Art Deco hotel in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Moe, the trust's president, said he was worried that the
empty buildings could deteriorate quickly. ``Governors Island could
be on a slippery slope to serious deterioration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moe urged the governor and the mayor to appoint a commission to
quickly come up with alternatives, before the opportunity to
preserve the island is lost. Levine said the reports would answer
this request.
</P>
<P>
   The trust president compared Governors Island with the south
side of Ellis Island, which, unlike the north side, has not been
restored. Last year, the trust put Ellis Island on its list of most
endangered places, an action it believes helped secure a $6 million
Congressional appropriation to stabilize the buildings on the south
side.
</P>
<P>
   If New York does not take over the island by 2002, federal law
requires that it be auctioned for a price Congress has estimated at
$500 million. As part of the process of marketing the island,
hearings on a draft environmental impact statement will be held
June 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Financing is critical to any redevelopment plan. The Urban Land
Institute, a Washington organization of real estate professionals,
issued a report last year saying any development on Governors
Island would probably need an initial infusion of capital to
jump-start it. Giuliani has several times suggested that casino
development may be a way to get this investment.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea worries many of the groups most interested in the
island's development. ``We can't find anyone who thinks a casino
will work here,'' said Brendan Sexton, president of the Municipal
Art Society. He worries that a bridge from Brooklyn to the island
might be necessary to transport the crowds needed to support a
large casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly want public access, but you don't want thousands
and thousands of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of civic groups plan to present a plan in September
for a number of uses. Members cite political difficulties with
gambling. Marcia Reiss, policy director for the Parks Council,
pointed out that gambling would have to pass the Legislature twice
and a statewide referendum once. ``I don't see it passing in New
York,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2154EDT &QL; 
