<HEADER>
A7422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-INTEL-NYT &LR;      06-12 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INTEL INSIDE . . . TARGET RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 13:
</P>
<P>
   With its antitrust lawsuit against Intel, the maker of chips for
nearly all personal computers, the Clinton administration took
another step this week to enforce old rules in a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Justice Department's suit against Microsoft last month,
the Federal Trade Commission's action challenges Intel's conduct as
a monopoly in a fast-changing business.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the government argues correctly that the law
prevents a monopoly from using its dominant position to muscle
competitors, even when competitors are also customers. But whereas
the Microsoft suit could reshape the computing industry, the Intel
suit seeks a modest outcome unlikely to hurt the company or
transform the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC is right to engage, along with the Justice Department,
in protecting competition in computers. But the Intel and Microsoft
cases are different in both scope and significance.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is accused of trying to use its monopoly in the
operating systems for personal computers to capture an even greater
monopoly in the Internet and related technologies, thereby
dominating the future course of the information age. Intel is
accused of withholding technical information on the use of its
chips from three Intel customers. Intel's objective, the FTC says,
was to force these customers to license the patents of their own
new products to Intel on favorable terms.
</P>
<P>
   Since these companies are also rivals in the development of new
chips and other products, the FTC charged that Intel's tactics were
an illegal use of its monopoly power. The suit demands that Intel
cease and desist from discriminating or threatening to discriminate
against ``any similarly situated'' customer.
</P>
<P>
   The atmospherics of the two cases are also different, in ways
that tell much about the nature of competition in the software
business. Intel and the FTC have made a commendable effort to lower
their voices. Intel executives have not followed Bill Gates'
example of vilifying the government for allegedly trying to stifle
innovation. The FTC, for its part, is trying not to be seen as
disabling Intel or sullying its reputation. The commission seems to
realize that, whereas software makers may distrust Microsoft, the
undisputed king of software, no one in the industry wants to see
Intel crippled. After all, Intel's investment of billions each year
in ever faster microprocessors, or chips, makes new generations of
software possible.
</P>
<P>
   Intel does not deny that it did what the FTC charges. Rather it
defends its actions as acceptable and legal in an extremely
competitive environment in which patent suits are endemic and its
own monopoly is actually quite precarious.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say the FTC will have a hard time proving that the
company's actions have hurt the consumers who buy computers. They
note, for example, that only one of the three companies cited by
the FTC makes microprocessors that compete with those of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In pressing its case, the FTC will have to demonstrate with
precision how Intel allegedly tried to undercut competing products
or inventions, and to what degree these actions have hurt
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But because of the constructive atmosphere on both sides, many
people in the business hope that Intel can reach an agreement with
its rivals to refrain from practices that are deemed
anti-competitive. That would be a more welcome development than
having both sides ground down in a protracted court case that could
take years before a final verdict is reached. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
