<HEADER>
A7426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-SQUARE-RECRUITI     06-12 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-RECRUITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECRUITING STATION TO GET THAT TIMES SQUARE LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In keeping with the neon-infused rejuvenation of the
area, the famous armed forces recruiting station at the crossroads
of Times Square will be replaced with a flashier recruiting center
just in time for New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The stainless-steel and tinted-glass building has been a fixture
in Times Square since 1950, signing up more recruits than any other
booth in the country _ and serving as a target of protests against
the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   The $600,000 project is being financed by the Army Corps of
Engineers, which says it is wants a building that will fit in with
the dizzying blur of neon signs, billboards, theme restaurants and
electronic ticker tapes that Times Square has become.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the new recruiting booth, first reported Friday in The
Daily News, call for glass walls that night and day will sparkle
red, white and blue in the shape of the American flag, and for a
curtain of nine video monitors showing the military at work.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new building, on the traffic island at 43rd Street
between Broadway and Seventh Avenue, will be smaller than the
existing booth, the four recruiters from the Army, Navy, Air Force
and Marines are promised more room because of a more efficient
design. And it will also have one amenity absent for the last 48
years: a restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll have a a modern look in keeping with all the changes in
Times Square,'' said Staff Sgt. Alberto Crespo, the Marine
recruiter on duty at the station Friday. ``But it will still
resemble a recruiting station.''
</P>
<P>
   Crespo works at one of four desks in the dark, cramped box,
which replaced what the Corps says was a ``cottage-style building''
put up in 1946. He said the center, despite its small size and
unfashionable look, outperformed every other recruiting operation,
sending about 200 men and women to the armed forces every year.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, the recruiting station has been at the center of
two debates that have nothing to do with war. City Councilman
Thomas K. Duane has suggested that the military, which pays the
city no rent for use of the traffic island, be evicted from the
spot. He argued that the armed forces' ``don't ask, don't tell''
policy requiring soldiers to remain silent about their
homosexuality violated city human rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Times Square Business Improvement District
said the station should be moved because it no longer fit in with
its glitzy neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But those efforts to push out the station set off an outpouring
of support for it, and prompted the Army Corps of Engineers to
speed up renovation plans.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Cassell, an architect at the Architecture Research
Office in Manhattan who designed the new station, said he tried to
create an icon that would be ``as strong as the memory of the
existing booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Shugert, a spokesman for the Army Corps of Engineers, said
the Corps was soliciting contractors. Demolition and construction
should begin in August, he said, with the new station opening in
time for a ribbon-cutting ceremony on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Handy, the director of the Mayor's Office of Veterans
Affairs, who supported keeping the recruiting station in Times
Square, said of the renovation plans: ``The military has to keep up
with modern times. It's appropriate that it be remodeled and moved
into the 21st century.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
