<HEADLINE>
STARR INQUIRY FOCUSES ON TALKS WITH POTENTIAL WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors looking into President Clinton's
relationship with a former White House intern are investigating
contacts between one of his senior aides and potential witnesses
shortly after the investigation began, according to lawyers who
have read a sealed legal opinion describing the contacts.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that according to the opinion, Bruce Lindsey,
deputy White House counsel, spoke with the lawyer for a former
chief White House steward, Michael McGrath. One person close to the
investigation by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel,
said Friday night that McGrath's lawyer had approached Lindsey to
discuss the intern matter.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said Lindsey had also contacted a former personal
assistant to the president, Stephen Goodin, and Vernon Jordan, the
Washington lawyer who is a close friend of Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has acknowledged helping Monica Lewinsky, the former
intern, find a job. Starr is investigating whether Clinton had an
affair with Ms. Lewinsky and tried to cover it up. Clinton has
denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr's interest in Lindsey's communications with witnesses
underscores the prosecutor's increasingly focus on how the White
House acted after learning that the Lewinsky investigation was
under way. In other words, Starr is investigating whether there was
a cover-up of a possible cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has invoked attorney-client privilege partly to block
questioning of Lindsey about his contacts with potential witnesses.
U.S. Judge Norma Holloway Johnson rejected that assertion of
privilege in an opinion that was released late last month with some
portions withheld.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles Times reported that the withheld
portions of the opinion described Lindsey's contacts with potential
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Without addressing the specific facts of the judge's opinion,
the White House on Friday defended any questioning of witnesses,
whether before or after they testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``That practice is universally recognized to be a necessary part
of any lawyer's effective representation of clients and has been
followed by counsel to Republican and Democratic presidents,'' said
Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official said it was important for White
House lawyers to contact potential witnesses or their lawyers to
determine whether prosecutors were seeking to learn about documents
or conversations that might be covered by a form of privilege.
</P>
<P>
   But another ally of the president's said that although Lindsey's
activities might have been legal, they were politically troubling
because they raised suspicions that he was coaching witnesses.
``From a political perception point of view, you might say, `Hey,
Bruce, that's not the smartest thing to do,''' this person said,
but added, ``What are we supposed to do, run around in the dark?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the parts of her opinion that were released in May, Ms.
Johnson made clear that she had no patience for the argument that
Lindsey's conversations with potential witnesses were privileged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the White House interviewed grand jury witnesses in order
to determine how and whether the president or his aides could avoid
compliance with grand jury subpoenas or otherwise obstruct the
investigation, then the witnesses' identities and the substance of
those interviews would shed light on this,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She also noted, ``White House attorneys are paid by U.S.
taxpayers to provide legal advice on official presidential
decisions, not the private decisions of President Clinton, and
certainly not private, potentially criminal conduct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
