<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-1stLd-     06-12 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-ART-1stLd-Writethru-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: since 1984.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Hachiro Hattori, a 75-year-old vendor of wrapping materials,
the solution is to put his pension income into his ailing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I can survive if we buy only food,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement offered new data only for the
January-to-March period, but since Japan's fiscal year ends March
30 the new figures meant that over the course of the last fiscal
year the nation's gross domestic product fell 0.7 percent. That was
the first absolute decline in output since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Exports for the first quarter also declined by 3.8 percent, the
first drop in a dozen years, as troubled Asian economies
drastically cut back on their imports from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There are no reliable figures to assess economic performance
since then but there is scant evidence of improvement. Still, with
Parliamentary elections next month, the government is trying
desperately to cheer people up.
</P>
<P>
   The elections will choose representatives to the parliament's
upper house, which is less important than the lower house. Still
the election is an important gauge of public sentiment, and Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto wants to do well so as to boost his own
standing and his ability to hold on to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Hashimoto won an expected victory when the Lower House
of Parliament rejected a no-confidence motion against his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Officials point out that the government's massive $111 billion
stimulus package seems about to be approved by the Parliament,
clearing the way for a rush of public funds into the economy. The
ruling Liberal Democratic Party is counting heavily on the public
money to pick up growth.
</P>
<P>
   But industrial production was down six percent in April from the
year before, corporate profits have tumbled 25 percent from the
previous year, prices are falling ominously, and some economists
warn that Japan may be sinking into a deflationary spiral.
Economists fear a vicious cycle in which falling prices and profits
would lead to rising unemployment, which would curb consumption and
bring down prices further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deflation, that's pretty clear.'' said Robert Alan
Feldman, an economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. But he added
that the stimulus package would stop the spiral, though not
deflation.
</P>
<P>
   Capital spending for the first quarter fell 5.1 percent, the
steepest decline since 1965. The government also released figures
Friday showing that Japanese manufacturers plan to reduce spending
by 4.4 percent on plant and equipment in the current fiscal year,
which began on April 1. The decline was the first one in four
years, according to the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly hard to see a way out at this point,'' said
Peter Morgan, an economist at HSBC Securities Japan Ltd. Morgan
said that Japan needs far-reaching restructuring and added, ``We
are talking about a fundamental transformation of the economic
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese government officials have annoyed some analysts by
seeming to downplay the seriousness of the situation. In the past,
they frequently argued that the economy was simply ''stagnant'' or
at a ``standstill,'' refusing to acknowledge that it was actually
contracting. Indeed, many foreign-based economists have contended
that Japan entered a recession many months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Economic Planning Agency here are expected to
meet later this month to formally discuss when the recession began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
