</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCAIN-JOKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. MCCAIN APOLOGIZES TO PRESIDENT CLINTON FOR JOKE ABOUT CHELSEA,
RENO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sen. John McCain formally apologized to President
Clinton on Friday for a crass joke he made earlier in the week at
the expense of the first lady, Chelsea Clinton and Attorney General
Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels terrible that he said it,'' McCain press aide Nancy
Ives said.
</P>
<P>
   Ives said a letter of apology had been hand-delivered to the
White House, but she declined to provide a copy to ``The Arizona
Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   Ives also would not repeat the joke that landed McCain in hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel comfortable telling you,'' she said. ``He feels
awful, and he regrets that he said it. . . . I just can't repeat
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Political sources told ``The Republic'' the joke went something
like this: Do you know why Chelsea Clinton is so ugly? Because
Janet Reno is her father.
</P>
<P>
   News of McCain's offending quip first appeared in the
``Washington'' ``Pos''t's ``Reliable Sources'' political column
Friday. It said McCain ``drew some gasps but more guffaws at a GOP
Senate fund-raiser Tuesday night'' when he launched the ``shocking
barb.'' The newspaper did not report the content of the remark.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Post'' quoted McCain as saying Thursday night: ``Yes, I
made a very unfortunate and insensitive remark. It was the wrong
thing to do, and I have no excuse for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton considered McCain's apology letter to be heartfelt,
White House Press Secretary Mike McCurry told ``The'' ``Republic''
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president certainly understands how you get caught saying
things you ordinarily wouldn't have said,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton may have even called McCain to assure him
there were no hard feelings. The president was traveling Friday,
and McCurry could not confirm whether the call had been placed.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also would not release McCain's letter of the
apology, saying the matter was private.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Clinton have been working side-by-side lately on a
number of contentious issues, including the tobacco bill and
campaign-finance reform. McCain has also come to Clinton's defense
on some of his nominations and foreign-policy decisions on the
ground that the chief executive's authority must be respected.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's gaffe comes just as he is eyeing a possible White House
bid in 2000, and enjoying a virtual lovefest in the national media.
Even CBS' hard-hitting Mike Wallace fawns over McCain. Wallace was
quoted in the ``Post'' this week as saying he might quit his job to
become McCain's press secretary if McCain gets the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was not the first time McCain has found himself
apologizing for his razor-edged remarks.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, McCain wrote a letter of apology to House Speaker
Newt Gingrich for comparing the GOP leader's poll numbers to mass
murderer Jeffrey Dahmer's.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, McCain referred to the Arizona Cardinals
as the ``St. Louis Cardinals'' during a speech at a Phoenix
fund-raiser for McCain's re-election campaign. Cardinals owner Bill
Bidwill was among those in attendance at the event.
</P>
<P>
   McCain told ``The Republic'' then that he wouldn't go overboard
in watching his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go through life anymore worrying about people taking
comments of mine out of context,'' he said. ``I also try to use
humor, and several times that's been distorted. It's just something
you've got to live with, and I'm too old to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, McCain even chuckled about his penchant for getting
into trouble with his blunt talk in a profile in ``Esquire''
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In the article, McCain was quoted as saying of his congressional
colleagues, ``The House doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his fellow senators, McCain added: ``Some of these guys,
have they even had lives? What have they done? . . . Aw, jeez, this
is exactly the kind of thing that gets me in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona voters, though, may be more understanding of McCain than
most.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1986 bid to fill the seat vacated by another outspoken
Arizona politician, the late Barry Goldwater, McCain made a joke to
a group of university students in which he referred to Leisure
World as ``Seizure World.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain won anyway. &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at 444-8546 or at
michael.murphy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Republic writer Jeff Barker contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
