<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAPANESE ECONOMY WEAKER THAN BELIEVED, DATA SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy, the world's second largest, sank at a stunning
annual rate of 5.3 percent in the first quarter of this year, the
government said in an official report that painted an even bleaker
picture than expected and confirmed that the nation is in a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   The report was released after Japan's battered stock market had
closed for the day, but the yen kept falling, reaching another
eight-year low against the dollar. Although the benchmark Nikkei
225 index rose 8.29 points, it finished the week with a loss of
301.1 points or nearly 2 percent, and is down 13 percent from its
March 2 high.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN STOCKS PLUNGE 8.1 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Korean stocks tumbled, returning to the 11-year lows reached
last month. The latest drop comes amid worries about the pace of
economic change and labor unrest. The key market index fell 8.1
percent, to 302.09 _ the lowest since January 1987.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER PRICES ROSE 0.2 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Prices paid to producers rose rose 0.2 percent in May _ the same
increase as in April _ largely because of a sharp gain in the cost
of prescription drugs. Analysts saw no sign of a pickup in
inflation in the data. Another economic report pointed to a
slowdown. Business inventories of unsold goods rose 0.2 percent in
April _ the slowest gain in three months.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN, SACHS PARTNERS MEET
</P>
<P>
   The 190 partners of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. met to consider a
proposal to turn the firm, Wall Street's last major private
partnership, into a public company. A Goldman spokesman said the
firm would probably announce Sunday whether or not the partners
backed the plan to go public.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM FILES FOR TROPICANA SALE
</P>
<P>
   Seagram expects to raise as much as $3.6 billion when it sells
its Tropicana juice business in an initial public offering, the
company said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. Seagram disclosed plans for an IPO on May 21, when it
agreed to acquire Polygram, the music giant, for $10.6 billion in
cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   OIL DRILLING MORATORIUM IS EXTENDED
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced a 10-year extension of the
moratorium on oil drilling off virtually all American ocean
coastlines. The moratorium does not affect areas off the Texas and
Louisiana coasts, where extensive drilling has been going on for
years.
</P>
<P>
   BIG STAKE IN BRITISH CABLE UNIT SOLD
</P>
<P>
   BCE, the Canadian telecommunications company, sold its 14.25
percent stake in Cable and Wireless Communications for (British
pounds)975.2 million ($1.59 billion), in a move to exit the British
cable television industry.
</P>
<P>
   VW UNIT TO BUY LAMBORGHINI
</P>
<P>
   A week after Volkswagen won its bid to acquire Rolls-Royce, the
German car maker is adding another storied name to its garage: the
company's Audi unit has agreed to buy Lamborghini SpA, the Italian
sports car maker. Terms were not disclosed, but analysts estimated
Lamborghini's worth at $111 million.
</P>
<P>
   FCC SCALES BACK INTERNET PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from lawmakers who argued that the program would
increase long-distance telephone rates, the Federal Communications
Commission decided to reduce by more than 40 percent the budget of
a plan to connect schools and libraries to the Internet.
Long-distance carriers are required to provide most of the money
for the program. Under the revised plan, $1.275 billion will be
raised this year, down from an original maximum of $2.25 billion.
</P>
<P>
   NEW GLOBAL INITIATIVE ON CHILD LABOR
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is supporting a proposed treaty to
outlaw the most exploitive forms of child labor. The new
International Labor Organization initiative comes 25 years after
the body first tried to curb such abuses. The new convention
focuses on such extreme forms of child labor as working in mines
and prostitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
