<SLUG> BC-BOX-LAHOYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WELL-RESTED DE LA HOYA SWAGGERS INTO THE SUN BOWL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOE DRAPE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ They have rushed his limousine hard enough to
crack a windshield and followed his entourage across town to
transform what was supposed to be a secret workout into a runway
show for 1,000 shrieking fans. Now, Oscar De La Hoya really goes
big.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 52,000 people are expected at the Sun Bowl on Saturday
night to witness De La Hoya make his first World Boxing Council
welterweight title defense of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That his opponent, a Frenchman named Patrick Charpentier, is the
No. 1 contender, is something rarely mentioned by De La Hoya or the
fans who have pursued the heartthrob across this border town with
the ardor usually witnessed on the mall tours of the teen-age
musical group Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen much of him,'' De La Hoya said. ``For somebody
to beat me up in that ring is going to be tough. It's going to be
impossible, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya, a four-time champion with a 27-0 record, credits a
six-month layoff, as well as El Paso's rock star reception, for his
new air of invincibility. The fight with the lightly regarded
Charpentier (27-4-1, 23 knockouts) was postponed two times while De
La Hoya recovered from ligament damage in his left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   But De La Hoya said the rest was badly needed after he moved up
to the 147-pound division to defeat David Kamau, Hector Camacho and
Wilfred Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``The layoff did some good,'' said De La Hoya, who will earn $4
million for the mandatory title defense. ``I fought five times in
1997. Going into the 147-pound division, I really felt a change in
my body strength and my speed. I feel like a new fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   He indeed looked muscular at Friday's weigh in, tipping the
scales at 147 pounds. But more important is the fighter's newfound
swagger, which he said was the result of finally deciding that he
wanted to stay in the boxing game. While keeping a grueling 1997
boxing schedule, De La Hoya, 25, often spoke about retiring to
pursue modeling or an acting career, or some other business
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the time off, I asked myself, `Do I really want to fight,
or do I want to do something else?''' he said. ``This is what I
chose. I'm the champ.''
</P>
<P>
   Every one of his appearances here has brought police barricades
and a crush of mostly female fans. Reasonably priced tickets _ from
$35 to $300 _ have insured that the 60,000-seat Sun Bowl will be
crowded. Promoters are expecting the second largest outdoor crowd
for a fight in the United States, behind the 61,000 at Yankee
Stadium in September 1955 for the Rocky Marciano-Archie Moore bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-five percent of our seats were less than $65, and 80
percent of our tickets have been sold to women,'' said the local
promoter, Nick Huzella. ``This is the biggest event this town has
ever held.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Charpentier has been a good sport about the
wild scenes that have graced his and De La Hoya's joint
appearances. He weighed in at 146 pounds and will collect $600,000
to play the Golden Boy's supporting actor. But Charpentier conceded
he was irked at being ignored. ``I'm no joke,'' he said through an
interpreter at a news conference. ``He's in for a tough fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no one really heard him. His defiant words were
drowned out by a blizzard of high-pitched requests for De La Hoya's
hand in marriage _ or other less formal arrangements. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
