</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENGTHENING AND UNWINDING THE ROAD TO NOVEMBER 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYERS Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The primary and caucus season for the presidential election of
2000 is still the better part of 20 months away. But the gathering
of a dozen Republican wannabes in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, this weekend
for one of those hey-look-me-over affairs _ no straw poll, just
speaking and schmoozing _ is proof positive that the race is well
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there was any doubt. The political pros in Iowa who
track such things say that because no incumbent will be running,
White House wannabes have been flocking to the state at a record
rate for months, at least five times the 1996 rate.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's gathering, sponsored by the state's Republican
Party, is being advertised as the ``First-in-the-Nation Gala'' _ a
pointed reminder that Iowa traditionally holds the first caucus,
not the first dog-and-pony gala (of which there have been others,
in other states).
</P>
<P>
   But will Iowa hold the first-in-the-nation caucus in 2000? And
will New Hampshire hold the first primary?
</P>
<P>
   For the past several weeks, secretaries of state from New
England, the West Coast and the Rocky Mountain states have been
conferring about how to adjust the primary and caucus season so
that it will not be as ``front-loaded'' in 2000 as it has been in
recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduling of the 1996 primaries and caucuses particularly
concerned election officials because so many states held their
contests early _ some seeking prestige, others seeking a bigger
nominating role _ that the process was over almost before it began.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will be decided until all state secretaries have had
their say during our annual meeting in Salt Lake in July,'' William
Galvin, secretary of the commonwealth of Massachusetts, reported
after a Wednesday conference with New England and California
election officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one idea that's got a lot of interest and might appeal to
state parties and legislatures is a carefully spread-out series of
regional primaries and caucuses, with the region that goes first in
one election going last four years later, and so forth. Iowa, like
New Hampshire, probably would be left alone, to go first as
always.''
</P>
<P>
   Lure of Bright Lights And Big, Barry-less City
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital is filled with former legislators who never
went back home after retiring or being turned out of office.
Seduced by the city's power, majesty and easy money in law and
lobbying, many find it hard to return to the place they once
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Pressler, a Republican, spent 22 years on Capitol Hill
representing South Dakota, initially in the House, later in the
Senate. In 1996, he failed to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   He did not head for home. Rather, he took up the practice of law
in Washington. Now he is thinking about getting back into politics
_ in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few days, he says, he will decide whether to run
for mayor, entering a race blown wide open when Marion Barry, a
Democrat, announced he would not seek re-election after five terms.
</P>
<P>
   Pressler would be a long shot, at best. A very long shot: a
white conservative Republican from one of the most rural states
running in a jurisdiction that is totally urban, overwhelmingly
Democratic and 90 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the daunting challenge he would face in winning even
Republican support for a run, since the leading Republican
candidate, Councilwoman Carol Schwartz, made the best showing ever
by a Republican against Barry when she captured more than 40
percent of the vote in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pressler predicted that should he run, his support for
school vouchers and tax breaks for residents and businesses could
be his ticket to victory in a city that has lost many families and
businesses in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Again, New Hampshire Daunts the Democrats
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire can be a tough place for Democrats, given that
they have long been outnumbered there by Republicans. Yet back in
1996, by aggressively raising money and recruiting strong
candidates, the party had an unusually good run, helping President
Clinton to a solid victory, electing Jeanne Shaheen as governor and
giving a scare to the Republican incumbents in all three
congressional contests.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic hopes of capitalizing on that success in 1998 are
waning fast.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gov. Shaheen is favored to win re-election, Democrats
stand no reasonable chance of gaining control of the state
Legislature, and the party's Congressional candidates have almost
no prospects for victory. The nagging old Democratic problems of
raising money and finding good contenders are back, and with them
the old, debilitating minority-party mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   Two Republican incumbents, Sen. Judd Gregg and Representative
Charles Bass, are heavy favorites for re-election because the
Democrats recruited to challenge them are underfinanced political
unknowns. And in the third contest, the Republican incumbent, Rep.
John Sununu, son of the former Gov. John H. Sununu, has no
Democratic opponent at all.
</P>
<P>
   He had one briefly, last week. But five days of uphill
campaigning convinced the challenger, Wayne Burton, an educator,
that 1998 was not going to be much of a Democratic year in New
Hampshire. He withdrew Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Burton had entered the race proclaiming he would show that a
``working professional'' and political neophyte could successfully
run for office and still hold down a full-time job. He pulled out
lamenting that he had ``proved just the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Initial elation turned into dread when the enormity of the
commitment became clear,'' he said. ``The system is not
particularly accessible to people with good ideas but modest
means.''
</P>
<P>
   His departure left dispirited Democratic leaders with just hours
to find another candidate before Friday's final deadline for
getting into the race passed.
</P>
<P>
   They found no one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
