<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-1STLD-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 NATIONS DEMAND END TO SERB ATTACKS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Changes number of aircraft to ``20 to 30'' in 15th graf. No
pickup.)  (th) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Reinforcing the NATO alliance's threat of military
action to stop the violence in Kosovo, the United States, Russia
and six other major industrial democracies meeting in London on
Friday demanded an immediate stop to Serb attacks on ethnic
Albanian civilians in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign ministers of the eight countries gave President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia until Tuesday to call off the offensive. He
is expected to see Russian President Boris Yeltsin, the country
most hesitant to consent to the use of force against the Serbs, in
Moscow that day.
</P>
<P>
   Russia joined Friday in urging Milosevic to use their meeting as
an occasion to announce compliance with other demands made by the
United States, Russia, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The other demands were that Milosevic allow international
monitors unimpeded and continuous access to Kosovo, let refugees
who fled Kosovo return to their homes with international aid and
resume talks with the Kosovo Albanian leadership under Ibrahim
Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   About 250 people have been killed in the fighting so far,
international officials believe, and between 60,000 and 85,000 have
been displaced during the Serb offensive in the province, which is
90 percent ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic will be making a grave mistake if he
imagines the international community will be as slow to respond in
Kosovo as it was in Bosnia,'' British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said after the meeting Friday, which was originally called to
coordinate the international response to nuclear weapons tests last
month by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The group of eight countries issued a statement Friday warning
Milosevic that if international demands were not met, there would
be ``moves to further measures to halt the violence and protect the
civilian population, including those that may require the
authorization of a U.N. Security Council resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said, ``We're all
working together as much as we can on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministers also urged the International Criminal Tribunal for
the former Yugoslavia in The Hague to extend its writ to cover
crimes against humanity in Kosovo by Serb commanders and their
political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   France, like Russia, has been insisting that before any NATO air
strikes or peacekeeping missions can be undertaken, a Security
Council resolution is needed to authorize the use of force in
Kosovo. The French said Friday's statement indicated that Russia
would deliver a strong message to Milosevic in Moscow next week.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Friday that
Moscow remained opposed to military action, but Hubert Vedrine, his
French counterpart, said, ``I think the Russian position is not yet
their last word.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States believes existing U.N. resolutions regarding
the former Yugoslavia provide sufficient authority for any military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Vedrine emphasized the importance of keeping Russia, a
traditional ally of Serbia, in the emerging international consensus
that the world may have to step in to stop the fighting from
spilling over into the rest of the Balkans if Milosevic does not
respond quickly. Russia did agree to the warning the group issued
Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meeting in Belgium on Thursday, NATO defense ministers
commissioned contingency plans for military intervention, including
possible air strikes against strategic military targets in Serbia,
and scheduled a large-scale demonstration of NATO air power across
the border from Kosovo in Albania and Macedonia that could take
place next week.
</P>
<P>
   The British Defense Ministry said Friday that the exercise could
involve some 20 to 30 aircraft from more than six NATO countries,
including Britain and the United States. Russia said it would not
participate.
</P>
<P>
   All except Russia and Japan have banned investment in Serbia and
frozen Serb assets held in their countries, and added an additional
sanction Friday by banning flights by Yugoslav airlines to their
territory. Japan, but not Russia, supported the ban and said it
would consider similar action.
</P>
<P>
   With Rugova, the ethnic Albanian leader, in London for talks
with some of the foreign ministers, the group also said that it
expected him to make clear that it rejected violence and acts of
terrorism, and said it was essential that ``Kosovo Albanian
extremists'' refrain from violent acts that the Serbs could use as
a pretext for continuing their offensive.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright and the other ministers made clear that they
believed Milosevic, not Rugova, was at fault for the premature
suspension of negotiations that had been arranged last month by
U.S. special envoy Richard Holbrooke, who got the United States and
the allies to hold off on economic sanctions so the talks could
begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The violence escalated to such a point that the talks had to
be suspended,'' Albright said, and the United States did not
believe Rugova had any choice but to break them off.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his reaction to the NATO decisions earlier this week,
Rugova said, ``I asked for more, but this is all right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
