<SLUG> BC-NY-TAX-BILLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI IGNORES COUNCIL AND MAILS TAX BILLS AT OLD RATE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MIKE ALLEN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration announced Friday that it
was ignoring property tax rates set by the City Council this week,
and had begun sending bills to the city's 900,000 property owners
at the old rate.
</P>
<P>
   The council immediately went to State Supreme Court Friday night
to try to stop the mailing, but the administration said most of the
bills had already been sent.
</P>
<P>
   The annual bills include a letter giving Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's account of the rate dispute, which erupted after the
City Council passed next year's city budget without negotiating
with the mayor. The notice, which opens ``Dear Taxpayer,'' accuses
the council of setting the tax rates ``in an invalid and improper
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please be assured that the mayor will do everything in his
power to reduce the City Council's proposed spending and to prevent
the property tax increase that the City Council would otherwise be
imposing on many of you,'' the notice says.
</P>
<P>
   Responding Friday to the mailing, Peter Vallone, the speaker of
the council, called it ``blatantly political, unnecessarily
alarming'' and ``full of falsehoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decibels of the debate, the two sets of rates would
produce the same amount of revenue. But under the council's
formula, the average owner of a single-family home would pay about
$50 more, while the average owner of a co-op or condominium would
pay about $65 less.
</P>
<P>
   With tax payments due on July 1, some confused taxpayers may
have to wait for a court to tell them how much they will have to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   After the mayor asserted that the council's budget was out of
balance and vetoed many of the members' favorite programs, both
sides predicted that a state court would wind up deciding the
makeup of the budget for the year beginning July 1. First, though,
the tax rates will have to be decided in a separate court case.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas McMahon, the council's finance director, shook his head
at what he called ``The Budget War of the Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We adopted a legally binding tax fixing, and the
administration's job is to mail out the bills,'' McMahon said. ``If
they insist on ignoring what the council does, a court will have to
decide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Mastro, the deputy mayor for operations, said the bills
had been printed and sent to private mail-order houses, and would
be received by most taxpayers Saturday or Monday. ``The mailing is
largely completed,'' he said. ``There's nothing the council can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Several government watchdog groups said that the notice was a
surprising act of hubris even for a mayor who relishes his
reputation for elbows-out ball. Douglas Criscitello, the director
of the New York City Independent Budget Office, contended that the
mayor was spending taxpayer funds as part of ``a political ploy to
make the council look bad.''
</P>
<P>
   And Conn Nugent, executive director of the Citizens Union of New
York, which has criticized both the mayor and the council for their
handling of the budget, called the politically charged wording of
the notices ``a misappropriation of power.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor took his case to taxpayers' mailboxes the day after
the council began airing its side in radio ads paid for by the
council leaders' political action committee. Listeners hear the
crack of the bat as an announcer says that Little League had become
``part of the budget battle _ the Giuliani administration versus
your City Council, and your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, who is seeking the Democratic nomination for governor
this year, referred to the mailings as ``propaganda.'' But the
administration said they were nothing new, since the Department of
Finance had included an explanation of the rate with past bills.
Mastro, the deputy mayor, asserted that this year's notices were
written in ``simple and straightforward language.''
</P>
<P>
   The council's lawyers went to State Supreme Court in Manhattan
Friday night, seeking a temporary restraining order against the
mailing. It was unclear Friday night when the court would act on
the request.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's announcement about the tax bills came after he spent
most of the morning, during his weekly radio show and at a news
conference, assailing the council for what he said was politicizing
the budget process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The budget has been turned into an election-year budget for
the speaker,'' Giuliani said at City Hall. ``He's been using the
budget as a political pawn.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
