<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-AZR </SLUG>
  
 MISSING `9s' IRKS ARIZONA LOT TERY PLAYERS  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Ruth Wennerlund, like many regular Lottery players,
uses familiar numbers when she purchases tickets. Her son was born
on Sept. 7, so she always bought Pick 3 tickets with the same three
numbers: 9-0-7.
</P>
<P>
   But after a month of playing the popular new game, she noticed
something odd. The number 9 never was selected during the nightly
computer drawings for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really strange,'' said Wennerlund, a Chandler resident.
``So, on Tuesday, I decided to call the Lottery and ask why nine
had never been picked.''
</P>
<P>
   Wennerlund said she was told that Lottery officials had
carefully examined the game and that there were no problems.
</P>
<P>
   So she was understandably surprised Friday morning when she read
in ``The Arizona Republic'' that the game had been suspended
because a computer glitch had left 9 out of the drawings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just so mad,'' said Wennerlund, who only days earlier
had thrown away all of her losing Lottery tickets. ``Why should I
save losing tickets? I don't understand why they didn't catch this
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Wennerlund wasn't alone in her frustration. Lottery officials
said they were bombarded with calls Friday from people who had
bought Pick 3 tickets with the number 9. Several people also have
complained that the computerized drawings in the game were
confusing to players.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials said customers may either mail in the bad
tickets for a refund, including postage costs, or return them in
person to the Phoenix or Tucson Lottery offices.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly Pick 3 drawings were suspended late Thursday because
a programming flaw meant anyone who chose the number 9 had no
chance at the top prize of $500. That digit was left out of the
software that picked the winning numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 1.2 million Pick 3 tickets sold at $1 apiece since the
game began May 4, about 76,000 had the number 9.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Katsenes, the Lottery's spokeswoman, said players who
bought tickets with the number 9 may mail them to: The Arizona
Lottery, P.O. Box 2913, Phoenix, AZ 85062.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket-holders may also return them to the Lottery's Phoenix
office, at 4740 E. University Drive, or the Tucson office, at 877
S. Alvernon Way.
</P>
<P>
   Katsenes said the refunds also apply to people who bought
tickets in advance for future Pick 3 drawings regardless of the
numbers they selected.
</P>
<P>
   She said Lottery officials haven't decided when to resume the
game, which was halted after staff members discovered the glitch in
the $1,000 computer software that picked the winning numbers. Elsym
Consulting of Atlanta provided the flawed software to the Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull said Friday that she had ``full confidence in the
people running the lottery.'' And the company works with other
states, she said, where it has a good record.
</P>
<P>
   The big dilemma, Hull said, is what to do about people who
bought tickets with the number 9 but don't have them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will straighten this out as quickly as possible, but we
don't want to lose the impetus of the game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the popularity of Pick 3 has helped the the
Lottery turn around its lagging sales. Arizona Bingo, which Pick 3
replaced, had lost $1.5 million since it started last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the introduction of Pick 3, sales had been running about
3.9 percent behind last year. Now they are 2.6 percent above last
year's figures, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Katsenes said officials are exploring their options, which
include continuing Pick 3 using computer drawings or switching to a
mechanical-ball system that is used for other lottery games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting to fully test the system,'' she said. ``Our
first priority is testing.'' &QL; 
Republic writer Kathleen Ingley contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
