<SLUG> BC-NY-WHISTLE-BLOWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE RULES U.S. GOVERNMENT CANNOT SUE STATE OR CITY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan ruled Friday that the
U.S. government may not sue the city or state under a special
whistleblower law that would allow it to recover triple damages for
money that the federal government said was fraudulently obtained
for foster care.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was seen as significant because the government
asserted that under the law, known as the False Claims Act, it
could sue the city and state for potential a verdict of about $112
million.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Denny Chin of U.S. District Court in Manhattan did not
come to any conclusion on the merits of the lawsuit, which asserts
that from 1990 to 1994, the city's Child Welfare Administration
fraudulently obtained payments from the federal government after
falsely reporting that services were delivered to thousands of
children in foster care.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that the federal government could still sue the
city and state, but only to recover its actual loss, which the suit
placed at about $37 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani called the ruling important, and said,
``The judge understood that applying the False Claims Act's treble
damages provisions to the city would only hurt the taxpayers, and
would do nothing to help better the condition of children in foster
care.'' He continued, ``The city has been making an enormous effort
to provide decent foster care services to children. The decision
will help us to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dennis Vacco echoed those comments, saying that
federal prosecutors had other legal mechanisms, short of seeking
triple damages to recoup money that they believe is improperly
billed.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, whose office in
1996 joined an earlier lawsuit filed by a whistleblower, said that
she was reviewing Chin's decision, but fully intended to pursue the
government's other claims against the city and state ``for their
alleged failure to provide necessary and mandated services to
foster children.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said that the issue was pending in another case before
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in which the government used
the law to sue the state of Vermont and addresses similar legal
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In dismissing the claims under the False Claims Act, Chin said
that the Civil War-era law had been passed to protect taxpayers,
not to ``provide the federal government with a means to punish city
and state taxpayers for the alleged wrongdoing of their local
government officials.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Congress did not intend that cities or states be
subject to the False Claims Act, which traditionally has been used
against defense contractors or other corporations accused of
falsely billing the government for work that was not performed.
</P>
<P>
   A law professor at Columbia University, John Coffee Jr., who has
studied the law, said Friday that the triple damages provision was
designed largely to deter misconduct, whether in the private sector
of the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you rule that the state and city are immune,'' Coffee said,
``That ends much of the incentive for the whistleblower to come
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations that led to the federal suit were raised
initially by Bracha Graber, a former midlevel employee of the city
agency, who, under the whistleblower law, stood to share 15 percent
to 25 percent of any money recovered by the government. Her lawyer,
Carl Loewenson Jr., said that he concurred with Ms. White's
statement, but had no further comment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2232EDT &QL; 
