<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT RED WINGS: A CHAMPIONSHIP DIMMED, ANOTHER AWAITED
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Detroit and its Red Wings waited 42 years to
celebrate, but their party lasted only six days. It ended with a
terrifying limousine crash one year ago _ on Friday, June 13 _ that
left two men with serious brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The victims, defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov and the trainer
Sergei Mnatsakanov, were riding in the back of the limousine, going
home from a golf outing, the last team function to celebrate the
Wings' first Stanley Cup since 1955. Police said the driver,
working without a valid license, might have dozed off at the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, the Wings find themselves back in the
tournament finals. When they took a 2-0 lead in the
four-of-seven-game championship round with a 5-4 overtime victory
over the Washington Capitals on Thursday night, they were cheered
on by their two disabled comrades, who viewed from high above the
ice in a private box at Detroit's Joe Louis Arena. Game 3 is in
Washington on Saturday night in the MCI Center.
</P>
<P>
   Two more victories will give the Wings their second consecutive
championship. There is a palpable sense around the team's extensive
fan following that another title, without any devastating
aftershocks, would give Detroit a better chance to enjoy the giddy
feeling that ended so quickly last year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to see or hear much premature joy in the
faces or voices of the Red Wings' stars. The crash left them with a
sober sense of perspective and purpose. They admit that thoughts of
the injuries are never too far from their minds. But they stress
that they do not want to cheapen the tragic event by using it as
motivation for a mere sports contest.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Stanley Cup last June, the Red Wings' captain,
Steve Yzerman, said Friday: ``At the time, we were all thinking
this is the most significant thing that could happen to us. Six
days later, we realized it wasn't. It's not something we use to
motivate ourselves or to generate excitement. It was definitely a
strong reminder that playing hockey is not the most significant
thing that can happen in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzerman scored two goals Thursday night as the Wings twice came
from two-goal deficits to win in overtime on a goal by Kris Draper.
In his 15th season, Yzerman leads his team in playoff points with
23 and is a strong candidate for the Conn Smythe trophy, which goes
to the tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his teammates, Yzerman plays with a sophisticated
blend of ease and focus. No matter how many mistakes this team
makes, the players seem able to cover up for each other and come
back with resolve. They celebrate goals and victories with
momentary emotion, but there is a cool professionalism about them
most other times.
</P>
<P>
   The limousine accident and its aftermath, Yzerman said,
contributed to the team personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows you to relax and play under control,'' he said. ``We
grew up a lot. We learned a lot. It's changed our perspective at
little for the benefit of our hockey, indirectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Shanahan, another veteran forward, said the anniversary
date ``is not that significant'' because ``we think of them every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do our best not to exploit their injuries to get up for
games or get the crowd going,'' Shanahan said. ``It's friendship.
It's always on our minds, in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   In another coincidence, the driver of the limousine, Richard
Gnida, will be released from prison next Friday. He pleaded guilty
last November to a misdemeanor charge of driving with a suspended
license and was supposed to serve nine months and be released in
August. (He must also perform 200 hours of community service at a
facility for persons who have suffered closed-head injuries.)
</P>
<P>
   But Gnida will get out early because of good behavior as a
prisoner. The judge who sentenced him, Kimberly Small of 48th
District Court in Michigan, said she was not pleased about the
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he should serve it,'' Small told The Detroit Free Press
for Friday's editions. ``The crime this man committed _ the
suffering he caused _ is very serious. It's frustrating. But the
jail is following the law, and I understand that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
