u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUTGERS-LAW-DEAN-NYT &LR;      06-12 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUTGERS-LAW-DEAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIFT LOST, A LAW SCHOOL DEAN SENT PACKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the brouhaha since the dismissal of the dean of
the Rutgers Law School in Newark earlier this week, the central
question has become: Who lost Dr. Bernard Yudowitz and his promise
of a $4 million donation?
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers president Francis Lawrence said it was the dean of the
law school who let the gift slip through the university's fingers
because he failed to notify top officials early enough about who
the donor was _ Yudowitz is a psychiatrist who runs a chain of
treatment centers in Massachusetts _ and about how much he planned
to give.
</P>
<P>
   The dean, Roger Abrams, said that he handled the process
properly and that it was top university officials who dragged their
feet. He said that on the day in March that he learned of the
potential gift, he told the Rutgers Foundation, the organization
set up to accept such gifts. ``Someone has to tell me how I
mishandled this because I didn't mishandle it,'' Abrams said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks after he initially made his offer to Rutgers,
Yudowitz decided instead to make a donation to Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers is one of about eight law schools that have dismissed or
moved to replace their deans this year, a trend that concerns some
in the legal academic community who worry about what a high
turnover means to the stability of the schools and their reputation
among law school hopefuls and alumni. Some of the dismissals had to
do with money in the high-pressure world of university
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   At Georgetown University, for example, the president, the Rev.
Leo O'Donovan, announced in April that he would replace the dean of
the law school, Judith Areen. O'Donovan had reportedly pressured
her to channel to the medical school some of the money that she had
raised. But after an outcry from alumni, faculty and students, the
president backed down from his decision to dismiss the dean.
</P>
<P>
   At Rutgers, the dismissal of the dean also drew widespread
opposition, from the faculty of the law school to the New Jersey
State Bar Association. But the board of governors said Friday that
it was standing behind Lawrence's decision.
</P>
<P>
   The board rejected a suggestion by the law school faculty to
postpone Abrams' removal until after September 1999, when the law
school moves into its new quarters on Washington Street in downtown
Newark. The school is also facing its recertification from the
American Bar Association and is in the midst of a major
fund-raising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is within the president's prerogative,'' said Richard
Levao, the chairman of the board. ``He hired the dean and has the
authority and the duty to relieve the dean of his position when he
considers it necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers officials also said Friday that they did not believe the
dismissal would hurt the law school or the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deans change,'' said Norman Samuels, the provost at the Newark
campus of Rutgers. ``This law school is a first-rate law school.
This is an unfortunate incident, but the institution is much larger
than the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   While both sides argue about whose fault it is that Dr. Yudowitz
turned elsewhere to donate his money, they agree that the matter
did not become contentious until after an article in The Newark
Star-Ledger disclosing a confidential memorandum that Abrams wrote
to his faculty. In that memo, Abrams said that the gift from a
potential donor had been lost because of the ``inept management of
this university,'' when top officials could not give the donor an
answer quickly enough on the terms of their acceptance of his gift.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams did not identify the donor, in keeping with a practice at
the university not to disclose such a name until after a gift is
final. But The Star-Ledger learned Yudowitz's identity and
published his name.
</P>
<P>
   After the article, Lawrence undertook an investigation of the
handling of the Yudowitz gift, and earlier this week, he dismissed
Abrams, who had been dean of the law school for five years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
