<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-RACIAL-TENSION-     06-12 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-RACIAL-TENSION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racial crime puts Texas town in national spotlight
 &HT;    By Mitch Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Racism is a problem with which America has tried
to deal for generations and now the brutal killing of James Byrd
Jr., a black man, has put Jasper in the middle of the country's
racial debate, some residents here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the victim had been white, all this would never have
happened,'' The Jasper NewsBoy Managing Editor Michael Journee said
about the global extent of the media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Racism has not been easy for Jasper residents to talk about in
the crucible of media attention the Byrd murder has drawn. The
horrific nature of the crime has triggered worldwide denouncements
of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what (the victim's) race was, we still would have
been hurt,'' said Mary Horn, a black Jasper resident and wife of
Jasper Mayor R.C. Horn. During his visit, civil rights leader Jesse
Jackson said it was a good sign for Jasper that its mayor was black
and its sheriff white.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they found Byrd's torso near a cemetery at the
end of a blood splattered three-mile trail. It is alleged Byrd was
beaten, chained to the back of a truck, then dragged. During the
dragging Byrd's head, neck and right arm were severed from his
body.
</P>
<P>
   Three white men _ Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur
Springs, and Shawn Allen Berry and John William King, both 23 and
of Jasper _ have been charged with the Byrd murder and are being
held in Jasper County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   This crime is a throwback to days when it was easier to tell if
someone was being discriminated against. In many cases, racism is
not that easy to identify. One Jasper resident said people
frequently see racism where it isn't and deny racism where it
exists.
</P>
<P>
   In the Byrd slaying, the racist motives seem transparent. Quotes
in the suspects' probable cause affidavit pointed to a racial
motive for the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Berry stated in a sworn affidavit that King and Brewer made
numerous derogatory and racial remarks about Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   According to Berry's statement, when the trio picked Byrd up,
King said: ``That's some (expletive) you don't need to be picking
up a (racial epithet).''
</P>
<P>
   According to Berry's statement, just before King and Brewer
began to beat Byrd, King said: ``Fixing to scare the (expletive)
out of this (racial epithet).''
</P>
<P>
   According to Berry's statement, as Byrd's chained body was being
dragged down the roadway, Brewer said: ``That (expletive) bouncing
all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Berry's statement, Brewer said: ``I kicked the
(expletive) out of that (racial epithet).''
</P>
<P>
   According to the affidavit, King told Berry: ``You're just as
guilty as we are. Besides, the same thing could happen to a (racial
epithet) lover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and white agree: it was a very violent crime,'' Jasper
Chamber of Commerce chairwoman-elect Diane Domenech said. ``Whites
in the community feel we need to better the relationship between
the races, but I never felt that black and white don't work well
together here.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Jasper and the surrounding areas have experiences
that happened early in their lives that shape their opinions for
life. Some people are just scared that the same thing could happen
to them or someone they love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust white people,'' Jasper resident Ethel Parks
said. ``I was raised not to trust them. My Momma told me they would
turn on you and I've had some experiences like that _ not here, but
in other places. I don't know if I could ever learn to trust
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have taken other lessons from their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Stark, a white resident of Newton, said she was six years
old when one of five black girls who were sisters had a rock thrown
at her. The girl retaliated, Mrs. Stark said, as many children
would. The girl who threw the rock was a white girl, and she went
home to tell her father her side of what happened, and in turn her
father told the sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff came to that black girl's house, Mrs. Stark said,
and ordered the girl's father to take the rawhide whip off the ring
on his front porch and give his daughter 10 lashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried as he apologized,'' Mrs. Stark said. ``'I'm sorry I
have to do this,' he said. You could see the tears running down his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I try to make friends with black people because I
know what they've gone through.''
</P>
<P>
   Journee said the real tragedy in Jasper is what has happened to
the Byrd family. The future of Jasper will be what the people make
of it, he said. Jasper is neither a racist town nor is it devoid of
prejudice, Journee suggested. The truth is somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   When all the cameras have stopped rolling and Jasper is out of
the national spotlight, the city's residents will have an
opportunity to work on race relations, Journee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For good or bad, (when the media leaves) everyone will be much
more aware of race,'' Journee said. ``I imagine there are good and
bad elements to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
