<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slam in 9th sends Expos by Braves
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Darond Stovall's grand slam in the ninth inning
lifted the Montreal Expos over the Atlanta Braves 7-5 Friday night
at Turner Field, costing Braves starter Greg Maddux his 10th win.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves carried a 5-2 lead into the ninth and opened the
inning with Mark Wohlers on the mound. Wohlers walked the first and
only batter he faced and was pulled by Braves manager Bobby Cox in
favor of Mike Cather. Cather walked a batter and hit another,
loading the bases, then allowed the homer to Stovall.
</P>
<P>
   The game was the first of a three-game series and drew a crowd
of 45,942.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko hit his 11th home run and Eddie Perez drove in two
more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux spotted Montreal an early one-run lead and then held the
Expos to one run and four hits through the seventh. Maddux walked
one while striking out eight. Maddux has allowed just four earned
runs in his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   Expos starter Javier Vazquez didn't make it to the fifth, after
giving up five runs (four earned) on eight hits. This was a stark
contrast to his first Turner Field appearance May 27, where he also
dueled Maddux through the seventh while allowing only one earned
run.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal closed the Braves' lead to 5-2 with a single run in the
fifth, Jose Vidro picking up a two-out RBI with a single over Walt
Weiss' head, bringing in Mark Grudzielanek from second.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves broke it open with a four-run fourth, much of which
the Expos brought upon themselves. Chipper Jones opened the inning
with an single and Vazquez's next pitch struck Andres Galarraga on
the upper left arm. Following a Klesko foul-out, Andruw Jones
brought in one run for a 2-1 lead with a double off the left field
wall, giving him eight RBI in his last nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Perez followed by floating a single just over the head of first
baseman Brad Fullmer's head. Two runs scored for a 4-1 lead as
Perez extended his hit streak to eight games. The play should have
ended there but right fielder Vladimir Guerrero bobbled the ball
once he finally got to it. Perez took off for second and somehow
avoided Grudzielanek's tag.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Maddux hit what should have been an
inning-ending grounder to shortstop, but Grudzielanek committed his
NL-high 16th error, allowing Perez to score for a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
