<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga well ahead of team-record HR pace
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Andres Galarraga isn't simply pursuing the Braves'
franchise home run record. He seems to have put it in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, when Eddie Mathews set the club record with 47, he had
20 home runs after 66 games. In 1971, when Hank Aaron tied Mathews,
he had 19 after 66 games. Galarraga had 25 entering Game 67 Friday
night, and had already passed Ryan Klesko's team-leading 24 of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Anything more than 47 would break the record for homers by a
Latin American, which Galarraga currently shares with Texas' Juan
Gonzalez and the retired George Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, I try to play with my own records,'' he said. ``So
if I'm hitting .300, I try to hit .305. I had 150 RBI (last year),
so maybe I can get 151. That helps keep me working on something
every year, trying to get something a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Or a lot more. Entering Friday, he was on track to hit 61
homers, a fact that has been largely overlooked amid the attention
given to Mark McGwire's pursuit of Roger Maris' record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be kind of quiet around (McGwire), but stay close to him,''
Galarraga said. ``That's fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's make a deal
</P>
<P>
   With 21 of their 49 draft picks under contract, including five
of their top 10, the Braves put their best pitch to sixth-round
selection Victor Menocal Friday, letting the unsigned shortstop
from Gainesville High School work out with the team before the
game. Menocal has signed with Georgia Tech, but can sign with the
Braves until he enrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The team in the meanwhile has no intention of signing its first
pick, right-handed Texas pitcher Matt Belisle, until July, when the
condition of his surgically repaired torn left ACL can be better
evaluated. The second-round pick's rehab is three to four weeks
ahead of schedule, according to Birmingham surgeon James Andrews,
who performed the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart expects to return to action tonight after missing
three games while his left shoulder recovers from a double dose of
cortisone. ... Radar guns at John Smoltz's rehab start Wednesday
timed all his fastballs between 90 and 93 mph, which didn't impress
Smoltz. ``If I had to pitch up here, it would have been much
tougher,'' he said. ... Announcer Skip Caray might return to the
booth tonight, though his back is still sore from a spill taken at
his home Wednesday, when he slipped off a treadmill while
exercising and landed on a stationary bike.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
