<HEADLINE>
FOR SALE: PLAYERS DEAL JERSEY NUMBERS FOR PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. -  &UR; Thomas Guynes' mother didn't raise a dummy.
</P>
<P>
   When Cardinals offensive guard  &UR; Lester Holmes asked if Guynes
would give him uniform No. 71, Guynes said he would be happy to
oblige for the right price.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a graduate of the University of Michigan, I felt equipped
from going through the best educational process to make the wisest
and most discerning decision,'' said Guynes, a second-year
offensive lineman. ``Being that I had no real attachment to 71,
that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Guynes then sold Holmes No. 71 and took No. 70.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate  &UR; Ty Howard, who wore No. 29 last year, made a similar
deal.
</P>
<P>
   He sold running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell No. 29 and took jersey No.
27.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a business proposition I couldn't turn down,'' said
Howard, a second-year cornerback from Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like 29, either. But I didn't tell Murrell that.'' &QL; 
Sock hop &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft pick  &UR; Andre Wadsworth has worn his socks over
his football cleats at this week's rookie camp, a habit he picked
up at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to feel warm,'' said Wadsworth, a 6-foot-4, 278-pound
defensive end. ``The hotter I get, the more sweaty, the better I
feel. It makes my feet warm.''
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason he does it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deion went to Florida State,'' Wadsworth said of Dallas
Cowboys cornerback  &UR; Deion Sanders. ``He always said, `You want to
look good, because if you look good, you feel good. If you feel
good, you play good. If you play good, you get paid good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As the third pick in last April's draft, Wadsworth will become
an instant millionaire when he signs.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle cornerback  &UR; Shawn Springs, the third pick overall in
1997, signed a deal worth $2.2 million a year. &QL; 
Huge fan &QL; 
 &UR; Roy Green, the Cardinals' all-time leading receiver, has a new
favorite rookie on the team.
</P>
<P>
   It's second-round pick  &UR; Corey Chavous, who earlier this week
changed his uniform number from No. 43 to No. 25 because it was
Green's number as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who the best player in the draft is, but I know
who the smartest is _ Corey Chavous,'' Green said of the safety
from Vanderbilt. &QL; 
Crowded room &QL; 
Rookie linebacker  &UR; Aaron Collins is one of 19 children, the
youngest of five sons who played at Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   He has 12 sisters and six brothers, ranging in age from 45 to
19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom's a trouper,'' said Collins, a 6-foot, 237-pound native of
Cinnaminson, N.J. ``She's strong. She took care of us. And Dad
worked hard to pay the bills.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the family tries to get together once a month. ``But
everyone won't be at the same (dinner) table except Thanksgiving,''
said Collins, whose brother,  &UR; Andre, recently signed with the
Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up with so many kids really wasn't as tough as you'd
think. There always was someone to hang with, someone to talk
to.'' &QL; 
Short shots &QL; 
Cardinals starting quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer, among the veterans
who attended this week's rookie camp, will miss some of next week's
practices to attend the wedding of his brother,  &UR; Brett, in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer will be at HoHoKam Park this morning in Mesa, directing
a free clinic for kids. The session will runs from 9 a.m. until
noon. Advance registration is required.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have learned that the most compensatory picks they
can receive in next year's draft for losing free agents is four.
The picks will come at the ends of Rounds 3 to 7.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals wide receiver  &UR; Rob Moore, whose contract will be up at
the end of the 1998 season, has switched agents again. He has gone
back to his original agent,  &UR; Gary Wichard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
