<HEADLINE>
RESTROOMS OPEN AT LAKE PLEAS ANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The two new restroom facilities at Lake Pleasant's
10-lane boat ramp now are completely functional.
</P>
<P>
   The restrooms, complete with running water, flush toilets, sinks
and outside spigots (but no way to dry your hands), were badly
needed at this extremely popular launch site in Maricopa County's
Lake Pleasant Regional Park.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lighting has been installed at the ramps. After a
catfishing trip to the lake this week that ended at nightfall, I
can attest that both the restrooms and the lights are welcomed _
the restrooms for obvious reasons, the lights because they provide
a homing beacon and illumination for prepping a boat for launch and
for preparing it to go home.
</P>
<P>
   The lake's popular scenic overlook also is open to the public
again after a closure to construct water lines to the new restrooms
and to Roadrunner Campground.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes at a perfect time, as KGME-AM (1460) radio's $1
million bass fishing tournament will conclude near those ramps at
about 5 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   The station is offering $1 million to anyone who catches a state
record bass between 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. today. The largest five-bass
limit weighed in is worth $1,000, the largest bass $750 and the
second-largest $500.
</P>
<P>
   Those prizes are available only to those who have paid a $35
entry fee. &QL; 
More Lake Pleasant &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An 1,800-acre closure in the Agua Fria River at Lake Pleasant,
imposed to help nesting bald eagles at the lake, will be opened
again Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The area is closed during the nesting season to help protect
eagles from harassment.
</P>
<P>
   This year, one pair of breeding eagles reproduced. The area
averages one or two successful hatches each year.
</P>
<P>
   The buoy lines and signs marking the closure will be removed
about 7 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, the Lake Pleasant area has produced about 5 percent
of all eagles hatched in Arizona. &QL; 
Arizonan in money &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Taylor Hutchings of Phoenix finished 15th in the 15th annual
Red Man All-American Bass Fishing Championship on the Mississippi
River near LaCrosse, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty of the top anglers in the nation competed in the three-day
tournament. They qualified through regional tournaments. After the
first two days, the top 10 anglers qualified for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchings, in his two days of competition, caught 14 pounds, 14
ounces worth of bass and won $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was  &UR; Kim Carver of Milledgeville, Ga., who caught 32
pounds, 8 ounces in three days of fishing. He won $100,000. &QL; 
Feeding frenzy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although largemouth and smallmouth fishing has dropped off at
Lake Powell, striped bass are on a feeding frenzy, according to
 &UR; Wayne
 &UR; Gustaveson, the Utah fisheries biologist who is considered to be a
guru on Lake Powell fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Because of heavy snowpack in the Rocky Mountains, Powell is
close to filling. The stripers are feeding heavily on plankton, a
small organism, because shad are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Because getting enough to eat is difficult with the smaller
forage, a frozen anchovy or a bright spoon dropped among the
stripers is deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The stripers are found in 15 to 30 feet of water. They generally
are found near prominent points and must be located with sonar. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
