<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-VIDEOS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO'S DASH FOR CRASH  
 DRIVERS SPLIT OVER APPEAL OF MAYHEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two stock car drivers dive side by side into Turn 1, each
determined to claim the same piece of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Unless one softens up on the throttle, there will be hell to
pay.
</P>
<P>
   No one budges.
</P>
<P>
   A second later, the machines trade paint, causing one to slide
into an uncontrollable twirl. The spinning car suffers a snapped
brake line and bursts into flames.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon, who is eyeballing a replay of the crash on
television, leans forward in his living room chair and blurts,
``That's me!''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of crash-and-smash video, where catchy
commercials featuring countless nasty wrecks are the staples of
motor racing junkies hooked on mechanical mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, some of the video's most fervent fans are the
sport's main players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a whole library full of them,'' NASCAR Winston Cup
driver Ken Schrader says. ``In most of them, it looks like they
(the drivers) are able to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon suffered no injuries in the crash he saw during a
commercial for one of the videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened at North Wilkesboro,'' Gordon says. ``I've seen a
few of my wrecks when I still was racing midgets and sprints. I
don't mind watching them if I know no one was seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them really amaze you. Like those airplane crashes.
I'm interested, but I've never bought them.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't put Winston Cup driver Derrike Cope in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't pay attention to that stuff,'' Cope says. ``I'm
one of those guys that won't read what's written and I try not to
watch too much on TV. I very seldom even watch races over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup driver Dale Jarrett agrees with Cope, even if he
knows a driver was able to walk away from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why people want to see that,'' Jarrett
says. ``I'm glad the drivers walked away, but it's still not
something I want to see or even think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people make a living by putting pieces like that
together, but it would be nice if they made more pieces about the
good things that go on in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup driver Bobby Hamilton, however, can envision a lot
worse things for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people make money doing a lot worse things,'' Hamilton
says. ``I think its pretty cool to sit around, drink a beer and
watch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hewitt, who made his Indy-car debut in last month's
Indianapolis 500, believes there's a market for such videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think half the fans that come to races come to see
the big crashes and fights,'' says Hewitt, who adds that he doesn't
see anything wrong with the videos. ``They love it. They're here
for the blood and guts. It's kind of like the World Wrestling
Federation to them. I don't think they want to see anyone get hurt,
but when they see a crash, it seems to pump them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they see a good race and a crash, it's perfect. But you
can't hold it against them. They pay big bucks to come to the
races. Crashing thrills people. It's unfortunate, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Open-wheel driver Dan Drinan, who nearly died six years ago in a
horrific crash in a U.S. Auto Club midget race at Springfield,
Ill., dislikes the videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it when people sensationalize tragedies,'' says
Drinan, who attended Scottsdale Chaparral High school but now lives
in Indianapolis. ``In my crash, I had a finger chopped off, it tore
my arms up, my elbow was dislocated and my face was all messed up.
I lived through that horrendous crash, but I was lucky. Stuff like
this hits too close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I really don't think the majority of fans come to see
crashes. I think it's the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian France, NASCAR Vice President for Marketing and
Communications, strongly agrees. France, however, also agrees that
there are exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest moments in NASCAR's 50-year history aren't about
crashes,'' France says in reference to NASCAR's 50-year anniversary
celebration. ``They're about things like memorable finishes in the
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we recognize that fans are fascinated by dramatic crashes
from time to time. But it's not what our sport is about. We like to
focus on the competition between the drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, sometimes, the competition can lead to a fiery end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see wrecks a little more often than the average person, so
it's not that big a deal for us,'' Gordon says. ``But if someone
gets hurt real bad, it's not something you enjoy watching over and
over again on a video.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody enjoys that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
