r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-JARRETT-AZ     06-12 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-JARRETT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT WILL RE MEMBER LA BONTE'S BUMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poor Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was socked twice Saturday in the waning moments of the
Pontiac Excitement 400 at Richmond International Raceway, arguably
costing the Ford Quality Care driver the NASCAR Winston Cup
victory.
</P>
<P>
   First, NASCAR officials decided to red flag the race seven laps
from the finish, allowing course workers time to clean debris and
oil from Turn 2, the site of a multicar crash on Lap 393.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's intention was to create a green flag finish for fans.
But in doing so, Jarrett, who was leading, became a victim. Had
officials displayed a yellow flag and not red, the race likely
would have ended under caution and Jarrett would have been crowned
the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the race resumed, Jarrett and Labonte began a fierce
battle for the lead. On Lap 398, two laps from the checkered flag,
Jarrett lost it.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte squeezed by after first bumping Jarrett with his Chevy
Monte Carlo, and won when, ironically, a Johnny Benson crash
coinciding with the Labonte-Jarrett tussle forced the race to end
under caution.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett still might have been able to fend off Labonte, but he
was operating with older tires that had become cold during the race
stoppage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not against finishing the race under green,'' Jarrett
said Tuesday. ``As a matter of fact, that's what the fans deserve,
and we're very conscious of that. As much as we want to say we're
just there to race and enjoy what we're doing, it is a show and
they (NASCAR) have an obligation to put on the best show for the
fans and the TV audience that they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``After talking with them and understanding their position, and
realizing it was a call they had to make in a span of about 10
seconds, they did what they thought was right for the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   But it cost Jarrett dearly.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Vice President for Competition Mike Helton said the
cleanup took 13 to 14 minutes, which would have encompassed 12 laps
had there not been a red flag.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Jarrett and Labonte slam dance, Helton said NASCAR
determined it ``just a racing incident.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be just a racing incident to NASCAR, but to Jarrett, it
was a racing incident that likely will have repercussions down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you put in the back of your mind,'' Jarrett
said. ``He (Labonte) didn't take me out. He hit me pretty hard, but
to say if we're racing side-by-side at Michigan (on Sunday) I'm
going to rough him up or anything, no, I'm not saying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's something you put in your memory bank and at
an opportune time, yeah, you may be a little bit rougher. But it's
not a matter that I'm going to go out and wreck Terry Labonte
because I don't intend on doing that. That's not the makeup of
NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I have to use the bumper a little bit at some point in
time, then that's what I'll have to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
