u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-WOMEN-FISHIN     06-12 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-WOMEN-FISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: WOMEN BRIDGING GAP AS KEYS FISHING GUIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent in category `l') 
(bl) 
 By NICHOLAS KARAS   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next time you head to the Florida Keys looking for someone
to guide you to a bonefish, tarpon or big grouper, you might be
surprised to find that your options have widened. A growing number
of women have become professional guides.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible ``glass captain's ceiling'' has been broken by a
handful of exceptionally qualified women who are becoming some of
the Keys' best fishing guides.
</P>
<P>
   Their course has not been easy. It is not that charters object
to female captains, but the extreme competitiveness between
skippers _ regardless of gender _ leaves little room even for
well-qualified women. If you do fish with a woman as your guide,
you will be impressed because she has crossed more hurdles to get
there than some men may have.
</P>
<P>
   THE place for a woman to look for work as a captain is the Keys,
the string of loosely connected coral islands that offers anglers
and would-be captains offshore fishing, flats fishing and
back-country fishing in Florida Bay. During the past few years,
nearly a dozen women have moved to the Keys, earned their Coast
Guard master's papers, and are now making a living guiding; half of
them are full-time guides. Most are thirtysomething, but a few are
older.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Lori Parker, 33, came to the profession through the back
door. She has been a steady fixture in the Keys since she was 16,
when her father, Captain Jack Kelly, moved there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fishing my entire life,'' she said. ``Maybe it was
my father's love of fishing that imbued me. I caught my first
tarpon when I was 8. Dad strapped me into the chair and yelled,
`Get him, wimp.' I was small for my age, but I beat the fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker got her license when she was just 19. ``It wasn't easy,''
she said. ``When I took the test, I was the only woman in a cramped
room filled with men. I heard a lot of snickering going on behind
me before the exam started. It unnerved me. I psyched out. Failed
it, but went back a second time and made it.''
</P>
<P>
   She began as a dive-boat mate, then spent a couple of years as a
skipper out of Boog Powell's marina. For the next seven years, she
worked as a mate on sport-fishing boats. ``My last job as a mate
was on an offshore boat,'' she said. ``The captain's wife, Linda
Luzzia, was a friend and a tarpon guide. If she could do it, so
could I.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker's father, who still guides out of Key West, helped her
buy and outfit her boat. Today, father and daughter often fish
together and daily share fishing information, via cellular phone,
when they are out of sight. She has guided full-time for the last
six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband, Ken, is in the refrigeration business and shares
my love of fishing,'' said Parker, who has a 6-year-old son. ``I
lead a normal life, like any other woman and mother who is working
or has a career. I pick up my son from the baby sitter at the end
of a trip. I clean house for a while then start dinner so it's
ready when Ken comes home. The only difference between me and other
career women is that my profession is a full-time fishing guide. It
IS my business.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker has made a specialty of fishing for tarpon in the deeper
channels around Key West and wreck fishing offshore. ``Because I
now compete for customers, a few guides resent me and continually
give me a hard time,'' she said. ``Most, however, don't. Many even
go out of their way to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker said she has had only one ``character'' resent her
because she was a woman. ``He wanted to fish a reef in the gulf,''
she said. ``He was with his family, and the weather was too bad for
safe fishing. Seas were rough and building. I refused to go. He
said it wasn't the weather, that I was chicken: `A woman should be
in the kitchen, not running a boat.' He chartered a bigger boat and
went to the reef. Everyone got seasick, and the skipper cut short
the charter.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Captain Donna Van Kirk, 42, of Marathon, Fla., started fishing
in New Jersey when her husband, Jim, a commercial fisherman, taught
her to chase blues and striped bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``When commercial fishing started to fall off 13 years ago, we
came to the Keys,'' she said. ``Jim trapped lobsters, and I fished
for fun. I worked the flats taking bonefish and permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most tarpon pile up in holes scoured around bridge
abutments,'' she continued. ``That's where I take my fares. I've
been flats fishing for 15 years but only began guiding in '94.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because Van Kirk is older, or because captains in Marathon
on Vaca Key are less competitive than those in Key West, she has
had little trouble gaining acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always friendly, talk to them, and wave when we pass on
the water, but I keep pretty much to myself,'' she said. ``I still
have a 17-year-old daughter to raise, and she fills my off-water
time. Who knows, maybe after she runs through these terrible teens,
she, too, might want to become a fishing guide.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES
</P>
<P>
   _ TINA BROWN fishes outside the Atlantic and keeps her boat
behind Porky's Bayside Restaurant in Marathon. Information: (305)
743-7150.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANN HOOLIHAN fishes the flats out of Bud N' Mary's Marina in
Islamorada. Information: (305) 664-5891.
</P>
<P>
   _ LINDA LUIZZA has two boats, one at Garrison Bight Marina, Key
West, and the other on a trailer, and fishes both the flats and
outside. Information: (305) 294-0803.
</P>
<P>
   _ LORI PARKER fishes out of Oceanside Marina in Key West and
specializes in fishing the Atlantic side for tarpon. Information:
(305) 292-1928.
</P>
<P>
   _ DONNA VAN KIRK, a flats guide out of Marathon, keeps her boat
on a trailer so she can fish anywhere in the Keys. Information:
(305) 743-2821.
</P>
<P>
   _ BOBBI VEE fishes the flats out of Bud N' Mary's Marina,
Islamorada. Information: (305) 664-2461.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
