<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SMUGGLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIZED FREIGHTER MAY HAVE BEEN SMUGGLERS' `MOTHER SHIP'
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SUSAN SACHS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the seizure of a freighter that is suspected of smuggling
Asian immigrants into the Bahamas this week, federal officials said
they were beginning to piece together the circuitous journey of 23
Chinese men who illegally landed on a New Jersey beach two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The 120-foot-long ship seized in the Caribbean, the Oriental I,
may have been a so-called mother ship used in one phase of a
smuggling operation involving many vessels, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oriental I, now in the custody of the U.S. Coast Guard, was
intercepted about 195 miles east of San Salvador Island on Monday.
Only an eight-man crew _ comprised of four Venezuelan and four
Korean nationals _ was on board at the time it was seized. But the
day before, U.S. Customs officials, watching from an airplane, saw
a group of people leaving the ship in a speedboat, which raced them
to Abaco Island in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian police were alerted and later found 24 Asian men _ 23
from China and one from Malaysia _ hiding near the island town of
Hole in the Wall. Those men have been detained as illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials say they believe the freighter, which is
registered in Venezuela, also played a role in the smuggling of the
Chinese immigrants who were dumped on the beach at Bay Head, N.J.,
on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants had traveled near the U.S. coast on the Oriental
I and were then transferred to a smaller boat, the Oops II, the
authorities said. But the Oops II lost its way in dense fog and ran
aground, leaving the immigrants to jump into the surf and flee
toward the mansions lining the shore of the wealthy town.
</P>
<P>
   The men were rounded up over the next few days and taken to the
Immigration and Naturalization Service detention center in
Elizabeth, N.J. The immigrants' lawyers have said they will all ask
for political asylum because they fear persecution in China.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they doubted that either group of immigrants _
those who ended up in New Jersey and those who were caught in the
Bahamas _ had traveled all the way from China on the freighter.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for one of the immigrants who landed in New Jersey said
that the smuggling route began in South America, the Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guy's trip took about two months,'' said the lawyer, Jules
Coven. He said his client, Dian Lu Jiang, flew from China to
Suriname, a country on the northeast coast of South America, before
boarding the first of three boats involved in the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980612.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT &LR;      06-12 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS HAND GAME TO MARLINS, 4-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The New York Mets did something Friday night they rarely
have done this season: They gave a game away.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dunwoody's infield single up the middle off second baseman
Carlos Baerga's glove scored Craig Counsell from third base with
two out in the ninth to give the Florida Marlins a come-from-behind
4-3 victory. The loss spoiled the Mets' chances of reaching a
season-best 12 games over .500; they are 36-26.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Marlins' second two-out rally in two innings. And it
made a loser of Brian Bohanon, who has been thrust into a set-up
role ever since Greg McMichael was sent to Los Angeles as part of
the Hideo Nomo trade.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon probably deserved a better fate. Counsell reached base
with one out and one on when his bouncer through the middle glanced
off Bohanon's bare left hand.
</P>
<P>
   The ball deflected to Baerga, who shoveled it with his glove to
shortstop Luis Lopez for the force at second base. But Lopez's
relay was not in time to double the speedy Counsell, and the Mets
still needed one more out.
</P>
<P>
   It never came. John Cangelosi, a pinch-hitter, followed with a
bloop single to center to move Counsell to third. And then the
left-handed hitting Dunwoody singled off the left-handed Bohanon,
as Counsell scampered home with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Met offense had sputtered. This time, the
pitching and defense were not able to overcome it.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile had tied the score at 3-3 on a two-out single off
Turk Wendell in the eighth. That Marlins' rally spoiled an
impressive pitching performance by Dennis Cook, whose only hit
allowed in two and a third innings innings of relief _ a two-out
double to Mark Kotsay _ immediately preceded Zeile's single.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could have regained the lead, but they left Lopez
stranded at third with one out after he led off the ninth inning
with a double. Matt Franco, who replaced Bernard Gilkey in left
field after Gilkey was hit in the face with a pitch in the third
inning, nearly put the Mets back ahead. But his liner back to the
box was snared by Matt Mantei, who had to leap for the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza followed by grounding out to short to end the inning
with the score still tied.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins had escaped in the ninth. The Mets did not.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets erased an early 2-0 deficit by piecing together three
third-inning runs on two hit batsmen, an error, two singles and a
sacrifice fly. And then, as usual, the pitching and defense took
over.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, a former Marlin, bailed out Masato Yoshii with two pitches
in the sixth inning after the Marlins had put runners on first and
third with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had battled his way through five and one third innings
before he put himself in position for trouble by committing a
two-base error on Kotsay's grounder to first. When Zeile followed
with a single to left, Yoshii was gone, after allowing five hits
and two runs, walking one and striking out three.
</P>
<P>
   On came Cook, who was one of the most valuable performers on
Florida's run to the World Series title last fall. With the tying
run on third, his first pitch to Cliff Floyd resulted in a foul pop
to first. On the next pitch, pinch-hitter Derrek Lee grounded to
the shortstop side of second, where Rey Ordonez made a sensational
sliding stop and backhanded toss to Baerga at second for the force
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez's defensive gem followed ones by Wayne Kirby and Piazza
in the second (they teamed to throw out Gregg Zaun at the plate as
he attempted to score from third on a fly to right); Yoshii, who
snared a nasty right-back-at-you liner from Dunwoody leading off
the third; and Brian McRae, whose sliding catch in center field off
a sinking liner by Zaun prevented the Marlins from scoring the
tying run in the fourth. That came one batter after Ordonez had
made a pretty over-the-shoulder catch on Ryan Jackson in short
center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' three-run third inning began on the scariest moment of
the evening: The rookie right-hander Ryan Dempster hit Gilkey just
below the left eye with a 1-2 fastball. The ball appeared to have
glanced off Gilkey's helmet before hitting his face. After a few
moments, Gilkey _ whose first-inning single snapped an 0 for 25
spell _ arose and walked off the field. X-rays showed no break. All
that remained was a bruise on Gilkey's face.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
