<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-12 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7618 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--Astros-Reds-HNS &LR;      06-12 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Reds-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Remlinger, Reds 
silence Astros 8-1
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CINCINNATI _ In 45 previous innings, the Cincinnati Reds had scored
six runs. On Friday night against the Astros, they got four in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   And what began with the possibility of an offensive explosion
fizzled as Cincinnati halted the Astros' five-game winning streak
with an 8-1 rout before a crowd of 21,310 at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly a game the Astros _ and starter Jose Lima _ would
like to forget. The lost not only to a Cincinnati club in last
place in the National League Central but to a pitcher who hadn't
won in more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   And Lima's fourth-inning exit was his earliest this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds' victory was only their second in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Remlinger (4-7) snapped a personal four-game losing streak,
allowing two hits in a season-high eight innings of work. He
retired 13 straight batters from the fourth inning to the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy pitched a great game,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
``In a way, it's better that a guy is going to shut you down that
way. If you're going to have a game where you give up eight runs,
you might as well do it when the other guy is pitching a
two-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger said, ``I was talking to (injured pitcher) Jose Rijo
during the last homestand and he told me to stop worrying about all
that other stuff. And he was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I walk a guy, I walk him, but I need to do it with
conviction and stop nibbling.''
</P>
<P>
   After a leadoff home run by Craig Biggio on the third pitch of
the game, the Astros couldn't muster any more offense. Moises
Alou's bloop single to right in the fourth inning was the last hit
the Astros got off Remlinger.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell and Jeff Bagwell singled in the ninth off reliever
Danny Graves.
</P>
<P>
   The four-hit output was the lowest total for the Astros since
Chicago's Kerry Wood pitched a one-hitter in his 20-strikeout
masterpiece May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger got off to an inauspicious start when Biggio hit a 1-1
pitch into the right-field bleachers, his second leadoff homer of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   But from then on, Remlinger held the National League's
best-hitting team in road games to one hit while striking out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``After he gave up a leadoff homer, you don't expect one hit the
rest of the night,'' said Bagwell. ``Obviously, one run in the
first inning is not enough. Down 5-1 in the third, with the offense
we have, it's definitely not out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima (7-3) suffered through his worst outing of the season,
allowing five runs and eight hits in 3 innings. Lima had pitched
six innings or more in all 13 of his starts until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who pitched a five-hit shutout against Kansas City in his
previous start, had trouble from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds hit just about everything Lima threw in the vicinity of
home plate during a four-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Greene, Barry Larkin, Eddie Taubensee and Dmitri Young
had consecutive singles, and Melvin Nieves delivered a two-run
single to give the Reds a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati had scored six runs total in its previous five games
_ all losses _ against Cleveland and San Diego. The eight runs were
the most by the Reds since they scored eight against Los Angeles on
May 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any excuses. Tonight, I was bad,'' Lima
said. ``If you leave pitches up to anybody, you are going to pay
the price. Everything was up, and they rocked it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better now than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin, the center of trade rumors last few days, homered
off Lima in the fifth inning. Larkin went 2-for-4 with a sacrifice
fly in a three-run eighth off Bob Scanlan, whose throwing error
helped the rally along.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he thought about taking Lima out after six of the
first eight batters reached base.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lima stayed in until the score was 5-1. Trever Miller
retired one batter in relief, and C.J. Nitkowski shut out the Reds
for three innings before Scanlan finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to happen sooner or later that Lima had a bad night on
the mound,'' Dierker said. ``He never got anything going his way.
That's the way it is. Sometimes, it's merciful to take a pitcher
out. I think he wanted to stay. That's admirable, but I just don't
think there was any future of him staying in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who entered the game with an NL-leading .271 average
on the road, did not have a runner reach third base after Biggio's
home run. The Astros put runners at first and second in the fourth
inning when Alou singled and Sean Berry walked, but Remlinger got
Carl Everett to line out to left field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
