<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER STATE SENATOR RE-ENTERS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks after he dropped out of the state Senate
race in the Bronx, Pedro Espada Jr. said Friday that he had changed
his mind and would run in the Democratic primary to regain the seat
he once held.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is certain to inject a new round of turbulence into
the political landscape in the Bronx. When he withdrew from the
race, Espada had said that it would help promote party unity while
also helping his son, Councilman Pedro Gautier Espada, mend his
relationship with Democratic Party officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Espada said he had reversed his decision because
Bronx Democratic officials had reneged on what he said were
promises to stop an investigation of his health-care business if he
pulled out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Espada said that the Bronx Democratic leader, Assemblyman
Roberto Ramirez, had indicated two weeks ago that he would ask
Robert Johnson, the Bronx district attorney, to end investigations
of Espada's finances at the Soundview Health Clinic if he did not
oppose the incumbent state senator, David Rosado.
</P>
<P>
   Espada and his son have had a volatile, on-again off-again
relationship with the Bronx Democratic organization for the last
two years. But it seemed that the two sides were mending fences
with Espada's decision not to seek his old seat.
</P>
<P>
   That decision was viewed as a victory for Ramirez, since it
would have reduced the number of Democratic officials facing
opponents in the party's primary in September. Instead, Ramirez and
the Democratic organization now seem destined for a highly charged
primary season.
</P>
<P>
   Espada said that his brother, Jose Espada, the owner of an
ambulance company, would now run for the Assembly against Ruben
Diaz Jr., who holds the seat once held by Pedro Gautier Espada, the
councilman. Also, Espada said, his son will oppose Rosado for the
position of Democratic leader in that district.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported Friday that it had obtained audio and
video tapes from Espada of a secretly recorded meeting between
Espada and Rosado as well as a meeting between Rosado and his son,
the councilman, two weeks ago. In those tapes, the paper said,
Rosado boasted of the Democratic Party's ability to influence the
Bronx district attorney either to investigate or call off
investigations of Espada's business, based on the former senator's
political decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez denied that there was any truth to what Rosado was
saying, calling it the most ``ludicrous statement I would have
possibly heard.'' Asked if there had been any deal offered by the
organization to persuade Espada to stay out of the race, Ramirez
said: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Reed, a spokesman for the Bronx district attorney,
declined to comment on what investigations, if any, his office was
conducting into Espada and his business. He added that, ``when
legal matters are under review in this office, political
considerations are not part of the decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rosado acknowledged that he had conversations with
the Espadas, but said that he sensed that he was being trapped and
had deliberately misled the two men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that he was trying to corner me into something,''
Rosado said Friday. ``I knew he was a liar, so I lied to a liar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
