<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN AMERICANS TAKE NEXT STEP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France _ Everything the United States has
accomplished on the soccer field the past four years the fine
second-round showing at the 1994 World Cup, that magical summer of
'95, the gutty finish to its '98 qualifying campaign, that
incredible triumph over Brazil just a few months ago means nothing
now.
</P>
<P>
   The strides this country has made in the world's sport, and the
deeds that have signaled its emergence as an international power of
sorts, will be put to the test the next couple weeks, and the
consensus is that the Americans haven't got a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission, to reach the knockout phase of the 16th World
Cup, appears well out of reach, so much so that American soccer's
top official admits he's not anticipating a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to make the second round,'' says Alan Rothenberg,
U.S. Soccer's president. ``Realistically, I don't expect to achieve
that goal. Realistically, I think we will fall a little short of
that goal and not make it out of the first round.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest obstacles to meeting the goal are pretty huge,
indeed: reigning European champion Germany, three-time World Cup
champs and participants in five of the last seven title games, and
Yugoslavia, which by all accounts has far more talent than the
Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams will escape the four-team Group F --- four
third-place teams, the United States among them, reached the second
round in '94 --- which means the Americans must overcome the
Germans (Monday in Paris) or the Yugoslavs (June 25 in Nantes),
along with Iran (June 21 in Lyon), if they are to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Mission impossible?
</P>
<P>
   ``The task of getting to the second round is much more difficult
than in '94,'' acknowledges Coach Steve Sampson. ``The second round
would be a wonderful accomplishment. But equally important is how
we play, to continue to show we're playing a much more
sophisticated style of soccer, more intelligent, more calculated,
with more taking of risks. Then we will have grown as a
soccer-playing nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past four years, especially in the time since Sampson
stepped in after Bora Milutinovic's dismissal in April 1995, the
Yanks have exhibited impressive growth, evolving from a
pseudoprofessional outfit that worked hard to confound its superior
foes to a capable, confident squad that seeks to impose its game,
an attacking style geared toward winning rather than avoided
losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In previous World Cups,'' Sampson says, ``we weren't on even
playing ground with our opponents. ... This team, given their
experience now, truly believes in themselves and believes that they
can beat Germany, Iran and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a very special effort to do well in this World Cup,
but I don't believe we've ever been better prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   The key, it appears, is a 3-6-1 alignment (three defenders, six
midfielders and one forward) geared toward providing playmaking
midfielder Claudio Reyna all the tools he needs to make the U.S.
attack go. Utilizing the Americans' depth in midfield and speed on
the flanks, the new formation is designed to clog up the middle of
the field, turn the defense from a liability to a strength, and
create a counterattack that causes problems for opponents.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so-so: The Yanks, with world-class goalkeeper Kasey
Keller in the nets, have shut out its last four foes but have had
trouble scoring goals. The return of striker Eric Wynalda from knee
surgery could answer many of the doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Also crucial are wingers Cobi Jones and Frankie Hejduk, if he is
sufficiently recovered from a hamstring ailment, who are capable of
causing chaos in opposing defenses. Defensive midfielders Chad
Deering and Brian Maisonneuve, both capable playmakers as well,
provide a foundation for the whole thing to work.
</P>
<P>
   That the United States hasn't tested the alignment against any
significant opposition since the 3-0 thrashing April 22 of fellow
World Cup finalist Austria is a bit worrisome. But Sampson, and his
players, aren't among those worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic,'' says defender Alexi Lalas, who along
with fellow '94 star Marcelo Balboa has moved to the bench in favor
of a swifter sweeper-and-markers defense of Thomas Dooley, Eddie
Pope and naturalized Frenchman David Regis. ``I think this is the
best American team ever. (We have) more experience, more leaders,
more character, more personality ...''
</P>
<P>
   Says Sampson: ``No one expects the United States to get out of
the first round. All the pressure is on Germany and Yugoslavia. We
have our own expectations, and our own expectations --- regardless
of what anybody else says --- is that we expect to get out of the
first round. ... We have a chance to do something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also have the chance of doing something special
... and still not reaching the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to do the best we can,'' says midfielder Tab
Ramos, one of three veterans --- with Wynalda and Balboa --- of the
1990 and 1994 World Cups. ``We have to play our best game, and if
that's not good enough, if it's beyond our reach, then there's
nothing we could've done anyway. But we'll be disappointed if we
don't do the best we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Germany comes in and doesn't play its best game, but we
play our best game, I think we can beat them. And same with
Yugoslavia. But if they play their best game and we also play our
best game, it'll be hard. They have a better team than we do, and
so does Yugoslavia. There's nothing we can do about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-12-98 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
