<SLUG> BC-NY-PRINCIPAL-SENTENCED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICE PRINCIPAL SENTENCED IN GAMBLING OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The vice principal of a Brooklyn middle school who
amassed $2.5 million from a network of illegal Joker Poker gambling
machines in poor neighborhoods that he obsessively tended for 10
years was sentenced in federal court Friday to 15 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Metzger, a guidance counselor and vice principal of
Intermediate School 218 in East New York, concealed his wealth from
his wife, hiding thousands of dollars in small bills and coins in a
one-room apartment that he rented in Queens, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Metzger, a school board employee of 33 years, pleaded guilty to
operating and hiding the profits of an illegal gambling business
two years ago. When investigators burst into his Kew Gardens
apartment to arrest him, they found him alone at the kitchen table,
rolling quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Denis Hurley of U.S. District Court did not fine Metzger,
who has forfeited all his gambling profits. But his school board
pension will be garnished to pay $500,000 in federal taxes on the
$2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the whole 10-year period, he didn't spend any money,'' said
Richard Weber, an assistant U.S. prosecutor. On the day they
arrested Metzger, investigators found $18,000 in a bureau drawer,
including $5,000 in dollar bills and piles of loose quarters. One
safe deposit box contained $550,000. But the apartment was ``almost
bare,'' Weber said. ``A little wooden bed, a TV, and money
magazines: Money, Mutual Fund magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holbrook, N.Y., home where Metzger lived with his wife,
Judith, also a school board employee, and raised their son and
daughter was a ``typical middle-income house, mortgaged up, with
him driving a Saturn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, Metzger, 55, owned as many as 50 slot machines, all
in poor neighborhoods in Brooklyn, Queens and the Bronx and
accessible to teen-agers, Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors and IRS investigators discovered the slot
machines after police officers complained that residents with
little money were gambling away their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Seven other people convicted of operating illegal slot machines
are scheduled for sentencing soon.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Lotto, Metzger's lawyer, said his client, whose salary as
a vice principal was more than $60,000, was obsessively afraid of
growing old in poverty. Maintaining the gambling machines was
exhausting, dangerous work that Metzger did alone, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to go several times a week to empty them,'' Lotto said.
``He would drive all over Brooklyn and the Bronx. He'd go to
collect money in these bodegas in the middle of the night. He was
afraid he'd get killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said Metzger deposited $900,000 in Swiss bank accounts and
about $750,000 in accounts in the names of relatives, and had cash
in several safe deposit boxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
