<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT &LR;      06-12 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURPLUS IN STARTING ROTATION FORCES MENDOZA TO BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rain washed out the scheduled game between the New
York Yankees and the Cleveland Indians Friday night at Yankee
Stadium, but it could not mute the machinations of a team trying
not to lose a step in its march to become the biggest winner in
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who did not immediately reschedule the game, have
the major leagues' best record at 46-14. But they are being forced
to tinker with rotations and lineups, the latter because of
injuries to Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams, the former because of
a glut of successful starters.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre took care of one of those problems Friday by
shifting Ramiro Mendoza from the starting rotation to the bullpen
after learning that Andy Pettitte, who left Thursday night's game
in Montreal with an apparent injury, will not miss a turn.
</P>
<P>
   Torre told Mendoza, Friday night's scheduled starter, that he
would not only lose the turn but would also have to relinquish his
position in the rotation until further notice. That decision came
in the wake of two sizzling outings by Orlando Hernandez, the Cuban
defector who won his first two major-league starts while filling in
for the injured David Cone and David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Now Wells has recovered from a twinge in his left shoulder. Cone
has put a dog bite on his pitching hand behind him and will start
against the Indians today. And Pettitte is also fine, one day after
the left-hander was removed because of a sore buttocks.
</P>
<P>
   With six healthy starters, Torre was left with a decision about
how to reduce the number to five. It was not a tough choice, even
though Torre is a huge fan of Mendoza, who is 4-1 with a 4.00
earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, conceded Torre, ``is tough to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mendoza hasn't done anything wrong,'' Torre said, but he added
that the ease with which Hernandez ``pitched the other day was
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza was informed of the change of role before the Yankees
officially postponed Friday night's game. He left the clubhouse
before Torre informed reporters and was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he had emphasized to Mendoza his continued importance
to the team, primarily in innings such as the sixth and seventh,
where other relievers have struggled of late. Mendoza's sinker and
ability to coax ground-ball outs and double plays made him
successful in such a role at times last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What works against him is he has done it before,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   So the manager tried to couch the news in terms of its not being
a demotion. But, Torre admitted, ``at first blush, he's not buying
this; he buys it, but it's disappointing to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision had to be made, if only to settle one of the
team's few problems, Torre said. The other one _ the lineup _
remained unresolved, however. Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop and No.
2 hitter, is suffering from a strained abdominal muscle and is not
scheduled to come off the disabled list until next Sunday.
Williams, the center fielder and cleanup hitter, sprained his right
knee on Wednesday night and is out at least two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now my challenge is trying to figure out a lineup,''
Torre said. ``It's so easy when you have Bernie in there. Now, it's
trying to find the combination I'll be comfortable with. But as far
as the challenge, it's still the pitching. If we pitch, I think we
have enough ways we can score runs to be able to offset our
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, who signed with the Yankees as a 16-year-old in
1990, finally got his first call to the major leagues on Thursday
when he was informed by his manager at Class AAA Columbus, Stump
Merrill, that he would take Bernie Williams' roster spot. ``He
called me in and told me I was scratched from the lineup _ `you're
going to the big club,' he said,'' said Ledee, his eyes welling as
he spoke Friday. ``I couldn't talk, I couldn't say anything. I
started to shake, I was so nervous.'' ... Andy Pettitte, who felt a
twinge in the buttocks while running out a sacrifice bunt on
Thursday in Montreal, was checked Friday by the team physician,
Stuart Hershon, ``for about 10 seconds, and I'm fine,'' the pitcher
said. ... Williams, though concerned about suffering his first knee
injury during an awkward slide into third base, was also relieved.
``Whenever you hear it's going to be two weeks, that's better than
surgery,'' the center fielder said. ``It's still sensitive to the
touch, but I can walk on it, which is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
